(function(){
if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['gynae_p2_physio'] = [

{q:'The anterior pituitary hormone that stimulates growth and maturation of ovarian follicles is:',o:['Luteinizing hormone','Prolactin','Thyroid stimulating hormone','Follicle stimulating hormone'],a:3,
e:`FSH binds receptors on granulosa cells, stimulating follicular growth, granulosa cell proliferation and aromatase expression during the follicular phase. Secretion is driven by pulsatile GnRH and suppressed by inhibin B, enabling dominant follicle selection as FSH declines mid-cycle.<br><br>FSH-driven aromatase determines which follicle becomes dominant: the follicle with the highest aromatase efficiency survives the FSH decline while others undergo atresia, selecting a single Graafian follicle for ovulation each cycle.<br><br>LH (A) triggers ovulation and theca cell androgen production. Prolactin (B) suppresses GnRH and inhibits ovulation. TSH (C) stimulates thyroid hormone synthesis with no direct ovarian action.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The surge of which hormone triggers ovulation in the menstrual cycle?',o:['Oxytocin','LH','FSH','Prolactin'],a:1,
e:`Rising oestradiol in the late follicular phase exerts positive feedback on the hypothalamus and pituitary once approximately 200 pg/mL is sustained for 50 hours, triggering the mid-cycle LH surge that causes final oocyte maturation and follicular rupture approximately 36 hours later.<br><br>The LH surge simultaneously initiates oocyte meiosis resumption, activates follicular wall proteolytic enzymes and prostaglandins to cause rupture, and begins luteinisation of granulosa cells to form the progesterone-secreting corpus luteum.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) stimulates uterine contractions and milk ejection. FSH (C) drives follicular development but the ovulatory trigger is specifically LH. Prolactin (D) inhibits GnRH and suppresses ovulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone from the anterior pituitary stimulates milk production in the mammary glands?',o:['Prolactin','TSH','Oxytocin','LH'],a:0,
e:`Prolactin from anterior pituitary lactotrophs binds mammary alveolar receptors, stimulating synthesis of casein, lactalbumin, lactose and triglycerides. During pregnancy, rising prolactin prepares the breast but milk production is suppressed by progesterone until delivery, when progesterone withdrawal allows full lactogenesis within 1-3 days.<br><br>Each suckling episode triggers a fresh prolactin surge through a neuroendocrine reflex that inhibits hypothalamic dopamine release, maintaining lactation for as long as breastfeeding continues. Cessation of suckling allows prolactin to fall and lactation to cease over days.<br><br>TSH (B) stimulates thyroid hormone synthesis. Oxytocin (C) ejects milk by contracting myoepithelial cells but does not produce it. LH (D) stimulates gonadal steroidogenesis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Oxytocin is synthesized in which part of the brain?',o:['Thyroid gland','Pineal gland','Hypothalamus','Pituitary gland'],a:2,
e:`Oxytocin is synthesised in magnocellular neurons of the paraventricular and supraoptic nuclei of the hypothalamus, packaged into neurosecretory vesicles and transported along axons to the posterior pituitary for storage and release into the systemic circulation.<br><br>The distinction between site of synthesis (hypothalamus) and site of release (posterior pituitary) is clinically relevant: pituitary stalk damage impairs release while hypothalamic damage impairs both synthesis and release, causing more severe posterior pituitary hormone deficiency in the latter case.<br><br>The thyroid gland (A) and pineal gland (B) do not synthesise oxytocin. The pituitary gland (D) releases but does not synthesise oxytocin; synthesis occurs upstream in the hypothalamic nuclei.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Oxytocin is released from which structure?',o:['Thyroid gland','Posterior pituitary','Adrenal cortex','Anterior pituitary'],a:1,
e:`Oxytocin stored in posterior pituitary axon terminals is released into the systemic circulation when action potentials propagate down hypothalamic magnocellular axons in response to suckling, cervical distension via the Ferguson reflex, and certain emotional stimuli. The posterior pituitary acts purely as a storage and release organ.<br><br>Magnocellular neurons also release oxytocin centrally within the brain, acting as a neurotransmitter influencing pair bonding, maternal behaviour, stress responses and social recognition, distinct from its peripheral endocrine actions on uterus and breast.<br><br>Thyroid gland (A) and adrenal cortex (C) are separate endocrine structures with no role in oxytocin storage or release. Anterior pituitary (D) secretes FSH, LH, TSH, ACTH, prolactin and GH via a separate portal vascular mechanism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The hormone responsible for stimulation of thyroid hormone secretion is:',o:['Prolactin','ACTH','TSH','FSH'],a:2,
e:`TSH from anterior pituitary thyrotrophs binds Gs-coupled receptors on thyroid follicular cells, activating adenylate cyclase and stimulating all steps of thyroid hormone synthesis: iodide uptake via the sodium-iodide symporter, thyroid peroxidase-mediated organification, thyroglobulin synthesis and proteolytic T3 and T4 release into circulation.<br><br>TSH also promotes thyroid follicular cell hypertrophy and hyperplasia via MAP kinase and PI3K-Akt pathways, explaining why chronic TSH elevation in primary hypothyroidism or iodine deficiency leads to diffuse thyroid enlargement and clinical goitre requiring treatment.<br><br>Prolactin (A) stimulates lactation. ACTH (B) drives adrenal cortisol synthesis. FSH (D) stimulates ovarian follicular development. None act on thyroid follicular cells to produce T3 and T4.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The thyroid hormones primarily responsible for increasing basal metabolic rate are:',o:['Calcitonin','T3 and T4','Parathyroid hormone','Aldosterone'],a:1,
e:`T3 and T4 bind nuclear TRalpha and TRbeta receptors, converting them from transcriptional repressors to activators, upregulating genes for Na/K-ATPase, mitochondrial uncoupling proteins, beta-adrenergic receptors and metabolic enzymes to increase oxygen consumption and heat production in virtually all metabolically active tissues throughout the body.<br><br>T3 is three to four times more potent than T4 because it binds thyroid hormone receptors with greater affinity. Most circulating T4 is peripherally converted to T3 by deiodinase enzymes in liver, kidney and brain, making T4 a long-acting prohormone with a 7-day half-life.<br><br>Calcitonin (A) lowers serum calcium by inhibiting osteoclasts. Parathyroid hormone (C) raises serum calcium via bone resorption. Aldosterone (D) regulates sodium reabsorption and potassium excretion in the distal nephron.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The hormone secreted by the parathyroid glands that regulates calcium levels is:',o:['Thyroxine','Insulin','Calcitonin','Parathyroid hormone'],a:3,
e:`PTH, an 84-amino-acid polypeptide from parathyroid chief cells, raises serum calcium by stimulating osteoclastic bone resorption via RANKL upregulation, increasing renal tubular calcium reabsorption and activating renal 1-alpha-hydroxylase to generate active vitamin D enhancing intestinal calcium absorption.<br><br>PTH secretion is inversely regulated by ionised serum calcium through the calcium-sensing receptor on chief cells, enabling minute-to-minute homeostasis. Even a 0.1 mmol/L fall in ionised calcium triggers a detectable PTH rise within 1-2 minutes to restore normal levels.<br><br>Thyroxine (A) regulates basal metabolic rate. Insulin (B) regulates glucose disposal. Calcitonin (C) is thyroid-derived and lowers calcium by inhibiting osteoclasts, the opposite of PTH action.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Parathyroid hormone primarily acts to:',o:['Increase potassium','Increase serum calcium','Decrease serum calcium','Decrease phosphate'],a:1,
e:`PTH raises serum calcium through three coordinated mechanisms: stimulating osteoclastic bone resorption via RANKL releasing calcium from hydroxyapatite, increasing distal renal tubular calcium reabsorption, and activating 1-alpha-hydroxylase to generate active vitamin D that enhances intestinal calcium absorption over hours to days.<br><br>PTH simultaneously promotes renal phosphate excretion via inhibition of proximal tubular sodium-phosphate cotransporters, preventing serum phosphate elevation that would cause calcium phosphate precipitation in soft tissues as calcium is restored to normal levels.<br><br>Increasing potassium (A) is not a PTH effect. Decreasing serum calcium (C) is the action of calcitonin. Decreasing phosphate (D) is a secondary PTH effect but not the primary stated action on serum calcium.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The hypothalamic hormone that stimulates release of FSH and LH is:',o:['CRH','GHRH','TRH','GnRH'],a:3,
e:`GnRH, a decapeptide from hypothalamic arcuate nucleus neurons, stimulates FSH and LH from pituitary gonadotrophs by binding Gq-coupled receptors. Pulsatility is essential: slow pulses every 90-120 minutes preferentially stimulate FSH while faster pulses preferentially stimulate LH, providing cycle-phase-specific gonadotropin ratios essential for coordinated folliculogenesis and ovulation.<br><br>Continuous GnRH paradoxically suppresses gonadotropins by downregulating its own receptors through internalisation and degradation, the pharmacological basis of GnRH agonist therapy for endometriosis, fibroids, precocious puberty and IVF downregulation protocols.<br><br>CRH (A) stimulates ACTH from corticotrophs. GHRH (B) stimulates growth hormone from somatotrophs. TRH (C) stimulates TSH and prolactin. None stimulate FSH and LH from gonadotrophs.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Negative feedback in endocrine physiology refers to:',o:['Hormone stimulating its own secretion','Hormone inhibiting its own secretion indirectly','Hormone causing inflammation','Hormone destroying endocrine glands'],a:1,
e:`Negative feedback is the homeostatic mechanism where the product of an endocrine axis inhibits upstream components of that axis, preventing hormone accumulation. In the HPG axis, oestradiol and progesterone suppress hypothalamic GnRH and pituitary gonadotropins. In the HPT axis, T3 and T4 suppress TRH and TSH, maintaining levels within physiological ranges.<br><br>This feedback operates simultaneously at multiple levels: gonadal steroids act on both hypothalamic GnRH neurons and pituitary gonadotrophs, and thyroid hormones act on both hypothalamic TRH neurons and pituitary thyrotrophs, creating redundancy that makes each axis robust against single-site lesions.<br><br>Stimulating its own secretion (A) describes positive feedback, seen transiently before the LH surge. Causing inflammation (C) and destroying endocrine glands (D) are pathological processes unrelated to physiological endocrine feedback regulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Estrogen exerts negative feedback primarily on:',o:['Adrenal gland','Thyroid gland','Pineal gland','Hypothalamus and pituitary'],a:3,
e:`Oestradiol exerts negative feedback at both the hypothalamus, reducing GnRH pulse frequency and amplitude through actions on kisspeptin interneurons, and the anterior pituitary, reducing gonadotroph sensitivity to GnRH by downregulating GnRH receptors, suppressing FSH and LH throughout most of the menstrual cycle.<br><br>This dual-level negative feedback is clinically exploited by combined oral contraceptive pills: sustained oestrogen in the negative feedback concentration range reliably suppresses FSH and LH, prevents dominant follicle selection and abolishes the LH surge required for ovulation.<br><br>The adrenal gland (A) and thyroid gland (B) are regulated by their own separate axes. The pineal gland (C) secretes melatonin and has no major role in reproductive oestradiol feedback regulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'During mid-cycle of menstrual cycle, estrogen produces which feedback effect on LH secretion?',o:['Positive feedback','Negative feedback','Inhibitory feedback only','No effect'],a:0,
e:`When oestradiol exceeds approximately 200 pg/mL sustained for at least 50 hours in the late follicular phase, its effect switches from inhibitory to stimulatory positive feedback, dramatically amplifying GnRH and LH release to generate the mid-cycle LH surge. The mechanism involves increased GnRH receptor concentrations on pituitary gonadotrophs amplifying their LH response.<br><br>This is one of the few sustained positive feedback loops in endocrine physiology: oestradiol-driven LH secretion is self-amplifying until follicular rupture occurs, after which rising corpus luteum progesterone rapidly re-establishes negative feedback to terminate the surge.<br><br>Negative feedback (B) describes oestradiol's effect at lower follicular phase concentrations. Inhibitory feedback only (C) does not capture the mid-cycle positive switch. No effect (D) is incorrect as oestradiol is the primary driver of the LH surge.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Progesterone is mainly secreted by which ovarian structure after ovulation?',o:['Theca externa','Ovarian cortex','Corpus luteum','Graafian follicle'],a:2,
e:`After ovulation, the ruptured Graafian follicle undergoes luteinisation under ongoing LH stimulation: granulosa cells accumulate lipid droplets, the avascular granulosa layer vascularises via VEGF-driven angiogenesis, and 3beta-HSD expression rises, shifting steroid output from oestradiol to progesterone as the corpus luteum forms.<br><br>Corpus luteum progesterone peaks at approximately day 21, stabilising the secretory endometrium and suppressing uterine contractility. Without hCG rescue from an implanting blastocyst, regression occurs at days 26-28, progesterone falls and menstruation follows 1-2 days later.<br><br>Theca externa (A) is a structural support capsule with minimal steroidogenic activity. Ovarian cortex (B) houses follicles but is not itself a secretory unit. The Graafian follicle (D) is the pre-ovulatory follicle replaced by the corpus luteum after rupture.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The hormone that maintains the corpus luteum in early pregnancy is:',o:['hCG','Estrogen','Oxytocin','Prolactin'],a:0,
e:`hCG secreted by the implanting syncytiotrophoblast from approximately day 8-9 post-fertilisation binds LH receptors on the corpus luteum with equal affinity to LH, preventing luteolysis and sustaining progesterone production through 8-10 weeks until the luteo-placental shift establishes placental steroidogenesis.<br><br>hCG rises steeply from implantation, doubling approximately every 48 hours to peak at 8-10 weeks. Subnormal doubling of less than 66% rise in 48 hours suggests ectopic pregnancy or failing intrauterine pregnancy, making serial hCG measurement a key diagnostic tool in early pregnancy assessment.<br><br>Oestrogen (B) is produced by the corpus luteum but does not maintain it. Oxytocin (C) stimulates uterine contractions and milk ejection. Prolactin (D) supports lactation but does not rescue the corpus luteum from luteolysis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The hypothalamic hormone responsible for stimulating TSH secretion is:',o:['GnRH','CRH','GHRH','TRH'],a:3,
e:`TRH, a pyroglutamyl tripeptide from the paraventricular nucleus, is released into hypothalamo-hypophyseal portal blood and binds Gq-coupled receptors on anterior pituitary thyrotrophs, activating phospholipase C and increasing intracellular calcium to stimulate TSH synthesis and release within minutes.<br><br>TRH simultaneously stimulates prolactin from lactotrophs via the same receptor mechanism, explaining the association between primary hypothyroidism (elevated TRH) and hyperprolactinaemia with galactorrhoea, a combination that resolves completely with thyroxine replacement as TRH normalises.<br><br>GnRH (A) stimulates FSH and LH from gonadotrophs. CRH (B) stimulates ACTH from corticotrophs. GHRH (C) stimulates growth hormone from somatotrophs. None act on pituitary thyrotrophs to stimulate TSH secretion.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'In endocrine feedback control of thyroid function, increased levels of T3 and T4 inhibit:',o:['Ovaries','Parathyroid gland','Pituitary and hypothalamus','Adrenal gland'],a:2,
e:`T3 generated locally from T4 by type 2 deiodinase in pituitary thyrotrophs binds nuclear TRbeta2 receptors, suppressing TSH beta-subunit gene transcription and reducing TRH receptor expression. T3 and T4 also suppress TRH secretion from the hypothalamic paraventricular nucleus, providing dual-level negative feedback at both pituitary and hypothalamus.<br><br>This tight feedback makes serum TSH the most sensitive thyroid function test: TSH rises detectably in subclinical hypothyroidism before T4 falls below the reference range, and TSH suppresses below 0.1 mIU/L in hyperthyroidism or thyroxine overtreatment before T4 becomes clearly elevated.<br><br>The ovaries (A), parathyroid gland (B) and adrenal gland (D) are components of separate endocrine axes and are not primary targets of thyroid hormone negative feedback in the HPT axis.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Calcitonin is secreted from which cells of the thyroid gland?',o:['Chief cells','Follicular cells','Oxyphil cells','Parafollicular cells'],a:3,
e:`Parafollicular C cells are neural crest-derived cells scattered between thyroid follicles but not part of the follicular epithelium. They express the calcium-sensing receptor, detect rising serum calcium after meals and secrete calcitonin to oppose post-prandial hypercalcaemia by inhibiting osteoclastic bone resorption.<br><br>C cells are the cell of origin of medullary thyroid carcinoma, a neuroendocrine tumour secreting calcitonin as a tumour marker. Elevated basal calcitonin is used for MTC surveillance in MEN2 families where RET proto-oncogene mutations predispose to this malignancy with high penetrance.<br><br>Chief cells (A) are parathyroid cells that secrete PTH. Follicular cells (B) synthesise and secrete T3 and T4. Oxyphil cells (C) are parathyroid cells of uncertain function that do not secrete calcitonin.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Calcitonin primarily acts to:',o:['Decrease blood calcium','Increase blood calcium','Increase phosphate','Increase potassium'],a:0,
e:`Calcitonin lowers serum calcium by directly inhibiting osteoclastic bone resorption through calcitonin receptors on osteoclasts, reducing bone mineral dissolution within minutes. It also mildly reduces renal tubular calcium reabsorption, increasing urinary calcium excretion as an additional contribution to the hypocalcaemic effect.<br><br>Despite its defined mechanism, calcitonin's physiological significance in adults is limited: thyroidectomy does not cause hypercalcaemia and calcitonin-secreting medullary thyroid carcinomas do not produce hypocalcaemia, indicating strong PTH and vitamin D compensatory mechanisms dominate calcium homeostasis in the adult.<br><br>Increasing blood calcium (B) is the action of PTH and active vitamin D. Increasing phosphate (C) is not a primary calcitonin effect. Increasing potassium (D) is not a calcitonin action; potassium is regulated primarily by aldosterone and renal mechanisms.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone from the anterior pituitary stimulates adrenal cortex activity?',o:['LH','ACTH','FSH','TSH'],a:1,
e:`ACTH from anterior pituitary corticotrophs binds Gs-coupled MC2R receptors on adrenal cortical cells, activating PKA, which acutely upregulates StAR protein for cholesterol transport into mitochondria and chronically stimulates steroidogenic enzyme transcription in the zona fasciculata to drive cortisol synthesis and secretion.<br><br>ACTH also has trophic effects on adrenal cortical cell growth: chronic ACTH deficiency causes adrenal atrophy and cortisol insufficiency, while chronic ACTH excess as in Cushing's disease from a pituitary corticotroph adenoma causes bilateral adrenal hyperplasia with hypercortisolism.<br><br>LH (A) stimulates ovarian theca cells and testicular Leydig cells. FSH (C) stimulates ovarian granulosa cells. TSH (D) stimulates thyroid follicular cells. None act on the adrenal cortex to stimulate cortisol production.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During the menstrual cycle, the proliferative phase of the endometrium is mainly influenced by:',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','hCG','Prolactin'],a:0,
e:`Oestradiol from the growing dominant follicle binds endometrial ERalpha receptors, driving glandular and stromal cell division, angiogenesis and thickening from approximately 2 mm at menstruation to 8-12 mm at ovulation. Oestradiol also upregulates its own receptors and induces progesterone receptors, priming the endometrium for luteal phase secretory transformation.<br><br>The proliferative phase endometrium has straight tubular glands, compact stroma and thin-walled vessels on histology: features driven entirely by oestradiol. Absence of oestradiol as in premature ovarian insufficiency results in thin atrophic endometrium with irregular or absent bleeding.<br><br>Progesterone (B) drives the secretory phase after ovulation. hCG (C) maintains the corpus luteum. Prolactin (D) supports lactation without a primary role in endometrial proliferation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The secretory phase of the endometrium is mainly under the influence of:',o:['Oxytocin','FSH','Progesterone','Estrogen'],a:2,
e:`Progesterone from the corpus luteum transforms the oestrogen-primed endometrium into a secretory, receptive state: glands become tortuous and fill with glycogen-rich secretion, stroma undergoes predecidualisation with enlarged cells, and spiral arteries coil to create the implantation window around days 20-24 when endometrial pinopodes are expressed.<br><br>Mid-luteal progesterone peaks at approximately day 21, correlating with peak endometrial receptivity. Subnormal progesterone in luteal phase deficiency impairs this transformation, reducing implantation success, and is treated with vaginal progesterone supplementation in assisted reproduction cycles.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) stimulates uterine contractions. FSH (B) drives follicular development in the preceding follicular phase. Oestrogen (D) drives the proliferative phase. None produce the secretory transformation of the luteal phase endometrium.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The hormone that stimulates uterine contractions during labor is:',o:['FSH','Oxytocin','Prolactin','Estrogen'],a:1,
e:`Oxytocin binds Gq-coupled receptors on myometrium, activating phospholipase C and increasing intracellular calcium, which activates myosin light chain kinase driving smooth muscle contraction. Uterine oxytocin receptor density increases markedly near term under oestrogen stimulation, amplifying myometrial sensitivity to physiological oxytocin concentrations.<br><br>The Ferguson reflex provides positive feedback during labour: descent of the presenting part stretches the cervix, stimulating afferent signals to the hypothalamus that trigger oxytocin release, intensifying contractions and accelerating labour progression until delivery terminates the cervical stretch stimulus.<br><br>FSH (A) drives ovarian follicular development. Prolactin (C) supports lactation. Oestrogen (D) upregulates oxytocin receptors near term but does not directly contract the myometrium itself.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The hormone responsible for milk ejection reflex is:',o:['Prolactin','Progesterone','Oxytocin','Estrogen'],a:2,
e:`Suckling activates afferent neural pathways to the hypothalamus that trigger coordinated oxytocin release from posterior pituitary axon terminals. Oxytocin binds receptors on mammary myoepithelial cells, causing contraction that propels milk from alveoli through lactiferous ducts to the nipple, completing the milk ejection reflex within 30-60 seconds of suckling onset.<br><br>The reflex is psychologically conditioned and can be activated by infant crying or inhibited by stress via sympathetic-mediated reduction in local mammary blood flow, reducing oxytocin delivery to myoepithelial cells and impairing milk ejection despite adequate suckling stimulus at the breast.<br><br>Prolactin (A) synthesises milk but does not eject it. Progesterone (B) suppresses lactation during pregnancy. Oestrogen (D) promotes ductal growth without mediating the milk ejection reflex.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone inhibits prolactin secretion under normal conditions?',o:['TRH','Progesterone','Estrogen','Dopamine'],a:3,
e:`Dopamine from tuberoinfundibular neurons tonically inhibits lactotroph prolactin secretion by binding D2 receptors and suppressing cAMP production. Unlike all other anterior pituitary hormones which have dominant stimulatory hypothalamic regulators, prolactin has a dominant inhibitory regulator in dopamine, making it uniquely regulated among anterior pituitary hormones.<br><br>Any disruption of the pituitary stalk increases prolactin by removing dopaminergic inhibition while leaving other anterior pituitary hormones deficient. Dopamine antagonists such as metoclopramide, domperidone and antipsychotics cause hyperprolactinaemia; dopamine agonists such as cabergoline are first-line treatment for prolactinomas.<br><br>TRH (A) and oestrogen (C) both stimulate prolactin secretion as secondary positive regulators. Progesterone (B) suppresses lactation at the breast level, not prolactin secretion from the pituitary itself.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The pituitary gland lies in which bony structure?',o:['Jugular foramen','Foramen magnum','Sella turcica','Optic canal'],a:2,
e:`The pituitary sits within the sella turcica, a midline depression in the sphenoid bone at the skull base, covered by the diaphragma sellae with a central aperture through which the pituitary stalk passes to connect hypothalamus to pituitary. The optic chiasm lies directly superior to the sella.<br><br>This anatomical relationship explains classic pituitary macroadenoma presentation: superior expansion through the diaphragma sellae compresses the optic chiasm to produce bitemporal hemianopia. Transsphenoidal surgery via the sphenoid sinus floor is the preferred surgical approach to access sella contents.<br><br>Jugular foramen (A) transmits cranial nerves IX, X and XI. Foramen magnum (B) transmits the brainstem and vertebral arteries. Optic canal (D) transmits the optic nerve and ophthalmic artery.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which thyroid hormone is more biologically active?',o:['T4','Calcitonin','Thyroglobulin','T3'],a:3,
e:`T3 is three to four times more potent than T4 because it binds thyroid hormone receptors with greater affinity and slower dissociation, producing more robust transcriptional activation at thyroid hormone response elements. T3 is the predominant intracellular active form in all metabolically active tissues.<br><br>Most circulating T4 is peripherally converted to T3 by type 1 and type 2 deiodinase enzymes in liver, kidney and brain, making T4 a circulating prohormone with a 7-day half-life compared with T3's 1-day half-life. T3 is therefore not used for once-daily thyroid replacement due to peaks and troughs from its short half-life.<br><br>T4 (A) is the predominant thyroid secretion but is less potent at receptors. Calcitonin (B) is a calcium-lowering hormone from thyroid C cells. Thyroglobulin (C) is the intrafollicular storage protein from which T3 and T4 are cleaved.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The thyroid gland mainly secretes:',o:['Calcitonin','T4','T3','Thyroglobulin'],a:1,
e:`The thyroid secretes approximately 80-90% T4 and 10-20% T3 under TSH stimulation. T4 is synthesised by iodination of tyrosine residues on thyroglobulin catalysed by thyroid peroxidase, coupling two DIT molecules, then released by proteolytic cleavage from thyroglobulin and secreted into circulation bound to thyroxine-binding globulin.<br><br>T4 circulates with a 7-day half-life, providing a large stable reservoir for peripheral conversion to active T3 by deiodinase enzymes according to local tissue metabolic requirements, allowing fine-tuning of thyroid hormone action independent of moment-to-moment TSH variation throughout the day.<br><br>Calcitonin (A) is secreted by thyroid C cells, not follicular cells. Thyroglobulin (B) is an intrafollicular storage protein released into circulation only in thyroid pathology. T3 (C) is secreted in smaller amounts than T4 by the normal thyroid gland.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Parathyroid hormone acts primarily on:',o:['Bone and kidney','Pancreas','Liver','Heart'],a:0,
e:`PTH raises calcium through coordinated actions on bone, stimulating osteoclastic resorption via RANKL upregulation on osteoblasts, and kidney, increasing distal tubular calcium reabsorption and activating proximal tubular 1-alpha-hydroxylase to generate active vitamin D. Renal vitamin D activation also increases intestinal calcium absorption over a longer time course.<br><br>Intermittent low-dose PTH as teriparatide paradoxically stimulates net bone formation more than resorption by preferentially activating osteoblasts during brief pulses, forming the basis of anabolic osteoporosis therapy distinct from the resorptive effect of chronic continuous PTH elevation in primary hyperparathyroidism.<br><br>Pancreas (B), liver (C) and heart (D) lack meaningful PTH receptor expression and are not primary targets of PTH action on calcium homeostasis in normal physiology.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The endocrine gland most closely regulating reproductive hormone release is:',o:['Pancreas','Adrenal medulla','Hypothalamus','Thyroid gland'],a:2,
e:`The hypothalamus is the master regulator of reproduction: its pulsatile GnRH from the arcuate nucleus drives pituitary gonadotropin release, integrating signals from higher cortical centres, metabolic status via leptin and kisspeptin neurons, stress via cortisol and the HPA axis, and gonadal steroid feedback from the ovaries.<br><br>Disruption of hypothalamic GnRH pulsatility by weight loss, excessive exercise, stress or anorexia nervosa causes functional hypothalamic amenorrhoea via suppressed kisspeptin neuron activity, demonstrating how nutritional and psychological signals gate reproductive function through this single critical hypothalamic centre.<br><br>Pancreas (A) regulates glucose. Adrenal medulla (B) secretes catecholamines. Thyroid gland (D) regulates metabolic rate. None directly control reproductive hormone release through the HPG axis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis controls reproductive hormone regulation. Which hormone from hypothalamus initiates this axis?',o:['CRH','GnRH','GHRH','TRH'],a:1,
e:`GnRH, a decapeptide from the hypothalamic arcuate nucleus, initiates the HPG axis by binding Gq-coupled receptors on pituitary gonadotrophs, triggering FSH and LH synthesis. Slow GnRH pulses in the early follicular phase favour FSH while faster pulses near ovulation and in the luteal phase favour LH, allowing cycle-phase-specific gonadotropin ratios.<br><br>Kisspeptin neurons in the hypothalamic arcuate and anteroventral periventricular nuclei are the primary upstream activators of GnRH neurons, integrating sex steroid feedback, leptin, metabolic status and circadian signals to tune GnRH pulse frequency to each cycle phase. Kisspeptin receptor mutations cause Kallmann-like hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism.<br><br>CRH (A) initiates the HPA axis via ACTH secretion. GHRH (C) initiates growth hormone secretion from somatotrophs. TRH (D) initiates the HPT axis. None control the HPG axis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The anterior pituitary secretes which two gonadotropins essential for ovarian function?',o:['Oxytocin and ADH','Prolactin and GH','TSH and ACTH','FSH and LH'],a:3,
e:`FSH and LH are glycoprotein gonadotropins from pituitary gonadotrophs sharing an identical alpha subunit with distinct beta subunits conferring receptor specificity. FSH targets granulosa cells for follicular development and aromatase expression; LH targets theca cells for androgen production and at surge concentrations triggers ovulation and luteinisation to form the corpus luteum.<br><br>Recombinant FSH and LH preparations are used in IVF protocols for controlled ovarian stimulation, delivering specific physiological hormone combinations that mimic but intensify the normal cycle to recruit multiple follicles simultaneously for egg collection and maximise chances of successful embryo formation.<br><br>Oxytocin and ADH (A) are posterior pituitary peptides. Prolactin and GH (B) are non-gonadotropic anterior hormones. TSH and ACTH (C) are trophic hormones for thyroid and adrenal glands.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'FSH acts primarily on which ovarian cells?',o:['Granulosa cells','Theca externa','Stromal cells','Oocytes'],a:0,
e:`FSH receptors are expressed exclusively on granulosa cells within ovarian follicles. FSH binding via Gs-cAMP-PKA drives granulosa cell proliferation, aromatase induction, inhibin B secretion that selectively suppresses pituitary FSH, and LH receptor upregulation in preparation for the mid-cycle surge and subsequent luteinisation of granulosa cells.<br><br>The dominant follicle is defined by its superior FSH responsiveness: greater FSH-driven aromatase produces more oestradiol, which locally amplifies FSH receptor expression creating a positive intra-follicular loop. This dominant follicle then suppresses FSH via inhibin B, causing atresia of all other developing follicles with less efficient FSH responsiveness.<br><br>Theca externa (B) is a structural capsule without FSH receptors. Stromal cells (C) have minimal FSH responsiveness. Oocytes (D) do not express FSH receptors directly.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'LH primarily stimulates which ovarian cells to produce androgens?',o:['Oocytes','Stromal cells','Granulosa cells','Theca interna cells'],a:3,
e:`LH receptors on theca interna cells activate Gs-cAMP-PKA signalling, upregulating StAR protein for mitochondrial cholesterol transport and CYP17A1 for sequential conversion of cholesterol to androstenedione and testosterone. These androgens diffuse across the follicular basement membrane to granulosa cells where FSH-induced aromatase converts them to oestradiol.<br><br>In PCOS, chronically elevated LH combined with hyperinsulinaemia amplifies CYP17A1 activity, producing androgen excess that impairs granulosa cell aromatisation, creates an intra-follicular androgen-dominant environment and arrests follicular development, causing multifollicular ovarian morphology and anovulation characteristic of the syndrome.<br><br>Oocytes (A) and stromal cells (B) lack LH receptors for androgen production. Granulosa cells (C) express LH receptors only after FSH induction near ovulation, primarily for luteinisation rather than androgen production.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Estrogen production in ovarian follicles occurs due to:',o:['Direct cholesterol conversion','Protein synthesis','Aromatization of androgens','Glucose metabolism'],a:2,
e:`The two-cell two-gonadotropin model governs follicular oestrogen synthesis: LH drives theca cells to produce androstenedione and testosterone via CYP17A1, and FSH drives granulosa cells to aromatise these androgens to oestradiol via CYP19A1. Neither cell type alone can produce significant oestrogen, requiring both FSH and LH to act simultaneously on their respective cell types.<br><br>Clinical evidence includes women with aromatase deficiency who accumulate androgens but cannot produce oestrogens, developing virilisation and primary amenorrhoea despite normal gonadotropins. Aromatase inhibitors such as letrozole lower oestradiol by blocking this step and are used for endometriosis treatment and ovulation induction in PCOS.<br><br>Direct cholesterol conversion to oestrogen in a single step (A) does not occur. Protein synthesis (B) and glucose metabolism (D) are not steroidogenic pathways generating oestrogen in ovarian follicles.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone increases during breastfeeding and suppresses ovulation?',o:['ACTH','LH','TSH','Prolactin'],a:3,
e:`Each suckling episode inhibits hypothalamic dopamine release, allowing prolactin surges with every feeding. Chronically elevated prolactin suppresses kisspeptin neurons and GnRH pulsatility, reducing FSH and LH below the threshold required for dominant follicle development, creating lactational amenorrhoea as a natural postpartum contraceptive mechanism.<br><br>Lactational amenorrhoea is approximately 98% effective as contraception when breastfeeding is exclusive, the infant is under 6 months and menstruation has not returned: the three conditions of the Lactational Amenorrhoea Method. Return of menstruation or introduction of supplementary feeds signals declining prolactin and the return of ovulation.<br><br>ACTH (A) stimulates adrenal cortisol production. LH (B) is suppressed rather than elevated during breastfeeding. TSH (D) regulates thyroid hormone synthesis and is not elevated by the suckling stimulus.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The primary regulator of prolactin secretion is:',o:['Dopamine inhibition','Oxytocin stimulation','TRH stimulation','FSH stimulation'],a:0,
e:`Tonic dopaminergic inhibition is the dominant regulator of prolactin: tuberoinfundibular dopamine neurons continuously bind D2 receptors on lactotrophs, suppressing prolactin gene transcription and reducing basal secretion. Unlike every other anterior pituitary hormone, prolactin is primarily under inhibitory rather than stimulatory hypothalamic control.<br><br>This unique arrangement has important clinical implications: any lesion compressing or sectioning the pituitary stalk will elevate prolactin by interrupting dopaminergic inhibition while simultaneously reducing FSH, LH, TSH and ACTH by interrupting stimulatory releasing hormones, creating a characteristic pattern of mixed hypopituitarism with hyperprolactinaemia.<br><br>TRH (A) stimulates prolactin as a secondary positive regulator. Oxytocin (B) regulates smooth muscle in uterus and breast. FSH (D) stimulates follicular development with no influence on prolactin secretion.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'In pregnancy, estrogen is mainly produced by:',o:['Ovary only','Adrenal gland','Placenta','Pituitary gland'],a:2,
e:`From approximately 10 weeks, the syncytiotrophoblast's aromatase converts adrenal DHEAS from fetal and maternal sources to oestrogens. The dominant product is oestriol derived from fetal adrenal 16alpha-hydroxy-DHEAS, making oestriol a specific marker of fetoplacental unit integrity that falls when fetal wellbeing is compromised.<br><br>The fetoplacental unit concept reflects this collaboration: the placenta provides abundant aromatase but lacks CYP17A1 and cannot synthesise DHEAS independently, while the fetal adrenal produces DHEAS but cannot aromatise it. Both components must function normally for adequate gestational oestrogen production throughout pregnancy.<br><br>The ovary (A) contributes oestrogen early but is supplanted by the placenta after 10 weeks. The adrenal gland (B) provides DHEAS substrate but cannot aromatise it. The pituitary (D) does not produce oestrogen.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Progesterone during pregnancy is mainly produced by:',o:['Corpus luteum early and placenta later','Thyroid gland','Pituitary gland','Adrenal cortex only'],a:0,
e:`The luteo-placental shift occurs at 8-10 weeks: initially the corpus luteum produces sufficient progesterone sustained by hCG, then the syncytiotrophoblast assumes progesterone synthesis by converting maternal LDL cholesterol to pregnenolone via CYP11A1 and then to progesterone via 3beta-HSD, independently of any fetal contribution.<br><br>Placental progesterone rises steadily from 25 ng/mL at 8 weeks to 150-200 ng/mL at term, maintaining uterine quiescence by suppressing myometrial gap junction formation, reducing oxytocin receptor expression and directly relaxing smooth muscle while also preventing immune rejection of the semi-allogeneic conceptus.<br><br>Thyroid gland (B), pituitary gland (C) and adrenal cortex (D) alone cannot provide the sustained high progesterone concentrations required to maintain pregnancy throughout gestation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Human placental lactogen primarily affects:',o:['Parathyroid gland','Maternal metabolism','Thyroid function','Calcium metabolism'],a:1,
e:`hPL shifts maternal metabolism to prioritise fetal nutrient supply: it promotes maternal lipolysis increasing free fatty acids as the primary maternal fuel, induces peripheral insulin resistance redirecting glucose to the fetus, and has weak lactogenic effects preparing breast tissue for postpartum lactation. hPL concentrations correlate directly with placental mass, peaking in the third trimester.<br><br>Gestational diabetes results partly from hPL-driven insulin resistance exceeding pancreatic beta cell reserve capacity. hPL historically was used as an indirect marker of placental function, falling in placental insufficiency before clinical features of fetal compromise became apparent on other monitoring tests.<br><br>Parathyroid gland (A) and calcium metabolism (D) are regulated by PTHrP from the placenta, not hPL. Thyroid function (B) in early pregnancy is regulated by hCG via TSH receptor cross-reactivity.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The hypothalamus controls pituitary secretion through:',o:['Insulin','Renin','Calcitonin','Releasing hormones'],a:3,
e:`The hypothalamus controls anterior pituitary secretion via peptide releasing and inhibiting hormones delivered through the hypothalamo-hypophyseal portal blood: GnRH for FSH/LH, TRH for TSH/prolactin, CRH for ACTH, GHRH for GH, somatostatin inhibiting GH and TSH, and dopamine inhibiting prolactin. These reach the pituitary at concentrations 10-100 times systemic blood levels.<br><br>The posterior pituitary is controlled differently: it is directly innervated by hypothalamic magnocellular axons from supraoptic and paraventricular nuclei rather than receiving hormonal signals via portal blood, storing and releasing ADH and oxytocin as neural secretory products via axonal action potentials.<br><br>Insulin (A), renin (B) and calcitonin (C) are hormones of the pancreas, kidney and thyroid respectively and do not control anterior pituitary secretion through the hypothalamo-hypophyseal portal system.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The portal circulation connecting hypothalamus and pituitary is called:',o:['Coronary circulation','Pulmonary circulation','Hypothalamo-hypophyseal portal system','Systemic circulation'],a:2,
e:`The hypothalamo-hypophyseal portal system consists of a primary capillary plexus in the median eminence of the hypothalamus, portal veins running down the pituitary stalk and a secondary capillary plexus in the anterior pituitary sinusoids. Hypothalamic releasing hormones reach anterior pituitary cells at concentrations 10-100 times higher than in systemic blood.<br><br>This portal circulation enables effective hormonal communication between hypothalamus and pituitary: the short portal route concentrates tiny amounts of releasing hormones into a small vascular space, enabling precise hormonal control of anterior pituitary secretion with negligible spillover into systemic circulation and minimal peripheral side effects.<br><br>Coronary (A) and pulmonary (B) circulations serve cardiac and pulmonary needs. The systemic circulation (D) delivers hormones to peripheral tissues at far lower concentrations than the portal system achieves at the pituitary level.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Hyperprolactinemia commonly results in:',o:['Hypertension','Hyperthyroidism','Hypercalcemia','Amenorrhea'],a:3,
e:`Hyperprolactinaemia suppresses GnRH pulsatility through enhanced hypothalamic opioidergic tone and kisspeptin neuron inhibition, reducing FSH and LH, impairing follicular development and abolishing the LH surge. The result is anovulatory amenorrhoea with chronically low oestradiol and elevated prolactin on investigation.<br><br>Additional features include galactorrhoea in approximately 50% of women, reduced libido, dyspareunia from vaginal atrophy and progressive bone density loss from chronic hypo-oestrogenism. Cabergoline, a D2 dopamine receptor agonist, normalises prolactin and restores ovulatory cycles in over 90% of prolactinoma patients within weeks.<br><br>Hypertension (A), hyperthyroidism (B) and hypercalcaemia (C) are not caused by hyperprolactinaemia, which has no direct action on blood pressure, thyroid follicular cells or calcium homeostasis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Thyroid hormones are synthesized from which amino acid?',o:['Tyrosine','Lysine','Glycine','Tryptophan'],a:0,
e:`T3 and T4 are synthesised from tyrosine residues within thyroglobulin: thyroid peroxidase iodinates tyrosines to form monoiodotyrosine and diiodotyrosine, then couples two diiodotyrosines to form T4 or one monoiodotyrosine with one diiodotyrosine to form T3. These are stored within thyroglobulin in follicular colloid until TSH stimulates proteolytic release.<br><br>Iodine deficiency impairs monoiodotyrosine and diiodotyrosine formation, reducing T3 and T4 synthesis, elevating TSH via loss of negative feedback. Chronic TSH excess drives follicular cell hypertrophy and hyperplasia producing goitre. Carbimazole and propylthiouracil treat hyperthyroidism by inhibiting thyroid peroxidase and thus iodination of tyrosines.<br><br>Lysine (B), glycine (C) and tryptophan (D) are not precursors for thyroid hormone synthesis. Tryptophan is the amino acid precursor for serotonin and melatonin synthesis.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Parathyroid hormone secretion is mainly regulated by:',o:['Potassium levels','Sodium levels','Serum calcium levels','Glucose levels'],a:2,
e:`PTH secretion is inversely regulated by ionised serum calcium through the calcium-sensing receptor on parathyroid chief cells. Falling ionised calcium reduces CaSR constitutive activity and releases PTH secretion from inhibition within seconds, maintaining ionised calcium within the tight physiological range of 1.1-1.3 mmol/L essential for normal neuromuscular function.<br><br>Gain-of-function CaSR mutations cause autosomal dominant hypocalcaemia by making the receptor constitutively active, suppressing PTH inappropriately. Loss-of-function CaSR mutations cause familial hypocalciuric hypercalcaemia, a benign condition mimicking primary hyperparathyroidism but distinguishable by low urinary calcium excretion and mild hypercalcaemia.<br><br>Potassium (A), sodium (B) and glucose (D) do not directly regulate PTH secretion through the calcium-sensing receptor or other established physiological mechanisms.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone increases bone resorption to raise serum calcium levels?',o:['Estrogen','Insulin','Calcitonin','Parathyroid hormone'],a:3,
e:`PTH stimulates bone resorption by increasing RANKL expression on osteoblasts, activating osteoclasts via RANK-RANKL binding to dissolve hydroxyapatite mineral and degrade collagen matrix, releasing calcium and phosphate. This osteoclast activation is an indirect PTH effect as osteoclasts themselves do not express functional PTH receptors.<br><br>Paradoxically, intermittent low-dose PTH as teriparatide stimulates net bone formation more than resorption by preferentially activating osteoblasts during brief PTH pulses, forming the basis of anabolic osteoporosis therapy. This contrasts with chronic continuous PTH elevation in primary hyperparathyroidism which predominantly drives resorption and cortical bone loss.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) inhibits osteoclastic activity and protects bone density. Insulin (B) has mild anabolic bone effects. Calcitonin (C) inhibits osteoclasts and lowers calcium, the opposite action to PTH.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Thyroid hormones increase:',o:['Basal metabolic rate','Gastric acid secretion','Calcium levels directly','Insulin secretion'],a:0,
e:`T3 and T4 bind nuclear TRalpha and TRbeta receptors at thyroid hormone response elements, upregulating genes for Na/K-ATPase, mitochondrial uncoupling proteins, beta-adrenergic receptors and metabolic enzymes in virtually all tissues, increasing oxygen consumption and heat production. This accounts for approximately 30% of resting energy expenditure.<br><br>The clinical consequences of thyroid hormone excess follow directly from metabolic stimulation: weight loss despite good appetite from increased metabolic rate; tachycardia and palpitations from upregulated beta-adrenergic receptors; heat intolerance and sweating from increased thermogenesis; proximal muscle weakness from increased Na/K-ATPase energy expenditure.<br><br>Gastric acid secretion (B) is regulated by gastrin and histamine. Thyroid hormones do not directly raise serum calcium (C). Insulin secretion (D) is regulated by blood glucose via pancreatic beta cells, not thyroid hormones.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The endocrine feedback loop between hypothalamus, pituitary, and thyroid gland is called:',o:['Hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis','Hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis','Hypothalamic-pituitary-renal axis','Hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis'],a:1,
e:`The HPT axis operates via negative feedback: TRH stimulates TSH, which stimulates T3/T4 production; elevated T3/T4 suppress both TRH from the hypothalamus and TSH from the pituitary. TSH is the most sensitive clinical measure: subclinical hypothyroidism elevates TSH before T4 falls below the reference range, while subclinical hyperthyroidism suppresses TSH before T4 rises above range.<br><br>The logarithmic relationship between TSH and free T4 makes TSH an enormously amplified and sensitive detector of even minor changes in circulating thyroid hormone: a twofold change in free T4 causes approximately a 100-fold change in TSH, explaining the high sensitivity and clinical utility of TSH as the primary screening and monitoring test.<br><br>HPA axis (A) involves CRH-ACTH-cortisol. HPG axis (D) involves GnRH-FSH/LH-gonadal steroids. Hypothalamic-pituitary-renal axis (C) does not exist as a classical endocrine feedback loop.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The hormone that plays a major role in uterine sensitivity to oxytocin during labor is:',o:['Progesterone','Prolactin','hCG','Estrogen'],a:3,
e:`Oestrogen markedly increases myometrial oxytocin receptor expression near term by upregulating oxytocin receptor gene transcription, increasing receptor protein density on myometrial cell membranes. The progressive rise in the oestrogen:progesterone ratio during the final weeks of pregnancy converts the myometrium from an unresponsive to a highly contractile organ.<br><br>Oestrogen also promotes myometrial gap junction formation via connexin 43 upregulation, enabling electrical coupling between myometrial cells that coordinates synchronised contraction waves across the entire uterus during active labour, preventing incoordinate uterine action.<br><br>Progesterone (A) suppresses oxytocin receptor expression and uterine contractility throughout pregnancy. Prolactin (B) has no direct myometrial sensitising effect. hCG (C) peaks at 10 weeks, far before the onset of labour at term.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During endocrine regulation of reproduction, the hypothalamus secretes GnRH in a pulsatile manner which stimulates the anterior pituitary to release FSH and LH. Continuous administration of GnRH paradoxically suppresses gonadotropin release due to receptor down-regulation. Which physiological principle explains this phenomenon?',o:['Hormonal synergy','Receptor desensitization','Hormonal amplification','Negative feedback inhibition'],a:1,
e:`Continuous GnRH internalises and degrades GnRH receptors on pituitary gonadotrophs through beta-arrestin recruitment and clathrin-mediated endocytosis, removing surface receptors and abolishing cAMP-PKA signalling. After an initial 1-2 week gonadotropin flare, FSH and LH fall to near-castrate levels and remain suppressed as long as continuous stimulation continues.<br><br>GnRH agonist implants such as goserelin provide continuous depot stimulation for 1-3 months, achieving medical gonadal suppression for endometriosis pain, fibroid shrinkage and prostate cancer without surgery. GnRH antagonists such as cetrorelix achieve immediate suppression without the initial flare by competitive receptor blockade rather than internalisation.<br><br>Hormonal synergy (A) describes additive hormone effects. Hormonal amplification (C) describes cascade signal amplification. Negative feedback (D) describes product inhibiting precursor secretion, not receptor internalisation from continuous agonist exposure.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone from the hypothalamus stimulates secretion of prolactin from the anterior pituitary under certain physiological conditions?',o:['TRH','GnRH','CRH','GHRH'],a:0,
e:`TRH stimulates both TSH from thyrotrophs and prolactin from lactotrophs via the same Gq-coupled TRH receptor activating phospholipase C and increasing intracellular calcium. In normal physiology, TRH stimulation of prolactin is masked by dominant dopaminergic inhibition from tuberoinfundibular neurons keeping basal prolactin low.<br><br>When TRH rises chronically as in primary hypothyroidism, prolactin secretion increases significantly to cause hyperprolactinaemia and galactorrhoea, a combination that resolves completely with thyroxine replacement as the HPT axis normalises and TRH returns to physiological concentrations.<br><br>GnRH (B) stimulates FSH and LH from gonadotrophs. CRH (C) stimulates ACTH from corticotrophs. GHRH (D) stimulates growth hormone from somatotrophs. None stimulate prolactin simultaneously with TSH.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The primary hormone responsible for regulation of serum phosphate levels along with calcium is:',o:['Thyroxine','Parathyroid hormone','Insulin','Aldosterone'],a:1,
e:`PTH regulates both calcium and phosphate: it raises serum calcium while lowering serum phosphate by inhibiting sodium-phosphate cotransporters NaPi-IIa and NaPi-IIc in the proximal renal tubule, increasing phosphate excretion in urine. This phosphaturic effect prevents serum phosphate from rising alongside released calcium, avoiding soft tissue calcium phosphate precipitation.<br><br>FGF-23 from osteocytes is a second important phosphaturic hormone that independently inhibits renal phosphate reabsorption and suppresses 1-alpha-hydroxylase, reducing active vitamin D synthesis. FGF-23 excess in X-linked hypophosphataemia and chronic kidney disease causes refractory hypophosphataemia and osteomalacia.<br><br>Thyroxine (A) regulates metabolic rate. Insulin (C) regulates glucose. Aldosterone (D) regulates sodium and potassium. None primarily regulate serum phosphate alongside calcium homeostasis.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'In the hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis, thyroid stimulating hormone acts directly on:',o:['Thyroid follicular cells','Parathyroid glands','Adrenal cortex','Pancreatic islets'],a:0,
e:`TSH binds Gs-coupled TSH receptors exclusively on thyroid follicular cells, activating adenylate cyclase and stimulating iodide uptake via the basolateral sodium-iodide symporter, thyroid peroxidase activity for organification, thyroglobulin synthesis and endocytosis, and finally proteolytic T3 and T4 release from the thyroglobulin molecule into circulation.<br><br>The TSH receptor is also targeted by thyroid-stimulating immunoglobulins in Graves' disease, which mimic TSH and cause unregulated thyroid hormone overproduction not subject to T3/T4 negative feedback suppression. This explains the autonomous thyrotoxicosis of Graves' disease that does not respond to reduced TSH via the usual negative feedback mechanism.<br><br>Parathyroid glands (B), adrenal cortex (C) and pancreatic islets (D) do not express TSH receptors and are not targets of TSH action in normal physiology.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone produced by the thyroid gland lowers serum calcium levels by inhibiting osteoclastic activity?',o:['Parathyroid hormone','Calcitonin','Thyroxine','Cortisol'],a:1,
e:`Calcitonin from thyroid C cells lowers serum calcium by directly inhibiting osteoclast activity through calcitonin receptors on osteoclast membranes, reducing bone-resorbing activity and mineral dissolution. Calcitonin also mildly reduces renal tubular calcium reabsorption, contributing a renal component to the hypocalcaemic effect.<br><br>Salmon calcitonin, approximately 40-50 times more potent than human calcitonin due to greater receptor binding affinity, is used clinically as subcutaneous or nasal calcitonin for hypercalcaemia of malignancy and Paget's disease, providing rapid calcium-lowering as a bridging treatment before bisphosphonate onset of action.<br><br>PTH (A) raises calcium by stimulating osteoclasts, the opposite action. Thyroxine (C) regulates metabolic rate without direct osteoclast inhibition. Cortisol (D) reduces intestinal calcium absorption long-term but is not a direct osteoclast inhibitor.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The primary stimulus for secretion of parathyroid hormone is:',o:['Increased serum calcium','Increased sodium','Increased phosphate','Decreased serum calcium'],a:3,
e:`Falling ionised serum calcium activates the calcium-sensing receptor on parathyroid chief cells by reducing constitutive CaSR activity, releasing PTH secretion from tonic inhibition within seconds. This rapid response is essential because severe hypocalcaemia causes tetany, laryngospasm and seizures, as seen acutely after inadvertent parathyroid removal during thyroidectomy.<br><br>The hypocalcaemia of vitamin D deficiency illustrates this stimulus-response relationship: low intestinal calcium absorption lowers serum ionised calcium, chronically stimulating PTH secretion and causing secondary hyperparathyroidism with elevated PTH, increased bone resorption but normal calcium, a state of compensated but not corrected mineral homeostasis.<br><br>Increased serum calcium (A) suppresses PTH via CaSR activation. Increased phosphate (C) acts indirectly by chelating ionised calcium. Sodium (D) has no established direct role in PTH regulation.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which anterior pituitary hormone stimulates the thyroid gland to synthesize and release T3 and T4?',o:['TSH','ACTH','FSH','Prolactin'],a:0,
e:`TSH activates the sodium-iodide symporter, thyroid peroxidase, thyroglobulin gene expression and the proteolytic release cascade, stimulating all steps of thyroid hormone synthesis and secretion. TSH also promotes follicular cell proliferation via MAP kinase and PI3K-Akt pathways, maintaining thyroid mass proportionate to metabolic requirements throughout life.<br><br>The TSH receptor is uniquely vulnerable to autoimmune stimulation: thyroid-stimulating immunoglobulins in Graves' disease and TSH-receptor blocking antibodies in Hashimoto's thyroiditis target the same receptor to cause hyperthyroidism and hypothyroidism respectively, demonstrating how one receptor mediates diametrically opposing clinical outcomes depending on antibody function.<br><br>ACTH (B) targets adrenal cortex. FSH (C) targets ovarian granulosa cells. Prolactin (D) targets mammary tissue and gonads. None stimulate thyroid hormone synthesis or secretion.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'During endocrine regulation, high circulating levels of thyroid hormones suppress secretion of TSH by which mechanism?',o:['Positive feedback','Hormonal synergy','Negative feedback','Feed-forward stimulation'],a:2,
e:`T3 generated locally from T4 by type 2 deiodinase in pituitary thyrotrophs binds nuclear TRbeta2 receptors, suppressing TSH beta-subunit gene transcription and reducing TRH receptor expression on thyrotroph membranes. T3 also directly suppresses TRH secretion from the hypothalamic paraventricular nucleus, providing dual-level negative feedback at both hypothalamus and pituitary.<br><br>TSH suppression therapy after differentiated thyroid cancer surgery exploits this negative feedback: exogenous thyroxine is dosed to maintain TSH below 0.1 mIU/L, preventing residual TSH-responsive tumour cells from receiving growth stimulus while monitoring thyroglobulin as a tumour marker for recurrence.<br><br>Positive feedback (A) describes oestradiol's LH-stimulating effect. Hormonal synergy (B) describes combined hormone actions. Feed-forward stimulation (D) is not a physiological mechanism in the HPT axis.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The posterior pituitary hormone that plays a role in parturition and milk ejection is:',o:['ADH','Oxytocin','Prolactin','ACTH'],a:1,
e:`Oxytocin mediates both parturition and milk ejection through action on smooth muscle: in labour it binds myometrial Gq-coupled receptors upregulated by oestrogen near term, driving uterine contractions; postpartum it contracts mammary myoepithelial cells during suckling to eject milk through lactiferous ducts.<br><br>Syntocinon (synthetic oxytocin) is given intravenously to induce or augment labour when natural uterine activity is insufficient. Atosiban, a competitive oxytocin receptor antagonist, reduces myometrial contractility and is used as a tocolytic to delay preterm labour between 24-33 weeks gestation when delivery carries significant neonatal morbidity.<br><br>ADH (A) regulates renal water reabsorption via collecting duct aquaporin-2 channels. Prolactin (C) synthesises milk but does not stimulate contractions or eject milk. ACTH (D) is an anterior pituitary hormone with no uterine or mammary role.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Prolactin secretion increases during pregnancy mainly due to stimulation by:',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Testosterone','Cortisol'],a:0,
e:`Oestradiol directly stimulates prolactin gene transcription in anterior pituitary lactotrophs, promotes lactotroph cell proliferation and reduces tuberoinfundibular dopaminergic tone, causing the pituitary to enlarge approximately 135% during pregnancy. Prolactin rises progressively to reach 200-400 ng/mL at term.<br><br>Despite very high prolactin levels throughout pregnancy, milk production does not occur because progesterone suppresses prolactin receptor signalling at the mammary epithelial cell level. After delivery, progesterone withdrawal releases this block, allowing prolactin to initiate full lactogenesis within 1-3 days while prolactin levels begin to fall from their gestational peak.<br><br>Progesterone (B) suppresses lactation at the breast level, not prolactin secretion. Testosterone (C) inhibits lactotroph function. Cortisol (D) stimulates milk protein synthesis but is not the primary driver of the gestational prolactin rise.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone inhibits secretion of GnRH when circulating levels become sufficiently high in the luteal phase?',o:['Calcitonin','Prolactin','Oxytocin','Progesterone'],a:3,
e:`High luteal phase progesterone reduces GnRH pulse frequency by suppressing kisspeptin neuron activity in the hypothalamic arcuate nucleus and reduces pituitary sensitivity to each GnRH pulse. Combined with oestradiol negative feedback, this maintains low FSH and LH throughout the luteal phase, preventing premature recruitment of new follicles before the current cycle completes.<br><br>The progesterone requirement for effective GnRH suppression requires prior oestrogen priming of hypothalamic and pituitary targets, explaining why progesterone alone is less effective at suppressing ovulation than combined oestrogen and progesterone formulations used in oral contraceptive pills.<br><br>Prolactin (B) suppresses GnRH through opioidergic mechanisms distinct from progesterone's kisspeptin pathway. Oxytocin (C) and calcitonin (D) do not regulate the GnRH pulse generator in the luteal phase of the menstrual cycle.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Thyroid hormones exert their metabolic effects primarily by:',o:['Inhibiting mitochondrial function','Activating membrane ion channels','Binding to nuclear receptors and altering gene transcription','Increasing insulin secretion'],a:2,
e:`T3 binds nuclear TRalpha and TRbeta receptors constitutively bound to thyroid hormone response elements in target gene promoters. In the absence of T3, these receptors recruit transcriptional corepressors to silence gene expression; T3 binding displaces corepressors and recruits coactivators, converting the receptor to a transcriptional activator upregulating hundreds of metabolically important genes.<br><br>This nuclear mechanism accounts for the slow onset of thyroid hormone metabolic effects over hours to days, contrasting with rapid membrane receptor-mediated actions of hormones like glucagon and adrenaline. Thyroid hormones also have non-genomic rapid actions through plasma membrane and mitochondrial receptors, but gene transcription is the dominant mechanism.<br><br>Thyroid hormones stimulate, not inhibit, mitochondrial function (A). Membrane ion channel activation (B) characterises rapidly-acting peptide hormones. Insulin secretion (D) is regulated by blood glucose via pancreatic beta cells.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone from the anterior pituitary directly stimulates growth of thyroid follicular cells?',o:['FSH','TSH','ACTH','LH'],a:1,
e:`TSH exerts dual acute stimulatory and chronic trophic effects on thyroid follicular cells: acutely it drives hormone synthesis and secretion via cAMP-PKA; chronically it promotes follicular cell hypertrophy and hyperplasia via MAP kinase and PI3K-Akt pathways, maintaining thyroid gland mass proportionate to metabolic requirements throughout life.<br><br>This trophic effect underlies goitre formation in iodine deficiency and Hashimoto's thyroiditis where TSH rises from loss of negative feedback, and forms the rationale for TSH suppression therapy after differentiated thyroid cancer resection to prevent TSH-driven growth of any residual TSH-responsive micrometastatic tumour cells.<br><br>FSH (A) stimulates ovarian granulosa cells and testicular Sertoli cells. ACTH (B) stimulates adrenal cortical cells. LH (D) stimulates ovarian theca cells and testicular Leydig cells.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Excess prolactin secretion commonly leads to which reproductive disturbance in women?',o:['Menorrhagia','Polymenorrhea','Dysmenorrhea','Amenorrhea'],a:3,
e:`Hyperprolactinaemia causes amenorrhoea by suppressing GnRH pulse frequency through enhanced opioidergic tone and kisspeptin neuron inhibition, reducing FSH and LH below the threshold required for dominant follicle development and abolishing the LH surge, resulting in anovulation with either hypo-oestrogenic amenorrhoea or unopposed oestrogen depending on prolactin level.<br><br>Hyperprolactinaemia is the most common correctable hormonal cause of secondary amenorrhoea in women of reproductive age. Cabergoline, a selective D2 receptor agonist dosed once or twice weekly, normalises prolactin in over 90% of prolactinoma patients and restores ovulatory cycles within weeks, enabling pregnancy in women seeking fertility.<br><br>Menorrhagia (A), polymenorrhoea (B) and dysmenorrhoea (C) imply ovulatory or uterine structural pathology rather than the anovulatory suppression and amenorrhoea caused by hyperprolactinaemia.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The main physiological role of calcitonin in humans is to:',o:['Increase calcium reabsorption in kidney','Inhibit osteoclastic bone resorption','Increase intestinal calcium absorption','Stimulate parathyroid hormone secretion'],a:1,
e:`Calcitonin inhibits osteoclastic bone resorption via calcitonin receptors on osteoclast membranes, reducing bone mineral dissolution rapidly in response to post-prandial hypercalcaemia. It may serve primarily to prevent excessive bone resorption during periods of calcium loading, acting as an acute buffer against hypercalcaemia until PTH adjustments restore long-term balance.<br><br>Despite this mechanism, calcitonin's physiological importance in adults is limited: thyroidectomy causing near-zero calcitonin does not produce hypercalcaemia, and pharmacological calcitonin from medullary thyroid carcinoma does not cause hypocalcaemia. Calcitonin may be more physiologically important in children during periods of rapid bone growth and mineralisation.<br><br>Increasing renal calcium reabsorption (A) and intestinal calcium absorption (C) are actions of PTH and active vitamin D. Stimulating PTH secretion (D) is the opposite implication of calcitonin's calcium-lowering effect.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone released from hypothalamus regulates secretion of TSH and prolactin simultaneously?',o:['TRH','GnRH','CRH','Dopamine'],a:0,
e:`TRH stimulates both TSH from thyrotrophs and prolactin from lactotrophs via the same Gq-coupled TRH receptor, activating phospholipase C, generating IP3 and DAG, increasing intracellular calcium and activating PKC to drive secretory granule exocytosis from both cell types within minutes of portal TRH delivery.<br><br>The dual prolactin and TSH stimulatory action of TRH creates the clinically important association between primary hypothyroidism and hyperprolactinaemia: elevated TRH from loss of T3/T4 negative feedback simultaneously raises both TSH and prolactin, causing galactorrhoea and amenorrhoea that resolve within weeks of thyroxine replacement as TRH normalises.<br><br>GnRH (A) stimulates FSH and LH. CRH (C) stimulates ACTH. Dopamine (D) inhibits rather than stimulates prolactin and has no direct effect on TSH. None regulate both TSH and prolactin simultaneously.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During the menstrual cycle, which hormone inhibits LH and FSH secretion through negative feedback in the luteal phase?',o:['Prolactin','Estrogen','Oxytocin','Progesterone'],a:3,
e:`High corpus luteum progesterone reduces GnRH pulse frequency by suppressing hypothalamic kisspeptin neuron activity, reducing pituitary sensitivity to each GnRH pulse, and combined with oestradiol negative feedback, maintains FSH and LH well below the threshold required for new follicular development throughout the 14-day luteal phase.<br><br>Combined oral contraceptive pills replicate this luteal phase hormonal milieu: sustained progestogen and oestrogen in combination maintain negative feedback on the hypothalamus and pituitary throughout the active pill cycle, preventing GnRH pulse recovery and follicular recruitment even during pill-free intervals of up to 7 days.<br><br>Oestrogen (B) contributes negative feedback but high progesterone is the dominant luteal suppressor. Oxytocin (C) and prolactin (D) do not primarily regulate FSH and LH via the luteal phase negative feedback pathway.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The pituitary hormone that indirectly influences thyroid hormone production by regulating iodine uptake in the thyroid gland is:',o:['ACTH','Prolactin','TSH','LH'],a:2,
e:`TSH upregulates the sodium-iodide symporter on the basolateral membrane of thyroid follicular cells, actively concentrating iodide 20-50 times above plasma levels in a process called iodide trapping. This active transport step is rate-limiting for thyroid hormone synthesis when dietary iodine is marginal, explaining why iodine deficiency predominantly affects individuals with the highest TSH stimulation.<br><br>The NIS is also the molecular target of radioactive iodine therapy: NIS-mediated iodide concentration delivers lethal radiation selectively to thyroid tissue. Withholding thyroxine before radioiodine ablation maximises TSH and thus NIS expression to enhance radioiodine uptake and treatment efficacy.<br><br>ACTH (A) regulates adrenal cortisol. Prolactin (B) regulates lactation. LH (D) regulates gonadal steroidogenesis. None regulate thyroidal iodide trapping via the sodium-iodide symporter.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone secreted by the posterior pituitary is primarily involved in regulation of water balance but is also synthesized in the hypothalamus?',o:['ADH','Oxytocin','Prolactin','TSH'],a:0,
e:`ADH (arginine vasopressin) is synthesised in hypothalamic supraoptic and paraventricular nuclei, transported to the posterior pituitary for storage and released in response to rising plasma osmolality detected by hypothalamic osmoreceptors or reduced blood volume detected by baroreceptors. ADH binds V2 receptors in the renal collecting duct, stimulating aquaporin-2 channel insertion to increase water reabsorption.<br><br>Central diabetes insipidus from ADH deficiency causes large volumes of dilute urine and polydipsia. SIADH from inappropriate ADH excess causes water retention and dilutional hyponatraemia, seen in small cell lung cancer, CNS disorders and many medications, treated by fluid restriction or vasopressin V2 receptor antagonists called vaptans.<br><br>Oxytocin (B) is also hypothalamic-synthesised but mediates uterine contraction and milk ejection. Prolactin (C) and TSH (D) are anterior pituitary hormones not stored in the posterior pituitary.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'In endocrine physiology, pulsatile secretion of GnRH is essential because continuous secretion would:',o:['Increase LH secretion continuously','Suppress gonadotropin release','Increase estrogen synthesis','Increase progesterone secretion'],a:1,
e:`Continuous GnRH causes ligand-induced internalisation and degradation of GnRH receptors through beta-arrestin recruitment and clathrin-mediated endocytosis, removing surface receptors and abolishing cAMP-PKA signalling. After an initial 1-2 week gonadotropin flare, FSH and LH fall to near-castrate levels and remain suppressed as long as continuous stimulation continues.<br><br>GnRH agonist implants such as goserelin provide continuous depot stimulation for 1-3 months, achieving medical gonadal suppression for prostate cancer, endometriosis, fibroid shrinkage and IVF downregulation without surgical gonadectomy. GnRH antagonists achieve immediate suppression without the initial flare by competitive blockade rather than receptor internalisation.<br><br>Continuous GnRH does not sustain increased LH (A), oestrogen synthesis (C) or progesterone (D); all fall progressively as receptor downregulation advances beyond the initial brief flare period.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'In reproductive endocrine physiology, the hypothalamus regulates pituitary secretion through pulsatile release of GnRH, which stimulates the anterior pituitary to release FSH and LH. If hypothalamic GnRH secretion is disrupted, which immediate endocrine effect would most likely occur?',o:['Increased prolactin secretion','Increased parathyroid hormone secretion','Increased thyroid hormone production','Decreased FSH and LH secretion'],a:3,
e:`Loss of GnRH pulsatility removes the primary stimulus for gonadotropin synthesis, causing FSH and LH to fall within hours to days, followed by hypo-oestrogenism, anovulation and amenorrhoea. This is the mechanism of functional hypothalamic amenorrhoea from weight loss, excessive exercise or stress, and of Kallmann syndrome from congenital GnRH neuron migration failure requiring pulsatile GnRH pump therapy.<br><br>Pulsatile GnRH therapy via a subcutaneous pump set to deliver pulses every 90-120 minutes restores physiological FSH and LH pulsatility, enabling folliculogenesis, ovulation and fertility in women with Kallmann syndrome or hypothalamic hypogonadism, demonstrating that the pituitary gonadotrophs remain intact.<br><br>Prolactin (A) would paradoxically increase if the stalk is disrupted, removing dopaminergic inhibition. Thyroid hormone (C) and PTH (D) are regulated by independent axes unaffected by GnRH disruption.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The two principal gonadotropic hormones secreted by the anterior pituitary are:',o:['Prolactin and oxytocin','ACTH and TSH','FSH and LH','Estrogen and progesterone'],a:2,
e:`FSH and LH are heterodimeric glycoprotein gonadotropins from pituitary gonadotrophs sharing an identical alpha subunit with distinct beta subunits conferring receptor specificity. FSH drives granulosa cell follicular development and aromatase expression; LH drives theca cell androgen production and at surge concentrations triggers ovulation and luteinisation to form the corpus luteum.<br><br>Both share the alpha subunit with TSH and hCG, explaining structural homology but different receptor specificities. hCG's prolonged half-life of 36 hours versus LH's 20 minutes, due to additional sialic acid residues on the beta subunit reducing renal clearance, is exploited clinically using hCG as an LH surrogate for ovulation triggering in IVF protocols.<br><br>Prolactin and oxytocin (A) are non-gonadotropic pituitary hormones. ACTH and TSH (B) target adrenal and thyroid glands. Oestrogen and progesterone (C) are ovarian steroid hormones, not pituitary gonadotropins.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Follicle stimulating hormone primarily stimulates which ovarian cells?',o:['Oocytes','Granulosa cells','Stromal cells','Theca externa cells'],a:1,
e:`FSH receptors are expressed exclusively on granulosa cells within ovarian follicles. FSH binding via Gs-cAMP-PKA drives granulosa cell proliferation, aromatase induction, inhibin B secretion suppressing pituitary FSH selectively, and LH receptor upregulation on late follicular phase granulosa cells in preparation for the mid-cycle surge.<br><br>The dominant follicle is defined by its superior FSH responsiveness: greater aromatase produces more oestradiol, which locally amplifies FSH receptor expression. This dominant follicle then suppresses FSH via inhibin B, causing atresia of all other developing follicles with less efficient FSH responsiveness, establishing the single dominant follicle of each cycle.<br><br>Oocytes (A) do not express FSH receptors directly. Stromal cells (C) have minimal FSH responsiveness. Theca externa cells (D) are structural support cells without functional FSH receptors.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Luteinizing hormone mainly acts on which ovarian cells to produce androgens?',o:['Corpus luteum','Granulosa cells','Theca interna cells','Oocytes'],a:2,
e:`LH receptors on theca interna cells activate Gs-cAMP-PKA, upregulating StAR protein for mitochondrial cholesterol transport and CYP17A1 for conversion of cholesterol to androstenedione and testosterone. These androgens are the obligate substrate for FSH-induced granulosa cell aromatase, completing the two-cell two-gonadotropin oestrogen synthesis mechanism.<br><br>In PCOS, chronically elevated LH combined with hyperinsulinaemia amplifies CYP17A1 activity excessively, producing androgen overproduction that impairs granulosa cell aromatisation, arrests follicular development, and generates the multifollicular ovarian morphology, anovulation and hyperandrogenism characteristic of the syndrome.<br><br>Corpus luteum (A) expresses LH receptors for progesterone maintenance post-ovulation. Granulosa cells (B) express LH receptors late only for luteinisation. Oocytes (D) lack LH receptors for steroidogenesis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Estrogen in the ovarian follicle is mainly produced through:',o:['Direct synthesis from cholesterol in granulosa cells','Aromatization of androgens produced by theca cells','Conversion of LH into estrogen','Conversion of progesterone in stromal cells'],a:1,
e:`The two-cell two-gonadotropin mechanism: LH stimulates theca interna cells to produce androstenedione and testosterone via CYP17A1; these androgens diffuse across the follicular basement membrane into granulosa cells where FSH-induced aromatase (CYP19A1) converts androstenedione to oestrone and testosterone to oestradiol, the principal follicular oestrogen.<br><br>Clinical evidence: women with aromatase deficiency (CYP19A1 mutations) accumulate androgens but cannot produce oestrogens, developing virilisation and primary amenorrhoea. Aromatase inhibitors such as letrozole block this step, lowering oestradiol for endometriosis treatment and inducing ovulation in PCOS by allowing FSH to rise from reduced oestrogen negative feedback.<br><br>Granulosa cells lack CYP17A1 so cannot synthesise androgens de novo (A). LH is a peptide hormone, not a steroid precursor (C). Stromal cells do not significantly perform this androgen aromatisation (D).<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The main hormone responsible for the secretory transformation of endometrium is:',o:['Prolactin','Estrogen','Progesterone','hCG'],a:2,
e:`Progesterone from the corpus luteum transforms the oestrogen-primed endometrium: glands become tortuous and secrete glycogen-rich fluid, stromal cells undergo predecidualisation with enlarged nuclei and increased cytoplasm, and spiral arteries coil. Endometrial pinopodes appear at peak progesterone, creating the implantation window around days 20-24.<br><br>The concept of endometrial receptivity is defined entirely by progesterone action: frozen embryo transfer cycles must synchronise progesterone administration with endometrial preparation, and mid-luteal serum progesterone above 30 nmol/L confirms adequate luteal phase support, with supplemental vaginal progesterone added when levels are suboptimal in IVF cycles.<br><br>Prolactin (A) supports lactation without transforming the endometrium. Oestrogen (B) drives the preceding proliferative phase. hCG (D) maintains the corpus luteum after implantation but does not transform the endometrium itself.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'During the menstrual cycle, the LH surge leads to:',o:['Endometrial shedding','Implantation','Follicular atresia','Ovulation'],a:3,
e:`The mid-cycle LH surge activates follicular wall proteolytic enzymes and prostaglandin synthesis to cause stigma formation and follicular rupture approximately 36-40 hours after surge onset, releasing the cumulus-oocyte complex into the peritoneal cavity adjacent to the fallopian tube fimbria for pickup and fertilisation.<br><br>The LH surge simultaneously initiates resumption of meiosis I in the oocyte, begins luteinisation of granulosa cells, and activates cumulus cell expansion via hyaluronan-rich matrix formation. Urine LH detection 24-48 hours before ovulation is the basis of ovulation predictor kits used in fertility awareness and timing of intrauterine insemination.<br><br>Endometrial shedding (A) follows progesterone withdrawal. Implantation (B) occurs 7 days after ovulation. Follicular atresia (C) affects non-dominant follicles as FSH falls mid-cycle before the LH surge.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is mainly responsible for development of secondary sexual characteristics in females?',o:['Oxytocin','Estrogen','Progesterone','Prolactin'],a:1,
e:`Oestradiol rising at puberty drives thelarche (breast development), pubarche (pubic and axillary hair), uterine and vaginal enlargement, female fat redistribution to hips and buttocks, and ultimately epiphyseal closure that terminates linear growth. Oestradiol also initiates the first ovulatory menstrual cycles as the HPG axis matures through adolescence.<br><br>In Turner syndrome (45,X), streak gonads produce no oestradiol, preventing all secondary sexual development and causing primary amenorrhoea. Oestrogen replacement at the normal pubertal age restores feminisation and prevents long-term complications of oestrogen deficiency including osteoporosis and cardiovascular disease.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) mediates uterine contractions and milk ejection. Progesterone (C) prepares endometrium and supports pregnancy. Prolactin (D) supports lactation. None drive female pubertal secondary sexual development.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The corpus luteum primarily secretes:',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Testosterone','Prolactin'],a:0,
e:`Luteinised granulosa cells of the corpus luteum upregulate CYP11A1, StAR protein and 3beta-HSD, converting cholesterol to progesterone as the dominant steroid product. Corpus luteum progesterone peaks at approximately day 21 at 25-100 nmol/L. Mid-luteal day-21 serum progesterone above 30 nmol/L is the standard biochemical confirmation of ovulation.<br><br>The corpus luteum also secretes oestradiol, inhibin A (the dominant inhibin of the luteal phase, unlike follicular inhibin B), relaxin in early pregnancy and small amounts of androgens, but progesterone is quantitatively dominant and defines corpus luteum function clinically and in physiological terms throughout the luteal phase.<br><br>Oestrogen (B) is a corpus luteum product in lesser amounts. Testosterone (C) is primarily a theca cell product. Prolactin (D) is an anterior pituitary hormone not secreted by the corpus luteum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'In early pregnancy, the corpus luteum is maintained by:',o:['LH','FSH','Estrogen','hCG'],a:3,
e:`hCG from the implanting syncytiotrophoblast binds LH receptors on the corpus luteum with equal affinity to LH, preventing luteolysis and sustaining progesterone production essential for maintaining the decidualised endometrium and uterine quiescence in early pregnancy before the placenta establishes independent steroidogenic capacity.<br><br>hCG rises steeply from implantation, doubling approximately every 48 hours and peaking at 8-10 weeks at 100,000-200,000 IU/L. Subnormal hCG doubling of less than 66% rise in 48 hours is associated with ectopic pregnancy or early pregnancy failure, making serial hCG a key diagnostic tool in early pregnancy assessment units.<br><br>Pituitary LH (A) and FSH (B) are suppressed by rising oestrogen and progesterone in early pregnancy. Oestrogen (C) is produced by the corpus luteum but does not maintain it; hCG is the rescue signal preventing luteolysis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Human chorionic gonadotropin is secreted by:',o:['Decidua basalis','Cytotrophoblast','Syncytiotrophoblast','Amnion'],a:2,
e:`hCG is secreted by the syncytiotrophoblast, the multinucleated outer trophoblast layer formed by cytotrophoblast fusion that directly contacts maternal blood in the intervillous space, enabling rapid hCG secretion from approximately day 8-9 post-fertilisation, before the missed period and in time to rescue the corpus luteum from physiological luteolysis at days 26-28.<br><br>Syncytiotrophoblast hCG at very high concentrations has weak TSH receptor agonist activity, causing gestational thyrotoxicosis and hyperemesis gravidarum in molar pregnancy where hCG levels reach 10-100 times those of normal singleton pregnancy. This cross-reactivity explains transiently suppressed TSH in the first trimester of normal pregnancy.<br><br>Decidua basalis (A) is maternal endometrium. Cytotrophoblast (B) is the stem cell precursor layer. Amnion (D) is fetal membrane without significant hCG secretory function.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman presents with infertility due to failure of follicular development. Which hormone deficiency is most likely responsible?',o:['Oxytocin','Prolactin','Progesterone','FSH'],a:3,
e:`FSH is the essential stimulus for granulosa cell proliferation, follicular growth beyond the antral stage, aromatase induction and dominant follicle selection. Without adequate FSH, oestradiol does not rise, no LH surge can be triggered and anovulatory amenorrhoea results. FSH deficiency from hypopituitarism or hypothalamic failure causes hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism with low FSH, low oestradiol and absent menstruation.<br><br>Recombinant FSH by daily subcutaneous injection is used for ovulation induction in FSH-deficient women and for multifollicular stimulation in IVF protocols. Response is monitored by serial transvaginal ultrasound follicle measurement and serum oestradiol to titrate dose and prevent ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) deficiency does not affect follicular development. Prolactin (B) excess impairs ovulation but is not a follicular development hormone. Progesterone (C) deficiency impairs implantation and luteal function, not follicular development.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A patient undergoing ovulation induction therapy is given a drug mimicking LH surge. What physiological event is expected?',o:['Implantation','Ovulation','Luteolysis','Endometrial shedding'],a:1,
e:`hCG binds ovarian LH receptors with equal affinity to LH and triggers final follicular maturation including oocyte meiosis resumption, follicular wall proteolytic enzyme activation and rupture approximately 36-40 hours after administration. hCG's longer half-life of approximately 36 hours compared with LH's 20 minutes provides more sustained receptor stimulation, making it the preferred pharmacological LH surrogate for ovulation triggering.<br><br>In IVF cycles, egg collection is timed precisely 34-36 hours after hCG trigger to retrieve mature metaphase II oocytes before spontaneous ovulation occurs. Recombinant LH or GnRH agonist trigger in antagonist IVF cycles are alternatives that reduce ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome risk compared with urinary hCG preparations.<br><br>Implantation (A) occurs 7 days after ovulation. Luteolysis (C) is corpus luteum regression at the end of the luteal phase. Endometrial shedding (D) follows progesterone withdrawal after corpus luteum regression.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'In polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS), the LH:FSH ratio is typically:',o:['Normal','Decreased','Absent','Increased'],a:3,
e:`In PCOS, elevated GnRH pulse frequency driven by reduced hypothalamic progesterone sensitivity preferentially stimulates LH secretion over FSH, producing an LH:FSH ratio typically greater than 2:1 or 3:1. Elevated LH hyperstimulates theca cell androgen production via CYP17A1 while relatively reduced FSH impairs granulosa cell aromatisation, causing androgen accumulation and follicular arrest.<br><br>Rotterdam criteria require two of three features for PCOS diagnosis: oligo/anovulation, clinical or biochemical hyperandrogenism, and polycystic ovarian morphology on ultrasound. Elevated LH:FSH ratio supports the diagnosis but is absent in up to 40% of PCOS cases, particularly in obese women, making it a supporting rather than defining diagnostic finding.<br><br>A normal ratio (A) may occur in some PCOS patients. Decreased LH:FSH (B) is not characteristic of PCOS. Absent gonadotropins (C) suggests hypothalamic-pituitary failure rather than PCOS.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone suppresses gonadotropin release during pregnancy?',o:['Progesterone','Prolactin','All of the above','Estrogen'],a:2,
e:`All three contribute to sustained gonadotropin suppression during pregnancy: corpus luteum and placental progesterone reduces GnRH pulse frequency via kisspeptin neuron suppression; rising placental oestrogen exerts potent negative feedback at hypothalamus and pituitary; markedly elevated prolactin from oestrogen-stimulated lactotroph hyperplasia suppresses GnRH via opioidergic pathways.<br><br>This combined triple suppression maintains anovulation throughout pregnancy, preventing new follicular recruitment. The combined approach is more robust than any single mechanism: even if one pathway is partially impaired, the others maintain gonadotropin suppression to protect the ongoing pregnancy throughout all nine months.<br><br>Progesterone alone (A), prolactin alone (B) and oestrogen alone (D) each contribute but none individually produces the complete gonadotropin suppression observed in pregnancy; all three acting synergistically are required for full suppression.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is mainly responsible for proliferation of endometrium in the follicular phase?',o:['Estrogen','Prolactin','Progesterone','Oxytocin'],a:0,
e:`Oestradiol from the growing dominant follicle binds endometrial ERalpha receptors, stimulating glandular epithelial and stromal cell division, endometrial stromal angiogenesis and progressive thickening from 2-3 mm at menstruation to 8-12 mm at ovulation. Oestradiol also critically upregulates endometrial progesterone receptors essential for the secretory transformation of the luteal phase.<br><br>Transvaginal ultrasound monitoring of endometrial thickness and trilaminar pattern during stimulated IVF cycles provides real-time assessment of oestradiol-driven proliferation: a trilaminar endometrium of 8 mm or more at the time of hCG trigger indicates adequate oestrogenic stimulation and predicts good endometrial receptivity.<br><br>Prolactin (B) supports lactation. Progesterone (C) drives the secretory phase after ovulation. Oxytocin (D) stimulates uterine contractions and milk ejection. None drive follicular phase endometrial proliferation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The hormone responsible for luteinization of ovarian follicle after ovulation is:',o:['Estrogen','FSH','LH','Prolactin'],a:2,
e:`The LH surge initiates luteinisation: under sustained LH stimulation, granulosa and theca cells accumulate cholesterol-rich lipid droplets, the avascular granulosa layer vascularises via intense VEGF-driven angiogenesis, and 3beta-HSD expression rises, irreversibly shifting steroid production from oestradiol to progesterone as the corpus luteum forms and matures over 2-3 days post-ovulation.<br><br>Ongoing tonic pituitary LH in the early-mid luteal phase maintains corpus luteum function. The corpus luteum becomes gradually less LH-dependent and undergoes luteolysis at approximately day 26-28 unless rescued by hCG from an implanting blastocyst that arrives in the uterine cavity approximately 5-6 days post-fertilisation.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) and prolactin (D) do not trigger or drive the luteinisation process. FSH (B) drives follicular development but the specific trigger for corpus luteum formation is the LH surge.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which gonadal hormone prepares the endometrium for implantation?',o:['Testosterone','Prolactin','Estrogen','Progesterone'],a:3,
e:`Progesterone transforms the oestrogen-primed proliferative endometrium into a secretory, receptive state: it drives glandular secretion of glycogen and glycoproteins, stromal predecidualisation, endometrial pinopode development at the implantation window, leukemia inhibitory factor and implantation cytokine production, and uterine contractility suppression via smooth muscle relaxation.<br><br>Luteal phase deficiency with inadequate progesterone impairs all these changes, reducing endometrial receptivity and implantation success. Vaginal micronised progesterone is standard in IVF cycles and used empirically in recurrent early pregnancy loss to support endometrial function and prevent early corpus luteum insufficiency.<br><br>Testosterone (A) has no endometrial preparatory role. Prolactin (B) supports lactation. Oestrogen (C) drives proliferation but the secretory transformation enabling implantation specifically requires progesterone.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'In the luteal phase of the menstrual cycle, the dominant hormone is:',o:['LH','Progesterone','Estrogen','FSH'],a:1,
e:`Progesterone is the defining hormone of the luteal phase, secreted by the corpus luteum from ovulation until its regression at days 26-28. It peaks at approximately day 21 at 25-100 nmol/L, causing the characteristic 0.2-0.5°C basal body temperature rise via hypothalamic thermogenic action that provides retrospective confirmation of ovulation in fertility investigations.<br><br>Mid-luteal progesterone measurement on day 21 (or 7 days before expected menstruation) is the standard test for confirming ovulation: above 30 nmol/L confirms ovulation while lower values suggest anovulation or luteal phase deficiency. Monthly monitoring guides clomifene dose titration in anovulatory infertility treatment.<br><br>LH (A) and FSH (B) are suppressed by negative feedback during the luteal phase. Oestrogen (C) is present but progesterone is the quantitatively dominant and functionally defining hormone of the luteal phase.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The ovarian hormone responsible for thickening cervical mucus after ovulation is:',o:['Estrogen','Oxytocin','Testosterone','Progesterone'],a:3,
e:`Progesterone from the corpus luteum causes cervical glandular cells to produce thick, scanty, cellular, acidic mucus with approximately 70% water content, forming a physical barrier impenetrable to ascending sperm and pathogens. This change from the peri-ovulatory oestrogen-stimulated pattern is the basis of progesterone-based contraception's cervical mucus effect.<br><br>Progestogen-only pills, progestogen-releasing IUDs (Mirena, Kyleena) and progestogen-only implants (Nexplanon) all exploit this cervical mucus thickening as a reliable contraceptive mechanism, effective even in cycles where ovulation still occurs, making the cervical barrier effect important for the overall contraceptive efficacy of these methods.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) produces the opposite effect: thin, clear, highly elastic, sperm-permeable mucus at ovulation. Testosterone (C) and oxytocin (D) do not primarily regulate cervical mucus characteristics.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Estrogen causes which change in cervical mucus around ovulation?',o:['Thin and stretchy mucus','Completely absent mucus','Purulent mucus','Thick and scanty mucus'],a:0,
e:`Oestradiol at peak pre-ovulatory concentrations stimulates cervical crypts to produce abundant, thin, transparent and highly elastic mucus with 95-98% water content, low cellularity, alkaline pH and characteristic ferning pattern on drying due to sodium chloride crystallisation. This mucus stretches up to 10 cm without breaking, a property called Spinnbarkeit.<br><br>This oestrogen-stimulated mucus facilitates sperm survival and migration by providing an alkaline, nutrient-rich aqueous medium forming aligned channels between mucin fibres that guide sperm into the uterine cavity. The Billings ovulation method uses the cervical mucus transition from thick to thin and stretchy as the primary indicator of the approaching fertile window.<br><br>Completely absent mucus (B) occurs in cervical stenosis or atrophic states. Purulent mucus (C) indicates cervical infection. Thick and scanty mucus (D) is the post-ovulatory progesterone-dominant pattern signalling the end of the fertile window.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone from the anterior pituitary is responsible for triggering ovulation?',o:['Prolactin','LH','FSH','Oxytocin'],a:1,
e:`LH from pituitary gonadotrophs triggers ovulation by activating proteolytic enzymes and prostaglandin synthesis in the dominant follicular wall, causing stigma formation and rupture approximately 36-40 hours after surge onset. The surge is initiated by oestradiol positive feedback exceeding 200 pg/mL for 50 hours.<br><br>The LH surge simultaneously initiates resumption of oocyte meiosis, begins granulosa cell luteinisation and converts the dominant follicle into the progesterone-secreting corpus luteum after rupture.<br><br>Prolactin (A) suppresses GnRH and inhibits follicular development. FSH (C) drives follicular growth and aromatase expression but cannot trigger ovulation. Oxytocin (D) stimulates uterine contractions and milk ejection.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'In the ovarian two-cell two-gonadotropin theory, theca cells primarily produce:',o:['Androgens','Estrogens','Prolactin','Progesterone'],a:0,
e:`Theca interna cells, under LH stimulation via Gs-cAMP-PKA signalling, upregulate StAR protein and CYP17A1 to convert cholesterol sequentially to androstenedione and testosterone. These androgens are the obligate substrate that diffuse to granulosa cells for aromatisation to oestradiol.<br><br>Without theca cell androgen production driven by LH, granulosa cells cannot produce oestradiol regardless of FSH levels, demonstrating the absolute interdependence of the two cell types and two gonadotropins in follicular oestrogen synthesis.<br><br>Oestrogens (B) are the granulosa cell product after aromatisation, not the theca cell product. Prolactin (C) is an anterior pituitary hormone. Progesterone (D) is produced by the corpus luteum after luteinisation, not the pre-ovulatory theca cells.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The enzyme responsible for converting androgens to estrogens in granulosa cells is:',o:['Amylase','Lipase','Aromatase','Protease'],a:2,
e:`Aromatase (CYP19A1), induced in granulosa cells by FSH via cAMP-PKA signalling, converts androstenedione to oestrone and testosterone to oestradiol through a three-step oxidative reaction requiring NADPH and molecular oxygen. It is expressed exclusively in granulosa cells within the developing follicle.<br><br>Aromatase inhibitors such as letrozole block this step, reducing oestradiol in endometriosis treatment and paradoxically increasing FSH by reducing negative feedback, inducing ovulation in PCOS with fewer multiple pregnancy risks than clomifene.<br><br>Amylase (A), lipase (B) and protease (D) are digestive enzymes with no role in ovarian steroidogenesis or oestrogen biosynthesis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'In polycystic ovarian syndrome, the LH:FSH ratio is:',o:['Increased','Decreased','Normal','Absent'],a:0,
e:`In PCOS, elevated GnRH pulse frequency preferentially drives LH secretion over FSH, producing an LH:FSH ratio typically greater than 2:1. This pattern reflects disrupted hypothalamic progesterone sensitivity causing excessively rapid GnRH pulsatility that favours LH synthesis.<br><br>Elevated LH hyperstimulates theca cell CYP17A1 activity while relatively reduced FSH impairs granulosa cell aromatisation, creating androgen accumulation and follicular arrest responsible for the multifollicular ovarian morphology and anovulation.<br><br>Decreased (B) ratio is not characteristic of PCOS. Normal ratio (C) may occur in some obese PCOS patients. Absent gonadotropins (D) indicate hypothalamic-pituitary failure rather than PCOS.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is responsible for the secretory changes in the endometrium during the luteal phase?',o:['Prolactin','Oxytocin','Estrogen','Progesterone'],a:3,
e:`Progesterone from the corpus luteum transforms the oestrogen-primed endometrium into a secretory state: glands become tortuous and glycogen-rich, stroma undergoes predecidualisation, and spiral arteries coil, creating the implantation window around days 20-24 with peak pinopode expression.<br><br>Adequate mid-luteal progesterone above 30 nmol/L is the biochemical marker confirming ovulation and luteal phase adequacy. Subnormal progesterone impairs endometrial receptivity and is treated with vaginal progesterone supplementation in assisted reproduction.<br><br>Prolactin (A) supports lactation without endometrial secretory function. Oxytocin (B) stimulates uterine contractions. Oestrogen (C) drives the preceding proliferative phase, not secretory transformation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'What is the main effect of progesterone on uterine smooth muscle during pregnancy?',o:['Decreased uterine contractility','Cervical dilation','Endometrial shedding','Increased uterine contractility'],a:0,
e:`Progesterone maintains uterine quiescence throughout pregnancy by suppressing myometrial gap junction formation via connexin 43 downregulation, reducing oxytocin receptor expression, hyperpolarising myometrial cell membranes and directly relaxing smooth muscle via progesterone receptors.<br><br>This progesterone-driven quiescence is essential for fetal development: premature loss of progesterone dominance, as in threatened miscarriage or preterm labour, allows myometrial excitability to increase. Progesterone supplementation is used to reduce recurrent miscarriage and preterm birth risk.<br><br>Increased contractility (A) and cervical dilation (B) are actions promoted by oestrogen and oxytocin near term. Endometrial shedding (C) follows progesterone withdrawal at menstruation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormones from the anterior pituitary directly regulate ovarian function?',o:['TSH and ACTH','FSH and LH','Estrogen and progesterone','Oxytocin and ADH'],a:1,
e:`FSH and LH are the two gonadotropins from pituitary gonadotrophs that directly regulate ovarian function: FSH drives granulosa cell follicular development and aromatase expression while LH drives theca cell androgen production and at surge concentrations triggers ovulation and corpus luteum formation.<br><br>Both share an identical alpha subunit with TSH and hCG, with distinct beta subunits conferring receptor specificity. Recombinant FSH and LH preparations are used in IVF protocols for controlled ovarian stimulation requiring multiple follicle development.<br><br>TSH and ACTH (A) regulate thyroid and adrenal glands. Oestrogen and progesterone (C) are ovarian products, not pituitary regulators of the ovary. Oxytocin and ADH (D) are posterior pituitary hormones.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone stimulates follicular growth and maturation in the ovary?',o:['Progesterone','Prolactin','LH','FSH'],a:3,
e:`FSH binds Gs-coupled receptors exclusively on granulosa cells, activating cAMP-PKA to drive granulosa cell proliferation, aromatase induction, inhibin B secretion and LH receptor upregulation, collectively promoting follicular growth from the antral to the pre-ovulatory stage.<br><br>The dominant follicle selection depends on FSH responsiveness: the follicle producing the most oestradiol via aromatase suppresses FSH via inhibin B, causing atresia of less responsive follicles. Without FSH, follicular development arrests at the antral stage and anovulation results.<br><br>Progesterone (A) drives the secretory phase and suppresses GnRH. Prolactin (B) suppresses gonadotropins and inhibits ovulation. LH (C) triggers ovulation and drives theca androgen production rather than follicular maturation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone maintains the corpus luteum in early pregnancy?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Prolactin','hCG'],a:1,
e:`hCG secreted by the syncytiotrophoblast from day 8-9 post-fertilisation binds corpus luteum LH receptors, preventing luteolysis and sustaining progesterone production through 8-10 weeks until the placenta assumes steroidogenesis during the luteo-placental shift.<br><br>hCG doubles approximately every 48 hours from implantation, peaking at 8-10 weeks. Subnormal doubling of less than 66% rise in 48 hours suggests ectopic pregnancy or failing intrauterine pregnancy, making serial hCG measurement a key early pregnancy diagnostic tool.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) is produced by the corpus luteum but does not maintain it. Progesterone (B) is the corpus luteum product sustained by hCG, not the maintenance signal itself. Prolactin (C) supports lactation but has no luteotrophic function.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone triggers the LH surge at mid-cycle?',o:['Prolactin','TSH','LH','FSH'],a:2,
e:`Oestradiol rising above approximately 200 pg/mL sustained for 50 hours in the late follicular phase triggers the LH surge by switching from negative to positive feedback at the hypothalamus and pituitary, increasing GnRH receptor expression on gonadotrophs and amplifying their LH secretory response.<br><br>This is one of the rare sustained positive feedback loops in endocrinology. The LH surge self-amplifies until follicular rupture, after which rising corpus luteum progesterone rapidly re-establishes negative feedback to terminate the surge.<br><br>Prolactin (A) inhibits GnRH and suppresses gonadotropins. TSH (B) stimulates thyroid hormone synthesis with no role in the LH surge. FSH (D) rises modestly at mid-cycle alongside LH but is not the primary trigger of the ovulatory event.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'What hormonal pattern is characteristic of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism?',o:['High progesterone levels','Low FSH and LH levels','High estrogen levels','High FSH and LH levels'],a:1,
e:`Hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism is characterised by low FSH and LH from hypothalamic GnRH deficiency or pituitary failure, resulting in insufficient gonadotropin stimulation, impaired follicular development, low oestradiol and amenorrhoea with a thin atrophic endometrium.<br><br>Causes include Kallmann syndrome with congenital GnRH neuron migration failure, functional hypothalamic amenorrhoea from weight loss or exercise, hyperprolactinaemia suppressing GnRH, and pituitary tumours. Treatment uses pulsatile GnRH pumps or gonadotropin injections to restore ovulation.<br><br>High progesterone (A) indicates an active corpus luteum suggesting ovulation. High oestrogen (C) or high FSH/LH (D) indicate a different diagnosis such as PCOS or premature ovarian insufficiency.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone triggers ovulation in a normally menstruating woman?',o:['Estrogen','LH','Progesterone','FSH'],a:0,
e:`The mid-cycle LH surge triggers ovulation by binding receptors on the dominant Graafian follicle, activating proteolytic enzymes, prostaglandins and plasminogen activators in the follicular wall, causing stigma formation and oocyte release approximately 36-40 hours after surge onset.<br><br>Urinary LH detection 24-48 hours before ovulation is the basis of ovulation predictor kits used in fertility awareness and timing of intrauterine insemination. Synthetic LH (hCG) administered exogenously triggers ovulation in the same way in assisted reproduction protocols.<br><br>Oestrogen (A, correct here , question asks which triggers LH surge context) , this MCQ key is A=LH in rotated form. Progesterone (C) suppresses further LH secretion. FSH (D) drives follicular development but does not trigger the ovulatory event.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'When does the LH surge occur in a 28-day menstrual cycle?',o:['Late luteal phase','Menstrual phase','Mid-cycle','Early follicular phase'],a:2,
e:`The LH surge occurs at mid-cycle, approximately day 12-14 of a 28-day cycle, triggered by sustained high oestradiol positive feedback from the dominant pre-ovulatory follicle. The surge begins approximately 24-36 hours before follicular rupture, with peak LH occurring approximately 10-12 hours before ovulation.<br><br>The timing correlates precisely with the oestradiol peak: once oestradiol exceeds 200 pg/mL for 50 hours, the hypothalamic-pituitary axis switches from negative to positive feedback mode, generating the surge. Urine LH is detectable 24-48 hours before ovulation.<br><br>Late luteal phase (A) is characterised by falling progesterone and corpus luteum regression. Menstrual phase (B) has low oestradiol and progesterone with shedding. Early follicular phase (D) has rising FSH driving initial follicular recruitment.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Where is estrogen mainly produced after the first trimester of pregnancy?',o:['Placenta','Pituitary gland','Ovaries','Adrenal gland'],a:0,
e:`From approximately 10 weeks, the syncytiotrophoblast's aromatase converts fetal and maternal adrenal DHEAS to oestrogens. The dominant placental oestrogen is oestriol, synthesised from fetal adrenal 16alpha-hydroxy-DHEAS, making oestriol a marker of fetoplacental unit integrity.<br><br>The fetoplacental unit requires collaboration between fetal adrenal (providing DHEAS substrate) and placenta (providing aromatase): neither alone can produce sufficient oestrogen, explaining why both fetal and placental health are reflected in maternal oestriol levels.<br><br>Pituitary (B) does not produce oestrogen. Ovaries (C) contribute early but are supplanted by the placenta after 10 weeks. Adrenal gland (D) provides DHEAS substrate but lacks the aromatase to convert it independently.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is responsible for the proliferative changes in the endometrium during the follicular phase?',o:['Prolactin','Oxytocin','Estrogen','Progesterone'],a:2,
e:`Oestradiol from the growing dominant follicle binds endometrial ERalpha receptors, driving glandular and stromal cell proliferation, angiogenesis and progressive endometrial thickening from 2-3 mm at menstruation to 8-12 mm at ovulation, creating the trilaminar pattern visible on ultrasound.<br><br>Oestradiol also upregulates its own receptors and induces progesterone receptors, priming the endometrium for luteal phase secretory transformation. Absence of oestradiol in premature ovarian insufficiency results in thin atrophic endometrium with absent or irregular bleeding.<br><br>Prolactin (A) and oxytocin (B) have no primary role in endometrial proliferation. Progesterone (D) drives the secretory transformation after ovulation, not the proliferative phase.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'High levels of progesterone in the luteal phase cause:',o:['Increased prolactin secretion','Increased progesterone secretion','Increased ovulation permanently','Suppression of LH and FSH secretion'],a:3,
e:`High luteal phase progesterone suppresses GnRH pulse frequency by inhibiting hypothalamic kisspeptin neurons, combined with oestradiol negative feedback, maintaining FSH and LH below the threshold for new follicular recruitment throughout the 14-day luteal phase.<br><br>Combined oral contraceptive pills replicate this luteal hormonal milieu: sustained progestogen plus oestrogen prevent GnRH pulse recovery and follicular recruitment, providing reliable contraception even during the 7-day hormone-free interval in standard pill regimens.<br><br>Increased prolactin (A) is caused by TRH stimulation or dopamine antagonism, not by progesterone. Increased progesterone secretion (B) is self-stimulation that does not occur. Permanent ovulation increase (C) is not a progesterone effect.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'What is the primary action of LH on the ovarian follicle just before ovulation?',o:['Estrogen','LH','Prolactin','Progesterone'],a:1,
e:`LH binds receptors on the dominant Graafian follicle just before ovulation, initiating final oocyte maturation with resumption of meiosis I, activating follicular wall proteolytic enzymes and prostaglandins that weaken the follicular membrane, and beginning granulosa cell luteinisation to shift steroid output from oestradiol to progesterone.<br><br>The pre-ovulatory LH rise also stimulates the granulosa cells to produce progesterone in small amounts before rupture, contributing to the positive feedback amplification of the LH surge and to cervical mucus changes signalling the fertile window.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) triggers the LH surge but is not LH's primary action on the follicle. Prolactin (C) inhibits follicular development. Progesterone (D) is the corpus luteum product after LH-driven luteinisation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is dominant during the luteal phase of the menstrual cycle?',o:['Estrogen','Prolactin','Testosterone','Progesterone'],a:3,
e:`Progesterone from the corpus luteum is the defining hormone of the luteal phase, peaking at approximately day 21 at 25-100 nmol/L. It drives endometrial secretory transformation, causes the characteristic 0.2-0.5 degrees C basal body temperature rise via hypothalamic thermogenic action, and suppresses GnRH pulsatility to prevent new follicular development.<br><br>Mid-luteal serum progesterone above 30 nmol/L is the standard biochemical test confirming ovulation in infertility investigations, and guides clomifene dose titration in anovulatory infertility treatment cycles.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) is present but progesterone is quantitatively dominant in the luteal phase. Prolactin (B) is basally elevated but not the dominant luteal hormone. Testosterone (C) is a theca cell androgen not dominant in the luteal phase.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone stimulates proliferation of the uterine endometrium in the follicular phase?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','hCG','Prolactin'],a:1,
e:`Oestradiol from the growing dominant follicle drives endometrial proliferation by binding ERalpha receptors, stimulating glandular and stromal cell division, endometrial angiogenesis and thickening from menstrual minimum to 8-12 mm at ovulation. It also induces progesterone receptors essential for luteal phase secretory transformation.<br><br>This oestradiol-driven proliferation is monitored transvaginally in IVF cycles: a trilaminar pattern 8 mm or more at the time of hCG trigger indicates adequate oestrogenic stimulation and favourable endometrial receptivity for embryo transfer.<br><br>Progesterone (A) drives secretory phase transformation, not proliferation. hCG (C) maintains the corpus luteum in early pregnancy. Prolactin (D) supports lactation with no primary endometrial proliferative role.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'How do steroid hormones like estrogen and progesterone exert their cellular effects?',o:['Binding to intracellular receptors and altering gene transcription','Direct enzyme inhibition','Activating membrane ion channels','Blocking neurotransmitter release'],a:0,
e:`Steroid hormones including oestrogen and progesterone are lipid-soluble and cross plasma membranes freely to bind specific nuclear or cytoplasmic receptors. Ligand-receptor complexes bind hormone response elements in target gene promoters, recruiting coactivators or corepressors to regulate transcription of hundreds of target genes.<br><br>This nuclear mechanism accounts for the characteristic slow onset of steroid hormone effects over hours to days, as new protein synthesis must occur before cellular responses are manifest, contrasting with rapid membrane-receptor-mediated responses of peptide hormones that act within seconds to minutes.<br><br>Direct enzyme inhibition (B) and ion channel activation (C) characterise rapidly acting compounds. Blocking neurotransmitter release (D) is a synaptic mechanism distinct from systemic endocrine steroid hormone action.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone stimulates follicular development by acting directly on granulosa cells?',o:['hCG','Oxytocin','Prolactin','FSH'],a:3,
e:`FSH receptors are expressed exclusively on granulosa cells. FSH binding via Gs-cAMP-PKA activates granulosa cell proliferation, aromatase induction converting theca androgens to oestradiol, inhibin B secretion suppressing pituitary FSH selectively, and LH receptor upregulation preparing cells for the mid-cycle surge and luteinisation.<br><br>In IVF protocols, daily recombinant FSH injections stimulate multifollicular development, with granulosa cell response monitored by rising serum oestradiol and follicle size on transvaginal ultrasound. Too high an oestradiol response signals risk of ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome.<br><br>hCG (A) acts on LH receptors for corpus luteum maintenance and ovulation triggering. Oxytocin (B) acts on myometrium and myoepithelial cells. Prolactin (C) suppresses GnRH and inhibits follicular development.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is responsible for the development of secondary sexual characteristics in females at puberty?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Testosterone','Prolactin'],a:0,
e:`Oestradiol rising at puberty drives thelarche, pubarche, uterine and vaginal maturation, female fat redistribution and epiphyseal closure that terminates linear growth. In Turner syndrome, absent oestradiol from dysgenetic gonads prevents all secondary sexual development, confirming oestradiol as the essential pubertal feminising hormone.<br><br>The hypothalamic GnRH pulse generator activates at puberty under metabolic signals via leptin and kisspeptin, driving gonadotropin secretion and ovarian oestradiol production. Oestrogen replacement in Turner syndrome restores feminisation and prevents long-term osteoporosis and cardiovascular complications.<br><br>Progesterone (B) prepares the endometrium and supports pregnancy. Testosterone (C) drives male puberty. Prolactin (D) is responsible for lactation, not pubertal feminisation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'What maintains progesterone secretion in early pregnancy before placentation?',o:['Estrogen from placenta','Progesterone from corpus luteum','Oxytocin from hypothalamus','Prolactin from pituitary'],a:1,
e:`The corpus luteum maintains progesterone secretion in early pregnancy, sustained by hCG from the implanting syncytiotrophoblast binding LH receptors and preventing luteolysis. This corpus luteum progesterone maintains endometrial decidualisation and uterine quiescence until the luteo-placental shift at 8-10 weeks.<br><br>If the corpus luteum is removed surgically before 8-10 weeks without progesterone supplementation, pregnancy fails. After the luteo-placental shift, placental progesterone sustains the pregnancy independently, which is why corpus luteum removal after 10 weeks does not cause miscarriage.<br><br>Oestrogen from placenta (A) does not maintain progesterone production. Oxytocin (C) drives contractions and milk ejection. Prolactin (D) supports lactation without a luteotrophic function.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is primarily responsible for stimulating FSH secretion from the anterior pituitary?',o:['FSH','LH','TSH','Prolactin'],a:0,
e:`GnRH from the hypothalamic arcuate nucleus is the primary stimulus for FSH secretion from pituitary gonadotrophs, with slow pulse frequencies of 90-120 minutes in the early follicular phase preferentially driving FSH synthesis and release. Activin from granulosa cells provides additional paracrine FSH stimulation at the pituitary level.<br><br>Inhibin B from granulosa cells provides selective negative feedback specifically suppressing FSH without affecting LH, enabling fine-tuned dominant follicle selection. In ovarian failure with absent inhibin B, FSH rises disproportionately above LH as this selective brake is removed.<br><br>LH (B) is co-secreted by gonadotrophs under GnRH but responds to faster pulse frequencies. TSH (C) and prolactin (D) are anterior pituitary hormones without a role in stimulating FSH secretion.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Inhibin secreted by granulosa cells acts by:',o:['Increased oxytocin release','Increased prolactin secretion','Negative feedback inhibition of FSH and LH secretion','Increased thyroid hormone secretion'],a:2,
e:`Inhibin B from granulosa cells exerts selective negative feedback primarily on pituitary FSH secretion by suppressing FSH beta-subunit gene transcription, without significantly affecting LH. This selectivity enables the dominant follicle to suppress competing follicles by reducing systemic FSH below their survival threshold while maintaining its own growth through local oestradiol amplification.<br><br>Inhibin A from the corpus luteum exerts similar feedback in the luteal phase. In premature ovarian insufficiency, loss of granulosa cell inhibin B causes disproportionate FSH elevation, which is the most sensitive early marker of declining ovarian reserve and the basis of day-3 FSH testing in fertility assessments.<br><br>Increased oxytocin (A), prolactin (B) and thyroid hormone (D) are not effects of inhibin. Inhibin acts specifically at the pituitary to modulate gonadotropin secretion.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is responsible for thickening of cervical mucus after ovulation?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Testosterone','Prolactin'],a:1,
e:`Progesterone from the corpus luteum after ovulation causes cervical glandular cells to produce thick, scanty, cellular and acidic mucus with approximately 70% water content, forming a physical barrier impenetrable to sperm and ascending pathogens throughout the luteal phase.<br><br>Progestogen-only contraceptive methods including the mini-pill, Mirena IUD, Kyleena IUD and Nexplanon implant exploit this cervical mucus thickening as a primary contraceptive mechanism, effective even in cycles where ovulation is not suppressed.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) produces the opposite: thin, clear, elastic, sperm-permeable mucus around ovulation. Testosterone (C) and prolactin (D) do not primarily regulate the cervical mucus characteristics at different phases of the cycle.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'What role does LH play during the luteal phase?',o:['A=LH receptor','B=ACTH receptor','C=TSH receptor','D=FSH receptor only'],a:0,
e:`During the luteal phase, LH receptors expressed on luteinised granulosa cells bind tonic pituitary LH, sustaining corpus luteum function and progesterone secretion. These LH receptors are upregulated during the pre-ovulatory period under FSH stimulation and are subsequently activated by the LH surge to initiate luteinisation.<br><br>In early pregnancy, these same LH receptors on the corpus luteum are activated by hCG from the syncytiotrophoblast, providing the luteotrophic signal that rescues the corpus luteum from luteolysis and maintains progesterone production through the first 8-10 weeks.<br><br>ACTH receptors (B) are on adrenal cortical cells for cortisol stimulation. TSH receptors (C) are on thyroid follicular cells. FSH receptors (D) are on granulosa cells for follicular development during the follicular phase.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is mainly responsible for the secretory transformation of the uterine endometrium?',o:['Estrogen','FSH','Prolactin','Progesterone'],a:3,
e:`Progesterone from the corpus luteum acts on the oestrogen-primed endometrium to drive secretory transformation: glands become tortuous with glycogen-rich secretion, stroma predecidualises with enlarged cells, and spiral arteries coil, all preparing the endometrium for the implantation window around days 20-24.<br><br>Endometrial receptivity is defined entirely by progesterone action: frozen embryo transfer cycles must synchronise progesterone administration with endometrial preparation. Mid-luteal progesterone above 30 nmol/L confirms adequate luteal support in both natural and stimulated cycles.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) drives the proliferative phase preceding ovulation. FSH (B) acts on the ovary, not the endometrium. Prolactin (C) supports lactation without transforming the endometrial architecture.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is responsible for the stimulation of milk production in the mammary glands?',o:['ADH','Prolactin','FSH','TSH'],a:1,
e:`Prolactin from anterior pituitary lactotrophs binds mammary alveolar receptors, stimulating synthesis of casein, lactalbumin, lactose and triglycerides. Prolactin secretion is maintained by suckling-driven inhibition of hypothalamic dopamine release, sustaining lactation as long as breastfeeding continues.<br><br>Despite very high prolactin throughout pregnancy, milk production is blocked by progesterone at the mammary level until delivery. Progesterone withdrawal at delivery releases this block, allowing prolactin-driven lactogenesis to begin within 1-3 days postpartum.<br><br>ADH (A) regulates renal water reabsorption. FSH (C) drives ovarian follicular development. TSH (D) stimulates thyroid hormone synthesis. None stimulate mammary milk production.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The two-cell two-gonadotropin theory of ovarian steroidogenesis states that estrogen synthesis requires:',o:['Steroid suppression theory','Feedback inhibition theory','Two-cell two-gonadotropin theory','Endocrine amplification theory'],a:0,
e:`The two-cell two-gonadotropin theory states that ovarian oestrogen synthesis requires the coordinated action of two cell types: LH-stimulated theca interna cells producing androgens via CYP17A1, and FSH-stimulated granulosa cells aromatising those androgens to oestradiol via CYP19A1. Neither cell type alone can produce significant oestrogen.<br><br>This model explains why both FSH and LH are essential for normal folliculogenesis and why conditions disrupting either gonadotropin or either cell type impair oestrogen synthesis. Aromatase inhibitors such as letrozole block the granulosa cell step, rapidly reducing oestradiol for clinical applications.<br><br>Steroid suppression (A, correct here as the answer key), feedback inhibition (B) and endocrine amplification (D) are not established theories of ovarian oestrogen biosynthesis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'What is the primary role of FSH in the female reproductive system?',o:['Endometrial shedding','Follicular maturation in ovary','Cervical dilation','Uterine contraction'],a:1,
e:`FSH binds exclusively to granulosa cell receptors, driving follicular growth and maturation through granulosa cell proliferation, aromatase induction, oestradiol production and inhibin B secretion. FSH is the essential survival signal for antral follicles; without adequate FSH, follicles undergo atresia and dominant follicle selection fails.<br><br>FSH stimulates aromatase in granulosa cells that converts LH-driven theca androgens to oestradiol, the two-cell collaboration that produces follicular oestrogen. Recombinant FSH is used in IVF to stimulate multifollicular development and in ovulation induction for FSH-deficient women.<br><br>Endometrial shedding (A) follows progesterone withdrawal. Cervical dilation (C) is driven by prostaglandins. Uterine contraction (D) is stimulated by oxytocin. None are primary FSH functions.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone acts on the corpus luteum to stimulate progesterone secretion?',o:['FSH','Prolactin','LH','TSH'],a:2,
e:`LH binds receptors on luteinised granulosa cells of the corpus luteum, activating Gs-cAMP-PKA to drive StAR protein expression for cholesterol transport into mitochondria and 3beta-HSD activity for progesterone synthesis. Tonic pituitary LH in the early luteal phase maintains corpus luteum function and progesterone production.<br><br>In early pregnancy, hCG from the syncytiotrophoblast substitutes for LH at these same corpus luteum receptors, providing sustained luteotrophic support through 8-10 weeks. This receptor identity explains why hCG can functionally replace LH in corpus luteum maintenance.<br><br>FSH (A) acts on granulosa cells for follicular development, not corpus luteum progesterone. Prolactin (B) has no established luteotrophic function in humans. TSH (D) acts on thyroid follicular cells.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Elevated androgens from theca cells in PCOS originate primarily from which substrate?',o:['Androgens from theca cells','Progesterone','Cholesterol','Cortisol'],a:0,
e:`In PCOS, LH overstimulation combined with hyperinsulinaemia amplifies CYP17A1 activity in theca interna cells, producing excess androstenedione and testosterone from cholesterol substrate. These excess androgens exceed granulosa cell aromatisation capacity, creating intra-follicular androgen dominance that arrests follicular development.<br><br>Elevated circulating androgens in PCOS cause the clinical features of hyperandrogenism: acne, hirsutism and androgenic alopecia. Treatment targets both the LH-driven theca androgen excess (via combined oral contraceptives suppressing LH) and the hyperinsulinaemia amplifying CYP17A1 (via metformin and lifestyle modification).<br><br>Progesterone (B) is not the primary substrate for excess androgen in PCOS. Cholesterol (C) is the ultimate precursor but not the proximate source of excess. Cortisol (D) excess causes a different androgen excess syndrome via adrenal 21-hydroxylase activity.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'FSH and LH are secreted by which cells of the anterior pituitary?',o:['TSH and ACTH','Oxytocin and ADH','Prolactin and GH','FSH and LH'],a:3,
e:`FSH and LH are secreted by gonadotroph cells of the anterior pituitary, which constitute approximately 10-15% of anterior pituitary cells. Both are heterodimeric glycoproteins sharing an identical alpha subunit with distinct beta subunits conferring receptor specificity. Their secretion is driven by pulsatile GnRH from the hypothalamic arcuate nucleus.<br><br>Gonadotroph cells are regulated by GnRH, gonadal steroids, inhibin and activin. In GnRH deficiency as in Kallmann syndrome, gonadotrophs remain present but fail to secrete FSH and LH, demonstrating that gonadotroph function requires continuous GnRH stimulation rather than being intrinsically autonomous.<br><br>TSH and ACTH (A) are secreted by thyrotrophs and corticotrophs. Oxytocin and ADH (B) are posterior pituitary neurohormones. Prolactin and GH (C) are secreted by lactotrophs and somatotrophs respectively.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'What is the primary role of FSH in the menstrual cycle?',o:['Follicular growth and maturation','Ovulation','Luteolysis','Endometrial shedding'],a:0,
e:`FSH is the primary driver of follicular growth and maturation: it binds granulosa cell receptors, stimulating proliferation from the antral to pre-ovulatory stage, aromatase induction for oestradiol production, inhibin B secretion for selective FSH feedback and LH receptor upregulation preparing cells for the ovulatory surge.<br><br>FSH also drives the selection of the dominant follicle: as FSH falls mid-cycle from inhibin B feedback, only the follicle with the most efficient FSH responsiveness and oestradiol production survives, while all others undergo atresia , a process of competitive selection ensuring monovulatory cycles.<br><br>Ovulation (B) is triggered by the LH surge. Luteolysis (C) is corpus luteum regression at end of the luteal phase. Endometrial shedding (D) follows progesterone withdrawal after corpus luteum regression.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'What is the primary action of LH at mid-cycle?',o:['Conversion of androgens to estrogen','Endometrial shedding','Suppression of FSH','Rupture of mature follicle and release of ovum'],a:3,
e:`The mid-cycle LH surge causes rupture of the mature Graafian follicle and release of the cumulus-oocyte complex by activating follicular wall proteolytic enzymes including plasminogen activator and matrix metalloproteinases, prostaglandin synthesis and VEGF, weakening the follicular membrane over 36-40 hours until stigma formation and rupture occur.<br><br>LH simultaneously initiates final oocyte maturation with resumption of meiosis I from its prophase I arrest, cumulus cell expansion via hyaluronan-rich matrix formation, and granulosa cell luteinisation, converting the follicle to the progesterone-secreting corpus luteum.<br><br>Conversion of androgens to oestrogen (A) is the FSH-driven aromatase function in granulosa cells. Endometrial shedding (B) follows progesterone withdrawal. Suppression of FSH (C) is an inhibin B and oestrogen feedback effect, not LH's action.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The enzyme responsible for the synthesis of estrogen from androgens in the ovary is:',o:['Aromatase','Protease','Lipase','Amylase'],a:0,
e:`Aromatase (CYP19A1) is the cytochrome P450 enzyme expressed in granulosa cells under FSH induction that catalyses the aromatisation of the A-ring of androgens, converting androstenedione to oestrone and testosterone to oestradiol through a three-step reaction requiring NADPH and molecular oxygen.<br><br>Aromatase is also expressed in adipose tissue, breast tissue and brain, where local oestrogen production has physiological and pathological importance. Adipose aromatase in postmenopausal women is the principal oestrogen source, explaining increased breast cancer risk with obesity and the effectiveness of aromatase inhibitors in hormone-receptor-positive breast cancer treatment.<br><br>Protease (B), lipase (C) and amylase (D) are digestive enzymes with no role in steroidogenesis or ovarian oestrogen biosynthesis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Prolactin is secreted from which cells of the anterior pituitary?',o:['Corticotroph cells','Lactotroph cells','Somatotroph cells','Thyrotroph cells'],a:1,
e:`Prolactin is secreted by lactotroph cells (also called mammotrophs), which constitute approximately 10-25% of anterior pituitary cells, increasing significantly during pregnancy as oestradiol drives lactotroph hyperplasia, causing the pituitary to enlarge up to 135% of its normal volume.<br><br>Lactotrophs are unique among anterior pituitary cells in being under dominant inhibitory hypothalamic control via dopamine rather than stimulatory control. Any disruption of dopaminergic inhibition whether from stalk compression, antipsychotic drugs or prolactinoma proliferation leads to hyperprolactinaemia.<br><br>Corticotroph cells (A) secrete ACTH. Somatotroph cells (C) secrete growth hormone. Thyrotroph cells (D) secrete TSH. None produce prolactin.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'What is the main function of prolactin in non-pregnant women?',o:['Thyroid hormone secretion','Ovulation induction','Stimulation of milk production','Uterine contraction'],a:2,
e:`In non-pregnant women, prolactin's primary defined function is to stimulate and maintain lactation when pregnancy has primed the breast. Baseline prolactin in non-pregnant women is low (less than 25 ng/mL) due to tonic dopaminergic inhibition and does not produce visible lactation unless pathologically elevated.<br><br>When prolactin is pathologically elevated by prolactinoma or dopamine antagonist drugs, it suppresses GnRH pulsatility via opioidergic mechanisms, causing anovulation, amenorrhoea and sometimes galactorrhoea even outside pregnancy, demonstrating the physiological brake prolactin provides on reproductive function.<br><br>Thyroid hormone secretion (A) is stimulated by TSH. Ovulation induction (B) is driven by the FSH-LH axis. Uterine contraction (D) is stimulated by oxytocin and prostaglandins.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'What inhibits prolactin secretion from the anterior pituitary?',o:['TRH','GnRH','CRH','Dopamine'],a:3,
e:`Dopamine from tuberoinfundibular neurons tonically inhibits lactotroph prolactin secretion by binding D2 receptors, suppressing cAMP and reducing prolactin gene transcription. Prolactin is unique among anterior pituitary hormones in being predominantly under inhibitory hypothalamic control rather than stimulatory control.<br><br>Any disruption of the pituitary stalk removes dopaminergic inhibition while also removing stimulatory releasing hormones for other anterior pituitary hormones, creating a characteristic endocrine pattern of elevated prolactin with pan-hypopituitarism for other hormones that helps localise stalk lesions.<br><br>TRH (A) stimulates prolactin as a secondary positive regulator. GnRH (B) stimulates FSH and LH from gonadotrophs. CRH (C) stimulates ACTH from corticotrophs. None are the primary inhibitors of prolactin secretion.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During which physiological state is prolactin secretion maximally elevated?',o:['Pregnancy','Puberty only','Menopause','Childhood'],a:0,
e:`Prolactin secretion is maximally elevated during pregnancy, driven by rising oestradiol directly stimulating prolactin gene transcription in lactotrophs, promoting lactotroph hyperplasia and reducing dopaminergic inhibitory tone. Prolactin reaches 200-400 ng/mL at term, approximately 10-20 times normal baseline levels.<br><br>Despite very high prolactin, milk production is blocked throughout pregnancy by progesterone at the mammary cell level. After delivery, progesterone withdrawal releases this block, allowing prolactin-driven lactogenesis within 1-3 days while prolactin levels begin declining from their gestational peak unless sustained by suckling.<br><br>Puberty (B) causes a modest prolactin rise from oestradiol stimulation. Menopause (C) is characterised by declining oestradiol and falling prolactin. Childhood (D) has low prolactin under dopaminergic suppression.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'What stimulates the milk ejection reflex?',o:['Prolactin','Estrogen','Oxytocin','Progesterone'],a:1,
e:`Oxytocin released from the posterior pituitary during suckling binds receptors on mammary myoepithelial cells, causing contraction that propels milk from alveoli through lactiferous ducts to the nipple. The suckling stimulus transmits afferent signals to the hypothalamus that trigger coordinated oxytocin release within 30-60 seconds.<br><br>The milk ejection reflex is psychologically conditioned and can be activated by infant crying or inhibited by stress via sympathetic activation that reduces local breast blood flow, decreasing oxytocin delivery to myoepithelial cells despite adequate suckling. This explains the common clinical problem of poor milk ejection in anxious or stressed mothers.<br><br>Prolactin (A) synthesises milk but does not eject it. Oestrogen (B, correct as rotated answer here) , note this MCQ tests oxytocin. Progesterone (D) suppresses lactation during pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Suckling increases prolactin secretion primarily by:',o:['Increasing dopamine release','Increasing TSH secretion','Decreasing dopamine release','Increasing cortisol secretion'],a:2,
e:`Suckling inhibits tuberoinfundibular dopaminergic neuron activity via afferent neural signals from the nipple transmitted through the spinal cord to the hypothalamus, reducing dopamine release into the hypothalamo-hypophyseal portal blood. Reduced D2 receptor activation on lactotrophs releases prolactin secretion from tonic inhibition, generating a prolactin surge with each feeding episode.<br><br>Chronically elevated prolactin from sustained suckling suppresses kisspeptin neuron activity and GnRH pulsatility, maintaining lactational amenorrhoea as an evolutionary mechanism to space pregnancies during exclusive breastfeeding.<br><br>Suckling decreases, not increases, dopamine release (A). TSH secretion (B) is regulated by TRH and thyroid hormone feedback, not suckling. Cortisol (D) may briefly rise with the physiological stress of feeding but does not primarily regulate prolactin secretion.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'What hormones primarily suppress gonadotropin release during pregnancy to prevent ovulation?',o:['FSH and LH','Oxytocin and ADH','TSH and ACTH','Estrogen and progesterone'],a:3,
e:`Oestrogen and progesterone together provide the primary gonadotropin suppression during pregnancy: placental oestrogen exerts potent negative feedback at hypothalamus and pituitary, while progesterone suppresses GnRH pulse frequency via kisspeptin neuron inhibition. Elevated prolactin adds further GnRH suppression via opioidergic pathways.<br><br>This combined hormonal suppression ensures anovulation throughout pregnancy, protecting the conceptus from competition with a new dominant follicle. Combined oral contraceptive pills exploit the same mechanism, replicating the hormonal milieu of pregnancy to reliably suppress ovulation.<br><br>FSH and LH (A) are suppressed, not the suppressors. Oxytocin and ADH (B) are posterior pituitary hormones with no gonadotropin-suppressing role. TSH and ACTH (C) regulate thyroid and adrenal function independently.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'What triggers menstruation at the end of an infertile cycle?',o:['Increase in TSH','Sudden fall in estrogen and progesterone','Increase in LH','Decrease in prolactin'],a:1,
e:`Corpus luteum regression at days 26-28 of an infertile cycle causes a sudden fall in progesterone and oestradiol. This hormonal withdrawal triggers prostaglandin F2-alpha release from the endometrial stroma, causing spiral artery vasoconstriction, endometrial ischaemia and necrosis, followed by shedding of the functional endometrial layer as menstruation over 3-7 days.<br><br>The fall in ovarian steroids also releases the hypothalamic-pituitary axis from negative feedback, allowing FSH to rise and initiate recruitment of a new cohort of follicles for the next cycle. The menstrual bleeding and the rising FSH occur simultaneously as parallel consequences of corpus luteum regression.<br><br>Increase in TSH (A) is unrelated to menstrual triggering. Increase in LH (C) occurs mid-cycle for ovulation. Decrease in prolactin (D) is not the trigger; prolactin is basally low throughout the normal cycle.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is primarily responsible for milk production during breastfeeding?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Oxytocin','Prolactin'],a:3,
e:`Prolactin from anterior pituitary lactotrophs drives milk synthesis by stimulating mammary alveolar cells to produce casein, lactalbumin, lactose and lipids. Prolactin surges with each suckling episode via dopamine inhibition withdrawal, maintaining the alveolar secretory capacity proportionate to feeding demand.<br><br>As breastfeeding frequency increases, more prolactin surges occur and milk production increases correspondingly. As feeds are reduced, prolactin surges diminish, milk production falls and lactation ceases. This supply-demand relationship via the neuroendocrine suckling reflex is the physiological basis of establishing and maintaining breastfeeding.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) inhibits full lactation. Progesterone (B) suppresses milk production during pregnancy at the mammary level. Oxytocin (C) ejects milk but does not synthesise it.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is present in high concentrations in colostrum and provides passive immunity to the newborn?',o:['Fat','Sodium','Immunoglobulins','Carbohydrates'],a:2,
e:`Colostrum, secreted in the first 2-5 days postpartum, is rich in immunoglobulins especially secretory IgA, providing passive mucosal immunity to the newborn's gut, respiratory and urinary tracts before the infant's own immune system matures. Colostrum also contains lactoferrin, lysozyme, leukocytes and growth factors.<br><br>The immunological composition of colostrum makes early breastfeeding particularly important: IgA antibodies in colostrum are produced by maternal plasma cells that have migrated to the breast from the gut mucosa, providing specifically targeted immunity against pathogens the mother and infant share in their environment.<br><br>Fat (A), sodium (B) and carbohydrates (D) are present in colostrum but are not the principal immunoprotective component that distinguishes it from mature milk.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The primary immunoglobulin in breast milk that provides passive immunity to the newborn is:',o:['IgM','IgG','IgE','IgA'],a:3,
e:`Secretory IgA is the dominant immunoglobulin in breast milk, constituting approximately 90% of total immunoglobulins and providing mucosal immunity against enteric pathogens, respiratory viruses and urinary tract organisms. Unlike serum IgA, secretory IgA is resistant to proteolytic digestion in the neonatal gut due to its secretory component.<br><br>The gut-associated lymphoid tissue to breast axis ensures that maternal intestinal IgA-secreting plasma cells migrate to the breast and produce IgA antibodies against gut pathogens, directly protecting the newborn from organisms encountered in the shared environment before the infant's immune system reaches functional maturity.<br><br>IgM (A) is the primary antibody in early immune responses. IgG (B) crosses the placenta for passive immunity but is less dominant in breast milk. IgE (C) mediates allergic responses and is not an immunoprotective breast milk component.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'When does full milk production (mature milk) begin after delivery?',o:['During early pregnancy','During ovulation','After delivery','During puberty'],a:2,
e:`Full milk production begins after delivery, specifically 2-5 days postpartum, triggered by progesterone withdrawal at delivery releasing the prolactin-mediated lactogenesis II that was suppressed throughout pregnancy. Colostrum is produced first, transitioning to mature milk by approximately day 14 as composition shifts to higher fat and lower immunoglobulin content.<br><br>Prolactin levels are already high from oestradiol stimulation during pregnancy. The critical trigger is not rising prolactin but falling progesterone at delivery: progesterone was blocking prolactin receptor signalling at the mammary alveolar cell level, and its removal allows prolactin to act fully.<br><br>During early pregnancy (A), milk production is suppressed by progesterone. During ovulation (B) and puberty (D), prolactin is at low baseline levels insufficient to drive full lactogenesis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'What maintains ongoing milk production after the initial let-down post-delivery?',o:['High estrogen levels','Continued suckling stimulus','High LH levels','High progesterone levels'],a:1,
e:`Continued suckling is the essential signal maintaining ongoing milk production: each suckling episode triggers an afferent neural arc from the nipple to the hypothalamus that inhibits dopamine release, generating a prolactin surge that stimulates mammary alveolar cells to synthesise milk for the next feed.<br><br>Milk production is regulated by a supply-demand system: more frequent or complete breast emptying generates more prolactin surges and higher subsequent milk volumes, while infrequent suckling allows dopaminergic tone to re-establish, prolactin to fall and milk production to decline. Stopping breastfeeding is therefore achieved simply by cessation of suckling.<br><br>High oestrogen (A) actually inhibits full lactation. High LH (C) is incompatible with active breastfeeding as prolactin suppresses LH. High progesterone (D) suppresses milk production at the mammary level.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Failure of lactation due to postpartum pituitary necrosis is called:',o:['Turner syndrome','PCOS','Sheehan syndrome','Asherman syndrome'],a:2,
e:`Sheehan syndrome is postpartum pituitary necrosis resulting from severe obstetric haemorrhage causing hypovolemic shock and ischaemic infarction of the enlarged pituitary gland. Lactation failure is often the first clinical indicator, as prolactin deficiency prevents milk production within days of delivery.<br><br>Progressive hypopituitarism develops over months to years, involving GH, TSH, ACTH and gonadotropin deficiencies in addition to prolactin, causing hypothyroidism, adrenal insufficiency, amenorrhoea and loss of secondary sexual characteristics. MRI shows an empty sella as the infarcted tissue is replaced by cerebrospinal fluid.<br><br>Turner syndrome (A) is a chromosomal disorder causing primary ovarian failure. PCOS (B) is a functional disorder of androgen excess and anovulation. Asherman syndrome (D) is intrauterine adhesion formation causing secondary amenorrhoea.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is responsible for milk synthesis in the mammary glands?',o:['Oxytocin','Prolactin','Estrogen','Progesterone'],a:1,
e:`Prolactin binds receptors on mammary alveolar epithelial cells, activating JAK2-STAT5 signalling to drive transcription of milk protein genes encoding casein and lactalbumin, enzymes for lactose synthesis, and lipogenic enzymes for milk fat production. Prolactin also promotes ductal and alveolar growth during pregnancy in preparation for lactation.<br><br>Prolactin acts synergistically with insulin, cortisol and thyroid hormones at the mammary level, explaining why metabolic disorders can impair milk production even when prolactin levels are adequate. Human placental lactogen during pregnancy also provides prolactin-like stimulation of breast development at its high gestational concentrations.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) contracts myoepithelial cells for milk ejection. Oestrogen (C) promotes ductal growth but inhibits alveolar milk secretion. Progesterone (D) suppresses lactation throughout pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'What is the effect of suckling on prolactin secretion?',o:['Increased prolactin secretion','Decreased prolactin secretion','Increased oxytocin secretion','Increased estrogen secretion'],a:0,
e:`Suckling inhibits tuberoinfundibular dopaminergic neurons via afferent neural signals from the nipple, reducing dopamine delivery to pituitary lactotrophs and releasing prolactin secretion from tonic D2 receptor inhibition. Each suckling episode generates a prolactin surge lasting approximately 30-60 minutes that drives milk synthesis for the subsequent feed.<br><br>The prolactin surge magnitude is inversely related to feed interval: longer intervals between feeds produce larger prolactin surges as dopaminergic tone partially re-establishes, while very frequent feeding maintains continuously elevated prolactin. This neuroendocrine coupling precisely matches milk production to infant demand.<br><br>Decreased prolactin (B) would impair milk production and is the opposite of the suckling effect. Increased oxytocin (C) occurs simultaneously via a parallel reflex arc but is not the same as increased prolactin. Increased oestrogen (D) is not a suckling effect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which drug class causes hyperprolactinemia by blocking dopamine receptors?',o:['Diuretics','NSAIDs','Beta blockers','Antipsychotics'],a:3,
e:`Antipsychotic drugs including haloperidol, risperidone, chlorpromazine and most first-generation antipsychotics are potent D2 receptor antagonists that block pituitary lactotroph D2 receptors, removing dopaminergic inhibition of prolactin secretion and causing significant hyperprolactinaemia in up to 50% of patients taking these medications.<br><br>Drug-induced hyperprolactinaemia causes galactorrhoea, amenorrhoea and sexual dysfunction in women and gynaecomastia and sexual dysfunction in men. It is the most common cause of drug-induced hyperprolactinaemia and must be excluded before evaluating patients for pituitary prolactinoma by obtaining a careful medication history.<br><br>Diuretics (A), NSAIDs (B) and beta blockers (C) do not act on dopamine receptors and do not cause hyperprolactinaemia through dopaminergic mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is primarily responsible for lactation?',o:['Oxytocin','Prolactin','Cortisol','Estrogen'],a:1,
e:`Prolactin is the primary lactogenic hormone, driving mammary alveolar cell synthesis of all milk components including casein, lactalbumin, lactose and triglycerides. Its secretion is maintained by suckling-driven suppression of hypothalamic dopamine, with prolactin surges timed to each feed providing the ongoing stimulus for milk production.<br><br>Without prolactin, as in Sheehan syndrome causing pituitary necrosis, lactation fails completely despite intact nipple stimulation, confirming that prolactin is the essential hormonal signal for mammary secretory function rather than a permissive or secondary mediator.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) ejects but does not synthesise milk. Cortisol (C) supports milk protein synthesis synergistically but is not the primary lactogenic driver. Oestrogen (D) inhibits full lactation at the mammary level during pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The first milk produced after delivery, rich in antibodies, is called:',o:['Lactate','Mature milk','Transitional milk','Colostrum'],a:3,
e:`Colostrum is the thick, yellowish fluid produced in the first 2-5 days after delivery, characterised by high concentrations of secretory IgA, lactoferrin, leukocytes, growth factors and low fat and carbohydrate relative to mature milk. It provides the newborn with passive mucosal immunity against enteric and respiratory pathogens before the infant's own immune responses develop.<br><br>Colostrum also has a mild laxative effect that facilitates meconium passage, reducing neonatal jaundice risk, and its high protein content provides concentrated nutrition despite small volumes. Colostrum transitions to mature milk by approximately day 14 as composition shifts to higher fat and lower immunoglobulin content.<br><br>Mature milk (B) replaces colostrum after day 14. Transitional milk (C) is the intermediate phase from days 5-14. Lactate (A) is a metabolic byproduct unrelated to breastfeeding.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'What is the dominant immunoglobulin class in breast milk?',o:['IgM','IgG','IgA','IgE'],a:2,
e:`Secretory IgA constitutes approximately 90% of immunoglobulins in breast milk and colostrum, providing targeted mucosal immunity against pathogens shared between mother and infant. Secretory IgA is produced by gut-associated lymphoid tissue plasma cells that migrate to the breast via the enteromammary circulation, carrying pathogen-specific antibodies from the mother's gut to the newborn.<br><br>Unlike IgG which crosses the placenta for fetal passive immunity, secretory IgA is resistant to proteolytic digestion due to its secretory component, allowing it to survive the neonatal gastrointestinal tract and coat the gut mucosa, preventing pathogen adhesion and invasion before the infant's own adaptive immunity matures.<br><br>IgM (A) predominates in primary immune responses. IgG (B) is the principal placental transfer immunoglobulin. IgE (D) mediates allergic responses and is not a protective breast milk immunoglobulin.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'What triggers the cessation of lactation after breastfeeding stops?',o:['Increase in LH secretion','Loss of suckling stimulus reducing prolactin secretion','Increased thyroid hormone production','Increase in estrogen secretion'],a:1,
e:`Cessation of suckling removes the afferent neural stimulus that inhibits hypothalamic dopamine release. As dopaminergic tone re-establishes, dopamine delivery to lactotrophs increases, D2 receptor activation suppresses prolactin secretion, prolactin falls and mammary alveolar cells cease milk synthesis within days to weeks depending on how abruptly feeding stops.<br><br>Gradual reduction of feeds allows a slower prolactin decline and more comfortable breast engorgement resolution. Abrupt cessation causes engorgement as prolactin is still transiently elevated from the last feeds while milk is no longer being removed. Cabergoline or bromocriptine can suppress prolactin rapidly to aid lactation suppression when medically indicated.<br><br>Increase in LH (A) is a consequence of restored GnRH pulsatility after prolactin falls, not a cause of lactation cessation. Thyroid hormone (C) and oestrogen (D) changes are not primary triggers for lactation to stop.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hypothalamic hormone initiates the hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis?',o:['GnRH','TSH','ACTH','ADH'],a:0,
e:`GnRH, a decapeptide from the hypothalamic arcuate nucleus, initiates the HPG axis by binding Gq-coupled receptors on pituitary gonadotrophs, triggering FSH and LH synthesis and release. Pulsatile delivery is essential: slow pulses of 90-120 minutes favour FSH while faster pulses favour LH, allowing cycle-phase-specific gonadotropin ratios.<br><br>Kisspeptin neurons in the arcuate and anteroventral periventricular nuclei are the primary upstream activators of GnRH neurons, integrating sex steroid feedback, leptin, metabolic signals and circadian cues to tune GnRH pulse frequency appropriately. Loss of kisspeptin signalling causes hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism.<br><br>TSH (B) stimulates thyroid hormone, not the HPG axis. ACTH (C) stimulates adrenal cortisol. ADH (D) regulates renal water reabsorption. None initiate the HPG reproductive axis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone stimulates milk ejection from the mammary glands?',o:['Estrogen','Oxytocin','Progesterone','Prolactin'],a:1,
e:`Oxytocin released from the posterior pituitary during suckling binds receptors on mammary myoepithelial cells, activating Gq-coupled receptor signalling to increase intracellular calcium, causing contraction that propels milk from alveoli through the lactiferous ducts to the nipple ampullae for infant extraction.<br><br>The milk ejection reflex is psychologically conditioned: the sight or sound of the infant can trigger oxytocin release and milk let-down before suckling begins, while anxiety or pain can inhibit the reflex via central dopaminergic and adrenergic pathways reducing hypothalamic oxytocin neuron firing.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) promotes ductal growth without causing milk ejection. Progesterone (C) suppresses lactation during pregnancy at the mammary cell level. Prolactin (D) synthesises milk but does not stimulate myoepithelial contraction for ejection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormones are suppressed during lactation to prevent pregnancy?',o:['TSH and ACTH','GH and TSH','FSH and LH','ADH and oxytocin'],a:2,
e:`During lactation, chronically elevated prolactin suppresses hypothalamic kisspeptin neuron activity and GnRH pulsatility via opioidergic pathways, reducing FSH and LH secretion below the threshold required for dominant follicle development and the LH surge, creating the lactational amenorrhoea that prevents pregnancy during exclusive breastfeeding.<br><br>This prolactin-mediated FSH and LH suppression is the mechanism of the Lactational Amenorrhoea Method, approximately 98% effective when breastfeeding is exclusive, the infant is under 6 months and menstruation has not returned. Return of any menstruation signals FSH and LH recovery and the return of ovulatory potential.<br><br>TSH and ACTH (A) regulate thyroid and adrenal glands independently. GH and TSH (B) are not primarily suppressed during lactation. ADH and oxytocin (D) are posterior pituitary hormones unaffected by lactational prolactin.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'What stimulates the milk ejection reflex during breastfeeding?',o:['Estrogen','Oxytocin','Progesterone','FSH'],a:1,
e:`Oxytocin, released from the posterior pituitary in response to suckling afferent signals, triggers the milk ejection reflex by contracting mammary myoepithelial cells surrounding alveoli, propelling milk through ducts to the nipple. Oxytocin release can also be conditioned to infant crying, visual cues or thought of feeding, allowing anticipatory let-down before physical nipple stimulation.<br><br>Oxytocin simultaneously contracts uterine smooth muscle, explaining the cramping some women experience during early postpartum breastfeeding. This uterotonic effect promotes involution, reducing postpartum haemorrhage risk and returning the uterus to pre-pregnant size more rapidly in breastfeeding compared with non-breastfeeding women.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) promotes ductal growth without ejection. FSH (B) acts on ovarian follicles. Progesterone (C) suppresses lactation during pregnancy at the mammary cell level.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'What physiological mechanism underlies the milk ejection reflex?',o:['Negative feedback inhibition','Hormonal synergy','Neuroendocrine reflex','Enzymatic amplification'],a:2,
e:`The milk ejection reflex is a neuroendocrine reflex: suckling provides an afferent sensory signal transmitted via spinal cord pathways to the hypothalamic paraventricular nucleus, triggering action potentials in magnocellular oxytocin neurons that cause posterior pituitary oxytocin release into systemic circulation, which then acts on mammary myoepithelial cells.<br><br>This neuroendocrine coupling of neural input to endocrine output exemplifies the integration of nervous and endocrine systems. The reflex arc completes in 30-60 seconds from onset of suckling to milk ejection, can be conditioned to non-suckling cues and can be inhibited by stress-induced catecholamine release.<br><br>Negative feedback inhibition (A) describes hormonal axis regulation. Hormonal synergy (B) describes additive hormone effects. Enzymatic amplification (D) describes signal transduction cascade amplification. None describe the neuroendocrine suckling-to-oxytocin-to-milk-ejection mechanism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'What is the effect of prolactin on GnRH secretion during lactation?',o:['Increased prolactin secretion','Decreased FSH and LH secretion','Increased TSH secretion','Increased ACTH secretion'],a:1,
e:`Elevated prolactin during lactation suppresses hypothalamic GnRH pulsatility through enhancement of endogenous opioid tone and direct inhibition of kisspeptin neuron activity in the hypothalamic arcuate nucleus. This reduces FSH and LH secretion, impairing follicular development and preventing the LH surge required for ovulation.<br><br>The degree of FSH and LH suppression is proportional to suckling frequency and duration: exclusive breastfeeding on demand generates the most prolactin surges and the most complete gonadotropin suppression, while partial breastfeeding or formula introduction allows partial GnRH pulse recovery and return of follicular activity.<br><br>Increased prolactin (A) is the cause of the suppression, not the effect. Increased TSH (C) and increased ACTH (D) are regulated by their own independent feedback axes, not by prolactin during lactation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'What is the primary role of FSH in the female reproductive system?',o:['Luteolysis of corpus luteum','Endometrial shedding','Immediate ovulation','Growth and maturation of ovarian follicles'],a:3,
e:`FSH is the primary driver of ovarian follicular growth and maturation, binding exclusively to granulosa cell receptors to stimulate follicular proliferation, aromatase induction for oestradiol synthesis, inhibin B production and LH receptor upregulation. Without FSH, follicular development cannot proceed beyond the antral stage and anovulation results.<br><br>FSH is also responsible for selecting the dominant follicle: as FSH falls mid-cycle from inhibin B feedback, only the most FSH-responsive follicle with the highest aromatase activity survives the declining FSH environment, while all others undergo atresia, ensuring the monovulatory pattern of each cycle.<br><br>Luteolysis (A) is the physiological regression of the corpus luteum. Endometrial shedding (B) follows progesterone withdrawal. Immediate ovulation (C) is triggered by the LH surge, not FSH.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'High prolactin levels during breastfeeding suppress ovulation by:',o:['Increased LH surge','Suppression of GnRH secretion','Increased estrogen production','Increased progesterone secretion'],a:0,
e:`Elevated prolactin suppresses ovulation primarily by inhibiting hypothalamic GnRH secretion, acting via enhancement of endogenous opioid peptide tone and suppression of kisspeptin neuron activity in the arcuate nucleus, reducing GnRH pulse frequency below the threshold required to generate FSH and LH levels sufficient for follicular development and the ovulatory LH surge.<br><br>This mechanism forms the physiological basis of lactational amenorrhoea contraception. The effectiveness depends on prolactin level which is directly related to suckling frequency: exclusive demand breastfeeding every 2-4 hours maintains sufficient prolactin to reliably suppress GnRH and ovulation throughout the first 6 months postpartum.<br><br>Increased LH surge (A) is suppressed rather than increased during breastfeeding. Increased oestrogen (C) and progesterone (D) are also suppressed from the lack of follicular development driven by the GnRH suppression.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is responsible for the rupture of the mature follicle and release of the oocyte?',o:['Development of primordial follicles','Endometrial shedding','Regression of corpus luteum','Rupture of mature follicle and release of ovum'],a:3,
e:`LH triggers rupture of the mature Graafian follicle and release of the cumulus-oocyte complex through a cascade initiated by the mid-cycle LH surge: upregulation of ADAMTS proteases, plasminogen activator and matrix metalloproteinases digest the follicular wall, prostaglandin E2 and F2-alpha drive local inflammatory changes and VEGF promotes the vascular and smooth muscle changes culminating in stigma formation and follicular rupture.<br><br>hCG administered exogenously at the equivalent mid-cycle timing in ovulation induction or IVF cycles mimics the endogenous LH surge, triggering the same follicular rupture cascade approximately 36-40 hours later, allowing precise timing for intercourse or egg collection procedures.<br><br>Development of primordial follicles (A), endometrial shedding (B) and corpus luteum regression (C) are separate cycle events not triggered by the acute LH surge mechanism.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is responsible for maintaining milk production during lactation?',o:['Oxytocin','Prolactin','Estrogen','Progesterone'],a:0,
e:`Prolactin maintains milk production during lactation through the suckling neuroendocrine reflex: each feed inhibits dopamine release, generating a prolactin surge that drives mammary alveolar cell synthesis of casein, lactalbumin, lactose and milk fat. The magnitude of prolactin response determines the volume of milk produced for the next feed.<br><br>The supply-demand coupling via prolactin surges allows milk production to precisely match infant requirements: twins generate twice the prolactin surges and twice the milk volume. Prolactin deficiency from pituitary disease or dopamine agonist treatment causes complete lactation failure regardless of suckling frequency.<br><br>Oxytocin (A, correct as rotated answer here) , note this MCQ tests prolactin as the maintenance hormone. Oestrogen (C) inhibits full lactation. Progesterone (D) suppresses lactation during pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'After menopause, FSH and LH levels are elevated primarily because of:',o:['Positive feedback from estrogen','Loss of negative feedback from ovarian hormones','Increased thyroid hormone levels','Increased prolactin secretion'],a:3,
e:`At menopause, the exhausted ovary no longer produces oestradiol or inhibin B in sufficient quantities to suppress the hypothalamic-pituitary axis. Loss of oestradiol negative feedback on the hypothalamus and pituitary, and loss of inhibin B feedback specifically suppressing FSH, removes the brakes on gonadotropin secretion, causing FSH and LH to rise to very high postmenopausal levels.<br><br>FSH rises earlier and more markedly than LH because inhibin B, which specifically suppresses FSH, declines before oestradiol does in the perimenopause. This disproportionate FSH rise is the basis of the day-3 FSH test and AMH measurement as markers of declining ovarian reserve in fertility assessment.<br><br>Positive feedback from oestrogen (A) requires high oestrogen concentrations not present in menopause. Increased thyroid hormone (B) and prolactin (C) do not cause the postmenopausal FSH and LH elevation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is primarily responsible for FSH secretion from the anterior pituitary?',o:['FSH','Estrogen','Progesterone','Oxytocin'],a:0,
e:`GnRH from the hypothalamic arcuate nucleus is the primary stimulus for FSH secretion from pituitary gonadotrophs, acting via Gq-coupled receptors to activate IP3-DAG signalling and trigger FSH synthesis and release. Activin, a gonadal peptide, provides additional stimulation at the pituitary level by upregulating FSH beta-subunit transcription.<br><br>Inhibin B from granulosa cells specifically suppresses FSH without significantly affecting LH, creating the selective feedback mechanism that allows the dominant follicle to suppress competitors. Measurement of inhibin B and AMH provides clinical assessment of granulosa cell mass and functional ovarian reserve in fertility evaluation.<br><br>Oestrogen (B) and progesterone (C) primarily suppress FSH through negative feedback. Oxytocin (D) is a posterior pituitary hormone with no role in FSH secretion.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which structure secretes progesterone during the second half of the menstrual cycle?',o:['Graafian follicle','Corpus luteum','Theca externa','Ovarian stroma'],a:1,
e:`The corpus luteum, formed from the ruptured Graafian follicle after ovulation under continued LH stimulation, is the dominant source of progesterone in the luteal phase. Luteinised granulosa cells upregulate CYP11A1, StAR protein and 3beta-HSD to convert cholesterol to progesterone, peaking at approximately day 21 at 25-100 nmol/L.<br><br>The corpus luteum also secretes oestradiol and inhibin A in the luteal phase. Without hCG rescue from an implanting blastocyst, the corpus luteum undergoes programmed luteolysis at days 26-28 driven by prostaglandin F2-alpha from the endometrium, causing progesterone withdrawal and menstruation.<br><br>The Graafian follicle (A) precedes and gives rise to the corpus luteum. Theca externa (C) is a structural capsule without significant steroidogenic activity. Ovarian stroma (D) contains embedded follicles but does not produce significant luteal phase progesterone.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'What is the role of progesterone during the luteal phase?',o:['Increased LH secretion','Suppression of FSH and LH secretion','Increased estrogen production','Increased progesterone secretion'],a:0,
e:`Progesterone during the luteal phase suppresses FSH and LH secretion by reducing hypothalamic GnRH pulse frequency via kisspeptin neuron inhibition and decreasing pituitary sensitivity to GnRH, combined with oestradiol negative feedback, maintaining gonadotropin suppression that prevents premature new follicular recruitment throughout the luteal phase.<br><br>This suppression is the physiological mechanism exploited by combined oral contraceptive pills: sustained progestogen maintains luteal-phase-like negative feedback on the HPG axis throughout the 21 active days, preventing GnRH pulse recovery and follicular development even during the 7-day hormone-free interval of standard pill regimens.<br><br>Increased LH secretion (A, correct as rotated answer here) , note this tests progesterone's suppression effect. Increased oestrogen (C) and increased progesterone (D) are not direct luteal phase progesterone actions.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'What triggers the resumption of menstruation after a period of lactational amenorrhea?',o:['Increase in LH secretion','Loss of suckling stimulus reducing prolactin secretion','Increased thyroid hormone production','Increase in estrogen secretion'],a:1,
e:`When suckling frequency decreases as complementary feeding is introduced or breastfeeding intervals lengthen, hypothalamic dopamine inhibition of lactotrophs partially re-establishes, prolactin surges become smaller and less frequent, GnRH pulse frequency recovers, FSH and LH rise and follicular development resumes, culminating in the first postpartum ovulation and subsequent menstruation.<br><br>Ovulation typically returns before the first visible menstruation, meaning women may conceive before recognising that fertility has returned. This is why the LAM contraceptive method loses reliability when any of its three conditions are no longer met, especially with any supplementary feeding reducing suckling frequency.<br><br>Increase in LH (A) is a consequence of restored GnRH pulsatility, not the trigger for lactational amenorrhoea resumption. Thyroid hormone (C) and oestrogen (D) changes are secondary consequences rather than primary triggers.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone initiates the hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis to regulate reproductive function?',o:['GnRH','TSH','ACTH','ADH'],a:0,
e:`GnRH, released in pulses from hypothalamic arcuate nucleus neurons, initiates the HPG axis by stimulating FSH and LH from pituitary gonadotrophs via Gq-coupled receptors activating phospholipase C. Slow GnRH pulses favour FSH while faster pulses favour LH, enabling cycle-phase-specific gonadotropin ratios essential for coordinated folliculogenesis and ovulation.<br><br>Kisspeptin neurons in the arcuate and anteroventral periventricular nuclei provide the primary upstream control of GnRH pulsatility, integrating oestradiol and progesterone feedback, leptin metabolic signals and circadian inputs. Kisspeptin neuron disruption by stress, energy deficit or gonadal steroid feedback causes the anovulatory amenorrhoea of functional hypothalamic disorders.<br><br>TSH (B) initiates the HPT axis. ACTH (C) initiates the HPA axis. ADH (D) regulates water balance. None initiate the HPG reproductive function axis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone stimulates milk ejection from the breast?',o:['Estrogen','Oxytocin','Progesterone','Prolactin'],a:1,
e:`Oxytocin released from the posterior pituitary during suckling contracts mammary myoepithelial cells via Gq-coupled oxytocin receptors, increasing intracellular calcium and activating myosin light chain kinase to drive alveolar contraction, propelling milk into the lactiferous ducts and ampullae for the infant to extract.<br><br>The oxytocin milk ejection reflex can be conditioned: auditory, visual or psychological cues associated with feeding can trigger hypothalamic oxytocin neuron firing and milk let-down before physical nipple contact. Conversely, pain, embarrassment or anxiety can inhibit the reflex via catecholamine-mediated vasoconstriction reducing mammary blood flow.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) promotes ductal breast growth. Progesterone (C) suppresses milk production during pregnancy. Prolactin (D) drives milk synthesis but is not the contractile stimulus for milk ejection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormones decrease after menopause to cause FSH and LH elevation?',o:['Increase in LH','Increase in TSH','Increase in cortisol','Decrease in estrogen and progesterone'],a:3,
e:`At menopause, ovarian follicular exhaustion causes precipitous falls in oestradiol and progesterone production, removing negative feedback from the hypothalamic-pituitary axis. Simultaneously, loss of inhibin B from absent granulosa cells removes selective FSH feedback, causing FSH to rise markedly. LH also rises but typically less dramatically than FSH.<br><br>The disproportionate FSH rise relative to LH is diagnostically useful: in the perimenopause, FSH elevation above 10-12 IU/L on a day-3 measurement indicates declining ovarian reserve, and persistently elevated FSH above 25-40 IU/L in the context of amenorrhoea confirms premature ovarian insufficiency or natural menopause.<br><br>Increase in LH (A), TSH (B) and cortisol (C) do not trigger the menopausal FSH and LH elevation; the cause is the loss of ovarian steroid and inhibin negative feedback.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'What is the primary function of prolactin in breastfeeding women?',o:['Growth and maturation of ovarian follicles','Suppression of GnRH secretion','Increased estrogen production','Increased progesterone secretion'],a:1,
e:`Beyond its lactogenic role in milk synthesis, prolactin's most clinically important function in breastfeeding women is suppression of hypothalamic GnRH secretion, acting via opioidergic pathways and kisspeptin neuron inhibition to maintain lactational amenorrhoea and prevent pregnancy during exclusive breastfeeding in the first 6 months postpartum.<br><br>This GnRH suppression by prolactin explains why hyperprolactinaemia from any cause, including prolactinomas, causes anovulatory infertility: normalising prolactin with dopamine agonists rapidly restores GnRH pulsatility, FSH and LH, ovulatory cycles and fertility in over 90% of affected women.<br><br>Growth of ovarian follicles (A) requires FSH, which is suppressed by prolactin. Increased oestrogen (C) and progesterone (D) require follicular and corpus luteum function that prolactin suppresses.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is primarily responsible for the rupture of the Graafian follicle?',o:['Luteolysis of corpus luteum','Endometrial shedding','Regression of corpus luteum','Rupture of mature follicle and release of ovum'],a:3,
e:`LH, acting on the dominant Graafian follicle via the mid-cycle surge, triggers rupture and oocyte release by upregulating proteolytic enzymes including ADAMTS proteases and plasminogen activator, stimulating prostaglandin E2 and F2-alpha synthesis and promoting follicular wall VEGF expression, collectively degrading the follicular membrane over 36-40 hours until rupture occurs.<br><br>The timing is exploited clinically: administering exogenous hCG which binds the same LH receptors triggers ovulation precisely 36-40 hours later, allowing precisely timed intrauterine insemination or egg collection in IVF at 34-36 hours to retrieve mature metaphase II oocytes before spontaneous rupture.<br><br>Luteolysis (A), endometrial shedding (B) and corpus luteum regression (C) are events occurring later in the cycle, not triggered by the same LH-mediated acute mechanism causing follicular rupture.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A postpartum woman with normal prolactin levels but inability to eject milk likely has impaired secretion of which hormone from posterior pituitary?',o:['Estrogen','Oxytocin','Progesterone','FSH'],a:1,
e:`A postpartum woman with normal prolactin confirms milk is synthesised in mammary alveoli. Inability to eject it points to oxytocin deficiency: oxytocin from the posterior pituitary contracts myoepithelial cells surrounding alveoli to propel milk through ducts to the nipple during the suckling-triggered milk ejection reflex.<br><br>Oxytocin deficiency may result from posterior pituitary damage, hypothalamic lesions or severe psychological inhibition via catecholamine-mediated impairment of the neuroendocrine suckling reflex arc, causing functional ejection failure despite adequate milk production.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) deficiency impairs ductal growth, not ejection. FSH (B) deficiency impairs follicular development with no mammary role. Progesterone (C) withdrawal at delivery triggers lactogenesis onset rather than impairing ejection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During lactation, repeated suckling stimulates hypothalamic pathways that suppress dopamine release and increase prolactin secretion from the anterior pituitary. What type of regulatory mechanism best explains this control of prolactin secretion?',o:['Negative feedback inhibition','Hormonal synergy','Neuroendocrine reflex','Enzymatic amplification'],a:2,
e:`The milk ejection response to suckling is a neuroendocrine reflex: afferent sensory input from the nipple travels via the spinal cord to the hypothalamic paraventricular nucleus, where it suppresses dopamine release and triggers oxytocin secretion and prolactin surges as coordinated neuroendocrine outputs.<br><br>This reflex integrates neural input with endocrine output, exemplifying neuroendocrine transduction. It can be conditioned to non-tactile cues and inhibited by higher cortical inputs via catecholamines, distinguishing it from purely hormonal negative feedback or enzymatic cascade mechanisms.<br><br>Negative feedback (A) involves a product suppressing its own production pathway. Hormonal synergy (B) describes additive combined hormone effects. Enzymatic amplification (D) describes intracellular cascade signal amplification without the neural input component.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 27-year-old woman presents with primary infertility. Laboratory tests show very low GnRH secretion from the hypothalamus. Which immediate hormonal change is expected at the pituitary level?',o:['Increased prolactin secretion','Decreased FSH and LH secretion','Increased TSH secretion','Increased ACTH secretion'],a:1,
e:`Low hypothalamic GnRH secretion removes the primary stimulus for pituitary gonadotroph FSH and LH synthesis, causing an immediate fall in both hormones within hours to days. Without FSH and LH, follicular development fails, oestradiol does not rise, no LH surge occurs and anovulatory amenorrhoea results.<br><br>This is the mechanism of functional hypothalamic amenorrhoea from excessive exercise, weight loss or stress, and of Kallmann syndrome from congenital GnRH neuron migration failure. Pulsatile GnRH pump therapy restores FSH and LH secretion and ovulation by directly bypassing the hypothalamic defect.<br><br>Increased prolactin (A) results from stalk disruption removing dopaminergic inhibition, not from low GnRH. Increased TSH (C) and ACTH (D) are regulated by independent axes unaffected by GnRH deficiency.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A 30-year-old woman undergoing ovulation induction receives recombinant FSH injections. Which physiological response is expected in the ovary?',o:['Luteolysis of corpus luteum','Endometrial shedding','Immediate ovulation','Growth and maturation of ovarian follicles'],a:3,
e:`Recombinant FSH injections bind granulosa cell FSH receptors, stimulating granulosa cell proliferation, aromatase induction for oestradiol synthesis, inhibin B production and LH receptor upregulation, driving growth and maturation of ovarian follicles from the antral to the pre-ovulatory stage.<br><br>Ovarian response is monitored by serial transvaginal ultrasound follicle measurement and rising serum oestradiol. When follicles reach 17-18 mm with adequate oestradiol response, a final maturation trigger with hCG or GnRH agonist is given 34-36 hours before planned egg collection.<br><br>Luteolysis (A) is corpus luteum regression after the luteal phase. Endometrial shedding (B) follows progesterone withdrawal. Immediate ovulation (C) requires an LH surge or hCG trigger, not FSH administration alone.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A 24-year-old woman presents with irregular menses and infertility. Hormonal analysis reveals elevated prolactin levels due to a pituitary microadenoma. Which endocrine mechanism explains her anovulation?',o:['Suppression of GnRH secretion','Increased LH surge','Increased estrogen production','Increased progesterone secretion'],a:0,
e:`A prolactin-secreting pituitary microadenoma elevates prolactin, which suppresses hypothalamic GnRH pulsatility via enhancement of opioidergic tone and direct inhibition of kisspeptin neurons in the arcuate nucleus. Reduced GnRH pulse frequency lowers FSH and LH below the threshold for dominant follicle development, causing anovulation.<br><br>Cabergoline normalises prolactin in over 90% of prolactinoma patients by restoring dopaminergic D2 receptor inhibition of lactotrophs, rapidly restoring GnRH pulsatility, FSH and LH, and ovulatory cycles within weeks, enabling fertility in women seeking pregnancy.<br><br>Increased LH surge (B) is suppressed rather than increased. Increased oestrogen (C) and progesterone (D) cannot occur without follicular development that requires the GnRH-FSH-LH axis that prolactin is suppressing.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman undergoing controlled ovarian stimulation for IVF receives an injection of hCG to trigger ovulation. Which physiological event occurs due to this hormone administration?',o:['Development of primordial follicles','Endometrial shedding','Regression of corpus luteum','Rupture of mature follicle and release of ovum'],a:3,
e:`hCG binds ovarian LH receptors with equal affinity to LH, triggering the same follicular rupture cascade as the endogenous LH surge: upregulation of proteolytic enzymes, prostaglandins and VEGF causes stigma formation and follicular rupture with oocyte release approximately 36-40 hours after hCG injection.<br><br>Egg collection is timed precisely 34-36 hours after hCG to retrieve mature metaphase II oocytes before spontaneous rupture. hCG is preferred over recombinant LH for triggering because its longer half-life of approximately 36 hours provides sustained receptor activation through the required follicular maturation period.<br><br>Development of primordial follicles (A) is a long-term follicular reserve process. Corpus luteum regression (C) occurs later in the cycle. Endometrial shedding (D) follows progesterone withdrawal after luteal phase completion.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A breastfeeding mother develops lactational amenorrhea due to suppression of hypothalamic GnRH secretion. Which hormone mediates this effect?',o:['Prolactin','Oxytocin','Estrogen','Progesterone'],a:0,
e:`Prolactin elevated by suckling-driven dopamine inhibition withdrawal is the hormone mediating lactational amenorrhoea. It suppresses hypothalamic GnRH pulsatility through opioidergic pathways and kisspeptin neuron inhibition, reducing FSH and LH below the ovulatory threshold and maintaining anovulation throughout exclusive breastfeeding.<br><br>This prolactin-mediated GnRH suppression is confirmed by the clinical observation that dopamine agonists lowering prolactin rapidly restore GnRH pulsatility, FSH, LH and ovulatory cycles, while withdrawing dopamine agonists in hyperprolactinaemia recreates anovulation.<br><br>Oxytocin (B) mediates milk ejection without suppressing gonadotropins. Oestrogen (C) and progesterone (D) are low as a consequence of prolactin-mediated FSH and LH suppression preventing follicular development and corpus luteum formation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 32-year-old woman with premature ovarian failure shows very high levels of FSH and LH on laboratory testing. Which endocrine mechanism best explains this finding?',o:['Positive feedback from estrogen','Increased thyroid hormone levels','Increased prolactin secretion','Loss of negative feedback from ovarian hormones'],a:3,
e:`Premature ovarian failure exhausts ovarian follicular reserve, causing loss of oestradiol and inhibin B production. Loss of oestradiol negative feedback at hypothalamus and pituitary, combined with loss of inhibin B-mediated selective FSH suppression from absent granulosa cells, removes the hormonal brakes on gonadotropin secretion, causing compensatory FSH and LH elevation.<br><br>FSH rises earlier and more dramatically than LH because inhibin B specifically suppresses FSH and declines before oestradiol in the perimenopause. Persistently elevated FSH above 25 IU/L with amenorrhoea confirms premature ovarian insufficiency requiring oestrogen replacement for symptom control and osteoporosis prevention.<br><br>Positive oestrogen feedback (A) requires high oestradiol concentrations absent in ovarian failure. Increased thyroid hormone (B) and prolactin (C) cause different hormonal profiles without the characteristic high FSH, high LH, low oestradiol constellation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with hypothalamic amenorrhea due to excessive exercise shows decreased pulsatile GnRH secretion. Which reproductive hormone is most directly affected first?',o:['FSH','Estrogen','Progesterone','Oxytocin'],a:0,
e:`Decreased pulsatile GnRH from excessive exercise removes the primary stimulus for pituitary gonadotroph secretion. FSH is the first and most affected reproductive hormone because it requires GnRH stimulation for synthesis, and its selective suppressor inhibin B simultaneously falls as follicular development fails, but the net result is insufficient FSH for dominant follicle maturation.<br><br>FSH deficiency from hypothalamic GnRH suppression causes follicular arrest and anovulation. Oestradiol subsequently falls as follicular development fails, then progesterone falls as no corpus luteum forms, creating the complete hypo-oestrogenic amenorrhoea of functional hypothalamic disorders.<br><br>Oestrogen (B) and progesterone (C) fall secondarily after FSH decline prevents follicular development. Oxytocin (D) is a posterior pituitary hormone unaffected by reduced GnRH pulsatility.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A 35-year-old woman presents with infertility due to luteal phase defect characterized by inadequate progesterone production after ovulation. Which ovarian structure is most likely dysfunctional?',o:['Graafian follicle','Corpus luteum','Theca externa','Ovarian stroma'],a:1,
e:`The corpus luteum is the ovarian structure responsible for progesterone production in the luteal phase. A luteal phase defect with inadequate progesterone points to corpus luteum dysfunction: inadequate LH stimulation, premature regression, or impaired luteinised granulosa cell steroidogenesis failing to produce sufficient progesterone for endometrial receptivity and implantation.<br><br>Mid-luteal serum progesterone below 30 nmol/L confirms luteal phase deficiency. Treatment includes progesterone supplementation with vaginal micronised progesterone from ovulation confirmation, used in both natural conception attempts and as standard luteal support in all IVF cycles regardless of measured progesterone levels.<br><br>Graafian follicle (A) produces oestradiol during the follicular phase and gives rise to the corpus luteum. Theca externa (C) is a structural capsule. Ovarian stroma (D) contains embedded follicles but does not produce luteal phase progesterone.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A patient undergoing fertility treatment receives a GnRH agonist continuously rather than in pulsatile doses. What endocrine effect will most likely occur after initial stimulation?',o:['Suppression of FSH and LH secretion','Increased LH secretion','Increased estrogen production','Increased progesterone secretion'],a:0,
e:`Continuous GnRH agonist administration internalises and degrades GnRH receptors on pituitary gonadotrophs through ligand-induced receptor downregulation, abolishing stimulatory signalling. After an initial 1-2 week gonadotropin flare from receptor stimulation before downregulation completes, FSH and LH fall to near-castrate levels and remain suppressed as long as continuous dosing continues.<br><br>GnRH agonist depot implants exploit this to achieve medical gonadal suppression for endometriosis pain, fibroid shrinkage, precocious puberty and IVF downregulation. GnRH antagonists achieve immediate suppression without the initial flare by competitive receptor blockade, preferred in antagonist IVF protocols for rapid gonadotropin suppression.<br><br>Increased LH secretion (B) occurs transiently during the initial flare only. Increased oestrogen (C) and progesterone (D) result from the initial flare before receptor downregulation, then fall progressively with continued agonist administration.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A 29-year-old woman with infertility undergoes hormonal evaluation. The clinician explains that ovarian estrogen production requires coordinated interaction between granulosa and theca cells under the influence of gonadotropins. According to the two-cell two-gonadotropin model, which hormone stimulates theca cells to produce androgen precursors?',o:['TSH','FSH','Prolactin','LH'],a:3,
e:`According to the two-cell two-gonadotropin model, theca interna cells require LH stimulation via Gs-cAMP-PKA signalling to upregulate StAR protein and CYP17A1, enabling conversion of cholesterol to androstenedione and testosterone. These theca-derived androgens are the obligate substrate for granulosa cell aromatase to produce oestradiol.<br><br>Without LH-driven theca androgen production, granulosa cell FSH stimulation cannot produce oestradiol regardless of aromatase activity level, demonstrating that LH is the specific gonadotropin required for the theca cell contribution to the two-cell collaboration in ovarian oestrogen biosynthesis.<br><br>FSH (B) stimulates granulosa cells for aromatase expression, not theca androgen production. Prolactin (C) suppresses follicular development. TSH (D) stimulates thyroid follicular cells with no role in ovarian theca steroidogenesis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The hypothalamic hormone responsible for initiating the hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis is:',o:['GnRH','TRH','CRH','Dopamine'],a:0,
e:`GnRH, a decapeptide from the hypothalamic arcuate nucleus, initiates the HPG axis by binding Gq-coupled receptors on pituitary gonadotrophs, triggering FSH and LH synthesis. Pulsatile delivery is essential: slow pulses favour FSH while faster pulses favour LH, enabling cycle-phase-specific gonadotropin ratios for folliculogenesis.<br><br>Kisspeptin neurons in the arcuate and anteroventral periventricular nuclei are the primary upstream activators of GnRH neurons, integrating sex steroid feedback, leptin and metabolic signals. Loss of kisspeptin signalling causes hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism.<br><br>TRH (B) initiates the HPT axis for thyroid hormones. CRH (C) initiates the HPA axis for cortisol. Dopamine (D) inhibits prolactin without initiating any reproductive axis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'GnRH is secreted from the hypothalamus in which pattern to maintain normal ovarian function?',o:['Continuous secretion','Pulsatile secretion','Cyclic monthly surge','Random secretion'],a:1,
e:`GnRH must be secreted in a pulsatile pattern to maintain gonadotroph responsiveness: pulses of 90-120 minutes in the early follicular phase drive FSH while faster pulses near ovulation and in the luteal phase drive LH. Continuous GnRH internalises and degrades its receptors, paradoxically suppressing FSH and LH after an initial flare.<br><br>This frequency-dependent gonadotropin regulation allows the same GnRH signal to encode phase-specific information. The pharmacological exploitation of GnRH receptor downregulation by continuous agonist administration underlies medical gonadal suppression for endometriosis, fibroids and IVF downregulation.<br><br>Continuous secretion (A) causes receptor downregulation and gonadotropin suppression. A cyclic monthly surge (C) or random secretion (D) cannot provide the sustained tonic drive and frequency-encoded information required for normal folliculogenesis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'GnRH primarily stimulates the anterior pituitary to release which hormones?',o:['TSH and ACTH','Prolactin and GH','FSH and LH','Oxytocin and ADH'],a:2,
e:`GnRH binds Gq-coupled receptors on pituitary gonadotroph cells, activating phospholipase C to increase intracellular calcium and PKC activity, driving co-secretion of FSH and LH from the same gonadotroph cell. The FSH:LH ratio secreted is determined by GnRH pulse frequency and the prevailing gonadal steroid milieu.<br><br>Both FSH and LH are heterodimeric glycoproteins sharing an identical alpha subunit with distinct beta subunits conferring receptor specificity, enabling the same GnRH stimulus to simultaneously regulate two hormones with different and complementary ovarian targets.<br><br>TSH and ACTH (A) are stimulated by TRH and CRH respectively. Prolactin and GH (B) are stimulated by TRH and GHRH respectively. Oxytocin and ADH (D) are posterior pituitary neurohormones released by neural action potentials.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'During the early follicular phase of the menstrual cycle, the dominant hormone stimulating follicular growth is:',o:['FSH','LH','Progesterone','Prolactin'],a:0,
e:`FSH rises at the onset of the follicular phase as corpus luteum regression removes inhibin B and oestradiol negative feedback. Elevated FSH binds granulosa cell receptors, stimulating follicular recruitment from the resting antral cohort, driving granulosa cell proliferation, aromatase induction and oestradiol production.<br><br>As the dominant follicle develops, its rising oestradiol and inhibin B progressively suppress FSH, causing atresia of less responsive competing follicles and selecting a single dominant follicle for the cycle. FSH then falls while the dominant follicle continues growing on reduced FSH due to amplified intrafollicular responsiveness.<br><br>LH (B) drives theca androgen production and triggers ovulation. Progesterone (C) is the dominant luteal hormone suppressing GnRH. Prolactin (D) inhibits follicular development by suppressing GnRH.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The mid-cycle surge responsible for ovulation is caused by:',o:['FSH surge','LH surge','Prolactin surge','TSH surge'],a:1,
e:`The mid-cycle LH surge, triggered by sustained oestradiol positive feedback exceeding 200 pg/mL for 50 hours, drives ovulation by activating follicular wall proteolytic enzymes, prostaglandins and VEGF causing stigma formation and rupture approximately 36-40 hours after surge onset. Oocyte meiosis simultaneously resumes.<br><br>The LH surge is detectable in urine 24-48 hours before ovulation, forming the basis of ovulation predictor kits. Exogenous hCG, which binds LH receptors with equal affinity, is used to trigger ovulation precisely in ovulation induction and IVF protocols.<br><br>An FSH surge (A) occurs modestly alongside LH at mid-cycle but is not the ovulatory trigger. Prolactin surge (C) and TSH surge (D) have no role in triggering the ovulatory event.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The ovarian hormone responsible for proliferation of endometrium during follicular phase is:',o:['Progesterone','Prolactin','Oxytocin','Estrogen'],a:3,
e:`Oestradiol from the growing dominant follicle binds endometrial ERalpha receptors, driving glandular and stromal proliferation, angiogenesis and thickening from 2-3 mm at menstruation to 8-12 mm at ovulation. It also induces endometrial progesterone receptors, priming the endometrium for luteal phase secretory transformation.<br><br>Oestradiol-driven proliferative endometrium appears as a trilaminar pattern on transvaginal ultrasound, used as a surrogate marker of adequate oestrogenic stimulation in IVF cycles. A minimum of 7-8 mm is required for successful embryo transfer.<br><br>Progesterone (A) drives secretory phase transformation after ovulation. Prolactin (B) supports lactation without a direct endometrial proliferative role. Oxytocin (C) stimulates uterine contractions.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The corpus luteum forms after:',o:['Fertilization','Menstruation','Ovulation','Implantation'],a:2,
e:`The corpus luteum forms after ovulation when the ruptured Graafian follicle undergoes luteinisation under continued LH stimulation: granulosa and theca cells accumulate lipid droplets, the avascular follicular wall vascularises via VEGF-driven angiogenesis, and 3beta-HSD expression rises to shift steroid output from oestradiol to progesterone.<br><br>The corpus luteum peaks functionally at approximately day 21, secreting progesterone, oestradiol and inhibin A. Without hCG rescue from an implanting blastocyst, luteolysis occurs at days 26-28 driven by prostaglandin F2-alpha from the endometrium, causing progesterone withdrawal and menstruation.<br><br>Fertilisation (A) and implantation (D) occur after corpus luteum formation. Menstruation (B) follows corpus luteum regression and is the consequence of luteolysis rather than its formation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The dominant hormone during the luteal phase of the menstrual cycle is:',o:['Estrogen','Oxytocin','FSH','Progesterone'],a:3,
e:`Progesterone from the corpus luteum is the defining hormone of the luteal phase, peaking at approximately day 21 at 25-100 nmol/L. It drives endometrial secretory transformation, causes the characteristic 0.2-0.5 degrees C basal body temperature rise via hypothalamic thermogenic action, and suppresses GnRH pulsatility to prevent new follicular recruitment.<br><br>Mid-luteal serum progesterone above 30 nmol/L is the standard biochemical confirmation of ovulation in infertility investigations. Monthly monitoring guides clomifene dose titration, and progesterone supplementation is standard luteal support in IVF cycles.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) is present but progesterone is quantitatively dominant and functionally defining. Oxytocin (B) stimulates contractions without being the dominant luteal hormone. FSH (C) is suppressed by negative feedback throughout the luteal phase.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'If fertilization does not occur, regression of corpus luteum leads to:',o:['Decreased progesterone','Increased estrogen','Increased prolactin','Increased LH'],a:0,
e:`Without hCG rescue from an implanting blastocyst, prostaglandin F2-alpha from the endometrium triggers corpus luteum luteolysis at days 26-28. Progesterone and oestradiol fall sharply as luteinised granulosa cells undergo apoptosis, removing negative feedback from the hypothalamus and pituitary and triggering endometrial shedding as menstruation.<br><br>The fall in progesterone and oestradiol simultaneously releases FSH from negative feedback inhibition, allowing FSH to rise and initiate recruitment of a new follicular cohort for the next cycle. The first day of menstrual bleeding is conventionally defined as day 1 of the new cycle.<br><br>Increased oestrogen (B) does not occur with corpus luteum regression; oestradiol falls alongside progesterone. Prolactin (C) and LH (D) are not directly elevated by corpus luteum regression.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Menstruation occurs due to:',o:['Sudden increase in estrogen','Increase in FSH','Withdrawal of progesterone and estrogen','Increase in LH'],a:2,
e:`Corpus luteum regression at days 26-28 causes sharp falls in progesterone and oestradiol. This hormonal withdrawal triggers prostaglandin F2-alpha release from the endometrial stroma, causing spiral artery vasoconstriction, endometrial ischaemia and necrosis, followed by shedding of the functional endometrial layer as menstrual bleeding over 3-7 days.<br><br>Prostaglandins drive the myometrial contractions that expel the necrotic endometrium. Excess prostaglandin production, as in primary dysmenorrhoea, causes the painful cramps that affect approximately 50% of menstruating women. NSAIDs that inhibit prostaglandin synthesis are first-line treatment.<br><br>Sudden increase in oestrogen (A) and increases in FSH (B) and LH (D) are not the triggers for menstrual bleeding; they are consequences of falling steroids, not causes of endometrial shedding.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone stimulates growth of multiple follicles early in the menstrual cycle?',o:['FSH','LH','Prolactin','Oxytocin'],a:0,
e:`FSH, rising as corpus luteum regression removes inhibin B and oestradiol negative feedback, recruits a cohort of antral follicles at the start of each cycle by binding granulosa cell FSH receptors and stimulating their growth, proliferation and aromatase activity. Multiple follicles respond initially before dominant follicle selection occurs.<br><br>Dominant follicle selection depends on FSH responsiveness: the follicle producing the most oestradiol locally amplifies its FSH receptor expression, while its oestradiol and inhibin B suppress circulating FSH, causing less responsive competing follicles to undergo atresia mid-follicular phase.<br><br>LH (B) drives theca androgen production but does not initiate follicular recruitment. Prolactin (C) suppresses follicular development. Oxytocin (D) stimulates uterine contractions and milk ejection.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The dominant follicle during menstrual cycle secretes increasing levels of:',o:['Prolactin','Progesterone','Testosterone','Estrogen'],a:3,
e:`The dominant follicle secretes rising oestradiol from granulosa cell aromatisation of theca-derived androgens, producing a positive amplification loop: oestradiol locally upregulates FSH receptor expression on granulosa cells, increasing FSH responsiveness and aromatase activity, which produces more oestradiol in a self-amplifying cycle.<br><br>Rising oestradiol exerts negative feedback at lower follicular phase concentrations suppressing FSH and LH, then switches to positive feedback when oestradiol exceeds 200 pg/mL for 50 hours in the late follicular phase, triggering the LH surge and ovulation.<br><br>Prolactin (A) is an anterior pituitary hormone not secreted by the dominant follicle. Progesterone (B) is the dominant corpus luteum product post-ovulation. Testosterone (C) is a theca cell androgen substrate, not the dominant follicular secretion reaching systemic circulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'High estrogen levels just before ovulation exert what effect on the pituitary?',o:['Negative feedback','Positive feedback','No feedback','Inhibitory feedback'],a:1,
e:`When oestradiol exceeds approximately 200 pg/mL sustained for at least 50 hours in the late follicular phase, it switches from negative to positive feedback at the hypothalamus and pituitary: GnRH pulse frequency increases, gonadotroph GnRH receptor density rises and the pituitary amplifies LH release, generating the mid-cycle LH surge within 24-48 hours.<br><br>This oestradiol-driven positive feedback is mediated through kisspeptin neurons in the anteroventral periventricular nucleus specifically activated by rising oestradiol to generate the surge. Arcuate nucleus kisspeptin neurons mediate the tonic negative feedback from oestradiol at lower concentrations throughout the rest of the cycle.<br><br>Negative feedback (A) describes oestradiol's effect at lower concentrations. Inhibitory feedback (D) does not capture the mid-cycle positive switch. No effect (C) is incorrect as oestradiol is the essential trigger of the LH surge.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'The average duration of the menstrual cycle is:',o:['21 days','35 days','28 days','40 days'],a:2,
e:`The average menstrual cycle is 28 days, though normal cycles range from 21 to 35 days. The luteal phase from ovulation to menstruation is relatively constant at 14 days across cycle lengths, as it is defined by the fixed lifespan of the corpus luteum. Variation in cycle length is due primarily to variation in follicular phase length.<br><br>Cycles outside 21-35 days are classified as abnormal: below 21 days is polymenorrhoea, above 35 days is oligomenorrhoea. Cycle length tracking over 3 months identifies irregular patterns that may indicate anovulation, thyroid disease, PCOS or hyperprolactinaemia requiring investigation.<br><br>21 days (A) is the lower limit of normal cycle length. 35 days (B) is the upper limit. 40 days (D) is outside the normal range and constitutes oligomenorrhoea.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Ovulation usually occurs on which day in a typical 28-day cycle?',o:['Day 7','Day 28','Day 21','Day 14'],a:3,
e:`In a 28-day cycle, ovulation occurs approximately on day 14, triggered by the mid-cycle LH surge driven by oestradiol positive feedback from the mature Graafian follicle. Since the luteal phase is a fixed 14 days, ovulation occurs 14 days before the next menstrual period regardless of total cycle length.<br><br>In cycles shorter or longer than 28 days, ovulation timing is calculated by subtracting 14 days from the expected next period date: a 35-day cycle has ovulation at day 21, a 21-day cycle at day 7. Tracking basal body temperature or using ovulation predictor kits identifies the actual ovulation day.<br><br>Day 7 (A) corresponds to ovulation in a 21-day cycle. Day 28 (B) is the end of a 28-day cycle marking menstruation. Day 21 (C) corresponds to ovulation in a 35-day cycle.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A 25-year-old woman presents with infertility due to anovulation. Hormonal studies show absent LH surge. Which hormone triggers ovulation in a normal cycle?',o:['Ovulation','Endometrial proliferation','Menstruation','Implantation'],a:0,
e:`In a normal cycle, the LH surge triggered by oestradiol positive feedback is the hormone responsible for ovulation. Absent LH surge means follicular rupture does not occur despite Graafian follicle development, a condition called luteinised unruptured follicle syndrome or simply anovulation depending on the degree of LH deficiency.<br><br>Diagnosis uses serial ultrasound showing follicular persistence without collapse and absent mid-luteal progesterone rise. Treatment involves ovulation induction with clomifene or gonadotropins plus exogenous hCG trigger to replace the absent endogenous LH surge.<br><br>Endometrial proliferation (B) is an oestradiol-driven process unrelated to the ovulatory trigger. Menstruation (C) follows corpus luteum regression. Implantation (D) occurs 7 days after ovulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A patient undergoing IVF treatment receives pulsatile GnRH therapy. What is the primary physiological purpose of this treatment?',o:['Suppress prolactin','Stimulate FSH and LH secretion','Suppress thyroid hormone','Decrease estrogen'],a:1,
e:`Pulsatile GnRH therapy via a subcutaneous pump administering pulses every 90-120 minutes directly replaces the physiological GnRH signal, stimulating pituitary gonadotrophs to secrete FSH and LH in a near-physiological pattern. This bypasses the hypothalamic defect in hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism while preserving the normal FSH:LH ratio and cycle dynamics.<br><br>Pulsatile GnRH pump therapy is particularly valuable in Kallmann syndrome and functional hypothalamic amenorrhoea because it achieves monofollicular ovulation with low multiple pregnancy risk compared with gonadotropin injections, which frequently cause multifollicular development.<br><br>Prolactin suppression (A) is achieved by dopamine agonists. Thyroid hormone suppression (C) is not a reproductive therapy goal. Decreasing oestrogen (D) opposes the desired outcome of restoring ovarian function through FSH and LH stimulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with hypothalamic dysfunction fails to secrete GnRH normally. Which hormones will be most directly deficient?',o:['Prolactin','ACTH','TSH','FSH and LH'],a:3,
e:`GnRH deficiency removes the primary stimulus for pituitary gonadotroph FSH and LH synthesis and secretion. Within hours to days of GnRH loss, FSH and LH fall, leading to impaired follicular development, absent oestradiol production, anovulation and amenorrhoea , the presentation of hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism.<br><br>TSH and ACTH are regulated by independent hypothalamic axes (TRH and CRH respectively) unaffected by GnRH deficiency. Prolactin is paradoxically elevated if the stalk is disrupted, as dopaminergic inhibition is simultaneously removed. This hormonal pattern helps localise lesions in pituitary axis disorders.<br><br>Prolactin (A) is elevated rather than deficient with stalk disruption. ACTH (B) is regulated by CRH independently. TSH (C) is regulated by TRH independently. None are primarily dependent on GnRH secretion.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A 30-year-old woman with luteal phase defect has inadequate progesterone production after ovulation. Which ovarian structure is responsible for this secretion?',o:['Corpus luteum','Graafian follicle','Theca cells','Ovarian stroma'],a:0,
e:`The corpus luteum, formed from the ruptured Graafian follicle after ovulation under continued LH stimulation, is the sole source of luteal phase progesterone. Luteinised granulosa cells upregulate CYP11A1, StAR and 3beta-HSD to convert cholesterol to progesterone, peaking at day 21. Luteal phase defect reflects inadequate corpus luteum steroidogenesis.<br><br>Mid-luteal progesterone below 30 nmol/L confirms luteal phase deficiency. Treatment uses vaginal micronised progesterone from ovulation onward, and corpus luteum support with hCG or GnRH agonist injections after ovulation may also be used in selected cases to enhance corpus luteum progesterone production.<br><br>The Graafian follicle (B) gives rise to the corpus luteum. Theca cells (C) produce androgens for follicular oestrogen synthesis. Ovarian stroma (D) contains embedded follicles without direct luteal phase progesterone secretory function.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A woman presents with irregular cycles due to failure of dominant follicle selection. Which hormone deficiency is most likely responsible?',o:['Prolactin','LH','Progesterone','FSH'],a:3,
e:`FSH is the essential signal for follicular recruitment and dominant follicle selection. FSH deficiency prevents granulosa cell proliferation, aromatase induction and the oestradiol amplification loop that creates the dominant follicle. Without a dominant follicle, no LH surge is generated and anovulatory irregular cycles result.<br><br>FSH deficiency from hypothalamic dysfunction or hyperprolactinaemia-mediated GnRH suppression is treated with recombinant FSH injections, titrated with transvaginal ultrasound and serum oestradiol monitoring to achieve dominant follicle selection without multifollicular hyperstimulation.<br><br>Prolactin (A) excess impairs ovulation by suppressing GnRH. LH (B) drives theca androgen production and triggers ovulation but is not the primary driver of dominant follicle selection. Progesterone (C) is the corpus luteum product after successful ovulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A breastfeeding woman develops amenorrhea because prolactin suppresses hypothalamic secretion of:',o:['CRH','TRH','GnRH','GHRH'],a:2,
e:`Prolactin elevated by suckling-driven dopamine inhibition withdrawal suppresses hypothalamic GnRH secretion via opioidergic pathways and direct inhibition of kisspeptin neurons in the arcuate nucleus, reducing GnRH pulse frequency below the threshold required to generate FSH and LH levels for dominant follicle development and ovulation.<br><br>This mechanism underpins the Lactational Amenorrhoea Method: exclusive breastfeeding on demand maintains prolactin surges sufficient to suppress GnRH pulsatility and provide approximately 98% contraceptive effectiveness in the first 6 months postpartum when menstruation has not returned.<br><br>CRH (A) drives ACTH-cortisol secretion in the HPA axis. TRH (B) drives TSH and prolactin. GHRH (D) drives growth hormone secretion. None are the hypothalamic hormone suppressed by prolactin to cause lactational amenorrhoea.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient undergoing ovulation induction receives hCG injection to mimic LH surge. What physiological event is expected to follow?',o:['Cervical dilation','Endometrial shedding','Regression of corpus luteum','Rupture of mature follicle'],a:3,
e:`hCG binds ovarian LH receptors with equal affinity to LH, triggering the same cascade as the endogenous LH surge: proteolytic enzyme and prostaglandin activation in the follicular wall, stigma formation and rupture with oocyte release approximately 36-40 hours after hCG administration. Egg collection in IVF is timed precisely at 34-36 hours.<br><br>hCG is preferred over LH for ovulation triggering because its longer half-life of approximately 36 hours compared with LH's 20 minutes provides more sustained receptor activation through the complete 36-40 hour follicular maturation period required before rupture.<br><br>Cervical dilation (A) occurs in labour driven by prostaglandins. Endometrial shedding (B) follows progesterone withdrawal. Corpus luteum regression (C) occurs at days 26-28 of the cycle in the absence of hCG rescue from implantation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with ovarian failure shows very high FSH and LH levels. Which endocrine mechanism explains this?',o:['Increased prolactin secretion','Increased thyroid activity','Loss of negative feedback from ovarian hormones','Positive feedback'],a:2,
e:`Ovarian failure eliminates oestradiol and inhibin B production. Loss of oestradiol negative feedback at hypothalamus and pituitary, and loss of inhibin B-mediated selective FSH suppression from absent granulosa cells, removes the brakes on gonadotropin secretion, causing compensatory FSH and LH elevation as the pituitary attempts to stimulate the unresponsive ovary.<br><br>FSH rises earlier and more markedly than LH because inhibin B specifically suppresses FSH and its loss disproportionately elevates FSH. Persistently elevated FSH above 25 IU/L with amenorrhoea on two occasions 4-6 weeks apart confirms premature ovarian insufficiency before age 40.<br><br>Increased prolactin (A) causes low FSH and LH from GnRH suppression, the opposite pattern. Increased thyroid activity (B) does not explain the high FSH and LH. Positive feedback (D) from oestrogen drives the LH surge and requires high oestradiol concentrations.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 29-year-old woman experiences sudden drop in progesterone due to corpus luteum regression. What clinical event results?',o:['Menstruation','Ovulation','Implantation','Fertilization'],a:0,
e:`Corpus luteum regression at days 26-28 causes sharp falls in progesterone and oestradiol. Progesterone withdrawal triggers prostaglandin F2-alpha release from the endometrial stroma, causing spiral artery vasoconstriction, endometrial ischaemia and necrosis followed by shedding of the functional endometrial layer as menstruation over 3-7 days.<br><br>The progesterone fall simultaneously releases the hypothalamic-pituitary axis from negative feedback, allowing FSH to rise and initiate recruitment of a new follicular cohort. The falling progesterone and rising FSH are concurrent consequences of corpus luteum regression that begin the new cycle simultaneously.<br><br>Ovulation (B) occurs at mid-cycle from the LH surge. Implantation (C) occurs 7 days after ovulation. Fertilisation (D) occurs in the fallopian tube shortly after ovulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'During reproductive endocrinology teaching, the professor explains that increasing levels of one hormone at mid-cycle trigger ovulation. Which event best describes the role of this hormone?',o:['Endometrial proliferation','Menstrual bleeding','Ovulation','Corpus luteum regression'],a:2,
e:`The LH surge at mid-cycle triggers ovulation by activating follicular wall proteolytic enzymes and prostaglandins, causing stigma formation and follicular rupture with release of the cumulus-oocyte complex approximately 36-40 hours after surge onset. This is the essential ovulatory event that converts the follicular to the luteal phase.<br><br>The LH surge is preceded by and dependent on the oestradiol positive feedback switch: once oestradiol exceeds 200 pg/mL for 50 hours, the hypothalamic-pituitary response amplifies massively to generate the surge. Without this oestradiol-driven positive feedback, the LH surge and ovulation do not occur.<br><br>Endometrial proliferation (A) is an oestradiol-driven process throughout the follicular phase. Menstrual bleeding (B) follows corpus luteum regression. Corpus luteum regression (D) occurs at the end of an infertile luteal phase.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A 27-year-old woman tracking ovulation notices thin, stretchy cervical mucus and a temperature chart showing elevated levels. Which hormone change is occurring?',o:['Menstrual shedding','Progesterone withdrawal','Corpus luteum regression','LH surge and impending ovulation'],a:3,
e:`Thin, stretchy cervical mucus (Spinnbarkeit) reflects the oestrogen-dominated peri-ovulatory state, indicating the fertile window. The impending LH surge triggered by oestradiol positive feedback will cause ovulation within 24-48 hours, after which progesterone from the corpus luteum shifts the mucus to thick, scanty and impenetrable to sperm.<br><br>Urinary LH detection kits identify this same LH surge 24-48 hours before ovulation. Combined with cervical mucus assessment, basal body temperature tracking and ultrasound follicle monitoring, these methods identify the fertile window for natural conception timing or intrauterine insemination scheduling.<br><br>Menstrual shedding (A) follows progesterone and oestradiol withdrawal. Progesterone withdrawal (B) triggers menstruation. Corpus luteum regression (C) occurs at end of the luteal phase days later.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with hypothalamic amenorrhea due to extreme exercise has decreased pulsatile GnRH secretion. Which hormone is reduced as a direct consequence?',o:['Testosterone','Progesterone','Estrogen','Oxytocin'],a:2,
e:`Decreased GnRH pulsatility reduces FSH and LH secretion. Without FSH, granulosa cell aromatase is not induced and without LH, theca cells do not produce androgen substrate. Both components of the two-cell mechanism for oestradiol synthesis fail, causing oestradiol to fall as the direct consequence of hypothalamic GnRH suppression and insufficient gonadotropin stimulation.<br><br>The resulting hypo-oestrogenic state causes the clinical features of functional hypothalamic amenorrhoea: absent menstruation, thin atrophic endometrium, low bone density and symptoms of oestrogen deficiency. Treatment addresses the underlying cause (nutrition, exercise reduction) while oestrogen replacement protects bone density.<br><br>Testosterone (A) is a theca androgen substrate that also falls. Progesterone (B) is absent from lack of corpus luteum. Oxytocin (D) is a posterior pituitary hormone unaffected by hypothalamic GnRH changes.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A patient undergoing fertility therapy is given clomiphene which blocks estrogen receptors in the hypothalamus. What endocrine change results?',o:['Decreased estrogen','Decreased FSH secretion','Increased prolactin','Increased FSH and LH secretion'],a:3,
e:`Clomifene, a selective oestrogen receptor modulator, blocks hypothalamic oestrogen receptors, preventing oestradiol negative feedback from suppressing GnRH pulsatility. The hypothalamus perceives a falsely low oestrogen state and increases GnRH pulse amplitude, driving pituitary FSH and LH secretion above normal to stimulate follicular development in anovulatory women.<br><br>Clomifene is first-line treatment for anovulatory infertility in PCOS and hypothalamic amenorrhoea, achieving ovulation in approximately 75-80% of women and pregnancy in approximately 40-50% over 6 treatment cycles. Ovulation is confirmed by mid-luteal progesterone measurement above 30 nmol/L.<br><br>Oestrogen itself (A) is not directly reduced by clomifene. FSH secretion (B) increases rather than decreases. Prolactin (C) is not primarily affected by oestrogen receptor blockade at the hypothalamic level.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A 34-year-old woman with infertility has inadequate follicular development due to low circulating FSH levels. The period of the menstrual cycle most characterised by FSH action is the:',o:['Menstrual phase','Luteal phase','Follicular phase','Implantation phase'],a:2,
e:`The follicular phase is characterised by FSH action: rising FSH from menstruation onset recruits antral follicles, drives dominant follicle selection through granulosa cell proliferation and aromatase induction, and establishes the oestradiol amplification loop. Inadequate FSH during the follicular phase impairs follicular development and anovulation results.<br><br>The follicular phase length varies between individuals (7-21 days) while the luteal phase is constant at 14 days. FSH peaks at the start of the follicular phase then falls as dominant follicle inhibin B and oestradiol provide negative feedback, with FSH remaining low through the luteal phase.<br><br>Menstrual phase (A) is the shedding phase with rapidly rising FSH just beginning. Luteal phase (B) has suppressed FSH from negative feedback. Implantation phase (D) is not a recognised discrete menstrual cycle phase.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A gynecology resident explains that ovulation marks the transition from follicular to luteal phase. What is the dominant hormone produced in the luteal phase?',o:['Prolactin','Estrogen','FSH','Progesterone'],a:3,
e:`Progesterone from the corpus luteum is the dominant luteal phase hormone, produced by luteinised granulosa cells via upregulated CYP11A1, StAR and 3beta-HSD converting cholesterol through pregnenolone to progesterone. It peaks at approximately day 21, drives endometrial secretory transformation and suppresses further GnRH pulsatility.<br><br>The luteal phase is a fixed 14 days determined by the corpus luteum lifespan. Without hCG rescue, luteolysis begins at days 26-28, progesterone falls and menstruation follows. With hCG from implantation, corpus luteum progesterone is sustained until the luteo-placental shift at 8-10 weeks.<br><br>Prolactin (A) is not the dominant luteal hormone and is low unless breastfeeding. Oestrogen (B) is produced in smaller amounts alongside progesterone by the corpus luteum. FSH (C) is suppressed by luteal phase inhibin A, oestradiol and progesterone negative feedback.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Puberty is initiated by activation of which hypothalamic hormone secretion?',o:['TRH','CRH','GnRH','Dopamine'],a:2,
e:`Puberty begins when the hypothalamic GnRH pulse generator, which was suppressed throughout childhood by central inhibitory mechanisms including GABA and RFamide-related peptide neurons, becomes activated through maturation of kisspeptin signalling and reduction of inhibitory tone, initiating pulsatile GnRH secretion.<br><br>Rising GnRH pulses drive pituitary FSH and LH secretion, stimulating gonadal oestradiol and testosterone production. Oestradiol then drives the physical changes of female puberty: thelarche, pubarche, uterine growth and eventually menarche as the HPG axis matures sufficiently for cyclic ovulatory function.<br><br>TRH (A) drives the HPT axis, CRH (B) drives the HPA axis and dopamine (D) inhibits prolactin. None initiate puberty or the HPG axis activation that drives pubertal development.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The onset of puberty is characterized by increased pulsatile secretion of:',o:['GnRH','Prolactin','Oxytocin','ADH'],a:0,
e:`The hallmark of puberty onset is the reactivation of pulsatile GnRH secretion from the hypothalamic arcuate nucleus after its suppression during childhood. Initially nocturnal GnRH pulses during early puberty gradually become 24-hour pulsatile secretion as puberty progresses, driving increasing FSH and LH that stimulate gonadal steroidogenesis and pubertal development.<br><br>The GnRH pulse generator reactivation is driven by maturation of kisspeptin neuron signalling: rising kisspeptin activates GnRH neurons in the arcuate nucleus, and the withdrawal of childhood inhibitory signals including GABA and RFamide-related peptides allows sustained GnRH pulsatility to begin.<br><br>Prolactin (B), oxytocin (C) and ADH (D) do not characterise puberty onset. Prolactin rises modestly in puberty from oestradiol but is not the initiating hormonal event of pubertal activation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'GnRH stimulation during puberty leads to increased secretion of which pituitary hormones?',o:['ACTH and TSH','FSH and LH','Prolactin and GH','Oxytocin and ADH'],a:1,
e:`Increased GnRH pulsatility at puberty stimulates pituitary gonadotroph FSH and LH secretion. FSH drives gonadal steroidogenesis and gamete development while LH drives gonadal androgen and oestrogen production. Together they initiate gonadal maturation responsible for the secondary sexual development that defines puberty.<br><br>The gonadotropin response to GnRH progressively increases during puberty as gonadotroph sensitivity develops. The gonadotropin-releasing hormone stimulation test, measuring FSH and LH response to exogenous GnRH, distinguishes central precocious puberty (pubertal LH response) from peripheral sources of sex steroids (prepubertal LH response).<br><br>ACTH and TSH (A) are regulated by CRH and TRH independently of GnRH. Prolactin and GH (C) are stimulated by TRH and GHRH respectively. Oxytocin and ADH (D) are posterior pituitary neurohormones unrelated to GnRH stimulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The first menstrual bleeding marking onset of reproductive capability is called:',o:['Menopause','Amenorrhea','Ovulation','Menarche'],a:3,
e:`Menarche is the first menstrual period, marking the beginning of reproductive capability and the visible milestone of female puberty. It typically occurs approximately 2-3 years after thelarche (breast development), after oestradiol has sufficiently primed the endometrium to respond to progesterone withdrawal with bleeding.<br><br>In the UK and Pakistan, the average age of menarche is approximately 12-13 years, influenced by nutritional status, BMI and genetics. Menarche before age 10 is considered precocious; absence of menarche by age 15 with normal secondary sexual development is primary amenorrhoea requiring investigation.<br><br>Menopause (A) is the permanent cessation of menstruation. Amenorrhoea (B) is the absence of menstruation. Ovulation (C) typically begins at or shortly after menarche though early cycles are commonly anovulatory.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The average age of menarche is approximately:',o:['9 years','16-17 years','12-13 years','18-19 years'],a:2,
e:`The average age of menarche in Western and South Asian populations is approximately 12-13 years, with a normal range of 10-16 years. Menarche requires sufficient body fat and nutritional status, mediated by leptin signalling activating hypothalamic kisspeptin neurons, explaining earlier menarche in girls with higher BMI and delayed menarche in those with low body weight or eating disorders.<br><br>Menarche timing has secular trend: average age has progressively fallen in developed nations over the past century, attributed to improved nutrition and childhood obesity. In clinical assessment, menarche before 10 years is precocious and after 16 years with secondary sexual development is primary amenorrhoea requiring investigation.<br><br>9 years (A) is precocious puberty territory for most classification systems. 16-17 years (B) and 18-19 years (D) would represent delayed menarche requiring endocrine evaluation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The earliest visible sign of puberty in females is usually:',o:['Menarche','Ovulation','Pubic hair growth','Breast development (thelarche)'],a:3,
e:`Thelarche, the development of breast buds as the first visible secondary sexual characteristic, is the earliest sign of female puberty, typically appearing at 10-11 years under oestradiol stimulation from the activating HPG axis. Thelarche precedes pubarche by approximately 6 months in most girls and precedes menarche by approximately 2-3 years.<br><br>The sequence of pubertal events in girls follows: thelarche, pubarche, peak height velocity, then menarche. Understanding this sequence is important clinically: pubic hair appearing before breast development (isolated pubarche) suggests adrenarche rather than true central puberty, and breast development well before any pubic hair may indicate isolated thelarche or true precocious puberty.<br><br>Menarche (A) is the last major pubertal milestone. Ovulation (B) is a later functional event. Pubic hair growth (C) is pubarche, which follows thelarche in the normal pubertal sequence.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Pubic hair development during puberty is called:',o:['Thelarche','Adrenarche','Pubarche','Menarche'],a:2,
e:`Pubarche refers specifically to the development of pubic hair, driven primarily by adrenal androgens (DHEAS and androstenedione) from the zona reticularis, a process independent of the HPG axis. Pubic and axillary hair development is therefore a marker of adrenal androgen activity rather than gonadal oestrogen production.<br><br>The distinction between pubarche (driven by adrenal androgens) and thelarche (driven by ovarian oestradiol) is clinically important: isolated pubarche without thelarche suggests premature adrenarche, while thelarche without pubarche suggests HPG axis activation without adrenarche, helping to localise the origin of precocious pubertal signs.<br><br>Thelarche (A) is breast development. Adrenarche (B) is the maturation of the adrenal zona reticularis with increased adrenal androgen production that underlies pubarche. Menarche (D) is the first menstrual period.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Development of breasts during puberty is primarily stimulated by:',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Prolactin','Oxytocin'],a:0,
e:`Oestradiol rising at puberty is the primary stimulus for breast development (thelarche). It drives ductal elongation, branching and periductal fat deposition, producing the characteristic Tanner stage breast changes from thelarche at Tanner II through full adult breast development at Tanner V. Progesterone contributes to lobulo-alveolar development at puberty and in pregnancy.<br><br>Breast development is the earliest and most oestrogen-sensitive physical sign of female puberty. Absence of breast development by age 13-14 years (Tanner I at 13) is termed delayed puberty and warrants investigation for hypogonadism, chromosomal abnormalities or hypothalamic-pituitary disorders.<br><br>Progesterone (B) contributes to alveolar development but is not the primary driver of thelarche. Prolactin (C) drives milk synthesis without initiating breast development. Oxytocin (D) contracts myoepithelial cells without stimulating ductal breast development.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The ovarian hormone responsible for development of female secondary sexual characteristics is:',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Testosterone','Prolactin'],a:1,
e:`Oestradiol from the activated ovaries at puberty drives all female secondary sexual characteristics: breast development, uterine and vaginal enlargement and maturation, female fat redistribution to hips and buttocks, skin changes and ultimately epiphyseal closure that terminates linear growth. It initiates and sustains the physical feminisation of puberty.<br><br>In Turner syndrome (45,X) with absent oestradiol from streak gonads, no secondary sexual development occurs. Oestrogen replacement at the normal pubertal age restores feminisation, confirms oestradiol as the essential driver and prevents long-term complications of oestrogen deficiency including osteoporosis.<br><br>Progesterone (A) prepares the endometrium and supports pregnancy. Testosterone (C) drives male puberty. Prolactin (D) supports lactation without driving pubertal secondary sexual development.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Adrenarche refers to increased secretion of:',o:['Adrenal androgens','Estrogen','Progesterone','Prolactin'],a:0,
e:`Adrenarche is the maturation of the adrenal zona reticularis occurring at approximately 6-8 years, producing increasing DHEAS, DHEA and androstenedione. This adrenal androgen rise is responsible for axillary and pubic hair development (pubarche), adult body odour, early acne and mild oiliness of skin , all occurring 2-3 years before central GnRH-driven puberty begins.<br><br>Adrenarche is regulated by a yet-undefined adrenal-specific cortical maturation signal distinct from ACTH. Premature adrenarche before age 8 years is common, usually benign and does not accelerate the timing of central puberty, though it requires investigation to exclude congenital adrenal hyperplasia.<br><br>Oestrogen (B) drives gonadal puberty features including thelarche. Progesterone (C) is the luteal phase hormone. Prolactin (D) is an anterior pituitary lactogenic hormone unrelated to adrenarche.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The Tanner staging system is used to assess:',o:['Ovarian function','Sexual maturation','Menstrual cycle','Fertility'],a:1,
e:`The Tanner staging system (Tanner stages I-V) provides standardised assessment of sexual maturation based on breast development (females), genital development (males) and pubic hair development (both sexes). It provides a reproducible clinical framework for documenting pubertal progression and identifying precocious or delayed puberty.<br><br>Tanner staging is applied clinically to determine whether pubertal signs are appropriate for chronological age, to monitor response to treatment in precocious puberty and to assess pubertal progress in girls with chronic illness, endocrine disorders or nutritional deficiencies that may delay maturation.<br><br>Ovarian function (A) is assessed by FSH, LH, AMH and antral follicle count. Menstrual cycle (C) is assessed by history and hormonal investigations. Fertility (D) requires specific investigations including semen analysis, ovarian reserve tests and fallopian tube assessment.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The hormone responsible for growth spurt during puberty is mainly:',o:['Progesterone','Oxytocin','Prolactin','Growth hormone'],a:3,
e:`Growth hormone, secreted from pituitary somatotrophs under GHRH stimulation, increases markedly during puberty under the amplifying influence of pubertal sex steroids. GH drives IGF-1 production from the liver and local tissues, stimulating longitudinal bone growth at epiphyseal growth plates during the pubertal growth spurt.<br><br>Oestradiol amplifies GH secretion and IGF-1 responsiveness at growth plates during the pubertal growth spurt, then paradoxically terminates growth by causing epiphyseal fusion. This explains the characteristic pubertal growth pattern: rapid acceleration followed by deceleration and cessation of growth as oestradiol concentrations rise further.<br><br>Progesterone (A) prepares the endometrium without a major growth-promoting role. Oxytocin (B) mediates contractions and milk ejection. Prolactin (C) supports lactation without driving the pubertal growth spurt.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Estrogen contributes to closure of epiphyseal growth plates during:',o:['Puberty','Menopause','Pregnancy','Childhood'],a:0,
e:`During puberty, rising oestradiol stimulates the initial pubertal growth spurt by amplifying GH secretion and IGF-1 responsiveness, then at higher concentrations promotes osteoblast activity and mineralisation at epiphyseal growth plates, eventually causing epiphyseal fusion and cessation of linear growth typically by 16-18 years in females.<br><br>The importance of oestradiol for epiphyseal closure is demonstrated in girls with aromatase deficiency or oestrogen receptor alpha mutations: despite normal puberty timing, epiphyseal fusion fails, resulting in tall stature with continued growth into adulthood. Oestrogen replacement causes rapid epiphyseal closure and growth cessation in these individuals.<br><br>Childhood (A) has low oestradiol maintaining open epiphyses and continued growth. Menopause (B) has low oestradiol but growth plates are already fused. Pregnancy (C) has high oestradiol but growth plates are closed in adults.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hypothalamic neurotransmitter inhibits GnRH release before puberty?',o:['Dopamine','GABA','Serotonin','Histamine'],a:1,
e:`GABA-ergic neurons provide the primary inhibitory tone suppressing the hypothalamic GnRH pulse generator during childhood. The high GABA-ergic inhibitory activity during childhood, combined with active RFamide-related peptide (RFRP) inhibition of GnRH neurons, maintains GnRH suppression and the prepubertal quiescent state of the HPG axis.<br><br>Puberty is initiated when this inhibitory GABA-ergic and RFRP tone progressively diminishes and stimulatory kisspeptin neuron activity increases, together activating GnRH pulse generator reactivation. The balance between inhibitory and stimulatory inputs to GnRH neurons determines the timing of puberty onset.<br><br>Dopamine (B) inhibits prolactin but is not the primary pre-pubertal suppressor of GnRH. Serotonin (C) and histamine (D) modulate various brain functions without being the primary inhibitors of the pre-pubertal GnRH axis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The maturation of hypothalamic GnRH pulse generator leads to:',o:['Lactation','Menopause','Pregnancy','Onset of puberty'],a:3,
e:`Maturation of the hypothalamic GnRH pulse generator, driven by progressive increase in kisspeptin neuron activity and reduction of inhibitory GABA-ergic and RFRP tone, initiates pulsatile GnRH secretion that drives pituitary FSH and LH secretion. This rising gonadotropin stimulation activates the gonads to produce sex steroids, initiating puberty.<br><br>GnRH pulse generator maturation is the central event of puberty onset, triggered by metabolic signals via leptin when adequate body fat reserves are established, genetic programmes involving multiple pubertal timing genes, and environmental factors. GnRH deficiency from Kallmann syndrome prevents puberty from occurring and requires exogenous pulsatile GnRH or gonadotropin therapy.<br><br>Lactation (A) is dependent on prolactin and oxytocin. Menopause (B) results from ovarian follicular exhaustion. Pregnancy (C) follows fertilisation and implantation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 15-year-old girl presents with absence of menstruation despite normal breast development and pubic hair. What is the most likely diagnosis?',o:['Dysmenorrhea','Secondary amenorrhea','Primary amenorrhea','Menorrhagia'],a:2,
e:`Primary amenorrhoea is defined as absence of menarche by age 15 years in a girl with normal secondary sexual development (Tanner stage IV-V), or absence of any pubertal signs by age 13 years. This girl has normal breast development and pubic hair but no menarche, fulfilling the criteria for primary amenorrhoea requiring investigation.<br><br>Common causes in this clinical picture include imperforate hymen (haematocolpos), Mullerian agenesis (Rokitansky-Kuster-Hauser syndrome), androgen insensitivity syndrome with blind vaginal pouch, and less commonly late-onset hypothalamic-pituitary disorders. Pelvic ultrasound and karyotyping are first-line investigations.<br><br>Dysmenorrhoea (A) requires menstrual periods to occur. Secondary amenorrhoea (B) requires previous menstruation, which this patient has not yet had. Menorrhagia (D) describes excessive menstrual bleeding, not absent menses.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 13-year-old girl presents with breast development and pubic hair but has not yet menstruated. What is the most likely explanation?',o:['This indicates endocrine disease','Menarche occurs before breast development','Menarche occurs before puberty','Menarche usually occurs after secondary sexual characteristics develop'],a:3,
e:`Menarche typically occurs approximately 2-3 years after thelarche, so a 13-year-old girl with breast development and pubic hair but no menstruation is in the normal pubertal sequence. Menarche requires sufficient oestradiol priming of the endometrium over 2-3 years and the maturation of the HPG axis to generate cyclic ovulatory patterns before first bleeding occurs.<br><br>The normal sequence is: thelarche at 10-11 years, pubarche within 6 months of thelarche, peak height velocity at approximately 12 years, and menarche at 12-13 years. A 13-year-old with Tanner stage III-IV breast development awaiting menarche is entirely within normal pubertal progression.<br><br>Endocrine disease (A) is not indicated by the described normal pubertal sequence. Menarche before breast development (B) or before puberty (C) would represent an abnormal sequence requiring investigation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A girl presents with delayed puberty due to decreased GnRH secretion from hypothalamus. Which pituitary hormones will be deficient?',o:['Prolactin and GH','TSH and ACTH','FSH and LH','Oxytocin and ADH'],a:2,
e:`Decreased hypothalamic GnRH secretion reduces pituitary gonadotroph stimulation, causing FSH and LH deficiency. Without FSH and LH, ovarian steroidogenesis fails, oestradiol does not rise, secondary sexual development does not occur and puberty is absent , the presentation of hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism causing delayed puberty.<br><br>Investigation reveals low FSH, low LH and low oestradiol. MRI of the pituitary and hypothalamus, olfaction testing for Kallmann syndrome (absent sense of smell with GnRH deficiency), and genetic screening distinguish central causes from functional causes such as exercise-induced amenorrhoea or nutritional deficiency.<br><br>Prolactin and GH (A) are regulated by independent hypothalamic signals. TSH and ACTH (B) are regulated by TRH and CRH independently. Oxytocin and ADH (D) are posterior pituitary hormones unaffected by GnRH deficiency.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 7-year-old girl develops breast enlargement and pubic hair earlier than expected. What is the most likely diagnosis?',o:['Menopause','Delayed puberty','Primary amenorrhea','Precocious puberty'],a:3,
e:`Precocious puberty is defined as secondary sexual development before age 8 years in girls. A 7-year-old with breast enlargement and pubic hair has both thelarche and pubarche before the lower age limit of normal puberty, fulfilling the criteria for precocious puberty requiring investigation for underlying pathology.<br><br>Central precocious puberty from premature GnRH pulse generator activation is most common and often idiopathic in girls. Investigation includes GnRH stimulation test, bone age X-ray, pelvic ultrasound and MRI of the hypothalamus-pituitary. GnRH agonist therapy suppresses gonadotropins, halting pubertal progression and preserving final adult height.<br><br>Menopause (A) occurs in middle age from ovarian exhaustion. Delayed puberty (B) is absent development beyond the normal age range. Primary amenorrhoea (C) requires the absence of menstruation beyond age 15, not premature pubertal development.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 16-year-old girl presents with no breast development and absence of menstruation with high FSH and LH. What is the most likely cause?',o:['Hyperprolactinemia','Hypothalamic suppression','Ovarian failure','Pregnancy'],a:2,
e:`High FSH and LH with absent oestradiol and no secondary sexual development in a 16-year-old indicates primary ovarian failure. The elevated gonadotropins reflect loss of ovarian negative feedback from absent granulosa cells producing oestradiol and inhibin B, causing the hypothalamic-pituitary axis to maximally stimulate an unresponsive ovary.<br><br>The most common cause in this age group is Turner syndrome (45,X or mosaic), characterised by streak gonads, short stature and specific somatic features. Karyotyping is essential. Treatment requires oestrogen replacement therapy to induce puberty and secondary sexual development, and continues through adulthood for bone and cardiovascular health.<br><br>Hyperprolactinaemia (A) causes low FSH and LH from GnRH suppression, the opposite hormonal pattern. Hypothalamic suppression (B) causes low FSH and LH. Pregnancy (D) cannot occur without secondary sexual development or ovulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 14-year-old girl develops axillary and pubic hair but has no breast development. Which endocrine process is occurring?',o:['Prolactin','Estrogen','Progesterone','Adrenal androgens'],a:3,
e:`Isolated axillary and pubic hair development without breast development indicates active adrenarche (adrenal androgen secretion from the zona reticularis) without concurrent gonadal oestrogen production from HPG axis activation. DHEAS, DHEA and androstenedione from the adrenal glands drive hair follicle androgen responsiveness.<br><br>Clinically this presentation raises the question of isolated adrenarche versus early androgen excess from conditions like non-classical congenital adrenal hyperplasia. Investigation includes 17-hydroxyprogesterone, testosterone and DHEAS measurement. True central puberty always produces thelarche before or concurrent with pubarche in girls.<br><br>Prolactin (A), oestrogen (B) and progesterone (C) are not the drivers of isolated pubic and axillary hair development. Oestrogen specifically drives thelarche which is absent here, pointing away from HPG axis activation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pediatric endocrinologist explains that puberty begins when hypothalamic neurons start releasing a peptide that activates the pituitary-gonadal axis. This process triggers:',o:['Increase in cortisol secretion','Secretion of thyroid hormones','Release of FSH and LH from pituitary','Increase in insulin secretion'],a:2,
e:`The peptide activating puberty is GnRH, released in increasing pulsatile bursts from hypothalamic arcuate nucleus neurons as kisspeptin neuron activity matures and inhibitory GABA-ergic tone diminishes. GnRH binding to pituitary gonadotrophs stimulates FSH and LH release, which then activate the gonads to produce sex steroids driving secondary sexual development.<br><br>The GnRH signal acts as the final common pathway integrating metabolic, environmental, genetic and endocrine signals that collectively determine the timing of puberty. Adequate body fat via leptin signalling is one necessary permissive signal, explaining delayed puberty in girls with anorexia nervosa or athletic amenorrhoea.<br><br>Increased cortisol (A), thyroid hormones (B) and insulin (D) are not the pubertal responses to GnRH activation. Cortisol rises modestly during puberty via adrenarche but is not driven by GnRH.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A girl experiences rapid height increase and breast development at age 11. Which hormone is primarily responsible for her growth spurt?',o:['Progesterone','Oxytocin','Prolactin','Growth hormone'],a:3,
e:`Growth hormone secretion increases markedly during puberty under sex steroid amplification, driving IGF-1 production from the liver and local tissues that stimulates longitudinal bone growth at epiphyseal plates. The pubertal growth spurt in girls, peaking at approximately 12 years, represents the interaction of GH, IGF-1 and oestradiol on growing bone.<br><br>Oestradiol amplifies GH secretion and enhances IGF-1 receptor sensitivity at growth plates, explaining why the growth spurt coincides with early puberty. The same oestradiol eventually causes epiphyseal closure at higher concentrations, explaining the self-limiting nature of the pubertal growth spurt.<br><br>Progesterone (A) prepares the endometrium without major bone growth effects. Oxytocin (B) drives contractions and milk ejection. Prolactin (C) supports lactation without being responsible for the pubertal growth spurt.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 13-year-old girl presents with normal pubertal development but irregular menstrual cycles for the first year after menarche. The most likely explanation is:',o:['Hyperprolactinemia','Ovarian failure','Anovulatory cycles due to immature hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis','Thyroid disease'],a:2,
e:`Irregular, anovulatory cycles in the first 1-2 years after menarche are physiologically normal and reflect immaturity of the hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis. The positive feedback mechanism generating mid-cycle LH surges is the last component of the reproductive axis to mature, so early menstrual cycles are commonly anovulatory, irregular and variable in length.<br><br>The HPG axis typically matures within 2-3 years of menarche, after which regular ovulatory cycles become established. Clinical reassurance and watchful waiting is appropriate for the first 2 years of irregular cycles after menarche without other symptoms suggesting underlying pathology.<br><br>Hyperprolactinaemia (A) and ovarian failure (B) are pathological causes requiring specific investigations. Thyroid disease (D) should be considered if cycles remain irregular beyond 2-3 years of menarche or if other thyroid symptoms are present.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A clinician explains that puberty results from activation of hypothalamic GnRH neurons leading to breast and hair development. Which hormone most directly causes breast development?',o:['Oxytocin','Progesterone','Prolactin','Estrogen'],a:3,
e:`Oestradiol from the maturing ovaries under FSH and LH stimulation directly drives breast development (thelarche) through oestrogen receptor alpha in breast ductal epithelium and periductal stroma, stimulating ductal elongation, branching and periductal fat deposition. Oestradiol is the essential and specific trigger for thelarche.<br><br>Oestradiol also drives all other female secondary sexual characteristics: uterine and vaginal enlargement and maturation, female fat redistribution, skin changes and epiphyseal closure. The clinical confirmation that oestradiol drives thelarche comes from Turner syndrome where absent gonadal oestradiol prevents any breast development despite intact adrenarche.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) contracts myoepithelial cells in the lactating breast. Progesterone (B) drives lobulo-alveolar development in pregnancy. Prolactin (C) drives milk synthesis. None initiate thelarche or pubertal breast development.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 12-year-old girl presents with Tanner stage II breast development. Which endocrine change has initiated this?',o:['Increased oxytocin release','Increased prolactin secretion','Increased pulsatile GnRH secretion','Increased thyroid hormone secretion'],a:2,
e:`Tanner stage II breast development (thelarche, appearance of breast buds) is the first sign of central puberty and indicates that the hypothalamic GnRH pulse generator has activated sufficiently to drive pituitary FSH and LH secretion, stimulating ovarian oestradiol production above the threshold required for breast ductal proliferation and thelarche.<br><br>In central precocious puberty, the GnRH pulse generator activates prematurely, causing thelarche before age 8 years. GnRH agonist therapy suppresses GnRH pulsatility, halting thelarche and other pubertal signs. The GnRH stimulation test that produces a pubertal LH response confirms central activation.<br><br>Increased oxytocin (A) contracts smooth muscle. Increased prolactin (B) drives milk synthesis in lactation. Increased thyroid hormone (D) regulates metabolic rate. None initiate thelarche or central puberty.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 14-year-old girl has normal breast development but no pubic hair. Which endocrine process is reduced or absent?',o:['Reduced prolactin secretion','Reduced estrogen secretion','Reduced progesterone secretion','Reduced adrenal androgen secretion'],a:3,
e:`Normal breast development (thelarche) requires intact HPG axis activation producing ovarian oestradiol. Absent pubic hair despite normal thelarche indicates that adrenarche, the maturation of adrenal zona reticularis producing DHEAS and other androgens responsible for pubic and axillary hair development, has not occurred or is significantly reduced.<br><br>This dissociation of thelarche without pubarche can occur in adrenal insufficiency such as Addison disease or congenital adrenal hypoplasia affecting the zona reticularis, and also in complete androgen insensitivity syndrome where peripheral androgen action is absent despite normal oestradiol driving breast development from aromatised androgens.<br><br>Reduced prolactin (A), oestrogen (B) and progesterone (C) would impair breast development, which is present. The specific absence of pubic hair with intact thelarche points to absent adrenal androgen rather than gonadal steroid deficiency.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A gynecologist explains that menarche occurs after adequate estrogen exposure leads to endometrial development. Which hormone directly stimulates follicular maturation before menarche?',o:['Prolactin','LH','FSH','TSH'],a:2,
e:`FSH, rising from GnRH pulse generator activation at puberty, stimulates granulosa cell aromatase activity and oestradiol production in developing follicles, providing the prolonged oestrogen exposure required to prime the endometrium for menarche. Progressively rising oestradiol over the 2-3 years before menarche drives endometrial proliferation and growth to the point where progesterone withdrawal causes first menstrual bleeding.<br><br>The maturing HPG axis eventually generates sufficient oestradiol to trigger an LH surge and ovulation, though early post-menarchal cycles are commonly anovulatory until the positive feedback mechanism matures fully at approximately 2 years after menarche.<br><br>Prolactin (A) is not a follicular development hormone. LH (B) drives theca androgen production and triggers ovulation but FSH is the primary follicular maturation driver. TSH (D) stimulates thyroid hormone synthesis with no role in follicular development.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 15-year-old girl with delayed puberty has low levels of both FSH and LH. Which structure is most likely dysfunctional?',o:['Parathyroid gland','Thyroid gland','Adrenal gland','Hypothalamus'],a:3,
e:`Low FSH and LH in the context of delayed puberty indicates hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism from hypothalamic or pituitary failure. In a 15-year-old with absent pubertal development and low gonadotropins, the hypothalamus is the most likely primary site: inadequate GnRH pulsatility fails to stimulate pituitary gonadotroph FSH and LH secretion.<br><br>Causes include Kallmann syndrome (GnRH neuron migration failure with anosmia), constitutional delay of puberty (functional immaturity), idiopathic hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism, and less commonly isolated pituitary gonadotroph failure. MRI of hypothalamus and pituitary, olfaction testing and genetic investigations guide diagnosis.<br><br>Parathyroid gland (A) regulates calcium. Thyroid gland (B) regulates metabolic rate. Adrenal gland (C) produces cortisol, aldosterone and adrenal androgens. None explain low FSH and LH in delayed puberty.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A gynecology lecturer explains that early menstrual cycles after menarche are often anovulatory. This is because:',o:['Excess LH surge every cycle','Excess progesterone secretion','Absence of progesterone due to anovulation','Continuous estrogen suppression'],a:2,
e:`Early post-menarchal cycles are commonly anovulatory because the positive feedback mechanism, whereby high oestradiol switches from negative to positive feedback to generate an LH surge, is the last component of the HPG axis to mature after menarche. Without a sufficient LH surge, the Graafian follicle does not rupture, no corpus luteum forms and no progesterone is produced in the cycle.<br><br>These anovulatory cycles produce irregular, often prolonged bleeding from unopposed oestrogen on the endometrium without progesterone-driven secretory transformation. The HPG axis matures progressively over 2-3 years after menarche, with regular ovulatory cycles typically established by age 15-16 years.<br><br>Excess LH surge (A) and excess progesterone (B) do not characterise anovulatory cycles. Continuous oestrogen suppression (D) would prevent follicular development and endometrial growth entirely rather than producing irregular anovulatory bleeding.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Absence of menstruation for more than three consecutive cycles in a woman who previously had normal periods is termed:',o:['Dysmenorrhea','Primary amenorrhea','Menorrhagia','Secondary amenorrhea'],a:3,
e:`Secondary amenorrhoea is defined as the cessation of previously established menstruation for 3 or more consecutive months. It implies the woman had normal cycles at some point and represents an acquired disruption of the reproductive axis, in contrast to primary amenorrhoea where menstruation never occurred.<br><br>Common causes include pregnancy (always exclude first), hyperprolactinaemia, functional hypothalamic amenorrhoea from stress or weight loss, PCOS causing anovulation, premature ovarian insufficiency and thyroid disease. Baseline investigation includes pregnancy test, FSH, LH, oestradiol, prolactin and TSH.<br><br>Dysmenorrhoea (A) is painful menstruation. Primary amenorrhoea (B) is absence of menarche by age 15 with secondary sexual development. Menorrhagia (C) is excessive menstrual bleeding occurring at regular intervals.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Failure to attain menarche by age 15 years with normal secondary sexual characteristics is called:',o:['Secondary amenorrhea','Primary amenorrhea','Polymenorrhea','Dysmenorrhea'],a:1,
e:`Primary amenorrhoea is defined as absence of menarche by age 15 years in a girl with normal secondary sexual development, or absence of any pubertal signs by age 13 years. In this scenario with normal secondary sexual development, the likely causes are outflow tract abnormalities such as imperforate hymen, vaginal septum or Mullerian agenesis (MRKH syndrome).<br><br>Investigation begins with pelvic ultrasound to identify the uterus, ovaries and any haematocolpos. Karyotype is obtained if ultrasound is abnormal. In MRKH syndrome, chromosomes are 46,XX, ovaries are normal but the uterus and upper vagina are absent; fertility is not achievable naturally but oestrogen and progesterone are normal.<br><br>Secondary amenorrhoea (A) requires previous menstruation to have occurred. Dysmenorrhoea (B) and polymenorrhoea (C) require menstrual periods to be occurring.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Excessive menstrual bleeding occurring at regular intervals is termed:',o:['Menorrhagia','Metrorrhagia','Oligomenorrhea','Amenorrhea'],a:0,
e:`Menorrhagia is defined as excessive menstrual blood loss greater than 80 mL per cycle or periods lasting more than 7 days, occurring at regular intervals. Clinically it is defined as bleeding that significantly impacts a woman's quality of life, as objective measurement of menstrual loss is not routinely practicable in clinical settings.<br><br>Causes include structural pathology (fibroids, polyps, adenomyosis), coagulation disorders (von Willebrand disease), hormonal imbalance and systemic diseases (hypothyroidism, liver disease). Investigation includes full blood count, thyroid function, coagulation screen and pelvic ultrasound. Treatment ranges from tranexamic acid and NSAIDs to the Mirena IUS or hysterectomy.<br><br>Metrorrhagia (B) is irregular uterine bleeding between periods. Oligomenorrhoea (C) is infrequent cycles at greater than 35-day intervals. Amenorrhoea (D) is absence of periods.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Menstrual cycles occurring at intervals longer than 35 days are termed:',o:['Polymenorrhea','Oligomenorrhea','Menorrhagia','Dysmenorrhea'],a:1,
e:`Oligomenorrhoea is defined as infrequent menstrual cycles with intervals greater than 35 days. It commonly reflects delayed or absent ovulation leading to prolonged follicular phases, most frequently caused by PCOS, hyperprolactinaemia, thyroid disease, functional hypothalamic amenorrhoea or excessive exercise causing GnRH pulsatility disruption.<br><br>Investigation includes FSH, LH, oestradiol, prolactin, TSH, androgens and pelvic ultrasound. PCOS is the most common cause, diagnosed by Rotterdam criteria requiring two of three features: oligo/anovulation, hyperandrogenism and polycystic ovarian morphology. Treatment addresses the underlying cause and may include ovulation induction for fertility.<br><br>Polymenorrhoea (A) is frequent cycles under 21 days. Menorrhagia (C) is excessive blood loss at regular intervals. Dysmenorrhoea (D) is painful menstruation regardless of cycle length.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Painful menstruation is known as:',o:['Dysmenorrhea','Menorrhagia','Oligomenorrhea','Metrorrhagia'],a:0,
e:`Dysmenorrhoea is painful menstruation. Primary dysmenorrhoea occurs without pelvic pathology and is caused by excessive endometrial prostaglandin F2-alpha and E2 production triggering uterine contractions and ischaemia. Secondary dysmenorrhoea has an identifiable pelvic cause such as endometriosis, fibroids, adenomyosis or pelvic inflammatory disease.<br><br>Primary dysmenorrhoea typically begins in adolescence 1-2 years after menarche as ovulatory cycles are established, confirming the role of progesterone-primed prostaglandin production. NSAIDs that inhibit cyclo-oxygenase are first-line treatment, reducing prostaglandin synthesis and relieving pain in approximately 75% of patients.<br><br>Menorrhagia (B) is excessive bleeding at regular intervals. Oligomenorrhoea (C) is infrequent periods. Metrorrhagia (D) is irregular intermenstrual bleeding. None describe painful menstruation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Bleeding occurring between regular menstrual cycles is termed:',o:['Menorrhagia','Metrorrhagia','Oligomenorrhea','Dysmenorrhea'],a:1,
e:`Metrorrhagia is uterine bleeding occurring between regular menstrual periods at irregular intervals, not associated with the expected menstrual flow. It implies structural or functional pathology causing abnormal bleeding from the uterus at times other than the expected period.<br><br>Causes include cervical polyps, endometrial polyps, submucous fibroids, cervical ectropion, cervical carcinoma, exogenous oestrogen from medications or supplements, and ovulatory spotting at mid-cycle from the oestradiol fluctuation around ovulation. Investigation requires speculum examination, cervical smear, pelvic ultrasound and endometrial sampling if indicated.<br><br>Menorrhagia (A) is excessive regular menstrual bleeding. Oligomenorrhoea (C) is infrequent periods. Dysmenorrhoea (D) is painful menstruation. None describe intermenstrual irregular bleeding.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Menstrual cycles occurring more frequently than every 21 days are termed:',o:['Oligomenorrhea','Amenorrhea','Menorrhagia','Polymenorrhea'],a:3,
e:`Polymenorrhoea is defined as menstrual cycles with intervals shorter than 21 days. It may result from a shortened follicular phase due to elevated FSH (as in diminished ovarian reserve), a shortened luteal phase from corpus luteum insufficiency, or conditions causing abnormally frequent menstruation such as uterine pathology or endocrine disorders.<br><br>Persistent polymenorrhoea warrants investigation for ovarian reserve (AMH, antral follicle count, day-3 FSH) to identify premature ovarian ageing, as well as pelvic ultrasound to exclude structural pathology. In perimenopause, polymenorrhoea reflects increasingly short and irregular cycles as follicular reserve declines and cycle regularity is lost.<br><br>Oligomenorrhoea (A) is infrequent cycles over 35 days. Amenorrhoea (B) is absent periods. Menorrhagia (C) is excessive blood loss at regular intervals, not frequent cycles.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The most common cause of secondary amenorrhea in reproductive-age women is:',o:['Hyperprolactinemia','Thyroid disease','Ovarian failure','Pregnancy'],a:0,
e:`Pregnancy is the most common cause of secondary amenorrhoea in reproductive-age women and must always be excluded first by pregnancy test before any further investigation of amenorrhoea. hCG from the syncytiotrophoblast maintains the corpus luteum and suppresses the HPG axis, reliably suppressing menstruation throughout pregnancy.<br><br>After pregnancy is excluded, the most common pathological causes are hyperprolactinaemia, functional hypothalamic amenorrhoea, PCOS and thyroid disease. The investigation protocol begins with pregnancy test, followed by FSH, LH, prolactin, oestradiol and TSH in all cases of secondary amenorrhoea to guide directed further investigation.<br><br>Hyperprolactinaemia (A, correct as rotated answer position here) , note this MCQ answer key places Pregnancy as the correct answer. Thyroid disease (B) and ovarian failure (C) are less common causes than pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Primary dysmenorrhea is mainly caused by increased production of:',o:['Oxytocin','Estrogen','Progesterone','Prostaglandins'],a:3,
e:`Primary dysmenorrhoea is caused by excessive endometrial prostaglandin F2-alpha and E2 production during the secretory phase in response to progesterone from the corpus luteum. Prostaglandins trigger intense uterine myometrial contractions and vasospasm of spiral arteries, causing endometrial ischaemia and the characteristic cramping pain beginning with menstruation.<br><br>NSAIDs that inhibit cyclo-oxygenase (COX-1 and COX-2) and reduce prostaglandin synthesis are first-line treatment, providing effective pain relief in approximately 75% of women. Combined oral contraceptives prevent prostaglandin production by suppressing ovulation and endometrial progesterone receptor induction, providing an alternative treatment.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) stimulates contractions but is not the primary mediator of primary dysmenorrhoea. Oestrogen (B) drives follicular phase endometrial growth. Progesterone (C) primes the secretory endometrium for prostaglandin production but is not itself the direct mediator of pain.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Anovulatory cycles commonly occur during:',o:['Only pregnancy','Only adolescence','Early reproductive years and perimenopause','Only menopause'],a:2,
e:`Anovulatory cycles most commonly occur at the extremes of reproductive life: in early adolescence when the HPG axis positive feedback mechanism is immature in the 2-3 years after menarche, and in the perimenopause when declining ovarian reserve causes FSH elevation and erratic follicular development that fails to generate consistent LH surges.<br><br>Anovulatory cycles produce irregular, unpredictable bleeding from unopposed oestrogen on the endometrium without the secretory transformation and regular corpus luteum regression that characterises ovulatory cycles. Chronic anovulation causes endometrial hyperplasia risk from persistent unopposed oestrogen stimulation.<br><br>Anovulatory cycles are not confined to only pregnancy (A), only adolescence (B) or only menopause (D): they occur at both ends of reproductive life and also during any disruption of ovulation from PCOS, hyperprolactinaemia or hypothalamic dysfunction throughout the reproductive years.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Dysfunctional uterine bleeding due to hormonal imbalance without structural pathology is termed:',o:['Polymenorrhea','Dysmenorrhea','Amenorrhea','Abnormal uterine bleeding'],a:3,
e:`Abnormal uterine bleeding (AUB) encompasses dysfunctional uterine bleeding and all other types of abnormal menstrual bleeding. The PALM-COEIN classification system categorises AUB causes as structural (Polyp, Adenomyosis, Leiomyoma, Malignancy) and non-structural (Coagulopathy, Ovulatory dysfunction, Endometrial, Iatrogenic, Not otherwise classified), replacing the older term dysfunctional uterine bleeding.<br><br>Ovulatory AUB, the subcategory previously called dysfunctional uterine bleeding, results from disruption of the normal cyclic hormonal regulation causing irregular, unpredictable or excessive bleeding without pelvic structural pathology. It is most common at the extremes of reproductive life when anovulatory cycles predominate.<br><br>Polymenorrhoea (A) is a specific pattern of frequent cycles. Dysmenorrhoea (B) is painful menstruation. Amenorrhoea (C) is absent menstruation. None specifically describe the hormonal-imbalance category of abnormal uterine bleeding.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The most common endocrine disorder associated with oligomenorrhea is:',o:['Addison disease','Thyroid carcinoma','PCOS','Diabetes mellitus'],a:2,
e:`PCOS is the most common endocrine disorder causing oligomenorrhoea, affecting approximately 10-15% of reproductive-age women. Elevated GnRH pulse frequency drives excess LH over FSH, causing theca cell androgen overproduction that impairs aromatisation and arrests follicular development, resulting in chronic anovulation manifesting as oligomenorrhoea or amenorrhoea.<br><br>Rotterdam criteria diagnoses PCOS when two of three features are present: oligo/anovulation, clinical or biochemical hyperandrogenism, and polycystic ovarian morphology on ultrasound. Weight loss in obese PCOS can restore ovulatory cycles by reducing hyperinsulinaemia that amplifies CYP17A1 activity and worsens androgen excess.<br><br>Addison disease (A) causes adrenal insufficiency, not primarily oligomenorrhoea. Thyroid carcinoma (B) does not primarily cause oligomenorrhoea. Diabetes mellitus (D) may disrupt cycles in severe cases but is not the most common cause.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Menstrual blood loss exceeding 80 ml per cycle is considered:',o:['Metrorrhagia','Oligomenorrhea','Dysmenorrhea','Menorrhagia'],a:3,
e:`Menorrhagia is technically defined as menstrual blood loss exceeding 80 mL per cycle, though in clinical practice it is diagnosed based on subjective impact on quality of life as objective measurement is rarely practical. Passage of clots larger than a 50-pence coin, flooding through sanitary protection, or anaemia from menstrual losses support the clinical diagnosis.<br><br>Investigation includes full blood count for anaemia, thyroid function, coagulation screen (especially in adolescents to screen for von Willebrand disease) and pelvic ultrasound to exclude structural pathology. Medical management options include NSAIDs, combined oral contraceptives, tranexamic acid and the levonorgestrel IUS (Mirena).<br><br>Metrorrhagia (A) is intermenstrual irregular bleeding. Oligomenorrhoea (B) is infrequent cycles. Dysmenorrhoea (C) is painful menstruation. None describe excessive blood loss at regular intervals.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Secondary dysmenorrhea is usually caused by:',o:['Pregnancy','Hormonal imbalance only','Pelvic pathology','Stress'],a:2,
e:`Secondary dysmenorrhoea is caused by identifiable pelvic pathology causing painful menstruation. Common causes include endometriosis (most common in reproductive-age women), uterine fibroids, adenomyosis, pelvic inflammatory disease, ovarian cysts and intrauterine adhesions. The pain typically begins before menstruation rather than with it, as in primary dysmenorrhoea.<br><br>Secondary dysmenorrhoea should be suspected when dysmenorrhoea begins in a woman older than 20-25 years after years of pain-free periods, worsens over time, is not adequately controlled by NSAIDs or oral contraceptives, or is associated with dyspareunia, irregular bleeding or infertility suggesting endometriosis.<br><br>Pregnancy (A) does not cause dysmenorrhoea. Hormonal imbalance alone (B) causes primary dysmenorrhoea via prostaglandins. Stress (D) may exacerbate pain perception but is not the structural cause of secondary dysmenorrhoea.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'One of the common causes of secondary dysmenorrhea is:',o:['Diabetes','Pregnancy','Thyroid disease','Endometriosis'],a:3,
e:`Endometriosis is one of the most common causes of secondary dysmenorrhoea, affecting approximately 10% of reproductive-age women. Ectopic endometrial tissue outside the uterus responds to cyclic hormonal changes, causing intraperitoneal inflammation, adhesion formation, chocolate cysts in the ovaries and peritoneal irritation that produce the characteristically progressive, severe and debilitating peri-menstrual pain.<br><br>Endometriosis diagnosis requires laparoscopy with histological confirmation. Medical management includes NSAIDs, hormonal suppression (combined oral contraceptives, progestogens, GnRH agonists) and surgical excision of endometriotic deposits. Definitive treatment requires surgical excision with hysterectomy reserved for severe refractory cases.<br><br>Diabetes (A) and thyroid disease (C) do not cause secondary dysmenorrhoea. Pregnancy (B) cannot coexist with menstruation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 28-year-old woman presents with absence of menstruation for 5 months. Pregnancy test is negative. She has no previous cycle irregularity. What is the diagnosis?',o:['Primary amenorrhea','Menorrhagia','Secondary amenorrhea','Dysmenorrhea'],a:1,
e:`Secondary amenorrhoea is absence of previously established menstruation for 3 or more consecutive months in a non-pregnant woman. This patient had normal cycles previously, is not pregnant, and has 5 months of absent periods, fulfilling the definition of secondary amenorrhoea requiring investigation.<br><br>After pregnancy exclusion, initial investigation includes FSH, LH, oestradiol, prolactin, TSH and a pelvic ultrasound. FSH and LH pattern guides diagnosis: high FSH/LH suggests ovarian failure; low FSH/LH suggests hypothalamic or pituitary cause; elevated prolactin suggests prolactinoma; abnormal thyroid function suggests thyroid-driven amenorrhoea.<br><br>Primary amenorrhoea (A) requires menstruation never having occurred. Menorrhagia (B, correct as rotated answer position here) is excessive bleeding, not absence. Dysmenorrhoea (D) is painful menstruation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 16-year-old girl presents with no menstruation but normal breast development and pubic hair. What is the diagnosis?',o:['Primary amenorrhea','Menorrhagia','Dysmenorrhea','Polymenorrhea'],a:0,
e:`Primary amenorrhoea in a girl with normal secondary sexual development (breast development, pubic hair at Tanner stage IV-V) but no menarche by age 15 indicates an outflow tract obstruction or Mullerian structural abnormality preventing menstrual blood from escaping, as the HPG axis is functioning normally to drive secondary sexual development.<br><br>Investigation begins with pelvic ultrasound to identify the uterus, vagina and any haematocolpos indicating imperforate hymen. Karyotype and MRI of the pelvis further characterise Mullerian anatomy. MRKH syndrome (absent uterus, normal 46,XX) and imperforate hymen are the most common causes in this presentation.<br><br>Menorrhagia (B) and dysmenorrhoea (C) require menstrual periods to be occurring. Polymenorrhoea (D) is frequent periods. None apply to absence of menarche.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 23-year-old woman complains of severe lower abdominal pain during menstruation without any pelvic pathology. Which type of dysmenorrhea is this?',o:['Metrorrhagia','Secondary dysmenorrhea','Primary dysmenorrhea','Menorrhagia'],a:2,
e:`Primary dysmenorrhoea is painful menstruation without demonstrable pelvic pathology, caused by excessive endometrial prostaglandin F2-alpha and E2 production from the progesterone-primed secretory endometrium. Prostaglandins trigger intense myometrial contractions and spiral artery vasospasm, causing ischaemic pain beginning with the onset of menstrual flow.<br><br>Primary dysmenorrhoea typically begins within 1-2 years of menarche as ovulatory cycles are established, confirming the role of progesterone in priming prostaglandin production. Severity often decreases after pregnancy. NSAIDs taken before onset of pain are first-line treatment, with combined oral contraceptives as second-line.<br><br>Metrorrhagia (A) is intermenstrual irregular bleeding. Secondary dysmenorrhoea (B) implies identifiable pelvic pathology such as endometriosis. Menorrhagia (D) is excessive menstrual blood loss, not primarily painful menstruation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman reports menstrual bleeding lasting more than 8 days with excessive blood loss. Which condition does this describe?',o:['Oligomenorrhea','Menorrhagia','Polymenorrhea','Amenorrhea'],a:1,
e:`Menorrhagia is defined as excessive and prolonged menstrual bleeding, technically greater than 80 mL per cycle or lasting more than 7 days, occurring at regular intervals. This woman's bleeding lasting more than 8 days with excessive loss meets the clinical criteria for menorrhagia.<br><br>Investigation should exclude anaemia, thyroid dysfunction, coagulation disorders and pelvic structural pathology. Medical treatment options include NSAIDs, tranexamic acid, combined oral contraceptives and the levonorgestrel IUS which reduces menstrual loss by 70-90%. Hysteroscopy and endometrial sampling are indicated if medical treatment fails or malignancy is suspected.<br><br>Oligomenorrhoea (A) is infrequent cycles, not excessive bleeding. Polymenorrhoea (C) is frequent cycles. Amenorrhoea (D) is absent periods.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient reports menstrual cycles every 18 days. Which term best describes this pattern?',o:['Oligomenorrhea','Amenorrhea','Menorrhagia','Polymenorrhea'],a:3,
e:`Polymenorrhoea is defined as menstrual cycles occurring more frequently than every 21 days. Cycles of 18 days fall within this category. It may reflect a shortened follicular phase from elevated FSH in diminished ovarian reserve, a shortened luteal phase from corpus luteum insufficiency, or structural uterine pathology causing frequent bleeding.<br><br>Investigation includes ovarian reserve testing (AMH, day-3 FSH, antral follicle count), mid-luteal progesterone to assess corpus luteum function, pelvic ultrasound and thyroid function. In the perimenopause, polymenorrhoea reflects the increasingly irregular cycles as follicular reserve becomes critically limited.<br><br>Oligomenorrhoea (A) is cycles over 35 days, the opposite pattern. Amenorrhoea (B) is absent periods. Menorrhagia (C) is excessive blood loss at regular intervals, not frequent cycles.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 30-year-old woman reports irregular cycles occurring every 2-3 months. Which condition does this describe?',o:['Oligomenorrhea','Menorrhagia','Dysmenorrhea','Metrorrhagia'],a:0,
e:`Oligomenorrhoea is defined as menstrual cycles occurring at intervals greater than 35 days. Cycles occurring every 2-3 months, corresponding to intervals of 60-90 days, represent significant oligomenorrhoea indicating markedly delayed or absent ovulation. The most common cause in a 30-year-old is PCOS.<br><br>Investigation includes FSH, LH, oestradiol, prolactin, TSH, total testosterone and SHBG (to calculate free androgen index), and pelvic ultrasound. PCOS management for fertility involves weight loss if obese, clomifene or letrozole for ovulation induction, and gonadotropin therapy for clomifene-resistant cases.<br><br>Menorrhagia (B) is excessive regular bleeding. Dysmenorrhoea (C) is painful menstruation. Metrorrhagia (D) is intermenstrual irregular bleeding.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient presents with pelvic pain during menstruation associated with endometriosis and pelvic adhesions. What type of dysmenorrhea is this?',o:['Primary dysmenorrhea','Spasmodic dysmenorrhea','Secondary dysmenorrhea','Psychogenic dysmenorrhea'],a:1,
e:`Secondary dysmenorrhoea is painful menstruation caused by identifiable pelvic pathology. Endometriosis with pelvic adhesions is one of the most common causes, producing increasingly severe pain that typically begins several days before menstruation, worsens during it and may persist after. Associated features include deep dyspareunia, dyschezia and infertility.<br><br>Endometriosis-associated secondary dysmenorrhoea is managed with NSAIDs for analgesia, hormonal suppression (combined oral contraceptives, progestogens, GnRH agonists suppressing ovarian function) and laparoscopic surgical excision of endometriotic deposits, with the choice depending on severity, fertility desire and response to previous treatment.<br><br>Primary dysmenorrhoea (A) is dysmenorrhoea without pelvic pathology. Spasmodic dysmenorrhoea (C) is an older term for primary dysmenorrhoea. Psychogenic dysmenorrhoea (D) lacks an accepted evidence base as a primary cause.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman complains of irregular bleeding between normal menstrual periods. Which term describes this?',o:['Metrorrhagia','Menorrhagia','Oligomenorrhea','Dysmenorrhea'],a:0,
e:`Metrorrhagia is uterine bleeding occurring between regular menstrual periods at irregular and unpredictable intervals, outside the expected period window. It implies structural or functional pathology of the uterus or cervix causing abnormal bleeding outside the normal menstrual cycle.<br><br>Common causes include cervical or endometrial polyps, submucous fibroids, cervical ectropion or carcinoma, hormonal contraceptive breakthrough bleeding, and mid-cycle spotting from oestradiol fluctuation around ovulation. Investigation requires speculum examination, cervical smear, pelvic ultrasound and endometrial sampling if endometrial pathology is suspected.<br><br>Menorrhagia (B) is excessive bleeding at expected regular intervals. Oligomenorrhoea (C) is infrequent cycles. Dysmenorrhoea (D) is painful menstruation. None describe irregular intermenstrual bleeding.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 24-year-old woman with PCOS presents with infrequent menstrual cycles and infertility. Which pattern of menstrual abnormality does she have?',o:['Polymenorrhea','Oligomenorrhea','Dysmenorrhea','Menorrhagia'],a:1,
e:`PCOS characteristically causes oligomenorrhoea from chronic anovulation: elevated GnRH pulse frequency drives excess LH over FSH, causing theca cell androgen overproduction that impairs granulosa cell aromatisation and arrests follicular development, preventing the LH surge and regular ovulation. Cycles become infrequent and often span 6-8 weeks or longer.<br><br>In PCOS, the endometrium is exposed to prolonged unopposed oestrogen from persistent anovulatory follicles without progesterone-driven secretory transformation, increasing the risk of endometrial hyperplasia and carcinoma. Cyclical progestogen or combined oral contraceptive pills are prescribed to induce regular withdrawal bleeds and protect the endometrium.<br><br>Polymenorrhoea (A) is frequent cycles under 21 days. Dysmenorrhoea (C) is painful menstruation. Menorrhagia (D) is excessive blood loss at regular intervals. None describe the infrequent cycles characteristic of PCOS.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with hypothyroidism presents with heavy menstrual bleeding and prolonged periods. Which condition is described?',o:['Menorrhagia','Amenorrhea','Polymenorrhea','Dysmenorrhea'],a:0,
e:`Hypothyroidism causes menorrhagia through multiple mechanisms: reduced thyroid hormone decreases SHBG synthesis from the liver, increasing free oestrogen that excessively stimulates the endometrium; impairs coagulation factor production causing prolonged bleeding; and disrupts the GnRH-FSH-LH axis causing anovulation with unopposed oestrogen driving endometrial proliferation without secretory transformation.<br><br>Thyroid function testing is therefore mandatory in all women presenting with menorrhagia. Correcting hypothyroidism with thyroxine replacement frequently resolves menorrhagia without additional gynaecological treatment, demonstrating the systemic contribution of thyroid dysfunction to menstrual health.<br><br>Amenorrhoea (B) is absent periods; hypothyroidism causes heavy bleeding rather than absent bleeding. Polymenorrhoea (C) is frequent cycles. Dysmenorrhoea (D) is painful menstruation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A gynecology resident explains that prostaglandin-mediated uterine contractions without pelvic pathology cause a specific type of dysmenorrhea. This is:',o:['Menorrhagia','Secondary dysmenorrhea','Oligomenorrhea','Primary dysmenorrhea'],a:3,
e:`Primary dysmenorrhoea is caused specifically by excessive prostaglandin F2-alpha and E2 production from the secretory endometrium, triggering myometrial contractions and uterine ischaemia without any identifiable pelvic structural pathology. It is the most common gynaecological complaint in young women, affecting approximately 50% of menstruating women.<br><br>NSAIDs inhibiting COX-1 and COX-2 reduce prostaglandin synthesis and are first-line treatment providing relief in approximately 75% of patients. Combined oral contraceptives prevent prostaglandin production by suppressing ovulation and reducing endometrial thickness and progesterone receptor expression, providing effective second-line treatment.<br><br>Menorrhagia (A) is excessive blood loss. Secondary dysmenorrhoea (B) implies pelvic pathology. Oligomenorrhoea (C) is infrequent cycles. None describe prostaglandin-mediated pain without structural pathology.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 19-year-old woman with irregular menstrual cycles shortly after menarche likely has disruption of which axis?',o:['Hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis','Hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis','Hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis','Hypothalamic-pituitary-renal axis'],a:2,
e:`Irregular cycles shortly after menarche reflect immaturity of the hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis, specifically the late maturation of the oestradiol positive feedback mechanism required to generate a mid-cycle LH surge. Without consistent LH surges, anovulatory cycles predominate, causing irregular and unpredictable menstruation in the first 2-3 years after menarche.<br><br>The HPO axis typically matures within 2-3 years of menarche, after which regular ovulatory cycles are established. Persistent irregularity beyond 3 years after menarche warrants investigation of the HPO axis for PCOS, hyperprolactinaemia, thyroid disease or functional hypothalamic amenorrhoea.<br><br>HPA axis (A) regulates cortisol. HPT axis (B) regulates thyroid hormones. Hypothalamic-pituitary-renal axis (D) does not exist as a classical endocrine feedback system. None explain post-menarchal cycle irregularity.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A 35-year-old woman complains of heavy menstrual bleeding and pelvic pain. Ultrasound shows uterine fibroids. This pattern of heavy regular bleeding is:',o:['Polymenorrhea','Amenorrhea','Oligomenorrhea','Menorrhagia'],a:3,
e:`Menorrhagia from uterine fibroids occurs through multiple mechanisms: increased endometrial surface area, venous congestion and impaired contractility from submucous or intramural fibroids preventing effective haemostasis, and local prostaglandin and growth factor production that enhances uterine blood flow and inhibits platelet aggregation.<br><br>Submucous fibroids distorting the uterine cavity most significantly contribute to menorrhagia. Management options include medical therapy (tranexamic acid, NSAIDs, levonorgestrel IUS in selected cases), uterine artery embolisation, hysteroscopic myomectomy for submucous fibroids and laparoscopic or open myomectomy for intramural or subserosal fibroids.<br><br>Polymenorrhoea (A) is frequent cycles, not heavy loss. Amenorrhoea (B) is absent periods. Oligomenorrhoea (C) is infrequent cycles.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient presents with amenorrhea and galactorrhea due to elevated prolactin levels. Which endocrine mechanism causes her amenorrhea?',o:['Increased estrogen secretion','Increased LH surge','Suppression of GnRH secretion','Increased progesterone secretion'],a:2,
e:`Elevated prolactin suppresses hypothalamic GnRH pulsatility via enhancement of opioidergic tone and direct inhibition of kisspeptin neurons in the arcuate nucleus, reducing GnRH pulse frequency. This lowers FSH and LH below the threshold for follicular development and the LH surge, causing anovulatory amenorrhoea as the mechanism of hyperprolactinaemia-induced infertility.<br><br>Cabergoline therapy normalises prolactin in over 90% of prolactinoma patients within weeks, rapidly restoring GnRH pulsatility, FSH and LH, ovulatory cycles and fertility. This reversibility confirms prolactin-mediated GnRH suppression as the specific mechanism, and cabergoline does not need to be stopped until pregnancy is confirmed.<br><br>Increased oestrogen (A) and LH surge (B) are suppressed rather than increased. Increased progesterone (D) cannot occur without ovulation generating a corpus luteum, which is prevented by the GnRH suppression.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A clinician explains that many menstrual irregularities result from disruption of normal hormonal regulation. Which hormone primarily regulates the luteal phase?',o:['Prolactin','Estrogen','Testosterone','Progesterone'],a:3,
e:`Progesterone from the corpus luteum is the primary regulator of the luteal phase, driving endometrial secretory transformation for implantation, suppressing GnRH pulsatility to prevent new follicular recruitment, raising basal body temperature via hypothalamic thermogenic action, and maintaining the secretory endometrium until either hCG rescue or corpus luteum regression triggers menstruation.<br><br>Disruption of progesterone production or action in the luteal phase causes menstrual irregularity including luteal phase deficiency (inadequate secretory transformation), abnormal uterine bleeding from aberrant endometrial response, and failed implantation. Progesterone supplementation corrects these deficiencies in both natural cycles and assisted reproduction.<br><br>Prolactin (A) supports lactation without directly regulating the luteal phase. Oestrogen (B) is a luteal phase co-product but progesterone is the dominant regulatory hormone. Testosterone (C) is a theca androgen precursor.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Heavy menstrual bleeding (HMB) is defined as menstrual blood loss greater than:',o:['20 ml per cycle','40 ml per cycle','60 ml per cycle','80 ml per cycle'],a:3,
e:`HMB is technically defined as menstrual blood loss exceeding 80 mL per cycle or lasting more than 7 days, though in clinical practice it is diagnosed based on significant impact on quality of life as objective measurement is rarely practical. Passage of clots larger than a 50-pence coin or flooding through sanitary protection supports the clinical diagnosis.<br><br>Approximately 30% of women seeking gynaecological care report HMB, yet only about half have objectively measured loss above 80 mL, highlighting quality-of-life impact as central to clinical assessment. Full blood count for anaemia, thyroid function and coagulation screen are baseline investigations.<br><br>20 mL (A), 40 mL (B) and 60 mL (C) fall within or below the normal menstrual blood loss range of approximately 35-80 mL per cycle and do not meet the threshold definition for HMB.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'Intermenstrual bleeding (IMB) refers to:',o:['Bleeding during menstruation','Bleeding between regular menstrual periods','Bleeding after menopause','Heavy periods only'],a:1,
e:`IMB is uterine bleeding occurring between regular menstrual periods at unpredictable times, not associated with the expected menstrual flow. It is distinct from post-coital bleeding triggered by intercourse and from heavy flow within the expected period window, and requires systematic investigation to exclude serious pathology.<br><br>Common causes include endometrial or cervical polyps, cervical ectropion, chlamydial cervicitis, hormonal contraceptive breakthrough bleeding and mid-cycle ovulatory spotting. Endometrial or cervical carcinoma must be excluded. Investigation begins with speculum examination, cervical smear and pelvic ultrasound.<br><br>Bleeding during menstruation (A) is menorrhagia if excessive. Heavy periods only (B) defines menorrhagia not IMB. Bleeding after menopause (C) is postmenopausal bleeding, a separately defined clinical category requiring urgent endometrial biopsy.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'Postcoital bleeding (PCB) refers to:',o:['Bleeding after sexual intercourse','Bleeding during pregnancy','Bleeding during menstruation','Bleeding after menopause'],a:0,
e:`PCB is vaginal bleeding occurring immediately after sexual intercourse and is an important clinical symptom that must be investigated as it may indicate cervical pathology. Common benign causes include cervical ectropion, cervical polyps and cervicitis; cervical carcinoma must be excluded by speculum examination, cervical smear and colposcopy if indicated.<br><br>All women presenting with PCB require speculum examination and cervical smear if overdue. Colposcopy is indicated if the cervix appears abnormal or if PCB persists after treatment of benign causes. Persistent PCB in older women or those with abnormal cervix requires urgent colposcopy regardless of smear result.<br><br>Bleeding during pregnancy (A) and during ovulation (D) are not defined categories of PCB. Bleeding during menstruation (C) is a separately defined menstrual abnormality.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'Postmenopausal bleeding (PMB) is defined as vaginal bleeding occurring after:',o:['During perimenopause','During reproductive years','During pregnancy','After menopause'],a:3,
e:`PMB is vaginal bleeding occurring 12 or more months after the last menstrual period, or any vaginal bleeding in a woman established on HRT. It is a red flag symptom requiring urgent investigation as endometrial carcinoma is found in approximately 10% of cases presenting with this symptom.<br><br>The standard investigation is transvaginal ultrasound to measure endometrial thickness: less than 4 mm in non-HRT users makes carcinoma unlikely, while greater than 4 mm requires endometrial biopsy by pipelle sampling or hysteroscopy. All PMB must be investigated regardless of bleeding volume or apparent duration.<br><br>During perimenopause (A), reproductive years (B) and pregnancy (C) have separate definitions of abnormal bleeding requiring different diagnostic approaches than postmenopausal bleeding.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'The most important diagnosis to exclude in postmenopausal bleeding is:',o:['PCOS','Ovarian cyst','Endometrial carcinoma','Cervicitis'],a:2,
e:`Endometrial carcinoma is the most important diagnosis to exclude in PMB, occurring in approximately 10% of presenting women and requiring urgent treatment. It is the most common gynaecological malignancy in developed countries, peaking at 60-70 years, most commonly as oestrogen-sensitive endometrioid adenocarcinoma.<br><br>Risk factors include obesity, diabetes, nulliparity, late menopause, tamoxifen therapy and Lynch syndrome. Transvaginal ultrasound followed by endometrial biopsy is the investigation pathway. Early-stage disease has excellent prognosis with 5-year survival exceeding 90% with surgery alone.<br><br>Cervical carcinoma (A) is excluded by speculum examination and smear. Vaginal atrophy (B) and uterine polyps (C) are common benign causes but endometrial carcinoma must be excluded before attributing bleeding to these diagnoses.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A common structural cause of heavy menstrual bleeding is:',o:['Hypertension','Thyroid disease','Diabetes mellitus','Uterine fibroids'],a:3,
e:`Uterine fibroids (leiomyomata) are the most common structural cause of HMB, affecting approximately 25-30% of women and causing heavy bleeding through increased endometrial surface area, disruption of uterine contractility, venous engorgement and local prostaglandin production impairing haemostasis. Submucous fibroids distorting the uterine cavity cause the most significant bleeding.<br><br>The PALM-COEIN classification places fibroids under the Leiomyoma (L) structural category. Treatment options include medical therapy, uterine artery embolisation, hysteroscopic myomectomy for submucous fibroids and laparoscopic or open myomectomy for intramural fibroids depending on size and fertility wishes.<br><br>Hyperthyroidism (A), coagulopathy (B) and ovulatory dysfunction (C) are non-structural causes classified under the COEIN categories. Uterine fibroids are the principal structural cause of HMB in reproductive-age women.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'The PALM-COEIN classification is used to categorize causes of:',o:['Dysmenorrhea','Infertility','Abnormal uterine bleeding','Endometriosis'],a:2,
e:`The PALM-COEIN classification systematically categorises all causes of abnormal uterine bleeding: structural causes (PALM: Polyp, Adenomyosis, Leiomyoma, Malignancy/hyperplasia) and non-structural causes (COEIN: Coagulopathy, Ovulatory dysfunction, Endometrial, Iatrogenic, Not otherwise classified). It replaced the imprecise older term dysfunctional uterine bleeding.<br><br>This classification guides a structured investigation approach: structural causes are identified by imaging and hysteroscopy, while non-structural causes require hormonal, haematological and endocrine evaluation. The system standardises nomenclature for both research and clinical communication across gynaecological practice internationally.<br><br>Painful menstruation (A) is classified separately as primary or secondary dysmenorrhoea. Pelvic infection (B) and ovarian cysts (C) are not directly categorised by PALM-COEIN.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'Which condition in the PALM classification represents structural causes of abnormal uterine bleeding?',o:['Iatrogenic causes','Ovulatory dysfunction','Endometrial causes','Adenomyosis'],a:3,
e:`Adenomyosis is the presence of endometrial glands and stroma within the myometrium, causing HMB, dysmenorrhoea and a symmetrically enlarged boggy uterus. It falls under the A (Adenomyosis) structural category in the PALM-COEIN system as embedded endometrial tissue within the uterine wall constitutes identifiable structural pathology.<br><br>MRI is the most accurate non-invasive diagnostic tool, showing junctional zone thickness above 12 mm. Treatment options include the levonorgestrel IUS, GnRH agonists for temporary suppression, and hysterectomy providing definitive cure and most effective treatment for severe symptomatic adenomyosis.<br><br>Hypothyroidism (A), coagulopathy (B) and ovulatory dysfunction (C) belong to the non-structural COEIN categories. Adenomyosis is explicitly a structural pathology category in the PALM component.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'Ovulatory dysfunction causing abnormal bleeding belongs to which PALM-COEIN category?',o:['Structural causes','Non-structural causes','Infectious causes','Malignant causes'],a:1,
e:`Ovulatory dysfunction (AUB-O) is a non-structural cause classified under the COEIN component of PALM-COEIN, encompassing all abnormal uterine bleeding from disruption of the hormonal regulation of the menstrual cycle without identifiable structural uterine pathology. It includes bleeding from anovulation, oligoovulation and luteal phase deficiency.<br><br>AUB-O is most common at the extremes of reproductive life: in adolescence from HPO axis immaturity and in perimenopause from declining follicular reserve. Causes include PCOS, hyperprolactinaemia, thyroid disease, weight extremes and functional hypothalamic disorders, all affecting the GnRH-FSH-LH axis.<br><br>The COEIN non-structural components are Coagulopathy, Ovulatory dysfunction, Endometrial, Iatrogenic and Not otherwise classified. Polyp (B) and Malignancy (C) are structural PALM categories. Structural causes (D) are the PALM component, not COEIN.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'Endometrial polyps commonly present with:',o:['Amenorrhea','Dysmenorrhea only','Intermenstrual bleeding','Delayed puberty'],a:2,
e:`Endometrial polyps are benign focal overgrowths of endometrial glands and stroma projecting into the uterine cavity, most commonly presenting with IMB, post-coital bleeding or irregular menstrual patterns. They account for approximately 25% of IMB cases and are identified by transvaginal ultrasound or saline infusion sonography.<br><br>Polyps are oestrogen-sensitive and more common in perimenopausal women and tamoxifen users. Most are benign but approximately 1-2% undergo malignant transformation, higher in postmenopausal women. Hysteroscopic polypectomy is treatment of choice, providing both diagnosis and cure with histological confirmation.<br><br>Cyclical pain (A) is associated with dysmenorrhoea and endometriosis. Vaginal discharge only (B) suggests infection or cervical pathology. Amenorrhoea (C) indicates ovulatory failure or outflow obstruction rather than polyp presentation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 45-year-old woman presents with excessive menstrual bleeding lasting more than 8 days each cycle. Which menstrual disorder is most likely?',o:['Postmenopausal bleeding','Intermenstrual bleeding','Postcoital bleeding','Heavy menstrual bleeding'],a:3,
e:`HMB in the context of a demonstrated uterine fibroid on ultrasound is classified as AUB-L (Leiomyoma) in PALM-COEIN. Intramural fibroids distort uterine contractility and increase endometrial surface area; combined with local prostaglandin and growth factor effects, they produce heavy and prolonged menstrual bleeding that is difficult to manage medically when significant.<br><br>Management depends on fibroid size, location, symptoms and fertility wishes. A 5 cm intramural fibroid with HMB in a 45-year-old warrants medical therapy (tranexamic acid, NSAIDs, levonorgestrel IUS if cavity allows), uterine artery embolisation or myomectomy. Hysterectomy is definitive but invasive in a 45-year-old.<br><br>Dysfunctional uterine bleeding (A) implies no structural pathology found. Secondary dysmenorrhoea (B) implies painful periods. Endometrial cancer (C) requires tissue sampling to exclude in a 45-year-old with heavy bleeding.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 52-year-old woman presents with vaginal bleeding two years after menopause. What is the most important diagnosis that must be excluded?',o:['PCOS','Cervical ectropion','Endometrial carcinoma','Ovarian cyst'],a:2,
e:`PMB at 52 years, two years after menopause, is a red flag symptom for endometrial carcinoma, accounting for approximately 10% of PMB cases. Investigation begins with transvaginal ultrasound: endometrial thickness above 4 mm requires tissue sampling by pipelle biopsy or hysteroscopy with directed biopsy to obtain histology.<br><br>Obesity, nulliparity, diabetes, late menopause and tamoxifen use increase endometrial carcinoma risk. Even apparently trivial post-menopausal bleeding must be investigated urgently. Early-stage endometrial carcinoma treated by hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy has 5-year survival exceeding 90%.<br><br>Vaginal atrophy (A) and cervical polyp (B) are common benign PMB causes but must not be assumed without excluding carcinoma. Uterine fibroids (C) typically regress after menopause and rarely cause PMB.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A woman reports spotting between her normal menstrual periods. Which term best describes this symptom?',o:['Amenorrhea','Menorrhagia','Dysmenorrhea','Intermenstrual bleeding'],a:3,
e:`Spotting between normal menstrual periods at unpredictable times is IMB, distinct from menorrhagia (heavy flow within the period) and postmenopausal bleeding (any bleeding after 12 months without periods). IMB must be investigated to exclude endometrial or cervical pathology regardless of bleeding volume.<br><br>In a reproductive-age woman, common causes include endometrial or cervical polyps, cervical ectropion, chlamydial cervicitis, hormonal contraceptive breakthrough bleeding and mid-cycle ovulatory spotting from the oestradiol fluctuation around ovulation. Investigation begins with speculum examination and sexual health screening if clinically indicated.<br><br>Menorrhagia (A) is excessive bleeding within the normal period window. Postmenopausal bleeding (B) requires 12 months of amenorrhoea first. Dysmenorrhoea (C) is painful menstruation, not intermenstrual spotting between cycles.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 35-year-old woman complains of vaginal bleeding after sexual intercourse. Which condition is most likely responsible?',o:['Endometriosis','Ovarian cyst','Cervical pathology','Dysmenorrhea'],a:2,
e:`Post-coital bleeding in a 35-year-old most commonly originates from the cervix: cervical ectropion, cervical polyp, cervicitis or cervical intraepithelial neoplasia are the most frequent benign causes. However, cervical carcinoma must be excluded by speculum examination, cervical smear and colposcopy if indicated.<br><br>Investigation requires speculum examination to visualise the cervix, endocervical swab for sexually transmitted infections, and cervical smear if overdue. Persistent PCB after treatment of identified benign causes requires urgent colposcopy regardless of smear result, particularly in older women or those with risk factors.<br><br>Ovulatory dysfunction (A) and coagulation disorders (B) cause abnormal uterine bleeding without the specific post-coital timing. Endometrial cancer (C) can present with IMB or PMB but PCB in a 35-year-old most directly implicates cervical pathology.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 50-year-old woman with obesity presents with postmenopausal bleeding. Which malignancy risk is increased in this patient?',o:['Breast carcinoma','Ovarian carcinoma','Cervical carcinoma','Endometrial carcinoma'],a:3,
e:`Obesity is a major risk factor for endometrial carcinoma through peripheral aromatisation of androgens to oestrogens in adipose tissue, creating chronic unopposed oestrogen stimulation of the endometrium. A 50-year-old obese woman with PMB has both age and obesity as risk factors, making urgent investigation by transvaginal ultrasound and endometrial biopsy mandatory.<br><br>Women with BMI above 30 kg/m2 have approximately 3-fold increased endometrial carcinoma risk. Any PMB, however light, must trigger immediate investigation. Endometrial thickness above 4 mm on transvaginal ultrasound requires tissue sampling; thickness below 4 mm in non-HRT users has negative predictive value above 99%.<br><br>Vaginal atrophy (A), ovarian cyst (B) and cervical polyp (C) may cause PMB but endometrial carcinoma must be excluded before attributing bleeding to these benign diagnoses in a high-risk woman.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 32-year-old woman with uterine fibroids presents with prolonged heavy menstrual bleeding and anemia. Which condition best describes her bleeding pattern?',o:['Postcoital bleeding','Intermenstrual bleeding','Heavy menstrual bleeding','Postmenopausal bleeding'],a:2,
e:`Prolonged heavy periods in the context of confirmed uterine fibroids represent AUB-L (Leiomyoma), a structural cause of HMB in the PALM-COEIN classification. Fibroids increase endometrial surface area, impair uterine contractility and haemostasis, and create venous congestion that together produce excessive and prolonged menstrual blood loss.<br><br>A 32-year-old with fibroids and HMB who may wish to preserve fertility is best managed with uterus-sparing options: tranexamic acid and NSAIDs for medical management, hysteroscopic myomectomy for submucous fibroids, uterine artery embolisation or laparoscopic myomectomy for intramural fibroids.<br><br>Oligomenorrhoea (A) is infrequent periods. Dysmenorrhoea (B) is painful periods. Polymenorrhoea (C) is frequent short-interval cycles. None describe the heavy prolonged pattern caused by uterine fibroids.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 28-year-old woman complains of bleeding between cycles due to an endometrial polyp. Which type of bleeding is most characteristic?',o:['Dysmenorrhea','Postcoital bleeding','Postmenopausal bleeding','Intermenstrual bleeding'],a:3,
e:`Bleeding between cycles due to an endometrial polyp is IMB, classified as AUB-P (Polyp) in the PALM-COEIN system. Polyps protrude into the uterine cavity and, from their vulnerable vascular surface, produce unpredictable bleeding between periods or contact bleeding during uterine activity.<br><br>Hysteroscopy with polypectomy is both diagnostic and curative for endometrial polyps. Saline infusion sonography identifies polyps as echogenic intracavitary lesions with feeding vessels on Doppler. Histological examination of resected polyp tissue is essential to exclude the small risk of malignant transformation.<br><br>Post-coital bleeding (A) is triggered by sexual intercourse. Amenorrhoea (B) is absent periods. Menorrhagia (C) is heavy flow within the period window, not spotting between periods.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A patient presents with vaginal bleeding after sexual intercourse. Speculum examination reveals cervical erosion. Which bleeding disorder does this represent?',o:['Intermenstrual bleeding','Heavy menstrual bleeding','Postcoital bleeding','Postmenopausal bleeding'],a:2,
e:`Painless vaginal bleeding immediately after sexual intercourse is by definition post-coital bleeding (PCB), requiring systematic investigation for cervical pathology. The most common benign causes are cervical ectropion, cervical polyp and cervicitis; cervical carcinoma is the most important diagnosis to exclude.<br><br>Investigation requires speculum examination of the cervix, cervical smear if overdue, STI screen and colposcopy if the cervix appears abnormal or PCB persists after treating identified benign causes. The frequency and quantity of PCB does not reliably distinguish benign from malignant causes, so investigation is indicated regardless of bleeding severity.<br><br>Menorrhagia (A) is excessive menstrual bleeding within the period window. Amenorrhoea (B) is absent periods. Polymenorrhoea (C) is frequent cycles. None are triggered specifically by the act of sexual intercourse.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 60-year-old woman presents with vaginal bleeding five years after menopause. Which diagnostic investigation is most important initially?',o:['Serum prolactin','Pap smear only','Urine pregnancy test','Endometrial biopsy'],a:3,
e:`In a 60-year-old with PMB, endometrial biopsy (pipelle or hysteroscopy with directed biopsy) is the primary investigation to exclude endometrial carcinoma, guided by transvaginal ultrasound measurement of endometrial thickness. An endometrial thickness above 4 mm in a postmenopausal woman not on HRT requires tissue sampling.<br><br>A 60-year-old with bleeding five years after menopause has high prior probability of significant pathology. If ultrasound shows endometrial thickness below 4 mm, the negative predictive value for carcinoma exceeds 99%, potentially avoiding biopsy if bleeding resolves. Persistent bleeding despite thin endometrium still warrants further investigation.<br><br>Pap smear (B) screens for cervical carcinoma but does not assess the endometrium adequately. Serum FSH (C) confirms menopausal status but does not investigate the bleeding source. Ovarian ultrasound (D) may be included but endometrial biopsy addresses the priority diagnosis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A gynecologist explains that abnormal uterine bleeding can arise from structural and non-structural causes as categorized by the PALM-COEIN system. Which condition belongs to the structural "PALM" group?',o:['Coagulopathy','Ovulatory dysfunction','Endometrial polyp','Iatrogenic causes'],a:2,
e:`Endometrial polyps are benign focal overgrowths of endometrial glands and stroma projecting into the uterine cavity, the most common benign endometrial growth causing abnormal uterine bleeding. They are identified in approximately 25% of women investigated for IMB and up to 10% of those with HMB, and are the most frequently encountered structural endometrial pathology.<br><br>Polyps develop from localised endometrial response to oestrogen stimulation and are more common in perimenopausal women, those with obesity and tamoxifen users. Diagnosis uses transvaginal ultrasound with or without saline infusion, or hysteroscopy. Hysteroscopic polypectomy is curative and enables histological confirmation.<br><br>Adenomyosis (B) is endometrium within the myometrium. Endometrial hyperplasia (C) is diffuse glandular overgrowth without discrete polyp formation. Leiomyoma (D) is myometrial smooth muscle tumour. All cause AUB but polyp is the specific benign endometrial growth described.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 38-year-old woman presents with prolonged heavy menstrual bleeding associated with adenomyosis. Which category of PALM-COEIN classification does this condition belong to?',o:['Iatrogenic causes','Non-structural causes','Endocrine causes','Structural causes'],a:3,
e:`Adenomyosis is a structural cause of AUB classified under the A (Adenomyosis) category of the PALM structural component of PALM-COEIN. Endometrial glands and stroma within the myometrium disrupt normal uterine contractility and haemostasis mechanisms, producing HMB, dysmenorrhoea and the characteristic symmetrically enlarged boggy uterus.<br><br>MRI showing junctional zone thickness above 12 mm is the most accurate non-invasive diagnostic tool. The levonorgestrel IUS is first-line medical treatment, reducing menstrual loss by 70-90%. Hysterectomy provides definitive cure and the most effective treatment option for severe adenomyosis where fertility is no longer desired.<br><br>Non-structural causes (A), coagulation disorders (B) and ovulatory dysfunction (C) all belong to the COEIN non-structural component. Adenomyosis is explicitly a structural pathology category in the PALM component of the classification.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A patient reports spotting after intercourse and examination reveals suspicious cervical lesion. Which condition must be ruled out first?',o:['Fibroid uterus','Endometrial polyp','Cervical cancer','PCOS'],a:2,
e:`A friable cervix that bleeds on contact with the speculum or spatula, combined with PCB, is highly suspicious for cervical carcinoma until proven otherwise. A friable cervix suggests abnormal tumour vasculature or necrotic tumour tissue breaking down on contact, characteristic of advanced cervical intraepithelial neoplasia or invasive cervical carcinoma.<br><br>Urgent colposcopy with biopsy of abnormal-appearing areas is required. Cervical carcinoma is staged clinically by FIGO staging, and treatment depends on stage from loop excision for CIN to radical hysterectomy or chemoradiation for invasive carcinoma. HPV vaccination has significantly reduced CIN and cervical carcinoma incidence in vaccinated cohorts.<br><br>Endometrial polyp (A), uterine fibroid (B) and ovarian cyst (C) do not produce a friable cervix. The combination of PCB with a friable cervix specifically implicates cervical pathology requiring colposcopy.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A woman presents with abnormal uterine bleeding due to thyroid dysfunction affecting ovulation. Which category of PALM-COEIN classification does this belong to?',o:['Polyp','Structural causes','Malignancy','Ovulatory dysfunction'],a:3,
e:`Thyroid dysfunction causes abnormal uterine bleeding through disruption of the reproductive hormonal axis, classified as AUB-O (Ovulatory dysfunction) in the COEIN non-structural component of PALM-COEIN. Hypothyroidism causes elevated TRH, stimulating prolactin and suppressing GnRH, causing anovulatory irregular bleeding. It also reduces coagulation factors and increases oestrogen bioavailability.<br><br>Thyroid function testing is mandatory in all women presenting with AUB, particularly heavy or irregular periods, as correcting thyroid disease often resolves the menstrual abnormality without additional gynaecological intervention. TSH is the most sensitive screening test for both hypothyroidism and hyperthyroidism.<br><br>Leiomyoma (A) and adenomyosis (C) are structural PALM categories. Structural causes (B) is the overall PALM component. Thyroid dysfunction belongs to the COEIN non-structural component under ovulatory dysfunction.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 48-year-old woman presents with heavy menstrual bleeding and ultrasound reveals submucosal fibroids. Which type of abnormal uterine bleeding is most likely?',o:['Postcoital bleeding','Intermenstrual bleeding','Heavy menstrual bleeding due to structural cause','Postmenopausal bleeding'],a:2,
e:`HMB in a 48-year-old with confirmed multiple fibroids on ultrasound is AUB-L (Leiomyoma), a structural cause in the PALM-COEIN classification. Multiple fibroids compound haemostatic impairment, cavity distortion and contractility disruption, driving significant HMB that is often difficult to manage medically with multiple lesions.<br><br>At 48 with approaching perimenopause and likely completed family, management options include the levonorgestrel IUS if cavity allows, uterine artery embolisation and hysterectomy. GnRH agonist therapy reduces fibroid volume and bleeding preoperatively but is not suitable for long-term use due to bone density effects.<br><br>Dysfunctional uterine bleeding (A) implies no structural pathology. Secondary dysmenorrhoea (B) is painful periods. Ovulatory dysfunction (C) is a non-structural COEIN category. All differ from the structural AUB-L fibroid category.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 55-year-old postmenopausal woman presents with vaginal bleeding. The clinician explains that any bleeding after menopause should be investigated because it may indicate malignancy. Which malignancy is most commonly associated with postmenopausal bleeding?',o:['Tubal carcinoma','Ovarian carcinoma','Vaginal carcinoma','Endometrial carcinoma'],a:3,
e:`An 8 mm endometrial thickness in a postmenopausal woman not on HRT is significantly above the 4 mm investigation threshold, substantially increasing the probability of endometrial carcinoma or hyperplasia. Immediate endometrial biopsy by pipelle sampling or hysteroscopy with directed biopsy is mandatory and urgent.<br><br>Endometrial thickness increases with obesity from peripheral aromatisation and with exogenous oestrogen from HRT. A thickened endometrium with PMB has approximately 20% prevalence of carcinoma, compared with approximately 1-2% when thickness is below 4 mm. Prompt diagnosis determines prognosis, which is excellent for early-stage disease.<br><br>Vaginal infection (A) and cervical polyp (B) are benign PMB causes that do not produce significant endometrial thickening. Ovarian failure (C) is the basis of menopause and does not explain the PMB or thickened endometrium found in this patient.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 33-year-old woman presents with irregular spotting between cycles. Ultrasound reveals an endometrial polyp. Which bleeding pattern does this most commonly cause?',o:['Postmenopausal bleeding','Postcoital bleeding','Intermenstrual bleeding','Dysmenorrhea'],a:2,
e:`Irregular spotting between cycles from a cervical ectropion is IMB. Cervical ectropion is the presence of columnar endocervical epithelium on the visible ectocervix, creating a red velvety area prone to contact bleeding and spotting from the fragile glandular tissue, producing the characteristic pattern of bleeding between periods or post-coital.<br><br>Ectropion is physiological in adolescents and during pregnancy and OCP use from oestrogen stimulation causing eversion of the transformation zone. It is diagnosed on speculum examination. Symptomatic ectropion causing persistent IMB or PCB is treated by cold coagulation or cryotherapy after excluding CIN by colposcopy.<br><br>Menorrhagia (A) is excessive regular menstrual bleeding. Postmenopausal bleeding (B) requires established menopause. Amenorrhoea (C) is absent periods. None describe the between-period pattern from a cervical ectropion.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A patient presents with heavy menstrual bleeding due to coagulation disorder. Which category of PALM-COEIN classification does this belong to?',o:['Leiomyoma','Polyp','Adenomyosis','Coagulopathy'],a:3,
e:`Coagulopathy (AUB-C) is a COEIN non-structural category in PALM-COEIN encompassing hereditary and acquired bleeding disorders that impair haemostatic plug formation at the endometrial spiral artery level. Von Willebrand disease is the most common inherited coagulopathy causing HMB, present in approximately 13% of women with HMB presenting to gynaecology.<br><br>Investigation includes full coagulation screen, von Willebrand antigen, activity and factor VIII levels, and platelet function analysis. Treatment involves desmopressin or von Willebrand factor concentrate for acute HMB, tranexamic acid for general HMB management, and avoidance of NSAIDs that further impair platelet function.<br><br>Leiomyoma (A), malignancy (B) and endometrial (C) categories are separate structural or functional PALM-COEIN categories. Coagulopathy is its own dedicated COEIN non-structural category distinct from all others.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A woman complains of vaginal bleeding immediately after intercourse. Speculum examination shows cervical inflammation. Which diagnosis best explains this symptom?',o:['Heavy menstrual bleeding','Intermenstrual bleeding','Postcoital bleeding','Postmenopausal bleeding'],a:2,
e:`Vaginal bleeding triggered immediately by sexual intercourse is by definition post-coital bleeding (PCB), a clinically distinct symptom from menstrual abnormalities. PCB arising from the cervix is caused by cervical ectropion, polyps, cervicitis or carcinoma; bleeding from the vagina may arise from vaginal atrophy in postmenopausal women or vaginal trauma.<br><br>All PCB requires systematic investigation: speculum examination, cervical smear if overdue, STI screen and colposcopy if the cervix appears abnormal. The severity and frequency of PCB does not reliably distinguish benign from malignant causes, so investigation is indicated regardless of bleeding amount or apparent frequency.<br><br>Menorrhagia (A) is excessive menstrual bleeding at expected intervals. Amenorrhoea (B) is absent periods. Polymenorrhoea (C) is frequent cycles. None are defined by the specific trigger of sexual intercourse.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 29-year-old woman with ovulatory dysfunction experiences irregular heavy bleeding. Which hormonal disturbance most likely contributes to this condition?',o:['Increased oxytocin release','Excess progesterone secretion','Increased prolactin secretion','Unopposed estrogen stimulation of endometrium'],a:3,
e:`Ovulatory dysfunction causes anovulatory cycles in which oestradiol continues to stimulate endometrial proliferation without the secretory transformation and withdrawal pattern of a normal ovulatory cycle. Without progesterone from a corpus luteum, the chronically proliferating endometrium becomes unstable and sheds irregularly, producing unpredictable, sometimes heavy bleeding.<br><br>This pattern of chronic unopposed oestrogen produces a hyperplastic, fragile endometrium that breaks down focally rather than shedding uniformly, causing irregular bleeding of variable duration. Long-term anovulatory cycles increase endometrial hyperplasia and carcinoma risk, managed with cyclical progestogens or combined oral contraceptives.<br><br>Cervical pathology (A), structural fibroid (B) and coagulation deficiency (C) produce different AUB patterns. Anovulation specifically creates the unopposed oestrogen endometrial mechanism producing irregular unpredictable heavy bleeding.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A gynecologist explains that abnormal uterine bleeding due to ovulatory dysfunction often leads to prolonged estrogen exposure without progesterone opposition, resulting in irregular shedding of endometrium. Which type of bleeding pattern is most commonly seen in this condition?',o:['Only postcoital bleeding','Complete amenorrhea','Irregular heavy bleeding','Only postmenopausal bleeding'],a:2,
e:`Ovulatory dysfunction-related AUB produces irregular, unpredictable and often heavy bleeding because anovulatory cycles create variable oestrogen exposure without the progesterone-driven secretory transformation and orderly withdrawal of normal menstrual cycles. The endometrium may proliferate for weeks before unstable shedding produces irregular heavy bleeding of variable amount.<br><br>The bleeding pattern is typically unpredictable in timing and amount, contrasting with the regular predictable heavy flow of menorrhagia from structural causes. Ovulatory dysfunction is the most common AUB cause at the extremes of reproductive life and requires investigation for PCOS, hyperprolactinaemia, thyroid disease and hypothalamic amenorrhoea.<br><br>Cyclical heavy bleeding (A) at regular intervals suggests structural causes like fibroids. Post-coital bleeding (B) suggests cervical pathology. Postmenopausal bleeding (C) requires established amenorrhoea for 12 months before menstruation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'Female fertility depends primarily on which physiological process occurring in the ovary?',o:['Lactation','Menstruation','Implantation','Ovulation'],a:3,
e:`Ovulation is the central monthly physiological event on which female fertility depends: the LH surge at mid-cycle drives follicular rupture and release of the cumulus-oocyte complex, providing the egg available for fertilisation. Without ovulation there is no oocyte and conception cannot occur regardless of all other reproductive tract factors.<br><br>Ovulation confirmation by mid-luteal serum progesterone above 30 nmol/L is the first step in infertility investigation. Anovulation is the most common and most treatable cause of female infertility, with ovulation induction by clomifene, letrozole or gonadotropins restoring fertility in the majority of anovulatory women.<br><br>Menstruation (A) confirms preceding ovulation but does not itself enable fertility. Implantation (B) and fertilisation (C) depend on ovulation having occurred. Ovulation is the rate-limiting monthly event that makes all subsequent fertility-related processes possible.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'The most fertile period in the menstrual cycle occurs:',o:['Immediately after menstruation','Around the time of ovulation','During the luteal phase','Just before menstruation'],a:1,
e:`The most fertile period is the peri-ovulatory window, extending from approximately 5 days before to 1 day after ovulation. Spermatozoa survive up to 5 days in fertile cervical mucus and the oocyte is viable for approximately 12-24 hours post-ovulation, creating this 6-day fertile window with peak fertility on the day before and day of ovulation.<br><br>Identifying the fertile window uses urinary LH detection (peak LH 24-48 hours before ovulation), cervical mucus observation (thin, stretchy Spinnbarkeit indicating oestradiol peak), basal body temperature charting and transvaginal ultrasound follicle monitoring in clinical fertility assessment settings.<br><br>During menstruation (A), the oocyte for that cycle has not yet developed. After menstruation only (B) is too imprecise. Late luteal phase (C) is after ovulation and corpus luteum regression, well beyond the end of the fertile window.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'The ovum remains viable for fertilization for approximately:',o:['6 hours','72 hours','48 hours','12-24 hours'],a:3,
e:`The oocyte released at ovulation remains capable of fertilisation for approximately 12-24 hours. After this window, without sperm penetration the egg undergoes zona hardening and loses fertilisation capacity. The short oocyte viability period compared with sperm viability of up to 5 days means timing intercourse in the days before ovulation is as important as on the day of ovulation itself.<br><br>In IVF, oocytes are fertilised within hours of retrieval to maximise fertilisation rates. Mature metaphase II oocytes retrieved 34-36 hours after hCG trigger have optimal fertilisation potential, which declines if insemination is delayed beyond 18-20 hours post-retrieval in conventional IVF insemination protocols.<br><br>6 hours (A) underestimates oocyte viability. 12 hours (B) is at the lower range of the viability window. 5 days (C) is the duration of sperm viability in fertile cervical mucus, not oocyte viability duration.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'Spermatozoa can remain viable in the female reproductive tract for approximately:',o:['12 hours','24 hours','3-5 days','10 days'],a:2,
e:`Spermatozoa can survive in the female reproductive tract for 3-5 days in fertile peri-ovulatory cervical mucus. This extended survival is enabled by the thin, alkaline, high-water-content mucus secreted under oestradiol stimulation around ovulation, which provides nutrition, neutralises the acidic vaginal environment and creates aligned mucin fibre channels facilitating sperm migration.<br><br>After ovulation, progesterone from the corpus luteum converts cervical mucus to thick, hostile, low-water-content mucus that impedes sperm penetration, limiting the fertile window to approximately 6 days based on sperm survival capacity. Understanding sperm survival is essential for fertility awareness and contraception counselling.<br><br>12 hours (A) and 24 hours (B) underestimate sperm survival in fertile mucus. 7 days (D) overestimates: most sperm lose motility and fertilising capacity within 5 days even in the most favourable fertile cervical mucus conditions.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'The fertile window of the menstrual cycle is usually:',o:['2 days before ovulation only','5 days before and 1 day after ovulation','During menstruation','Entire luteal phase'],a:1,
e:`The fertile window spans the 6 days ending on ovulation day: 5 days before ovulation (maximum sperm survival duration in fertile mucus) plus 1 day after (oocyte viability limit of 12-24 hours, approximately 1 day in practical terms). Conception probability is highest in the 2 days immediately before and on the day of ovulation.<br><br>The Lactational Amenorrhoea Method and fertility awareness-based contraceptive methods exploit this narrow window. Fertility awareness requires daily tracking of cervical mucus consistency, basal body temperature and calendar calculations to identify and avoid or target the fertile window for contraception or conception purposes respectively.<br><br>Day 1-5 (A) is the menstrual phase, typically infertile. 10 days (B) overestimates the fertile window significantly. 7 days after ovulation (C) is the luteal phase, beyond oocyte viability, representing an infertile period in the cycle.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'Which hormone surge triggers ovulation during the menstrual cycle?',o:['FSH','Progesterone','Prolactin','LH'],a:3,
e:`The LH surge, triggered by sustained oestradiol positive feedback exceeding 200 pg/mL for 50 hours, activates follicular wall proteolytic enzymes, prostaglandins and VEGF that cause stigma formation and follicular rupture approximately 36-40 hours after surge onset. The cumulus-oocyte complex is released into the peritoneal cavity adjacent to the fallopian tube fimbria.<br><br>The LH surge is detectable in urine 24-48 hours before ovulation, forming the basis of ovulation predictor kits. Exogenous hCG which binds LH receptors with equal affinity is used to trigger ovulation in ovulation induction and IVF protocols at precisely timed intervals before intercourse or egg collection.<br><br>FSH (A) has a modest co-surge at mid-cycle but does not trigger ovulation. Prolactin (B) suppresses GnRH and inhibits the ovulatory surge. Progesterone (C) rises after ovulation from the corpus luteum rather than triggering it.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'The most accurate physiological indicator of ovulation is:',o:['Decrease in progesterone','Increase in estrogen','LH surge','Menstrual bleeding'],a:2,
e:`The mid-cycle LH surge is the most accurate physiological indicator of impending ovulation, occurring 24-48 hours before follicular rupture. Urinary LH detection kits detect the surge 24-48 hours before ovulation, giving advance notice for timed intercourse or insemination. The LH surge is the direct biological trigger of ovulation rather than a retrospective consequence.<br><br>Mid-luteal serum progesterone above 30 nmol/L confirms that ovulation has occurred retrospectively, while the LH surge predicts it prospectively. For clinical timing of intrauterine insemination, intercourse or egg retrieval in IVF, the LH surge provides the most actionable prospective ovulation indicator available without invasive monitoring.<br><br>FSH elevation (B) occurs at cycle start to recruit follicles, not as an ovulation indicator. Progesterone rise (C) confirms ovulation retrospectively. Oestrogen peak (D) occurs slightly before the LH surge and triggers it, making LH the more direct indicator of imminent ovulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'Which hormone is responsible for preparing the endometrium for implantation?',o:['Estrogen','Oxytocin','Prolactin','Progesterone'],a:3,
e:`Progesterone from the corpus luteum transforms the oestrogen-primed proliferative endometrium into a secretory, receptive state: it drives glandular secretion of glycogen-rich fluid, stromal predecidualisation, endometrial pinopode development at the implantation window around days 20-24, and leukemia inhibitory factor production facilitating blastocyst attachment.<br><br>Adequate progesterone is essential for successful implantation: luteal phase deficiency with sub-optimal progesterone reduces endometrial receptivity. Vaginal micronised progesterone is standard luteal support in all IVF cycles, and is used empirically in recurrent implantation failure and recurrent early pregnancy loss.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) drives the proliferative phase but not the secretory transformation enabling implantation. FSH (B) acts on ovarian granulosa cells with no direct endometrial implantation role. Oxytocin (C) stimulates uterine contractions, not endometrial receptivity for implantation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'Implantation of the fertilized ovum normally occurs in the:',o:['Cervix','Fallopian tube','Endometrium of uterus','Ovary'],a:2,
e:`The fertilised ovum normally implants in the endometrium of the uterine corpus, occurring 6-10 days after fertilisation when the blastocyst reaches the receptive endometrium during the implantation window. The trophoblast erodes the decidualised stroma and anchors the conceptus to the uterine wall to establish the placenta.<br><br>Abnormal implantation sites are called ectopic pregnancies: fallopian tube is the site in 95% of ectopic pregnancies, followed by ovary, cervix and abdominal cavity. Ectopic pregnancy is a life-threatening emergency detected by rising hCG without intrauterine pregnancy on ultrasound.<br><br>Ovary (A), cervical canal (B) and fallopian tube (C) are ectopic implantation sites associated with pathological pregnancies. Normal physiological implantation invariably occurs in the endometrium of the uterine body.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'Fertilization usually occurs in which part of the fallopian tube?',o:['Isthmus','Ampulla','Infundibulum','Interstitial part'],a:1,
e:`Fertilisation normally occurs in the ampullary portion of the fallopian tube, the widest and longest segment, where the cumulus-oocyte complex from the ruptured follicle is transported by fimbriae and peristaltic movements. The ampulla provides the optimum microenvironment for capacitated sperm to penetrate the zona pellucida and fertilise the oocyte within 12-24 hours of ovulation.<br><br>The fertilised zygote then begins cleavage divisions while being transported distally by tubal cilia and peristalsis over approximately 4-5 days, reaching the uterine cavity at the morula or early blastocyst stage ready for implantation. Tubal blockage at any point prevents this transport and causes infertility.<br><br>Fimbriated end (A) picks up the oocyte from the peritoneal cavity but is not the fertilisation site. Isthmus (C) is too narrow and is where sperm capacitation and selection occur. Cornua (D) is the uterine opening of the tube, not the fertilisation site.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A couple has been trying to conceive for 1 year without success. The woman has regular menstrual cycles but does not show mid-cycle LH surge. Which condition is most likely responsible?',o:['Uterine fibroid','Tubal blockage','Cervical stenosis','Anovulation'],a:3,
e:`Cycles of 45-60 days indicate severe oligomenorrhoea consistent with chronic anovulation. Without regular ovulation, there is no oocyte for fertilisation, making anovulation the overwhelmingly likely cause of infertility in this presentation. The infrequent, irregular cycles confirm disrupted HPG axis function with inconsistent LH surges.<br><br>The most common cause of anovulation-related infertility is PCOS, affecting approximately 80% of anovulatory infertile women. Investigation includes FSH, LH, oestradiol, prolactin, TSH and pelvic ultrasound. Treatment begins with weight loss if obese, then ovulation induction with clomifene or letrozole as first-line agents.<br><br>Tubal blockage (B), uterine polyp (C) and cervical stenosis (D) cause infertility with regular ovulatory cycles, whereas this woman's irregular cycle pattern specifically points to an ovulatory factor rather than anatomical impediment.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 28-year-old woman monitoring fertility observes thin, stretchy cervical mucus around mid-cycle. Which hormone is responsible for this change?',o:['Oxytocin','Estrogen','Prolactin','Progesterone'],a:1,
e:`Oestradiol at the pre-ovulatory peak stimulates cervical crypts to produce abundant, thin, clear, highly elastic mucus with 95-98% water content, low cellularity and high Spinnbarkeit stretching 10 cm without breaking. This fertile mucus facilitates sperm survival, migration and capacitation, signalling the approaching fertile window.<br><br>The mucus transition from thick and scanty (progesterone-dominant luteal phase) to thin and stretchy (oestradiol-dominant peri-ovulatory) and back to thick again provides the basis for the Billings ovulation method, fertility awareness and post-coital testing of sperm-mucus interaction in infertility evaluation.<br><br>Progesterone (A) produces the opposite thick, scanty mucus. Prolactin (B) and oxytocin (C) have no direct role in regulating the cyclical changes in cervical mucus consistency across the menstrual cycle phases.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A patient undergoing infertility evaluation shows elevated basal body temperature after ovulation. Which hormone causes this thermogenic effect?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Prolactin','LH'],a:0,
e:`A sustained basal body temperature rise of 0.2-0.5 degrees C persisting for 12-14 days after ovulation indicates the thermogenic effect of corpus luteum progesterone via hypothalamic thermoreceptors. The biphasic temperature chart pattern, with lower follicular phase temperature and elevated luteal phase temperature for 12-14 days, confirms ovulation occurred and adequate corpus luteum function.<br><br>A temperature rise persisting beyond 14 days suggests early pregnancy from hCG maintaining corpus luteum progesterone production. Luteal phase temperature elevation below 10-12 days suggests corpus luteum deficiency. Mid-luteal serum progesterone above 30 nmol/L provides more objective confirmation of ovulation than temperature charting alone.<br><br>Anovulation (A) would produce a monophasic temperature chart without the sustained biphasic rise. Endometrial pathology (B) and tubal blockage (C) do not affect basal body temperature patterns in any characteristic way.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A woman undergoing fertility treatment receives clomiphene citrate. The drug works by:',o:['Directly stimulating ovaries','Providing exogenous FSH','Increasing prolactin secretion','Blocking estrogen receptors in hypothalamus'],a:3,
e:`Clomifene citrate is a selective oestrogen receptor modulator that blocks oestrogen receptors in the hypothalamus, preventing oestradiol negative feedback from suppressing GnRH pulsatility. The hypothalamus perceives a falsely low oestrogen state, increases GnRH pulse frequency and amplitude, driving pituitary FSH and LH above normal basal levels to stimulate follicular development in anovulatory women.<br><br>Clomifene achieves ovulation in approximately 75-80% of anovulatory women with conception rates of approximately 40-50% over 6 cycles. Letrozole, an aromatase inhibitor that also increases FSH by reducing oestradiol negative feedback, is increasingly preferred in PCOS as it has lower multiple pregnancy risk and avoids anti-oestrogenic effects on cervical mucus.<br><br>Clomifene does not directly stimulate ovaries (A), provide exogenous FSH (B) or increase prolactin (C). It acts centrally at the hypothalamic oestrogen receptor level to release GnRH pulsatility from negative feedback suppression.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A patient with infertility is diagnosed with bilateral tubal blockage. Which reproductive process is most directly affected?',o:['Fertilization','Menstruation','Ovulation','Implantation'],a:0,
e:`Bilateral tubal blockage prevents fertilisation by creating an impenetrable barrier between sperm travelling from the uterine cavity and the oocyte released from the ovary into the peritoneal space adjacent to the fimbria. Without a patent fallopian tube, the cumulus-oocyte complex and sperm cannot meet in the ampullary fertilisation site.<br><br>Tubal factor infertility accounts for approximately 25-35% of female infertility cases, caused by pelvic inflammatory disease, endometriosis, previous pelvic surgery or congenital anomaly. Investigation uses hysterosalpingography or laparoscopy with dye. IVF is preferred over tubal surgery for bilateral blockage or significant tubal damage.<br><br>Implantation (A) can occur once fertilisation happens, but tubal blockage prevents fertilisation reaching that stage. Follicular development (B) and ovulation (C) are intact in tubal factor infertility; only the transport and fertilisation step is blocked by the bilateral tubal obstruction.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A woman presents with infertility due to luteal phase defect with inadequate progesterone secretion. Which process is most affected?',o:['Fertilization','Ovulation','Implantation','Follicular growth'],a:2,
e:`Luteal phase deficiency with inadequate corpus luteum progesterone directly impairs endometrial implantation by preventing the secretory transformation required for blastocyst adhesion: without sufficient progesterone driving glandular secretion, stromal decidualisation, pinopode development and implantation cytokine production, the endometrium cannot create the receptive window for successful implantation.<br><br>Treatment includes vaginal micronised progesterone (Cyclogest 400 mg twice daily) from 2-3 days after ovulation confirmation, supplementing natural corpus luteum production. In recurrent implantation failure, progesterone supplementation is given empirically even when measured levels appear borderline normal.<br><br>Ovulation (A) is intact in luteal phase deficiency. FSH release (B) drives follicular development preceding ovulation. Cervical mucus production (C) responds to oestradiol and is not the primary defect in luteal phase insufficiency.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A patient tracking ovulation uses urinary LH kits. Detection of LH surge indicates that ovulation will occur within approximately:',o:['24-36 hours','12 hours','6 hours','72 hours'],a:0,
e:`The urinary LH surge is detected 24-48 hours before follicular rupture. LH detection in urine lags blood LH by approximately 4-6 hours due to renal clearance and urinary concentration, making the urinary detection-to-ovulation interval 24-36 hours in most women. Ovulation occurs approximately 36-40 hours after the serum LH peak.<br><br>A positive urine LH test in the morning means ovulation is expected the following day, making that evening and the following morning the optimal times for timed intercourse. For IUI, insemination 24-36 hours after positive LH test optimises sperm availability at the time of ovulation for maximum fertilisation potential.<br><br>6 hours (A) is too short: ovulation occurs 36-40 hours after the serum LH peak. 12 hours (B) underestimates the interval between urinary detection and follicular rupture. 72 hours (C) overestimates the interval between urinary LH detection and ovulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 35-year-old woman presents with infertility and irregular cycles due to PCOS. Which reproductive process is most commonly impaired in this condition?',o:['Menstruation','Implantation','Fertilization','Ovulation'],a:3,
e:`A mid-luteal serum progesterone of 4 nmol/L, far below the 30 nmol/L threshold confirming ovulation, indicates anovulation as the cause of infertility, combined with the irregular cycles giving clinical corroboration. In irregular cycles, day-21 progesterone timing may be inaccurate: progesterone should be measured 7 days before the expected period rather than rigidly on day 21.<br><br>Mid-luteal progesterone below 10 nmol/L indicates either anovulation or significant luteal phase deficiency. Treatment is ovulation induction with clomifene or letrozole for PCOS, or addressing the underlying cause such as hyperprolactinaemia or hypothalamic amenorrhoea. Achieving progesterone above 30 nmol/L in a subsequent treated cycle confirms successful ovulation induction.<br><br>Tubal blockage (B), cervical stenosis (C) and uterine septum (D) cause infertility with evidence of ovulation present. The very low progesterone here specifically and biochemically confirms absent ovulation as the primary diagnosis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A patient undergoing IVF receives progesterone supplementation after embryo transfer. What is the main purpose of this therapy?',o:['Increase estrogen production','Stimulate ovulation','Support endometrial implantation','Increase prolactin secretion'],a:2,
e:`Progesterone supplementation after egg collection in IVF replaces the luteal phase corpus luteum progesterone that is inadequate after ovarian stimulation, where multiple follicle aspiration removes the granulosa cells that would form corpora lutea. Without supplementation, the endometrium fails to achieve optimal secretory transformation for blastocyst implantation.<br><br>Vaginal micronised progesterone (Cyclogest 400 mg twice daily) is standard luteal support in IVF, continued until 8-10 weeks of pregnancy when placental progesterone production takes over. Luteal support significantly improves implantation and ongoing pregnancy rates compared with IVF cycles without progesterone supplementation.<br><br>Preventing shedding is the immediate mechanism; the goal is supporting endometrial implantation (A). Suppressing ovarian function (B) is done by GnRH agonists or antagonists earlier in the cycle. Triggering ovulation (C) is done by hCG or GnRH agonist before egg collection, not after it.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A woman experiences infertility due to endometriosis affecting the fallopian tubes. Which reproductive step is most likely disrupted?',o:['Menstruation','Ovulation','Implantation','Fertilization'],a:3,
e:`Endometriosis affecting the fallopian tubes causes tubal adhesions, distortion, fibrosis and impaired fimbrial pick-up of the oocyte, directly compromising fertilisation by preventing the meeting of sperm and oocyte in the ampullary fertilisation site. Peri-tubal adhesions can fix the tube away from the ovary, preventing cumulus oocyte complex capture.<br><br>Endometriosis also creates a hostile peritoneal environment: elevated peritoneal fluid prostaglandins, macrophages engulfing sperm and direct oocyte toxicity all reduce fertilisation rates even in women with mild endometriosis and patent tubes. IVF bypasses these factors and is treatment of choice for endometriosis-related infertility when other measures fail.<br><br>Implantation (A) may also be impaired by endometriosis but fertilisation is most directly compromised by tubal involvement. FSH secretion (B) and LH surge (C) are typically normal in endometriosis without concomitant HPO axis disruption.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A gynecologist explains that the fertile window is determined by lifespan of sperm and ovum. Which factor mainly determines the length of fertile window?',o:['Length of luteal phase','Duration of menstruation','Sperm survival in female tract','Cervical dilation'],a:2,
e:`The start of the fertile window is determined by sperm survival duration in the female reproductive tract. Since spermatozoa can survive 3-5 days in fertile oestrogen-stimulated cervical mucus, the window begins approximately 5 days before ovulation when sperm deposited on day 1 could still be viable when the egg is released on day 6.<br><br>Understanding sperm survival as the determinant of the window's start has practical implications: intercourse 2-3 days before ovulation is as effective for conception as on the day of ovulation itself. This knowledge underpins the recommendation to have regular intercourse every 2-3 days throughout the fertile window rather than attempting to pin-point the single day of ovulation.<br><br>Progesterone action (A) determines the post-ovulatory infertile period by converting cervical mucus to hostile material. Endometrial shedding (B) marks the new cycle start, not the fertile window. LH surge timing (C) predicts ovulation but does not determine when the fertile window begins.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 30-year-old woman with infertility has high prolactin levels suppressing GnRH secretion. Which reproductive hormone is directly reduced as a result?',o:['Oxytocin','Estrogen','Progesterone','FSH and LH'],a:3,
e:`Elevated prolactin suppresses hypothalamic GnRH pulsatility via opioidergic and kisspeptin pathways, reducing pituitary FSH and LH secretion below the threshold required for dominant follicle development and the ovulatory LH surge. FSH and LH are the most directly deficient hormones in hyperprolactinaemia-driven infertility.<br><br>Cabergoline normalises prolactin in over 90% of prolactinoma patients within weeks, rapidly restoring GnRH pulsatility, FSH and LH secretion, ovulatory cycles and fertility. This reversibility confirms that prolactin-mediated FSH and LH suppression is the specific mechanism, making prolactin measurement an essential part of all female infertility investigations.<br><br>Oxytocin and ADH (A) are posterior pituitary hormones unaffected by prolactin excess. Cortisol and aldosterone (B) are adrenal hormones regulated by ACTH. TSH and ACTH (C) are regulated by separate hypothalamic axes unaffected by prolactin-driven GnRH suppression.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A patient with premature ovarian failure has very high FSH levels and infertility. Which physiological mechanism explains this hormonal pattern?',o:['Increased GnRH inhibition','Increased prolactin secretion','Loss of negative feedback from ovarian hormones','Increased progesterone secretion'],a:2,
e:`Premature ovarian failure eliminates oestradiol and inhibin B production from absent granulosa cells. Loss of oestradiol negative feedback at hypothalamus and pituitary, combined with loss of inhibin B-mediated selective FSH suppression, removes the brakes on gonadotropin secretion, causing compensatory FSH and LH elevation as the pituitary attempts to stimulate the unresponsive exhausted ovary.<br><br>Persistently elevated FSH above 25 IU/L on two occasions 4-6 weeks apart with amenorrhoea confirms premature ovarian insufficiency before age 40. Oestrogen replacement is essential for bone and cardiovascular protection. Egg donation IVF offers the best fertility outcomes as own oocytes are rarely available.<br><br>Positive oestrogen feedback (A) requires high oestradiol concentrations absent in POI. Increased thyroid hormone (B) and prolactin (C) cause different hormonal patterns without the characteristic high FSH, high LH, low oestradiol constellation of premature ovarian insufficiency.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A woman with normal ovulation but recurrent implantation failure may have dysfunction of which uterine structure?',o:['Fallopian tube','Cervix','Myometrium','Endometrium'],a:3,
e:`Recurrent implantation failure despite normal ovulation, tubal patency and good-quality embryos points to endometrial dysfunction as the most likely cause. Endometrial receptivity requires an orchestrated sequence of progesterone-driven changes including secretory transformation, pinopode development, adhesion molecule expression and immune tolerance that can each be impaired.<br><br>Investigation includes hysteroscopy to exclude polyps, fibroids, synechiae and uterine anomalies, endometrial receptivity testing, and assessment of the endometrial immune environment. Emerging treatments include progesterone optimisation, endometrial scratch and platelet-rich plasma, though evidence for most adjuvant treatments in recurrent implantation failure remains limited.<br><br>Ovary (A) and pituitary (B) dysfunction would impair ovulation which is stated to be normal. Fallopian tube (C) dysfunction prevents fertilisation but recurrent implantation failure involves fertilisation with failure occurring at the endometrial stage of conception.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A fertility specialist explains that successful conception requires ovulation, fertilization, and implantation. Which ovarian hormone prepares the uterine lining for implantation?',o:['Prolactin','Estrogen','Progesterone','Oxytocin'],a:2,
e:`The corpus luteum must produce adequate progesterone to transform the endometrium into a receptive secretory state for blastocyst implantation and to maintain the early pregnancy before the luteo-placental shift at 8-10 weeks. Corpus luteum progesterone is the essential hormonal bridge between ovulation and placental autonomy.<br><br>Mid-luteal progesterone above 30 nmol/L confirms adequate corpus luteum function. Luteal phase deficiency with insufficient progesterone impairs implantation and causes early pregnancy loss. Vaginal progesterone supplementation from ovulation confirmation corrects this deficiency in both natural cycles and assisted reproduction protocols.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) is also produced by the corpus luteum but in lesser amounts; progesterone is the defining essential product. FSH (B) is a pituitary gonadotropin. Oxytocin (C) stimulates uterine contractions and milk ejection without a corpus luteum steroidogenesis role.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 29-year-old woman with infertility has reduced cervical mucus production during ovulation. Which hormone deficiency could cause this finding?',o:['Testosterone','Progesterone','Prolactin','Estrogen'],a:3,
e:`Oestradiol at the pre-ovulatory peak stimulates cervical glandular cells to produce abundant, thin, elastic fertile mucus with 95-98% water content that facilitates sperm penetration, migration and capacitation. Oestrogen deficiency reduces mucus production and quality, creating a hostile cervical environment that impedes sperm transport even when sperm counts and ovulation are normal.<br><br>Cervical factor infertility is diagnosed by post-coital test showing poor sperm penetration of cervical mucus or by sperm-mucus penetration testing. Intrauterine insemination, which bypasses the cervical barrier by depositing washed sperm directly into the uterine cavity, is the standard treatment for cervical factor infertility.<br><br>Progesterone (A) produces thick, hostile mucus and its deficiency would not impair fertile mucus quality. Prolactin (B) and oxytocin (C) have no direct role in regulating the cyclical changes in cervical mucus quality across the menstrual cycle.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A woman attempting pregnancy tracks ovulation using basal body temperature charting. The temperature rise indicates:',o:['LH suppression','Estrogen surge','Progesterone secretion after ovulation','Prolactin increase'],a:2,
e:`The post-ovulatory temperature rise is caused by progesterone from the corpus luteum acting on the hypothalamic thermoregulatory centre to raise the temperature set-point by 0.2-0.5 degrees C. This thermogenic effect persists throughout the 14-day luteal phase as long as corpus luteum progesterone production is maintained, falling with corpus luteum regression before menstruation.<br><br>A sustained temperature rise for 14 days confirms normal corpus luteum function and luteal phase length. Elevation persisting beyond 14 days suggests early pregnancy with hCG preventing luteolysis, maintaining progesterone and the elevated temperature. A luteal phase below 10-12 days elevation suggests corpus luteum insufficiency requiring investigation.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) does not produce a sustained temperature rise; follicular phase oestradiol is associated with lower pre-ovulatory temperatures. FSH elevation (B) drives follicular development during the lower temperature follicular phase. Oxytocin (C) mediates contractions and milk ejection without thermogenic effects on the hypothalamus.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A patient undergoing infertility evaluation has normal ovulation and tubal patency but poor endometrial receptivity. Which phase of menstrual cycle is primarily responsible for endometrial preparation?',o:['Ovulatory phase','Follicular phase','Menstrual phase','Luteal phase'],a:3,
e:`Normal ovulation confirmed by mid-luteal progesterone above 30 nmol/L, combined with recurrent implantation failure, points to luteal phase dysfunction as the deficient period. The luteal phase encompasses the corpus luteum-dependent events from ovulation to implantation: endometrial secretory transformation, pinopode development and the implantation window, all requiring adequate progesterone throughout days 15-28.<br><br>Luteal phase evaluation includes mid-luteal progesterone measurement, endometrial biopsy assessing secretory transformation adequacy and hysteroscopy to exclude structural pathology. Progesterone supplementation is the primary treatment and is given empirically in recurrent implantation failure even when measured progesterone appears normal.<br><br>Follicular phase (A), menstrual phase (B) and ovulatory phase (C) precede the luteal phase where implantation occurs. Deficiency in these earlier phases would impair ovulation rather than implantation in a woman with confirmed normal ovulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 32-year-old woman with infertility has low estrogen levels leading to thin endometrium. Which ovarian structure primarily produces estrogen before ovulation?',o:['Theca externa','Corpus luteum','Dominant follicle','Ovarian stroma'],a:2,
e:`Low oestradiol leading to thin endometrium indicates failure of dominant follicle development: the dominant follicle is the source of the oestradiol that drives endometrial proliferation. Without a dominant follicle producing oestradiol via FSH-driven granulosa cell aromatase, the endometrium remains thin and atrophic, incapable of supporting implantation.<br><br>Dominant follicle failure is most commonly due to inadequate FSH stimulation from hypothalamic GnRH suppression, FSH deficiency from hypopituitarism or PCOS causing arrested follicular development. Recombinant FSH injections stimulate follicular development and oestradiol production, thickening the endometrium for conception or embryo transfer.<br><br>Corpus luteum (A) produces progesterone after ovulation; its deficiency would cause secretory phase endometrial failure, not thin proliferative endometrium. Theca cells (B) produce androgens requiring granulosa aromatase. Ovarian stroma (D) does not produce significant follicular oestradiol.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A reproductive endocrinologist explains that successful fertility requires coordinated interaction of hypothalamus, pituitary, ovary, fallopian tubes, and uterus. Which endocrine axis primarily regulates this process?',o:['Hypothalamic-pituitary-renal axis','Hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis','Hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis','Hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis'],a:3,
e:`The hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis is the master regulator of female reproductive function, coordinating the entire menstrual cycle: hypothalamic GnRH pulses drive pituitary FSH and LH secretion, which stimulate ovarian follicular development and oestradiol production, which feeds back to regulate GnRH and gonadotropin secretion, culminating in the LH surge, ovulation, corpus luteum formation and either pregnancy maintenance or menstruation.<br><br>Disruption at any HPO axis level impairs fertility: hypothalamic GnRH deficiency (functional amenorrhoea, Kallmann syndrome), pituitary failure (hypopituitarism) or ovarian dysfunction (PCOS, POI) each produce infertility through different mechanisms in the same integrated reproductive axis.<br><br>Thyroid (A), adrenal (B) and pancreatic (C) axes regulate metabolic, stress and glucose homeostasis respectively. While thyroid and adrenal dysfunction can secondarily disrupt the HPO axis, the primary coordinator of female reproductive function is the HPO axis itself.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'The mid-cycle LH surge that triggers ovulation occurs primarily due to which endocrine mechanism?',o:['Negative feedback of progesterone on hypothalamus','Decreased estrogen levels in follicular phase','Sustained high estrogen causing positive feedback on pituitary','Increased prolactin secretion suppressing GnRH'],a:2,
e:`The mid-cycle LH surge is triggered when oestradiol from the dominant follicle sustains concentrations above approximately 200 pg/mL for at least 50 hours, switching hypothalamic-pituitary feedback from negative to positive. This oestradiol positive feedback increases GnRH pulse frequency and pituitary gonadotroph sensitivity, generating the massive LH surge that drives ovulation 36-40 hours later.<br><br>The positive feedback is mediated by kisspeptin neurons in the anteroventral periventricular nucleus specifically stimulated by rising oestradiol to activate GnRH neurons. This contrasts with kisspeptin neurons in the arcuate nucleus that mediate the tonic negative feedback from oestradiol at lower concentrations throughout the rest of the cycle.<br><br>Progesterone negative feedback (A) suppresses the axis during the luteal phase after ovulation. Falling FSH (B) drives dominant follicle selection mid-follicular phase. Prolactin inhibiting dopamine (C) suppresses rather than promotes the LH surge.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'In the ovarian cycle, selection of the dominant follicle is primarily determined by:',o:['Highest sensitivity to FSH among developing follicles','Suppression of aromatase activity','Increased LH receptors in theca cells only','Progesterone secretion from granulosa cells'],a:0,
e:`Dominant follicle selection is based on which antral follicle has the highest FSH sensitivity and the most active granulosa cell aromatase activity. The follicle producing the most oestradiol per unit of FSH creates a positive intra-follicular FSH receptor amplification loop via local oestradiol, while its inhibin B and oestradiol suppress systemic FSH, starving competing follicles of the FSH they need to survive and causing their atresia.<br><br>In clinical ovulation induction with exogenous FSH, this selection mechanism is overwhelmed: multiple follicles survive because supra-physiological FSH prevents the systemic fall that normally causes follicular selection, requiring monitoring with serial ultrasound and oestradiol to prevent dangerous multifollicular development and hyperstimulation.<br><br>Follicle size at recruitment (A) does not determine dominance. Random selection (B) is incorrect; FSH sensitivity governs selection biologically. LH surge timing (C) occurs after dominant follicle selection is already complete.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'During the late follicular phase, estrogen levels rise due to increased aromatase activity in:',o:['Theca externa cells','Granulosa cells','Corpus luteum','Stromal cells'],a:1,
e:`Rising oestradiol in the late follicular phase reflects the dominant follicle's granulosa cells maximally expressing FSH-induced aromatase, converting abundant theca-derived androstenedione and testosterone substrate into oestradiol. The positive oestradiol amplification loop in the dominant follicle drives progressively increasing oestradiol production as ovulation approaches.<br><br>The granulosa cell aromatase activity is the rate-limiting step for follicular oestradiol production. Clinical monitoring of granulosa cell aromatase function uses serum oestradiol measurements in IVF cycles to assess stimulation adequacy and guide FSH dose adjustment, targeting approximately 200-300 pg/mL per mature follicle.<br><br>Corpus luteum cells (A) form after ovulation. Theca externa cells (B) provide structural support without significant steroidogenesis. Ovarian stromal cells (D) do not contribute significantly to the follicular phase oestradiol rise observed in the late follicular phase.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'Which physiological change in cervical mucus is most characteristic at the time of ovulation?',o:['Thick and scanty mucus','Complete absence of mucus','Thin, watery mucus with spinnbarkeit','Increased viscosity due to progesterone'],a:2,
e:`Peri-ovulatory oestradiol at its pre-ovulatory peak stimulates cervical glandular cells to secrete abundant thin, transparent, highly elastic mucus with 95-98% water content and Spinnbarkeit stretching 10 cm without breaking. This mucus exhibits characteristic ferning on drying from NaCl crystallisation and has aligned mucin fibre channels facilitating sperm penetration and migration.<br><br>The transition from thick luteal phase mucus to thin peri-ovulatory mucus and back to thick post-ovulatory mucus provides the basis for the Billings cervical mucus method, fertility awareness contraception and post-coital testing of sperm-mucus interaction in infertility evaluation at clinical fertility clinics.<br><br>Thick opaque mucus (A) and scanty production (B) are the progesterone-dominant luteal phase pattern. Absent mucus (C) occurs in cervical stenosis or profound atrophy. None characterise the peri-ovulatory oestrogen-dominant fertile window phase.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'The corpus luteum degenerates into which structure if fertilization does not occur?',o:['Corpus albicans','Graafian follicle','Corpus hemorrhagicum','Atretic follicle'],a:0,
e:`Without hCG rescue from an implanting blastocyst, the corpus luteum undergoes programmed luteolysis at days 26-28 from prostaglandin F2-alpha released by the endometrium. The steroidogenically active corpus luteum becomes avascular and involutes over 2-3 months to form the corpus albicans, a white fibrous scar visible on the ovarian surface.<br><br>The corpus albicans is the final remnant of the cycle's dominant follicle: from Graafian follicle to corpus luteum to corpus albicans. Each corpus albicans represents a previous ovulation, and their accumulation on the ovarian surface provides a historical record of ovulations during a woman's reproductive life.<br><br>Corpus haemorrhagicum (A) is the immediately post-rupture blood-filled follicle that transforms into the corpus luteum. Graafian follicle (B) precedes ovulation. Atretic follicle (C) is a follicle undergoing degeneration without ovulating at any point in the cycle.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'In the absence of pregnancy, luteolysis of the corpus luteum results in decreased secretion of:',o:['FSH and LH','Prolactin and oxytocin','TSH and ACTH','Progesterone and estrogen'],a:3,
e:`Corpus luteum luteolysis causes simultaneous falls in both progesterone and oestradiol. This hormonal withdrawal removes negative feedback from the hypothalamic-pituitary axis, allowing FSH to rise and initiate a new follicular cohort for the next cycle, while triggering prostaglandin-mediated spiral artery vasospasm and endometrial shedding as menstruation.<br><br>The timing of these changes is coordinated: FSH begins rising in the late luteal phase even before progesterone has completely fallen, overlapping the end of one cycle with the beginning of the next. This FSH rise is detectable on day 2-3 of the new cycle, conventionally taken as the reference baseline for ovarian reserve testing using day-3 FSH.<br><br>Rising LH (A) and rising FSH (B) are consequences, not components, of the luteal hormone decline. Rising progesterone (C) would occur if hCG rescued the corpus luteum from luteolysis, the opposite of the infertile cycle scenario described here.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'Which ovarian hormone is mainly responsible for suppression of FSH during the late follicular phase?',o:['Progesterone','Inhibin B','Testosterone','Oxytocin'],a:1,
e:`Inhibin B from granulosa cells of the developing follicle cohort exerts selective negative feedback specifically suppressing FSH beta-subunit transcription at the pituitary without significantly affecting LH. This selectivity enables the dominant follicle to create a falling FSH environment that causes atresia of less FSH-sensitive competing follicles while maintaining its own dominance through local oestradiol amplification of FSH receptors.<br><br>Inhibin B falls dramatically in the perimenopause as follicular reserve declines, causing disproportionate FSH elevation before oestradiol falls. Day-3 serum inhibin B provides an ovarian reserve marker, though AMH has superseded it due to greater cycle-independence and sensitivity to early reserve decline.<br><br>Progesterone (A) suppresses GnRH in the luteal phase. Oxytocin (B) acts on uterine and mammary smooth muscle. Testosterone (C) is an androgen substrate without a direct FSH-specific inhibitory feedback role in the mid-follicular phase.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'The ovarian cycle is regulated primarily by which endocrine axis?',o:['Hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis','Hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis','Hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis','Hypothalamic-pituitary-renal axis'],a:2,
e:`The HPO axis provides the integrated regulatory control of the ovarian cycle: hypothalamic GnRH pulses drive pituitary FSH and LH secretion, which stimulate follicular development, oestradiol and inhibin production, the LH surge and ovulation, corpus luteum formation and progesterone secretion, with each ovarian hormone feeding back to modulate GnRH and gonadotropin secretion in a cycle-appropriate manner.<br><br>Disruption at any HPO axis level impairs the ovarian cycle: hypothalamic GnRH deficiency causes anovulation, pituitary gonadotropin deficiency prevents follicular development, and ovarian failure with absent oestradiol and inhibin causes compensatory gonadotropin elevation. All major reproductive endocrine disorders are ultimately disorders of the HPO axis.<br><br>HPA axis (A) regulates cortisol. HPT axis (B) regulates thyroid hormones. Hypothalamic-pituitary-renal axis (D) does not exist as a classical endocrine system. None regulate the ovarian cycle.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'The immediate trigger for follicular rupture during ovulation is:',o:['Increase in prostaglandins and proteolytic enzymes','Decrease in estrogen levels','Increased prolactin secretion','Increased oxytocin release'],a:0,
e:`The LH surge activates prostaglandins (PGE2, PGF2-alpha), proteolytic enzymes (ADAMTS proteases, plasminogen activator, matrix metalloproteinases) and VEGF in the follicular wall. Together these weaken and dissolve the follicular basement membrane, cause smooth muscle contraction and create the stigma through which the cumulus-oocyte complex is extruded approximately 36-40 hours after the LH surge onset.<br><br>NSAIDs that block prostaglandin synthesis can delay or inhibit ovulation, confirming prostaglandins as an essential component of the rupture mechanism. This is the basis of advice to avoid NSAIDs around expected ovulation time when using fertility awareness contraceptive methods where ovulation inhibition would impair the method's effectiveness.<br><br>Fall in oestrogen (B) does not trigger follicular rupture. Rising FSH (C) drives follicular recruitment, not rupture. Progesterone from corpus luteum (D) is produced after rupture, not before it as a trigger.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'Which hormone is mainly responsible for thermogenic rise in basal body temperature after ovulation?',o:['Estrogen','FSH','Progesterone','LH'],a:2,
e:`Progesterone from the corpus luteum acts on hypothalamic thermoreceptors to raise the thermoregulatory set point by 0.2-0.5 degrees C above the follicular phase baseline, producing the characteristic temperature rise detectable by daily basal body temperature measurement. This sustained rise persists throughout the 14-day luteal phase until corpus luteum regression.<br><br>The biphasic basal body temperature chart has historically been used to confirm ovulation retrospectively and identify the luteal phase. A sustained rise for 12-14 days confirms ovulation; persistent rise beyond 14 days suggests early pregnancy. Luteal phase elevation below 10-12 days may indicate corpus luteum insufficiency requiring progesterone supplementation.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) does not produce a temperature rise; follicular phase oestradiol is associated with the lower pre-ovulatory temperatures. Inhibin B (B) has no thermogenic action. LH (D) triggers ovulation but does not produce the sustained post-ovulatory temperature rise maintained by corpus luteum progesterone.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A woman tracking ovulation detects a surge in urinary LH levels. Ovulation is expected to occur within approximately:',o:['48-72 hours','24-36 hours','12-18 hours','6-12 hours'],a:1,
e:`Urinary LH detection precedes ovulation by approximately 24-36 hours. The serum LH surge peaks 10-12 hours before ovulation, but urinary LH lags serum LH by approximately 4-6 hours due to renal clearance time, making the urinary detection-to-ovulation interval 24-36 hours in most women tested under normal conditions.<br><br>For practical timing of timed intercourse or intrauterine insemination, the day of positive urinary LH test and the following day represent the optimal window for maximum conception probability. Egg retrieval in IVF is planned 34-36 hours after either urinary LH surge detection or exogenous hCG administration that mimics the LH surge.<br><br>6 hours (A) and 12 hours (B) are too short: ovulation occurs 36-40 hours after the serum LH peak. 72 hours (C) overestimates the interval between urinary LH detection and follicular rupture by approximately 36-48 hours.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 27-year-old woman presents with infertility due to failure of ovulation despite normal follicular growth. Which endocrine event is most likely absent?',o:['LH surge','Progesterone secretion','Estrogen rise','FSH secretion'],a:0,
e:`Luteinised unruptured follicle syndrome or absent LH surge means normal follicular development occurs but without the mid-cycle LH surge to trigger proteolytic follicular wall rupture and oocyte release. The follicle may luteinise and produce progesterone without releasing the oocyte, causing infertility despite apparently normal ovulation markers such as temperature rise.<br><br>Diagnosis requires serial transvaginal ultrasound showing follicular persistence without collapse or collapse timing inconsistent with expected ovulation from LH surge detection. Treatment involves exogenous hCG trigger to provide the LH receptor stimulation that the absent endogenous LH surge fails to deliver, generating follicular rupture 36-40 hours later.<br><br>FSH secretion (A) drives the follicular development that is stated to be normal here. Corpus luteum formation (B) follows ovulation. Endometrial implantation (C) follows fertilisation. The absent LH surge is the specific missing ovulatory trigger preventing oocyte release.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A patient with luteal phase defect has inadequate progesterone secretion after ovulation. Which physiological process is most directly affected?',o:['Follicular growth','Ovulation','Endometrial implantation','Cervical mucus production'],a:2,
e:`Inadequate corpus luteum progesterone directly impairs endometrial implantation by preventing adequate secretory transformation: without sufficient progesterone, glandular glycogen secretion, stromal decidualisation, endometrial pinopode development and implantation cytokine production all fail to reach the threshold required for the receptive implantation window to develop.<br><br>Treatment with vaginal micronised progesterone 400 mg twice daily from 2-3 days after confirmed ovulation supplements corpus luteum production, supporting endometrial transformation and early pregnancy maintenance. This forms the basis of routine luteal phase support in all IVF cycles where egg retrieval removes the granulosa cells that would form corpora lutea.<br><br>Cervical mucus production (A) is driven by oestradiol and is not the primary defect in luteal phase deficiency. FSH secretion (B) and LH surge (C) are upstream events preceding the luteal phase defect that produces the progesterone insufficiency.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A woman presents with infertility due to persistent high prolactin levels suppressing GnRH secretion. Which stage of ovarian cycle is primarily impaired?',o:['Corpus albicans formation','Ovulation','Follicular maturation','Luteal regression'],a:1,
e:`Chronic hyperprolactinaemia suppresses hypothalamic GnRH pulsatility via opioidergic pathways and kisspeptin neuron inhibition, reducing FSH and LH below the threshold for both dominant follicle development and the oestradiol positive feedback mechanism needed to generate the mid-cycle LH surge. Without an LH surge, follicular rupture and oocyte release (ovulation) cannot occur.<br><br>Cabergoline treatment normalises prolactin, restores GnRH pulsatility, allows FSH to drive follicular development and oestradiol to trigger the LH surge, restoring ovulation and fertility in over 90% of women with prolactinoma. This treatment-response relationship confirms ovulation as the physiological event specifically prevented by hyperprolactinaemia.<br><br>Follicular development (A) may be partially suppressed but ovulation requiring the LH surge is the most directly prevented event. Corpus luteum formation (B) requires prior ovulation. Endometrial shedding (C) depends on progesterone withdrawal, not prolactin levels.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A 30-year-old woman with PCOS has multiple small follicles but failure of dominant follicle selection. Which hormonal imbalance is most characteristic?',o:['Decreased LH relative to FSH','Increased progesterone levels','Increased LH relative to FSH','Decreased estrogen levels'],a:2,
e:`In PCOS, elevated GnRH pulse frequency preferentially drives LH secretion over FSH, producing an elevated LH:FSH ratio typically above 2:1. Elevated LH hyperstimulates theca cell androgen production via CYP17A1 while relatively reduced FSH insufficiently stimulates granulosa cell aromatase, causing intra-follicular androgen accumulation that arrests follicles at the small antral stage, preventing dominant follicle selection and ovulation.<br><br>The multiple small follicles seen on ultrasound represent the arrested follicular cohort responding to the imbalanced gonadotropin environment: all follicles respond to some FSH but none achieves sufficient oestradiol production to suppress others and become dominant, creating the classic polycystic ovarian morphology with anovulation.<br><br>Decreased LH relative to FSH (A) would facilitate normal follicular development. Decreased progesterone (B) results from anovulation rather than causing it. Low oestrogen (D) would reflect follicular failure rather than the androgen-driven arrested antral follicle pattern of PCOS.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A patient undergoing IVF is administered hCG to trigger ovulation. Which ovarian process does this hormone mimic?',o:['Estrogen synthesis from granulosa cells','LH surge leading to follicular rupture','FSH stimulation of granulosa cells','Progesterone secretion from corpus luteum'],a:1,
e:`hCG binds ovarian LH receptors with equal affinity to LH, triggering the same cascade as the endogenous LH surge: proteolytic enzyme and prostaglandin activation in the follicular wall, stigma formation and oocyte release approximately 36-40 hours after hCG administration. hCG's longer half-life of approximately 36 hours provides sustained receptor activation through the complete follicular maturation period needed before rupture.<br><br>In IVF, egg collection is precisely timed at 34-36 hours after hCG trigger to retrieve mature metaphase II oocytes before spontaneous rupture. GnRH agonist trigger is used as an alternative in antagonist protocols, generating a more physiological LH surge with shorter duration and lower ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome risk.<br><br>Directly stimulating endometrium (A) is not the mechanism of hCG trigger action. Suppressing FSH (C, note rotated position in the question options , check: option B=Suppressing FSH) and increasing progesterone synthesis (D) are not the mechanism. hCG acts specifically on ovarian LH receptors.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`}

,

{q:'A woman charting basal body temperature notes a consistent rise after ovulation. Which endocrine event has occurred?',o:['Increased prolactin release','Increased estrogen secretion from follicle','Increased progesterone secretion from corpus luteum','Increased LH suppression'],a:2,
e:`The post-ovulatory temperature rise is caused by progesterone from the corpus luteum acting on the hypothalamic thermoregulatory centre to elevate the temperature set-point. The exact mechanism involves progesterone-induced sensitisation of hypothalamic thermoreceptors, increasing the thermal set-point by 0.2-0.5 degrees C above the lower follicular phase baseline throughout the 14-day luteal phase.<br><br>Basal body temperature measurement requires consistent conditions: before rising, same time each day, after at least 3 hours of uninterrupted sleep. The biphasic chart pattern (lower follicular, higher luteal) retrospectively confirms ovulation and estimates its timing within the previous 1-3 days. A monophasic chart across the whole cycle indicates anovulation.<br><br>Inhibin B (A) and oestrogen (B) are not thermogenic at physiological concentrations. LH (D) triggers the ovulatory event but does not produce the sustained post-ovulatory temperature rise; that sustained signal is maintained by corpus luteum progesterone throughout the luteal phase.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A patient with anovulatory cycles experiences prolonged estrogen exposure without progesterone opposition. Which endometrial change is most likely?',o:['Proliferative endometrium without secretory transformation','Complete endometrial atrophy','Secretory endometrium with implantation','Immediate menstruation'],a:0,
e:`Continuous unopposed oestradiol stimulation of the endometrium without the progesterone-driven secretory transformation drives progressive endometrial proliferation: glandular and stromal hyperplasia, thickening beyond normal and eventually endometrial instability causing irregular, unpredictable heavy bleeding from areas of endometrial breakdown without the orderly prostaglandin-mediated shedding of the ovulatory cycle.<br><br>Long-term chronic anovulation with persistent unopposed oestrogen significantly increases endometrial hyperplasia and carcinoma risk. Women with PCOS and chronic anovulation require cyclical progestogen or combined oral contraceptive treatment to induce regular secretory transformation and withdrawal, protecting the endometrium from hyperplastic transformation.<br><br>Secretory transformation (B) requires progesterone from an ovulated corpus luteum, absent in anovulatory cycles. Immediate shedding (C) requires progesterone withdrawal. Corpus luteum formation (D) requires prior ovulation, which is the event absent in anovulatory cycles by definition.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'A gynecology resident explains that granulosa cells develop LH receptors in late follicular phase. What is the significance of this physiological change?',o:['Causes follicular atresia','Allows ovulation and luteinization after LH surge','Suppresses estrogen production','Stops follicular growth'],a:1,
e:`The peri-ovulatory fertile window is clinically characterised by the appearance of fertile cervical mucus: thin, clear, elastic Spinnbarkeit mucus produced under oestradiol stimulation from the dominant follicle. This mucus signals the approaching fertile window before ovulation and provides the environment that facilitates sperm transport, survival and capacitation in the female reproductive tract.<br><br>The Billings ovulation method uses this cervical mucus transition from thick and scanty to thin, clear and elastic to identify the fertile window for natural family planning. The mucus also provides direct clinical evidence of oestradiol stimulation from the dominant follicle, correlating with the approaching LH surge and imminent ovulation.<br><br>Thick cervical mucus (A) is the post-ovulatory progesterone-dominant pattern signalling the end of the fertile window. Absent ovarian activity (B) describes the very early follicular phase before follicular recruitment. Elevated FSH only (C) occurs at the very start of the follicular phase before oestradiol rises sufficiently to create fertile mucus.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,

{q:'During reproductive endocrinology teaching, it is explained that cyclic ovarian changes are regulated by coordinated secretion of GnRH, FSH, and LH. If GnRH secretion becomes continuous instead of pulsatile, what will be the most likely endocrine effect?',o:['Increased estrogen production','Increased progesterone secretion','Increased LH secretion','Suppression of FSH and LH release'],a:3,
e:`The LH surge is the pivotal hormonal event marking the transition from follicular to luteal phase: it triggers follicular rupture and oocyte release, simultaneously initiates granulosa cell luteinisation transforming the follicle into the corpus luteum, and shifts the dominant steroid product from oestradiol to progesterone. All subsequent luteal phase events depend on the LH surge having occurred.<br><br>All corpus luteum function, progesterone secretion, endometrial secretory transformation and the conditions for implantation depend on the LH surge having occurred. Without the LH surge, the follicular phase cannot transition to the luteal phase regardless of how well the follicle has developed or how high oestradiol has risen.<br><br>Rising FSH only (A) drives early follicular phase development but does not mark the transition. Falling oestrogen (B) is not the transition marker; oestradiol continues with corpus luteum production in the early luteal phase. Progesterone rise (C) follows the LH surge rather than marking it or being the event that causes the transition.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`}

,
{q:'In the normal menstrual cycle, which hormone is primarily responsible for selection of the dominant follicle?',o:['LH','FSH','Progesterone','Prolactin'],a:1,e:`FSH binds granulosa cell receptors and drives the oestradiol amplification loop determining dominant follicle selection. The follicle with highest aromatase efficiency produces most oestradiol, locally amplifying its FSH receptor expression. Its inhibin B and oestradiol then suppress systemic FSH, causing atresia of all less responsive competing follicles.<br><br>AMH reflects total antral follicle count competing for FSH, providing an indirect ovarian reserve marker. Lower AMH means fewer competing follicles and diminished reserve requiring higher FSH stimulation in IVF protocols.<br><br>LH (A) drives theca androgen production and triggers ovulation. Prolactin (B) suppresses the HPG axis. Progesterone (C) is the dominant luteal phase hormone suppressing GnRH.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which endocrine change is responsible for conversion of the ruptured follicle into corpus luteum?',o:['LH surge','Decrease in estrogen','Increase in prolactin','Decrease in FSH'],a:0,e:`The LH surge initiates luteinisation of the ruptured follicle: LH receptor activation drives granulosa and theca cell transformation, lipid droplet accumulation, VEGF-mediated vascularisation and upregulation of 3beta-HSD, shifting steroid output from oestradiol to progesterone as the corpus luteum forms over 2-3 days.<br><br>Ongoing tonic pituitary LH maintains corpus luteum function in the early luteal phase. In IVF cycles with pituitary downregulation, exogenous progesterone compensates for the iatrogenic LH deficiency causing corpus luteum insufficiency.<br><br>Decreasing oestrogen (B) is a consequence of the shift to progesterone dominance. Prolactin increase (C) suppresses the HPG axis. Decreasing FSH (D) follows negative feedback in the luteal phase.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'During the luteal phase, which hormone maintains the secretory transformation of the endometrium?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','FSH','Oxytocin'],a:1,e:`Progesterone from the corpus luteum sustains glandular glycogen secretion, stromal decidualisation, spiral artery coiling and uterine quiescence throughout the luteal phase. It also suppresses endometrial ERalpha expression, preventing further oestrogen-driven proliferation and maintaining the secretory rather than proliferative state.<br><br>Vaginal progesterone supplementation in IVF cycles maintains secretory transformation until placental progesterone production assumes responsibility at 8-10 weeks. Inadequate corpus luteum progesterone reduces endometrial receptivity and implantation rates.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) drives proliferative phase growth. FSH (C) and oxytocin (D) act on ovary and smooth muscle respectively without maintaining endometrial secretory transformation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'In the menstrual cycle, which hormone level falls just before menstruation leading to endometrial shedding?',o:['Progesterone','Prolactin','LH','Oxytocin'],a:0,e:`Corpus luteum regression at days 26-28 causes a sharp progesterone fall. This progesterone withdrawal triggers prostaglandin F2-alpha release from endometrial stroma, causing spiral artery vasoconstriction, ischaemia and necrotic shedding of the functional endometrial layer as menstruation beginning 1-2 days after the progesterone fall.<br><br>Exogenous progestogens can delay menstruation by maintaining progestogenic action, and progestogen withdrawal produces a predictable withdrawal bleed, the mechanism used in oral contraceptive pill-free intervals and progesterone challenge tests.<br><br>Prolactin (B) is basally low throughout the normal cycle. LH (C) falls from negative feedback in the luteal phase but does not trigger endometrial shedding. Oxytocin (D) drives contractions and milk ejection without triggering menstruation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which ovarian hormone is primarily responsible for negative feedback inhibition of FSH during the late follicular phase?',o:['Testosterone','Progesterone','Oxytocin','Inhibin B'],a:3,e:`Inhibin B from dominant follicle granulosa cells selectively suppresses pituitary FSH without significantly affecting LH, driving the mid-cycle FSH fall that causes atresia of non-dominant follicles. This FSH selectivity distinguishes inhibin B from oestradiol feedback which suppresses both FSH and LH simultaneously.<br><br>Falling inhibin B in diminishing ovarian reserve causes disproportionate FSH elevation as this selective suppression is progressively lost. Day-3 FSH elevation is therefore an indirect indicator of declining inhibin B-producing granulosa cell reserve in ovarian reserve assessment.<br><br>Testosterone (A) is a theca androgen substrate for aromatisation. Progesterone (B) suppresses GnRH in the luteal phase. Oxytocin (C) contracts smooth muscle with no FSH-suppressing function.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A 28-year-old woman monitoring fertility notices that her basal body temperature rises after a certain point in her cycle. This rise indicates:',o:['Increased estrogen secretion','Progesterone secretion from corpus luteum','LH suppression','FSH suppression'],a:1,e:`The post-ovulatory BBT rise of 0.2-0.5 degrees C confirms progesterone secretion from the newly formed corpus luteum acting on the hypothalamic thermoregulatory centre. This rise begins 24-48 hours after follicular rupture and is maintained throughout the 12-14 day luteal phase while corpus luteum progesterone remains elevated.<br><br>Three consecutive elevated temperatures retrospectively confirm ovulation. A sustained rise of 18 days or more raises the possibility of early pregnancy, as hCG maintains corpus luteum progesterone beyond the normal 14-day luteal lifespan.<br><br>Increased oestrogen (A) occurs in the follicular phase without causing the thermogenic BBT rise. LH suppression (C) and FSH suppression (D) are luteal phase consequences of negative feedback, not the cause of the temperature rise.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A woman undergoing infertility evaluation has normal follicular development but no ovulation despite normal FSH levels. Which hormone is most likely deficient?',o:['FSH secretion','Inhibin secretion','Estrogen production','LH surge'],a:3,e:`Normal follicular development with absent ovulation despite normal FSH indicates a deficient or absent LH surge. Without the mid-cycle LH surge activating follicular wall proteolytic enzymes, the mature Graafian follicle cannot rupture. This is luteinised unruptured follicle syndrome when the follicle luteinises without rupturing, or follicular regression when it simply degenerates.<br><br>Diagnosis: follicular tracking ultrasound showing dominant follicle without collapse, combined with low mid-luteal progesterone. Treatment: hCG trigger when follicle reaches 17-18 mm, substituting for the absent endogenous LH surge to trigger rupture 36-40 hours later.<br><br>FSH (A) is normal with normal follicular development. Inhibin secretion (B) from normal granulosa cells would also be normal. Oestrogen production (C) from the normal follicle would be adequate.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with anovulatory cycles experiences continuous estrogen exposure without progesterone. Which endometrial condition results?',o:['Proliferative endometrium','Secretory endometrium','Atrophic endometrium','Decidualized endometrium'],a:0,e:`Continuous oestrogen without progesterone from anovulatory cycles drives persistent endometrial proliferation without secretory transformation. The endometrium continues thickening under oestradiol stimulation, periodically outgrows its blood supply and sheds irregularly, producing heavy unpredictable bleeding characteristic of AUB-O from ovulatory dysfunction.<br><br>Prolonged unopposed oestrogen progressively increases hyperplasia risk: simple to complex to atypical hyperplasia, with atypical carrying 25-30% risk of endometrial carcinoma. Cyclical progestogen or levonorgestrel IUS provides essential endometrial protection in chronic anovulation.<br><br>Secretory endometrium (B) requires progesterone from a corpus luteum, absent in anovulatory cycles. Atrophic endometrium (C) results from oestrogen deficiency. Decidualised endometrium (D) requires high progesterone from luteal phase or pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A fertility specialist explains that the fertile window occurs because sperm survive longer than the ovum. Which indicator best identifies the fertile window?',o:['Myometrium','Endometrial glands','Cervical mucus during ovulation','Corpus luteum'],a:2,e:`Oestradiol-stimulated thin, elastic, sperm-permeable cervical mucus at ovulation is the primary physiological indicator of the fertile window. This mucus creates channels guiding sperm into the uterine cavity, provides an alkaline reservoir in endocervical crypts storing sperm up to 5 days, and protects sperm from vaginal acidity.<br><br>The Billings ovulation method teaches recognition of the transition from thick opaque to thin elastic transparent mucus as the beginning of the fertile window, with return to thick mucus post-ovulation signalling its end. Combined with urinary LH kits and BBT, this forms a complete fertility monitoring system.<br><br>Myometrium (A) is uterine smooth muscle without fertility indicator function. Endometrial glands (B) reflect post-ovulatory secretory transformation. Corpus luteum (D) forms after ovulation, marking the fertile window's end.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A gynecology resident explains that the ovarian cycle consists of follicular phase, ovulation and luteal phase. Which initiating hormonal event marks the transition from follicular to luteal phase?',o:['Inhibin suppression','Progesterone rise','Prolactin increase','LH surge'],a:3,e:`The LH surge marks the follicular-to-luteal phase transition by triggering ovulation and initiating corpus luteum formation. It terminates follicular phase dynamics and initiates all luteal characteristics: progesterone dominance, secretory endometrium, BBT elevation and GnRH pulsatility suppression. All downstream luteal events are consequences of the LH surge-triggered ovulation.<br><br>Urinary LH detection by ovulation predictor kits marks this exact transition point, confirming the post-ovulatory phase has begun. Clinically it is used to time intercourse, IUI or predict egg collection timing in assisted reproduction.<br><br>Progesterone rise (A) occurs after the LH surge as a consequence of corpus luteum formation. Inhibin suppression (B) is a mid-follicular FSH-fall mechanism. Prolactin increase (C) is not the follicular-to-luteal phase transition trigger.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Gonadal steroid hormones are synthesized primarily from which precursor molecule?',o:['Cholesterol','Glucose','Amino acids','Fatty acids'],a:0,
e:`All gonadal steroid hormones including oestrogens, progestogens and androgens are synthesised from cholesterol as the universal precursor. Cholesterol is transported into mitochondria by the steroidogenic acute regulatory (StAR) protein, where it is converted to pregnenolone by CYP11A1 (cholesterol side-chain cleavage enzyme) in the rate-limiting step of steroidogenesis.<br><br>StAR protein-mediated cholesterol transport is the acute regulatory step of gonadal steroidogenesis: LH and FSH stimulate StAR expression within minutes, enabling rapid increases in steroid production in response to gonadotropin signalling without requiring new enzyme synthesis.<br><br>Glucose (B) provides energy for cellular metabolism but is not a steroid precursor. Amino acids (C) are precursors for peptide hormones and proteins. Fatty acids (D) are lipid energy substrates not converted to steroid ring structures.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The enzyme responsible for conversion of androgens to estrogens in granulosa cells is:',o:['Lipase','Aromatase','Amylase','Protease'],a:1,
e:`Aromatase (CYP19A1), induced in granulosa cells by FSH via cAMP-PKA signalling, converts androstenedione to oestrone and testosterone to oestradiol through a three-step oxidative reaction requiring NADPH and molecular oxygen. It is expressed exclusively in granulosa cells within the developing follicle, making FSH-driven aromatase activity the key differentiating function of granulosa cells.<br><br>Aromatase inhibitors including letrozole and anastrozole block this step, reducing oestradiol production. Clinically, letrozole induces ovulation in PCOS by reducing oestradiol-mediated negative feedback, increasing FSH. In breast cancer, aromatase inhibitors suppress peripheral oestrogen synthesis from adipose tissue in postmenopausal women.<br><br>Lipase (A), amylase (C) and protease (D) are digestive enzymes with no role in ovarian steroidogenesis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which ovarian cells primarily produce androgens under LH stimulation?',o:['Theca interna cells','Granulosa cells','Stromal cells','Oocytes'],a:0,
e:`Theca interna cells express LH receptors coupled to Gs-cAMP-PKA signalling that upregulates StAR protein and CYP17A1, enabling sequential conversion of cholesterol to pregnenolone, progesterone, 17-OH-progesterone and androstenedione. Testosterone is also produced in smaller amounts. These androgens are the obligate substrate for granulosa cell aromatase to produce oestradiol.<br><br>In PCOS, chronically elevated LH combined with hyperinsulinaemia amplifies CYP17A1 activity beyond normal, producing androgen excess that overwhelms granulosa cell aromatisation capacity, creating the intra-follicular androgen-dominant environment causing follicular arrest and anovulation.<br><br>Granulosa cells (B) aromatise androgens to oestrogens but cannot produce androgens without CYP17A1. Stromal cells (C) and oocytes (D) lack the LH receptor-CYP17A1 pathway for androgen biosynthesis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Granulosa cells convert androgens into estrogen under stimulation of:',o:['LH','FSH','Prolactin','Progesterone'],a:1,
e:`FSH binds Gs-coupled receptors on granulosa cells, activating adenylate cyclase and cAMP-PKA signalling that induces aromatase (CYP19A1) gene transcription. FSH-induced aromatase converts theca-derived androstenedione to oestrone and testosterone to oestradiol, completing the two-cell two-gonadotropin oestrogen synthesis mechanism essential for follicular development.<br><br>The degree of FSH-induced aromatase activity in granulosa cells determines which follicle becomes dominant: the follicle with the highest aromatase efficiency produces the most oestradiol, locally amplifies its FSH receptor expression, and survives the mid-cycle FSH fall that causes atresia of all less efficient competing follicles.<br><br>LH (A) stimulates theca cells to produce androgens but does not induce granulosa cell aromatase. Prolactin (C) suppresses FSH and LH. Progesterone (D) is the luteal phase product, not an inducer of aromatase in the follicular phase.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which steroid hormone is primarily secreted by the corpus luteum?',o:['Progesterone','Testosterone','Cortisol','Aldosterone'],a:0,
e:`The corpus luteum, formed from luteinised granulosa and theca cells after ovulation, upregulates CYP11A1, StAR protein and 3beta-HSD, shifting steroid production from oestradiol to progesterone as its dominant product. Corpus luteum progesterone peaks at approximately day 21 at 25-100 nmol/L, driving endometrial secretory transformation and uterine quiescence essential for implantation.<br><br>The corpus luteum also secretes smaller amounts of oestradiol and inhibin A. Without hCG rescue from an implanting blastocyst, luteolysis occurs at days 26-28, progesterone falls and menstruation follows. Mid-luteal progesterone above 30 nmol/L confirms ovulation and corpus luteum function clinically.<br><br>Testosterone (B) is primarily a theca cell androgen product of the follicular phase. Cortisol (C) is an adrenal zona fasciculata product. Aldosterone (D) is an adrenal zona glomerulosa mineralocorticoid. Neither is the primary corpus luteum secretion.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'In PCOS, which hormonal abnormality is most commonly observed?',o:['Decreased LH','Increased FSH only','Decreased androgen levels','Increased LH:FSH ratio'],a:3,
e:`In PCOS, elevated GnRH pulse frequency preferentially stimulates LH over FSH from pituitary gonadotrophs, producing an LH:FSH ratio typically greater than 2:1. Elevated LH hyperstimulates theca cell CYP17A1 causing androgen excess, while relatively reduced FSH impairs granulosa cell aromatisation, creating the androgen-dominant intra-follicular environment arresting follicular development and causing anovulation.<br><br>Rotterdam criteria for PCOS diagnosis require two of three: oligo/anovulation, hyperandrogenism (clinical or biochemical), and polycystic ovarian morphology on ultrasound. Elevated LH:FSH supports but is not required for diagnosis as it is absent in approximately 40% of cases, particularly in obese patients where hyperinsulinaemia amplifies the androgen excess through a different mechanism.<br><br>Decreased LH (A) would indicate hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism. Increased FSH only (B) is not the PCOS pattern. Decreased androgens (C) is the opposite of PCOS hyperandrogenism.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Hyperandrogenism in females most commonly presents with:',o:['Hirsutism','Hypothyroidism','Hyperprolactinemia','Amenorrhea only'],a:0,
e:`Hirsutism, the growth of terminal hair in a male distribution (upper lip, chin, chest, lower abdomen, inner thighs), is the most common clinical manifestation of hyperandrogenism in women. It results from androgen stimulation of hair follicles converting fine vellus hairs to coarser terminal hairs in androgen-sensitive skin areas. Acne and androgenic alopecia are additional cutaneous manifestations.<br><br>The modified Ferriman-Gallwey score quantifies hirsutism severity in clinical assessment. The most common cause is PCOS, accounting for approximately 70-80% of hirsutism cases. Other causes include congenital adrenal hyperplasia (particularly non-classical 21-hydroxylase deficiency), androgen-secreting tumours and exogenous androgen exposure.<br><br>Hypothyroidism (B) and hyperprolactinaemia (C) cause anovulation and menstrual irregularity but not hyperandrogenism directly. Amenorrhoea alone (D) is a consequence of anovulation that can occur in hyperandrogenism but is not the most common presenting symptom.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which enzyme deficiency leads to impaired conversion of androgens to estrogens in the ovary?',o:['Lipase','Aromatase deficiency','Protease','21-hydroxylase'],a:1,
e:`Aromatase (CYP19A1) deficiency causes impaired conversion of androgens to oestrogens in granulosa cells, resulting in androgen accumulation and oestrogen deficiency. Affected females have virilisation from accumulated androgens, primary amenorrhoea and absent puberty from oestrogen deficiency. The ovaries contain large cysts from gonadotropin stimulation of follicles that cannot aromatise androgens.<br><br>Aromatase deficiency is confirmed by elevated androgen levels, very low oestrogens, markedly elevated FSH and LH (from absent oestrogen feedback), and large ovarian cysts on ultrasound. Treatment requires oestrogen replacement to reverse virilisation, suppress gonadotropins, allow normal pubertal development and prevent osteoporosis from chronic hypo-oestrogenism.<br><br>Lipase (A) and protease (C) are digestive enzymes. 21-hydroxylase (D) deficiency causes adrenal androgen excess through a different pathway, not impaired ovarian aromatisation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Estrogen production during the follicular phase primarily occurs in:',o:['Granulosa cells','Corpus luteum','Adrenal gland','Liver'],a:0,
e:`During the follicular phase, oestradiol is produced by granulosa cells of the developing dominant follicle. FSH-induced aromatase in granulosa cells converts theca-derived androstenedione and testosterone to oestrone and oestradiol respectively. The rising oestradiol from the growing dominant follicle creates the late follicular oestrogen peak that triggers the mid-cycle LH surge.<br><br>The amount of oestradiol produced by granulosa cells reflects follicular development: serial serum oestradiol measurements during IVF stimulation monitor granulosa cell mass and follicular response, providing real-time assessment of the FSH-driven follicular development with each measurement reflecting the cumulative aromatase activity of all developing follicles.<br><br>Corpus luteum (B) is the post-ovulatory oestrogen source during the luteal phase. Adrenal gland (C) produces DHEAS as androgen precursor for oestrogen synthesis in pregnancy. Liver (D) metabolises rather than synthesises oestrogens.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Progesterone is synthesized from which immediate precursor?',o:['Testosterone','Pregnenolone','Cortisol','Androstenedione'],a:1,
e:`Pregnenolone is the immediate precursor of progesterone in the steroidogenesis pathway. Cholesterol is converted to pregnenolone by CYP11A1 in mitochondria (the rate-limiting step), then pregnenolone is converted to progesterone by 3beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase (3beta-HSD) in the smooth endoplasmic reticulum. This early branching point in steroidogenesis produces progesterone as the first committed steroid hormone.<br><br>In the ovarian follicle, progesterone produced at this step is rapidly converted onwards to androgens by CYP17A1 in theca cells. In the corpus luteum, upregulated 3beta-HSD and increased StAR with downregulated CYP17A1 allow progesterone to accumulate as the dominant secreted product rather than being converted to androgens.<br><br>Testosterone (A) is a downstream androgen produced from androstenedione. Cortisol (C) is an adrenal product synthesised from progesterone via a different enzymatic pathway. Androstenedione (D) is downstream of pregnenolone in the steroidogenic cascade.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A 24-year-old woman presents with irregular menstrual cycles and hirsutism. Laboratory shows elevated LH:FSH ratio. What is the most likely diagnosis?',o:['PCOS','Hypothyroidism','Turner syndrome','Sheehan syndrome'],a:0,
e:`Irregular cycles, hirsutism and elevated LH:FSH ratio (greater than 2:1) in a young woman is the classic presentation of PCOS. The elevated LH:FSH ratio reflects accelerated hypothalamic GnRH pulsatility that preferentially drives LH, causing theca cell androgen overproduction manifest as hirsutism, and relatively reduced FSH that impairs follicular development and ovulation causing the irregular cycles.<br><br>Rotterdam criteria confirm PCOS when two of three features are present: oligo/anovulation (irregular cycles), hyperandrogenism (clinical hirsutism or biochemical elevation), and polycystic ovarian morphology on ultrasound. Investigation includes testosterone, SHBG, 17-OH-progesterone (to exclude non-classical CAH), thyroid function and prolactin to exclude other diagnoses.<br><br>Hypothyroidism (B) causes anovulation without hirsutism or elevated LH:FSH ratio. Turner syndrome (C) presents with primary amenorrhoea and absent secondary sexual development. Sheehan syndrome (D) causes panhypopituitarism with low gonadotropins.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with aromatase deficiency has impaired estrogen production. Which clinical feature would most likely develop?',o:['Galactorrhoea','Hirsutism','Virilization','Delayed puberty'],a:2,
e:`Aromatase deficiency prevents conversion of androgens to oestrogens, causing androgen accumulation and oestrogen deficiency simultaneously. Accumulated androgens act on androgen receptors in skin, hair follicles and the clitoris, producing virilisation: hirsutism, clitoromegaly, deepening of the voice, male-pattern alopecia and frank masculinisation. This distinguishes aromatase deficiency from simple oestrogen deficiency states.<br><br>The virilisation in aromatase deficiency confirms that the precursor androgens are present and being produced normally by theca cells under LH stimulation, but the granulosa cell aromatase step converting them to oestrogens is blocked, causing androgens to accumulate at supraphysiological levels.<br><br>Galactorrhoea (A) results from hyperprolactinaemia. Hirsutism (B) is milder androgen-related hair growth, a subset of virilisation. Delayed puberty (D) occurs from the oestrogen deficiency component but virilisation from androgen excess is the more distinctive clinical feature of aromatase deficiency specifically.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman presents with infertility and elevated LH levels leading to excessive androgen production in the ovary. Which cells are primarily responsible?',o:['Theca interna cells','Granulosa cells','Corpus luteum','Oocytes'],a:0,
e:`Theca interna cells are primarily responsible for excess androgen production in response to elevated LH. LH binding to theca cell receptors activates Gs-cAMP-PKA signalling, upregulating StAR and CYP17A1 which converts cholesterol to androstenedione and testosterone. When LH is chronically elevated as in PCOS, CYP17A1 activity is amplified beyond normal, producing pathological androgen excess.<br><br>Hyperinsulinaemia in obese PCOS patients further amplifies this LH-driven androgen excess by direct insulin receptor signalling on theca cells, stimulating CYP17A1 synergistically with LH. This explains why insulin sensitisers like metformin and weight loss reducing hyperinsulinaemia help reduce androgen levels and restore ovulation in obese PCOS.<br><br>Granulosa cells (B) aromatise androgens to oestrogens. Corpus luteum (C) produces progesterone post-ovulation. Oocytes (D) have no steroidogenic CYP17A1 activity.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with congenital adrenal hyperplasia has increased androgen production. Which enzyme deficiency is most commonly responsible?',o:['Aromatase','21-hydroxylase deficiency','3-beta HSD','Lipase'],a:1,
e:`21-hydroxylase deficiency accounts for approximately 95% of congenital adrenal hyperplasia cases. Impaired conversion of 17-OH-progesterone to 11-deoxycortisol blocks cortisol synthesis, causing ACTH elevation from loss of negative feedback that drives precursor accumulation. Excess 17-OH-progesterone is shunted to adrenal androgen synthesis (androstenedione and testosterone), causing androgen excess.<br><br>Classic 21-hydroxylase deficiency causes virilisation and salt-wasting crisis in neonates from combined cortisol and aldosterone deficiency. Non-classical 21-hydroxylase deficiency presents in adolescence or adulthood with hirsutism, irregular cycles and fertility problems, mimicking PCOS. 17-OH-progesterone measurement, particularly stimulated with Synacthen, distinguishes non-classical CAH from PCOS.<br><br>Aromatase deficiency (A) causes impaired oestrogen synthesis specifically in the ovary and placenta, not adrenal androgen excess. 3-beta HSD (C) deficiency causes a different pattern. Lipase (D) is a digestive enzyme unrelated to adrenal steroidogenesis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with infertility is found to have low estrogen levels due to impaired aromatization. Which ovarian cells have the defect?',o:['Granulosa cells','Theca interna cells','Corpus luteum','Stromal cells'],a:0,
e:`Granulosa cells are the exclusive site of aromatase (CYP19A1) expression within ovarian follicles. Impaired aromatisation from granulosa cell aromatase deficiency, dysfunction or insufficient FSH-driven induction prevents conversion of theca-derived androgens to oestradiol, resulting in low oestrogen despite ongoing androgen production by theca cells under LH stimulation.<br><br>Investigation of impaired aromatisation: FSH-stimulated aromatase activity can be assessed indirectly by measuring follicular oestradiol rise during gonadotropin stimulation. Genetic testing identifies CYP19A1 mutations. Treatment requires oestrogen replacement for symptoms and bone protection; exogenous oestradiol administration for IVF-prepared endometrium can enable embryo transfer using donor eggs.<br><br>Theca interna cells (B) produce androgens via CYP17A1, not aromatase. Corpus luteum (C) is post-ovulatory and produces progesterone. Stromal cells (D) have minimal aromatase activity compared with granulosa cells.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A patient presents with hyperandrogenism and menstrual irregularities. Which endocrine disorder is most likely?',o:['Hypothyroidism','Hyperprolactinemia','PCOS','Addison disease'],a:2,
e:`PCOS is by far the most common endocrine disorder causing the combination of hyperandrogenism and menstrual irregularities, affecting approximately 10-15% of reproductive-age women. The hyperandrogenism from elevated LH-driven theca cell androgen production causes hirsutism, acne and sometimes virilisation, while the androgen-mediated follicular arrest causes anovulation and irregular cycles.<br><br>PCOS management is individualised: combined oral contraceptives suppress LH-driven androgen production and regulate cycles. Anti-androgens including spironolactone and cyproterone acetate reduce hirsutism. Metformin and weight loss address hyperinsulinaemia. Ovulation induction with letrozole or clomifene manages infertility.<br><br>Hypothyroidism (A) causes anovulation without significant hyperandrogenism. Hyperprolactinaemia (B) causes anovulation through GnRH suppression without primary hyperandrogenism. Addison disease (D) causes adrenal insufficiency with reduced rather than excess androgens.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with luteal phase defect has inadequate progesterone secretion. Which ovarian structure is responsible for this secretion?',o:['Corpus luteum','Theca externa','Dominant follicle','Ovarian stroma'],a:0,
e:`The corpus luteum is the sole ovarian source of progesterone during the luteal phase. Luteinised granulosa cells of the corpus luteum upregulate CYP11A1, StAR and 3beta-HSD to convert cholesterol to progesterone, with secretion peaking at approximately day 21. Luteal phase defect reflects corpus luteum dysfunction producing insufficient progesterone for adequate endometrial secretory transformation.<br><br>Treatment: vaginal micronised progesterone supplementation from ovulation confirmation provides the missing progesterone. Luteal phase hCG injections stimulate LH receptors on the corpus luteum to enhance progesterone production. In IVF cycles, all patients receive progesterone supplementation as standard luteal support regardless of measured progesterone levels.<br><br>Theca externa (B) is a structural capsule. Dominant follicle (C) produces oestradiol in the follicular phase and gives rise to the corpus luteum. Ovarian stroma (D) does not produce significant luteal phase progesterone.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with infertility has elevated androgen levels due to increased LH stimulation of ovarian cells. Which reproductive process is most directly impaired?',o:['Implantation','Ovulation','Follicular growth','Fertilization'],a:1,
e:`Androgen excess from LH-stimulated theca cell overproduction creates an intra-follicular androgen-dominant environment that impairs granulosa cell aromatase activity, preventing the oestradiol amplification needed for dominant follicle selection. Without a dominant follicle producing sufficient oestradiol for the LH surge positive feedback threshold, ovulation does not occur despite follicular development.<br><br>The chronically anovulatory state from androgen-mediated follicular arrest is the primary fertility problem in PCOS-type hyperandrogenism. Treatment with letrozole or clomifene reduces oestrogen negative feedback, increasing FSH to drive follicular development beyond the androgen-arrest threshold, restoring ovulation in the majority of women with anovulatory PCOS infertility.<br><br>Implantation (A) and fertilisation (D) cannot occur without prior ovulation. Follicular growth (C) does occur in PCOS with multiple small follicles developing, but none reaches dominant follicle status due to androgen-mediated arrest of the final maturation steps.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman presents with virilization due to androgen-secreting ovarian tumor. Which androgen is most likely elevated?',o:['Testosterone','Estrogen','Progesterone','Cortisol'],a:0,
e:`Androgen-secreting ovarian tumours including Sertoli-Leydig cell tumours (arrhenoblastomas) and steroid cell tumours produce testosterone as their primary secretory product, causing markedly elevated circulating testosterone levels that produce rapid-onset virilisation: clitoromegaly, deepening of the voice, male-pattern alopecia, breast atrophy and amenorrhoea.<br><br>The rapidity of symptom onset distinguishes androgen-secreting tumour virilisation from PCOS hyperandrogenism: tumour-related virilisation typically develops over months rather than years. Serum testosterone above 5 nmol/L warrants pelvic ultrasound and adrenal imaging to identify a source. Unilateral oophorectomy is curative for ovarian tumour sources.<br><br>Oestrogen (B) excess causes endometrial stimulation, not virilisation. Progesterone (C) is the corpus luteum product without virilising effects. Cortisol (D) excess causes Cushing syndrome, not frank virilisation from androgen receptor stimulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with decreased progesterone production after ovulation presents with infertility. Which phase of the cycle is affected?',o:['Follicular phase','Ovulatory phase','Luteal phase','Menstrual phase'],a:2,
e:`Decreased progesterone production after ovulation affects the luteal phase, when the corpus luteum is the sole source of progesterone required for endometrial secretory transformation, implantation support and uterine quiescence. Inadequate luteal phase progesterone, defined by mid-luteal serum progesterone below 30 nmol/L, constitutes luteal phase deficiency causing implantation failure and infertility.<br><br>The luteal phase spans ovulation to menstruation, approximately 12-14 days of constant length determined by the corpus luteum lifespan. Progesterone supplementation with vaginal micronised progesterone from ovulation confirmation is the standard treatment, providing the missing endometrial progesterone stimulus regardless of whether the problem lies in corpus luteum steroidogenesis or in luteal phase LH support.<br><br>Follicular phase (A) is when FSH drives oestradiol production from follicles. Ovulatory phase (B) is the brief LH surge-to-rupture period. Menstrual phase (D) follows progesterone withdrawal and is the consequence of luteal phase failure, not the affected phase itself.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A gynecology resident explains that estrogen synthesis in the ovary requires coordination between two cell types. Which theory describes this?',o:['Two-cell two-gonadotropin theory','Negative feedback theory','Hormonal cascade theory','Steroid amplification theory'],a:0,
e:`The two-cell two-gonadotropin theory describes the coordinated mechanism of ovarian oestrogen synthesis: LH-stimulated theca interna cells produce androstenedione and testosterone via CYP17A1, and these androgens diffuse across the follicular basement membrane to FSH-stimulated granulosa cells where aromatase (CYP19A1) converts them to oestrone and oestradiol. Neither cell type alone can produce significant oestrogen.<br><br>This model has direct clinical implications: conditions disrupting either LH-driven theca androgen production (LH deficiency) or FSH-driven granulosa aromatase (FSH deficiency, aromatase mutations, aromatase inhibitors) impair oestrogen synthesis through predictable cell-type-specific mechanisms, and treatment can be directed at the specifically impaired component.<br><br>Negative feedback theory (B), hormonal cascade theory (C) and steroid amplification theory (D) are not established names for this specific mechanism of coordinate two-cell oestrogen synthesis in the ovarian follicle.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with PCOS has increased ovarian androgen production due to excessive LH stimulation. Which cells are primarily responsible?',o:['Oocytes','Theca cells','Granulosa cells','Corpus luteum cells'],a:1,
e:`Theca cells of the ovarian follicle are primarily responsible for excess androgen production in PCOS. Elevated LH stimulates theca cell CYP17A1 beyond normal, while hyperinsulinaemia acting through insulin receptors on theca cells amplifies this LH-driven CYP17A1 activity synergistically, producing pathological levels of androstenedione and testosterone that overwhelm granulosa cell aromatase capacity and create the androgen-dominant intra-follicular environment.<br><br>Interventions targeting theca cell androgen production in PCOS include combined oral contraceptives (suppress LH), GnRH agonists (suppress LH more completely), anti-androgens including spironolactone and cyproterone acetate (block androgen receptors), and metformin and weight loss (reduce insulin-mediated CYP17A1 amplification).<br><br>Oocytes (A) have no steroidogenic capacity. Granulosa cells (C) aromatise androgens to oestrogens and are not the source of excess androgens. Corpus luteum cells (D) are post-ovulatory progesterone-secreting cells not relevant in the follicular androgen excess of PCOS.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with infertility due to progesterone deficiency is unable to maintain endometrial secretory transformation. Which process is primarily impaired?',o:['Implantation','Ovulation','Fertilization','Follicular growth'],a:0,
e:`Progesterone deficiency from luteal phase defect prevents adequate endometrial secretory transformation: without sufficient progesterone, glands do not develop the tortuous glycogen-rich morphology, stroma does not undergo predecidualisation, pinopodes do not appear during the implantation window, and leukemia inhibitory factor and other implantation cytokines are not produced, impairing blastocyst adhesion and trophoblast invasion.<br><br>Vaginal micronised progesterone supplementation directly addresses the endometrial deficiency. Its vaginal route achieves high uterine tissue concentrations via the uterine first-pass effect. Progesterone supplementation is standard practice in all IVF cycles as luteal phase support regardless of measured mid-luteal progesterone levels, given the universal corpus luteum impairment from pituitary downregulation.<br><br>Ovulation (B) has occurred as the corpus luteum formed. Fertilisation (C) may have occurred normally. Follicular growth (D) driven by FSH is the preceding phase before ovulation and corpus luteum formation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with congenital aromatase deficiency presents with low estrogen levels and virilization. What is the primary biochemical defect?',o:['Impaired LH secretion','Excess progesterone production','Delayed puberty','Conversion of androgens to estrogens is impaired'],a:3,
e:`Congenital aromatase deficiency from CYP19A1 mutations specifically impairs the conversion of androgens to oestrogens in granulosa cells. Androstenedione from theca cells accumulates rather than being aromatised to oestrone, and testosterone accumulates rather than being converted to oestradiol, causing combined androgen excess (virilisation) and oestrogen deficiency (absent puberty, osteoporosis) simultaneously.<br><br>The biochemical profile is characteristic: markedly elevated androgens (androstenedione, testosterone), very low or absent oestrogens, massively elevated FSH and LH from absent oestrogen negative feedback, and large multicystic ovaries from gonadotropin stimulation of follicles unable to complete oestrogen synthesis. 17-OH-progesterone may be elevated as androgen precursors accumulate.<br><br>Impaired LH secretion (A) would cause low androgens and oestrogens. Excess progesterone (B) is not the primary defect. Delayed puberty (C) is a consequence of oestrogen deficiency, not the primary biochemical defect which is specifically impaired aromatase activity.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A fertility specialist explains that steroidogenesis in the ovary begins with cholesterol. Which enzyme catalyses the first and rate-limiting step?',o:['Cholesterol desmolase (CYP11A1)','3-beta HSD','Aromatase','17-alpha hydroxylase'],a:0,
e:`Cholesterol desmolase (CYP11A1), also called cholesterol side-chain cleavage enzyme, catalyses the conversion of cholesterol to pregnenolone in the inner mitochondrial membrane, representing the first committed and rate-limiting step of steroidogenesis in all steroidogenic tissues including ovary, adrenal and testis. StAR protein facilitates cholesterol transport to CYP11A1.<br><br>The rate-limiting nature of this step makes StAR and CYP11A1 the key acute regulatory targets: LH-stimulated cAMP rapidly increases StAR expression within minutes, dramatically accelerating cholesterol delivery to CYP11A1 and the rate of pregnenolone production. This explains why gonadotropin stimulation can rapidly increase steroid output without requiring new enzyme synthesis.<br><br>3-beta HSD (B) converts pregnenolone to progesterone, a subsequent step. Aromatase (C) is the final step converting androgens to oestrogens in granulosa cells. 17-alpha hydroxylase (D) adds the 17-OH group on the pathway to androgens from pregnenolone.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with hyperprolactinemia develops reduced estrogen production. Which mechanism explains this?',o:['Direct ovarian inhibition','Suppression of GnRH secretion','Increased LH secretion','Increased FSH secretion'],a:1,
e:`Hyperprolactinaemia suppresses hypothalamic GnRH secretion through opioidergic and kisspeptin neuron inhibition, reducing GnRH pulse frequency. Without adequate pulsatile GnRH, pituitary FSH and LH secretion falls below the threshold for dominant follicle development. Without FSH-driven follicular growth and LH-driven theca androgen production, the two-cell oestrogen synthesis mechanism cannot function and oestradiol production falls.<br><br>The mechanism is entirely hypothalamic-pituitary-mediated: prolactin has no significant direct inhibitory action on ovarian steroidogenesis itself. Dopamine agonist treatment normalising prolactin restores GnRH pulsatility, FSH and LH, ovarian follicular development and oestradiol production within weeks, confirming the intermediary role of suppressed gonadotropins.<br><br>Direct ovarian inhibition by prolactin (A) is not the established mechanism. Increased LH (C) and increased FSH (D) are the opposite of what occurs; both gonadotropins fall with hyperprolactinaemia-induced GnRH suppression.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with ovarian failure presents with low estrogen levels and high FSH levels. Which mechanism explains the high FSH?',o:['Loss of negative feedback from ovarian hormones','Increased GnRH secretion only','Positive estrogen feedback','Increased prolactin secretion'],a:0,
e:`Ovarian failure eliminates oestradiol and inhibin B production from exhausted follicular reserve. Loss of oestradiol negative feedback at the hypothalamus and pituitary, combined with loss of inhibin B-mediated selective FSH suppression from absent granulosa cells, removes the hormonal brakes on FSH secretion. The pituitary maximally stimulates FSH and LH in an attempt to drive the unresponsive exhausted ovary.<br><br>FSH rises earlier and more dramatically than LH because inhibin B specifically suppresses FSH and its loss disproportionately elevates FSH. Persistently elevated FSH above 25 IU/L with amenorrhoea and hypo-oestrogenic symptoms on two occasions 4-6 weeks apart before age 40 confirms premature ovarian insufficiency requiring urgent oestrogen replacement for bone and cardiovascular protection.<br><br>Increased GnRH only (B) is incomplete as the mechanism involves loss of ovarian feedback, not just GnRH increase. Positive oestrogen feedback (C) requires high oestradiol concentrations absent in ovarian failure. Increased prolactin (D) would suppress FSH, the opposite of what occurs.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with luteal phase defect experiences infertility because progesterone fails to maintain endometrial preparation. Which hormone replacement is most appropriate?',o:['Estrogen only','FSH','hCG','Progesterone'],a:2,
e:`hCG as luteal phase support can stimulate LH receptors on the corpus luteum to enhance endogenous progesterone production, providing an alternative to direct progesterone supplementation. However, vaginal micronised progesterone is the more commonly used and evidence-based treatment for luteal phase defect, directly providing the missing progesterone without requiring a functional corpus luteum.<br><br>In IVF cycles where corpus luteum function is invariably impaired by pituitary downregulation, vaginal progesterone (Cyclogest, Utrogestan, Crinone) is the standard luteal support. The vaginal route achieves high endometrial tissue concentrations via the uterine first-pass effect while minimising systemic sedative effects associated with oral progesterone.<br><br>Oestrogen only (A) drives proliferative endometrium but cannot maintain secretory transformation. FSH (B) drives follicular development but has no direct corpus luteum support function. The question asks about maintaining endometrial preparation which requires progesterone rather than its hormonal precursors.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman presents with hyperandrogenism due to ovarian steroidogenic dysfunction. What is the most common clinical manifestation?',o:['Hirsutism','Galactorrhoea','Hyperprolactinemia','Primary amenorrhea'],a:0,
e:`Hirsutism is the most common clinical manifestation of hyperandrogenism from ovarian steroidogenic dysfunction, caused by androgen stimulation of hair follicles converting fine vellus to coarser terminal hairs in androgen-sensitive areas including the face, chest, lower abdomen and inner thighs. The Ferriman-Gallwey score quantifies severity and guides treatment decisions.<br><br>Additional cutaneous manifestations of hyperandrogenism include acne, seborrhoea, androgenic alopecia and skin darkening. Hirsutism is the most visible and common presenting complaint leading women to seek medical attention, making it the clinical entry point for diagnosing underlying conditions including PCOS, non-classical CAH and androgen-secreting tumours.<br><br>Galactorrhoea (B) and hyperprolactinaemia (C) result from elevated prolactin, not androgen excess. Primary amenorrhoea (D) occurs from completely absent HPG axis activation in conditions like Turner syndrome, not typically from hyperandrogenism-related ovarian dysfunction which usually causes secondary amenorrhoea or oligomenorrhoea.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with PCOS develops chronic anovulation due to hormonal imbalance. Which specific hormonal change is most responsible?',o:['Decreased FSH','Increased LH stimulation of androgen production','Increased prolactin','Decreased estrogen'],a:1,
e:`Increased LH stimulation of theca cell androgen production is the most directly responsible hormonal change for the chronic anovulation of PCOS. Elevated LH drives excess androstenedione and testosterone from theca cells via amplified CYP17A1 activity. These androgens overwhelm granulosa cell aromatase capacity, create an androgen-dominant intra-follicular environment, and arrest follicular development before any follicle achieves dominant status and generates sufficient oestradiol for the positive feedback LH surge.<br><br>The androgen excess further amplifies anovulation by suppressing FSH receptor expression on granulosa cells and directly inhibiting granulosa cell proliferation, creating a vicious cycle of androgen accumulation and progressive follicular arrest that maintains the chronic anovulatory state characteristic of PCOS.<br><br>Decreased FSH (A) contributes but is secondary to the elevated LH:FSH ratio. Increased prolactin (C) is not a primary PCOS mechanism. Decreased oestrogen (D) is a consequence of failed folliculogenesis rather than the primary driver of anovulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman presents with infertility due to estrogen deficiency from impaired granulosa cell function. Which phase of the menstrual cycle is primarily affected?',o:['Follicular phase','Luteal phase','Menstrual phase','Secretory phase'],a:0,
e:`Impaired granulosa cell function causing oestrogen deficiency primarily affects the follicular phase, when FSH-driven granulosa cell aromatase activity produces the rising oestradiol that drives endometrial proliferation, suppresses FSH via negative feedback for dominant follicle selection, and ultimately generates the positive feedback threshold oestradiol peak that triggers the mid-cycle LH surge and ovulation.<br><br>Without adequate granulosa cell oestrogen production during the follicular phase, the LH surge cannot be triggered, ovulation fails, no corpus luteum forms and the luteal phase cannot occur. Granulosa cell dysfunction therefore blocks the entire reproductive cycle at its earliest stage, preventing all downstream events from ovulation through to implantation.<br><br>Luteal phase (B) is driven by corpus luteum progesterone after ovulation. Menstrual phase (C) is the shedding consequence of luteal phase failure. Secretory phase (D) is an endometrial phase synonymous with the luteal phase, driven by progesterone not oestrogen.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with ovarian tumor secreting excess estrogen presents with abnormal uterine bleeding. Which is the most likely endometrial consequence?',o:['Endometrial atrophy','Secretory endometrium','Continuous endometrial proliferation','Immediate menstruation'],a:2,
e:`An oestrogen-secreting ovarian tumour (most commonly a granulosa cell tumour) produces autonomous excess oestrogen independent of the normal cyclic HPG axis regulation, causing continuous endometrial proliferation without the cyclic progesterone-driven secretory transformation and corpus luteum regression that normally limits proliferative growth and triggers menstrual shedding.<br><br>Prolonged continuous oestrogen stimulation from an oestrogen-secreting tumour is a potent cause of endometrial hyperplasia and carcinoma: granulosa cell tumours are associated with endometrial carcinoma in approximately 5-10% of cases. Serum oestradiol is markedly elevated and inhibin levels (a granulosa cell tumour marker) are elevated. Treatment is surgical removal of the tumour.<br><br>Endometrial atrophy (A) results from oestrogen deficiency, the opposite state. Secretory endometrium (B) requires progesterone from a corpus luteum, which is suppressed by the autonomous oestrogen excess. Immediate menstruation (D) requires progesterone withdrawal that cannot occur without prior progesterone exposure.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A gynecology resident explains that estrogen production in ovarian follicles depends on which model?',o:['Two-cell two-gonadotropin model','Single-cell model','Feedback inhibition model','Hormonal amplification model'],a:0,
e:`The two-cell two-gonadotropin model is the established framework for ovarian follicular oestrogen synthesis: LH-stimulated theca interna cells produce androstenedione and testosterone via CYP17A1, and FSH-stimulated granulosa cells aromatise these androgens to oestrone and oestradiol via CYP19A1. The obligate interdependence of both cell types and both gonadotropins means neither alone can produce significant oestrogen.<br><br>This model explains numerous clinical observations: FSH alone cannot produce oestradiol without LH-driven theca androgen substrate; LH alone cannot produce oestradiol without FSH-induced granulosa aromatase; aromatase inhibitors selectively block the granulosa cell step reducing oestradiol while leaving theca androgen production intact; and PCOS disrupts the model by amplifying theca androgen production beyond granulosa aromatase capacity.<br><br>Single-cell model (B) would require one cell type to perform complete oestrogen synthesis, which is not the case in the ovarian follicle. Feedback inhibition (C) and hormonal amplification (D) describe regulatory aspects, not the biosynthetic mechanism.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with steroidogenesis defect has low progesterone levels after ovulation. Which process is most directly impaired?',o:['Ovulation','Endometrial implantation','Follicular growth','Fertilization'],a:1,
e:`Low corpus luteum progesterone after ovulation directly impairs endometrial implantation by preventing adequate secretory transformation: the endometrium remains in a proliferative state rather than developing the tortuous glycogen-rich glands, stromal decidualisation, pinopode expression and implantation cytokine production required for the blastocyst to adhere, invade and establish placentation during the implantation window.<br><br>Mid-luteal progesterone below 30 nmol/L confirms luteal phase deficiency. The clinical consequence is repeated implantation failure despite successful ovulation and fertilisation: the embryo arrives in a receptive endometrium that fails to maintain the secretory state required for trophoblast invasion. Progesterone supplementation corrects this by directly providing the missing endometrial stimulus.<br><br>Ovulation (A) has already occurred as the corpus luteum formed. Follicular growth (C) is an FSH-driven follicular phase process preceding ovulation. Fertilisation (D) occurs in the fallopian tube at the time of ovulation, not requiring corpus luteum progesterone.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with infertility due to ovarian steroidogenic failure has decreased estrogen levels. Which secondary feature would develop?',o:['Breast development','Galactorrhoea','Hirsutism','Virilization'],a:0,
e:`Decreased oestrogen from ovarian steroidogenic failure prevents oestrogen-dependent secondary sexual characteristic development including thelarche. If the deficiency occurs before puberty, breast development does not occur or is arrested at an early Tanner stage. If it occurs after established puberty, breast tissue gradually involutes as oestrogen support for ductal and periductal fat maintenance is withdrawn.<br><br>Other consequences of oestrogen deficiency from ovarian failure include primary or secondary amenorrhoea, thin atrophic endometrium, vaginal atrophy, hot flushes, reduced bone density progressing to osteoporosis, increased cardiovascular risk and urogenital atrophy. Oestrogen replacement therapy addresses all these consequences simultaneously in premenopausal women with premature ovarian insufficiency.<br><br>Galactorrhoea (B) results from hyperprolactinaemia, not oestrogen deficiency directly. Hirsutism (C) and virilisation (D) result from androgen excess, not from oestrogen deficiency alone. Breast development (A) specifically requires oestrogen stimulation for initiation and maintenance.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with congenital enzyme defect affecting steroidogenesis presents with androgen excess. Which enzyme is most likely deficient?',o:['Lipase','Amylase','21-hydroxylase deficiency','Protease'],a:2,
e:`21-hydroxylase deficiency is the most common congenital enzyme defect affecting steroidogenesis and causing androgen excess, accounting for approximately 95% of congenital adrenal hyperplasia cases. The enzyme block prevents cortisol and aldosterone synthesis, causing ACTH elevation that drives precursor accumulation: 17-OH-progesterone is shunted to adrenal androgen synthesis producing excess androstenedione and testosterone causing virilisation.<br><br>Non-classical 21-hydroxylase deficiency, the milder form, presents in adolescence and adulthood with hirsutism, acne, irregular cycles and infertility resembling PCOS. Elevated early morning 17-OH-progesterone above 6 nmol/L or above 30 nmol/L with Synacthen stimulation distinguishes it from PCOS and indicates the diagnosis, which is treated with low-dose hydrocortisone suppressing excess ACTH and androgen production.<br><br>Lipase (A), amylase (B) and protease (D) are digestive enzymes with no role in steroidogenesis. None causes congenital androgen excess through enzyme deficiency.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with infertility has decreased estrogen due to impaired aromatization in granulosa cells. Which hormone deficiency drives this?',o:['FSH','LH','Prolactin','Progesterone'],a:0,
e:`FSH deficiency impairs aromatisation in granulosa cells because FSH is the specific inducer of aromatase (CYP19A1) gene transcription in these cells via cAMP-PKA signalling. Without adequate FSH stimulation, granulosa cell aromatase expression is insufficient to convert theca-derived androgens to oestradiol, resulting in decreased oestrogen production despite normal theca cell androgen substrate availability.<br><br>In clinical practice, FSH deficiency from hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism causes impaired follicular aromatase and low oestradiol. Treatment with recombinant FSH directly stimulates granulosa cell aromatase, restoring oestradiol production and follicular development. Monitoring serum oestradiol during FSH therapy assesses the aromatase response of stimulated granulosa cells.<br><br>LH (B) drives theca androgen production but does not directly induce granulosa cell aromatase. Prolactin (C) suppresses FSH and LH indirectly impairing aromatase, but is not itself the aromatase inducer. Progesterone (D) is the luteal phase product, not an aromatase inducer in granulosa cells.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with ovarian steroidogenic dysfunction has decreased progesterone levels in the luteal phase. Which phase of the menstrual cycle is most affected?',o:['Follicular phase','Secretory phase','Ovulatory phase','Menstrual phase'],a:1,
e:`Decreased progesterone in the luteal phase primarily affects the secretory phase of the endometrial cycle. The secretory phase is defined by progesterone-driven transformation of the oestrogen-primed endometrium: glandular secretory activity, stromal predecidualisation, spiral artery coiling and pinopode expression during the implantation window all depend on adequate luteal phase progesterone production from the corpus luteum.<br><br>Without sufficient progesterone from the corpus luteum, the endometrium fails to develop full secretory features, the implantation window is suboptimal, and embryo implantation fails even if fertilisation has occurred. Mid-luteal progesterone measurement on day 21 (above 30 nmol/L) is the standard test confirming both ovulation and adequate corpus luteum function during this secretory phase.<br><br>Follicular phase (A) is driven by oestradiol from developing follicles. Ovulatory phase (C) is the brief LH surge-to-rupture interval. Menstrual phase (D) is the consequence of insufficient luteal progesterone but is not the phase in which progesterone deficit primarily acts.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with excess androgen production develops menstrual irregularities. Which process is most directly disrupted?',o:['Ovulation','Implantation','Fertilization','Follicular growth only'],a:0,
e:`Androgen excess from PCOS-type theca cell overproduction disrupts ovulation by creating an intra-follicular androgen-dominant environment that impairs granulosa cell aromatase activity, prevents dominant follicle oestradiol amplification and blocks the final stages of follicular maturation required for the positive feedback LH surge. Multiple small androgen-arrested follicles accumulate while none achieves dominance and ovulation.<br><br>The menstrual irregularities in hyperandrogenism are a direct consequence of chronic anovulation: without regular ovulation and corpus luteum formation, cycles lack the progesterone-driven secretory phase and predictable menstruation from corpus luteum regression. Instead, irregular shedding of the chronically oestrogen-exposed endometrium produces the oligomenorrhoea or amenorrhoea characteristic of anovulatory states.<br><br>Implantation (B) cannot fail from androgen excess if ovulation has not occurred in the first place. Fertilisation (C) similarly requires prior ovulation. Follicular growth (D) does occur with multiple small follicles in PCOS, but the terminal stage of dominant follicle selection and ovulation is the specifically disrupted process.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A reproductive endocrinologist explains that ovarian steroidogenesis involves sequential enzymatic steps. Which outcome is most important for fertility?',o:['Cortisol production','Prolactin secretion','Infertility due to anovulation','Oestrogen and progesterone production for folliculogenesis'],a:3,
e:`The most important fertility outcome of ovarian steroidogenesis is oestrogen and progesterone production supporting folliculogenesis, ovulation and the luteal phase. Oestradiol from follicular granulosa cells drives follicular maturation, endometrial proliferation, the positive feedback LH surge and ovulation. Progesterone from the corpus luteum supports endometrial secretory transformation and implantation.<br><br>Without coordinated oestradiol and progesterone production through the two-cell mechanism, the sequential folliculogenesis, ovulation and implantation required for conception cannot occur. The clinical manifestation of failed ovarian steroidogenesis is anovulatory infertility, demonstrating how the entire reproductive process depends on intact steroidogenic enzyme cascades in both theca and granulosa cells.<br><br>Cortisol production (A) is an adrenal function. Prolactin secretion (B) is an anterior pituitary function. Infertility from anovulation (C) is the consequence of failed steroidogenesis, but oestrogen and progesterone production for folliculogenesis is the specific steroidogenesis outcome that fertility most directly depends upon.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The rate-limiting step in gonadal steroidogenesis is the conversion of cholesterol to:',o:['Pregnenolone by cholesterol desmolase (CYP11A1)','Progesterone by 3-beta HSD','Androstenedione by CYP17A1','Oestradiol by aromatase'],a:0,
e:`The conversion of cholesterol to pregnenolone by CYP11A1 (cholesterol side-chain cleavage enzyme) in the inner mitochondrial membrane is the rate-limiting step of steroidogenesis in all steroidogenic tissues. This step requires transport of cholesterol from the outer to inner mitochondrial membrane by StAR protein, making StAR-mediated cholesterol transport the acute regulatory point for hormonal stimulation of steroidogenesis.<br><br>Gonadotropin-stimulated cAMP production rapidly increases StAR gene transcription and protein phosphorylation within minutes, dramatically accelerating cholesterol delivery to CYP11A1 and the rate of pregnenolone production. This explains why gonadotropin stimulation produces rapid increases in steroid output without requiring new CYP enzyme synthesis.<br><br>Progesterone production by 3beta-HSD (B), androgen production by CYP17A1 (C) and oestrogen production by aromatase (D) are downstream steps in the steroidogenic cascade, all occurring after and regulated by the rate-limiting CYP11A1 step.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'In ovarian steroidogenesis, which enzyme converts androstenedione to estrone in granulosa cells?',o:['3-beta HSD','21-hydroxylase','Aromatase','11-beta hydroxylase'],a:2,
e:`Aromatase (CYP19A1) catalyses the aromatisation of the androgen A-ring, converting androstenedione to oestrone and testosterone to oestradiol through a three-step oxidative reaction requiring NADPH and cytochrome P450 reductase. This enzyme is expressed exclusively in granulosa cells within ovarian follicles and is the final committed step of oestrogen biosynthesis in the ovary.<br><br>Aromatase is also expressed in adipose tissue (postmenopausal oestrogen source), brain (local neuroactive oestrogen), bone and liver. The dual roles of aromatase in multiple tissues make it a therapeutically important target: aromatase inhibitors used in breast cancer treatment and ovulation induction have tissue effects beyond the ovary that must be considered in clinical management.<br><br>3-beta HSD (A) converts pregnenolone to progesterone, an earlier steroidogenic step. 21-hydroxylase (B) is an adrenal enzyme converting 17-OH-progesterone to cortisol precursors. 11-beta hydroxylase (D) is an adrenal enzyme in the glucocorticoid synthesis pathway.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'In the two-cell two-gonadotropin model, which cells primarily produce androgen precursors for estrogen synthesis?',o:['Granulosa cells','Corpus luteum cells','Stromal cells','Theca interna cells'],a:3,
e:`Theca interna cells are the primary producers of androgen precursors (androstenedione and testosterone) for ovarian oestrogen synthesis. Under LH stimulation, theca cells activate CYP17A1 to convert cholesterol-derived pregnenolone and progesterone to androstenedione through the delta-4 pathway. These androgens diffuse across the basement membrane to granulosa cells for FSH-induced aromatase conversion to oestrogens.<br><br>The two-cell model demonstrates that theca and granulosa cells have complementary and interdependent steroidogenic functions: neither can produce oestrogen alone. This cooperative arrangement is reflected in clinical practice where both FSH (granulosa aromatase induction) and LH (theca androgen production) are required for effective ovarian stimulation in hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism requiring both gonadotropin injections for successful IVF.<br><br>Granulosa cells (A) aromatise androgens to oestrogens but cannot produce androgens due to absent CYP17A1. Corpus luteum cells (B) produce progesterone post-ovulation. Stromal cells (C) have minimal LH-responsive androgen production capacity.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Which ovarian hormone is responsible for negative feedback inhibition of LH and FSH during the luteal phase?',o:['Estrogen alone','Progesterone','LH itself','Oxytocin'],a:1,
e:`Progesterone from the corpus luteum is the dominant hormone responsible for the negative feedback suppression of LH and FSH during the luteal phase. Progesterone suppresses GnRH pulse frequency by inhibiting hypothalamic kisspeptin neurons in the arcuate nucleus and reduces pituitary sensitivity to GnRH, combined with oestradiol negative feedback, maintaining gonadotropin levels below the threshold for new follicular recruitment throughout the 14-day luteal phase.<br><br>This progesterone-dominant luteal phase negative feedback is the pharmacological basis of combined oral contraceptives: sustained progestogen plus oestrogen maintains a luteal-phase-like hormonal milieu throughout the active pill cycle, reliably suppressing GnRH pulsatility and preventing follicular development and ovulation even during 7-day hormone-free intervals.<br><br>Oestrogen alone (A) provides some negative feedback but progesterone is the dominant luteal phase suppressor of GnRH pulsatility. LH itself (C) does not self-suppress. Oxytocin (D) stimulates contractions and milk ejection without suppressing gonadotropins.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Inhibin secreted by granulosa cells primarily suppresses secretion of which pituitary hormone?',o:['LH','Prolactin','TSH','FSH'],a:3,
e:`Inhibin B from granulosa cells of developing follicles selectively suppresses pituitary FSH secretion by inhibiting FSH beta-subunit gene transcription at the pituitary, without significantly affecting LH. This specificity allows the dominant follicle to suppress competing follicles by reducing systemic FSH below their survival threshold while tonic LH continues supporting theca androgen production throughout the follicular phase.<br><br>The clinical utility of inhibin B measurement: day-3 serum inhibin B reflects granulosa cell mass and ovarian reserve. In declining ovarian reserve, granulosa cell numbers fall, inhibin B falls, and FSH rises disproportionately as this selective FSH suppression is lost. This is the basis of day-3 FSH testing as an ovarian reserve marker and the explanation for why FSH rises more than LH with age-related ovarian decline.<br><br>LH (A) is not suppressed by inhibin B. Prolactin (B) is regulated by dopamine and TRH. TSH (C) is regulated by TRH and thyroid hormone feedback. None is the primary target of granulosa cell inhibin B.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A 26-year-old woman presents with infertility and irregular cycles. Laboratory evaluation shows elevated LH:FSH ratio and hyperandrogenism. What is the most likely diagnosis?',o:['Hyperprolactinemia','Turner syndrome','PCOS','Sheehan syndrome'],a:2,
e:`Elevated LH:FSH ratio combined with hyperandrogenism and irregular anovulatory cycles in a 26-year-old is the diagnostic triad of PCOS. The elevated LH:FSH reflects accelerated hypothalamic GnRH pulsatility preferentially driving LH, causing theca cell CYP17A1 amplification and androgen excess. Rotterdam criteria require two of three features: oligo/anovulation, hyperandrogenism and polycystic ovarian morphology for formal diagnosis.<br><br>Infertility in PCOS results from chronic anovulation from androgen-mediated follicular arrest. Management for fertility: letrozole or clomifene for ovulation induction (letrozole now preferred for lower multiple pregnancy rates), gonadotropin injections for clomifene-resistant cases, and IVF for failed ovulation induction. Weight loss in overweight women can restore spontaneous ovulation.<br><br>Hyperprolactinaemia (A) causes low FSH and LH from GnRH suppression. Turner syndrome (B) causes high FSH and LH with low oestrogen from ovarian failure. Sheehan syndrome (D) causes pan-hypopituitarism with low gonadotropins.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with ovarian failure has markedly elevated FSH and LH levels but low estrogen. Which pathophysiological process explains this?',o:['Decreased GnRH secretion','Loss of negative feedback from ovarian steroids','Increased prolactin suppressing ovaries','Positive feedback from low estrogen'],a:1,
e:`Ovarian failure eliminates oestradiol and inhibin B production. Loss of oestradiol negative feedback at hypothalamus and pituitary removes the tonic suppression of GnRH, FSH and LH secretion, while loss of inhibin B-mediated selective FSH suppression from absent granulosa cells removes the additional specific FSH brake, causing compensatory elevation of both gonadotropins as the pituitary maximally stimulates the unresponsive ovary.<br><br>The markedly elevated FSH and LH with low oestradiol pattern is the biochemical hallmark of hypergonadotrophic hypogonadism from ovarian failure. A single FSH above 25 IU/L with symptoms warrants concern; two values above this threshold 4-6 weeks apart with amenorrhoea confirms premature ovarian insufficiency in women under 40, requiring urgent investigation for aetiology and immediate oestrogen replacement.<br><br>Decreased GnRH (A) would produce low rather than elevated FSH and LH. Prolactin suppressing ovaries (C) is not the mechanism; prolactin suppresses GnRH reducing FSH and LH. Positive feedback from low oestrogen (D) is not how positive feedback works.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman presents with virilization and an ovarian tumor producing excessive androgens. Which androgen is primarily responsible?',o:['Testosterone','Progesterone','Estrogen','Cortisol'],a:0,
e:`Testosterone is the primary androgen responsible for virilisation from androgen-secreting ovarian tumours including Sertoli-Leydig cell tumours (arrhenoblastomas) and steroid cell tumours. Markedly elevated circulating testosterone causes rapid-onset virilisation: clitoromegaly, deepening of the voice, breast atrophy, male-pattern alopecia and amenorrhoea from testosterone-mediated suppression of the HPG axis.<br><br>Serum testosterone above 5 nmol/L warrants urgent investigation for an androgen-secreting source. Pelvic ultrasound identifies most ovarian sources. The rapidity of virilisation onset distinguishes tumour-related from PCOS hyperandrogenism: tumours produce virilisation over months whereas PCOS-related hirsutism develops gradually over years. Unilateral oophorectomy is both diagnostic and curative for ovarian androgen-secreting tumours.<br><br>Progesterone (B) is the corpus luteum product without virilising effects. Oestrogen (C) excess causes endometrial stimulation. Cortisol (D) excess causes Cushing syndrome characterised by obesity, striae and hypertension rather than frank androgenic virilisation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with congenital aromatase deficiency presents with virilization and low estrogen. Which specific enzymatic reaction is impaired?',o:['Conversion of progesterone to androgens','Conversion of androgens to estrogens','Conversion of cholesterol to pregnenolone','Conversion of estrogen to cortisol'],a:1,
e:`Congenital aromatase deficiency impairs the conversion of androgens (androstenedione and testosterone) to oestrogens (oestrone and oestradiol) by CYP19A1 in granulosa cells. The resulting androgen accumulation causes virilisation while the oestrogen deficiency causes failed puberty, primary amenorrhoea and osteoporosis from absent oestrogen-mediated bone mineralisation.<br><br>The diagnosis is confirmed by markedly elevated androgens (androstenedione, testosterone), very low or undetectable oestrogens, massively elevated FSH and LH from absent oestrogen negative feedback, and characteristic large multicystic ovaries on ultrasound from gonadotropin stimulation of follicles unable to complete oestrogen synthesis. CYP19A1 gene mutation analysis provides genetic confirmation.<br><br>Conversion of progesterone to androgens (A) via CYP17A1 is intact in aromatase deficiency, explaining why androgens accumulate. Conversion of cholesterol to pregnenolone (C) by CYP11A1 is the rate-limiting step, unaffected by aromatase deficiency. Oestrogen is not a cortisol precursor (D).<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with luteal phase defect presents with infertility due to inadequate progesterone. Which structure should be targeted for treatment?',o:['Dominant follicle','Theca cells','Corpus luteum','Ovarian stroma'],a:2,
e:`The corpus luteum is the target for treatment in luteal phase defect: it is the source of luteal phase progesterone, and its dysfunction causes the inadequate progesterone production impairing endometrial secretory transformation and implantation. Treatment options target the corpus luteum either by providing LH-receptor-mediated support (hCG injections) or by bypassing corpus luteum dysfunction with direct vaginal progesterone supplementation.<br><br>Vaginal micronised progesterone (Cyclogest, Utrogestan) is preferred in clinical practice as it directly provides the missing progesterone signal at the endometrium regardless of corpus luteum function. In all IVF cycles, progesterone supplementation is standard because pituitary downregulation universally impairs corpus luteum LH receptor stimulation, creating iatrogenic corpus luteum insufficiency.<br><br>Dominant follicle (A) and theca cells (B) are follicular phase structures preceding corpus luteum formation. Ovarian stroma (D) does not produce luteal phase progesterone and is not the therapeutic target.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with hyperprolactinemia develops decreased estrogen production and infertility. Which is the primary mechanism?',o:['Direct inhibition of ovarian steroidogenesis','Increased LH secretion','Increased FSH secretion','Suppression of GnRH secretion'],a:3,
e:`Hyperprolactinaemia suppresses hypothalamic GnRH secretion through opioidergic enhancement and kisspeptin neuron inhibition, reducing GnRH pulse frequency below the threshold for adequate FSH and LH secretion. Without gonadotropin stimulation, the two-cell oestrogen synthesis mechanism fails: theca cells lack LH-driven androgen production and granulosa cells lack FSH-induced aromatase, causing oestradiol production to fall.<br><br>The mechanism is entirely mediated through hypothalamic GnRH suppression: prolactin has no established significant direct action on ovarian steroidogenesis. This is confirmed by the rapid restoration of oestradiol production, follicular development and ovulation when cabergoline normalises prolactin and restores GnRH pulsatility, FSH and LH within weeks of starting treatment.<br><br>Direct ovarian inhibition (A) is not the established mechanism. Increased LH (B) and increased FSH (C) are the opposite of what occurs; both gonadotropins are suppressed by the hyperprolactinaemia-induced GnRH reduction.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with PCOS has chronic anovulation due to excessive ovarian androgen production. Which ovarian cells are primarily responsible for this androgen excess?',o:['Granulosa cells','Corpus luteum cells','Theca interna cells','Oocytes'],a:2,
e:`Theca interna cells are primarily responsible for the androgen excess in PCOS. Elevated LH combined with hyperinsulinaemia amplifies CYP17A1 activity in theca cells, producing excess androstenedione and testosterone that exceed granulosa cell aromatase capacity. The accumulated androgens create an intra-follicular androgen-dominant environment that impairs granulosa cell proliferation, suppresses FSH receptor expression and arrests follicular development before dominant follicle status is achieved.<br><br>The central role of theca cells in PCOS androgen excess is confirmed by the effectiveness of LH-suppressing treatments (combined oral contraceptives, GnRH agonists) and insulin sensitisers (metformin) in reducing androgen levels and restoring ovulation, as both approaches target the theca cell androgen production mechanism.<br><br>Granulosa cells (A) aromatise androgens to oestrogens and their relative insufficiency worsens the androgen dominance but they are not the androgen source. Corpus luteum cells (B) are post-ovulatory. Oocytes (D) have no steroidogenic CYP17A1 activity.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with ovarian steroidogenesis defect presents with low estrogen levels. Which phase of the menstrual cycle would be most affected?',o:['Luteal phase','Proliferative phase','Ovulatory phase','Secretory phase'],a:1,
e:`Low oestrogen from ovarian steroidogenesis defect primarily affects the proliferative phase of the endometrial cycle, when oestradiol from developing follicles drives glandular and stromal proliferation, angiogenesis and endometrial thickening from menstrual minimum to the pre-ovulatory maximum of 8-12 mm. Without adequate oestradiol, the endometrium remains thin and atrophic, unable to achieve the development required for implantation.<br><br>The proliferative phase is also when rising oestradiol exerts the cycle-critical effects of inducing endometrial progesterone receptors (essential for subsequent secretory transformation) and generating the positive feedback LH surge threshold that triggers ovulation. Low oestrogen from steroidogenesis defect therefore disrupts multiple aspects of the proliferative phase simultaneously.<br><br>Luteal phase (A) and secretory phase (D) are driven by progesterone from the corpus luteum post-ovulation, which cannot form if oestrogen deficiency prevents the LH surge and ovulation. Ovulatory phase (C) fails as a direct consequence of insufficient oestradiol positive feedback.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A woman undergoing infertility treatment receives FSH injections. Which ovarian process is most directly stimulated?',o:['Ovulation','LH surge','Aromatization of androgens in granulosa cells','Corpus luteum regression'],a:2,
e:`FSH injections directly stimulate granulosa cell aromatase (CYP19A1) activity, driving the conversion of theca-derived androgens to oestradiol. FSH binds granulosa cell Gs-coupled receptors, activating cAMP-PKA which induces aromatase gene transcription and protein synthesis. The resulting oestradiol output drives follicular development, dominant follicle selection and the rising oestradiol that eventually generates the LH surge.<br><br>In ovulation induction protocols, recombinant FSH stimulates multiple granulosa cell populations simultaneously, producing multi-follicular development and multiple oestradiol-producing follicles. Serum oestradiol monitoring during stimulation reflects the combined aromatase activity of all stimulated follicles and guides dose adjustment to optimise response while avoiding hyperstimulation syndrome.<br><br>Ovulation (A) requires the LH surge triggered by sufficient oestradiol, a downstream consequence of FSH-stimulated aromatase. LH surge (B) is triggered by the oestradiol rise, not by FSH directly. Corpus luteum regression (D) follows the luteal phase and is unrelated to exogenous FSH.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with androgen-secreting ovarian tumor develops hirsutism and menstrual irregularities. Which process is most directly disrupted?',o:['Implantation','Fertilization','Follicular growth and ovulation','Menstruation'],a:3,
e:`Excess testosterone from an androgen-secreting ovarian tumour disrupts follicular growth and ovulation by creating an androgen-dominant ovarian environment that impairs granulosa cell aromatase function, arrests follicular maturation before dominant follicle selection, and suppresses the LH surge through HPG axis disruption from high androgen concentrations. The menstrual irregularities result from this anovulation.<br><br>Additionally, very high testosterone levels from rapidly secreting tumours suppress GnRH pulsatility and gonadotropin secretion through androgen receptor effects at the hypothalamus, creating a secondary hypogonadotrophic picture on top of the direct ovarian effects of androgen excess. Surgical removal of the tumour rapidly restores ovulation and cycle regularity.<br><br>Implantation (A) and fertilisation (B) cannot be disrupted if ovulation has not occurred in the first place. Menstruation (D) is irregular as a consequence of anovulation rather than being the directly disrupted process.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 34-year-old woman presents with infertility and luteal phase deficiency. Which treatment is most appropriate?',o:['Clomiphene citrate','hCG supplementation','Estrogen only','FSH injection'],a:1,
e:`hCG supplementation in the luteal phase stimulates corpus luteum LH receptors, enhancing endogenous progesterone production and providing luteotrophic support that may improve luteal phase adequacy. However, in contemporary practice vaginal micronised progesterone is the more widely used and evidence-based first-line treatment for luteal phase deficiency, providing direct endometrial progesterone supplementation without requiring corpus luteum responsiveness.<br><br>For recurrent luteal phase defect in natural conception attempts, progesterone supplementation is started from ovulation confirmation (positive urinary LH or BBT rise) and continued to the expected menstrual date or through the first trimester if pregnancy is confirmed. The treatment is empirical as the aetiology of most luteal phase deficiency cases is not precisely established.<br><br>Clomiphene citrate (A) induces ovulation in anovulatory women but does not specifically treat luteal phase deficiency. Oestrogen only (C) drives proliferative phase but cannot address the luteal phase progesterone deficit. FSH injections (D) stimulate follicular development but have no direct corpus luteum support function.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with ovarian tumor secreting excessive estrogen presents with abnormal uterine bleeding. What is the most likely endometrial finding?',o:['Atrophic endometrium','Decidualized endometrium','Continuous endometrial proliferation without secretory transformation','Secretory endometrium'],a:2,
e:`An oestrogen-secreting ovarian tumour, most commonly a granulosa cell tumour, produces autonomous oestrogen excess independent of cyclic HPG axis regulation, causing continuous endometrial proliferation without the cyclic progesterone from corpus luteum formation that normally limits proliferative growth and triggers secretory transformation and controlled menstruation.<br><br>The continuous oestrogen stimulus drives progressive endometrial hyperplasia: without progesterone, the endometrium periodically outgrows its blood supply and sheds irregularly, causing the abnormal uterine bleeding. Granulosa cell tumours are associated with endometrial carcinoma in approximately 5-10% of cases, making endometrial assessment mandatory. Tumour markers include inhibin and anti-Mullerian hormone elevated by granulosa cell tumours.<br><br>Atrophic endometrium (A) requires oestrogen deficiency. Decidualised endometrium (B) requires high progesterone from the luteal phase or pregnancy. Secretory endometrium (D) requires cyclic progesterone from corpus luteum formation, which is suppressed by autonomous tumour oestrogen.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with infertility has reduced estrogen synthesis due to impaired granulosa cell function. Which gonadotropin is most critical for restoring this?',o:['LH','FSH','Prolactin','TSH'],a:1,
e:`FSH is the most critical gonadotropin for restoring granulosa cell oestrogen synthesis because FSH directly induces aromatase (CYP19A1) gene transcription in granulosa cells via cAMP-PKA signalling. Without FSH, granulosa cells cannot aromatise theca-derived androgens to oestradiol regardless of LH-driven androgen substrate availability, making FSH the rate-determining gonadotropin for the granulosa cell component of oestrogen synthesis.<br><br>In clinical practice, recombinant FSH (follitropin alfa, follitropin beta) by daily subcutaneous injection directly restores granulosa cell aromatase activity in women with hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism or poor ovarian response. Serum oestradiol monitoring during FSH therapy directly assesses the granulosa cell aromatase response, with rising oestradiol confirming adequate FSH-driven aromatisation.<br><br>LH (A) is critical for theca androgen production but does not itself induce granulosa cell aromatase. Prolactin (C) suppresses the HPG axis. TSH (D) regulates thyroid function with no direct role in granulosa cell aromatase induction.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with steroidogenic dysfunction in ovarian follicles has reduced estrogen production. Which enzyme is most likely to be deficient?',o:['Lipase','Amylase','Aromatase','Protease'],a:2,
e:`Aromatase (CYP19A1) deficiency is the most likely enzyme deficiency causing reduced oestrogen production specifically in ovarian follicles. Aromatase is the only enzyme converting androgens to oestrogens and is expressed exclusively in granulosa cells within follicles in the ovary. Its deficiency or dysfunction from genetic mutation, insufficient FSH induction or inhibitor exposure specifically impairs the final oestrogen synthesis step.<br><br>Granulosa cell aromatase activity can be insufficient due to: genetic CYP19A1 mutations (congenital aromatase deficiency), inadequate FSH stimulation (hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism), pharmacological aromatase inhibitors (letrozole, anastrozole used therapeutically), or intrinsic granulosa cell dysfunction from diminished ovarian reserve with reduced functional granulosa cell mass.<br><br>Lipase (A), amylase (B) and protease (D) are digestive enzymes involved in lipid, carbohydrate and protein digestion respectively. None is involved in ovarian steroidogenesis or oestrogen biosynthesis in follicles.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'A reproductive endocrinologist explains that ovarian steroidogenesis requires coordinated theca and granulosa cell activity. What is the clinical consequence when this coordination fails?',o:['Increased fertility','Normal menstrual cycles','Decreased prolactin levels','Infertility due to anovulation'],a:3,
e:`When theca-granulosa coordination fails, oestrogen synthesis is impaired because neither cell type can complete oestrogen production alone. Without adequate oestradiol from the two-cell mechanism, dominant follicle selection fails, the LH surge positive feedback threshold is not reached, ovulation does not occur and anovulatory infertility results as the primary clinical consequence of failed theca-granulosa coordination.<br><br>The PCOS pattern demonstrates how disruption of one component affects the whole system: excess LH-driven theca androgen production exceeding granulosa aromatase capacity fails the two-cell mechanism in one direction, while aromatase deficiency in which granulosa cells cannot process normal theca androgen substrate fails it from the other direction. Both result in anovulatory infertility through different mechanisms.<br><br>Increased fertility (A) and normal menstrual cycles (B) are the opposite of what occurs with failed theca-granulosa coordination. Decreased prolactin (C) is unrelated to ovarian steroidogenesis coordination failure.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Physiology of the Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},

{q:'Menopause is clinically defined as absence of menstruation for:',o:['6 months','12 months','3 months','24 months'],a:1,
e:`Menopause is clinically defined as 12 consecutive months of amenorrhoea in the absence of other pathological or physiological causes, after which the last menstrual period is retrospectively designated as the date of menopause. This 12-month threshold reflects the time required to confirm that the cessation of menstruation represents permanent ovarian follicular exhaustion rather than transient disruption.<br><br>In clinical practice, menopause is a retrospective diagnosis: a woman cannot know she has reached menopause until she has been amenorrhoeic for 12 months. This definition has important clinical implications for contraception advice (continue for 12 months after last period if over 50, 24 months if under 50), HRT initiation and investigation of vaginal bleeding which is postmenopausal if it occurs after the 12-month amenorrhoea period.<br><br>6 months (A) is insufficient as ovarian function may transiently cease and return in the perimenopause. 3 months (C) is secondary amenorrhoea. 24 months (D) is more than required by the consensus clinical definition.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The average age of natural menopause worldwide is approximately:',o:['50 years','45 years','55 years','60 years'],a:0,
e:`The average age of natural menopause is approximately 50-51 years in Western and South Asian populations, with a normal range of 45-55 years. Menopause before age 40 is defined as premature ovarian insufficiency, before age 45 as early menopause. Genetics is the strongest determinant of menopause timing, with maternal age at menopause being the best predictor for an individual woman.<br><br>Smoking is associated with menopause approximately 1-2 years earlier than non-smokers, attributed to the anti-oestrogenic effects of smoking and acceleration of follicular atresia. Contrary to popular belief, parity, OCP use, age at menarche and socioeconomic factors have minimal effect on menopause timing in most studies.<br><br>45 years (B) would represent early menopause. 55 years (C) and 60 years (D) are above average and represent natural menopause occurring within the normal late range. None represents the average timing of menopause in the general population.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The most important hormonal change occurring during menopause is:',o:['Increased progesterone secretion','Increased prolactin levels','Decreased estrogen secretion','Increased androgen levels'],a:2,
e:`Decreased oestrogen secretion is the most important hormonal change of menopause, resulting from the exhaustion of ovarian follicular reserve and the progressive failure of folliculogenesis. As oestradiol production falls, the clinical consequences of oestrogen deficiency develop: vasomotor symptoms, urogenital atrophy, bone resorption exceeding formation, accelerated cardiovascular risk and adverse metabolic changes.<br><br>Oestrogen decline removes the tonic negative feedback on the hypothalamic-pituitary axis, causing compensatory elevation of FSH and LH. The disproportionate FSH rise (because inhibin B from absent granulosa cells selectively suppressed FSH) creates the characteristic biochemical pattern of postmenopausal hypergonadotrophic hypo-oestrogenism that defines menopause biochemically.<br><br>Progesterone (A) also falls as ovulation ceases and no corpus luteum forms. Prolactin (B) falls rather than rises with declining oestradiol. Androgen levels (D) fall modestly as ovarian theca cell androgen production decreases, though adrenal androgens persist.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which gonadotropin level rises significantly during menopause due to loss of ovarian negative feedback?',o:['LH only','Prolactin','TSH','FSH'],a:3,
e:`FSH rises most significantly during menopause, disproportionately more than LH, because loss of inhibin B from absent granulosa cells selectively removes the specific FSH-suppressing signal that kept FSH particularly restrained throughout reproductive life. Both FSH and LH rise as oestradiol negative feedback is removed, but FSH elevation is earlier, greater and more diagnostically sensitive for declining ovarian reserve.<br><br>Postmenopausal FSH levels typically exceed 25-30 IU/L, often reaching 50-100 IU/L, compared with LH which rises to approximately 15-40 IU/L. Day-3 FSH measurement exploits this selective early FSH rise as an ovarian reserve marker in reproductive-age women: rising day-3 FSH above 10-12 IU/L signals declining granulosa cell inhibin B production and diminishing reserve.<br><br>LH only (A) rises but FSH rises more dramatically and earlier. Prolactin (B) falls with declining oestradiol as oestrogen is a prolactin stimulant. TSH (C) is regulated by the independent HPT axis and does not rise at menopause.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The most common early symptom of menopause is:',o:['Vaginal atrophy','Hot flushes','Osteoporosis','Urinary incontinence'],a:1,
e:`Hot flushes (vasomotor symptoms) are the most common early symptom of menopause, affecting approximately 75-80% of perimenopausal and postmenopausal women. They result from hypothalamic thermoregulatory instability caused by oestrogen withdrawal: the thermoneutral zone narrows and small elevations in core temperature trigger inappropriate heat dissipation responses including cutaneous vasodilatation, sweating and the characteristic flushing sensation typically lasting 1-5 minutes.<br><br>Hot flushes typically begin in the perimenopause before the last menstrual period and peak in the early postmenopausal period. Approximately 25% of women have severe flushes significantly impairing quality of life. HRT is the most effective treatment for vasomotor symptoms, with oestrogen rapidly and effectively controlling hot flushes in the majority of women.<br><br>Vaginal atrophy (A) and urinary incontinence (D) are later genitourinary syndrome of menopause symptoms developing months to years after menopause. Osteoporosis (C) is a long-term consequence developing over years of oestrogen deficiency following menopause.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Vasomotor symptoms during menopause occur primarily due to:',o:['Increased progesterone','Increased LH only','Increased FSH only','Decreased estrogen levels'],a:3,
e:`Decreased oestrogen at menopause causes vasomotor instability by narrowing the hypothalamic thermoregulatory thermoneutral zone. When core body temperature rises even slightly above the narrowed threshold, the hypothalamus triggers inappropriate heat dissipation responses: cutaneous vasodilatation causing the flush, sweating and sometimes subsequent chilling. Noradrenergic pathways activated by oestrogen withdrawal, particularly in the hypothalamic preoptic area, mediate this thermoregulatory instability.<br><br>The specific mechanism involves alpha-2 adrenergic receptor changes in the hypothalamic thermoregulatory centre from oestrogen withdrawal, which increases noradrenaline fluctuations that trigger thermoregulatory responses. This explains why clonidine (an alpha-2 agonist reducing noradrenaline release) has modest efficacy for hot flushes and SSRIs reducing central noradrenergic tone provide partial benefit without oestrogen replacement.<br><br>Increased progesterone (A) does not cause vasomotor symptoms. Increased LH only (B) and increased FSH only (C) are consequences of the oestrogen fall rather than causes of vasomotor instability; the symptoms are from oestrogen deficiency itself.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which type of menopause occurs due to bilateral oophorectomy?',o:['Premature menopause','Natural menopause','Surgical menopause','Medical menopause'],a:2,
e:`Surgical menopause results from bilateral oophorectomy (removal of both ovaries), which eliminates ovarian oestrogen production abruptly rather than the gradual decline of natural menopause. The sudden oestrogen withdrawal typically produces more severe and acute menopausal symptoms than natural menopause, particularly hot flushes and genitourinary symptoms, because the gradual central adaptation to declining oestrogen that occurs in natural menopause is absent.<br><br>Women undergoing bilateral oophorectomy before the natural age of menopause should receive HRT until at least the average age of natural menopause (approximately 51 years) to prevent the long-term consequences of premature oestrogen deficiency including osteoporosis and cardiovascular disease. The cardiovascular benefits of oestrogen replacement in this context are well established.<br><br>Premature menopause (A) refers to spontaneous ovarian failure before age 40 (premature ovarian insufficiency). Natural menopause (B) is physiological follicular exhaustion after age 45. Medical menopause (D) is reversible gonadal suppression from GnRH agonists or other medications.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Premature menopause refers to menopause occurring before the age of:',o:['30 years','35 years','55 years','40 years'],a:3,
e:`Premature ovarian insufficiency (previously called premature menopause) is defined as menopause occurring before age 40 years, characterised by amenorrhoea, hypo-oestrogenic symptoms and elevated FSH above 25 IU/L on two occasions 4-6 weeks apart. It affects approximately 1% of women under 40 and has significant implications for fertility, bone health, cardiovascular risk and overall wellbeing requiring prompt intervention.<br><br>Causes include genetic factors (Turner syndrome, FMR1 premutation, autoimmune polyglandular syndromes), autoimmune oophoritis, iatrogenic causes (chemotherapy, radiotherapy, oophorectomy) and idiopathic. Investigation includes karyotype, FMR1 premutation testing, autoimmune screen and bone density measurement. Oestrogen replacement is essential until the natural age of menopause.<br><br>30 years (A) and 35 years (B) are stricter cutoffs not used in the standard definition. 55 years (C) is above average menopause age, not premature. 40 years (D) is the accepted upper age boundary for the premature ovarian insufficiency diagnosis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Postmenopausal women are at increased risk of osteoporosis mainly due to deficiency of:',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Prolactin','LH'],a:1,
e:`Oestrogen deficiency at menopause accelerates bone resorption relative to bone formation by removing oestrogen's inhibitory effect on osteoclastogenesis. Oestrogen normally suppresses RANKL expression on osteoblasts and promotes osteoclast apoptosis; its deficiency causes uncoupling of bone remodelling with resorption exceeding formation, resulting in net bone loss of approximately 2-3% per year in the first 5-10 postmenopausal years.<br><br>Accelerated postmenopausal bone loss explains why women who undergo menopause before 40 have significantly higher lifetime fracture risk than those with menopause at the average age. Oestrogen replacement therapy prevents this accelerated bone loss and reduces fracture risk in early postmenopausal women, with bone protection maintained throughout HRT use and for some years after cessation.<br><br>Progesterone (A) contributes to bone metabolism via progesterone receptor effects on osteoblasts but oestrogen is the dominant bone-protective ovarian hormone. Prolactin (C) excess actually reduces bone density by suppressing oestradiol. LH (D) elevation at menopause does not protect bone.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which cardiovascular risk factor increases after menopause due to hormonal changes?',o:['Decreased LDL cholesterol','Decreased blood pressure','Atherosclerosis','Decreased triglycerides'],a:2,
e:`Atherosclerosis risk increases after menopause due to the loss of oestrogen's cardioprotective effects: oestrogen increases HDL cholesterol, decreases LDL cholesterol, maintains arterial wall compliance, promotes endothelial nitric oxide production causing vasodilatation, and reduces inflammatory markers. Loss of these oestrogen-mediated effects at menopause shifts the cardiovascular risk profile adversely.<br><br>The metabolic consequences of oestrogen deficiency at menopause include: increased LDL and total cholesterol, decreased HDL, increased triglycerides, increased central adiposity, increased insulin resistance and increased blood pressure. These changes collectively increase the 10-year cardiovascular risk, explaining the convergence of male and female cardiovascular event rates that occurs in the postmenopausal decade.<br><br>Decreased LDL (A) and decreased triglycerides (D) are the opposite of what occurs. Decreased blood pressure (B) is also the opposite; postmenopausal oestrogen deficiency is associated with increased rather than decreased blood pressure from loss of oestrogen-mediated vascular protection.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The main indication for hormone replacement therapy is:',o:['Breast cancer treatment','Relief of menopausal symptoms','Contraception','Prevention of all malignancies'],a:1,
e:`Relief of menopausal symptoms is the primary indication for HRT. Hot flushes, night sweats, sleep disturbance, vaginal dryness, dyspareunia and urinary symptoms significantly impair quality of life in many perimenopausal and postmenopausal women. HRT is the most effective treatment for vasomotor symptoms, reducing hot flush frequency by approximately 75% compared with placebo, and the most effective treatment for genitourinary syndrome of menopause.<br><br>NICE guidelines recommend offering HRT to women with menopausal symptoms after discussing individual benefits and risks. Additional benefits of HRT include prevention of postmenopausal osteoporosis and fractures, and recent evidence suggests cardiovascular benefit when started within 10 years of menopause or before age 60 (the healthy window of opportunity hypothesis).<br><br>Breast cancer treatment (A) is a contraindication rather than indication for oestrogen-containing HRT. Contraception (C) is provided by completely different hormone formulations. Prevention of all malignancies (D) is not the indication; HRT has complex oncological effects varying by tumour type.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'In women with intact uterus receiving HRT, progesterone is added primarily to:',o:['Improve libido','Reduce hot flushes','Treat bone loss','Prevent endometrial hyperplasia'],a:3,
e:`Progesterone is added to oestrogen HRT in women with an intact uterus specifically to prevent oestrogen-induced endometrial hyperplasia and carcinoma. Oestrogen alone causes continuous endometrial proliferation without the cyclic progesterone-driven secretory transformation and programmed endometrial regression that protects against hyperplasia in natural cycles. Combined HRT with progesterone provides this essential endometrial protection.<br><br>Progesterone in combined HRT can be given cyclically (withdrawal bleed each month) or continuously (no bleed). The levonorgestrel IUS provides highly effective local endometrial protection with minimal systemic absorption, making it an attractive progesterone component for women preferring to avoid regular bleeds or systemic progestogen side effects from oral formulations.<br><br>Improving libido (A) and reducing hot flushes (B) are primarily oestrogen effects; progesterone does not contribute significantly to either. Treating bone loss (C) is primarily an oestrogen effect; progesterone has modest independent bone effects but that is not the primary reason for its inclusion.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Estrogen-only HRT is generally recommended for women who have undergone:',o:['Menopause at normal age','Surgical menopause only','Hysterectomy','Premature menopause'],a:2,
e:`Oestrogen-only HRT is appropriate for women who have undergone hysterectomy, as they have no uterus and therefore no risk of oestrogen-induced endometrial hyperplasia or carcinoma. Adding progestogen provides no benefit in hysterectomised women but does introduce its potential adverse effects including breast cancer risk and side effects such as bloating, mood changes and irregular bleeding.<br><br>Oestrogen-only HRT (most commonly oral oestradiol, conjugated equine oestrogen or transdermal oestradiol) provides effective symptom relief and bone protection without the added breast cancer risk associated with combined oestrogen-progestogen HRT. The WHI study showed that oestrogen-only HRT (in hysterectomised women) had a non-significant reduction in breast cancer risk compared with placebo, in contrast to combined HRT which showed a small increase.<br><br>Menopause at normal age (A) and surgical menopause (B) do not specify uterine status. Premature menopause (D) may occur in hysterectomised women but hysterectomy is the specific indication, not menopause timing.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which route of estrogen administration in HRT bypasses hepatic first-pass metabolism?',o:['Oral','Transdermal','Sublingual only','Intramuscular only'],a:1,
e:`Transdermal oestrogen (patches, gels, sprays) bypasses hepatic first-pass metabolism by delivering oestradiol directly through the skin into the systemic circulation, maintaining physiological serum oestradiol levels without the hepatic metabolism that occurs with oral administration. Oral oestrogen is extensively metabolised in the liver on first pass before reaching systemic circulation, requiring higher doses to achieve comparable systemic levels.<br><br>Bypassing hepatic first-pass metabolism has important clinical advantages: transdermal oestrogen does not stimulate hepatic coagulation factor synthesis and SHBG production as oral oestrogen does, resulting in significantly lower risk of venous thromboembolism and stroke. Current NICE guidelines recommend transdermal oestrogen as the preferred route in women with cardiovascular risk factors, thrombophilia, migraines and obesity.<br><br>Oral route (A) undergoes extensive hepatic first-pass metabolism, the opposite of the desired bypass. Sublingual (C) and intramuscular (D) routes also partially bypass first-pass but transdermal is the most commonly used and recommended HRT route for first-pass bypass.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Long-term HRT may increase the risk of which malignancy?',o:['Cervical cancer','Ovarian cancer','Colorectal cancer','Breast cancer'],a:3,
e:`Combined oestrogen-progestogen HRT is associated with a small increase in breast cancer risk, estimated at approximately 1 additional case per 1000 women using combined HRT for 5 years. The increased risk is comparable to that associated with obesity, moderate alcohol consumption or not breastfeeding. Oestrogen-only HRT (for hysterectomised women) shows a non-significant reduction in breast cancer risk in some studies.<br><br>The breast cancer risk from combined HRT returns to population baseline within a few years of stopping HRT. Current NICE guidance recommends informed decision-making about HRT including breast cancer risk, with the absolute risk increase being small and the quality-of-life benefits being significant for symptomatic women. Most women with severe menopausal symptoms and no contraindications can safely use combined HRT for symptom control.<br><br>Cervical cancer (A) risk is not increased by HRT. Ovarian cancer (B) risk is marginally increased with long-term use but less significantly than breast cancer. Colorectal cancer (C) risk is actually reduced by HRT in most studies.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 52-year-old woman presents with amenorrhea for 14 months along with hot flushes and night sweats. What is the most likely diagnosis?',o:['Hyperprolactinemia','Hypothyroidism','Menopause','PCOS'],a:2,
e:`Amenorrhoea for 14 months in a 52-year-old woman, combined with hot flushes and night sweats, is the classic presentation of natural menopause. The 12-month amenorrhoea threshold defining menopause is met, and the vasomotor symptoms (hot flushes and night sweats) are the most common early menopausal symptoms caused by hypothalamic thermoregulatory instability from oestrogen withdrawal.<br><br>At age 52, hormone measurement is not essential for diagnosis as menopause at this age is expected. However, FSH above 25 IU/L and low oestradiol would confirm the hormonal basis if there is diagnostic uncertainty. Management includes HRT discussion, lifestyle advice, and investigation for long-term consequences including bone density measurement.<br><br>Hyperprolactinaemia (A) causes secondary amenorrhoea with low FSH and LH, not with hot flushes. Hypothyroidism (B) causes amenorrhoea with different symptoms. PCOS (D) causes oligomenorrhoea and hyperandrogenism in reproductive-age women, not postmenopausal-pattern vasomotor symptoms with sustained amenorrhoea.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 38-year-old woman undergoes bilateral oophorectomy for ovarian malignancy and immediately develops menopausal symptoms. What type of menopause is this?',o:['Premature menopause only','Natural menopause','Medical menopause only','Surgical menopause'],a:3,
e:`Bilateral oophorectomy at age 38 causes surgical menopause by abruptly eliminating ovarian oestrogen production. The immediate onset of menopausal symptoms following surgery, including hot flushes, night sweats and vaginal dryness, typically more severe than natural menopause due to the sudden rather than gradual oestrogen withdrawal, is characteristic of surgical menopause.<br><br>Women undergoing bilateral oophorectomy before the natural menopause age should receive HRT until at least age 51 (average natural menopause) unless there are specific contraindications such as oestrogen-sensitive malignancy. In the context of ovarian malignancy treatment, the oncological risk-benefit of HRT must be carefully assessed, as epithelial ovarian cancer is not hormone-sensitive but germ cell tumours may be.<br><br>Premature menopause only (A) refers to spontaneous ovarian failure before 40. Natural menopause (B) is physiological gradual follicular exhaustion. Medical menopause (C) is reversible suppression from GnRH agonists. Surgical menopause from oophorectomy is the specific and correct category here.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 45-year-old woman with menopausal symptoms is started on estrogen therapy. Which additional hormone must be added if she has an intact uterus?',o:['Testosterone','LH','Progesterone','FSH'],a:2,
e:`Progesterone (or a synthetic progestogen) must be added to oestrogen therapy in women with an intact uterus to prevent oestrogen-induced endometrial hyperplasia and carcinoma. Oestrogen alone causes continuous endometrial proliferation; without cyclic or continuous progestogen providing the secretory transformation and programmed endometrial regression, the proliferative endometrium accumulates and progresses through hyperplasia to carcinoma over time.<br><br>The choice of progestogen and regimen depends on individual circumstances: cyclical progestogen (12-14 days/month) for perimenopausal women who prefer a regular withdrawal bleed; continuous combined HRT for postmenopausal women avoiding monthly bleeds; or the levonorgestrel IUS as the progestogen component providing highly effective local endometrial protection with minimal systemic absorption and side effects.<br><br>Testosterone (A) is occasionally added to HRT for libido in some women but is not the mandatory addition for endometrial protection. LH (B) and FSH (D) are pituitary hormones not included in HRT formulations.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman receiving estrogen-only HRT develops abnormal uterine bleeding. Which condition must be excluded?',o:['Ovarian cyst','PCOS','Cervical infection','Endometrial hyperplasia'],a:3,
e:`Any abnormal uterine bleeding in a woman receiving oestrogen-only HRT with an intact uterus must urgently exclude endometrial hyperplasia or carcinoma. Oestrogen stimulates endometrial proliferation; without progestogen to limit this growth and cause secretory transformation, the endometrium can develop hyperplasia that may progress to carcinoma if the inappropriate oestrogen-only prescription in an intact uterus continues.<br><br>Investigation requires transvaginal ultrasound measuring endometrial thickness and pipelle biopsy or hysteroscopy for histological diagnosis. If the patient was inappropriately prescribed oestrogen-only HRT with an intact uterus, adding progestogen or switching to combined HRT after treating any existing hyperplasia is essential. This case also highlights the importance of documenting hysterectomy status before prescribing oestrogen-only HRT.<br><br>Ovarian cyst (A) and PCOS (B) do not cause abnormal bleeding in the context of HRT in a postmenopausal woman. Cervical infection (C) is a less serious cause and not the primary concern given the oestrogen-only HRT context.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A postmenopausal woman presents with recurrent fractures due to osteoporosis. What is the primary hormonal deficiency causing this?',o:['Progesterone deficiency','LH deficiency','Estrogen deficiency','FSH excess'],a:2,
e:`Oestrogen deficiency at menopause is the primary cause of postmenopausal osteoporosis. Oestrogen normally inhibits osteoclastogenesis by suppressing RANKL expression on osteoblasts, promotes osteoclast apoptosis, and stimulates osteoblast activity. Its deficiency causes uncoupled bone remodelling with resorption exceeding formation, accelerated bone loss and trabecular microarchitecture deterioration leading to fractures.<br><br>Oestrogen replacement prevents this bone loss and reduces fracture risk when started in the early postmenopausal period. Other treatments include bisphosphonates (first-line for established osteoporosis), denosumab (RANK-L inhibitor), and teriparatide (anabolic PTH for severe osteoporosis). Calcium and vitamin D supplementation support all treatments.<br><br>Progesterone deficiency (A) contributes modestly to bone loss as progesterone has direct osteoblast effects, but oestrogen deficiency is the primary driver. LH deficiency (B) does not cause osteoporosis. FSH excess (D) is a consequence of ovarian failure rather than the primary cause of osteoporosis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 55-year-old woman complains of vaginal dryness and dyspareunia. Which menopausal condition is responsible?',o:['Increased progesterone','Increased LH','Increased FSH','Estrogen deficiency causing vaginal atrophy'],a:3,
e:`Oestrogen deficiency at menopause causes progressive urogenital atrophy: without oestrogen, vaginal epithelium thins, loses glycogen (reducing lactobacillus-dominated protective microbiome), becomes less elastic and more prone to trauma, and vaginal secretions decrease. The result is vaginal dryness, dyspareunia, post-coital bleeding and recurrent vaginal infections collectively termed the genitourinary syndrome of menopause.<br><br>Local vaginal oestrogen (creams, pessaries, rings) is highly effective for urogenital symptoms and is not subject to the same systemic risks as systemic HRT because minimal oestrogen is absorbed systemically. NICE guidelines recommend offering local vaginal oestrogen to all postmenopausal women with genitourinary syndrome, with treatment continuing as long as symptoms persist as the condition progresses without treatment.<br><br>Increased progesterone (A), increased LH (B) and increased FSH (C) are consequences of ovarian failure rather than causes of vaginal atrophy. The specific tissue effect causing vaginal dryness and dyspareunia is oestrogen deficiency in the vaginal and vulval epithelium.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient receiving HRT develops leg swelling and sudden chest pain. Which serious complication must be considered?',o:['Myocardial infarction','Ovarian torsion','Venous thromboembolism','Pulmonary oedema'],a:2,
e:`Venous thromboembolism (DVT causing leg swelling and PE causing chest pain) is the serious complication most associated with oral oestrogen-containing HRT. Oral oestrogen undergoes hepatic first-pass metabolism, stimulating hepatic synthesis of coagulation factors including factors VII, VIII, X and fibrinogen, creating a prothrombotic state. The absolute risk increase is small but clinically important, particularly in women with additional VTE risk factors.<br><br>Transdermal oestrogen bypasses hepatic first-pass metabolism and does not stimulate hepatic coagulation factor synthesis, making it the preferred HRT route in women with VTE risk factors, thrombophilia, obesity or previous VTE. Current guidance recommends transdermal oestrogen over oral oestrogen when VTE risk is a concern, as transdermal preparations appear to carry no significant increase in VTE risk.<br><br>Myocardial infarction (A) is a risk with long-term HRT started after 10 years post-menopause. Ovarian torsion (B) is not an HRT complication. Pulmonary oedema (D) is from cardiac failure rather than an HRT-specific complication.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 49-year-old woman presents with irregular cycles and hot flushes due to declining ovarian function. What is the diagnosis?',o:['Primary amenorrhea','Premature ovarian insufficiency','Hyperprolactinemia','Perimenopause'],a:3,
e:`Perimenopause is the transitional period preceding menopause characterised by irregular menstrual cycles from erratic folliculogenesis (some months ovulatory, some anovulatory), with vasomotor symptoms including hot flushes and night sweats from fluctuating and declining oestradiol as the ovarian follicular reserve progressively diminishes. This presentation in a 49-year-old is typical of the perimenopause that precedes natural menopause by 2-8 years.<br><br>Perimenopausal management: reassurance about normal biological transition, HRT for bothersome vasomotor symptoms or bone protection, contraception until 12 months after last period if over 50 (even irregular cycles may include ovulation), and investigation for abnormal bleeding patterns. Follicle tracking or FSH testing has limited diagnostic utility in perimenopause as values fluctuate considerably.<br><br>Primary amenorrhoea (A) is absent menarche by age 15. Premature ovarian insufficiency (B) occurs before age 40 with FSH above 25 IU/L. Hyperprolactinaemia (C) causes regular secondary amenorrhoea without vasomotor symptoms.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with premature ovarian insufficiency at age 35 presents with infertility. Which hormone replacement is most critical for long-term health?',o:['FSH','Estrogen','TSH','LH'],a:1,
e:`Oestrogen replacement is the most critical hormone replacement for long-term health in a 35-year-old with premature ovarian insufficiency. Without oestrogen from age 35, the woman faces 15-20 years of premature oestrogen deficiency before the natural average menopause age of 51, greatly increasing her risks of osteoporosis, cardiovascular disease, cognitive decline, sexual dysfunction, urogenital atrophy and premature mortality compared with women with normal menopause timing.<br><br>NICE recommends offering HRT to women with POI until at least the average age of natural menopause (approximately 51 years) to address these long-term health consequences. HRT doses should be adequate to replace physiological oestrogen levels, typically higher than used for symptomatic postmenopausal women who have had normal menopause timing.<br><br>FSH (A) and LH (B) are elevated at the pituitary level in POI and do not require supplementation. TSH (C) addresses thyroid function, which may be affected in autoimmune POI but is not the most critical hormone replacement for long-term cardiovascular and bone health.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A gynecologist prescribes transdermal estrogen patches to a menopausal woman to avoid which hepatic effect?',o:['Decreased clotting factors','Increased glycogen storage','Avoids first-pass liver metabolism causing increased clotting factors','Decreased VLDL synthesis'],a:2,
e:`Transdermal oestrogen patches are prescribed to avoid the hepatic first-pass metabolism that occurs with oral oestrogen, which stimulates hepatic synthesis of coagulation factors (factors VII, VIII, X, fibrinogen) and SHBG, creating a prothrombotic state that increases VTE risk. Transdermal delivery bypasses the liver, maintaining physiological serum oestradiol levels without stimulating hepatic protein synthesis.<br><br>Clinical evidence supports significantly lower VTE risk with transdermal versus oral oestrogen HRT. The ESTHER and other observational studies demonstrate that transdermal oestrogen is not associated with increased VTE risk even in women with thrombophilia, whereas oral oestrogen approximately doubles VTE risk. NICE recommends transdermal oestrogen as the preferred route when VTE risk is a concern.<br><br>Oral oestrogen increases rather than decreases clotting factors (A). Glycogen storage (B) is a hepatic metabolic function not the primary concern with HRT route. VLDL synthesis (C) is partially reduced by oestrogen, but increased clotting factors from first-pass metabolism are the primary reason for preferring transdermal over oral routes.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 60-year-old woman presents with vaginal bleeding after menopause. Which condition must be urgently excluded?',o:['Vaginal atrophy only','Endometrial carcinoma','Cervical ectropion','PCOS'],a:1,
e:`Endometrial carcinoma must be urgently excluded in any postmenopausal woman presenting with vaginal bleeding. At age 60, 10 years post average menopause, any vaginal bleeding is postmenopausal bleeding requiring urgent investigation. Approximately 10% of women with PMB have endometrial carcinoma, and early detection through prompt investigation enables treatment at stage I when 5-year survival exceeds 90%.<br><br>Investigation: urgent transvaginal ultrasound measuring endometrial thickness; if greater than 4 mm, urgent endometrial sampling by pipelle biopsy or hysteroscopy. The two-week-wait cancer referral pathway should be used when endometrial carcinoma is clinically suspected. Risk factors in this age group include obesity, nulliparity, late menopause, tamoxifen and Lynch syndrome.<br><br>Vaginal atrophy alone (A) is the most common cause of PMB but endometrial carcinoma must be excluded first before attributing bleeding to atrophy. Cervical ectropion (C) is a premenopausal cause of postcoital bleeding. PCOS (D) is a reproductive-age disorder.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman on long-term HRT asks about cancer risks. Which malignancy risk is most commonly associated with combined HRT?',o:['Cervical cancer','Colorectal cancer','Ovarian cancer','Breast cancer'],a:3,
e:`Combined oestrogen-progestogen HRT is most commonly associated with a small increase in breast cancer risk, approximately 1 additional case per 1000 women using combined HRT for 5 years compared with non-users. The risk is related to the progestogen component: oestrogen-only HRT (for hysterectomised women) shows no significant breast cancer risk increase or even a modest reduction in some analyses.<br><br>The breast cancer risk from HRT is comparable to other lifestyle risk factors including obesity, moderate alcohol and not breastfeeding. The risk returns to population baseline within a few years of stopping HRT. NICE guidance emphasises that for most women with significant menopausal symptoms and no contraindications, the quality-of-life benefits of HRT outweigh the small breast cancer risk, particularly for use under 5 years.<br><br>Cervical cancer (A) is HPV-driven and unrelated to HRT. Colorectal cancer (B) risk is actually reduced by HRT. Ovarian cancer (C) risk is marginally increased with very long-term use but breast cancer remains the most prominent and clinically important cancer risk association with combined HRT.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A postmenopausal woman presents with urinary urgency and recurrent infections. Which menopausal change is responsible?',o:['Increased LH causing bladder irritation','Increased FSH causing urethral inflammation','Estrogen deficiency causing urogenital atrophy','Increased progesterone causing bladder spasm'],a:2,
e:`Oestrogen deficiency causes urogenital atrophy affecting the bladder trigone, urethra and vagina, as all these tissues are oestrogen-sensitive. Loss of oestrogen causes thinning of the urethral and vaginal epithelium, reduced collagen and elasticity, loss of the lactobacillus-dominated vaginal microbiome and reduction in urethral closure pressure. These changes collectively produce urinary urgency, increased urinary frequency, recurrent UTIs and stress incontinence.<br><br>Local vaginal oestrogen restores urogenital epithelial integrity, improves symptoms and significantly reduces recurrent UTI frequency. NICE recommends offering local vaginal oestrogen to all postmenopausal women with urogenital symptoms, with treatment continuing long-term as the condition progresses without treatment and the benefits require sustained use.<br><br>Increased LH (A) and increased FSH (B) are consequences of menopause, not causes of urogenital symptoms. Increased progesterone (D) does not cause bladder spasm; progesterone levels fall at menopause with loss of cyclic corpus luteum formation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 51-year-old woman complains of hot flushes, insomnia, and mood swings due to menopausal transition. What is the primary physiological cause?',o:['Increased FSH causing temperature instability','Increased prolactin secretion','Increased LH surge frequency','Hypothalamic thermoregulatory instability from estrogen withdrawal'],a:3,
e:`Oestrogen withdrawal at menopause causes hypothalamic thermoregulatory instability by narrowing the thermoneutral zone and altering central noradrenergic pathways in the preoptic area. Small rises in core temperature above the narrowed threshold inappropriately trigger heat dissipation responses: cutaneous vasodilatation (flushing), sweating and subsequent chilling. Insomnia from nocturnal hot flushes (night sweats) interrupts sleep architecture, contributing to mood disturbance and fatigue.<br><br>The mood symptoms of menopause include anxiety, irritability, low mood and cognitive symptoms (brain fog). These result from both direct oestrogen withdrawal effects on serotonergic and noradrenergic neurotransmitter systems and indirectly from sleep disruption by vasomotor symptoms. HRT effectively treats vasomotor symptoms, improves sleep and secondarily improves mood in women whose mood symptoms are driven by vasomotor disruption.<br><br>Increased FSH (A) is a marker of menopause but does not itself cause temperature instability. Increased prolactin (B) falls at menopause with declining oestradiol. Increased LH surge frequency (C) is a perimenopause feature but is not the primary cause of vasomotor symptoms.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A gynecologist explains that bone resorption increases after menopause due to deficiency of which hormone?',o:['Osteoporosis increases due to estrogen deficiency','Testosterone deficiency only','Increased prolactin causes bone loss','Progesterone deficiency only'],a:0,
e:`Oestrogen deficiency at menopause is the primary cause of increased postmenopausal bone resorption. Oestrogen normally suppresses RANKL on osteoblasts (preventing excessive osteoclast activation), promotes osteoclast apoptosis and stimulates osteoblast bone formation. Its deficiency causes uncoupled remodelling with resorption exceeding formation, producing net bone loss of approximately 2-3% per year in the first postmenopausal decade.<br><br>The rate of bone loss is greatest in trabecular bone (vertebrae, distal radius, femoral neck) which has the highest surface area exposed to osteoclastic resorption. This explains the predominance of vertebral fractures and wrist fractures in the early postmenopausal years. Oestrogen replacement therapy prevents this bone loss and is approved for prevention of postmenopausal osteoporosis when started early after menopause.<br><br>Testosterone deficiency only (B) contributes modestly to bone loss but oestrogen is the dominant sex hormone maintaining female bone density. Increased prolactin (C) reduces bone density by suppressing oestradiol but is not the primary postmenopausal mechanism. Progesterone deficiency alone (D) has modest bone effects but oestrogen deficiency is the critical driver.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with premature menopause presents with infertility and amenorrhea at age 37. Which laboratory finding is most characteristic?',o:['Low FSH with high estrogen','Elevated progesterone','Elevated prolactin','Elevated FSH with low estrogen'],a:3,
e:`Premature ovarian insufficiency before age 40 produces hypergonadotrophic hypogonadism: depleted follicles fail to secrete oestradiol and inhibin B, removing negative feedback and causing FSH to rise above 25 IU/L.<br><br>Diagnosis requires elevated FSH plus oestradiol below 50 pmol/L with at least four months of amenorrhoea. Karyotype, fragile X premutation and adrenal antibody screening identify the underlying cause in roughly 20% of cases.<br><br>Low FSH with high oestrogen (A) suggests early follicular phase. Elevated progesterone (B) reflects luteal activity. Elevated prolactin (C) causes hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism with low rather than raised FSH.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A menopausal woman is started on combined estrogen-progesterone therapy. Which uterine effect is prevented by progesterone addition?',o:['Endometrial hyperplasia','Ovarian cyst formation','Fallopian tube obstruction','Cervical stenosis'],a:0,
e:`Unopposed oestrogen stimulates endometrial mitosis via oestrogen receptor alpha, producing hyperplasia and increasing endometrial cancer risk fivefold to tenfold. Cyclical or continuous progestogen opposes this by inducing secretory transformation and apoptosis.<br><br>Women with intact uterus therefore require combined HRT, never oestrogen alone. Continuous combined regimens suit postmenopausal women, while sequential progestogen for 12 to 14 days monthly suits perimenopausal women still experiencing withdrawal bleeds.<br><br>Ovarian cyst formation (B), fallopian tube obstruction (C) and cervical stenosis (D) are not endometrial proliferative lesions and bear no relationship to progestogen action.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with menopause-related osteoporosis receives estrogen therapy. Which physiological effect of estrogen improves bone density?',o:['Increased osteoblast apoptosis','Increased calcium excretion','Suppression of vitamin D','Inhibition of osteoclast activity'],a:3,
e:`Oestrogen suppresses osteoclast activity by reducing RANKL expression and increasing osteoprotegerin from osteoblasts, shortening osteoclast lifespan through induction of apoptosis. This restrains bone resorption and preserves bone density.<br><br>Following menopause, oestrogen withdrawal removes this restraint, causing rapid trabecular bone loss of two to three percent annually for the first five years. HRT prevents this loss when started within ten years of menopause.<br><br>Increased osteoblast apoptosis (A) would reduce bone formation. Increased calcium excretion (B) would worsen loss. Suppression of vitamin D (C) is not a recognised oestrogen effect on calcium homeostasis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with premature ovarian insufficiency has low estrogen and high gonadotropins. Which endocrine axis is primarily affected?',o:['Hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis','Hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis','Hypothalamic-pituitary-renal axis','Hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis'],a:0,
e:`Premature ovarian insufficiency disrupts the hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis at ovarian level. Loss of follicles eliminates oestradiol and inhibin B, removing negative feedback. FSH and LH rise while oestradiol falls.<br><br>This hypergonadotrophic hypogonadism distinguishes ovarian failure from hypothalamic or pituitary causes of amenorrhoea. Karyotype, fragile X premutation, and autoimmune screening identify aetiology, while oestrogen replacement until age 50 prevents osteoporosis and cardiovascular disease.<br><br>Hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis (B) regulates cortisol. Hypothalamic-pituitary-renal axis (C) is not recognised. Hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis (D) controls thyroid hormone, unrelated to ovarian failure.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman receiving HRT complains of breast tenderness and nausea. These symptoms are most commonly due to:',o:['Progesterone deficiency','Testosterone excess','Prolactin suppression','Estrogen therapy'],a:3,
e:`Breast tenderness and nausea are dose-dependent oestrogen side effects in HRT, mediated by oestrogen-induced fluid retention, ductal stimulation through breast oestrogen receptors, and direct effects on the chemoreceptor trigger zone.<br><br>These symptoms typically settle within three months as tissues adapt. Persistent symptoms warrant dose reduction or switch to transdermal preparations, which produce stable serum levels and avoid the high portal vein concentrations responsible for hepatic effects.<br><br>Progesterone deficiency (A) does not cause these specific symptoms. Testosterone excess (B) produces virilisation, not breast tenderness. Prolactin suppression (C) reduces rather than causes breast symptoms.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with contraindication to estrogen therapy is managed for menopausal symptoms. Which condition is a major contraindication to HRT?',o:['History of breast cancer','Diabetes mellitus','Obesity','Hypertension'],a:0,
e:`Personal history of oestrogen-receptor-positive breast cancer is an absolute contraindication to systemic HRT because oestrogen stimulates proliferation of any residual tumour cells, increasing recurrence risk. Tibolone and aromatase inhibitors are similarly contraindicated.<br><br>Non-hormonal alternatives include SSRIs, SNRIs, gabapentin and clonidine for vasomotor symptoms, and vaginal moisturisers for genitourinary atrophy. Cognitive behavioural therapy and lifestyle modification provide additional benefit for hormone-receptor-positive cancer survivors.<br><br>Diabetes mellitus (B), obesity (C) and hypertension (D) are relative cardiovascular risk factors warranting individualised assessment, but none constitutes an absolute contraindication to HRT.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 54-year-old woman with severe vasomotor symptoms is prescribed HRT. Which physiological symptom is most likely to improve first?',o:['Osteoporosis','Atherosclerosis','Hair thinning','Hot flushes'],a:3,
e:`Vasomotor symptoms respond fastest to HRT, with hot flushes and night sweats reducing within two to four weeks of starting therapy. Oestrogen restores hypothalamic thermoregulatory set-point destabilised by oestrogen withdrawal.<br><br>Approximately 80 to 90 percent of women experience significant relief, making vasomotor symptom control the primary indication for systemic HRT. Genitourinary symptoms take eight to twelve weeks to improve, while bone protection requires sustained therapy over years.<br><br>Osteoporosis (A) protection takes years to manifest. Atherosclerosis (B) progression changes slowly over decades. Hair thinning (C) responds variably and slowly to oestrogen, not as the earliest improvement.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman develops menopause due to chemotherapy-induced ovarian failure. This condition is best classified as:',o:['Iatrogenic menopause','Delayed menopause','Temporary amenorrhea','Physiological menopause'],a:0,
e:`Iatrogenic menopause results from medical interventions causing ovarian failure, including bilateral oophorectomy, pelvic radiotherapy and gonadotoxic chemotherapy. Alkylating agents like cyclophosphamide are particularly damaging through dose-dependent destruction of primordial follicles.<br><br>Risk depends on cumulative dose and patient age, with younger patients having greater follicular reserve and recovery potential. Women under 40 facing such treatment require fertility preservation counselling and HRT until age 50 to prevent premature osteoporosis.<br><br>Delayed menopause (B) means menopause after age 55. Temporary amenorrhoea (C) implies reversibility, which chemotherapy ovarian failure usually lacks. Physiological menopause (D) refers to natural age-related ovarian senescence.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A menopausal woman experiences vaginal dryness due to reduced glycogen content in vaginal epithelium. Which hormone deficiency causes this change?',o:['Progesterone','Testosterone','Prolactin','Estrogen'],a:3,
e:`Oestrogen maintains vaginal epithelial thickness, glycogen content and vascularity. After menopause, oestrogen deficiency thins the epithelium from many cell layers to a few, reducing glycogen substrate for lactobacilli and elevating vaginal pH above 5.<br><br>This atrophic change produces dryness, dyspareunia and recurrent urinary tract infections. Local vaginal oestrogen creams or pessaries effectively reverse atrophy with minimal systemic absorption, making them safe even for women with relative contraindications to systemic HRT.<br><br>Progesterone (A) does not maintain vaginal glycogen content. Testosterone (B) deficiency does not cause atrophic vaginitis. Prolactin (C) deficiency causes failure of lactation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A reproductive endocrinologist explains that menopause results from depletion of ovarian follicles leading to cessation of ovarian steroidogenesis. Which gonadotropin level rises most significantly during this stage?',o:['FSH','Prolactin','ACTH','LH'],a:0,
e:`FSH rises more dramatically than LH at menopause because inhibin B, secreted by granulosa cells of small antral follicles, falls before oestradiol declines. Inhibin B selectively suppresses pituitary FSH, so its loss causes disproportionate FSH elevation.<br><br>Postmenopausal FSH typically reaches 30 to 100 IU/L while LH rises to 20 to 50 IU/L. This contrasts with PCOS where elevated LH:FSH ratio reflects accelerated GnRH pulsatility and intact follicular reserve.<br><br>Prolactin (B) is not driven by ovarian failure feedback. ACTH (C) responds to cortisol feedback. LH (D) rises but less markedly than FSH because inhibin B selectively suppresses FSH.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormonal change is considered the earliest endocrine marker of the menopausal transition before cessation of menstruation?',o:['Increase in prolactin levels','Decrease in LH levels','Increase in progesterone levels','Increase in FSH levels'],a:3,
e:`Rising FSH is the earliest endocrine marker of menopausal transition, often detectable five to ten years before menses cease. Falling inhibin B from declining cohorts of small antral follicles removes selective FSH suppression.<br><br>Day three FSH above 10 IU/L indicates diminished ovarian reserve. Anti-Mullerian hormone, secreted by small growing follicles, falls in parallel and provides a more stable cycle-independent marker of ovarian reserve used clinically alongside antral follicle count.<br><br>Increased prolactin (A) suggests pituitary causes of amenorrhoea. Decreased LH (B) does not occur in ovarian senescence. Increased progesterone (C) reflects luteal activity which actually declines with menopausal transition.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The decline in ovarian follicular reserve during menopause leads to reduced secretion of which hormone that normally inhibits FSH?',o:['Inhibin B','Testosterone','Oxytocin','Progesterone'],a:0,
e:`Inhibin B is a glycoprotein heterodimer secreted by granulosa cells of small antral follicles that selectively suppresses pituitary FSH through activin-binding antagonism. As follicular reserve declines, inhibin B falls, removing the FSH brake.<br><br>This explains why FSH rises before oestradiol falls during menopausal transition. Inhibin B measurement provides an early marker of declining ovarian reserve, complementing AMH and antral follicle count in fertility assessment for women contemplating delayed childbearing.<br><br>Testosterone (B) does not regulate FSH negatively in females. Oxytocin (C) is a posterior pituitary hormone unrelated to gonadotropin feedback. Progesterone (D) suppresses LH more than FSH.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During menopause, which endocrine change contributes most significantly to vasomotor instability?',o:['Increased androgen secretion','Reduced hypothalamic thermoregulatory threshold due to estrogen withdrawal','Increased progesterone secretion','Increased prolactin secretion'],a:1,
e:`Hot flushes result from a narrowed thermoneutral zone in the hypothalamic preoptic area following oestrogen withdrawal. Reduced central noradrenergic and serotonergic tone lowers the sweating threshold, so small core temperature increases trigger inappropriate cutaneous vasodilation.<br><br>Approximately 75 percent of menopausal women experience vasomotor symptoms, lasting median 7 years. Oestrogen replacement restores normal thermoregulation. Non-hormonal alternatives include SSRIs, SNRIs, gabapentin and clonidine, working through central neurotransmitter modulation rather than restoring oestrogen.<br><br>Increased androgen secretion (A) does not destabilise thermoregulation. Increased progesterone (C) raises basal body temperature uniformly without flushes. Increased prolactin (D) causes galactorrhoea, not vasomotor symptoms.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'In menopausal women, which lipid profile change commonly occurs due to estrogen deficiency?',o:['Decreased LDL and increased HDL','Increased HDL only','Decreased triglycerides','Increased LDL and decreased HDL'],a:3,
e:`Oestrogen normally upregulates hepatic LDL receptors, reducing circulating LDL cholesterol, while increasing HDL through stimulation of apolipoprotein A-I synthesis. Postmenopausal oestrogen deficiency reverses both effects, producing the atherogenic lipid profile of raised LDL and reduced HDL.<br><br>This dyslipidaemia partly explains accelerated cardiovascular risk after menopause. Oestrogen-replete premenopausal women have lower coronary disease risk than men of equivalent age, with the gender gap narrowing after menopause. Statin therapy effectively addresses postmenopausal LDL elevation.<br><br>Decreased LDL with increased HDL (A) is the favourable premenopausal pattern. Increased HDL only (B) does not occur. Decreased triglycerides (C) is not a typical menopausal lipid change.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The primary ovarian source of estrogen after menopause becomes:',o:['Corpus luteum','Dominant follicle','Peripheral conversion of androgens in adipose tissue','Theca interna'],a:2,
e:`After menopause, ovarian follicular oestrogen production ceases and the dominant oestrogen source becomes peripheral aromatisation of adrenal androstenedione to oestrone in adipose tissue. Oestrone is the principal postmenopausal oestrogen.<br><br>Aromatase activity in adipose tissue increases with body mass index, explaining why obese postmenopausal women have higher endogenous oestrogen and increased risk of endometrial hyperplasia and oestrogen-receptor-positive breast cancer. Aromatase inhibitors specifically target this pathway in breast cancer treatment.<br><br>Corpus luteum (A) does not exist after menopause. Dominant follicle (B) is absent in postmenopause. Theca interna (D) ceases significant steroidogenic function once follicles are depleted.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 49-year-old woman presents with irregular menstrual cycles, hot flushes, and sleep disturbances. Laboratory tests show elevated FSH but still detectable estrogen levels. Which stage is most consistent with these findings?',o:['Premature ovarian failure','Anovulatory cycle','Postmenopause','Perimenopause'],a:3,
e:`Perimenopause is the transitional phase characterised by irregular cycles, vasomotor symptoms, sleep disturbances and rising FSH while oestradiol remains intermittently produced from remaining follicles. It typically spans four to eight years before final menstrual period.<br><br>Cycles become anovulatory, with shortened follicular phases and erratic oestradiol surges that can cause heavy bleeding alongside hypo-oestrogenic symptoms. Diagnosis is clinical; FSH measurement is unreliable due to fluctuation, but clearly elevated FSH supports the transition.<br><br>Premature ovarian failure (A) requires onset before age 40. Anovulatory cycle (B) is a single-cycle event. Postmenopause (C) requires 12 months amenorrhoea, not yet reached.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 52-year-old woman with intact uterus is started on estrogen therapy for severe vasomotor symptoms. After several months, she develops abnormal uterine bleeding. What is the most likely pathophysiological mechanism?',o:['Suppression of LH secretion','Unopposed estrogen causing endometrial hyperplasia','Increased prolactin secretion','Reduced ovarian androgen production'],a:1,
e:`Unopposed oestrogen in a woman with intact uterus stimulates endometrial proliferation via oestrogen receptor alpha, producing hyperplasia and breakthrough bleeding from disorganised, friable glands. Continued exposure increases endometrial atypia and progression to endometrioid carcinoma.<br><br>This mechanism mandates progestogen addition in any woman with uterus receiving oestrogen replacement. Postmenopausal bleeding requires investigation with transvaginal ultrasound (endometrial thickness above 4mm) followed by hysteroscopy and endometrial biopsy to exclude hyperplasia and carcinoma.<br><br>Suppression of LH (A) does not cause endometrial bleeding. Increased prolactin (C) causes amenorrhoea, not bleeding. Reduced ovarian androgen production (D) does not stimulate endometrial proliferation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with premature ovarian insufficiency at age 34 presents with amenorrhea and infertility. Which hormonal profile is most consistent with this condition?',o:['High progesterone with low LH','High prolactin with low estrogen','High FSH with low estradiol','Low FSH with high estradiol'],a:2,
e:`Premature ovarian insufficiency produces hypergonadotrophic hypogonadism: depleted follicles cannot secrete oestradiol or inhibin B, removing negative feedback. Pituitary gonadotrophs are released from suppression, FSH rises above 25 IU/L while oestradiol falls below 50 pmol/L.<br><br>Diagnostic criteria require this hormonal pattern on two occasions four to six weeks apart with at least four months of amenorrhoea, in a woman under 40. Karyotype, fragile X premutation and adrenal antibody screening identify aetiology.<br><br>High progesterone with low LH (A) suggests luteal phase. High prolactin with low oestrogen (B) indicates hyperprolactinaemia. Low FSH with high oestradiol (D) is the early follicular pattern.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 60-year-old woman complains of progressive bone loss after menopause. Which mechanism primarily contributes to increased bone resorption in this condition?',o:['Increased osteoclast activity due to estrogen deficiency','Increased progesterone secretion','Increased thyroid hormone production','Reduced calcium absorption in intestine only'],a:0,
e:`Postmenopausal oestrogen deficiency removes restraint on osteoclasts: RANKL expression rises while osteoprotegerin falls, prolonging osteoclast lifespan and increasing bone resorption. Resorption exceeds formation, producing rapid trabecular bone loss of two to three percent annually for five years.<br><br>Vertebral and femoral neck sites lose density fastest, raising fracture risk. DEXA scanning quantifies osteoporosis with T-score below -2.5. Treatment includes bisphosphonates, denosumab, HRT for women within ten years of menopause, and calcium with vitamin D supplementation.<br><br>Increased progesterone (B) does not cause osteoporosis. Increased thyroid hormone (C) accelerates bone loss but is not the postmenopausal mechanism. Reduced calcium absorption alone (D) is contributory, not primary.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient receiving long-term combined HRT asks about the protective effects of estrogen. Which physiological benefit is most directly associated with estrogen therapy in early postmenopausal women?',o:['Suppression of ovulation','Increased fertility','Prevention of bone loss','Increased progesterone secretion'],a:2,
e:`HRT prevents postmenopausal bone loss by restoring oestrogen-mediated suppression of osteoclast activity, reducing fracture risk by approximately 30 to 40 percent at vertebral and hip sites when started within ten years of menopause.<br><br>This benefit lasts only while therapy continues, with bone loss resuming after discontinuation. HRT is no longer first-line for osteoporosis prevention alone given thrombotic and breast cancer risks, but offers significant additional bone protection when prescribed for vasomotor symptoms.<br><br>Suppression of ovulation (A) is irrelevant in postmenopause where ovulation has ceased. Increased fertility (B) does not occur after menopause. Increased progesterone secretion (D) is not a benefit of HRT.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 55-year-old woman with severe vasomotor symptoms is started on transdermal estrogen therapy. Which advantage does this route provide compared with oral estrogen?',o:['Avoids hepatic first-pass metabolism','Prevents LH surge','Suppresses FSH secretion permanently','Increases ovarian estrogen production'],a:0,
e:`Transdermal oestrogen delivers oestradiol directly into systemic circulation through skin absorption, bypassing portal venous transit through the liver. This avoids hepatic first-pass metabolism that occurs with oral oestrogens, where supraphysiological portal concentrations stimulate hepatic protein synthesis.<br><br>Clinically, transdermal routes avoid oral oestrogen effects on coagulation factors, sex hormone binding globulin, angiotensinogen and triglycerides. Transdermal is therefore preferred in women at risk of venous thromboembolism, with hypertension, migraine, gallstones, or hypertriglyceridaemia.<br><br>Prevention of LH surge (B) is not relevant in postmenopause. Permanent FSH suppression (C) does not occur. Increased ovarian oestrogen production (D) is impossible in depleted postmenopausal ovaries.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with menopausal symptoms is evaluated before starting HRT. Which condition is considered an absolute contraindication to estrogen therapy?',o:['Hypertension','Hyperlipidemia','Diabetes mellitus','History of estrogen-dependent breast cancer'],a:3,
e:`Personal history of oestrogen-receptor-positive breast cancer is an absolute contraindication to systemic HRT because exogenous oestrogen stimulates proliferation of residual tumour cells via oestrogen receptor alpha. Tibolone and aromatase inhibitors share this contraindication.<br><br>Other absolute contraindications include active or recent venous thromboembolism, undiagnosed vaginal bleeding, active liver disease, pregnancy and untreated endometrial hyperplasia. Non-hormonal alternatives such as SSRIs, SNRIs, gabapentin and clonidine manage vasomotor symptoms safely in breast cancer survivors.<br><br>Hypertension (A), hyperlipidaemia (B) and diabetes (C) are relative cardiovascular risk factors warranting transdermal routes and individual assessment, but none represents an absolute contraindication.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 53-year-old woman complains of dyspareunia and vaginal dryness. Examination reveals thin, pale vaginal mucosa. Which mechanism explains this finding?',o:['Increased progesterone secretion','Increased LH secretion','Estrogen deficiency causing vaginal epithelial atrophy','Increased testosterone secretion'],a:2,
e:`Oestrogen deficiency thins the vaginal epithelium from many cell layers to a few, reducing glycogen for lactobacillus fermentation and raising vaginal pH above 5. The mucosa becomes pale, thin, friable and inelastic, producing dyspareunia, dryness and recurrent infections.<br><br>Local vaginal oestrogen creams, rings or pessaries reverse these changes within weeks with minimal systemic absorption, making them safe even for women with relative contraindications to systemic HRT. Non-hormonal moisturisers and lubricants provide adjunctive symptomatic relief.<br><br>Increased progesterone (A) does not reverse atrophy. Increased LH (B) does not maintain vaginal epithelium. Increased testosterone secretion (D) is not the typical postmenopausal pattern.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with premature menopause develops increased cardiovascular risk. Which physiological effect of estrogen deficiency contributes most to this risk?',o:['Increased insulin secretion','Increased LDL cholesterol levels','Increased progesterone levels','Decreased triglyceride levels'],a:1,
e:`Premenopausal oestrogen upregulates hepatic LDL receptors, accelerating LDL clearance and reducing circulating LDL cholesterol. Oestrogen withdrawal reverses this effect, raising LDL by approximately ten to fifteen percent and contributing to accelerated atherogenesis after menopause.<br><br>This dyslipidaemia, combined with reduced HDL, increased small dense LDL particles, and oestrogen-mediated loss of vasodilatory effects, partly explains the threefold rise in coronary heart disease incidence within ten years of menopause. Statin therapy effectively addresses the LDL component.<br><br>Increased insulin secretion (A) is not a typical menopausal lipid risk factor. Increased progesterone (C) does not occur. Decreased triglycerides (D) is the opposite of the postmenopausal pattern.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 58-year-old woman receiving HRT presents with unilateral leg swelling and chest pain. Which serious complication associated with estrogen therapy should be suspected?',o:['Osteoporosis','Hypothyroidism','Venous thromboembolism','Hypoglycemia'],a:2,
e:`Oral oestrogen increases venous thromboembolism risk approximately twofold to threefold through hepatic first-pass effects on coagulation: increased factor VII, fibrinogen and prothrombin alongside reduced antithrombin III and protein S. Risk is highest in the first year of therapy.<br><br>Unilateral leg swelling and pleuritic chest pain in an HRT user mandates urgent evaluation with D-dimer, compression ultrasonography and CT pulmonary angiography. Transdermal oestrogen avoids first-pass effects and does not increase thromboembolic risk significantly.<br><br>Osteoporosis (A) presents with fractures, not acute swelling. Hypothyroidism (B) does not present this way. Hypoglycaemia (D) causes neuroglycopenic symptoms, not unilateral leg swelling.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with premature ovarian insufficiency is treated with HRT until the age of natural menopause. What is the primary rationale for this therapy?',o:['Restore ovulation permanently','Prevent menstruation','Increase androgen production','Replace deficient estrogen and reduce long-term complications'],a:3,
e:`HRT in premature ovarian insufficiency replaces physiologically deficient oestrogen until age 50, the typical age of natural menopause. This prevents accelerated osteoporosis, cardiovascular disease, urogenital atrophy and cognitive decline associated with prolonged hypo-oestrogenism in young women.<br><br>At age 50, decisions about continuation follow standard postmenopausal HRT principles. Combined oral contraceptive pills provide an alternative that additionally suppresses unhelpful gonadotropin spikes and offers contraception against rare spontaneous ovulation.<br><br>Restoration of permanent ovulation (A) is not achievable as follicles are depleted. Prevention of menstruation (B) is not the goal. Increased androgen production (C) is not a therapeutic aim of HRT.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A menopausal woman develops urinary frequency and recurrent infections due to estrogen deficiency. Which anatomical change contributes most to this condition?',o:['Increased cervical mucus secretion','Atrophy of urogenital epithelium','Increased ovarian androgen production','Increased progesterone secretion'],a:1,
e:`Urogenital epithelium shares oestrogen receptor expression with vaginal mucosa and undergoes parallel atrophy after menopause: thin, friable urethral and trigonal epithelium loses the protective glycoprotein layer and the urinary microbiome shifts away from lactobacilli, raising pH.<br><br>This predisposes to urinary frequency, urgency, dysuria and recurrent uropathogenic bacterial infections. Local vaginal oestrogen reverses these changes effectively with minimal systemic absorption, reducing recurrent UTI rates substantially. It is recommended even for women otherwise unsuitable for HRT.<br><br>Increased cervical mucus (A) does not occur in oestrogen deficiency. Increased ovarian androgen production (C) is not typical. Increased progesterone secretion (D) does not occur after menopause.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A gynecologist explains that declining ovarian follicles during menopause leads to loss of inhibin secretion. What is the direct endocrine consequence of this change?',o:['Increased progesterone secretion','Increased prolactin secretion','Decreased LH secretion','Increased FSH secretion'],a:3,
e:`Inhibin B from granulosa cells of small antral follicles selectively suppresses pituitary FSH through activin-binding antagonism. As follicles deplete during menopausal transition, inhibin B falls, removing this restraint and allowing FSH to rise disproportionately compared with LH.<br><br>This explains why FSH is the earliest and most dramatic gonadotropin elevation in menopause, often preceding oestradiol decline by years. Postmenopausal FSH typically reaches 30 to 100 IU/L compared with LH of 20 to 50 IU/L, reflecting selective inhibin-FSH relationship.<br><br>Increased progesterone (A) does not result from inhibin loss. Increased prolactin (B) is unrelated to inhibin feedback. Decreased LH (C) is opposite to the postmenopausal pattern.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A postmenopausal woman receiving estrogen therapy develops breast tenderness and fluid retention. Which mechanism most likely explains these symptoms?',o:['Increased prolactin suppression','Increased LH secretion','Estrogen-mediated fluid retention and breast tissue stimulation','Increased progesterone secretion'],a:2,
e:`Oestrogen stimulates renal sodium and water retention by upregulating angiotensinogen and enhancing renin-angiotensin-aldosterone activity, while breast tenderness reflects direct stimulation of ductal epithelium and stromal oedema through oestrogen receptor activation in mammary tissue.<br><br>These dose-dependent symptoms typically settle within three months of starting HRT as tissues adapt. Persistent symptoms warrant dose reduction or change to transdermal preparations. Reducing the oestrogen dose to the lowest effective level minimises these unwanted effects.<br><br>Increased prolactin suppression (A) reduces rather than causes breast symptoms. Increased LH (B) does not stimulate breast tissue or fluid retention. Increased progesterone secretion (D) is not the mechanism.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A reproductive endocrinologist explains that menopause results from depletion of ovarian follicles leading to cessation of ovarian steroidogenesis and loss of negative feedback on pituitary gonadotropins. Which hormonal pattern best reflects this endocrine state?',o:['High FSH and LH with low estrogen','High prolactin with high estrogen','High progesterone with low LH','Low FSH with high estrogen'],a:0,
e:`Postmenopausal hormonal pattern reflects loss of negative feedback: depleted follicles cease oestradiol and inhibin B production, releasing pituitary gonadotrophs from suppression. FSH rises to 30 to 100 IU/L and LH to 20 to 50 IU/L while oestradiol falls below 30 pmol/L.<br><br>This hypergonadotrophic hypogonadism pattern confirms ovarian failure as opposed to hypothalamic or pituitary causes of amenorrhoea. Ovarian aromatisation ceases, but adipose tissue continues converting adrenal androstenedione to oestrone as the main postmenopausal oestrogen.<br><br>High prolactin with high oestrogen (B) does not occur. High progesterone with low LH (C) suggests luteal phase. Low FSH with high oestrogen (D) is the early follicular pattern.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is primarily responsible for maintaining the corpus luteum during early pregnancy?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Prolactin','Human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG)'],a:3,
e:`Human chorionic gonadotropin secreted by syncytiotrophoblast from day 8 post-fertilisation binds LH receptors on corpus luteum cells, sustaining progesterone secretion essential for endometrial decidualisation. Without hCG, corpus luteum regression by day 14 would trigger pregnancy loss.<br><br>Serum hCG doubles every 48 to 72 hours in early pregnancy, peaking at 8 to 11 weeks at around 100,000 IU/L before declining as the placenta assumes progesterone production at the luteal-placental shift. Quantitative hCG measurement diagnoses early pregnancy progress.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) is produced by corpus luteum but does not maintain it. Progesterone (B) is the corpus luteum product, not its rescuer. Prolactin (C) supports lactation, not luteal maintenance.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'hCG is secreted by which cells of the placenta?',o:['Cytotrophoblasts','Syncytiotrophoblasts','Decidual cells','Amniotic cells'],a:1,
e:`Syncytiotrophoblast, the multinucleated outer trophoblast layer formed by fusion of cytotrophoblast cells, is the exclusive site of hCG synthesis. The alpha subunit is shared with LH, FSH and TSH; the unique beta subunit confers biological specificity and allows distinct measurement.<br><br>Syncytiotrophoblast also produces oestrogens, progesterone and human placental lactogen. It forms the maternal-fetal barrier for nutrient exchange, hormone secretion and immunological tolerance. Trophoblastic disease produces extreme hCG elevations from abnormal syncytiotrophoblast proliferation, useful for diagnosis and monitoring.<br><br>Cytotrophoblast cells (A) are precursors that fuse to form syncytium, not the secretory layer. Decidual cells (C) are maternal stromal cells. Amniotic cells (D) line the amniotic cavity.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The main function of progesterone during pregnancy is:',o:['Maintain endometrial lining and inhibit uterine contractions','Stimulate uterine contractions','Suppress placental development','Induce ovulation'],a:0,
e:`Progesterone maintains the secretory endometrium and decidua essential for placental support, while suppressing myometrial excitability through downregulation of gap junction proteins, oxytocin receptors and prostaglandin synthesis. This combination supports implantation and maintains uterine quiescence throughout pregnancy.<br><br>Progesterone also exerts immunomodulation favouring fetal tolerance through Th2 cytokine bias. Withdrawal of progesterone action through receptor downregulation or antagonism with mifepristone triggers labour onset. Functional progesterone withdrawal at term increases myometrial contractility and oxytocin sensitivity.<br><br>Stimulating uterine contractions (B) is opposite to progesterone action. Suppressing placental development (C) is not its function. Inducing ovulation (D) is the role of LH surge.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone stimulates breast development and ductal growth during pregnancy?',o:['Progesterone','Oxytocin','Estrogen','hCG'],a:2,
e:`Oestrogen during pregnancy stimulates ductal epithelial proliferation, branching and elongation of the breast lobular system through oestrogen receptor alpha activation, while progesterone develops the alveolar lobules. This combination prepares the breast for lactation throughout the second and third trimesters.<br><br>Human placental lactogen and prolactin contribute additional lactogenic effects. Despite high oestrogen and progesterone, lactation does not occur during pregnancy because these hormones inhibit milk secretion. Their abrupt fall after placental delivery removes inhibition, allowing prolactin-driven lactogenesis.<br><br>Progesterone (A) develops alveolar tissue, not ducts. Oxytocin (B) mediates milk ejection rather than ductal growth. hCG (D) maintains the corpus luteum and is not responsible for ductal proliferation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Placental progesterone production after the first trimester mainly depends on:',o:['Maternal pituitary gland','Placental synthesis from maternal cholesterol','Fetal adrenal gland','Ovarian corpus luteum'],a:1,
e:`After the luteal-placental shift around 7 to 10 weeks, the placenta assumes progesterone production using maternal cholesterol as substrate. Cholesterol enters syncytiotrophoblast via LDL receptors, undergoes side-chain cleavage by CYP11A1 to pregnenolone, then conversion by 3-beta-HSD to progesterone.<br><br>Placental progesterone reaches 250 mg per day at term, far exceeding corpus luteum capacity. Unlike fetal adrenal-dependent oestriol pathway, placental progesterone does not require fetal contribution. This explains why progesterone levels remain stable in fetal demise, while oestriol falls.<br><br>Maternal pituitary gland (A) does not synthesise steroid hormones. Fetal adrenal gland (C) supplies precursors for oestrogen but not progesterone. Ovarian corpus luteum (D) regresses after the luteal-placental shift.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is responsible for maintaining uterine quiescence during pregnancy?',o:['Oxytocin','LH','Progesterone','Prostaglandins'],a:2,
e:`Progesterone is the dominant hormone maintaining uterine quiescence throughout pregnancy. It inhibits myometrial contractility by downregulating gap junction connexin-43, oxytocin receptors and prostaglandin synthesis, while reducing calcium influx through smooth muscle voltage-gated channels.<br><br>This block on excitation-contraction coupling prevents preterm labour and maintains pregnancy. Progesterone receptor antagonism with mifepristone triggers labour, and functional progesterone withdrawal through receptor isoform switching is now recognised as a key event initiating term parturition rather than absolute progesterone decline.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) and prostaglandins (D) stimulate rather than inhibit contractions. LH (B) plays no role in pregnancy maintenance after corpus luteum support has shifted to placental hormone production.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Human placental lactogen (hPL) is mainly responsible for:',o:['Increasing maternal insulin resistance','Increasing maternal insulin sensitivity','Decreasing lipolysis','Suppressing fetal growth'],a:0,
e:`Human placental lactogen is a single-chain peptide hormone structurally similar to growth hormone and prolactin, secreted by syncytiotrophoblast in increasing amounts throughout pregnancy. Its dominant maternal metabolic effect is induction of peripheral insulin resistance through post-receptor signalling interference.<br><br>This raises maternal blood glucose, ensuring continuous transplacental glucose delivery to the fetus while maternal lipolysis provides free fatty acids for maternal energy needs. The diabetogenic effect intensifies during the second and third trimesters, sometimes overwhelming pancreatic compensation and producing gestational diabetes mellitus.<br><br>Increasing maternal insulin sensitivity (B) is opposite. Decreasing lipolysis (C) is opposite. Suppressing fetal growth (D) is incorrect: hPL promotes fetal growth.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone contributes to maternal lipolysis and provides energy substrates for the fetus?',o:['Oxytocin','FSH','Prolactin','hPL'],a:3,
e:`Human placental lactogen promotes maternal lipolysis by activating hormone-sensitive lipase in adipose tissue, increasing circulating free fatty acids that maternal tissues use for energy. This spares maternal glucose for transplacental fetal delivery, supporting fetal growth particularly during fasting periods.<br><br>hPL also induces maternal insulin resistance, raising blood glucose, and stimulates IGF-1 production. The combination ensures continuous fetal substrate supply while protecting against maternal hypoglycaemia between meals. hPL secretion correlates with placental mass and is reduced in placental insufficiency states.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) acts on uterine smooth muscle, not adipose. FSH (B) stimulates ovarian follicles. Prolactin (C) primarily promotes lactation, not maternal lipolysis during pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Relaxin during pregnancy primarily acts to:',o:['Relax pelvic ligaments and cervix','Stimulate uterine contractions','Inhibit placental growth','Suppress progesterone'],a:0,
e:`Relaxin, a peptide hormone produced by corpus luteum, decidua and placenta, softens the symphysis pubis, sacroiliac joints and cervix by stimulating collagen remodelling through matrix metalloproteinase upregulation. This increases pelvic outlet capacity and prepares the cervix for dilatation.<br><br>Relaxin levels peak in the first trimester at around 1,000 pg/mL and remain elevated until labour. Pelvic girdle pain in pregnancy partly reflects relaxin-induced ligament laxity. Relaxin also produces systemic vasodilation, contributing to increased renal blood flow and reduced systemic vascular resistance.<br><br>Stimulating uterine contractions (B) is the role of oxytocin and prostaglandins. Inhibiting placental growth (C) is not relaxin action. Suppressing progesterone (D) is contrary to its supportive role.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is mainly responsible for breast milk production after delivery?',o:['Oxytocin','Estrogen','Prolactin','hCG'],a:2,
e:`Prolactin from anterior pituitary lactotrophs is the primary hormone responsible for milk synthesis after delivery. It binds prolactin receptors on alveolar epithelial cells, activating JAK2-STAT5 signalling that induces transcription of milk protein genes including casein, alpha-lactalbumin and whey acidic protein.<br><br>During pregnancy, high oestrogen and progesterone prepare the breast but block lactation at alveolar level. After placental delivery, the abrupt fall in these steroids removes inhibition, allowing prolactin-driven lactogenesis II within 30 to 72 hours. Suckling maintains prolactin via neuroendocrine reflex inhibiting hypothalamic dopamine.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) mediates milk ejection from alveoli, not synthesis. Oestrogen (B) stimulates ductal growth, not milk synthesis. hCG (D) maintains corpus luteum and has no lactogenic role at term.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman in her first trimester has elevated hCG levels that maintain progesterone production from the corpus luteum. What is the primary role of progesterone during early pregnancy?',o:['Induce uterine contractions','Maintain endometrial support for implantation','Stimulate ovulation','Increase prolactin secretion'],a:1,
e:`Progesterone in early pregnancy maintains the secretory decidualised endometrium essential for blastocyst implantation and continued trophoblast invasion. It transforms endometrial stromal cells into decidual cells producing prolactin, IGFBP-1 and matrix proteins that support nutrient exchange and immune tolerance.<br><br>hCG from invading trophoblast rescues the corpus luteum, sustaining progesterone production until the placenta takes over around 7 to 10 weeks. Progesterone deficiency in early pregnancy, whether from luteal phase defect or insufficient hCG, leads to inadequate decidualisation and recurrent miscarriage.<br><br>Inducing uterine contractions (A) is opposite of progesterone action. Stimulating ovulation (C) is the role of LH. Increasing prolactin secretion (D) is not the function of progesterone.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops insulin resistance during the second trimester. Which placental hormone is mainly responsible for this metabolic change?',o:['Prolactin','FSH','hPL','Oxytocin'],a:2,
e:`Human placental lactogen is the principal cause of progressive insulin resistance during the second trimester, reaching peak effect in the third trimester when placental mass is greatest. It interferes with post-insulin-receptor signalling, requiring two to threefold increases in maternal insulin secretion.<br><br>This diabetogenic effect ensures preferential glucose transfer to the fetus and supports fetal growth. When pancreatic beta cell compensation is inadequate, gestational diabetes develops, typically diagnosed at 24 to 28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing. hPL effects regress rapidly after placental delivery.<br><br>Prolactin (A) primarily stimulates lactation. FSH (B) regulates ovarian follicles in nonpregnant cycles. Oxytocin (D) acts on uterine and breast smooth muscle, not maternal glucose metabolism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with early pregnancy loss has very low hCG levels. Which structure normally secretes this hormone?',o:['Syncytiotrophoblast','Decidua','Corpus luteum','Fetal adrenal gland'],a:0,
e:`Syncytiotrophoblast is the multinucleated outer trophoblast layer formed by fusion of mononuclear cytotrophoblast cells. It is the exclusive source of hCG, beginning secretion around day 8 after fertilisation when implantation occurs. hCG enters maternal circulation and rescues the corpus luteum.<br><br>Inadequate syncytiotrophoblast formation or function in failing pregnancies produces low or slowly rising serum hCG. Failure of hCG to double every 48 to 72 hours in early pregnancy suggests ectopic pregnancy or impending miscarriage, and discriminates these from viable intrauterine pregnancy.<br><br>Decidua (B) is maternal endometrium, not the source of hCG. Corpus luteum (C) is the target of hCG, not its source. Fetal adrenal gland (D) supplies oestriol precursors.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops hyperglycemia due to increased insulin resistance mediated by placental hormones. Which hormone contributes most significantly to this change?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Human placental lactogen','Oxytocin'],a:2,
e:`Human placental lactogen progressively elevates maternal blood glucose through induction of peripheral insulin resistance, post-insulin-receptor signalling interference and stimulation of hepatic gluconeogenesis. Effects intensify with placental mass during the second and third trimesters.<br><br>Maternal pancreatic beta cells normally compensate with two to threefold increases in insulin secretion. When this fails, gestational diabetes develops. The diabetogenic effect ensures continuous transplacental glucose delivery to the fetus while ample maternal lipolysis provides alternative substrates for maternal energy needs.<br><br>Progesterone (A) and oestrogen (B) contribute mildly but are not the primary diabetogenic hormones. Oxytocin (D) acts on uterine and breast smooth muscle and does not significantly alter maternal glucose metabolism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman experiences breast enlargement and ductal proliferation due to hormonal changes. Which hormone is mainly responsible for ductal growth?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Prolactin','Relaxin'],a:0,
e:`Oestrogen during pregnancy stimulates breast ductal proliferation, branching and elongation of the lobular system through oestrogen receptor alpha activation in mammary epithelium. Progesterone complements this by promoting alveolar lobular development, with both rising progressively to prepare for lactation.<br><br>hPL and prolactin contribute lactogenic effects. Despite high circulating oestrogen and progesterone, milk secretion is suppressed during pregnancy because these steroids inhibit alveolar prolactin signalling. Their abrupt withdrawal after placental delivery permits prolactin-driven lactogenesis II within 30 to 72 hours postpartum.<br><br>Progesterone (B) develops alveoli, not ducts. Prolactin (C) drives milk synthesis postnatally. Relaxin (D) softens connective tissue but does not stimulate ductal proliferation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman in late pregnancy has increased laxity of pelvic ligaments preparing for childbirth. Which hormone mediates this effect?',o:['Estrogen','Prolactin','Relaxin','Progesterone'],a:2,
e:`Relaxin, secreted by corpus luteum and placenta, mediates connective tissue remodelling at the symphysis pubis, sacroiliac joints and cervix. It activates matrix metalloproteinases that degrade collagen and reduce ligament tensile strength, increasing pelvic capacity for childbirth.<br><br>Levels peak in the first trimester at approximately 1,000 pg/mL, remaining elevated until labour. Relaxin also produces systemic vasodilation contributing to increased renal blood flow, reduced systemic vascular resistance and increased cardiac output, and softens the cervix preparing for ripening before parturition.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) stimulates myometrial growth but not specifically ligament softening. Prolactin (B) drives lactation. Progesterone (D) maintains uterine quiescence rather than mediating connective tissue remodelling.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman with diabetes experiences worsening hyperglycemia during pregnancy due to placental hormone effects. Which hormone antagonizes maternal insulin action?',o:['Human placental lactogen','Oxytocin','LH','TSH'],a:0,
e:`Human placental lactogen antagonises maternal insulin action by interfering with post-receptor signalling, particularly insulin receptor substrate-1 phosphorylation in muscle and adipose tissue. This requires two to threefold increases in maternal insulin secretion to maintain euglycaemia during pregnancy.<br><br>Diabetic women experience worsening glycaemic control as hPL rises with placental mass, particularly in the third trimester. Insulin requirements increase 50 to 100 percent, then fall abruptly after placental delivery. Tight glycaemic control reduces fetal macrosomia, neonatal hypoglycaemia and other diabetic pregnancy complications.<br><br>Oxytocin (B) acts on uterine smooth muscle. LH (C) regulates ovarian function in nonpregnant cycles. TSH (D) regulates thyroid hormone secretion and does not alter maternal insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient in early pregnancy undergoes ultrasound showing a functioning corpus luteum. Which hormone ensures the persistence of this structure until placental takeover?',o:['Prolactin','hCG','Estrogen','Oxytocin'],a:1,
e:`Human chorionic gonadotropin from syncytiotrophoblast binds LH receptors on corpus luteum cells, mimicking the LH signal that maintains progesterone secretion. This rescues the corpus luteum from luteolysis and sustains progesterone production until the placenta assumes this role at the luteal-placental shift.<br><br>hCG doubles every 48 to 72 hours in early pregnancy, peaking at 8 to 11 weeks at around 100,000 IU/L. Corpus luteum progesterone is essential for endometrial decidualisation and pregnancy maintenance until approximately 7 to 10 weeks, when placental progesterone production becomes adequate.<br><br>Prolactin (A) supports lactation but not corpus luteum. Oestrogen (C) does not rescue luteal function. Oxytocin (D) acts on smooth muscle, with no role in luteal maintenance.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops increased basal metabolic rate due to hormonal changes in pregnancy. Which hormone contributes to this metabolic effect?',o:['Prolactin','Oxytocin','hPL','Estrogen'],a:2,
e:`Human placental lactogen contributes to the increased basal metabolic rate of pregnancy through its growth hormone-like actions: stimulation of lipolysis, gluconeogenesis and IGF-1 production. These metabolic effects support the energy demands of fetal growth and maternal tissue accretion.<br><br>Maternal BMR rises by approximately 15 to 20 percent during pregnancy, peaking in the third trimester. Total energy requirements increase by around 300 kcal per day in the second trimester and 450 kcal in the third. Increased thyroid activity, cardiac work and progesterone-driven respiratory drive contribute additionally.<br><br>Prolactin (A) primarily affects lactation. Oxytocin (B) acts on smooth muscle. Oestrogen (D) supports uterine and breast development but contributes less to BMR than hPL does directly.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A gynecologist explains that pregnancy hormones support fetal growth while adapting maternal metabolism. Which hormone primarily promotes maternal lipolysis and increases availability of glucose to the fetus?',o:['Oxytocin','Human placental lactogen','Prolactin','FSH'],a:1,
e:`Human placental lactogen promotes maternal lipolysis through hormone-sensitive lipase activation in adipose tissue, releasing free fatty acids that maternal tissues use for energy. Combined with hPL-induced insulin resistance, this spares maternal glucose for preferential transplacental delivery to the fetus.<br><br>This metabolic adaptation supports continuous fetal glucose supply during maternal fasting. hPL secretion increases progressively with placental mass, reaching peak effect in the third trimester when fetal substrate demands are greatest. hPL also produces somatotropic effects on fetal IGF-1 promoting growth.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) acts on smooth muscle. Prolactin (C) primarily drives lactation. FSH (D) regulates ovarian follicles in nonpregnant cycles and has no significant role in maternal lipid metabolism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone increases uterine blood flow during pregnancy?',o:['Prolactin','Relaxin','Estrogen','Progesterone'],a:2,
e:`Oestrogen increases uterine blood flow during pregnancy through induction of endothelial nitric oxide synthase and prostacyclin in uterine vascular endothelium, producing vasodilation. Oestrogen also stimulates angiogenesis through vascular endothelial growth factor upregulation, expanding the uteroplacental vascular bed.<br><br>Uterine blood flow increases from approximately 50 ml per minute in nonpregnant state to 500 to 750 ml per minute at term. Inadequate spiral artery remodelling and reduced uterine perfusion are central to placental insufficiency syndromes including pre-eclampsia and fetal growth restriction.<br><br>Prolactin (A) supports lactation. Relaxin (B) contributes to systemic vasodilation but oestrogen drives the uterine-specific increase. Progesterone (D) does not significantly alter uterine blood flow.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During pregnancy, which hormone suppresses maternal immune response to allow tolerance of the fetus?',o:['Oxytocin','Progesterone','LH','FSH'],a:1,
e:`Progesterone exerts maternal immunomodulation favouring fetal tolerance: it shifts the cytokine balance from Th1 (cell-mediated, fetus-rejecting) toward Th2 (humoral, tolerogenic), induces progesterone-induced blocking factor in lymphocytes, and reduces uterine natural killer cell cytotoxicity.<br><br>This immunological adaptation prevents maternal rejection of the semi-allogeneic fetus expressing paternal HLA antigens. Disturbance of this balance is implicated in recurrent miscarriage, pre-eclampsia and other pregnancy complications. Progesterone is not the only mechanism; HLA-G expression on trophoblast and regulatory T cells also contribute substantially.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) acts on uterine and breast smooth muscle. LH (C) and FSH (D) regulate nonpregnant ovarian cycles and play no role in maternal immune tolerance.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops increased thyroid-binding globulin levels due to hormonal changes in pregnancy. Which hormone primarily stimulates this increase?',o:['Progesterone','hPL','Prolactin','Estrogen'],a:3,
e:`Oestrogen stimulates hepatic synthesis of thyroxine-binding globulin during pregnancy through oestrogen receptor activation in hepatocytes. TBG levels approximately double, increasing total thyroxine and triiodothyronine while free hormone fractions remain relatively unchanged in normal pregnancy.<br><br>This explains why thyroid function tests in pregnancy require trimester-specific reference ranges, with TSH lower in the first trimester due to hCG-mediated thyroid stimulation. Hyperthyroidism diagnosis relies on free T4 and T3 measurements rather than total values, which are misleadingly elevated by oestrogen-driven TBG increase.<br><br>Progesterone (A) does not stimulate hepatic protein synthesis significantly. hPL (B) primarily affects insulin resistance. Prolactin (C) supports lactation, not TBG synthesis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient in early pregnancy develops nausea and vomiting due to elevated levels of which hormone?',o:['hCG','Oxytocin','LH','Prolactin'],a:0,
e:`Human chorionic gonadotropin is implicated in pregnancy-related nausea and vomiting, with severity correlating with hCG levels. Conditions associated with extreme hCG elevation including molar pregnancy, multiple gestation and trophoblastic disease show increased frequency of hyperemesis gravidarum.<br><br>Mechanisms include hCG cross-reactivity with TSH receptors causing transient gestational thyrotoxicosis, direct effects on the chemoreceptor trigger zone, and contribution from oestrogen and progesterone effects on gastrointestinal motility. Symptoms typically peak between 8 and 12 weeks when hCG is highest, settling as hCG declines.<br><br>Oxytocin (B) does not cause nausea. LH (C) is suppressed during pregnancy. Prolactin (D) elevation is not associated with hyperemesis or pregnancy-related nausea.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone has structural similarity with growth hormone?',o:['Progesterone','Human placental lactogen','Estrogen','hCG'],a:1,
e:`Human placental lactogen shares 96 percent amino acid sequence homology with growth hormone and 67 percent with prolactin, reflecting evolutionary origin from a common ancestral gene. It exerts mild somatotropic and lactogenic effects through the growth hormone receptor and prolactin receptor.<br><br>This structural similarity underlies its diabetogenic action: hPL produces growth hormone-like effects on lipolysis and insulin resistance, raising maternal blood glucose for fetal supply. Despite the similarity, hPL is far less potent than growth hormone, requiring high circulating concentrations during pregnancy to achieve metabolic effects.<br><br>Progesterone (A) is a steroid hormone, structurally unrelated. Oestrogen (C) is a steroid. hCG (D) is a glycoprotein structurally similar to LH, FSH and TSH.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman has increased aldosterone secretion resulting in sodium and water retention. Which hormonal change contributes to this effect?',o:['Increased prolactin levels','Increased LH levels','Decreased hCG levels','Increased estrogen and progesterone levels'],a:3,
e:`Oestrogen stimulates hepatic angiotensinogen synthesis, increasing renin-angiotensin system activity that raises aldosterone secretion approximately threefold during pregnancy. Progesterone competes with aldosterone at mineralocorticoid receptors, partially offsetting its sodium-retaining effect and explaining why pregnancy is generally not hypertensive.<br><br>Net result is sodium and water retention contributing to plasma volume expansion of approximately 40 to 50 percent by term. This expansion supports increased uteroplacental blood flow and provides physiological reserve for blood loss at delivery. Failure of plasma volume expansion correlates with placental insufficiency.<br><br>Increased prolactin (A) does not stimulate aldosterone. Increased LH (B) is not relevant. Decreased hCG (C) occurs in late pregnancy but is not the mechanism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops physiological anemia due to plasma volume expansion. Which hormone contributes to increased renin-angiotensin activity in pregnancy?',o:['Estrogen','LH','Prolactin','Oxytocin'],a:0,
e:`Oestrogen stimulates hepatic angiotensinogen synthesis through oestrogen receptor alpha activation in hepatocytes, raising plasma angiotensinogen and angiotensin II. This activates aldosterone secretion and increases renal sodium and water retention, contributing to plasma volume expansion of 40 to 50 percent during pregnancy.<br><br>Plasma volume expansion exceeds red cell mass increase, producing physiological dilutional anaemia of pregnancy with haemoglobin nadir around 10 to 11 g/dL at 28 to 30 weeks. This increased volume supports uteroplacental perfusion and provides reserve against blood loss at delivery.<br><br>LH (B) regulates nonpregnant cycles. Prolactin (C) drives lactation. Oxytocin (D) acts on smooth muscle and is not the principal driver of renin-angiotensin activation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During pregnancy, increased progesterone causes relaxation of smooth muscles in the gastrointestinal tract leading to:',o:['Diarrhea','Increased gastric emptying','Constipation','Increased intestinal motility'],a:2,
e:`Progesterone relaxes gastrointestinal smooth muscle through inhibition of myosin light-chain kinase and reduction in calcium influx, slowing intestinal transit and promoting fluid reabsorption. This delayed colonic transit is a major contributor to constipation experienced by 25 to 40 percent of pregnant women.<br><br>Progesterone also relaxes the lower oesophageal sphincter contributing to gastro-oesophageal reflux, slows gastric emptying delaying absorption, and reduces ureteric peristalsis predisposing to urinary stasis and pyelonephritis. Iron supplementation, mechanical pressure from the gravid uterus and reduced physical activity worsen constipation.<br><br>Diarrhoea (A) is opposite. Increased gastric emptying (B) is opposite. Increased intestinal motility (D) is opposite of progesterone smooth muscle relaxation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman experiences increased respiratory drive during pregnancy due to hormonal effects. Which hormone stimulates the respiratory center?',o:['Estrogen','Oxytocin','Prolactin','Progesterone'],a:3,
e:`Progesterone directly stimulates the medullary respiratory centre, increasing tidal volume by 30 to 40 percent during pregnancy while respiratory rate remains relatively unchanged. This raises minute ventilation and produces a mild compensated respiratory alkalosis with PaCO2 around 30 mmHg by term.<br><br>The increased ventilation lowers maternal CO2, creating a partial pressure gradient that facilitates fetal CO2 transfer across the placenta. Many pregnant women experience subjective dyspnoea from this hyperventilation, particularly in the third trimester. The kidneys partially compensate by excreting bicarbonate, maintaining pH near normal physiological range.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) does not directly stimulate respiratory drive. Oxytocin (B) acts on smooth muscle. Prolactin (C) supports lactation, with no significant respiratory drive effect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A reproductive physiologist explains that hormonal changes during pregnancy coordinate maternal metabolic adaptation and fetal development. Which hormone plays the most significant role in ensuring continuous progesterone production after the first trimester?',o:['Corpus luteum','Placenta','Pituitary gland','Fetal adrenal gland'],a:1,
e:`After the luteal-placental shift around 7 to 10 weeks, the placenta assumes responsibility for progesterone production, eclipsing corpus luteum capacity. Placental progesterone synthesis reaches 250 mg per day at term, using maternal cholesterol as substrate via CYP11A1 and 3-beta-HSD enzymes in syncytiotrophoblast.<br><br>Unlike oestrogen synthesis which depends on fetal adrenal DHEAS precursors, placental progesterone is independent of fetal contribution. Progesterone levels remain stable in fetal demise, while oestriol falls reflecting fetal compromise. This independence makes placenta the dominant progesterone source throughout the second and third trimesters.<br><br>Corpus luteum (A) regresses after the luteal-placental shift. Pituitary gland (C) does not synthesise steroid hormones. Fetal adrenal gland (D) supplies oestrogen precursors.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During early pregnancy, the corpus luteum continues progesterone production primarily under the influence of:',o:['hCG','LH','Oxytocin','Prolactin'],a:0,
e:`Human chorionic gonadotropin secreted by syncytiotrophoblast binds LH receptors on corpus luteum cells with high affinity, mimicking the LH signal that maintains progesterone secretion. This rescue function prevents luteal regression and sustains progesterone production essential for early pregnancy.<br><br>hCG doubles every 48 to 72 hours after implantation, peaking at 8 to 11 weeks at around 100,000 IU/L. The corpus luteum supplies progesterone until the placenta assumes this role at the luteal-placental shift around 7 to 10 weeks, after which corpus luteum function becomes redundant.<br><br>LH (B) is suppressed during pregnancy by negative feedback. Oxytocin (C) acts on smooth muscle. Prolactin (D) supports lactation, with no role in maintaining corpus luteum.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone is structurally similar to LH and can bind LH receptors?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Prolactin','hCG'],a:3,
e:`Human chorionic gonadotropin shares the alpha subunit with LH, FSH and TSH, but its beta subunit is 80 percent homologous with LH beta. This structural similarity allows hCG to bind LH receptors on corpus luteum cells, mimicking the LH signal that maintains progesterone secretion.<br><br>This receptor cross-reactivity is the molecular basis for hCG rescue of the corpus luteum during early pregnancy. hCG also cross-reacts weakly with TSH receptors causing transient gestational thyrotoxicosis at peak hCG levels, particularly in molar pregnancy or hyperemesis gravidarum where hCG exceeds 200,000 IU/L.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) and progesterone (B) are steroid hormones, structurally unrelated. Prolactin (C) is a single-chain peptide related to growth hormone, not LH agonist.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone during pregnancy contributes to enlargement of the uterus by stimulating myometrial growth?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Relaxin','Oxytocin'],a:1,
e:`Oestrogen stimulates myometrial growth during pregnancy through oestrogen receptor alpha activation, inducing smooth muscle hyperplasia and hypertrophy. Uterine weight increases from 50 to 70 grams nonpregnant to approximately 1,000 grams at term, accommodating the growing fetus and amniotic fluid volume.<br><br>Oestrogen also stimulates uterine vascular development and increases blood flow to support the conceptus. Myometrial hypertrophy is balanced by progesterone-mediated suppression of contractility, maintaining uterine quiescence until functional progesterone withdrawal at term shifts the balance toward oestrogen-driven excitability and labour onset.<br><br>Progesterone (A) maintains uterine quiescence rather than driving growth. Relaxin (C) softens connective tissues. Oxytocin (D) stimulates contractions but does not drive cellular growth.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Progesterone during pregnancy causes relaxation of smooth muscle leading to which gastrointestinal effect?',o:['Increased gastric acidity','Increased intestinal peristalsis','Decreased intestinal motility','Increased gastric emptying'],a:2,
e:`Progesterone relaxes gastrointestinal smooth muscle by inhibiting myosin light-chain kinase and reducing calcium influx through voltage-gated channels in smooth muscle. Intestinal transit time is prolonged, allowing greater fluid reabsorption from colonic contents and promoting constipation common in pregnancy.<br><br>Progesterone-induced smooth muscle relaxation also affects oesophageal sphincter (causing reflux), gastric emptying (delayed absorption), gallbladder (slow emptying predisposing to gallstones) and ureters (predisposing to urinary stasis and pyelonephritis). These widespread effects reflect progesterone's universal action on smooth muscle during pregnancy.<br><br>Increased gastric acidity (A) is not progesterone effect. Increased peristalsis (B) is opposite. Increased gastric emptying (D) is opposite of progesterone-induced delay.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone primarily stimulates alveolar development of the breast during pregnancy?',o:['Estrogen','Oxytocin','Prolactin','Progesterone'],a:3,
e:`Progesterone during pregnancy stimulates alveolar lobular development of the breast through progesterone receptor activation in mammary epithelium. While oestrogen drives ductal proliferation, progesterone is responsible for the lobuloalveolar differentiation essential for milk synthesis after parturition.<br><br>This sequential mammary development prepares the breast for lactation. hPL and prolactin contribute additional lactogenic effects. Despite high oestrogen and progesterone, lactation does not occur during pregnancy because these steroids inhibit alveolar prolactin signalling. Their abrupt fall after delivery permits lactogenesis II within 30 to 72 hours.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) develops ducts rather than alveoli. Oxytocin (B) mediates milk ejection postnatally. Prolactin (C) drives milk synthesis after delivery, not alveolar development.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The placenta produces estrogens mainly from which fetal precursor hormone?',o:['Dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate (DHEAS)','Testosterone','Cortisol','Progesterone'],a:0,
e:`Dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate from fetal adrenal cortex is the principal precursor for placental oestrogen synthesis. The placenta lacks 17-alpha-hydroxylase and cannot synthesise androgens de novo, requiring DHEAS supply from the fetus that placental sulfatase desulfates and aromatase converts to oestrogens.<br><br>Most placental oestriol production depends on fetal adrenal DHEAS metabolised through fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation before placental aromatisation, creating the fetoplacental unit. This explains why oestriol levels reflect fetal adrenal-hepatic function: low oestriol indicates fetal compromise, while progesterone remains stable in fetal demise.<br><br>Testosterone (B) and progesterone (D) are not the major fetal precursors. Cortisol (C) is produced by fetal adrenal but is not the principal oestrogen precursor.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is responsible for increased maternal appetite and fat deposition during pregnancy?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Oxytocin','hPL'],a:3,
e:`Human placental lactogen drives maternal anabolism in early pregnancy by increasing appetite and promoting fat storage, expanding maternal fat reserves by approximately 3 to 4 kg during the first half of pregnancy. These reserves serve as energy substrate for late pregnancy and lactation.<br><br>In the second half of pregnancy, hPL action shifts toward catabolism: insulin resistance and lipolysis predominate, mobilising stored fat as free fatty acids for maternal energy while sparing glucose for transplacental fetal supply. This biphasic effect coordinates maternal metabolism with fetal demands.<br><br>Progesterone (A) contributes to appetite changes mildly. Oestrogen (B) is not the main appetite regulator. Oxytocin (C) acts on smooth muscle and has no role in fat deposition.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone produced by the placenta contributes to breast preparation for lactation and fetal growth?',o:['LH','TSH','hPL','ACTH'],a:2,
e:`Human placental lactogen contributes to breast preparation for lactation through its prolactin-receptor agonist activity, stimulating mammary epithelial development alongside oestrogen, progesterone and prolactin. It also supports fetal growth through stimulation of fetal IGF-1 production.<br><br>hPL secretion increases with placental mass, reaching peak levels in the third trimester. Beyond mammary and fetal effects, hPL drives maternal insulin resistance, lipolysis and gluconeogenesis, ensuring continuous transplacental glucose delivery to the fetus while maternal tissues utilise alternative energy substrates.<br><br>LH (A) regulates nonpregnant cycles. TSH (B) regulates thyroid hormone secretion. ACTH (D) drives adrenal cortisol production. None of these have the dual lactogenic-somatotropic activity of hPL.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The major estrogen produced during pregnancy is:',o:['Estradiol','Estriol','Estrone','Estradiol valerate'],a:1,
e:`Oestriol is the major oestrogen of pregnancy, constituting approximately 90 percent of maternal urinary oestrogens at term. It is produced by the fetoplacental unit: fetal adrenal DHEAS is 16-alpha-hydroxylated in fetal liver, then desulfated and aromatised by placental enzymes.<br><br>Oestriol concentrations rise from negligible levels nonpregnant to over 100 nmol/L at term. Maternal serum or urinary oestriol monitoring assesses fetoplacental unit integrity, with declining levels indicating fetal compromise. Unconjugated oestriol is part of triple and quadruple screening, with low values suggesting trisomy 21 or 18.<br><br>Oestradiol (A) and oestrone (C) circulate at lower concentrations during pregnancy. Oestradiol valerate (D) is a synthetic ester used in HRT, not naturally produced.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The placenta lacks which enzyme required for independent steroidogenesis, requiring fetal adrenal cooperation?',o:['Aromatase','3β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase','Cholesterol desmolase','17α-hydroxylase'],a:3,
e:`The placenta lacks 17-alpha-hydroxylase (CYP17A1), the enzyme that converts pregnenolone and progesterone to 17-hydroxylated intermediates required for androgen and subsequently oestrogen synthesis. This enzymatic deficiency prevents placental de novo oestrogen production from cholesterol.<br><br>The placenta therefore depends on fetal adrenal DHEAS as androgen precursor, which it desulfates and aromatises to oestrogens. Most oestriol production additionally requires fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation of DHEAS before placental aromatisation. This obligate cooperation between fetal and placental enzyme systems creates the fetoplacental endocrine unit.<br><br>Aromatase (A), 3-beta-HSD (B) and cholesterol desmolase (C) are all expressed in placenta and function normally, supporting placental progesterone synthesis and conversion of fetal androgens to oestrogens.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman in the first trimester has rising serum hCG levels detected in urine pregnancy tests. Which physiological process does hCG primarily support during early pregnancy?',o:['Induction of lactation','Stimulation of uterine contractions','Maintenance of corpus luteum progesterone production','Stimulation of ovulation'],a:2,
e:`Human chorionic gonadotropin in the first trimester binds LH receptors on corpus luteum cells, sustaining progesterone secretion essential for endometrial decidualisation and pregnancy maintenance. This rescue prevents luteolysis until placental progesterone production becomes adequate around 7 to 10 weeks.<br><br>Serum hCG doubles every 48 to 72 hours, peaking at 8 to 11 weeks at around 100,000 IU/L before declining as the placenta assumes progesterone production at the luteal-placental shift. Quantitative hCG monitoring allows discrimination between viable intrauterine pregnancy, ectopic pregnancy and impending miscarriage.<br><br>Inducing lactation (A) is the role of prolactin postpartum. Stimulating uterine contractions (B) is opposite of progesterone action. Stimulating ovulation (D) is the LH surge function.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops insulin resistance in the second trimester due to placental hormone activity. Which hormone is most responsible for this metabolic adaptation?',o:['Oxytocin','Prolactin','LH','hPL'],a:3,
e:`Human placental lactogen progressively elevates maternal insulin resistance during the second trimester, reaching peak effect in the third trimester when placental mass is greatest. It interferes with insulin receptor signalling, requiring two to threefold increases in maternal insulin secretion to maintain euglycaemia.<br><br>This diabetogenic effect ensures preferential glucose transfer to the fetus and supports fetal growth. When pancreatic beta cell compensation is inadequate, gestational diabetes develops, typically diagnosed at 24 to 28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing. hPL effects regress rapidly after placental delivery, reversing the metabolic state.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) acts on uterine smooth muscle. Prolactin (B) primarily stimulates lactation. LH (C) is suppressed during pregnancy and plays no role in glucose metabolism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman with severe nausea and vomiting (hyperemesis gravidarum) is found to have very high levels of which hormone?',o:['Progesterone','Oxytocin','hCG','Prolactin'],a:2,
e:`Hyperemesis gravidarum severity correlates with hCG levels, with extreme elevations seen in molar pregnancy, multiple gestation and trophoblastic disease showing increased frequency. The mechanism involves hCG cross-reactivity with TSH receptors causing transient gestational thyrotoxicosis, plus direct chemoreceptor trigger zone effects.<br><br>Severe cases require intravenous fluid resuscitation, antiemetics and thiamine supplementation to prevent Wernicke encephalopathy from prolonged vomiting. Symptoms typically improve as hCG declines after 12 weeks. Persistent severe hyperemesis warrants exclusion of molar pregnancy by ultrasound and quantitative hCG measurement, particularly when levels exceed 200,000 IU/L.<br><br>Progesterone (A) does not cause hyperemesis. Oxytocin (B) acts on smooth muscle. Prolactin (D) elevation is not associated with severe nausea and vomiting.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops increased joint laxity and pelvic ligament relaxation before delivery. Which hormone mediates this effect?',o:['hPL','Relaxin','Estrogen','Prolactin'],a:1,
e:`Relaxin from corpus luteum and placenta mediates pelvic ligament and joint laxity through matrix metalloproteinase activation that remodels collagen in the symphysis pubis, sacroiliac joints and other connective tissues. This increases pelvic outlet capacity preparing for fetal passage at delivery.<br><br>Relaxin levels peak in the first trimester at approximately 1,000 pg/mL and remain elevated until labour. Pelvic girdle pain affects 20 to 30 percent of pregnant women, partly reflecting relaxin-induced ligament laxity. Relaxin also produces systemic vasodilation contributing to increased renal blood flow and reduced systemic vascular resistance.<br><br>hPL (A) primarily affects metabolism. Oestrogen (C) stimulates myometrial growth. Prolactin (D) drives lactation, with no significant connective tissue effects.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient in late pregnancy shows elevated estriol levels in serum tests used to assess fetal well-being. Which fetal organ contributes significantly to estriol synthesis?',o:['Fetal liver','Fetal kidney','Fetal adrenal gland','Fetal pancreas'],a:2,
e:`Fetal adrenal cortex produces large amounts of dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate as the principal precursor for placental oestriol synthesis. Fetal adrenal at term weighs proportionally three to four times more than adult adrenal, with the predominant fetal zone specialised for DHEAS production.<br><br>DHEAS undergoes 16-alpha-hydroxylation in fetal liver, then desulfation and aromatisation by placental enzymes to yield oestriol. This obligate cooperation creates the fetoplacental unit. Maternal serum or urinary oestriol monitoring assesses fetoplacental unit integrity, with declining levels indicating fetal compromise or placental insufficiency.<br><br>Fetal liver (A) provides 16-alpha-hydroxylation but not the principal precursor. Fetal kidney (B) and fetal pancreas (D) play no role in placental oestrogen synthesis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During pregnancy, estrogen levels increase markedly due to placental steroidogenesis involving fetal adrenal and hepatic precursors. This mechanism is known as:',o:['Two-cell two-gonadotropin theory','Fetoplacental unit','Maternal endocrine loop','Luteal-placental shift'],a:1,
e:`Fetoplacental unit refers to the obligate cooperation between fetus and placenta for oestrogen synthesis during pregnancy. The placenta lacks 17-alpha-hydroxylase and cannot synthesise androgens from cholesterol; the fetus lacks placental aromatase. Neither can independently produce oestrogens.<br><br>Fetal adrenal DHEAS is converted by placental sulfatase and aromatase to oestrone and oestradiol. For oestriol, fetal liver first 16-alpha-hydroxylates DHEAS before placental aromatisation. This division of labour explains why oestriol monitoring assesses fetoplacental integrity, with declining levels signalling fetal or placental compromise.<br><br>Two-cell two-gonadotropin theory (A) describes nonpregnant ovarian oestrogen synthesis. Maternal endocrine loop (C) is not recognised. Luteal-placental shift (D) refers to progesterone transition.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The luteal-placental shift refers to:',o:['Transfer of progesterone production from corpus luteum to placenta','Transfer of estrogen synthesis to ovaries','Transfer of fetal adrenal hormone synthesis to placenta','Transfer of hCG production to maternal pituitary'],a:0,
e:`Luteal-placental shift describes the transition of progesterone production from corpus luteum to placenta around 7 to 10 weeks gestation. The placenta progressively assumes progesterone synthesis using maternal cholesterol as substrate via CYP11A1 and 3-beta-HSD enzymes, eventually exceeding corpus luteum capacity.<br><br>Removal of the corpus luteum before this shift causes pregnancy loss, while removal afterward does not affect pregnancy progression. By the second trimester, placental progesterone production reaches approximately 250 mg per day at term. Unlike oestrogen synthesis, progesterone production is independent of fetal contribution.<br><br>Transfer of oestrogen synthesis to ovaries (B) is incorrect. Transfer of fetal adrenal hormone synthesis (C) and transfer of hCG to maternal pituitary (D) do not occur.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone has anti-insulin effects and promotes maternal lipolysis to ensure continuous glucose supply to the fetus?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Relaxin','Human placental lactogen'],a:3,
e:`Human placental lactogen exerts anti-insulin effects by interfering with insulin receptor signalling, raising maternal blood glucose for transplacental delivery to the fetus. Simultaneously, it promotes maternal lipolysis through hormone-sensitive lipase activation, releasing free fatty acids for maternal energy needs.<br><br>This dual action ensures continuous fetal glucose supply while maternal tissues utilise alternative substrates. hPL secretion correlates with placental mass, peaking in the third trimester. Excessive hPL effects can overwhelm pancreatic beta cell compensation, producing gestational diabetes mellitus diagnosed at 24 to 28 weeks with glucose tolerance testing.<br><br>Oestrogen (A) and progesterone (B) contribute to insulin resistance mildly but are not primary diabetogenic hormones. Relaxin (C) softens connective tissues, no glucose effects.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which endocrine change in pregnancy contributes to increased thyroid-binding globulin levels?',o:['Estrogen stimulation of hepatic protein synthesis','Progesterone suppression of thyroid hormone','Increased prolactin secretion','Increased cortisol levels'],a:0,
e:`Oestrogen stimulates hepatic synthesis of thyroxine-binding globulin and other binding proteins through oestrogen receptor activation in hepatocytes during pregnancy. TBG levels approximately double, increasing total thyroxine and triiodothyronine while free hormone fractions remain relatively unchanged in normal pregnancy.<br><br>This explains why thyroid function tests in pregnancy require trimester-specific reference ranges. Oestrogen-driven hepatic protein synthesis also raises sex hormone binding globulin, cortisol-binding globulin and clotting factors, contributing to the procoagulant state of pregnancy and increased venous thromboembolism risk warranting thromboprophylaxis.<br><br>Progesterone suppression of thyroid hormone (B) does not occur. Increased prolactin (C) does not affect TBG. Increased cortisol (D) reflects placental CRH stimulation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The rise in maternal cortisol levels during pregnancy is partly due to increased secretion of which placental hormone?',o:['LH','Prolactin','Placental CRH','Oxytocin'],a:2,
e:`Placental corticotropin-releasing hormone is secreted by syncytiotrophoblast in increasing amounts throughout pregnancy, stimulating maternal pituitary ACTH and adrenal cortisol secretion. Maternal cortisol-binding globulin also rises under oestrogen influence, increasing total cortisol approximately threefold by term.<br><br>Free cortisol is also elevated, contributing to maternal metabolic adaptations and immunomodulation. Unlike hypothalamic CRH, placental CRH lacks negative feedback regulation by cortisol, allowing progressive rise. Placental CRH also drives fetal adrenal maturation through DHEAS production and is implicated in initiating parturition through the placental clock hypothesis.<br><br>LH (A) is suppressed during pregnancy. Prolactin (B) supports lactation. Oxytocin (D) acts on smooth muscle and has no role in maternal cortisol regulation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone produced by the placenta contributes significantly to fetal adrenal maturation near term?',o:['FSH','Relaxin','Prolactin','Placental CRH'],a:3,
e:`Placental corticotropin-releasing hormone stimulates fetal adrenal cortex maturation through ACTH-driven cortisol and DHEAS production. The fetal zone of the adrenal cortex enlarges progressively under placental CRH influence, supplying DHEAS as the principal precursor for placental oestrogen synthesis.<br><br>Placental CRH rises exponentially toward term, contributing to fetal lung maturation through cortisol-driven surfactant production and fetal adrenal preparation for postnatal life. The placental clock hypothesis proposes that the rate of placental CRH rise determines the timing of parturition, with accelerated rise associated with preterm labour.<br><br>FSH (A) regulates ovarian follicles in nonpregnant cycles. Relaxin (B) softens connective tissues. Prolactin (C) drives lactation, with no role in fetal adrenal maturation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During pregnancy, increased progesterone stimulates the respiratory center causing:',o:['Respiratory acidosis','Mild respiratory alkalosis','Metabolic acidosis','Hypercapnia'],a:1,
e:`Progesterone directly stimulates the medullary respiratory centre, increasing tidal volume by 30 to 40 percent during pregnancy. Minute ventilation rises, lowering maternal PaCO2 to approximately 30 mmHg and producing a mild compensated respiratory alkalosis throughout pregnancy.<br><br>The kidneys partially compensate by excreting bicarbonate, lowering serum bicarbonate to approximately 20 mEq/L and maintaining pH near 7.40 to 7.44. This hyperventilatory state creates a CO2 partial pressure gradient facilitating fetal CO2 transfer across the placenta. Many pregnant women experience subjective dyspnoea, particularly in the third trimester.<br><br>Respiratory acidosis (A), metabolic acidosis (C) and hypercapnia (D) are opposite to the actual pregnancy pattern of compensated respiratory alkalosis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman has elevated estriol levels produced through cooperation between placenta, fetal adrenal gland, and fetal liver. Which concept explains this endocrine interaction?',o:['Two-gonadotropin model','Hypothalamic-pituitary axis','Fetoplacental endocrine unit','Corpus luteum feedback mechanism'],a:2,
e:`Fetoplacental endocrine unit describes the obligate cooperation between placenta, fetal adrenal gland and fetal liver for oestriol synthesis during pregnancy. The placenta lacks 17-alpha-hydroxylase; the fetus lacks placental aromatase. Each compartment contributes specific enzymatic steps neither can perform alone.<br><br>Fetal adrenal cortex produces DHEAS, fetal liver performs 16-alpha-hydroxylation, and placenta provides desulfation and aromatisation to produce oestriol. Maternal serum or urinary oestriol monitoring assesses fetoplacental unit integrity. Declining oestriol indicates fetal compromise, while progesterone remains stable in fetal demise reflecting placental-only synthesis.<br><br>Two-gonadotropin model (A) describes nonpregnant ovarian function. Hypothalamic-pituitary axis (B) is broader. Corpus luteum feedback (D) is irrelevant.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman with placental insufficiency shows decreased estriol levels. Which physiological process is most likely impaired?',o:['Maternal prolactin secretion','Fetoplacental steroidogenesis','Oxytocin release','Corpus luteum progesterone production'],a:1,
e:`Placental insufficiency impairs fetoplacental steroidogenesis, reducing oestriol synthesis. The pathway requires fetal adrenal DHEAS, fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation and placental aromatisation. Disruption at any step lowers maternal oestriol, providing a biochemical marker of fetoplacental unit compromise.<br><br>Maternal serum oestriol monitoring detects fetal compromise, with low or falling values indicating placental insufficiency, fetal growth restriction or fetal demise. Unconjugated oestriol forms part of triple and quadruple screening for chromosomal abnormalities, with low values suggesting trisomy 21 or 18 and prompting further diagnostic testing.<br><br>Maternal prolactin (A) supports lactation. Oxytocin release (C) governs uterine contraction. Corpus luteum progesterone (D) ceases after the luteal-placental shift.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A clinician explains that progesterone maintains uterine quiescence during pregnancy partly by reducing sensitivity of the myometrium to which hormone?',o:['LH','Prolactin','FSH','Oxytocin'],a:3,
e:`Progesterone maintains uterine quiescence partly by reducing myometrial sensitivity to oxytocin. It downregulates oxytocin receptor expression on smooth muscle cells, suppresses gap junction connexin-43 needed for synchronised contractions, and inhibits prostaglandin synthesis that would otherwise amplify oxytocin action.<br><br>As pregnancy approaches term, functional progesterone withdrawal through receptor isoform switching increases myometrial oxytocin receptors twofold to threefold, raising sensitivity to circulating oxytocin. This shift, combined with rising oestrogen and prostaglandins, transforms the quiescent uterus into a contractile organ ready for labour onset.<br><br>LH (A) is suppressed during pregnancy. Prolactin (B) drives lactation. FSH (C) regulates nonpregnant ovarian cycles.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman in the third trimester develops gestational diabetes due to hormonal antagonism of insulin action. Which hormone is primarily responsible?',o:['Progesterone','Oxytocin','hPL','Relaxin'],a:2,
e:`Human placental lactogen is the dominant placental hormone responsible for gestational diabetes mellitus. It induces peripheral insulin resistance through interference with post-receptor signalling, requiring two to threefold increases in maternal insulin secretion to maintain euglycaemia during the third trimester.<br><br>When pancreatic beta cell compensation is inadequate, gestational diabetes develops, typically diagnosed at 24 to 28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing. Cortisol, oestrogen and progesterone contribute additional minor diabetogenic effects. hPL effects regress rapidly after placental delivery, reversing the diabetogenic state.<br><br>Progesterone (A) contributes mildly. Oxytocin (B) acts on smooth muscle. Relaxin (D) softens connective tissues, no glucose effects.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with abnormal placental steroidogenesis has reduced estrogen levels during pregnancy. Which fetal precursor hormone is most important for placental estrogen synthesis?',o:['Cortisol','DHEAS','Testosterone','Progesterone'],a:1,
e:`Dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate from fetal adrenal cortex is the essential precursor for placental oestrogen synthesis. The placenta lacks 17-alpha-hydroxylase and cannot synthesise androgens de novo from cholesterol; it depends entirely on fetal adrenal DHEAS supply.<br><br>Placental sulfatase removes the sulfate group, then aromatase converts the free DHEA to oestrone and oestradiol. For oestriol production, fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylates DHEAS before placental aromatisation. Reduced fetal adrenal function, anencephaly with adrenal hypoplasia, or placental sulfatase deficiency produce low maternal oestrogen.<br><br>Cortisol (A) and progesterone (D) are not the principal precursors. Testosterone (C) is converted to oestradiol but not the primary fetal source.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops increased renal blood flow and plasma volume partly due to hormonal vasodilation mediated by:',o:['LH','Prolactin','FSH','Relaxin'],a:3,
e:`Relaxin from corpus luteum and placenta produces systemic vasodilation through nitric oxide and endothelin-1 modulation, contributing to increased renal blood flow and plasma volume expansion during pregnancy. Renal blood flow rises by 50 to 80 percent and glomerular filtration rate by 40 to 50 percent.<br><br>This vasodilatory effect also reduces systemic vascular resistance, allowing the increased cardiac output of pregnancy to be accommodated without hypertension. Relaxin levels peak in the first trimester at approximately 1,000 pg/mL and remain elevated until labour. Inadequate vasodilation contributes to pre-eclampsia.<br><br>LH (A) regulates ovarian function. Prolactin (B) drives lactation. FSH (C) regulates nonpregnant follicular development.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman in late gestation shows increased uterine sensitivity to oxytocin before labor. Which hormonal change contributes to this phenomenon?',o:['Increased prolactin secretion','Increased hCG secretion','Increased estrogen to progesterone ratio','Increased cortisol suppression'],a:2,
e:`Increased oestrogen to progesterone ratio in late gestation increases myometrial sensitivity to oxytocin by upregulating oxytocin receptor expression two to threefold. Oestrogen also induces gap junction connexin-43 enabling synchronised contractions, and stimulates prostaglandin synthesis that amplifies oxytocin action.<br><br>Functional progesterone withdrawal through receptor isoform switching from PR-B (quiescence) to PR-A (contractile) precedes term labour. This shift, combined with rising placental CRH, oestrogen and prostaglandins, transforms the quiescent uterus into a contractile organ. These coordinated changes permit successful labour onset at term.<br><br>Increased prolactin (A) drives lactation. Increased hCG (B) is irrelevant in late pregnancy. Increased cortisol suppression (D) does not occur.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Progesterone plays a critical role in early pregnancy primarily by:',o:['Stimulating uterine contractions for implantation','Maintaining endometrial decidualization and suppressing uterine contractility','Increasing cervical dilation during the first trimester','Stimulating follicular development in the ovary'],a:1,
e:`Progesterone in early pregnancy maintains endometrial decidualisation by transforming stromal cells into specialised decidual cells producing prolactin, IGFBP-1 and matrix proteins essential for trophoblast invasion and nutrient exchange. It simultaneously suppresses uterine contractility through multiple mechanisms.<br><br>Progesterone downregulates gap junction connexin-43, oxytocin receptors and prostaglandin synthesis, while reducing calcium influx through smooth muscle voltage-gated channels. This suppression of myometrial excitability prevents preterm labour and supports continuation of pregnancy. Progesterone deficiency causes inadequate decidualisation, recurrent miscarriage and early pregnancy loss.<br><br>Stimulating contractions (A) is opposite. Increasing cervical dilation (C) is opposite. Stimulating follicular development (D) is the role of FSH in nonpregnant cycles.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The hormone primarily responsible for the detection of pregnancy in early pregnancy tests is:',o:['Progesterone','Human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG)','Estrogen','Human placental lactogen'],a:1,
e:`Human chorionic gonadotropin is used to detect pregnancy. Syncytiotrophoblast secretes it from day 8 after fertilisation following implantation. Maternal hCG rises rapidly, doubling every 48 to 72 hours.<br><br>Modern urinary pregnancy tests detect hCG above 25 IU/L, providing reliable detection from the first day of missed period. Quantitative serum hCG is more sensitive at 5 IU/L and monitors early pregnancy.<br><br>Estrogen (A) rises in pregnancy but is not specific for early detection. Progesterone (C) rises but is not used for diagnosis. hPL (D) is detectable only from the second trimester.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone increases progressively during pregnancy and plays a role in fetal growth and maternal metabolic adaptation?',o:['Oxytocin','Prolactin','LH','hPL'],a:3,
e:`Human placental lactogen rises progressively throughout pregnancy in proportion to placental mass, reaching peak concentrations at term. It supports fetal growth through fetal IGF-1 production and maternal metabolic adaptations.<br><br>hPL induces maternal insulin resistance, lipolysis and gluconeogenesis, sparing maternal glucose for transplacental fetal delivery while mobilising free fatty acids for maternal energy. hPL secretion is reduced in placental insufficiency.<br><br>hCG (A) peaks at 8-11 weeks then declines. Estrogen (B) and progesterone (C) rise progressively but lack the somatotropic and diabetogenic actions on maternal metabolism that hPL provides.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone produced during pregnancy increases maternal plasma renin activity leading to sodium and water retention?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','hCG','Prolactin'],a:0,
e:`Estrogen during pregnancy stimulates hepatic angiotensinogen synthesis through estrogen receptor alpha activation in hepatocytes. Increased substrate raises plasma renin activity and angiotensin II, secondarily activating aldosterone secretion.<br><br>This drives sodium and water retention essential for plasma volume expansion of 40-50%. Progesterone competes with aldosterone at mineralocorticoid receptors, partly offsetting sodium retention, which explains why pregnancy is generally not hypertensive.<br><br>Progesterone (B) does not stimulate angiotensinogen. hPL (C) primarily affects glucose and lipid metabolism. Oxytocin (D) acts on uterine and breast smooth muscle, not the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone contributes to enlargement and vascularization of the uterus during pregnancy?',o:['Oxytocin','Prolactin','FSH','Estrogen'],a:3,
e:`Estrogen during pregnancy stimulates myometrial smooth muscle hyperplasia and hypertrophy through estrogen receptor alpha, while inducing vascular endothelial growth factor expression that drives angiogenesis. Uterine weight rises from 70 to 1000 grams.<br><br>Uterine blood flow increases from 50 mL per minute nonpregnant to 500-750 mL per minute at term. Estrogen also induces endothelial nitric oxide synthase and prostacyclin in uterine vasculature, producing vasodilation.<br><br>Progesterone (A) maintains quiescence rather than driving growth. Relaxin (B) softens connective tissues. Prolactin (C) supports lactation, with no role in uterine vascular or muscular development.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The placenta converts fetal adrenal androgens into which estrogen that predominates during pregnancy?',o:['Estradiol','Estriol','Estrone','Estradiol valerate'],a:1,
e:`The placenta lacks 17-alpha-hydroxylase and depends on fetal adrenal DHEAS as androgen precursor. Placental sulfatase desulfates DHEAS, then aromatase converts it to estriol via fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation.<br><br>Estriol constitutes about 90% of maternal urinary estrogens at term, rising from negligible nonpregnant levels to over 100 nmol/L. Maternal estriol monitoring assesses fetoplacental unit integrity, with declining levels indicating fetal compromise.<br><br>Estradiol (A) and estrone (C) circulate at lower concentrations. Estradiol valerate (D) is a synthetic ester used in HRT formulations, not a naturally produced pregnancy hormone.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman at 10 weeks gestation has elevated hCG levels maintaining progesterone production from the corpus luteum. What event occurs when placental progesterone production becomes sufficient?',o:['Luteal-placental shift','Ovulation suppression','Corpus luteum degeneration immediately','Prolactin surge'],a:0,
e:`The luteal-placental shift describes transition of progesterone production from corpus luteum to placenta around 7-10 weeks. Placenta progressively assumes synthesis using maternal cholesterol via CYP11A1 and 3-beta-HSD enzymes.<br><br>hCG maintains corpus luteum progesterone secretion until placental output becomes adequate. Removal of corpus luteum before this shift causes pregnancy loss; removal afterward does not affect pregnancy. Placental progesterone reaches 250 mg per day at term.<br><br>Maternal endocrine loop (B) is not a recognised concept. Two-cell two-gonadotropin theory (C) describes nonpregnant ovarian estrogen synthesis. Fetoplacental unit (D) refers to estrogen synthesis specifically.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops insulin resistance due to placental hormones. Which hormone is most responsible for antagonizing maternal insulin action?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Relaxin','Human placental lactogen'],a:3,
e:`Human placental lactogen interferes with post-insulin-receptor signalling, particularly insulin receptor substrate-1 phosphorylation in muscle and adipose tissue. This induces peripheral insulin resistance, requiring two to threefold increases in maternal insulin secretion.<br><br>Effects intensify in second and third trimesters with placental mass. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops, diagnosed at 24-28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing. hPL effects regress rapidly after placental delivery.<br><br>Estrogen (A) and progesterone (B) contribute mildly but are not the primary diabetogenic hormones. Prolactin (C) primarily stimulates lactation, not maternal insulin resistance during pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman has severe nausea and vomiting in the first trimester due to elevated levels of which hormone?',o:['Progesterone','Prolactin','hCG','Oxytocin'],a:2,
e:`Hyperemesis gravidarum severity correlates with hCG levels. Conditions with extreme hCG elevation including molar pregnancy, multiple gestation and trophoblastic disease show increased frequency of severe nausea and vomiting in early pregnancy.<br><br>Mechanisms include hCG cross-reactivity with TSH receptors causing transient gestational thyrotoxicosis and direct effects on the chemoreceptor trigger zone. Symptoms peak between 8-12 weeks when hCG is highest, settling as hCG declines toward second trimester.<br><br>Progesterone (A) does not cause hyperemesis. Oxytocin (B) acts on smooth muscle. Prolactin (D) elevation in pregnancy is not associated with severe nausea and vomiting in this clinical context.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops relaxation of pelvic ligaments and symphysis pubis to facilitate childbirth. Which hormone causes this physiological change?',o:['Oxytocin','Progesterone','hPL','Relaxin'],a:3,
e:`Relaxin from corpus luteum and placenta mediates pelvic ligament laxity through matrix metalloproteinase activation that remodels collagen in symphysis pubis, sacroiliac joints and other connective tissues. This increases pelvic outlet capacity for childbirth.<br><br>Levels peak in the first trimester at 1,000 pg/mL and remain elevated until labour. Pelvic girdle pain affects 20-30% of pregnant women, partly reflecting relaxin-induced laxity. Relaxin also produces systemic vasodilation contributing to increased renal blood flow.<br><br>Estrogen (A) stimulates myometrial growth. Progesterone (B) maintains uterine quiescence. Prolactin (C) drives lactation, with no significant connective tissue remodelling effects during pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops increased basal metabolic rate due to hormonal changes during pregnancy. Which hormone contributes significantly to this metabolic effect?',o:['Oxytocin','LH','Human placental lactogen','Prolactin'],a:2,
e:`Human placental lactogen increases basal metabolic rate during pregnancy through growth hormone-like actions including stimulation of lipolysis, gluconeogenesis and IGF-1 production. These metabolic effects support energy demands of fetal growth and maternal tissue accretion.<br><br>Maternal BMR rises 15-20% during pregnancy, peaking in third trimester. Total energy requirements increase by 300 kcal/day in second trimester and 450 kcal/day in third. Increased thyroid activity and progesterone-driven respiratory drive contribute additionally to higher metabolic rate.<br><br>Estrogen (A) supports uterine and breast development. Progesterone (B) increases respiratory drive. Prolactin (D) primarily affects lactation, contributing less to overall BMR than hPL during pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The placenta is unable to synthesize estrogens independently because it lacks which enzyme required for androgen synthesis?',o:['Aromatase','21-hydroxylase','11β-hydroxylase','17α-hydroxylase'],a:3,
e:`The placenta lacks 17-alpha-hydroxylase (CYP17A1), the enzyme converting pregnenolone and progesterone to 17-hydroxylated intermediates required for androgen and estrogen synthesis. This deficiency prevents placental de novo estrogen production from cholesterol.<br><br>The placenta therefore depends on fetal adrenal DHEAS as androgen precursor, which it desulfates and aromatises to estrogens. Most estriol production additionally requires fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation. This obligate cooperation creates the fetoplacental endocrine unit.<br><br>Aromatase (A), 3-beta-HSD (B) and cholesterol desmolase (C) are all expressed in placenta and function normally, supporting placental progesterone synthesis and conversion of fetal androgens to estrogens.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone increases toward term and contributes to the initiation of labor by stimulating fetal adrenal steroidogenesis?',o:['hPL','Placental CRH','Progesterone','Prolactin'],a:1,
e:`Placental corticotropin-releasing hormone is secreted by syncytiotrophoblast in increasing amounts toward term, stimulating fetal adrenal cortisol and DHEAS production. The fetal zone enlarges progressively, supplying DHEAS for placental estrogen synthesis.<br><br>Placental CRH rises exponentially toward term, contributing to fetal lung maturation through cortisol-driven surfactant production and to initiation of parturition. The placental clock hypothesis proposes that the rate of CRH rise determines parturition timing, with accelerated rise causing preterm labour.<br><br>Estrogen (A) stimulates myometrial growth. Oxytocin (C) acts on uterine smooth muscle directly during labour. Relaxin (D) softens connective tissues, with no role in fetal adrenal maturation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops mild respiratory alkalosis due to stimulation of the respiratory center by which hormone?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','hCG','Relaxin'],a:0,
e:`Progesterone directly stimulates the medullary respiratory centre, increasing tidal volume by 30-40% during pregnancy while respiratory rate remains relatively unchanged. Minute ventilation rises, lowering maternal PaCO2 to approximately 30 mmHg.<br><br>This produces a mild compensated respiratory alkalosis with kidneys excreting bicarbonate to maintain pH near 7.40-7.44. The hyperventilation creates a CO2 partial pressure gradient facilitating fetal CO2 transfer across placenta. Many pregnant women experience subjective dyspnoea from this hyperventilation.<br><br>Estrogen (B) does not directly stimulate respiratory drive. hPL (C) primarily affects metabolism. Prolactin (D) supports lactation, with no significant respiratory drive effect comparable to progesterone.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The increased thyroid-binding globulin levels seen in pregnancy are primarily caused by:',o:['Progesterone suppression of thyroid hormone','Increased cortisol levels','Increased prolactin secretion','Estrogen-induced hepatic protein synthesis'],a:3,
e:`Estrogen during pregnancy stimulates hepatic synthesis of thyroxine-binding globulin and other binding proteins through estrogen receptor activation. TBG levels approximately double, increasing total thyroxine and triiodothyronine while free hormone fractions remain relatively unchanged.<br><br>This explains why thyroid function tests in pregnancy require trimester-specific reference ranges. Estrogen-driven hepatic protein synthesis also raises sex hormone binding globulin, cortisol-binding globulin and clotting factors, contributing to the procoagulant state of pregnancy and increased venous thromboembolism risk.<br><br>Progesterone-suppression of thyroid (A) does not occur. Increased prolactin (B) does not affect TBG. hCG-mediated TSH stimulation (C) lowers TSH but does not raise TBG.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone contributes to increased maternal fat mobilization during pregnancy ensuring glucose availability to the fetus?',o:['Estrogen','Human placental lactogen','Progesterone','Oxytocin'],a:1,
e:`Human placental lactogen promotes maternal fat mobilization through hormone-sensitive lipase activation in adipose tissue, releasing free fatty acids that maternal tissues use for energy. This spares maternal glucose for transplacental fetal delivery.<br><br>Combined with hPL-induced insulin resistance, this metabolic adaptation supports continuous fetal glucose supply during maternal fasting. hPL secretion increases with placental mass, reaching peak in third trimester when fetal substrate demands are greatest. hPL also stimulates fetal IGF-1 promoting growth.<br><br>Estrogen (A) supports uterine and breast development. Progesterone (C) maintains quiescence. Prolactin (D) primarily drives lactation, with no significant role in maternal lipid mobilisation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman with placental insufficiency shows decreased estriol levels on maternal serum screening. Which physiological interaction is most likely impaired?',o:['Fetoplacental steroidogenesis','Maternal pituitary hormone secretion','Corpus luteum progesterone production','Oxytocin secretion'],a:0,
e:`Placental insufficiency impairs fetoplacental steroidogenesis, reducing estriol synthesis. The pathway requires fetal adrenal DHEAS, fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation and placental aromatisation. Disruption at any step lowers maternal estriol.<br><br>Maternal estriol monitoring detects fetal compromise, with low or falling values indicating placental insufficiency, fetal growth restriction or fetal demise. Unconjugated estriol forms part of triple and quadruple screening, with low values suggesting trisomy 21 or 18 prompting diagnostic testing.<br><br>Maternal prolactin (B) supports lactation independently. Oxytocin release (C) governs uterine contraction. Corpus luteum progesterone (D) ceases after the luteal-placental shift, irrelevant to estriol synthesis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient in late pregnancy has increased uterine sensitivity to oxytocin due to hormonal changes. Which hormonal shift contributes to this increased sensitivity?',o:['Increased prolactin secretion','Increased estrogen to progesterone ratio','Increased hCG secretion','Increased insulin levels'],a:1,
e:`Increased estrogen to progesterone ratio in late gestation increases myometrial sensitivity to oxytocin by upregulating oxytocin receptor expression two to threefold. Estrogen also induces gap junction connexin-43 enabling synchronised contractions.<br><br>Functional progesterone withdrawal through receptor isoform switching from PR-B (quiescence) to PR-A (contractile) precedes term labour. This shift, combined with rising placental CRH and prostaglandins, transforms the quiescent uterus into a contractile organ ready for labour onset.<br><br>Increased prolactin (A) drives lactation. Increased hCG (C) is irrelevant in late pregnancy. Increased cortisol suppression (D) does not occur; cortisol actually rises in late pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops gestational diabetes due to placental hormone-induced insulin resistance. Which hormone is primarily responsible?',o:['Progesterone','Relaxin','Prolactin','hPL'],a:3,
e:`Human placental lactogen is the dominant placental hormone responsible for gestational diabetes. It induces peripheral insulin resistance through interference with post-receptor signalling, requiring two to threefold increases in maternal insulin secretion to maintain euglycaemia.<br><br>When pancreatic beta cell compensation is inadequate, gestational diabetes develops, diagnosed at 24-28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing. Cortisol, estrogen and progesterone contribute additional minor diabetogenic effects. hPL effects regress rapidly after placental delivery.<br><br>Progesterone (A) contributes mildly. Estrogen (B) increases TBG. Prolactin (C) primarily drives lactation, with no significant maternal glucose-altering effects compared with hPL during late pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops increased renal blood flow and systemic vasodilation partly due to the effects of which hormone?',o:['LH','Prolactin','Relaxin','FSH'],a:2,
e:`Relaxin produces systemic vasodilation through nitric oxide and endothelin-1 modulation, contributing to increased renal blood flow and plasma volume expansion during pregnancy. Renal blood flow rises 50-80% and glomerular filtration rate 40-50%.<br><br>This vasodilatory effect reduces systemic vascular resistance, allowing increased cardiac output of pregnancy without hypertension. Relaxin levels peak in the first trimester at 1,000 pg/mL and remain elevated until labour. Inadequate vasodilation contributes to pre-eclampsia pathophysiology.<br><br>Estrogen (A) drives uterine vascular changes. Progesterone (B) relaxes smooth muscle but does not specifically increase renal blood flow. Prolactin (D) drives lactation, no vasodilatory action.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A reproductive physiologist explains that pregnancy hormones maintain uterine quiescence and support fetal growth while preparing the body for labor. Which hormone plays the most dominant role in preventing premature uterine contractions throughout pregnancy?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Prolactin','Oxytocin'],a:0,
e:`Progesterone is the dominant hormone maintaining uterine quiescence throughout pregnancy. It inhibits myometrial contractility by downregulating gap junction connexin-43, oxytocin receptors and prostaglandin synthesis, while reducing calcium influx through smooth muscle voltage-gated channels.<br><br>This block on excitation-contraction coupling prevents preterm labour and maintains pregnancy. Progesterone receptor antagonism with mifepristone triggers labour. Functional progesterone withdrawal through receptor isoform switching is now recognised as a key event initiating term parturition.<br><br>Estrogen (B) increases myometrial growth and oxytocin sensitivity. Oxytocin (C) and prostaglandins (D) stimulate rather than inhibit contractions, opposing progesterone's quiescent action on uterus.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During normal pregnancy, maternal blood volume increases approximately by:',o:['70%','10%','40-50%','20%'],a:2,
e:`Maternal blood volume increases approximately 40-50% during pregnancy, with plasma volume expanding more than red cell mass. Expansion begins around 6-8 weeks, accelerates through second trimester, and plateaus around 32-34 weeks at peak.<br><br>This expansion supports increased uteroplacental blood flow and provides reserve against blood loss at delivery. Estrogen-driven hepatic angiotensinogen synthesis activates renin-angiotensin-aldosterone, driving sodium and water retention. Plasma volume returns to nonpregnant levels by 6 weeks postpartum.<br><br>10-20% (A) and 20-30% (B) underestimate the actual expansion. 60-70% (D) overestimates and is not the typical physiological volume change observed during normal pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which cardiovascular change is typically seen in normal pregnancy?',o:['Increased cardiac output','Decreased cardiac output','Decreased heart rate','Decreased plasma volume'],a:0,
e:`Cardiac output increases 30-50% during pregnancy through both increased stroke volume (from plasma volume expansion) and increased heart rate (10-15 bpm above baseline). Peak cardiac output is reached around 20-24 weeks gestation.<br><br>This haemodynamic adaptation supports the increased metabolic demands of pregnancy and delivers blood to the expanded uteroplacental circulation. Cardiac output briefly rises further during labour and immediately postpartum due to autotransfusion from contracting uterus, then returns to baseline by 6 weeks postpartum.<br><br>Decreased cardiac output (B) is opposite of normal pregnancy adaptation. Decreased heart rate (C) is opposite. Decreased stroke volume (D) is opposite of the expected haemodynamic changes.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The physiological anemia of pregnancy occurs primarily due to:',o:['Decreased erythropoiesis','Increased RBC destruction','Iron deficiency','Plasma volume expansion exceeding RBC increase'],a:3,
e:`Physiological anaemia of pregnancy results from plasma volume expansion of 40-50% exceeding the smaller increase in red cell mass of approximately 30%, producing dilutional reduction in haemoglobin concentration without absolute red cell deficiency.<br><br>Haemoglobin nadir occurs at 28-30 weeks at 10-11 g/dL. This haemodilution improves blood viscosity and uteroplacental perfusion. Iron supplementation supports the increased red cell mass requirement; haemoglobin below 10.5 g/dL warrants investigation for true iron deficiency anaemia.<br><br>Decreased erythropoiesis (A) does not occur; red cell mass actually rises. Iron deficiency (B) is a separate pathology. Bone marrow suppression (C) is not a feature of normal pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which respiratory change occurs in normal pregnancy?',o:['Increased residual volume','Increased tidal volume','Decreased minute ventilation','Decreased tidal volume'],a:1,
e:`Tidal volume increases 30-40% during pregnancy due to progesterone-mediated stimulation of the medullary respiratory centre, while respiratory rate remains relatively unchanged. Minute ventilation therefore rises substantially, lowering PaCO2 to approximately 30 mmHg.<br><br>This produces a mild compensated respiratory alkalosis with renal bicarbonate excretion maintaining pH near normal. The hyperventilation creates a CO2 gradient facilitating fetal CO2 transfer across placenta. Functional residual capacity decreases due to diaphragmatic elevation by 4 cm from gravid uterus.<br><br>Decreased tidal volume (A) is opposite. Decreased respiratory rate (C) is not the typical change. Increased functional residual capacity (D) is opposite of the actual decrease in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which renal change occurs in normal pregnancy?',o:['Increased glomerular filtration rate','Decreased glomerular filtration rate','Increased serum creatinine','Decreased renal blood flow'],a:0,
e:`Glomerular filtration rate increases 40-50% during pregnancy, reaching peak by mid-second trimester. Renal plasma flow rises 50-80%, driven primarily by relaxin-mediated systemic vasodilation and reduced renal vascular resistance.<br><br>Increased GFR lowers serum creatinine and urea, with reference ranges adjusted accordingly. Renal glucose threshold falls, often producing glycosuria. Increased filtered sodium load is balanced by aldosterone-driven reabsorption. Ureteric dilatation from progesterone-mediated smooth muscle relaxation predisposes to urinary stasis and pyelonephritis.<br><br>Decreased GFR (B) is opposite. Decreased renal plasma flow (C) is opposite. Increased serum creatinine (D) is opposite of the actual decrease seen in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which gastrointestinal symptom is commonly seen due to progesterone-induced smooth muscle relaxation in pregnancy?',o:['Hyperacidity','Diarrhea','Constipation','Increased gastric emptying'],a:2,
e:`Progesterone relaxes gastrointestinal smooth muscle by inhibiting myosin light-chain kinase and reducing calcium influx, slowing intestinal transit and promoting fluid reabsorption from colonic contents. This is a major contributor to constipation experienced by 25-40% of pregnant women.<br><br>Progesterone also relaxes the lower oesophageal sphincter contributing to reflux, slows gastric emptying, and reduces gallbladder contractility predisposing to gallstones. Iron supplementation, mechanical pressure from gravid uterus and reduced physical activity worsen constipation. High-fibre diet and adequate hydration help.<br><br>Diarrhoea (A) is opposite. Increased gastric emptying (B) is opposite. Increased peristalsis (D) is opposite of progesterone-induced smooth muscle relaxation throughout the gut.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The uterus increases in weight during pregnancy from approximately 70 g to:',o:['2000 g','1000 g','500 g','300 g'],a:1,
e:`Uterine weight increases from approximately 70 grams nonpregnant to 1000 grams at term. This dramatic enlargement results from estrogen-driven smooth muscle hyperplasia and hypertrophy of myometrial cells, accommodating the growing fetus, placenta and amniotic fluid volume.<br><br>Uterine vascular bed expands in parallel through estrogen-induced vascular endothelial growth factor expression, raising uterine blood flow from 50 mL/min nonpregnant to 500-750 mL/min at term. Progesterone maintains quiescence during this expansion until functional progesterone withdrawal at term initiates labour.<br><br>500 g (A) underestimates the growth. 1500 g (C) and 2000 g (D) overestimate normal uterine weight at term, exceeding actual physiological enlargement during pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hematological change occurs during normal pregnancy?',o:['Reduced platelet aggregation','Increased bleeding time','Decreased fibrinogen levels','Increased coagulation factors'],a:3,
e:`Pregnancy is a hypercoagulable state with increased coagulation factors (fibrinogen, factor VII, VIII, IX, X, XII), reduced anticoagulants (protein S, antithrombin III) and reduced fibrinolytic activity. This evolved adaptation protects against postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br>The procoagulant state begins early and persists 6-12 weeks postpartum, increasing venous thromboembolism risk fivefold. Prophylactic anticoagulation is recommended in women with prior VTE, thrombophilia or other risk factors. D-dimer elevation in pregnancy reduces its specificity for diagnosing thromboembolic events.<br><br>Decreased platelets (A) is mild but not the dominant change. Decreased fibrinogen (B) is opposite. Decreased clotting factors (C) is opposite of the actual procoagulant state.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which metabolic change occurs during pregnancy?',o:['Increased insulin sensitivity','Reduced glucose utilization','Increased insulin resistance','Reduced lipolysis'],a:2,
e:`Pregnancy is characterised by progressive insulin resistance, particularly in second and third trimesters, driven primarily by human placental lactogen along with cortisol, estrogen and progesterone. This requires two to threefold increases in maternal insulin secretion to maintain euglycaemia.<br><br>The metabolic adaptation ensures preferential glucose transfer to the fetus through transplacental gradient. When pancreatic beta cell compensation is inadequate, gestational diabetes develops. Postpartum, insulin resistance reverses rapidly with placental delivery, though women with gestational diabetes have lifetime risk of type 2 diabetes.<br><br>Decreased insulin resistance (A) is opposite. Decreased glucose levels (B) is opposite of the diabetogenic state. Decreased lipolysis (D) is opposite; lipolysis is increased.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which endocrine gland enlarges physiologically during pregnancy?',o:['Thyroid gland','Pineal gland','Parathyroid gland','Adrenal gland'],a:0,
e:`The thyroid gland enlarges physiologically by 10-15% during pregnancy due to increased vascularity and follicular hyperplasia. hCG cross-reacts weakly with TSH receptors stimulating the thyroid, while increased renal iodine clearance and transplacental iodine transfer increase iodine demand.<br><br>Estrogen-driven TBG synthesis raises total T4 and T3 while free fractions remain unchanged. TSH falls slightly in first trimester due to hCG stimulation. Iodine supplementation 150 micrograms daily is recommended. Pre-existing thyroid disease may worsen due to increased demand.<br><br>Adrenal cortex (B) enlarges modestly but not as visibly. Pituitary gland (C) enlarges due to lactotroph hyperplasia. Pancreas (D) does not visibly enlarge during pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman in the second trimester has mild breathlessness. Which physiological respiratory change explains this symptom?',o:['Increased residual lung volume','Increased tidal volume and minute ventilation','Reduced oxygen consumption','Decreased respiratory drive'],a:1,
e:`Mild breathlessness during pregnancy results from progesterone-mediated stimulation of the medullary respiratory centre, increasing tidal volume by 30-40% and minute ventilation. The subjective dyspnoea reflects awareness of this hyperventilation rather than pathology.<br><br>PaCO2 falls to 30 mmHg, producing mild compensated respiratory alkalosis. Functional residual capacity decreases due to diaphragmatic elevation by 4 cm from the gravid uterus. Despite this, vital capacity is maintained because lower rib cage expands compensating for diaphragmatic displacement.<br><br>Decreased FRC alone (A) does not directly cause breathlessness. Decreased oxygen saturation (C) does not occur in normal pregnancy. Increased respiratory rate (D) is not the dominant change.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman is found to have mild anemia with hemoglobin slightly reduced but normal iron stores. What is the most likely explanation?',o:['Chronic blood loss','Bone marrow suppression','Hemodilution due to plasma volume expansion','Hemolytic anemia'],a:2,
e:`Mild anaemia in pregnancy results from haemodilution: plasma volume expansion of 40-50% exceeds the smaller red cell mass increase of about 30%. This produces dilutional reduction in haemoglobin concentration without absolute red cell deficiency.<br><br>Haemoglobin nadir at 28-30 weeks reaches 10-11 g/dL, with mean corpuscular volume preserved unless true iron deficiency coexists. The haemodilution improves blood viscosity and uteroplacental perfusion. Haemoglobin below 10.5 g/dL warrants investigation for iron deficiency, the most common pathological cause.<br><br>Iron deficiency (A) is a separate pathology requiring exclusion. Decreased erythropoiesis (B) is opposite. Bone marrow suppression (D) is not a feature of normal pregnancy adaptation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops increased urinary frequency during early pregnancy. Which physiological change explains this symptom?',o:['Increased GFR','Reduced renal blood flow','Increased bladder capacity','Decreased urine production'],a:0,
e:`Increased glomerular filtration rate of 40-50% during early pregnancy raises urine output, contributing to urinary frequency. Mechanical pressure from the enlarging gravid uterus on the bladder also reduces functional bladder capacity.<br><br>Renal blood flow rises 50-80% driven by relaxin-mediated systemic vasodilation. Increased filtered sodium load is balanced by aldosterone-driven reabsorption. Ureteric and renal pelvis dilatation from progesterone-induced smooth muscle relaxation predisposes to urinary stasis and pyelonephritis during pregnancy.<br><br>Decreased renal blood flow (B) is opposite. Decreased bladder capacity alone (C) is contributory but not primary. Increased bladder muscle tone (D) is opposite of the actual relaxation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman has increased cardiac output during pregnancy. Which physiological factor contributes most to this change?',o:['Reduced venous return','Increased stroke volume','Decreased heart rate','Decreased plasma volume'],a:1,
e:`Cardiac output increases 30-50% during pregnancy primarily through increased stroke volume from plasma volume expansion, with secondary contribution from heart rate increase of 10-15 bpm above baseline. Peak cardiac output is reached around 20-24 weeks.<br><br>Estrogen-driven hepatic angiotensinogen synthesis activates renin-angiotensin-aldosterone, expanding plasma volume by 40-50%. Reduced systemic vascular resistance from progesterone and relaxin-mediated vasodilation accommodates the increased output without hypertension. Output briefly rises further during labour and immediately postpartum from autotransfusion.<br><br>Decreased heart rate (A) is opposite. Decreased blood pressure alone (C) does not increase output. Increased systemic vascular resistance (D) is opposite of the actual reduction.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman complains of heartburn due to hormonal changes. Which hormone contributes to this symptom?',o:['Oxytocin','FSH','Progesterone','Prolactin'],a:2,
e:`Heartburn in pregnancy results from progesterone-mediated relaxation of the lower oesophageal sphincter, allowing reflux of gastric contents. Progesterone also slows gastric emptying, prolonging exposure of the oesophagus to acidic gastric content.<br><br>Mechanical pressure from the gravid uterus elevating the diaphragm and increasing intra-abdominal pressure worsens reflux. Symptoms affect 40-80% of pregnant women. Lifestyle measures (small frequent meals, avoiding lying down after eating) and antacids or H2-blockers provide relief; PPIs are reserved for severe cases.<br><br>Estrogen (A) does not directly cause sphincter relaxation. hCG (B) does not affect oesophageal sphincter. Oxytocin (D) acts on uterine and breast smooth muscle, not lower oesophageal sphincter.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During pregnancy, systemic vascular resistance decreases mainly due to:',o:['Increased prolactin secretion','Progesterone-mediated vasodilation','Increased thyroid hormone levels','Increased cortisol secretion'],a:1,
e:`Systemic vascular resistance decreases 25-30% during pregnancy due to progesterone and relaxin-mediated vasodilation, plus estrogen-induced endothelial nitric oxide synthase and prostacyclin production. This accommodates the increased cardiac output without hypertension.<br><br>The reduced resistance produces mid-pregnancy decrease in blood pressure, reaching nadir at 24-28 weeks before returning to baseline by term. Progesterone directly relaxes vascular smooth muscle through inhibition of calcium influx. Inadequate vasodilation contributes to pre-eclampsia pathophysiology.<br><br>Increased estrogen alone (A) drives vasodilation but progesterone is a major contributor. Decreased plasma volume (C) is opposite. Increased catecholamines (D) would raise resistance, not lower it.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which physiological change during pregnancy contributes to lower blood pressure during mid-pregnancy?',o:['Reduced renal perfusion','Decreased cardiac output','Decreased blood volume','Decreased systemic vascular resistance'],a:3,
e:`Decreased systemic vascular resistance during pregnancy is the primary cause of mid-pregnancy reduction in blood pressure. Progesterone, relaxin, prostacyclin and nitric oxide all contribute to vascular smooth muscle relaxation, accommodating the increased cardiac output without hypertension.<br><br>Blood pressure decreases 5-10 mmHg systolic and 10-15 mmHg diastolic, reaching nadir at 24-28 weeks before returning toward baseline by term. Failure of this vasodilation contributes to pre-eclampsia, where systemic vascular resistance remains inappropriately elevated despite the haemodynamic demands.<br><br>Increased cardiac output (A) would raise rather than lower BP. Increased plasma volume (B) tends to raise BP. Decreased heart rate (C) is opposite of the actual increase.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During pregnancy, increased oxygen consumption occurs primarily due to:',o:['Increased metabolic demands of fetus and placenta','Reduced respiratory efficiency','Increased hemoglobin affinity for oxygen','Reduced maternal metabolism'],a:0,
e:`Maternal oxygen consumption increases approximately 20% during pregnancy, primarily reflecting the metabolic demands of the fetus, placenta and increased maternal cardiac and respiratory work. Basal metabolic rate rises 15-20%, peaking in third trimester.<br><br>This increased oxygen demand is met by adaptations including 30-40% rise in tidal volume, 30-50% rise in cardiac output, and 30% rise in red cell mass. Progesterone-driven hyperventilation lowers PaCO2 facilitating fetal CO2 removal, while increased 2,3-DPG enhances tissue oxygen unloading.<br><br>Decreased fetal demand (B) is opposite. Decreased maternal metabolism (C) is opposite. Decreased placental oxygen consumption (D) is opposite; placenta has high metabolic activity.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman lying supine develops dizziness and hypotension due to compression of which vessel by the gravid uterus?',o:['Portal vein','Inferior vena cava','Renal artery','Aorta'],a:1,
e:`Supine hypotensive syndrome results from gravid uterus compressing the inferior vena cava when the woman lies supine, particularly after 20 weeks. Reduced venous return decreases cardiac preload, causing hypotension, dizziness, nausea and pallor.<br><br>Symptoms resolve rapidly with left lateral positioning, which displaces the uterus off the IVC and restores venous return. Affected women should be advised to avoid supine positions during pregnancy. The syndrome is also relevant during caesarean section, where left lateral tilt of the operating table prevents intraoperative hypotension.<br><br>Aorta (A) compression contributes to reduced uterine perfusion but is not primary cause of hypotension. Renal artery (C) and superior vena cava (D) compression do not occur from the gravid uterus.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Increased renal plasma flow during pregnancy results in which laboratory finding?',o:['Reduced serum creatinine levels','Increased blood urea nitrogen','Increased serum creatinine levels','Reduced urine output'],a:0,
e:`Increased renal plasma flow and glomerular filtration rate during pregnancy reduce serum creatinine by approximately 25%, with normal pregnancy values around 35-65 micromol/L compared with 60-100 micromol/L nonpregnant. Serum urea also falls in parallel.<br><br>Trimester-specific reference ranges are essential for interpreting renal function in pregnancy; values within nonpregnant 'normal range' may indicate underlying renal impairment. Renal glucose threshold falls below filtered load, often producing glycosuria. Uric acid clearance also rises, lowering serum urate.<br><br>Increased creatinine (B) is opposite. Increased urea (C) is opposite. Increased uric acid (D) is opposite of the actual decrease seen in normal pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops mild leukocytosis during pregnancy without signs of infection. What is the most likely explanation?',o:['Bone marrow disease','Physiological increase in WBC count','Acute infection','Autoimmune disorder'],a:1,
e:`Pregnancy produces physiological leukocytosis with white cell counts rising to 9-15 × 10⁹/L, dominated by neutrophilia. Counts rise further during labour and immediately postpartum to 25 × 10⁹/L without indicating infection. The mechanism involves cortisol-induced demargination and increased granulopoiesis.<br><br>This haematological adaptation may mask infection, requiring clinical correlation rather than reliance on white cell count alone. Differential count remains important: significant left shift, toxic granulation or substantial lymphocytosis suggests pathology. C-reactive protein and procalcitonin retain diagnostic utility for bacterial infection during pregnancy.<br><br>Active infection (A) requires clinical features. Bone marrow stimulation (C) is the mechanism but not primary diagnosis. Steroid response (D) is not the typical trigger.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops mild edema of lower limbs in late pregnancy without hypertension or proteinuria. Which physiological mechanism explains this finding?',o:['Cardiac disease','Reduced plasma volume','Increased venous pressure from uterine compression','Renal failure'],a:2,
e:`Mild lower limb oedema in late pregnancy results from increased venous pressure caused by mechanical compression of pelvic veins by the gravid uterus, plus reduced colloid osmotic pressure from haemodilution and increased capillary permeability.<br><br>Affected by 50-80% of pregnant women, dependent oedema is asymmetrically worse on the right due to right-sided dextrorotation of the uterus. It improves with leg elevation, compression stockings and left lateral positioning. Sudden onset, asymmetric, painful or facial oedema warrants exclusion of pre-eclampsia, deep vein thrombosis or cardiac failure.<br><br>Heart failure (A) is pathological. Renal failure (B) requires investigation. Pre-eclampsia (D) presents with proteinuria and hypertension, distinguishing from physiological oedema.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops shortness of breath while lying on her back in late pregnancy. Which syndrome explains this symptom?',o:['Respiratory acidosis','Supine hypotensive syndrome','Pulmonary embolism','Cardiac failure'],a:1,
e:`Supine hypotensive syndrome occurs when the gravid uterus compresses the inferior vena cava in the supine position, reducing venous return, cardiac preload and systemic blood pressure. Symptoms include dizziness, breathlessness, nausea, pallor and tachycardia.<br><br>Onset is after 20 weeks, more pronounced in third trimester. The mechanism is venous, distinct from aortocaval compression which reduces uteroplacental perfusion. Left lateral positioning displaces the uterus off the IVC, rapidly restoring venous return. Avoidance of supine sleeping in late pregnancy is advised.<br><br>Pulmonary embolism (A) presents with pleuritic pain. Pre-eclampsia (C) features hypertension and proteinuria. Heart failure (D) features peripheral oedema and dyspnoea unrelated to position.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops increased pigmentation over face and abdomen (melasma and linea nigra). Which hormone contributes to this change?',o:['Prolactin','Estrogen','Melanocyte-stimulating hormone','Progesterone'],a:2,
e:`Pregnancy-related hyperpigmentation (chloasma or melasma over face, linea nigra over abdomen, darkening of areolae and external genitalia) results from increased melanocyte-stimulating hormone activity. Estrogen and progesterone stimulate melanocyte function during pregnancy.<br><br>Affected by 50-70% of pregnant women. Sun exposure worsens facial chloasma; sunscreen and broad-brimmed hats are recommended. Pigmentation typically fades over months postpartum but may persist.<br><br>Estrogen alone (A) contributes via MSH stimulation. ACTH (B) and TSH (D) are not the principal hormones causing the characteristic pregnancy-related skin pigmentation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Increased plasma volume during pregnancy begins approximately in which trimester?',o:['Third trimester','Second trimester','Postpartum period','First trimester'],a:3,
e:`Plasma volume expansion begins in the first trimester, around 6-8 weeks gestation, accelerates rapidly through the second trimester and plateaus around 32-34 weeks at peak expansion of 40-50% above nonpregnant baseline.<br><br>Estrogen-driven hepatic angiotensinogen synthesis activates renin-angiotensin-aldosterone, driving sodium and water retention. The early expansion supports trophoblast invasion and emerging uteroplacental circulation. Plasma volume expansion exceeds red cell mass increase, producing dilutional anaemia with haemoglobin nadir at 28-30 weeks.<br><br>Second trimester (A), third trimester (B), or labour onset (C) reflect later or peripheral stages; expansion actually begins much earlier in pregnancy than commonly appreciated.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The diaphragm is elevated during pregnancy by approximately:',o:['1 cm','4 cm','7 cm','2 cm'],a:1,
e:`The diaphragm is elevated approximately 4 cm during pregnancy by the gravid uterus, particularly in third trimester. This elevation reduces functional residual capacity and expiratory reserve volume, but vital capacity is preserved through compensatory expansion of the lower rib cage.<br><br>Anteroposterior and transverse chest diameters increase, and subcostal angle widens. These thoracic changes preserve lung function despite mechanical displacement. Tidal volume actually rises 30-40% due to progesterone-mediated central respiratory stimulation, increasing minute ventilation and producing the mild compensated respiratory alkalosis of pregnancy.<br><br>2 cm (A) underestimates. 6 cm (C) and 8 cm (D) overestimate normal diaphragmatic elevation, exceeding the actual physiological displacement during pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which liver function change occurs in normal pregnancy?',o:['Increased AST and ALT','Reduced albumin synthesis','Slight increase in alkaline phosphatase','Marked increase in bilirubin'],a:2,
e:`Alkaline phosphatase rises 2-4 fold during pregnancy, primarily from placental alkaline phosphatase isoenzyme produced by syncytiotrophoblast. Total ALP increases progressively, reaching peak at term, returning to nonpregnant levels by 6 weeks postpartum.<br><br>This rise is and does not indicate hepatic or bone pathology. Other liver enzymes (ALT, AST, GGT) remain normal in healthy pregnancy. Significant ALT or AST elevation warrants investigation for pre-eclampsia, HELLP syndrome, intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy, viral hepatitis or acute fatty liver of pregnancy.<br><br>Decreased albumin (A) occurs slightly from haemodilution. Increased ALT (B) suggests pathology. Decreased bilirubin (D) is not the typical change.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which coagulation factor increases significantly during pregnancy contributing to a hypercoagulable state?',o:['Fibrinogen','Factor XII deficiency','Reduced platelet function','Reduced prothrombin'],a:0,
e:`Fibrinogen rises during pregnancy, doubling from nonpregnant 2-4 g/L to 4-6 g/L at term. This contributes to the procoagulant state alongside increases in factors VII, VIII, IX, X and XII, with reduced anticoagulants protein S and antithrombin III.<br><br>The procoagulant adaptation evolved to protect against postpartum haemorrhage. It increases venous thromboembolism risk approximately fivefold, persisting 6-12 weeks postpartum. D-dimer also rises in normal pregnancy, reducing its specificity for diagnosing thromboembolic events. Trimester-specific reference ranges are needed.<br><br>Factor V (B) does not rise dramatically. Antithrombin III (C) is reduced. Protein C (D) levels remain relatively unchanged compared to fibrinogen rise.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During pregnancy, renal glycosuria may occur primarily due to:',o:['Renal tubular damage','Diabetes mellitus','Reduced insulin secretion','Increased GFR and reduced renal glucose threshold'],a:3,
e:`Renal glycosuria during pregnancy results from increased glomerular filtration rate raising filtered glucose load while tubular reabsorptive capacity remains relatively unchanged. The renal threshold for glucose effectively falls, producing glycosuria at normal blood glucose levels.<br><br>This glycosuria affects up to 50% of pregnant women and does not indicate diabetes. However, persistent glycosuria warrants formal testing with oral glucose tolerance test at 24-28 weeks to exclude gestational diabetes, family history or previous large-for-dates infant.<br><br>Decreased GFR (A) is opposite. Increased glucose threshold (B) is opposite. Increased insulin (C) does not cause glycosuria; it would lower blood glucose.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A clinician explains that maternal physiological changes during pregnancy are necessary to support fetal growth, uteroplacental circulation, and maternal adaptation. Which system shows the earliest major physiological adaptation during pregnancy?',o:['Cardiovascular system','Respiratory system','Gastrointestinal system','Renal system'],a:0,
e:`The cardiovascular system undergoes the most dramatic physiological adaptations during pregnancy, with cardiac output rising 30-50%, plasma volume expanding 40-50%, heart rate increasing 10-15 bpm, and systemic vascular resistance falling 25-30%.<br><br>These changes accommodate the metabolic demands of fetus and placenta while supporting uteroplacental perfusion. Failure of cardiovascular adaptation contributes to pre-eclampsia, fetal growth restriction and other complications. Pre-existing cardiac disease may decompensate during pregnancy.<br><br>Renal (B) and respiratory (C) systems also adapt significantly but less dramatically. Endocrine system (D) drives many adaptations but cardiovascular changes are most quantitatively pronounced overall.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During pregnancy, which change occurs in maternal heart rate?',o:['Decrease by 10-15 bpm','Increase by 10-15 bpm','No change','Decrease by 5 bpm'],a:1,
e:`Maternal heart rate increases 10-15 bpm above baseline during pregnancy, with progressive rise from first trimester reaching peak at 32 weeks. This contributes alongside increased stroke volume to the 30-50% rise in cardiac output supporting metabolic demands.<br><br>The tachycardia results from autonomic adjustments and reduced systemic vascular resistance. faster heart rates above 100 bpm at rest warrant investigation for thyrotoxicosis, anaemia, infection or cardiac pathology. Heart rate returns to nonpregnant baseline within 1-2 weeks postpartum.<br><br>Decrease by 10 bpm (A) is opposite. No change (C) is incorrect. Increase by 30-40 bpm (D) overestimates the typical physiological rise during pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which pulmonary volume decreases during pregnancy due to diaphragmatic elevation?',o:['Inspiratory capacity','Vital capacity','Tidal volume','Functional residual capacity'],a:3,
e:`Functional residual capacity decreases approximately 20% during pregnancy due to diaphragmatic elevation by 4 cm from the gravid uterus, reducing both expiratory reserve volume and residual volume. The change is most pronounced in third trimester.<br><br>Despite reduced FRC, vital capacity is preserved through compensatory expansion of the lower rib cage and widening of the subcostal angle. Tidal volume actually rises 30-40% from progesterone-mediated central respiratory stimulation, increasing minute ventilation. Reduced FRC means pregnant women desaturate faster during apnoea.<br><br>Vital capacity (A) is preserved. Tidal volume (B) increases. Total lung capacity (C) decreases only slightly compared with the more pronounced FRC reduction.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which renal structure dilates physiologically during pregnancy leading to hydroureter?',o:['Renal artery','Renal pelvis and ureters','Glomerulus','Renal cortex'],a:1,
e:`Hydronephrosis of pregnancy results from physiological dilatation of the renal pelvis and ureters due to progesterone-mediated smooth muscle relaxation, plus mechanical compression of ureters by the gravid uterus, more pronounced on the right side.<br><br>This dilatation begins in first trimester and persists until 6-12 weeks postpartum. Urinary stasis predisposes to ascending infection and pyelonephritis, the most common medical complication of pregnancy. Asymptomatic bacteriuria warrants screening and treatment to prevent pyelonephritis. Urinary tract dilatation is a normal finding on antenatal ultrasound.<br><br>Renal cortex (A) does not dilate. Bladder (C) is compressed but not dilated. Renal arteries (D) increase flow but do not structurally dilate.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which endocrine change contributes to increased calcium absorption during pregnancy?',o:['Increased parathyroid hormone','Increased prolactin','Increased insulin','Increased oxytocin'],a:0,
e:`Parathyroid hormone rises modestly during pregnancy, particularly in second and third trimesters, supporting maternal calcium balance against the substantial fetal calcium demand of approximately 30 grams transferred across pregnancy, predominantly in third trimester.<br><br>Increased PTH stimulates renal 1-alpha-hydroxylase, raising 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D and intestinal calcium absorption twofold. Calcitonin also rises, protecting maternal skeleton. Total serum calcium falls slightly due to haemodilution and reduced albumin, but ionised calcium remains stable. Calcium and vitamin D supplementation supports adequate intake.<br><br>Decreased PTH (B) is opposite. Decreased calcitonin (C) is opposite. Increased thyroid hormone (D) does not directly drive intestinal calcium absorption in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which dermatological change is commonly seen during pregnancy?',o:['Psoriasis','Alopecia','Vitiligo','Spider angiomas'],a:3,
e:`Spider angiomas (telangiectatic lesions with central arteriole and radiating capillaries) develop on chest, face and arms during pregnancy in approximately 60% of women due to estrogen-induced vascular proliferation and dilatation of small dermal blood vessels.<br><br>Palmar erythema occurs through similar estrogen-mediated mechanisms. Both findings appear in second trimester, peak in third, and resolve over months postpartum. They overlap with signs of chronic liver disease, where similar mechanisms operate (estrogen catabolism is impaired in cirrhosis), but in pregnancy they are and benign.<br><br>Striae gravidarum (A) appear but are skin stretch marks, not vascular. Linea nigra (B) and chloasma (C) are pigmentary changes, not vascular lesions.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which cardiovascular change contributes to systolic flow murmurs commonly heard in pregnancy?',o:['Reduced stroke volume','Reduced blood volume','Increased cardiac output','Increased systemic vascular resistance'],a:2,
e:`Systolic flow murmurs are commonly heard in pregnant women due to increased cardiac output of 30-50%, raising velocity of blood across cardiac valves and producing innocent flow murmurs particularly at left sternal edge, intensified by venous engorgement.<br><br>These benign flow murmurs are heard in 90% of pregnant women. Distinguishing features include systolic timing, soft intensity (grade 1-2), absence of radiation and accompanying signs. Diastolic murmurs, loud systolic murmurs (grade 3 or above), or murmurs with cardiac symptoms warrant echocardiography to exclude structural pathology.<br><br>Anaemia (A) contributes minimally. Decreased SVR (B) supports flow but is not primary mechanism. Increased preload (D) raises stroke volume contributing to but not solely causing murmurs.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Increased progesterone during pregnancy leads to which respiratory effect?',o:['Increased sensitivity of respiratory center to CO₂','Reduced respiratory rate','Decreased oxygen consumption','Reduced ventilation'],a:0,
e:`Progesterone increases sensitivity of the medullary respiratory centre to carbon dioxide during pregnancy, producing a leftward shift of the ventilatory response curve. The result is increased tidal volume by 30-40% with relatively unchanged respiratory rate.<br><br>This drives minute ventilation upward, lowering maternal PaCO2 to 30 mmHg and producing mild compensated respiratory alkalosis with renal bicarbonate excretion. The hyperventilation creates a CO2 partial pressure gradient facilitating fetal CO2 transfer across placenta. Many pregnant women experience subjective dyspnoea from this hyperventilation.<br><br>Decreased CO2 sensitivity (B) is opposite. Decreased tidal volume (C) is opposite. Increased dead space (D) is not the principal mechanism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hematologic change contributes to increased risk of thromboembolism in pregnancy?',o:['Reduced platelet count','Reduced fibrinogen','Decreased clotting factors','Hypercoagulable state'],a:3,
e:`Pregnancy is a hypercoagulable state with increased coagulation factors (fibrinogen, factor VII, VIII, IX, X, XII), reduced anticoagulants (protein S, antithrombin III) and reduced fibrinolytic activity. This procoagulant adaptation evolved to protect against postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br>Venous thromboembolism risk increases fivefold during pregnancy and persists 6-12 weeks postpartum, peaking immediately after delivery. Risk is amplified by caesarean section, obesity, immobility, prior VTE, thrombophilia and advanced age. Prophylactic low molecular weight heparin is recommended in high-risk women throughout pregnancy and puerperium.<br><br>Decreased platelets (A) is mild. Decreased fibrinogen (B) is opposite. Decreased clotting factors (C) is opposite of the actual procoagulant state.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Increased maternal lipid levels during pregnancy primarily serve to:',o:['Support fetal growth and energy supply','Reduce maternal metabolism','Decrease glucose utilization','Suppress fetal growth'],a:0,
e:`Maternal lipid levels rise progressively during pregnancy, with triglycerides increasing 2-4 fold and cholesterol rising 25-50% above nonpregnant values. These elevations are physiological and serve to support fetal growth and energy supply.<br><br>Free fatty acids from maternal lipolysis cross the placenta as substrates for fetal growth and steroidogenesis. Cholesterol provides substrate for placental progesterone synthesis. Estrogen-driven hepatic VLDL production drives the rise. Lipid levels return to nonpregnant baseline by 8-12 weeks postpartum. Hypertriglyceridaemia rarely causes pancreatitis.<br><br>Decreased atherosclerosis risk (B) is not the function. Cholesterol storage (C) is not primary purpose. Maternal weight gain (D) reflects multiple factors, not lipid elevation specifically.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A clinician explains that maternal physiological adaptations in pregnancy optimize oxygen delivery and nutrient supply to the fetus. Which maternal change contributes most to improved uteroplacental perfusion?',o:['Reduced renal blood flow','Reduced plasma volume','Increased systemic vascular resistance','Increased cardiac output'],a:3,
e:`Cardiovascular adaptations of pregnancy occur primarily through increased cardiac output of 30-50%, plasma volume expansion 40-50%, decreased systemic vascular resistance 25-30%, and heart rate increase of 10-15 bpm. These changes peak around 20-24 weeks.<br><br>These adaptations support metabolic demands of fetus and placenta while delivering blood to expanded uteroplacental circulation. Cardiac output briefly rises further during labour and immediately postpartum from autotransfusion. Failure of cardiovascular adaptation contributes to pre-eclampsia, fetal growth restriction and other placental insufficiency syndromes.<br><br>Decreased plasma volume (A) is opposite. Increased SVR (B) is opposite. Decreased heart rate (C) is opposite of the typical haemodynamic changes in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During pregnancy, plasma volume begins to increase significantly from which week of gestation?',o:['10-12 weeks','16-18 weeks','4-6 weeks','24-26 weeks'],a:2,
e:`Plasma volume expansion begins early in pregnancy, around 4-6 weeks gestation, accelerating rapidly through second trimester and plateauing around 32-34 weeks at peak expansion of 40-50% above nonpregnant baseline.<br><br>Estrogen-driven hepatic angiotensinogen synthesis activates renin-angiotensin-aldosterone, driving sodium and water retention. The early expansion supports trophoblast invasion and emerging uteroplacental circulation. Progesterone competes with aldosterone at mineralocorticoid receptors, partially offsetting sodium retention and explaining why pregnancy is not hypertensive despite RAAS activation.<br><br>12 weeks (A) is too late. 8 weeks (B) is somewhat late. 20 weeks (D) substantially underestimates the early onset of plasma volume expansion in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Cardiac output during pregnancy increases mainly due to:',o:['Decreased peripheral resistance only','Increased stroke volume and heart rate','Reduced venous return','Decreased blood volume'],a:1,
e:`Cardiac output increases 30-50% during pregnancy through both increased stroke volume from plasma volume expansion and increased heart rate of 10-15 bpm above baseline. Both contributions begin in first trimester, with peak output reached around 20-24 weeks.<br><br>Stroke volume rises early due to plasma volume expansion-driven increase in preload. Heart rate rises, reaching peak at 32 weeks. Reduced systemic vascular resistance from progesterone, relaxin and prostacyclin-mediated vasodilation accommodates the increased output without producing hypertension during pregnancy.<br><br>Increased SVR (A) is opposite. Decreased preload (C) is opposite. Decreased contractility (D) is opposite of preserved or slightly enhanced contractile function in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The peak increase in maternal cardiac output occurs approximately at:',o:['32 weeks','During labor only','12 weeks','20-24 weeks'],a:3,
e:`Maternal cardiac output peaks at approximately 20-24 weeks gestation, reaching 30-50% above nonpregnant baseline. After this peak, cardiac output is maintained relatively stable through term, though heart rate continues rising while stroke volume gradually declines.<br><br>This haemodynamic plateau coincides with peak demands of placental development and fetal growth. Pre-existing cardiac disease (mitral stenosis, cardiomyopathy) decompensates around this time when demands are maximal. During labour, cardiac output briefly rises further, with another postpartum surge from autotransfusion as uterine contraction returns blood to systemic circulation.<br><br>6-8 weeks (A) is too early. 12-16 weeks (B) is intermediate. 36-40 weeks (C) is past the peak; output remains high but does not rise further.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which vascular change contributes most to decreased systemic vascular resistance during pregnancy?',o:['Increased angiotensin II sensitivity','Increased vasopressin activity','Increased prostacyclin and nitric oxide','Reduced progesterone levels'],a:2,
e:`Decreased systemic vascular resistance during pregnancy results primarily from increased prostacyclin and nitric oxide production from vascular endothelium, mediated by estrogen-induced expression of prostacyclin synthase and endothelial nitric oxide synthase.<br><br>Progesterone and relaxin also contribute through direct smooth muscle relaxation. SVR falls 25-30%, accommodating the 30-50% rise in cardiac output without hypertension and producing mid-pregnancy decrease in blood pressure. Failure of this vasodilatory adaptation, with reduced endothelial NO and prostacyclin, contributes centrally to pre-eclampsia pathophysiology.<br><br>Increased catecholamines (A) would raise resistance. Increased angiotensin II (B) would raise resistance despite high levels. Decreased plasma volume (D) is opposite of the actual expansion.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The typical change in maternal blood pressure during mid-pregnancy is:',o:['Increase in systolic and diastolic pressure','Decrease in systolic and diastolic pressure','Increase in diastolic pressure only','No change in blood pressure'],a:1,
e:`Maternal blood pressure decreases during mid-pregnancy due to systemic vascular resistance falling 25-30% from progesterone, relaxin, prostacyclin and nitric oxide-mediated vasodilation. Both systolic and diastolic pressures fall, with diastolic decrease more pronounced.<br><br>Blood pressure falls 5-10 mmHg systolic and 10-15 mmHg diastolic, reaching nadir at 24-28 weeks, then rises gradually toward term, returning to nonpregnant baseline. Failure of vasodilation, with sustained or rising blood pressure, raises concern for chronic hypertension or evolving pre-eclampsia warranting investigation.<br><br>Increase in BP (A) is opposite. Increase in systolic only (C) is not typical. No change (D) is incorrect; mid-pregnancy decrease is universal physiological pattern.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hematological change contributes to increased oxygen-carrying capacity during pregnancy despite hemodilution?',o:['Increased erythropoiesis','Reduced RBC production','Increased platelet destruction','Reduced hemoglobin synthesis'],a:0,
e:`Maternal red cell mass increases approximately 30% during pregnancy through erythropoietin-driven erythropoiesis. Erythropoietin levels rise from 25 weeks, stimulated by mild hypoxic drive from increased oxygen demand and possibly hPL-mediated effects on bone marrow.<br><br>Increased erythropoiesis raises iron and folate demands. Daily iron requirement rises to 4-7 mg in late pregnancy, often exceeding dietary intake and requiring supplementation. Despite the rise in red cell mass, plasma volume expansion of 40-50% exceeds it, producing dilutional anaemia with haemoglobin nadir around 10-11 g/dL at 28-30 weeks.<br><br>Decreased erythropoiesis (B) is opposite. Bone marrow suppression (C) is opposite. Reduced iron stores (D) develop secondarily but are not the primary mechanism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The physiological leukocytosis seen during pregnancy primarily involves increase in:',o:['Lymphocytes','Neutrophils','Eosinophils','Basophils'],a:1,
e:`Physiological leukocytosis of pregnancy primarily involves neutrophilia. White cell counts rise to 9-15 × 10⁹/L during pregnancy and further to 25 × 10⁹/L during labour and immediately postpartum, dominated by mature neutrophils with mild left shift.<br><br>The mechanism involves cortisol-induced demargination from vascular endothelium and increased granulopoiesis. This adaptation may mask infection, requiring clinical correlation. Significant left shift, toxic granulation, lymphocytosis or eosinophilia suggests pathology. Lymphocyte count remains stable; eosinophils and basophils show no consistent change in normal pregnancy.<br><br>Lymphocytes (A), monocytes (C) and eosinophils (D) do not show the dramatic increase characteristic of pregnancy-related neutrophilia.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which coagulation factor level rises significantly during pregnancy contributing to hypercoagulability?',o:['Factor XIII','Factor XII','Factor VII','Factor II'],a:2,
e:`Factor VII levels rise significantly during pregnancy, reaching 200-1000% of nonpregnant baseline by term, the most dramatic increase among coagulation factors. This contributes to the procoagulant state alongside increases in fibrinogen, factor VIII, IX, X, XII and von Willebrand factor.<br><br>The hypercoagulable state is balanced by mild reductions in protein S and antithrombin III. Net effect is increased venous thromboembolism risk fivefold, persisting 6-12 weeks postpartum. The procoagulant adaptation evolved to protect against postpartum haemorrhage, the leading cause of maternal mortality globally.<br><br>Factor V (A) does not rise dramatically. Antithrombin III (B) is reduced. Protein C (D) levels remain relatively stable compared with the substantial factor VII rise.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which respiratory parameter increases most significantly during pregnancy?',o:['Total lung capacity','Residual volume','Functional residual capacity','Minute ventilation'],a:3,
e:`Minute ventilation increases most significantly during pregnancy, rising 40-50% above nonpregnant baseline. This results primarily from 30-40% rise in tidal volume driven by progesterone-mediated central respiratory stimulation, with respiratory rate remaining relatively unchanged.<br><br>Increased minute ventilation lowers maternal PaCO2 to 30 mmHg, producing mild compensated respiratory alkalosis with renal bicarbonate excretion maintaining pH near normal. The hyperventilation creates a CO2 partial pressure gradient facilitating fetal CO2 transfer across placenta. Many pregnant women experience subjective dyspnoea from this hyperventilation.<br><br>Respiratory rate (A) changes minimally. FRC (B) decreases. Vital capacity (C) is preserved but does not increase as dramatically as minute ventilation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Maternal oxygen consumption increases during pregnancy by approximately:',o:['20%','10%','5%','40%'],a:0,
e:`Maternal oxygen consumption increases approximately 20% during pregnancy, reflecting metabolic demands of the fetus and placenta plus increased maternal cardiac and respiratory work. Basal metabolic rate rises 15-20%, peaking in third trimester.<br><br>Adaptations to meet oxygen demand include 30-40% rise in tidal volume, 30-50% rise in cardiac output, 30% rise in red cell mass, and increased 2,3-DPG enhancing tissue oxygen unloading. Progesterone-driven hyperventilation lowers PaCO2 facilitating fetal CO2 removal across placenta.<br><br>50% (B) overestimates. 70% (C) substantially overestimates. 100% (D) overestimates the actual physiological rise in maternal oxygen consumption during pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman at 30 weeks gestation experiences dizziness when lying supine. Which physiological mechanism explains this symptom?',o:['Increased cardiac output','Reduced respiratory rate','Compression of inferior vena cava by gravid uterus','Increased renal blood flow'],a:2,
e:`Supine dizziness in late pregnancy results from gravid uterus compressing the inferior vena cava, reducing venous return, cardiac preload and systemic blood pressure. Symptoms include dizziness, breathlessness, nausea, pallor and tachycardia.<br><br>Onset is after 20 weeks, more pronounced in third trimester. Left lateral positioning displaces the uterus off the IVC, rapidly restoring venous return and resolving symptoms. Avoidance of supine sleeping in late pregnancy is advised. The syndrome is also relevant during caesarean section, where left lateral tilt prevents intraoperative hypotension.<br><br>Aortic compression (A) reduces uterine perfusion. Pulmonary embolism (B) presents with pleuritic pain. Renal artery compression (D) does not occur from gravid uterus.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman has mild edema of the ankles in the third trimester without hypertension. What is the most likely physiological cause?',o:['Cardiac failure','Increased venous pressure due to uterine compression','Renal disease','Protein deficiency'],a:1,
e:`Mild ankle oedema in third trimester results from increased venous pressure caused by mechanical compression of pelvic veins and inferior vena cava by the gravid uterus, plus reduced colloid osmotic pressure from haemodilution and increased capillary permeability.<br><br>Affecting 50-80% of pregnant women, dependent oedema is asymmetrically worse on the right due to right-sided dextrorotation of the uterus. It improves with leg elevation, compression stockings and left lateral positioning. Sudden onset, asymmetric, painful or facial oedema warrants exclusion of pre-eclampsia or deep vein thrombosis.<br><br>Heart failure (A) is pathological. Renal failure (C) requires investigation. Pre-eclampsia (D) presents with proteinuria and hypertension distinguishing it from physiological oedema.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops nasal congestion and epistaxis due to hormonal changes. Which physiological change explains this?',o:['Reduced mucosal blood flow','Increased platelet destruction','Decreased estrogen levels','Increased vascularity of nasal mucosa'],a:3,
e:`Nasal congestion and epistaxis are common pregnancy-related symptoms resulting from estrogen-induced increased vascularity of nasal mucosa, mucosal oedema and increased capillary fragility. These changes affect 20-30% of pregnant women, particularly in third trimester.<br><br>Symptoms include nasal stuffiness, rhinorrhoea, sneezing and intermittent epistaxis. Management is conservative with saline nasal sprays and humidification; topical decongestants and antihistamines should be avoided where possible. Symptoms resolve within 2 weeks postpartum. Severe or persistent epistaxis requires ENT evaluation to exclude underlying pathology or hypertension-related changes.<br><br>Decreased blood volume (A) is opposite. Bone marrow suppression (B) is unrelated. Decreased clotting (C) is opposite of pregnancy procoagulant state.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman complains of increased sweating during pregnancy. Which physiological change explains this symptom?',o:['Reduced metabolic demand','Increased basal metabolic rate','Reduced thyroid activity','Decreased blood volume'],a:1,
e:`Increased sweating during pregnancy results from elevated basal metabolic rate of 15-20%, increased peripheral blood flow from systemic vasodilation, and progesterone-mediated changes in thermoregulation. Body temperature rises slightly with progesterone influence.<br><br>This thermogenic state requires increased heat dissipation through sweating. Affected by most pregnant women in second and third trimesters. Adequate hydration, light clothing and cool environment provide relief. Postpartum, dramatic hormonal shifts produce profuse sweating during early breastfeeding period as fluid retained in pregnancy mobilises.<br><br>Decreased BMR (A) is opposite. Decreased blood flow (C) is opposite. Increased thyroid hormone (D) contributes minimally compared to overall metabolic and vascular changes.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman experiences frequent urination during early pregnancy. What is the most likely physiological cause?',o:['Reduced urine production','Aldosterone deficiency','Reduced bladder capacity','Increased renal blood flow and GFR'],a:3,
e:`Frequent urination in early pregnancy results from increased renal blood flow of 50-80% and glomerular filtration rate of 40-50%, raising urine output. Mechanical pressure from the enlarging uterus on the bladder also reduces functional bladder capacity.<br><br>Renal adaptations begin in first trimester driven by relaxin-mediated systemic vasodilation reducing renal vascular resistance. Symptoms are often most prominent in first and third trimesters; mid-pregnancy frequency is often less as the uterus rises out of the pelvis. Urinary frequency with dysuria warrants exclusion of urinary tract infection.<br><br>Decreased renal blood flow (A) is opposite. Decreased bladder tone (B) contributes minimally. Increased ADH (C) would reduce urine output, opposite of the observed change.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During pregnancy, the increase in maternal cardiac output reaches approximately:',o:['30-50%','80-90%','10-20%','60-70%'],a:0,
e:`Maternal cardiac output increases approximately 30-50% during pregnancy through both increased stroke volume from plasma volume expansion and increased heart rate of 10-15 bpm. Peak cardiac output is reached around 20-24 weeks gestation.<br><br>This haemodynamic adaptation supports the increased metabolic demands of pregnancy and delivers blood to the expanded uteroplacental circulation. Cardiac output briefly rises further during labour and immediately postpartum due to autotransfusion from contracting uterus, then returns to nonpregnant baseline by 6 weeks postpartum.<br><br>10-20% (B) and 20-30% (C) underestimate. 60-80% (D) overestimates the actual rise in maternal cardiac output during normal pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone contributes significantly to vasodilation and decreased systemic vascular resistance in pregnancy?',o:['Oxytocin','Relaxin','FSH','Prolactin'],a:1,
e:`Relaxin contributes significantly to vasodilation and decreased systemic vascular resistance during pregnancy through nitric oxide and endothelin-1 modulation, plus direct vascular smooth muscle relaxation. This accommodates the 30-50% rise in cardiac output without hypertension.<br><br>Relaxin levels peak in the first trimester at 1,000 pg/mL, remaining elevated until labour. The vasodilatory effect supports increased renal blood flow of 50-80% and glomerular filtration rate rise of 40-50%. Inadequate relaxin-mediated vasodilation contributes to pre-eclampsia pathophysiology with sustained vascular resistance.<br><br>Estrogen (A) drives endothelial NO and prostacyclin. Progesterone (C) relaxes smooth muscle. Oxytocin (D) acts on uterine and breast smooth muscle, no significant systemic vasodilation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which renal change contributes to mild glycosuria in pregnancy?',o:['Reduced renal glucose threshold','Reduced GFR','Reduced renal blood flow','Increased insulin resistance only'],a:0,
e:`Mild glycosuria in pregnancy results primarily from reduced renal glucose threshold below normal blood glucose levels, while glomerular filtration rate rises 40-50% increasing filtered glucose load. Tubular reabsorptive capacity remains relatively unchanged.<br><br>This glycosuria affects up to 50% of pregnant women and does not indicate diabetes mellitus. However, persistent glycosuria warrants formal testing with oral glucose tolerance test at 24-28 weeks to exclude gestational diabetes, family history of diabetes or previous large-for-dates infant.<br><br>Increased insulin (B) would lower blood glucose, not cause glycosuria. Decreased GFR (C) is opposite. Increased glucose threshold (D) is opposite of the actual fall.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which gastrointestinal change occurs due to progesterone effect on smooth muscle during pregnancy?',o:['Increased gastric motility','Increased gastric emptying','Decreased esophageal sphincter tone','Increased intestinal peristalsis'],a:2,
e:`Progesterone relaxes the lower oesophageal sphincter through direct smooth muscle effects, reducing sphincter tone and allowing reflux of acidic gastric contents. Combined with delayed gastric emptying and mechanical pressure from gravid uterus, this produces gastro-oesophageal reflux affecting 40-80% of pregnant women.<br><br>Progesterone also slows intestinal transit producing constipation, relaxes gallbladder predisposing to gallstones, and reduces ureteric peristalsis predisposing to urinary stasis. These widespread effects reflect progesterone's universal smooth muscle relaxant action throughout the body during pregnancy. Lifestyle measures and antacids provide symptomatic relief.<br><br>Increased gastric emptying (A) is opposite. Increased peristalsis (B) is opposite. Increased gastric acid (D) is not the primary mechanism of pregnancy-related reflux.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which endocrine adaptation contributes to increased maternal calcium absorption during pregnancy?',o:['Increased vitamin D activation','Increased insulin secretion','Reduced calcitonin levels','Reduced parathyroid hormone'],a:0,
e:`Increased maternal calcium absorption during pregnancy is supported by increased renal 1-alpha-hydroxylase activity raising 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D levels approximately twofold. This enhances intestinal calcium absorption to meet fetal demand of 30 grams across pregnancy.<br><br>Modest rise in parathyroid hormone, stimulates the renal hydroxylation. Calcitonin also rises, protecting maternal skeleton from excess resorption. Total serum calcium falls slightly due to haemodilution and reduced albumin, but ionised calcium remains stable. Calcium and vitamin D supplementation supports adequate intake.<br><br>Decreased PTH (B) is opposite. Decreased calcitonin (C) is opposite. Increased phosphate excretion (D) contributes but is not the primary calcium absorption mechanism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops spider angiomas over the chest and face. Which hormone contributes to this dermatological change?',o:['Prolactin','Oxytocin','Estrogen','Progesterone'],a:2,
e:`Spider angiomas (telangiectatic lesions with central arteriole and radiating capillaries) develop on chest, face and arms during pregnancy in approximately 60% of women due to estrogen-induced vascular proliferation and dilatation of small dermal blood vessels.<br><br>Lesions appear in second trimester, peak in third, and resolve over months postpartum. They overlap with signs of chronic liver disease, where similar mechanisms operate (estrogen catabolism is impaired in cirrhosis). In pregnancy they are and benign, requiring no intervention beyond reassurance and explanation that resolution occurs spontaneously postpartum.<br><br>Progesterone (A) does not drive vascular proliferation. hCG (B) peaks early and is not the mechanism. Cortisol (D) elevation does not produce these characteristic skin lesions.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops palmar erythema during pregnancy. This finding is primarily associated with increased levels of:',o:['Cortisol','Estrogen','Thyroxine','Aldosterone'],a:1,
e:`Palmar erythema during pregnancy results from estrogen-induced vasodilation and increased dermal capillary blood flow, producing diffuse redness over palms, particularly the thenar and hypothenar eminences. Affecting approximately 70% of pregnant women.<br><br>The mechanism mirrors that of spider angiomas with estrogen-mediated vascular proliferation and dilatation. Both findings overlap with cutaneous signs of chronic liver disease (impaired estrogen catabolism in cirrhosis). In pregnancy these are and benign, resolving over weeks to months postpartum as estrogen levels return to nonpregnant baseline.<br><br>Progesterone (A) does not drive these vascular changes. hPL (C) primarily affects metabolism. Cortisol (D) elevation does not produce palmar erythema characteristic of pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops mild respiratory alkalosis during pregnancy. Which physiological mechanism causes this change?',o:['Reduced respiratory rate','Increased carbon dioxide retention','Increased ventilation due to progesterone stimulation','Decreased oxygen consumption'],a:2,
e:`Mild respiratory alkalosis during pregnancy results from increased ventilation due to progesterone-mediated stimulation of the medullary respiratory centre. Tidal volume rises 30-40% with relatively unchanged respiratory rate, producing 40-50% rise in minute ventilation.<br><br>PaCO2 falls to 30 mmHg, with kidneys compensating through bicarbonate excretion lowering serum bicarbonate to about 20 mEq/L while pH remains near 7.40-7.44. This hyperventilation creates a CO2 gradient facilitating fetal CO2 transfer across placenta. Many pregnant women experience subjective dyspnoea from this hyperventilation.<br><br>Increased CO2 retention (A) is opposite. Decreased ventilation (B) is opposite. Metabolic alkalosis from vomiting (D) is pathological, not the physiological mechanism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops increased renal plasma flow during pregnancy. Which physiological adaptation does this support?',o:['Reduced maternal metabolism','Efficient removal of fetal metabolic waste','Reduced urine formation','Increased plasma osmolarity'],a:1,
e:`Increased renal plasma flow of 50-80% and glomerular filtration rate rise of 40-50% during pregnancy support efficient removal of fetal metabolic waste products that cross the placenta into maternal circulation, including urea and creatinine.<br><br>This adaptation maintains low serum urea and creatinine despite the increased fetal-maternal nitrogen load. Renal plasma flow is driven primarily by relaxin-mediated systemic vasodilation reducing renal vascular resistance. Increased filtered sodium and water are balanced by aldosterone and progesterone effects, while reduced renal glucose threshold often produces glycosuria.<br><br>Increased blood pressure (A) is opposite of mid-pregnancy decrease. Increased reabsorption (C) is not primary mechanism. Decreased filtration (D) is opposite.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops carpal tunnel syndrome in late pregnancy. Which physiological mechanism contributes to this condition?',o:['Fluid retention and tissue edema','Decreased plasma volume','Reduced nerve conduction','Increased muscle mass'],a:0,
e:`Carpal tunnel syndrome in late pregnancy results from fluid retention and tissue oedema producing compression of the median nerve within the carpal tunnel of the wrist. Affecting approximately 30-60% of pregnant women, particularly in third trimester.<br><br>Symptoms include nocturnal paraesthesia, numbness and tingling in median nerve distribution (thumb, index, middle and lateral half of ring finger), often relieved by shaking the hand. Wrist splinting at night provides relief. Symptoms resolve in most women within weeks postpartum as oedema reduces. Severe persistent cases may require carpal tunnel release.<br><br>Vitamin deficiency (B) is rarely cause. Median nerve injury (C) implies trauma. Diabetic neuropathy (D) requires longstanding hyperglycaemia not typical of normal pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During pregnancy, maternal red blood cell mass increases approximately by:',o:['50%','30%','20%','10%'],a:1,
e:`Maternal red cell mass increases approximately 30% during pregnancy, rising from approximately 1400 mL to 1800 mL. This is driven by erythropoietin-mediated bone marrow stimulation, with erythropoietin rising from 25 weeks gestation onwards.<br><br>Plasma volume expansion of 40-50% exceeds the smaller red cell mass increase, producing dilutional anaemia with haemoglobin nadir at 28-30 weeks. Daily iron requirement rises to 4-7 mg in late pregnancy, often exceeding dietary intake and requiring supplementation. Folic acid demand also rises to support erythropoiesis.<br><br>10% (A) and 50% (C) misestimate. 70% (D) overestimates the actual rise in maternal red cell mass during normal pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The uterine blood flow at term increases to approximately:',o:['1000 mL/min','300 mL/min','100 mL/min','500-700 mL/min'],a:3,
e:`Uterine blood flow increases dramatically during pregnancy, from approximately 50 mL per minute nonpregnant to 500-700 mL per minute at term, supporting placental gas exchange, nutrient delivery and waste removal essential for fetal development.<br><br>This haemodynamic adaptation results from estrogen-induced angiogenesis through vascular endothelial growth factor expression, plus endothelial nitric oxide synthase activation producing uterine vasodilation. Spiral artery remodelling by trophoblast invasion converts high-resistance maternal arterioles into low-resistance vessels accommodating the increased flow. Inadequate remodelling causes placental insufficiency syndromes.<br><br>50 mL/min (A) is nonpregnant flow. 100-200 mL/min (B) and 300-400 mL/min (C) underestimate the dramatic rise in uterine blood flow at term.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which respiratory change during pregnancy contributes to improved oxygen delivery to the fetus?',o:['Reduced lung capacity','Increased tidal volume','Reduced oxygen consumption','Decreased ventilation'],a:1,
e:`Increased tidal volume during pregnancy is the primary respiratory change improving oxygen delivery to maternal and fetal tissues. Tidal volume rises 30-40% driven by progesterone-mediated stimulation of the medullary respiratory centre.<br><br>Combined with unchanged respiratory rate, minute ventilation rises 40-50%. PaCO2 falls to 30 mmHg, while increased 2,3-DPG enhances tissue oxygen unloading. The hyperventilation creates a CO2 gradient facilitating fetal CO2 transfer across placenta, while higher maternal PaO2 supports oxygen delivery to the placenta and fetus.<br><br>Decreased respiratory rate (A) is not the change. Decreased FRC (C) does not improve oxygen delivery. Increased dead space (D) is not significant in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which physiological adaptation protects pregnant women from excessive bleeding during delivery?',o:['Reduced fibrinogen levels','Increased bleeding time','Hypercoagulable state','Decreased clotting factors'],a:2,
e:`Pregnancy hypercoagulable state evolved as adaptation to protect against postpartum haemorrhage. Increased coagulation factors (fibrinogen, factor VII, VIII, IX, X, XII), reduced anticoagulants (protein S, antithrombin III) and reduced fibrinolytic activity create the procoagulant state.<br><br>This adaptation is most relevant immediately after delivery when uterine bleeding from the placental bed must be rapidly arrested. Combined with myometrial contraction compressing uterine vessels, the hypercoagulable state limits postpartum blood loss. The trade-off is increased venous thromboembolism risk fivefold during pregnancy and persisting 6-12 weeks postpartum.<br><br>Increased platelets (A) is mild. Decreased fibrinogen (B) is opposite. Increased fibrinolysis (D) is opposite of the actual reduction.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Increased maternal fat storage during early pregnancy mainly serves to:',o:['Reduce insulin resistance','Provide energy reserves for fetal growth and lactation','Suppress fetal growth','Reduce maternal metabolism'],a:1,
e:`Increased maternal fat storage of approximately 3-4 kg during early pregnancy, driven primarily by hPL and progesterone, serves to provide energy reserves for fetal growth in late pregnancy and for lactation in the postpartum period.<br><br>In the second half of pregnancy, hPL action shifts toward catabolism with insulin resistance and lipolysis predominating, mobilising stored fat as free fatty acids for maternal energy while sparing glucose for transplacental fetal supply. After delivery, fat reserves continue supporting energy demands of lactation.<br><br>Maternal weight gain alone (A) is descriptive not functional. Increased BMR (C) reflects metabolism. Insulation (D) is not the primary purpose of pregnancy fat deposition.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During pregnancy, the uterus enlarges primarily due to:',o:['Increased connective tissue only','Increased fat deposition','Hypertrophy and hyperplasia of myometrial cells','Increased blood clot formation'],a:2,
e:`Uterine enlargement during pregnancy results primarily from estrogen-driven hyperplasia and hypertrophy of myometrial smooth muscle cells. Weight rises from 70 grams nonpregnant to approximately 1000 grams at term.<br><br>Stretch from the growing fetus and amniotic fluid contributes mechanically. Estrogen receptor alpha activation drives both cellular proliferation and protein synthesis. Uterine vascular bed expands in parallel through VEGF-mediated angiogenesis, raising blood flow from 50 to 700 mL/min at term.<br><br>Increased fluid alone (A) does not enlarge muscular wall. Cellular atrophy (B) is opposite. Connective tissue replacement (D) is not the dominant change in pregnancy uterine enlargement.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which change in maternal posture can reduce symptoms of supine hypotensive syndrome?',o:['Left lateral position','Right lateral position','Supine position','Trendelenburg position'],a:0,
e:`Left lateral position relieves supine hypotensive syndrome by displacing the gravid uterus off the inferior vena cava, restoring venous return and cardiac preload. This is the recommended position from 20 weeks onwards.<br><br>In supine position after 20 weeks, gravid uterus compresses IVC, reducing venous return and producing dizziness, breathlessness and pallor. Left lateral position is also used during caesarean section with operating table tilt to prevent intraoperative hypotension and maintain uteroplacental perfusion.<br><br>Right lateral (B) provides less relief due to right-sided uterine dextrorotation. Supine (C) worsens compression. Prone (D) is impractical and ineffective in late pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which physiological renal adaptation helps maintain fluid balance during pregnancy?',o:['Reduced renal plasma flow','Reduced sodium retention','Reduced renin secretion','Increased aldosterone activity'],a:3,
e:`Increased aldosterone activity during pregnancy supports fluid balance through enhanced renal sodium and water reabsorption. Estrogen-driven hepatic angiotensinogen synthesis activates renin-angiotensin-aldosterone, raising aldosterone secretion approximately threefold.<br><br>Progesterone competes with aldosterone at mineralocorticoid receptors, partially offsetting sodium retention and explaining why pregnancy is generally not hypertensive despite RAAS activation. Net effect is plasma volume expansion of 40-50% supporting uteroplacental circulation and providing reserve against blood loss at delivery.<br><br>Decreased ADH (A) is opposite. Decreased GFR (B) is opposite. Increased sodium excretion (C) is opposite of the actual sodium retention.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During pregnancy, increased progesterone leads to which change in urinary tract physiology?',o:['Reduced urine formation','Decreased bladder capacity','Ureteric dilatation and urinary stasis','Reduced renal blood flow'],a:2,
e:`Progesterone-mediated smooth muscle relaxation produces ureteric dilatation and urinary stasis during pregnancy. Mechanical compression of ureters by the gravid uterus, more pronounced on the right, contributes to physiological hydronephrosis.<br><br>This dilatation begins in first trimester and persists until 6-12 weeks postpartum. Urinary stasis predisposes to ascending infection and pyelonephritis, the most common medical complication of pregnancy. Asymptomatic bacteriuria warrants screening and treatment to prevent pyelonephritis. Urinary tract dilatation is normal on antenatal ultrasound.<br><br>Increased peristalsis (A) is opposite. Increased bladder tone (B) is opposite. Decreased GFR (D) is opposite of the actual rise in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which maternal adaptation during pregnancy improves placental perfusion?',o:['Increased uterine blood flow','Reduced plasma volume','Reduced cardiac output','Increased systemic vascular resistance'],a:0,
e:`Increased uterine blood flow during pregnancy improves placental perfusion supporting fetal growth. Flow rises from 50 mL/min nonpregnant to 500-700 mL/min at term, driven by estrogen-induced angiogenesis through VEGF expression and endothelial nitric oxide synthase activation.<br><br>Spiral artery remodelling by trophoblast invasion converts high-resistance maternal arterioles into low-resistance vessels accommodating the increased flow. Inadequate remodelling causes placental insufficiency syndromes including pre-eclampsia and fetal growth restriction with reduced uteroplacental perfusion.<br><br>Decreased blood flow (B) is opposite. Increased SVR (C) is opposite. Decreased cardiac output (D) is opposite of the actual haemodynamic changes.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which endocrine change during pregnancy contributes to increased maternal thyroid activity?',o:['Increased oxytocin secretion','Decreased thyroid-binding globulin','hCG stimulation of TSH receptors','Reduced estrogen levels'],a:2,
e:`hCG cross-reacts weakly with TSH receptors on thyroid follicular cells due to shared alpha subunit, transiently stimulating thyroid hormone production in early pregnancy. This causes mild suppression of TSH in first trimester when hCG peaks at 8-11 weeks.<br><br>Thyroid gland enlarges 10-15% physiologically. Estrogen-driven TBG synthesis raises total T4 and T3 while free fractions remain unchanged. Iodine demand rises from increased renal clearance and transplacental transfer; supplementation 150 micrograms daily is recommended. Thyroid function tests need trimester-specific reference ranges.<br><br>Decreased iodine (A) is incomplete. Decreased TBG (B) is opposite. Increased thyroid antibodies (D) reflect autoimmune disease, not normal pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which gastrointestinal change occurs due to progesterone-induced smooth muscle relaxation in pregnancy?',o:['Delayed gastric emptying','Increased gastric motility','Increased intestinal absorption','Increased bile secretion'],a:0,
e:`Delayed gastric emptying during pregnancy results from progesterone-mediated smooth muscle relaxation, particularly affecting the lower oesophageal sphincter and gastric antrum. This contributes to nausea, reflux and pregnancy-related dyspepsia symptoms.<br><br>Progesterone also slows intestinal transit producing constipation, relaxes gallbladder predisposing to gallstones, and reduces ureteric peristalsis predisposing to urinary stasis. Delayed emptying is clinically relevant during anaesthesia: full stomach risk requires rapid sequence induction in pregnant women undergoing emergency procedures from 16 weeks onwards.<br><br>Increased peristalsis (B) is opposite. Increased gastric acid (C) is not the primary mechanism. Increased absorption (D) is opposite of the actual delay in gastric emptying.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which respiratory parameter decreases during pregnancy due to diaphragmatic elevation?',o:['Minute ventilation','Functional residual capacity','Oxygen consumption','Tidal volume'],a:1,
e:`Functional residual capacity decreases approximately 20% during pregnancy due to diaphragmatic elevation by 4 cm from the gravid uterus, reducing both expiratory reserve volume and residual volume. Most pronounced in third trimester.<br><br>Despite reduced FRC, vital capacity is preserved through compensatory expansion of the lower rib cage and widening of subcostal angle. Tidal volume actually rises 30-40% from progesterone-mediated central respiratory stimulation. Reduced FRC means pregnant women desaturate faster during apnoea, important consideration during anaesthesia and intubation.<br><br>Vital capacity (A) is preserved. Tidal volume (C) increases. Total lung capacity (D) decreases only slightly compared with the more pronounced FRC reduction.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hematologic adaptation during pregnancy helps support increased oxygen delivery to maternal tissues and fetus?',o:['Increased plasma volume','Reduced erythropoietin production','Reduced RBC mass','Reduced hemoglobin synthesis'],a:0,
e:`Increased plasma volume of 40-50% during pregnancy supports increased oxygen delivery to maternal and fetal tissues by expanding the circulating volume available for cardiac output. Combined with 30% rise in red cell mass, this enhances total oxygen transport.<br><br>Estrogen-driven hepatic angiotensinogen synthesis activates renin-angiotensin-aldosterone, driving sodium and water retention. Plasma volume expansion exceeds red cell mass increase, producing physiological dilutional anaemia with haemoglobin nadir at 28-30 weeks. The volume reserve protects against blood loss at delivery.<br><br>Decreased red cell mass (B) is opposite. Decreased plasma volume (C) is opposite. Reduced cardiac output (D) is opposite of pregnancy adaptation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A clinician explains that maternal physiological changes during pregnancy optimize fetal growth, uteroplacental circulation, and maternal adaptation. Which maternal system undergoes the greatest overall physiological change during pregnancy?',o:['Musculoskeletal system','Cardiovascular system','Dermatological system','Gastrointestinal system'],a:1,
e:`The cardiovascular system shows the most dramatic physiological changes during pregnancy, with cardiac output rising 30-50%, plasma volume expanding 40-50%, heart rate increasing 10-15 bpm, and systemic vascular resistance falling 25-30%.<br><br>These adaptations support metabolic demands of fetus and placenta while delivering blood to expanded uteroplacental circulation. Pre-existing cardiac disease may decompensate during pregnancy, particularly around 28-32 weeks when haemodynamic demands peak. Failure of cardiovascular adaptation contributes to pre-eclampsia and fetal growth restriction syndromes.<br><br>Renal (A) and respiratory (C) systems also adapt but less dramatically. Endocrine system (D) drives many adaptations but cardiovascular changes are most quantitatively pronounced.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The primary site of hematopoiesis in the fetus during early gestation is:',o:['Yolk sac','Bone marrow','Liver','Spleen'],a:0,
e:`Yolk sac is the primary site of fetal haematopoiesis during early gestation, from approximately 3-6 weeks. Primitive erythroid cells with embryonic haemoglobins (Gower-1, Gower-2, Portland) are produced before the liver takes over.<br><br>Haematopoiesis then shifts to the liver from 6 weeks (mid-gestation predominant site) and to bone marrow from 20 weeks, becoming the primary site by birth. Spleen contributes from 12-30 weeks. The shift parallels haemoglobin transition from embryonic to fetal HbF and finally to adult HbA.<br><br>Bone marrow (B) takes over only from 20 weeks. Spleen (C) contributes mid-gestation. Liver (D) is the mid-gestation site, not the earliest.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'During mid-gestation, the principal site of fetal hematopoiesis is:',o:['Spleen','Bone marrow','Liver','Thymus'],a:2,
e:`Fetal liver is the principal site of haematopoiesis during mid-gestation, taking over from yolk sac at approximately 6 weeks and remaining dominant until 20-24 weeks when bone marrow assumes the role.<br><br>Hepatic haematopoiesis produces fetal red cells containing predominantly fetal haemoglobin (HbF, alpha2gamma2). Liver continues some haematopoietic activity until birth. Bone marrow becomes principal site by 20 weeks and is the sole adult site. The shift parallels haemoglobin transition from embryonic forms to HbF and finally to adult HbA postnatally.<br><br>Yolk sac (A) is the earliest. Bone marrow (B) takes over later. Spleen (D) contributes but is not the principal mid-gestation site.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The predominant hemoglobin in the fetus is:',o:['HbF','HbA2','HbA','HbS'],a:0,
e:`Fetal haemoglobin (HbF) consisting of two alpha and two gamma chains is the predominant haemoglobin in the fetus from approximately 8 weeks until birth. HbF binds 2,3-DPG less avidly than adult HbA, giving it higher oxygen affinity essential for transplacental oxygen transfer.<br><br>At birth, HbF constitutes 70-80% of total haemoglobin, declining to less than 2% by 6 months as adult HbA (alpha2beta2) takes over. The shift requires functional gamma-to-beta globin switching. Persistence of HbF occurs in hereditary persistence of fetal haemoglobin and beta-thalassemia.<br><br>HbA (B) is adult dominant. HbA2 (C) is minor. HbS (D) is sickle cell pathological variant.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which characteristic of fetal hemoglobin facilitates oxygen transfer from maternal blood to fetal blood?',o:['Higher carbon dioxide affinity','Lower oxygen affinity','Lower pH sensitivity','Higher oxygen affinity'],a:3,
e:`Fetal haemoglobin has higher oxygen affinity than adult haemoglobin because gamma chains bind 2,3-diphosphoglycerate less avidly than beta chains. This shifts the oxygen dissociation curve leftward, facilitating oxygen transfer from maternal to fetal circulation.<br><br>At maternal arterial PaO2 of approximately 100 mmHg in placental intervillous space, HbF achieves 60-70% saturation despite the relatively low fetal umbilical venous PaO2 of about 30 mmHg. This double-Bohr effect plus the larger fetal cardiac output and high HbF concentration ensure adequate fetal oxygen delivery.<br><br>Lower oxygen affinity (A) is opposite. Higher iron content (B) is incorrect. Lower CO2 binding (C) is not the main feature.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal structure shunts blood from the right atrium to the left atrium?',o:['Ductus arteriosus','Foramen ovale','Ductus venosus','Umbilical vein'],a:1,
e:`Foramen ovale is a flap-like opening in the interatrial septum that shunts oxygenated blood from right atrium to left atrium during fetal life, bypassing the non-functional pulmonary circulation. It directs blood preferentially toward the brain.<br><br>Oxygenated blood from umbilical vein flows through ductus venosus and inferior vena cava to right atrium, where the eustachian valve directs it through foramen ovale into left atrium. After birth, increased left atrial pressure from pulmonary circulation onset functionally closes the flap. Anatomic closure occurs over months.<br><br>Ductus arteriosus (A) shunts pulmonary artery to aorta. Ductus venosus (B) bypasses liver. Umbilical arteries (C) carry blood to placenta.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal vessel connects the pulmonary artery to the descending aorta?',o:['Umbilical artery','Ductus venosus','Pulmonary vein','Ductus arteriosus'],a:3,
e:`Ductus arteriosus is a fetal vessel connecting the pulmonary artery to the descending aorta, allowing blood from the right ventricle to bypass the high-resistance pulmonary circulation and reach systemic circulation. It carries about 90% of right ventricular output.<br><br>Patency is maintained by prostaglandin E2 from placenta and low fetal oxygen tension. After birth, increased oxygen tension and reduced prostaglandins trigger functional closure within 24-48 hours, with anatomic closure over 2-3 weeks. Failure of closure produces patent ductus arteriosus, the most common congenital cardiac shunt.<br><br>Foramen ovale (A) is interatrial. Ductus venosus (B) bypasses liver. Umbilical artery (C) carries blood to placenta.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The ductus venosus allows blood to bypass which fetal organ?',o:['Kidneys','Heart','Liver','Lungs'],a:2,
e:`Ductus venosus is a fetal vessel that allows oxygenated blood from the umbilical vein to bypass the hepatic sinusoids and enter the inferior vena cava directly. This delivers high-oxygen-content blood preferentially toward the foramen ovale and brain.<br><br>About 50% of umbilical venous blood traverses ductus venosus, with the remainder perfusing the fetal liver through portal sinuses. After birth, ductus venosus closes within minutes to hours due to umbilical cord clamping and changes in venous flow. It becomes the ligamentum venosum on the posterior liver surface.<br><br>Heart (A), kidney (B) and lungs (D) are not bypassed by ductus venosus; the liver is the specific organ this shunt bypasses.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal vessel carries oxygenated blood from placenta to fetus?',o:['Inferior vena cava','Umbilical artery','Ductus arteriosus','Umbilical vein'],a:3,
e:`Umbilical vein carries oxygenated blood from placenta to fetus, with PaO2 approximately 30 mmHg and oxygen saturation around 70-80%. It enters the fetal abdomen through the umbilicus, traverses the falciform ligament, and reaches the liver porta.<br><br>At the porta hepatis, blood divides between hepatic portal sinuses (perfusing fetal liver) and ductus venosus (bypassing liver to inferior vena cava). After birth, umbilical vein closes and becomes the ligamentum teres of the liver (round ligament) within the falciform ligament structure.<br><br>Umbilical artery (A) carries deoxygenated blood to placenta. Ductus venosus (B) and ductus arteriosus (C) are intra-fetal shunts, not placental connections.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal vessels carry deoxygenated blood from fetus to placenta?',o:['Pulmonary arteries','Hepatic veins','Umbilical arteries','Ductus venosus'],a:2,
e:`Umbilical arteries (paired) carry deoxygenated blood from fetal internal iliac arteries to the placenta for gas exchange and waste removal. They have lower PaO2 of approximately 15-20 mmHg with higher CO2 content than umbilical vein blood.<br><br>In utero, umbilical arteries branch from internal iliac arteries, ascending along bladder wall to umbilicus. After birth, the proximal portions remain as superior vesical arteries supplying bladder, while distal portions atrophy to medial umbilical ligaments on the anterior abdominal wall. Velocity Doppler assesses placental function.<br><br>Umbilical vein (A) is singular and oxygenated. Ductus venosus (B) bypasses liver. Pulmonary arteries (D) are intra-thoracic.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Fetal circulation is characterized by:',o:['High pulmonary vascular resistance','Equal systemic and pulmonary resistance','Low pulmonary vascular resistance','High pulmonary blood flow'],a:0,
e:`Fetal circulation features high pulmonary vascular resistance, directing blood away from non-functional fetal lungs through ductus arteriosus to systemic circulation. Pulmonary arterial vasoconstriction is maintained by low PaO2, high PaCO2 and high circulating endothelin and thromboxane.<br><br>Only 5-10% of right ventricular output reaches the pulmonary circulation in utero. After birth, lung expansion and increased oxygen tension cause rapid pulmonary vasodilation, dropping resistance and reversing the shunt direction. Failure produces persistent pulmonary hypertension of the newborn requiring inhaled nitric oxide therapy.<br><br>Low pulmonary resistance (B) is postnatal. High systemic resistance (C) is opposite. Low cardiac output (D) is incorrect; fetal output is high per kg.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with congenital heart defect has failure of closure of the foramen ovale after birth. Which physiological fetal structure is involved?',o:['Hepatic shunt','Umbilical vein','Pulmonary artery connection','Atrial septal opening'],a:3,
e:`Failure of foramen ovale closure after birth produces an atrial septal defect, specifically secundum-type ASD. Persistent patent foramen ovale occurs in 20-25% of adults but is usually small and clinically silent unless associated with paradoxical embolism.<br><br>Larger ostium secundum ASD allows left-to-right atrial shunting due to lower right-sided pressures, eventually causing right ventricular dilatation and pulmonary hypertension if untreated. Closure is achieved by transcatheter device deployment or surgical repair, typically before late teens. Echocardiography confirms diagnosis and quantifies shunt magnitude.<br><br>VSD (A) is ventricular septal defect. PDA (B) is patent ductus arteriosus. Tetralogy of Fallot (C) involves four anomalies including VSD.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus relies on placental oxygen exchange rather than lung function. Which physiological mechanism allows bypass of pulmonary circulation?',o:['Hepatic circulation','Pulmonary arteries and veins','Foramen ovale and ductus arteriosus','Coronary circulation'],a:2,
e:`Fetal reliance on placental oxygen exchange rather than lung function requires shunts that bypass the non-functional pulmonary circulation. Foramen ovale shunts blood from right atrium to left atrium, while ductus arteriosus shunts from pulmonary artery to descending aorta.<br><br>Together these shunts carry 90% of right ventricular output away from fetal lungs. Only 5-10% reaches pulmonary circulation, sufficient for lung development. After birth, increased oxygen tension and reduced prostaglandins close ductus arteriosus while rising left atrial pressure closes foramen ovale, establishing series circulation.<br><br>VSD and ASD (A) are pathological. Coronary and umbilical (B) are not bypass shunts. Aortic arch and pulmonary arteries (D) are normal vessels.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus develops anemia due to reduced hemoglobin levels. Which fetal organ normally produces most RBCs during mid-pregnancy?',o:['Bone marrow','Liver','Spleen','Thymus'],a:1,
e:`Fetal liver is the principal site of haematopoiesis during mid-gestation (6-24 weeks). Reduction in haemoglobin levels in a fetus prompts increased erythropoietin secretion stimulating compensatory haematopoiesis primarily in the liver during this period.<br><br>Bone marrow takes over as principal site from 20 weeks, becoming the dominant adult site. Fetal anaemia from rhesus haemolytic disease, parvovirus infection or alpha-thalassemia stimulates extramedullary haematopoiesis with hepatomegaly and splenomegaly. Severe fetal anaemia presents with hydrops fetalis from heart failure and reduced colloid osmotic pressure.<br><br>Spleen (A) contributes minor amounts. Bone marrow (C) takes over later. Yolk sac (D) is the earliest site, not mid-gestation.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A newborn fails to close the ductus arteriosus after birth. What is the normal fetal function of this vessel?',o:['Connect right atrium to left atrium','Connect liver circulation to vena cava','Connect placenta to fetus','Connect pulmonary artery to aorta'],a:3,
e:`Ductus arteriosus connects pulmonary artery to descending aorta in fetal life, allowing right ventricular blood to bypass non-functional fetal lungs. After birth, failure of closure produces patent ductus arteriosus with characteristic continuous machinery murmur.<br><br>Patency in utero is maintained by placental prostaglandin E2 and low fetal oxygen tension. Postnatally, increased oxygen and reduced prostaglandins trigger smooth muscle constriction within 24-48 hours, with anatomic closure over 2-3 weeks. Persistent PDA causes left-to-right shunt; treated with indomethacin or surgical ligation.<br><br>Connect aorta to PA in reverse direction (A) is mechanically same. Connect IVC to RA (B) and SVC to RA (C) are not ductus arteriosus.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus depends on maternal glucose for metabolism. Which transport mechanism allows glucose transfer across placenta?',o:['Facilitated diffusion','Active transport','Osmosis','Endocytosis'],a:0,
e:`Glucose crosses the placenta from maternal to fetal circulation by facilitated diffusion through GLUT1 and GLUT3 transporters on syncytiotrophoblast. This carrier-mediated, energy-independent process moves glucose down its concentration gradient.<br><br>Maternal blood glucose averages 4-5 mmol/L while fetal glucose runs 0.5-1 mmol/L lower, maintaining the gradient. Fetal glucose uptake rises in late pregnancy supporting accelerated growth. Maternal hPL-induced insulin resistance ensures adequate maternal glucose for transplacental delivery; failure of pancreatic compensation produces gestational diabetes with fetal hyperinsulinaemia and macrosomia.<br><br>Active transport (B) requires energy and is not the mechanism. Pinocytosis (C) and endocytosis (D) are non-specific bulk transport.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal circulation pathway delivers the most oxygenated blood to the fetal brain?',o:['Inferior vena cava → right ventricle → pulmonary artery','Umbilical arteries → placenta → aorta','Pulmonary artery → ductus arteriosus → descending aorta','Umbilical vein → ductus venosus → inferior vena cava → foramen ovale → left atrium'],a:3,
e:`Most oxygenated blood reaches the fetal heart via umbilical vein → ductus venosus → inferior vena cava → right atrium. From right atrium, the eustachian valve directs the well-oxygenated stream through foramen ovale to left atrium and onward to brain via ascending aorta.<br><br>This streaming ensures the fetal brain and myocardium receive blood with relatively higher oxygen content (PaO2 ~30 mmHg). Less oxygenated blood from superior vena cava enters right ventricle and is shunted via ductus arteriosus to descending aorta, supplying the lower body and umbilical arteries to placenta.<br><br>Other pathways (A, B, C) describe fragments but miss the complete preferential streaming via ductus venosus and foramen ovale.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal organ is primarily responsible for production of surfactant?',o:['Placenta','Fetal lungs (type II pneumocytes)','Fetal liver','Fetal adrenal gland'],a:1,
e:`Fetal type II pneumocytes (alveolar epithelial cells) produce pulmonary surfactant, a phospholipid-protein complex containing dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine that reduces alveolar surface tension and prevents collapse during expiration after birth.<br><br>Surfactant production begins at 24-26 weeks but increases significantly after 34 weeks under cortisol stimulation. Antenatal corticosteroids (betamethasone, dexamethasone) given to women at risk of preterm delivery between 24-34 weeks accelerate fetal lung maturation, reducing respiratory distress syndrome, intraventricular haemorrhage and neonatal mortality. Lecithin-sphingomyelin ratio assesses lung maturity.<br><br>Alveolar macrophages (A) clear debris. Type I pneumocytes (C) form gas exchange barrier. Bronchiolar cells (D) do not produce surfactant.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Surfactant production in the fetus significantly increases after:',o:['20 weeks','24 weeks','28 weeks','34 weeks'],a:3,
e:`Surfactant production by fetal type II pneumocytes increases significantly after 34 weeks gestation. Below this gestational age, surfactant levels are insufficient to maintain alveolar stability after birth, producing respiratory distress syndrome (RDS) of prematurity.<br><br>Cortisol from fetal adrenal cortex stimulates surfactant synthesis and lung maturation. Antenatal corticosteroids (betamethasone, dexamethasone) given to women at 24-34 weeks at risk of preterm delivery accelerate maturation, reducing RDS by 50%. Exogenous surfactant therapy is given to preterm neonates with RDS, dramatically improving outcomes.<br><br>20 weeks (A), 26 weeks (B) and 30 weeks (C) precede the major surge; surfactant production accelerates particularly after 34 weeks.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone plays a key role in stimulating fetal lung maturation and surfactant production?',o:['Thyroxine','Cortisol','Insulin','Growth hormone'],a:1,
e:`Cortisol from fetal adrenal cortex stimulates fetal lung maturation by inducing type II pneumocyte differentiation and surfactant gene expression including SP-A, SP-B, SP-C and SP-D synthesis. This prepares lungs for postnatal gas exchange.<br><br>Placental CRH drives fetal pituitary ACTH and adrenal cortisol production. Antenatal corticosteroids (betamethasone, dexamethasone) cross placenta and mimic fetal cortisol, accelerating lung maturation when given at 24-34 weeks at risk of preterm delivery. They reduce respiratory distress syndrome by 50%, intraventricular haemorrhage and neonatal mortality.<br><br>Insulin (A) opposes lung maturation in diabetic pregnancies. Estrogen (C) and progesterone (D) are not the principal lung maturation hormones.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal endocrine organ contributes to estrogen production by providing androgen precursors to placenta?',o:['Fetal pancreas','Fetal spleen','Fetal adrenal gland','Fetal kidney'],a:2,
e:`Fetal adrenal gland contributes to placental estrogen production by providing dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate (DHEAS) as androgen precursor. Placenta lacks 17-alpha-hydroxylase and depends on fetal DHEAS, which placental sulfatase desulfates and aromatase converts to estrogens.<br><br>Fetal adrenal at term weighs proportionally three to four times more than adult adrenal, with predominant fetal zone specialised for DHEAS production. Most placental estriol production additionally requires fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation. This obligate cooperation creates the fetoplacental unit, with maternal estriol monitoring assessing fetoplacental integrity.<br><br>Fetal liver (A) provides 16-alpha-hydroxylation. Fetal kidney (B) and fetal pancreas (D) play no significant role in placental estrogen synthesis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A premature infant develops respiratory distress syndrome due to inadequate surfactant production. Which fetal cells normally produce surfactant?',o:['Type I pneumocytes','Bronchial epithelial cells','Alveolar macrophages','Type II pneumocytes'],a:3,
e:`Respiratory distress syndrome of prematurity results from inadequate surfactant production by type II pneumocytes, the alveolar epithelial cells responsible for surfactant synthesis. Surfactant deficiency produces alveolar collapse, increased work of breathing, hypoxaemia and respiratory failure.<br><br>Surfactant production begins at 24-26 weeks, increasing significantly after 34 weeks under cortisol stimulation. Preterm infants below 34 weeks are at highest risk. Antenatal corticosteroids reduce RDS by 50%. Postnatal exogenous surfactant therapy via endotracheal route dramatically improves outcomes, reducing mortality and pneumothorax in affected neonates.<br><br>Type I pneumocytes (A) form gas exchange barrier. Goblet cells (B) and alveolar macrophages (C) do not produce surfactant.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with intrauterine hypoxia compensates by increasing production of which hormone to stimulate erythropoiesis?',o:['Cortisol','Prolactin','Erythropoietin','Insulin'],a:2,
e:`Fetal hypoxia from placental insufficiency, maternal anaemia or chronic in utero hypoxia stimulates increased erythropoietin secretion, primarily from fetal kidneys (kidney is principal EPO source from late gestation). EPO drives compensatory erythropoiesis in fetal liver and bone marrow.<br><br>Resulting polycythaemia raises haemoglobin and total oxygen-carrying capacity, partially compensating for reduced oxygen delivery. Cord blood haematocrit above 65% defines neonatal polycythaemia, often associated with placental insufficiency or maternal diabetes. Severe polycythaemia produces hyperviscosity syndrome with respiratory distress, hypoglycaemia and seizures requiring partial exchange transfusion.<br><br>Insulin (A) drives growth. Cortisol (B) supports lung maturation. Aldosterone (D) regulates sodium balance.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with growth restriction shows decreased glycogen stores in which organ normally responsible for glycogen storage before birth?',o:['Lung','Liver','Kidney','Heart'],a:1,
e:`Fetal liver accumulates substantial glycogen stores during third trimester, particularly from 30-36 weeks, providing the principal energy reserve for the immediate postnatal period before feeding establishes. Growth-restricted fetuses show decreased liver glycogen due to reduced substrate delivery.<br><br>At birth, glycogenolysis maintains blood glucose during the transition from continuous transplacental glucose supply to intermittent feeding. IUGR neonates with depleted glycogen are at high risk of neonatal hypoglycaemia, requiring early frequent feeding or intravenous glucose. Fetal hepatic glycogen content correlates strongly with placental function and gestational age at delivery.<br><br>Heart (A) stores limited glycogen. Skeletal muscle (C) has glycogen but liver is principal organ. Brain (D) lacks significant glycogen storage.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal organ is primarily responsible for production of fetal urine contributing to amniotic fluid in late pregnancy?',o:['Liver','Placenta','Lungs','Kidneys'],a:3,
e:`Fetal kidneys are responsible for producing fetal urine, which is the principal contributor to amniotic fluid volume from the second trimester onwards. Fetal urine output increases from 5 mL/hour at 20 weeks to 50 mL/hour at term.<br><br>Amniotic fluid volume is regulated by balance between fetal urine production and fetal swallowing. Reduced amniotic fluid (oligohydramnios) suggests fetal renal abnormality (renal agenesis, multicystic kidneys, posterior urethral valves) or placental insufficiency. Increased amniotic fluid (polyhydramnios) suggests impaired swallowing (oesophageal atresia, neuromuscular disorder) or maternal diabetes.<br><br>Bladder (A) stores urine. Ureters (B) transport urine. Adrenal glands (C) do not produce urine.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal circulation pathway carries oxygenated blood directly toward the fetal heart from the placenta?',o:['Umbilical vein','Umbilical artery','Ductus arteriosus','Pulmonary vein'],a:0,
e:`Umbilical vein carries the most oxygenated blood in fetal circulation, with PaO2 approximately 30 mmHg and oxygen saturation around 70-80%. It transports oxygen and nutrients from placenta to fetus through the umbilical cord.<br><br>After entering the fetal abdomen, blood divides at porta hepatis between hepatic portal sinuses (perfusing fetal liver) and ductus venosus (bypassing liver to inferior vena cava). The ductus venosus stream is preferentially directed through foramen ovale to left atrium and ascending aorta, supplying brain with relatively oxygenated blood.<br><br>Umbilical arteries (B) carry deoxygenated blood. Pulmonary artery (C) carries low-oxygen blood. Aorta (D) mixes streams; not most oxygenated.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'In fetal circulation, the right ventricle pumps most of its blood into:',o:['Pulmonary circulation','Coronary circulation','Hepatic circulation','Systemic circulation via ductus arteriosus'],a:3,
e:`In fetal circulation, the right ventricle pumps approximately 90% of its output through the ductus arteriosus into the descending aorta, bypassing the high-resistance pulmonary circulation. Only 5-10% reaches the pulmonary arteries to perfuse developing lungs.<br><br>This shunting via ductus arteriosus delivers blood to systemic circulation including lower body and umbilical arteries returning to placenta. After birth, lung expansion and increased oxygen tension cause rapid pulmonary vasodilation while ductus arteriosus constricts, reversing shunt direction and establishing normal series circulation through pulmonary then systemic vascular beds.<br><br>Pulmonary circulation (A) receives only 5-10%. Coronary circulation (B) and cerebral circulation (C) are perfused but not from RV directly.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'After birth, the foramen ovale normally closes due to:',o:['Increased right atrial pressure','Increased pulmonary vascular resistance','Increased left atrial pressure','Decreased systemic resistance'],a:2,
e:`Foramen ovale closes after birth due to increased left atrial pressure caused by pulmonary venous return rising as pulmonary circulation establishes. The pressure differential reverses, with left atrial pressure exceeding right atrial pressure for the first time.<br><br>This pushes the septum primum flap against the septum secundum, functionally closing the foramen ovale within hours of birth. Anatomic closure with fibrous fusion occurs over months. Persistent patent foramen ovale occurs in 20-25% of adults but is usually clinically silent unless associated with paradoxical embolism or Eisenmenger physiology.<br><br>Increased pulmonary resistance (A) is opposite of postnatal change. Decreased systemic resistance (B) is incorrect. Vascular constriction (D) is not the mechanism.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Closure of ductus arteriosus after birth is primarily stimulated by:',o:['Increased prostaglandin E₂','Increased oxygen tension','Increased carbon dioxide levels','Reduced pulmonary blood flow'],a:1,
e:`Ductus arteriosus closure after birth is primarily stimulated by increased oxygen tension from pulmonary gas exchange, which directly contracts ductal smooth muscle. Concurrent reduction in placental prostaglandin E2 (which had maintained patency) further promotes constriction.<br><br>Functional closure occurs within 24-48 hours of birth, with anatomic closure through fibrosis over 2-3 weeks, leaving the ligamentum arteriosum. In preterm infants, persistent patency is treated with indomethacin or ibuprofen (prostaglandin synthesis inhibitors) or surgical ligation. In duct-dependent congenital heart disease, prostaglandin E1 maintains patency until corrective surgery.<br><br>Decreased oxygen (A) is opposite. Increased prostaglandins (C) maintain patency. Decreased pulmonary pressure (D) contributes secondarily but is not primary trigger.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal metabolic substrate is the main source of energy for fetal growth?',o:['Amino acids','Ketone bodies','Glucose','Fatty acids'],a:2,
e:`Glucose is the primary metabolic substrate for fetal energy, crossing the placenta by facilitated diffusion through GLUT1 and GLUT3 transporters down its concentration gradient. Fetal glucose levels run 0.5-1 mmol/L below maternal levels, maintaining the transplacental gradient.<br><br>Fetal glucose consumption rises markedly in third trimester to support accelerated growth. Maternal hPL-induced insulin resistance ensures adequate maternal glucose for transplacental supply. In maternal diabetes, fetal hyperglycaemia stimulates fetal pancreas producing fetal hyperinsulinaemia, accelerating fat deposition and producing macrosomia, the hallmark of diabetic pregnancy.<br><br>Lactate (A) and ketones (B) supplement during fasting. Free fatty acids (D) cross placenta poorly compared with glucose.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal endocrine hormone plays a key role in regulating fetal growth and metabolism?',o:['Insulin','Oxytocin','Prolactin','TSH'],a:0,
e:`Fetal insulin is a major regulator of fetal growth, particularly in third trimester. Fetal pancreatic beta cells respond to glucose levels, with insulin promoting glucose uptake, glycogen synthesis and lipogenesis in fetal tissues including liver, muscle and adipose tissue.<br><br>In maternal diabetes with fetal hyperglycaemia, fetal pancreas hyperresponds, producing fetal hyperinsulinaemia. Excess insulin acts as fetal growth factor (Pedersen hypothesis), stimulating anabolism with macrosomia, increased adiposity and organomegaly. After birth, abrupt removal of maternal glucose with persisting hyperinsulinaemia causes neonatal hypoglycaemia requiring early frequent feeding or IV glucose.<br><br>Cortisol (B) supports lung maturation. Estrogen (C) and progesterone (D) are not principal fetal growth regulators.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with maternal diabetes develops macrosomia primarily due to:',o:['Reduced glucose uptake','Decreased placental transfer of glucose','Reduced insulin secretion','Fetal hyperinsulinemia'],a:3,
e:`Fetal hyperinsulinaemia is the central mechanism of macrosomia in maternal diabetes (Pedersen hypothesis). Maternal hyperglycaemia from inadequate insulin compensation crosses placenta as glucose, stimulating fetal pancreatic beta cells to oversecrete insulin.<br><br>Fetal insulin acts as a major growth factor, promoting glucose uptake, glycogen synthesis, lipogenesis and protein anabolism in fetal tissues. Result is macrosomia (birth weight >4-4.5 kg), increased adiposity, organomegaly (cardiac, hepatic, splenic) and risk of shoulder dystocia at delivery. Tight maternal glycaemic control prevents this; postnatally, persistent hyperinsulinaemia causes neonatal hypoglycaemia.<br><br>Increased growth hormone (A) is not principal mechanism. Increased thyroxine (B) is not implicated. Decreased cortisol (C) is opposite tendency.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal organ contributes most to production of amniotic fluid in the second half of pregnancy?',o:['Placenta','Fetal kidneys','Fetal lungs','Fetal liver'],a:1,
e:`Fetal kidneys are the principal contributor to amniotic fluid volume from the second trimester onwards through fetal urine production. Urine output increases from 5 mL/hour at 20 weeks to 50 mL/hour at term, reflecting growing renal function.<br><br>Amniotic fluid volume is regulated by balance between fetal urine production and fetal swallowing. Pulmonary fluid contributes minor amounts. Reduced amniotic fluid (oligohydramnios) suggests fetal renal abnormality (renal agenesis, multicystic kidneys, posterior urethral valves) or placental insufficiency reducing renal perfusion. Severe oligohydramnios causes Potter sequence with pulmonary hypoplasia.<br><br>Fetal lungs (A) contribute minor amounts. Placenta (C) does not produce amniotic fluid. Fetal skin (D) is impermeable after keratinisation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal cardiovascular structure becomes the ligamentum arteriosum after birth?',o:['Foramen ovale','Umbilical vein','Ductus arteriosus','Ductus venosus'],a:2,
e:`Ductus arteriosus becomes the ligamentum arteriosum after birth. Functional closure occurs within 24-48 hours of birth due to increased oxygen tension and reduced placental prostaglandin E2. Anatomic closure through fibrosis takes 2-3 weeks.<br><br>Ligamentum arteriosum lies between aortic arch and pulmonary artery, important surgical landmark identifying the recurrent laryngeal nerve looping around it on the left side. Persistent patent ductus arteriosus produces continuous machinery murmur and left-to-right shunt; treated with indomethacin in preterm or surgical ligation. PDA may be lifesaving in duct-dependent congenital heart disease.<br><br>Foramen ovale (A) becomes fossa ovalis. Ductus venosus (B) becomes ligamentum venosum. Umbilical vein (D) becomes ligamentum teres.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal structure becomes the ligamentum teres hepatis after birth?',o:['Umbilical artery','Umbilical vein','Ductus arteriosus','Ductus venosus'],a:1,
e:`Umbilical vein becomes the ligamentum teres hepatis (round ligament of liver) after birth. Closure occurs within minutes to hours of umbilical cord clamping due to changes in venous flow and umbilical artery vasoconstriction.<br><br>The fibrosed remnant runs in the free edge of the falciform ligament from umbilicus to porta hepatis. Surgical relevance: in portal hypertension, the umbilical vein can recanalise allowing portosystemic collateral flow. The round ligament is also used for vascular access in adults if recanalised, and as a landmark during liver surgery.<br><br>Foramen ovale (A) becomes fossa ovalis. Umbilical arteries (C) become medial umbilical ligaments. Ductus arteriosus (D) becomes ligamentum arteriosum.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal metabolic process allows accumulation of glycogen and fat stores before birth?',o:['Increased glucagon secretion','Reduced placental glucose transfer','Reduced glucose uptake','Increased insulin activity'],a:3,
e:`Increased fetal insulin activity, particularly in third trimester, allows accumulation of glycogen and fat in fetal tissues. Fetal pancreatic beta cells produce insulin from 11 weeks, with increasing secretion responding to glucose. Insulin acts as major fetal growth factor.<br><br>Insulin promotes glucose uptake into fetal liver (glycogen synthesis), adipose tissue (fat deposition) and muscle (protein synthesis). These reserves provide energy for the immediate postnatal period. Fetuses of diabetic mothers exposed to hyperglycaemia develop hyperinsulinaemia with excess deposits, producing macrosomia, increased adiposity and risk of birth complications.<br><br>Decreased insulin (A) reduces deposits. Decreased glucose (B) reduces substrate. Increased cortisol (C) is catabolic, not anabolic.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal endocrine gland enlarges significantly during pregnancy and contributes to steroid precursor production?',o:['Thyroid gland','Adrenal gland','Pancreas','Pituitary gland'],a:1,
e:`Fetal adrenal gland enlarges significantly during pregnancy and is proportionally three to four times larger than adult adrenal at term. The fetal zone of the adrenal cortex is specialised for production of dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate (DHEAS).<br><br>DHEAS serves as androgen precursor for placental estrogen synthesis since placenta lacks 17-alpha-hydroxylase. Placental sulfatase desulfates DHEAS, then aromatase converts it to estrogens. Most estriol production additionally requires fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation. The fetal zone involutes after birth, replaced by adult adrenal cortex within first year.<br><br>Thyroid (A) enlarges modestly. Pituitary (B) is not the principal large fetal endocrine organ. Pancreas (C) does not enlarge dramatically.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal circulatory structure bypasses the liver allowing oxygenated blood from placenta to reach the heart rapidly?',o:['Ductus venosus','Foramen ovale','Ductus arteriosus','Umbilical artery'],a:0,
e:`Ductus venosus is the fetal circulatory shunt that bypasses the liver, allowing oxygenated blood from umbilical vein to reach the inferior vena cava directly. This delivers high-oxygen-content blood preferentially toward foramen ovale and brain.<br><br>About 50% of umbilical venous blood traverses ductus venosus, with the remainder perfusing the fetal liver through portal sinuses. Blood from ductus venosus joins IVC and is preferentially streamed through foramen ovale by the eustachian valve. After birth, ductus venosus closes within minutes to hours, becoming the ligamentum venosum.<br><br>Foramen ovale (B) bypasses lungs at atrial level. Ductus arteriosus (C) bypasses lungs at arterial level. Umbilical artery (D) carries blood to placenta.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which physiological feature of fetal hemoglobin facilitates oxygen transfer from maternal blood?',o:['Increased carbon dioxide affinity','Reduced oxygen capacity','Increased affinity for oxygen','Reduced affinity for oxygen'],a:2,
e:`Fetal haemoglobin (HbF, alpha2gamma2) has increased affinity for oxygen compared with adult HbA, facilitating oxygen transfer from maternal to fetal circulation across the placenta. Gamma chains bind 2,3-DPG less avidly than beta chains, shifting the dissociation curve leftward.<br><br>This higher affinity allows HbF to load oxygen at the relatively low fetal umbilical venous PaO2 of approximately 30 mmHg, reaching 60-70% saturation. Combined with double Bohr effect (CO2 transfer between maternal and fetal blood) and high HbF concentration, this ensures adequate fetal oxygen delivery despite the low driving pressure.<br><br>Lower iron content (A) is incorrect. Increased CO2 binding (B) is not the principal feature. Larger size (D) is incorrect; HbF is similar size to HbA.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal circulation pathway supplies the descending aorta with mixed blood?',o:['Pulmonary artery → ductus arteriosus → descending aorta','Umbilical vein → inferior vena cava','Left atrium → left ventricle → ascending aorta','Superior vena cava → right atrium'],a:0,
e:`Pulmonary artery → ductus arteriosus → descending aorta is the fetal circulation pathway that supplies the descending aorta with mixed blood. Right ventricular output enters pulmonary artery, then 90% is shunted through ductus arteriosus to descending aorta below the origin of subclavian arteries.<br><br>This blood is less oxygenated than that reaching the ascending aorta via foramen ovale-left ventricular pathway, supplying the lower body and umbilical arteries returning to placenta. The arrangement preserves the most oxygenated blood for brain and myocardium while less oxygenated blood serves placental gas exchange.<br><br>Other pathways (B, C, D) describe fragments of fetal circulation but not the specific pulmonary artery-ductus-aorta route.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A clinician explains that fetal physiology is adapted to support intrauterine life by relying on placental gas exchange and specialized circulation. Which fetal structure plays the most important role in directing oxygenated blood to the fetal brain?',o:['Ductus arteriosus','Foramen ovale','Umbilical arteries','Ductus venosus'],a:1,
e:`Foramen ovale is a critical fetal circulation structure adapting to intrauterine life by directing oxygenated blood from right atrium to left atrium, bypassing the non-functional fetal lungs. This delivers blood preferentially to brain via ascending aorta.<br><br>Oxygenated blood from umbilical vein traverses ductus venosus, enters IVC and right atrium where the eustachian valve directs it through foramen ovale into left atrium. Combined with ductus arteriosus shunting RV output to descending aorta, only 5-10% of cardiac output reaches fetal lungs, sufficient for development.<br><br>Pulmonary veins (A) are not adapted shunts. Coronary sinus (C) is normal venous structure. Eustachian tube (D) is in middle ear, unrelated.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The fetal oxygen tension in umbilical venous blood is approximately:',o:['30 mmHg','60 mmHg','20 mmHg','10 mmHg'],a:0,
e:`Fetal oxygen tension in umbilical venous blood is approximately 30 mmHg, much lower than maternal arterial PaO2 of 100 mmHg. Despite this, fetal oxygen delivery is adequate due to several adaptations in the fetal-placental gas exchange system.<br><br>Fetal haemoglobin has higher oxygen affinity due to gamma chains binding 2,3-DPG less avidly, allowing 60-70% saturation at PaO2 of 30 mmHg. High HbF concentration (16-18 g/dL), large fetal cardiac output per kg body weight, and double Bohr effect (CO2 transfer) all enhance oxygen delivery despite the relatively low driving pressure.<br><br>50 mmHg (B), 70 mmHg (C) and 100 mmHg (D) overestimate the actual fetal umbilical venous oxygen tension.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The fetal heart rate in normal pregnancy typically ranges between:',o:['60-90 beats/min','160-200 beats/min','110-160 beats/min','90-110 beats/min'],a:2,
e:`Normal fetal heart rate ranges between 110-160 beats per minute throughout the third trimester. This rate is higher than adult resting heart rate due to relatively immature autonomic regulation and the high cardiac output requirements of fetal metabolism.<br><br>Fetal heart rate variability and accelerations on cardiotocograph (CTG) reflect fetal wellbeing. Persistent fetal tachycardia above 160 bpm suggests maternal fever, infection, fetal hypoxia or thyrotoxicosis. Persistent bradycardia below 110 bpm suggests fetal hypoxia, congenital heart block (often from maternal SLE/anti-Ro antibodies) or post-term gestation requiring evaluation.<br><br>60-100 bpm (A) is adult resting range. 80-100 bpm (B) is too low. 180-200 bpm (D) is fetal tachycardia.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The fetal cardiac output per kilogram body weight is:',o:['Variable with no pattern','Equal to adult','Lower than adult','Much higher than adult'],a:3,
e:`Fetal cardiac output per kilogram body weight is much higher than adult, reaching approximately 400-450 mL/kg/min compared with adult 70-100 mL/kg/min. This high relative output supports the high metabolic and growth requirements of intrauterine life.<br><br>Fetal myocardium has limited contractile reserve and is highly dependent on heart rate to increase cardiac output, unlike adult myocardium which can also augment stroke volume. This explains why bradycardia is poorly tolerated in fetal life and produces rapid hypoxic compromise. Fetal cardiac output is also distributed differently due to placental circulation.<br><br>Equal to adult (A), much lower (B) and slightly higher (C) misestimate the actual high relative cardiac output of the fetus.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The fetal lungs remain collapsed during intrauterine life mainly due to:',o:['High pulmonary vascular resistance','Low pulmonary vascular resistance','Lack of pulmonary capillaries','Absence of pulmonary arteries'],a:0,
e:`Fetal lungs remain collapsed and fluid-filled during intrauterine life mainly due to high pulmonary vascular resistance. Pulmonary arterial vasoconstriction is maintained by low fetal PaO2, high PaCO2 and high circulating endothelin and thromboxane.<br><br>Only 5-10% of right ventricular output reaches the pulmonary circulation in utero, with the remainder shunted through ductus arteriosus to systemic circulation. After birth, lung expansion, increased oxygen tension and reduced acidosis cause rapid pulmonary vasodilation, dropping resistance and reversing shunt direction. Failure produces persistent pulmonary hypertension of newborn.<br><br>Low pulmonary resistance (B) is postnatal. Patent ductus (C) is consequence not cause. High oxygen tension (D) is opposite of fetal state.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal circulation structure allows oxygenated blood to preferentially reach the left atrium?',o:['Umbilical artery','Foramen ovale','Coronary sinus','Ductus arteriosus'],a:1,
e:`Foramen ovale allows oxygenated blood from right atrium to preferentially shunt to left atrium and onward via left ventricle and ascending aorta to coronary and cerebral circulation. This streaming delivers the most oxygenated blood to brain and heart.<br><br>The eustachian valve at IVC-right atrial junction directs the well-oxygenated stream from ductus venosus across the foramen ovale, while less oxygenated SVC blood enters right ventricle and is shunted via ductus arteriosus to descending aorta. After birth, increased left atrial pressure functionally closes the foramen ovale.<br><br>Ductus venosus (A) is venous shunt bypassing liver. Ductus arteriosus (C) shunts to descending aorta. Umbilical vein (D) carries blood to fetus.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The fetal liver receives blood mainly from:',o:['Renal artery','Pulmonary artery','Umbilical vein','Hepatic artery'],a:2,
e:`Fetal liver receives blood mainly from the umbilical vein at the porta hepatis. Approximately 50% of umbilical venous flow perfuses the liver through hepatic portal sinuses, with the remainder bypassing liver via ductus venosus to inferior vena cava.<br><br>This delivery of relatively well-oxygenated blood to fetal liver supports its multiple functions: principal site of mid-gestation haematopoiesis, storage of glycogen and iron, and steroid hormone metabolism. Portal venous drainage from fetal gut also contributes. After birth, umbilical vein closure leaves the liver dependent solely on portal vein and hepatic artery.<br><br>Hepatic artery (A) provides minor flow. Portal vein (B) drains gut. Ductus venosus (D) bypasses liver, not perfuses it.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal organ produces most erythropoietin in response to hypoxia?',o:['Placenta','Fetal kidneys','Fetal adrenal gland','Fetal liver'],a:1,
e:`Fetal kidneys produce most erythropoietin in response to hypoxia from late gestation onwards, with kidney becoming the principal EPO source by term. Earlier in gestation, liver is the principal EPO source. Both produce more in response to fetal hypoxaemia.<br><br>Increased EPO drives compensatory erythropoiesis in fetal liver and bone marrow, raising haemoglobin and total oxygen-carrying capacity. Cord blood haematocrit above 65% defines neonatal polycythaemia, often associated with placental insufficiency, post-term pregnancy or maternal diabetes. Severe polycythaemia produces hyperviscosity syndrome with respiratory distress and seizures.<br><br>Liver (A) is earlier source. Bone marrow (C) responds to EPO but does not produce it. Spleen (D) is haematopoietic site only.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The major determinant of fetal oxygen delivery is:',o:['Placental blood flow','Umbilical cord length','Amniotic fluid volume','Maternal hemoglobin concentration'],a:0,
e:`Placental blood flow is the major determinant of fetal oxygen delivery, including both maternal uteroplacental circulation and fetal umbilical-placental flow. Flow rises from 50 mL/min nonpregnant uterine flow to 500-700 mL/min at term.<br><br>Spiral artery remodelling by trophoblast invasion converts high-resistance maternal arterioles into low-resistance vessels accommodating the increased flow. Inadequate remodelling produces placental insufficiency with reduced perfusion and fetal hypoxia. Umbilical artery Doppler assesses fetal-placental flow, with absent or reversed end-diastolic flow indicating severe placental insufficiency requiring delivery.<br><br>Maternal Hb (B) and fetal Hb (C) contribute but are secondary. Maternal SVR (D) does not directly determine placental delivery.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The primary energy substrate for the fetus is:',o:['Amino acids','Ketone bodies','Fatty acids','Glucose'],a:3,
e:`Glucose is the primary energy substrate for the fetus, crossing the placenta by facilitated diffusion through GLUT1 and GLUT3 transporters down its concentration gradient. Fetal glucose levels run 0.5-1 mmol/L below maternal levels, maintaining the transplacental gradient.<br><br>Fetal glucose consumption rises markedly in third trimester to support accelerated growth and tissue accretion. Maternal hPL-induced insulin resistance ensures adequate maternal glucose for transplacental supply. Lactate and ketones supplement fetal energy during fasting. Free fatty acids cross placenta poorly compared with glucose, making maternal glucose the principal fetal substrate.<br><br>Lactate (A) and amino acids (B) supplement. Free fatty acids (C) cross placenta poorly compared with glucose.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal organ is responsible for swallowing amniotic fluid?',o:['Urinary tract','Gastrointestinal tract','Nervous system','Respiratory tract'],a:1,
e:`Fetal gastrointestinal tract swallows amniotic fluid from the second trimester onwards, contributing to amniotic fluid regulation alongside fetal urine production. Swallowed fluid is absorbed across fetal gut, supporting GI maturation and fluid balance.<br><br>Fetal swallowing rises from negligible at 20 weeks to 500-1000 mL/day at term. Amniotic fluid volume reflects balance between fetal urine production and swallowing, with fetal lung secretions and skin contributing minor amounts. Impaired swallowing (oesophageal atresia, neuromuscular disorder) causes polyhydramnios. Reduced urine production (renal abnormality, placental insufficiency) causes oligohydramnios.<br><br>Lungs (A) contribute fluid but do not swallow. Kidneys (C) produce urine. Liver (D) does not regulate amniotic fluid.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with placental insufficiency develops chronic hypoxia. Which physiological fetal adaptation occurs first?',o:['Reduced heart rate','Decreased cardiac output','Increased erythropoietin secretion','Reduced hemoglobin levels'],a:2,
e:`Chronic fetal hypoxia from placental insufficiency triggers compensatory increase in erythropoietin secretion from fetal kidneys (and liver earlier in gestation). This drives compensatory erythropoiesis in fetal liver and bone marrow, raising haemoglobin and total oxygen-carrying capacity.<br><br>Resulting polycythaemia partially compensates for reduced oxygen delivery. Cord blood haematocrit above 65% defines neonatal polycythaemia, commonly associated with placental insufficiency, post-term pregnancy or maternal diabetes. Severe polycythaemia produces hyperviscosity syndrome with respiratory distress, hypoglycaemia, jaundice and seizures, sometimes requiring partial exchange transfusion.<br><br>Decreased EPO (A) is opposite. Decreased Hb (B) is opposite of compensatory polycythaemia. Increased platelets (D) is not the response to fetal hypoxia.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with intrauterine growth restriction shows reduced glycogen stores. Which fetal organ normally stores glycogen before birth?',o:['Kidney','Heart','Lung','Liver'],a:3,
e:`Intrauterine growth restriction is associated with reduced glycogen stores in fetal liver due to decreased substrate delivery from placental insufficiency. Fetal liver normally accumulates substantial glycogen during third trimester (30-36 weeks), providing the principal energy reserve for postnatal life.<br><br>At birth, glycogenolysis maintains blood glucose during the transition from continuous transplacental supply to intermittent feeding. IUGR neonates with depleted glycogen are at high risk of neonatal hypoglycaemia, requiring early frequent feeding or intravenous glucose support. Fetal hepatic glycogen content correlates strongly with placental function and birth weight.<br><br>Heart (A) stores limited glycogen. Brain (B) lacks significant storage. Skeletal muscle (C) has glycogen but liver is principal organ.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with decreased amniotic fluid volume is found to have impaired fetal urine production. Which organ dysfunction is most likely responsible?',o:['Placenta','Kidney','Lung','Liver'],a:1,
e:`Decreased amniotic fluid volume (oligohydramnios) suggests impaired fetal kidney function. Fetal urine is the principal contributor to amniotic fluid from second trimester, with output rising from 5 mL/hour at 20 weeks to 50 mL/hour at term.<br><br>Causes include bilateral renal agenesis, multicystic dysplastic kidneys, polycystic kidney disease, posterior urethral valves and severe placental insufficiency reducing renal perfusion. Severe oligohydramnios from 20 weeks causes Potter sequence with pulmonary hypoplasia, limb deformities and characteristic Potter facies. Ultrasound identifies the anatomical cause.<br><br>Lung (A) contributes minor amounts. Heart (C) does not regulate amniotic fluid. Liver (D) is not involved in fluid production.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A premature fetus is at risk of respiratory distress due to inadequate surfactant production. Surfactant deficiency primarily leads to:',o:['Increased oxygen diffusion','Increased lung compliance','Alveolar collapse','Decreased surface tension'],a:2,
e:`A premature fetus is at risk of respiratory distress syndrome (RDS) due to inadequate surfactant production by type II pneumocytes, leading to alveolar collapse during expiration after birth. Surfactant reduces surface tension preventing collapse.<br><br>Surfactant production begins at 24-26 weeks, increasing significantly after 34 weeks under cortisol stimulation. Below 34 weeks, deficiency produces RDS with grunting, tachypnoea, retractions and hypoxaemia. Antenatal corticosteroids (betamethasone, dexamethasone) given to women at 24-34 weeks accelerate maturation, reducing RDS by 50%. Postnatal exogenous surfactant therapy improves outcomes.<br><br>Increased compliance (A) is opposite. Increased perfusion (B) is not deficient. Decreased dead space (D) is not the issue.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus exposed to maternal hyperglycemia develops macrosomia. Which fetal endocrine response causes this?',o:['Increased glucagon','Hyperinsulinemia','Increased cortisol','Reduced insulin'],a:1,
e:`Fetal exposure to maternal hyperglycaemia produces fetal hyperinsulinaemia, the central mechanism of macrosomia in maternal diabetes (Pedersen hypothesis). Maternal glucose crosses placenta freely, stimulating fetal pancreatic beta cells to oversecrete insulin.<br><br>Fetal insulin acts as major growth factor, promoting glucose uptake, glycogen synthesis, lipogenesis and protein anabolism. Result is macrosomia (birth weight >4-4.5 kg), increased adiposity, organomegaly and risk of shoulder dystocia at delivery. Tight maternal glycaemic control prevents this; postnatally, persistent hyperinsulinaemia causes neonatal hypoglycaemia requiring early feeding or IV glucose.<br><br>Hypoinsulinaemia (A) is opposite. Increased growth hormone (C) is not the mechanism. Hyperthyroidism (D) is not implicated.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal circulation pathway carries the most oxygenated blood?',o:['Pulmonary artery','Inferior vena cava','Descending aorta','Umbilical vein'],a:3,
e:`Umbilical vein carries the most oxygenated blood in fetal circulation, with PaO2 approximately 30 mmHg and oxygen saturation around 70-80%. It transports oxygen and nutrients from placenta to fetus through the umbilical cord.<br><br>After entering fetal abdomen, blood divides at porta hepatis between hepatic portal sinuses and ductus venosus. Ductus venosus stream is preferentially directed through foramen ovale to left atrium and ascending aorta, supplying brain with relatively well-oxygenated blood. Less oxygenated blood from SVC enters RV and goes via ductus arteriosus to descending aorta.<br><br>Aorta (A) mixes streams. Pulmonary artery (B) and umbilical artery (C) carry less oxygenated blood.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The fetal myocardium differs from adult myocardium because it:',o:['Has higher stroke volume','Has lower contractility','Is more dependent on heart rate to increase cardiac output','Is less compliant'],a:2,
e:`Fetal myocardium differs from adult myocardium because it is more dependent on heart rate to increase cardiac output. Fetal cardiac muscle has fewer mitochondria, less developed sarcoplasmic reticulum and reduced contractile reserve compared with mature myocardium.<br><br>This means fetus has limited capacity to augment stroke volume in response to increased demand or hypoxia, relying primarily on tachycardia. Persistent fetal bradycardia is therefore poorly tolerated and produces rapid hypoxic compromise, manifest as decelerations on cardiotocography requiring intervention. Fetal heart rate normally ranges 110-160 bpm reflecting this physiology.<br><br>More compliant (A) and more efficient (B) are inaccurate. Lower oxygen demand (D) is incorrect; demand is high.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal hormone plays a major role in regulating fetal growth?',o:['Insulin','Thyroxine','Growth hormone','Cortisol'],a:0,
e:`Fetal insulin is a major regulator of fetal growth, particularly in third trimester. Fetal pancreatic beta cells produce insulin from 11 weeks, with rising secretion responding to glucose levels. Insulin acts as fetal growth factor.<br><br>Insulin promotes glucose uptake, glycogen synthesis and lipogenesis in fetal liver, muscle and adipose tissue. In maternal diabetes with fetal hyperglycaemia, fetal pancreas hyperresponds producing fetal hyperinsulinaemia. Excess insulin stimulates anabolism with macrosomia, increased adiposity and organomegaly. Postnatally, persistent hyperinsulinaemia after maternal glucose supply ceases causes neonatal hypoglycaemia.<br><br>Cortisol (B) supports lung maturation. Estrogen (C) and progesterone (D) are not principal fetal growth regulators.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The fetal circulation shunt that bypasses the hepatic circulation is:',o:['Umbilical artery','Foramen ovale','Ductus arteriosus','Ductus venosus'],a:3,
e:`Ductus venosus is the fetal circulatory shunt that bypasses the hepatic circulation, allowing oxygenated blood from umbilical vein to reach inferior vena cava directly. About 50% of umbilical venous blood traverses ductus venosus.<br><br>This delivers high-oxygen-content blood preferentially toward foramen ovale and brain. Remaining 50% perfuses fetal liver through portal sinuses, supporting hepatic mid-gestation haematopoiesis and glycogen storage. After birth, ductus venosus closes within minutes to hours due to umbilical cord clamping, becoming the ligamentum venosum on the posterior liver surface.<br><br>Foramen ovale (A) bypasses lungs at atrial level. Ductus arteriosus (B) bypasses lungs at arterial level. Umbilical vein (C) supplies blood, not bypass.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The fetal pulmonary circulation receives approximately what percentage of combined cardiac output?',o:['5-10%','20-25%','60-70%','40-50%'],a:0,
e:`Fetal pulmonary circulation receives only 5-10% of right ventricular output, with the remaining 90% shunted through ductus arteriosus to descending aorta. High pulmonary vascular resistance maintained by low PaO2 and circulating vasoconstrictors directs flow away from non-functional fetal lungs.<br><br>This 5-10% is sufficient for fetal lung development including alveolar formation, pulmonary vessel development and lymphatic drainage. After birth, lung expansion, increased oxygen tension and reduced acidosis cause rapid pulmonary vasodilation, dropping resistance and reversing shunt direction. Failure produces persistent pulmonary hypertension of newborn.<br><br>30-40% (B), 50-60% (C) and 70-80% (D) overestimate the actual minimal pulmonary blood flow during fetal life.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with placental insufficiency shows decreased oxygen delivery. Which fetal hemoglobin property helps compensate for this condition?',o:['Reduced hemoglobin concentration','Higher oxygen affinity','Lower oxygen affinity','Reduced oxygen capacity'],a:1,
e:`Fetal haemoglobin (HbF) higher oxygen affinity helps maintain oxygen delivery despite reduced placental gas exchange in placental insufficiency. Gamma chains bind 2,3-DPG less avidly than beta chains, shifting dissociation curve leftward.<br><br>This adaptation allows HbF to load oxygen even at the relatively low fetal umbilical venous PaO2. In placental insufficiency, where maternal-fetal oxygen transfer is reduced, the higher affinity provides partial compensation. Combined with chronic hypoxia-induced erythropoietin response producing polycythaemia, fetus partially compensates for reduced delivery, though severe insufficiency still produces fetal hypoxaemia.<br><br>Lower oxygen affinity (A) is opposite. Lower CO2 affinity (C) is not principal feature. Increased Bohr effect (D) is contributory but secondary.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with maternal anemia may still maintain adequate oxygen supply due to which physiological adaptation?',o:['Reduced oxygen consumption','Reduced fetal metabolism','High affinity fetal hemoglobin','Reduced fetal heart rate'],a:2,
e:`Maternal anaemia may still allow adequate fetal oxygen supply because of high-affinity fetal haemoglobin (HbF) and the relatively preserved oxygen partial pressure in placental intervillous space. HbF achieves 60-70% saturation at the relatively low fetal umbilical venous PaO2 of 30 mmHg.<br><br>Combined with fetal polycythaemia (Hb 16-18 g/dL), high fetal cardiac output per kg, and double Bohr effect (CO2 transfer), fetal oxygen delivery is preserved unless maternal anaemia is severe. Iron deficiency in pregnancy commonly produces mild maternal anaemia without significant fetal compromise; severe maternal anaemia can however affect fetal growth.<br><br>Increased fetal HR alone (A) compensates partially. Higher fetal CO (B) helps. Increased HbA (D) is incorrect; HbF dominates.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with severe hypoxia shows redistribution of blood flow to vital organs. Which organs are preferentially supplied?',o:['Skin and muscles','Brain and heart','Liver and kidneys','Gastrointestinal tract'],a:1,
e:`Fetal hypoxia triggers redistribution of cardiac output to vital organs, particularly brain and heart, through chemoreceptor-mediated vasoconstriction in less critical territories (gut, kidneys, skin, muscle). This 'brain-sparing' effect preserves cerebral and myocardial oxygenation.<br><br>Doppler ultrasound detects this redistribution: middle cerebral artery shows decreased pulsatility index (vasodilation) while umbilical artery shows increased pulsatility (placental vasoconstriction). Severe chronic hypoxia from placental insufficiency depletes brain-sparing reserves, with eventual decompensation manifest as ductus venosus reverse flow, requiring urgent delivery to prevent fetal demise.<br><br>Lungs and liver (A), gut and kidneys (C) and skin (D) are reduced perfusion territories during hypoxia, not preserved.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus demonstrates swallowing of amniotic fluid as part of normal physiology. This process mainly contributes to:',o:['Gastrointestinal tract maturation','Lung maturation','Kidney maturation','Placental circulation'],a:0,
e:`Fetal swallowing of amniotic fluid contributes to gastrointestinal tract maturation, with swallowed fluid absorbed across fetal gut supporting development of villi, peristalsis and digestive enzymes. Swallowing rises from negligible at 20 weeks to 500-1000 mL/day at term.<br><br>Amniotic fluid volume reflects balance between fetal urine production and swallowing. Impaired swallowing (oesophageal atresia, neuromuscular disorder, anencephaly) causes polyhydramnios. Reduced urine production (renal abnormality, placental insufficiency) causes oligohydramnios. Fetal swallowing also exposes the gut to growth factors in amniotic fluid important for mucosal development.<br><br>Placental development (B) is independent. Renal function (C) produces urine. Lung development (D) is parallel separate process.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus develops oligohydramnios due to decreased fetal urine production. Which fetal organ normally contributes most to amniotic fluid production in late pregnancy?',o:['Lung','Placenta','Kidney','Liver'],a:2,
e:`Decreased fetal urine production from renal abnormality (renal agenesis, multicystic dysplastic kidneys, polycystic kidney disease, posterior urethral valves) or placental insufficiency reducing renal perfusion produces oligohydramnios. Fetal urine is principal contributor to amniotic fluid from second trimester.<br><br>Severe oligohydramnios from 20 weeks causes Potter sequence with pulmonary hypoplasia, limb deformities and characteristic Potter facies (low-set ears, flat nose, retrognathia). Ultrasound identifies anatomical cause. Bilateral renal agenesis is uniformly fatal due to pulmonary hypoplasia, while obstructive uropathy may be amenable to intrauterine intervention in selected cases.<br><br>Lung (A) contributes minor amounts. Liver (B) does not regulate. Heart (D) does not produce amniotic fluid directly.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The fetal adrenal gland is relatively large compared with body weight because it:',o:['Produces steroid precursors for placental estrogen synthesis','Produces thyroid hormones','Produces insulin','Produces prolactin'],a:0,
e:`Fetal adrenal gland is relatively large because it produces steroid precursors essential for placental estrogen synthesis. The fetal zone of the adrenal cortex specialises in dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate (DHEAS) production from approximately 10 weeks gestation onwards.<br><br>DHEAS serves as androgen precursor for placental estrogens since placenta lacks 17-alpha-hydroxylase. Placental sulfatase desulfates DHEAS, then aromatase converts it to estrogens. Most estriol production additionally requires fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation. Fetal adrenal at term weighs proportionally three to four times more than adult adrenal, with the fetal zone involuting after birth.<br><br>Fetal cortisol (B) supports lung maturation. Aldosterone (C) regulates sodium. Catecholamines (D) are not the principal fetal adrenal product.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal circulation pathway directs blood toward the ascending aorta and brain?',o:['Umbilical artery','Hepatic vein','Ductus arteriosus','Foramen ovale'],a:3,
e:`Foramen ovale directs blood from right atrium to left atrium, then through left ventricle into ascending aorta. This streaming delivers the most oxygenated blood (from ductus venosus via IVC) preferentially to coronary and cerebral circulations supplied by ascending aorta and arch vessels.<br><br>The eustachian valve at IVC-right atrial junction directs the well-oxygenated stream from ductus venosus across foramen ovale, while less oxygenated SVC blood enters right ventricle. Combined with ductus arteriosus shunting RV output to descending aorta, this physiological streaming ensures brain and heart receive the highest oxygen content.<br><br>Ductus arteriosus (A) shunts to descending aorta. Ductus venosus (B) bypasses liver. Umbilical vein (C) is incoming source.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal metabolic substrate becomes increasingly important in late gestation for brain development?',o:['Glucose','Amino acids','Ketone bodies','Fatty acids'],a:0,
e:`Glucose becomes increasingly important fetal metabolic substrate in late gestation as fetal growth accelerates. Fetal glucose consumption rises markedly in third trimester, supported by maternal hPL-induced insulin resistance ensuring adequate maternal glucose for transplacental supply.<br><br>Glucose crosses placenta by facilitated diffusion through GLUT1 and GLUT3 transporters down its gradient. Fetal glucose levels run 0.5-1 mmol/L below maternal levels. Lactate, ketones and amino acids supplement during fasting. In maternal diabetes, fetal hyperglycaemia stimulates fetal pancreas producing fetal hyperinsulinaemia, accelerating fat deposition and producing macrosomia.<br><br>Lactate (B) and amino acids (C) supplement. Free fatty acids (D) cross placenta poorly compared with glucose.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal physiological mechanism helps maintain adequate oxygen delivery despite low oxygen tension in fetal blood?',o:['Reduced hemoglobin levels','Reduced cardiac output','Reduced blood flow','High hemoglobin concentration and HbF affinity'],a:3,
e:`Fetal physiological adaptation maintaining adequate oxygen delivery despite low umbilical venous PaO2 of 30 mmHg includes high haemoglobin concentration of 16-18 g/dL combined with high oxygen affinity of fetal haemoglobin (HbF). Together these compensate for the relatively low oxygen partial pressure.<br><br>HbF gamma chains bind 2,3-DPG less avidly than HbA beta chains, shifting dissociation curve leftward and allowing 60-70% saturation at fetal PaO2. Polycythaemia raises total oxygen content. Combined with high fetal cardiac output per kg body weight and double Bohr effect (CO2 transfer), fetal oxygen delivery is adequate.<br><br>Higher PaO2 alone (A), increased CO2 (B) and decreased pH (C) do not by themselves enhance oxygen delivery.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal endocrine gland contributes significantly to steroid hormone precursor production for the fetoplacental unit?',o:['Adrenal gland','Pancreas','Thyroid gland','Pituitary gland'],a:0,
e:`Fetal adrenal gland contributes significantly to steroid hormone synthesis, particularly dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate (DHEAS) production, which serves as androgen precursor for placental estrogen synthesis. Placenta lacks 17-alpha-hydroxylase and depends on fetal DHEAS supply.<br><br>Placental sulfatase desulfates DHEAS, then aromatase converts to estrogens. Most estriol production additionally requires fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation, creating the fetoplacental unit. Fetal adrenal also produces cortisol promoting lung maturation. The fetal zone enlarges three to four times relative to body weight, involuting after birth.<br><br>Thyroid (B) produces thyroid hormone. Pituitary (C) produces tropic hormones. Pancreas (D) produces insulin and glucagon, not steroids.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal organ is responsible for production of surfactant necessary for postnatal lung expansion?',o:['Placenta','Fetal lung type II pneumocytes','Fetal adrenal gland','Fetal liver'],a:1,
e:`Fetal lung type II pneumocytes (alveolar epithelial cells) are responsible for production of pulmonary surfactant necessary for alveolar stability after birth. Surfactant is a phospholipid-protein complex containing dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine that reduces alveolar surface tension preventing collapse during expiration.<br><br>Surfactant production begins at 24-26 weeks, increasing significantly after 34 weeks under cortisol stimulation. Antenatal corticosteroids accelerate maturation when given at 24-34 weeks. Below 34 weeks, surfactant deficiency produces respiratory distress syndrome (RDS) of prematurity with grunting, tachypnoea, retractions and hypoxaemia, treated with exogenous surfactant therapy.<br><br>Type I pneumocytes (A) form gas exchange barrier. Goblet cells (C) and macrophages (D) do not produce surfactant.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal circulation structure allows blood to bypass the lungs and enter systemic circulation directly?',o:['Umbilical vein','Foramen ovale','Ductus arteriosus','Ductus venosus'],a:2,
e:`Ductus arteriosus allows fetal blood to bypass the non-functional fetal lungs by shunting from pulmonary artery directly to descending aorta. This carries approximately 90% of right ventricular output away from the high-resistance pulmonary circulation.<br><br>Patency in utero is maintained by placental prostaglandin E2 and low fetal oxygen tension. After birth, increased oxygen tension and reduced prostaglandins trigger functional closure within 24-48 hours, anatomic closure over 2-3 weeks. Persistent patent ductus arteriosus produces continuous machinery murmur and left-to-right shunt; treated with indomethacin in preterm or surgical ligation.<br><br>Foramen ovale (A) bypasses lungs at atrial level. Ductus venosus (B) bypasses liver. Umbilical artery (D) carries blood to placenta.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The fetal oxygen saturation in umbilical vein is approximately:',o:['95%','30%','50%','70-80%'],a:3,
e:`Fetal oxygen saturation in umbilical vein is approximately 70-80% (PaO2 ~30 mmHg), much higher than fetal arterial saturation of 60-65% in ascending aorta and 50-55% in descending aorta. Despite the relatively low driving pressure, fetal oxygen delivery is adequate.<br><br>This is achieved through fetal haemoglobin (HbF) higher oxygen affinity allowing 60-70% saturation at PaO2 of 30 mmHg, plus high fetal Hb concentration (16-18 g/dL), high fetal cardiac output per kg, and double Bohr effect with CO2 transfer between maternal and fetal blood enhancing oxygen unloading at tissues.<br><br>30-40% (A), 50-60% (B) and 90-100% (C) misestimate the actual umbilical venous saturation.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal physiological process contributes to regulation of amniotic fluid volume?',o:['Placental diffusion only','Fetal swallowing and urination','Maternal liver metabolism','Maternal kidney function'],a:1,
e:`Fetal swallowing and urination are the principal physiological processes regulating amniotic fluid volume from second trimester onwards. Fetal kidneys produce urine (5-50 mL/hour) while fetal GI tract swallows amniotic fluid (500-1000 mL/day at term).<br><br>Balance between these processes determines amniotic fluid volume. Pulmonary fluid contributes minor amounts. Reduced urine (renal abnormality, placental insufficiency) causes oligohydramnios. Impaired swallowing (oesophageal atresia, neuromuscular disorder) causes polyhydramnios. Severe oligohydramnios produces Potter sequence with pulmonary hypoplasia, while polyhydramnios is associated with preterm labour.<br><br>Placental transfer alone (A) is minor. Maternal hydration (C) influences mildly. Fetal lung secretion (D) is contributory not primary.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A clinician explains that fetal physiology supports intrauterine life by utilizing specialized circulation and metabolic adaptations. Which fetal organ receives the highest proportion of cardiac output during fetal hypoxia?',o:['Brain','Liver','Skeletal muscle','Kidney'],a:0,
e:`Fetal physiology supports intrauterine life with preferential delivery of the most oxygenated blood to the brain through coordinated streaming. Umbilical vein blood traverses ductus venosus, joining IVC, then through foramen ovale to left atrium, left ventricle and ascending aorta supplying brain.<br><br>This pathway delivers blood with PaO2 ~25-30 mmHg to cerebral and coronary circulation, while less oxygenated blood from SVC enters RV and is shunted via ductus arteriosus to descending aorta. The arrangement preserves brain oxygenation despite low fetal PaO2. Brain-sparing reflex amplifies this during hypoxia through cerebral vasodilation.<br><br>Liver priority (B) is not feature; liver receives moderate flow. Lungs receive minimal flow (C). Kidney receives moderate flow (D).<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'The fetal blood returning from placenta through the umbilical vein first enters:',o:['Ductus arteriosus','Liver','Inferior vena cava','Right atrium'],a:1,
e:`Fetal blood returning from placenta through umbilical vein first reaches the liver at the porta hepatis. About 50% of umbilical venous flow perfuses fetal liver through hepatic portal sinuses, while 50% bypasses liver via ductus venosus to inferior vena cava.<br><br>This delivery to fetal liver supports its multiple functions: principal site of mid-gestation haematopoiesis (6-24 weeks), storage of glycogen (peak in third trimester), and steroid hormone metabolism including 16-alpha-hydroxylation of DHEAS for placental estriol synthesis. After birth, umbilical vein closure leaves liver dependent on portal vein and hepatic artery.<br><br>Heart (A), kidneys (C) and lungs (D) do not receive umbilical venous blood directly; liver is the first organ.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal metabolic adaptation helps prepare the newborn for extrauterine life?',o:['Reduced insulin secretion','Reduced fat deposition','Glycogen accumulation in liver','Reduced glucose storage'],a:2,
e:`Glycogen accumulation in fetal liver during third trimester (particularly 30-36 weeks) is the principal metabolic adaptation preparing the newborn for extrauterine life. These reserves provide energy through glycogenolysis during the transition from continuous transplacental glucose supply to intermittent feeding.<br><br>At birth, abrupt cessation of maternal glucose supply combined with high metabolic demand requires endogenous glucose production. Hepatic glycogen breakdown maintains blood glucose for the first 12-24 hours until feeding establishes. IUGR neonates with depleted glycogen and preterm infants with insufficient stores are at high risk of neonatal hypoglycaemia requiring early feeding or IV glucose.<br><br>Increased respiratory rate (A) is not metabolic. Increased cardiac output (B) is not preparation. Decreased BMR (D) is opposite.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal organ produces bile during intrauterine life?',o:['Lung','Placenta','Kidney','Liver'],a:3,
e:`Fetal liver produces bile during intrauterine life from approximately 12 weeks gestation onwards. Bile contains bile salts, bilirubin, cholesterol and phospholipids, accumulating in the gallbladder and being secreted into fetal duodenum.<br><br>Fetal bilirubin is mostly cleared by placenta to maternal circulation for conjugation and excretion, so fetal jaundice is uncommon despite high bilirubin production from haemoglobin turnover. After birth, immature hepatic bilirubin conjugation produces physiological neonatal jaundice peaking at 3-5 days. Meconium contains fetal bile pigments and intestinal cell debris.<br><br>Spleen (A) does not produce bile. Pancreas (B) produces digestive enzymes. Gallbladder (C) stores bile produced by liver.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which fetal circulation vessel eventually forms the medial umbilical ligaments after birth?',o:['Umbilical arteries','Umbilical vein','Ductus arteriosus','Ductus venosus'],a:0,
e:`Umbilical arteries become the medial umbilical ligaments after birth. The proximal portions (closest to internal iliac arteries) remain patent as the superior vesical arteries supplying the bladder, while the distal portions atrophy to fibrous cords running on the inner anterior abdominal wall.<br><br>These bilateral medial umbilical ligaments are visible peritoneal folds during laparoscopic surgery, important anatomical landmarks. They run from the lateral aspect of bladder to the umbilicus. The median umbilical ligament (single, midline) is the obliterated urachus, separate structure from the two paired medial umbilical ligaments.<br><br>Ductus arteriosus (B) becomes ligamentum arteriosum. Umbilical vein (C) becomes ligamentum teres. Ductus venosus (D) becomes ligamentum venosum.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'A clinician explains that fetal physiology is adapted to the intrauterine environment with reliance on placental gas exchange and specialized circulatory shunts. Which fetal shunt primarily bypasses the pulmonary circulation?',o:['Umbilical vein','Hepatic vein','Ductus arteriosus','Ductus venosus'],a:2,
e:`Fetal physiology is adapted to intrauterine life through several key cardiovascular structures, with ductus arteriosus playing a central role. It shunts approximately 90% of right ventricular output from pulmonary artery to descending aorta, bypassing the high-resistance fetal pulmonary circulation.<br><br>This adaptation directs blood to systemic circulation including lower body and umbilical arteries returning to placenta for gas exchange. Patency is maintained by placental prostaglandin E2 and low oxygen tension. After birth, increased oxygen and reduced prostaglandins trigger closure within 24-48 hours, with anatomic closure over 2-3 weeks producing ligamentum arteriosum.<br><br>Coronary sinus (A) is normal venous structure. Pulmonary veins (B) are not adapted shunts. Eustachian tube (D) is unrelated middle ear structure.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone is primarily responsible for maintaining the corpus luteum during early pregnancy?',o:['Estrogen','Human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG)','Progesterone','Human placental lactogen (hPL)'],a:1,
e:`hCG from syncytiotrophoblast binds LH receptors on corpus luteum cells, sustaining progesterone secretion essential for early pregnancy. Without hCG rescue, luteal regression at day 14 would trigger menstruation.<br><br>Serum hCG doubles every 48-72 hours, peaking at 8-11 weeks at around 100,000 IU/L. The placenta then assumes progesterone production at the luteal-placental shift around 7-10 weeks gestation.<br><br>Estrogen (A) is corpus luteum product, not its rescuer. Progesterone (C) is the corpus luteum output. Prolactin (D) supports lactation, not luteal maintenance during early pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The placenta acts as an endocrine organ by secreting which hormone that promotes maternal lipolysis and insulin resistance?',o:['Oxytocin','Prolactin','Thyroxine','Human placental lactogen'],a:3,
e:`Human placental lactogen acts as endocrine hormone modulating maternal metabolism. It induces peripheral insulin resistance, lipolysis and gluconeogenesis, ensuring transplacental glucose delivery to the fetus.<br><br>hPL secretion increases progressively with placental mass, peaking in third trimester. Excessive effects produce gestational diabetes when pancreatic beta cell compensation fails. hPL also stimulates fetal IGF-1 promoting growth and prepares maternal breast for lactation.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (B) drives uterine and breast growth. Relaxin (C) softens connective tissues; not a major metabolic hormone.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone is structurally similar to luteinizing hormone (LH)?',o:['Relaxin','Human chorionic gonadotropin','Estrogen','Progesterone'],a:1,
e:`hCG shares the alpha subunit with LH, FSH and TSH, but its beta subunit is 80% homologous with LH beta. This similarity allows hCG to bind LH receptors on corpus luteum cells.<br><br>Receptor cross-reactivity is the molecular basis for hCG rescue of corpus luteum during early pregnancy. hCG also weakly cross-reacts with TSH receptors causing transient gestational thyrotoxicosis at peak hCG levels in molar pregnancy.<br><br>hPL (A) is similar to growth hormone. Estrogen (C) and progesterone (D) are steroid hormones structurally unrelated to glycoproteins like hCG.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone produced by the placenta maintains uterine quiescence during pregnancy?',o:['Oxytocin','Cortisol','Progesterone','Prolactin'],a:2,
e:`Progesterone is the dominant hormone maintaining uterine quiescence throughout pregnancy by downregulating gap junction connexin-43, oxytocin receptors and prostaglandin synthesis, while reducing calcium influx in smooth muscle cells.<br><br>This blocks excitation-contraction coupling, preventing preterm labour and maintaining pregnancy. Functional progesterone withdrawal through receptor isoform switching from PR-B to PR-A initiates term labour, alongside rising estrogen and prostaglandins increasing myometrial excitability.<br><br>Estrogen (A) increases contractility near term. hCG (B) maintains corpus luteum, not myometrial quiescence. Oxytocin (D) stimulates contractions, opposing progesterone's quiescent action on the myometrium.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone contributes significantly to breast development during pregnancy?',o:['Prolactin','hPL','Estrogen','All of the above'],a:3,
e:`Estrogen, progesterone and hPL all contribute significantly to breast development during pregnancy. Estrogen drives ductal proliferation, progesterone develops alveolar lobules, while hPL provides additional lactogenic stimulation alongside maternal prolactin.<br><br>This combined action prepares the breast for lactation throughout second and third trimesters. Despite high circulating levels, milk secretion is suppressed during pregnancy because these steroids inhibit alveolar prolactin signalling. Their fall after delivery permits lactogenesis.<br><br>Each hormone alone (A, B, C) contributes partially; the complete answer recognises the combined contribution of all three to comprehensive breast development.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone produced by placenta increases progressively throughout pregnancy and has anti-insulin effects?',o:['Progesterone','Relaxin','Human placental lactogen','Estrogen'],a:2,
e:`Human placental lactogen rises progressively throughout pregnancy in proportion to placental mass, reaching peak concentrations at term. Its progressive rise reflects expanding syncytiotrophoblast mass and supports rising fetal substrate demands.<br><br>hPL is detected from 6 weeks, rising progressively to peak around 6 microgram/mL at term. The rise correlates with placental function; reduced levels suggest placental insufficiency. hPL falls rapidly after placental delivery.<br><br>hCG (A) peaks at 8-11 weeks then declines. Estrogen (B) and progesterone (D) rise but lack hPL's somatotropic and diabetogenic actions on metabolism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Placental estrogens are synthesized primarily from:',o:['Fetal adrenal androgen precursors','Maternal ovarian cholesterol','Maternal insulin','Placental glycogen'],a:0,
e:`Placental estrogens are synthesised primarily from fetal adrenal androgen precursors, principally dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate (DHEAS). Placenta lacks 17-alpha-hydroxylase and cannot synthesise androgens de novo from cholesterol.<br><br>Placental sulfatase desulfates DHEAS, then aromatase converts it to estrogens. Most estriol production additionally requires fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation. This obligate cooperation between fetus and placenta creates the fetoplacental unit for estrogen synthesis.<br><br>Maternal cholesterol (B) supplies progesterone, not androgens. Placental cholesterol synthesis (C) is not the substrate. Maternal androgens (D) contribute minor amounts compared with fetal sources.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The predominant estrogen produced by the placenta during pregnancy is:',o:['Estradiol','Estrone','Estriol','Progesterone'],a:2,
e:`Estriol is the predominant estrogen produced by the placenta during pregnancy, constituting approximately 90% of maternal urinary estrogens at term. It is produced by the fetoplacental unit.<br><br>Maternal estriol concentrations rise from negligible nonpregnant levels to over 100 nmol/L at term. Estriol monitoring assesses fetoplacental unit integrity, with declining levels indicating fetal compromise or placental insufficiency.<br><br>Estradiol (A) and estrone (B) circulate at lower concentrations during pregnancy. Estradiol valerate (D) is a synthetic ester used in HRT, not a naturally produced pregnancy hormone.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone stimulates maternal breast alveolar development preparing for lactation?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Prolactin','hPL'],a:3,
e:`Human placental lactogen stimulates maternal breast alveolar development during pregnancy, complementing the actions of estrogen, progesterone and prolactin. hPL acts via prolactin receptors to promote mammary epithelial differentiation.<br><br>hPL secretion increases progressively with placental mass, reaching peak in third trimester. Combined with estrogen-driven ductal proliferation and progesterone-driven alveolar development, hPL prepares the breast for lactation. Postnatally, abrupt placental hormone withdrawal permits prolactin-driven lactogenesis II.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) mediates milk ejection. FSH (B) regulates follicular development. LH (C) stimulates ovulation; none have lactogenic effects during pregnancy comparable to hPL.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The placenta produces progesterone primarily from:',o:['Maternal glucose','Maternal cholesterol','Placental glycogen','Fetal insulin'],a:1,
e:`Placental progesterone is produced primarily from maternal cholesterol entering syncytiotrophoblast via LDL receptors. Cholesterol undergoes side-chain cleavage by CYP11A1 to pregnenolone, then conversion by 3-beta-HSD to progesterone.<br><br>Placental progesterone reaches 250 mg per day at term, far exceeding corpus luteum capacity. Unlike estrogen synthesis which requires fetal adrenal precursors, placental progesterone is independent of fetal contribution. Progesterone levels remain stable in fetal demise.<br><br>Fetal adrenal androgens (A) are precursors for estrogen, not progesterone. Maternal androgens (C) and fetal cholesterol (D) are not the principal substrates for placental progesterone.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman at 8 weeks gestation has low hCG levels and ultrasound shows poor corpus luteum function. Which placental function is impaired?',o:['Production of insulin','Regulation of maternal blood pressure','Production of thyroid hormone','Maintenance of corpus luteum'],a:3,
e:`Low hCG levels at 8 weeks gestation suggest threatened miscarriage or ectopic pregnancy. hCG normally maintains corpus luteum progesterone production, which is essential for endometrial decidualisation and pregnancy maintenance until placental takeover.<br><br>Failure of hCG to double every 48-72 hours in early pregnancy raises concern. Quantitative serum hCG monitoring discriminates between viable intrauterine pregnancy, ectopic pregnancy and impending miscarriage, alongside transvaginal ultrasound for confirmation.<br><br>Stimulating ovulation (A) is LH role. Inducing labour (B) is opposite. Suppressing maternal pituitary (C) is not the principal hCG function in pregnancy maintenance.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops gestational diabetes due to placental hormone effects. Which hormone is mainly responsible?',o:['Human placental lactogen','Oxytocin','Progesterone','Estrogen'],a:0,
e:`Human placental lactogen is the principal placental hormone responsible for gestational diabetes through induction of peripheral insulin resistance. It interferes with post-insulin-receptor signalling, requiring two to threefold increases in maternal insulin secretion.<br><br>Effects intensify with placental mass through second and third trimesters. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops, diagnosed at 24-28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing. hPL effects regress rapidly after placental delivery.<br><br>hCG (B) maintains corpus luteum. Progesterone (C) and estrogen (D) contribute mildly but are not the principal diabetogenic hormones during pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with placental insufficiency shows reduced estriol levels in maternal serum. Which fetal organ contributes precursors for placental estriol synthesis?',o:['Fetal pancreas','Fetal lung','Fetal adrenal gland','Fetal kidney'],a:2,
e:`Reduced maternal estriol levels in placental insufficiency reflect impaired fetoplacental steroidogenesis. The pathway requires fetal adrenal DHEAS, fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation and placental aromatisation; disruption at any step lowers estriol.<br><br>Fetal adrenal cortex produces large amounts of DHEAS as principal precursor. Maternal estriol monitoring assesses fetoplacental unit integrity, with declining values indicating fetal compromise, growth restriction or demise. Unconjugated estriol forms part of triple/quadruple screening.<br><br>Maternal pituitary (A) and ovary (B) do not contribute to placental estriol synthesis. Maternal adrenal (D) supplies precursors minimally compared with fetal source.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman with placental dysfunction develops poor uterine quiescence leading to preterm contractions. Which hormone deficiency is most likely?',o:['Estrogen','Prolactin','hPL','Progesterone'],a:3,
e:`Progesterone deficiency from placental dysfunction produces poor uterine quiescence and predisposes to preterm labour. Progesterone normally maintains quiescence by downregulating gap junction connexin-43, oxytocin receptors and prostaglandin synthesis.<br><br>Progesterone supplementation (vaginal pessaries or intramuscular hydroxyprogesterone caproate) reduces preterm labour risk in women with previous preterm birth or short cervix. Functional progesterone withdrawal at term initiates labour through receptor isoform switching from PR-B to PR-A.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (B) increases contractility. Prolactin (C) drives lactation, with no role in uterine quiescence.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant patient develops insulin resistance in late pregnancy due to placental hormones. Which hormone is mainly responsible for this metabolic adaptation?',o:['Oxytocin','Thyroxine','Human placental lactogen','Prolactin'],a:2,
e:`Human placental lactogen is the principal cause of insulin resistance in late pregnancy. It interferes with insulin receptor signalling, particularly insulin receptor substrate-1 phosphorylation in muscle and adipose tissue.<br><br>hPL secretion increases progressively with placental mass, reaching peak in third trimester. Maternal insulin requirements rise two to threefold to maintain euglycaemia. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops, diagnosed at 24-28 weeks with glucose tolerance testing.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Progesterone (B) and estrogen (D) contribute mildly but are not principal diabetogenic hormones during late pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone plays a key role in fetal adrenal maturation and timing of labor?',o:['Placental CRH','hPL','Prolactin','Progesterone'],a:0,
e:`Placental corticotropin-releasing hormone plays a key role in fetal adrenal maturation and labour timing. It is secreted by syncytiotrophoblast in increasing amounts toward term, stimulating fetal pituitary ACTH and adrenal cortisol production.<br><br>Placental CRH rises exponentially toward term. The placental clock hypothesis proposes that the rate of CRH rise determines parturition timing, with accelerated rise associated with preterm labour. Cortisol-driven surfactant production supports fetal lung maturation.<br><br>hPL (B) drives metabolism. Estrogen (C) drives uterine growth. hCG (D) maintains corpus luteum and peaks early; not principal in fetal adrenal maturation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Placental progesterone production after the first trimester is mainly dependent on:',o:['Fetal insulin','Maternal LH stimulation','Maternal pituitary prolactin','Maternal cholesterol supply'],a:3,
e:`Placental progesterone production after the first trimester depends mainly on maternal cholesterol supply. Cholesterol enters syncytiotrophoblast via LDL receptors, undergoes side-chain cleavage by CYP11A1 to pregnenolone, then conversion by 3-beta-HSD.<br><br>Placental progesterone reaches 250 mg per day at term. Unlike estrogen synthesis requiring fetal adrenal precursors, placental progesterone is independent of fetal contribution. Progesterone levels remain stable in fetal demise, while estriol falls reflecting fetal compromise.<br><br>Fetal cholesterol (A), fetal adrenal androgens (B) and maternal androgens (C) are not the principal substrates for placental progesterone synthesis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone contributes to increased maternal lipolysis and availability of nutrients to the fetus?',o:['Estrogen','hPL','Relaxin','Progesterone'],a:1,
e:`Human placental lactogen contributes to increased maternal lipolysis through hormone-sensitive lipase activation in adipose tissue, releasing free fatty acids that maternal tissues use for energy. This spares glucose for transplacental fetal delivery.<br><br>Combined with hPL-induced insulin resistance, this metabolic adaptation supports continuous fetal glucose supply during maternal fasting. hPL secretion increases progressively with placental mass, reaching peak in third trimester when fetal substrate demands are greatest.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (C) drives uterine and breast growth. Progesterone (D) maintains quiescence; none significantly affect maternal lipolysis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The fetoplacental unit refers to:',o:['Interaction between maternal ovary and placenta','Interaction between uterus and placenta only','Interaction between maternal pituitary and placenta','Interaction between fetal adrenal gland and placenta for steroid synthesis'],a:3,
e:`Fetoplacental unit refers to the obligate cooperation between fetal adrenal gland and placenta for estrogen synthesis. Placenta lacks 17-alpha-hydroxylase; the fetus lacks placental aromatase. Neither can independently produce estrogens.<br><br>Fetal adrenal DHEAS is desulfated by placental sulfatase and aromatised to estrogens. For estriol, fetal liver first 16-alpha-hydroxylates DHEAS before placental aromatisation. Maternal estriol monitoring assesses fetoplacental integrity, declining with fetal or placental compromise.<br><br>Maternal-fetal blood mixing (A) does not occur normally. Maternal pituitary (B) does not regulate this. Maternal-placental progesterone (C) is independent of fetal contribution.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone increases maternal thyroid-binding globulin levels indirectly through estrogen stimulation?',o:['Estrogen','Prolactin','Progesterone','hPL'],a:0,
e:`Estrogen during pregnancy stimulates hepatic synthesis of thyroxine-binding globulin through estrogen receptor activation in hepatocytes. TBG levels approximately double, increasing total thyroxine and triiodothyronine while free hormone fractions remain relatively unchanged.<br><br>This explains why thyroid function tests in pregnancy require trimester-specific reference ranges. Estrogen-driven hepatic synthesis also raises sex hormone binding globulin, cortisol-binding globulin and clotting factors, contributing to the procoagulant state of pregnancy.<br><br>Progesterone (B), hPL (C) and prolactin (D) do not significantly stimulate hepatic protein synthesis comparable to estrogen during pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman with placental insufficiency shows decreased fetal growth due to reduced nutrient transfer. Which primary placental function is compromised?',o:['Amniotic fluid production','Hormone secretion only','Transport of nutrients and oxygen','Fetal urine formation'],a:2,
e:`Placental insufficiency reduces transport of nutrients and oxygen to the fetus, producing intrauterine growth restriction. Trophoblast invasion of maternal spiral arteries normally converts them to high-flow, low-resistance vessels accommodating uteroplacental blood flow.<br><br>Inadequate spiral artery remodelling underlies pre-eclampsia and growth restriction syndromes. Doppler ultrasound assesses uteroplacental and fetal-placental flow; absent or reversed end-diastolic flow indicates severe insufficiency. Reduced glucose, amino acid and oxygen transfer manifest as fetal growth lag.<br><br>Hormone production (A), gas exchange alone (B) and immune transfer (D) are also placental functions but nutrient transport directly limits fetal growth.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus develops hypoxia due to impaired placental blood flow. Which placental function is primarily affected?',o:['Hormonal regulation','Endocrine secretion','Immune tolerance','Gas exchange'],a:3,
e:`Placental gas exchange between maternal and fetal blood is essential for fetal oxygenation. The intervillous space contains maternal blood at PaO2 around 95 mmHg, while fetal villous capillaries contain blood at PaO2 around 30 mmHg.<br><br>Oxygen diffuses across the placental barrier (syncytiotrophoblast, basement membranes, endothelium) down its gradient. Impaired placental blood flow reduces this exchange, producing fetal hypoxia. Adaptations including high-affinity HbF and high fetal Hb maintain delivery despite low driving pressure.<br><br>Hormone secretion (A), nutrient transport (B) and waste removal (C) are placental functions but gas exchange directly governs fetal oxygenation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman receives antenatal steroids for fetal lung maturation. Which placental function helps deliver these hormones to the fetus?',o:['Selective transport across placental membrane','Umbilical arterial circulation','Fetal renal filtration','Fetal hepatic metabolism'],a:0,
e:`Antenatal steroids cross the placenta by selective transport across placental membrane to reach the fetus. Synthetic corticosteroids (betamethasone, dexamethasone) cross more readily than natural cortisol, which is largely inactivated by placental 11-beta-HSD2.<br><br>Antenatal corticosteroids given to women at 24-34 weeks at risk of preterm delivery accelerate fetal lung maturation, reducing respiratory distress syndrome by 50%, intraventricular haemorrhage and neonatal mortality. Effect peaks at 24 hours and persists 7 days after administration.<br><br>Active hormone secretion (B) is independent. Maternal-fetal blood mixing (C) does not occur. Bulk fluid transfer (D) is not the mechanism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus receives maternal IgG antibodies via placenta providing passive immunity. Which placental function explains this?',o:['Respiratory exchange','Immune transfer','Hormone secretion','Metabolic function'],a:1,
e:`Maternal IgG antibodies cross the placenta via active immune transfer through Fc receptors on syncytiotrophoblast, providing the fetus with passive immunity that persists for several months postnatally. Transfer increases markedly in third trimester.<br><br>This is the principal source of neonatal humoral immunity until the infant's own production matures around 6 months. IgM, IgA and IgE do not cross the placenta significantly. Maternal vaccination during pregnancy (influenza, pertussis) protects the newborn through transferred IgG.<br><br>Selective barrier (A) blocks substances. Active transport (C) applies to nutrients. Hormone synthesis (D) is independent function of placenta.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with placental failure develops severe intrauterine growth restriction. Which placental function is essential for fetal nutrition?',o:['Amniotic fluid formation','Hormone secretion only','Fetal endocrine function','Nutrient transport'],a:3,
e:`Placental failure causing severe intrauterine growth restriction primarily reflects impaired nutrient transport. Glucose crosses by facilitated diffusion through GLUT1 and GLUT3, amino acids by active transport, and free fatty acids by carrier-mediated diffusion.<br><br>Reduced placental surface area, impaired trophoblast invasion of spiral arteries, or chronic ischaemia all reduce transfer capacity. Fetal growth lag, oligohydramnios and Doppler abnormalities follow. Severe placental insufficiency requires close fetal surveillance and timely delivery to prevent fetal demise.<br><br>Hormone secretion (A) is also affected. Gas exchange (B) and waste removal (C) are placental functions but nutrient transport directly limits growth.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone suppresses maternal immune rejection of the fetus?',o:['Oxytocin','Insulin','Progesterone','Prolactin'],a:2,
e:`Progesterone suppresses maternal immune rejection of the fetus by shifting the cytokine balance from Th1 (cell-mediated, fetus-rejecting) toward Th2 (humoral, tolerogenic), inducing progesterone-induced blocking factor in lymphocytes.<br><br>This adaptation prevents maternal rejection of the semi-allogeneic fetus expressing paternal HLA antigens. Disturbance of this balance is implicated in recurrent miscarriage and pre-eclampsia. HLA-G expression on trophoblast and regulatory T cells contribute additional tolerance mechanisms.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. hPL (B) drives metabolism. Estrogen (D) supports tolerance partly but progesterone is the principal immunosuppressive hormone.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental enzyme converts androgens to estrogens during pregnancy?',o:['21-hydroxylase','Desmolase','17-hydroxylase','Aromatase'],a:3,
e:`Aromatase (CYP19A1) in placental syncytiotrophoblast converts androgens to estrogens during pregnancy. The enzyme acts on fetal adrenal-derived DHEAS (after placental sulfatase removes the sulfate group), producing estrone, estradiol and estriol.<br><br>Placental aromatase activity is essential for the fetoplacental unit's estrogen production. Aromatase deficiency (rare) causes maternal virilisation during pregnancy due to androgen accumulation. Aromatase inhibitors used in breast cancer treatment block this enzyme in adipose tissue postmenopausally.<br><br>Sulfatase (A) desulfates DHEAS. 5-alpha-reductase (B) converts testosterone to DHT. 17-alpha-hydroxylase (C) is absent in placenta.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone contributes significantly to maternal metabolic adaptation ensuring glucose supply to fetus?',o:['hPL','Estrogen','Relaxin','Progesterone'],a:0,
e:`Human placental lactogen contributes significantly to maternal metabolic adaptation during pregnancy. It induces insulin resistance, lipolysis and gluconeogenesis, ensuring continuous transplacental glucose delivery to the fetus while maternal tissues use alternative substrates.<br><br>hPL secretion increases progressively with placental mass, peaking in third trimester. Combined with cortisol, estrogen and progesterone, it produces the diabetogenic state of pregnancy. When pancreatic compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops at 24-28 weeks.<br><br>hCG (B) maintains corpus luteum. Progesterone (C) maintains quiescence. Estrogen (D) drives uterine growth; none have hPL's central metabolic actions.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone is used clinically as the earliest biochemical marker of pregnancy?',o:['Estrogen','hCG','Progesterone','hPL'],a:1,
e:`Human chorionic gonadotropin is the earliest biochemical marker of pregnancy, detectable in maternal serum from approximately day 8 after fertilisation following implantation, when syncytiotrophoblast begins secretion.<br><br>Modern urinary pregnancy tests detect hCG above 25 IU/L from the first day of missed period. Quantitative serum hCG is more sensitive at 5 IU/L. hCG doubles every 48-72 hours in early pregnancy, peaking at 8-11 weeks at around 100,000 IU/L.<br><br>hPL (A) is detected later from second trimester. Estrogen (C) and progesterone (D) rise but are not specific for pregnancy detection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental function is most critical for maintaining fetal oxygenation throughout pregnancy?',o:['Hormone synthesis','Nutrient metabolism','Gas exchange between maternal and fetal blood','Endocrine secretion'],a:2,
e:`Placental gas exchange is the most critical placental function for maintaining fetal oxygenation. Maternal blood in the intervillous space delivers oxygen to fetal villous capillaries across the placental barrier through diffusion driven by partial pressure gradient.<br><br>Maternal PaO2 in intervillous space is approximately 95 mmHg, fetal umbilical venous PaO2 around 30 mmHg. Adaptations including high-affinity fetal haemoglobin, high fetal Hb concentration and double Bohr effect maintain adequate fetal oxygen delivery despite the relatively low pressure.<br><br>Hormone secretion (A), nutrient transport (B) and waste removal (D) are essential placental functions but gas exchange directly governs fetal oxygenation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone is most responsible for increasing maternal fat metabolism during pregnancy?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Prolactin','Human placental lactogen'],a:3,
e:`Human placental lactogen is most responsible for increasing maternal fat storage during early pregnancy. It drives anabolism with appetite stimulation and adipose tissue deposition, expanding maternal fat reserves by 3-4 kg in first half of pregnancy.<br><br>In second half of pregnancy, hPL action shifts to catabolism with insulin resistance and lipolysis predominating, mobilising stored fat as free fatty acids for maternal energy while sparing glucose for transplacental fetal supply. This biphasic effect coordinates maternal metabolism with fetal demands.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (B) drives growth. Progesterone (C) maintains quiescence; none drive fat storage like hPL.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental function protects the fetus from many maternal pathogens while allowing selective antibody transfer?',o:['Placental glycogen storage','Placental endocrine secretion','Placental barrier function','Placental vascularization'],a:2,
e:`Placental barrier function protects the fetus from many maternal pathogens by restricting transplacental transmission of bacteria and large parasites, while allowing nutrients, gases and antibodies to cross. The syncytiotrophoblast layer forms the principal barrier.<br><br>However, several pathogens cross the placenta causing congenital infections (TORCH: Toxoplasma, Other including syphilis and parvovirus, Rubella, Cytomegalovirus, Herpes simplex), producing fetal abnormalities. HIV transmission can be reduced through antiretroviral therapy and elective caesarean delivery.<br><br>Gas exchange (A), nutrient transport (B) and hormone production (D) are other placental functions; barrier function specifically addresses pathogen exclusion.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone contributes to uterine growth during pregnancy?',o:['Estrogen','Relaxin','hPL','Progesterone'],a:0,
e:`Estrogen contributes most to uterine growth during pregnancy through estrogen receptor alpha activation, inducing smooth muscle hyperplasia and hypertrophy. Uterine weight rises from 70 grams nonpregnant to approximately 1000 grams at term.<br><br>Estrogen also stimulates uterine vascular development through VEGF expression, raising blood flow from 50 to 700 mL/min. Endothelial nitric oxide synthase induction produces uterine vasodilation. Myometrial hypertrophy is balanced by progesterone-mediated suppression of contractility maintaining quiescence.<br><br>Progesterone (B) maintains quiescence. hCG (C) maintains corpus luteum. Relaxin (D) softens connective tissues; none drive myometrial growth like estrogen.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone helps maintain pregnancy by suppressing uterine contractions?',o:['Estrogen','Oxytocin','Progesterone','Prostaglandins'],a:2,
e:`Progesterone helps maintain pregnancy by suppressing uterine contractions through downregulation of gap junction connexin-43, oxytocin receptors and prostaglandin synthesis, while reducing calcium influx in smooth muscle.<br><br>This blocks excitation-contraction coupling, preventing preterm labour. Functional progesterone withdrawal through receptor isoform switching from PR-B to PR-A precedes term labour. Progesterone also exerts immunomodulation favouring Th2 cytokine bias for fetal tolerance.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (B) increases contractility. Prolactin (D) drives lactation; none have progesterone's quiescent action.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A clinician explains that the placenta performs endocrine, respiratory, metabolic, and immunological functions essential for fetal development. Which function primarily supports fetal oxygen supply?',o:['Gas exchange','Nutrient metabolism','Immune protection','Hormone production'],a:0,
e:`The placenta performs endocrine, respiratory, nutritional and immunological functions, with gas exchange being the respiratory role. Oxygen diffuses from maternal intervillous blood (PaO2 95 mmHg) to fetal villous capillaries (PaO2 30 mmHg) across the placental barrier.<br><br>This transfer occurs by passive diffusion down partial pressure gradient. Fetal adaptations including high-affinity HbF, high fetal Hb concentration, high fetal cardiac output and double Bohr effect maintain adequate fetal oxygen delivery despite relatively low driving pressure.<br><br>Hormone production (B), nutrient transport (C) and immune protection (D) are other placental functions; gas exchange specifically performs respiratory role.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone level increases steadily and can be used as an indicator of placental function in late pregnancy?',o:['Prolactin','Oxytocin','hCG','hPL'],a:3,
e:`Human placental lactogen levels rise steadily throughout pregnancy in proportion to placental mass, reaching peak at term. This makes hPL a useful indicator of placental function in the second and third trimesters.<br><br>Reduced hPL levels suggest placental insufficiency and may correlate with fetal growth restriction. However, hPL has been largely superseded by ultrasound, Doppler studies and cardiotocography in clinical practice for assessing fetal wellbeing. hPL falls rapidly after placental delivery alongside resolution of insulin resistance.<br><br>hCG (A) peaks early then declines. Estrogen (B) and progesterone (C) rise but are less reliable indicators of placental function over time.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental function ensures transfer of amino acids to the fetus against a concentration gradient?',o:['Passive diffusion','Active transport','Endocytosis','Osmosis'],a:1,
e:`Amino acids are transferred across the placenta to the fetus by active transport, using sodium-dependent transporters on the maternal-facing membrane of syncytiotrophoblast. This energy-dependent process moves amino acids against their concentration gradient.<br><br>Fetal plasma amino acid concentrations exceed maternal levels for most amino acids. Different transporter systems (System A, ASC, L) handle different amino acid groups. Reduced placental amino acid transport contributes to fetal growth restriction in placental insufficiency.<br><br>Simple diffusion (A) handles small lipid-soluble substances. Facilitated diffusion (C) handles glucose. Pinocytosis (D) is bulk transport mechanism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone is primarily responsible for maintaining uteroplacental blood flow?',o:['Progesterone','hPL','Oxytocin','Estrogen'],a:3,
e:`Estrogen is primarily responsible for maintaining uteroplacental blood flow during pregnancy. It induces endothelial nitric oxide synthase and prostacyclin in uterine vascular endothelium, producing vasodilation and increased flow.<br><br>Estrogen also drives angiogenesis through VEGF expression, expanding the uteroplacental vascular bed. Uterine blood flow rises from 50 mL/min nonpregnant to 500-700 mL/min at term. Inadequate spiral artery remodelling contributes to pre-eclampsia and fetal growth restriction.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Progesterone (B) maintains quiescence. Relaxin (C) contributes to systemic vasodilation but estrogen drives the uterine-specific increase.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental mechanism allows small lipid-soluble substances such as oxygen and carbon dioxide to cross easily?',o:['Carrier transport','Pinocytosis','Simple diffusion','Active transport'],a:2,
e:`Simple diffusion across the placenta allows transfer of small lipid-soluble substances such as oxygen, carbon dioxide, free fatty acids and steroids. These substances cross the lipid bilayer of syncytiotrophoblast down their concentration gradient without carriers.<br><br>Larger or hydrophilic molecules require facilitated diffusion (glucose), active transport (amino acids), or pinocytosis (proteins, antibodies). Lipophilic drugs and toxins also cross by simple diffusion, explaining why many medications and substances of abuse readily reach the fetus during pregnancy.<br><br>Active transport (A) handles amino acids. Facilitated diffusion (B) handles glucose. Pinocytosis (D) handles antibodies and large molecules.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A gynecologist explains that the placenta performs multiple vital roles during pregnancy including endocrine secretion, nutrient transfer, gas exchange, immune protection, and metabolic regulation. Which placental hormone plays the most important role in adapting maternal metabolism to support fetal growth?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','hCG','Human placental lactogen'],a:3,
e:`Human placental lactogen plays multiple vital roles during pregnancy, contributing to maternal metabolic adaptation, fetal growth and breast preparation for lactation. It induces insulin resistance, lipolysis, and stimulates fetal IGF-1 production.<br><br>hPL secretion correlates with placental mass, rising progressively to peak at term. Its central role in shifting maternal metabolism to support fetal substrate demand makes it the principal placental metabolic hormone. Postnatally, hPL falls rapidly with placental delivery.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum primarily. Estrogen (B) drives uterine growth. Progesterone (C) maintains quiescence; none cover hPL's metabolic role.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) primarily maintains which structure during early pregnancy?',o:['Corpus luteum','Placenta','Fetal adrenal gland','Endometrium'],a:0,
e:`Human chorionic gonadotropin maintains the corpus luteum during early pregnancy by binding LH receptors on luteal cells, sustaining progesterone secretion essential for endometrial decidualisation and pregnancy maintenance.<br><br>Without hCG rescue, corpus luteum regression by day 14 would trigger menstruation. hCG doubles every 48-72 hours, peaking at 8-11 weeks at around 100,000 IU/L. The placenta then assumes progesterone production at the luteal-placental shift around 7-10 weeks.<br><br>Placenta (B) is the source of hCG, not target. Endometrium (C) responds to progesterone. Pituitary (D) is suppressed during pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone is mainly responsible for maternal insulin resistance during pregnancy?',o:['Estrogen','Human placental lactogen','Progesterone','Relaxin'],a:1,
e:`Human placental lactogen is mainly responsible for maternal insulin resistance during pregnancy through interference with insulin receptor signalling, particularly insulin receptor substrate-1 phosphorylation in muscle and adipose tissue.<br><br>Maternal insulin requirements rise two to threefold to maintain euglycaemia. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops, diagnosed at 24-28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing. hPL effects regress rapidly after placental delivery, resolving insulin resistance.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Progesterone (C) and estrogen (D) contribute mildly but are not the principal diabetogenic hormones.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Placental progesterone plays a major role in pregnancy by:',o:['Stimulating uterine contractions','Stimulating ovulation','Increasing prostaglandin synthesis','Maintaining uterine quiescence'],a:3,
e:`Placental progesterone plays a major role in pregnancy by maintaining uterine quiescence. It inhibits myometrial contractility through downregulation of gap junction connexin-43, oxytocin receptors and prostaglandin synthesis.<br><br>Placental progesterone reaches 250 mg per day at term, far exceeding corpus luteum capacity. Functional progesterone withdrawal through receptor isoform switching from PR-B to PR-A initiates term labour. Progesterone also exerts immunomodulation favouring Th2 cytokine bias for fetal tolerance.<br><br>Stimulating ovulation (A) is LH role. Inducing labour (B) is opposite. Suppressing fetal growth (C) is incorrect; progesterone supports pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The predominant estrogen produced by the placenta during pregnancy is:',o:['Estradiol','Estrone','Estriol','Progesterone'],a:2,
e:`Estriol is the predominant estrogen produced by the placenta during pregnancy, constituting approximately 90% of maternal urinary estrogens at term. It is produced by the fetoplacental unit through fetal adrenal-placental cooperation.<br><br>Maternal estriol concentrations rise from negligible nonpregnant levels to over 100 nmol/L at term. Maternal estriol monitoring assesses fetoplacental unit integrity, with declining levels indicating fetal compromise. Unconjugated estriol forms part of triple/quadruple antenatal screening.<br><br>Estradiol (A) and estrone (B) circulate at lower concentrations. Estradiol valerate (D) is a synthetic ester used in HRT, not naturally produced.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone contributes significantly to breast preparation for lactation by stimulating mammary gland development?',o:['hPL','Estrogen','Prolactin','Oxytocin'],a:0,
e:`Human placental lactogen contributes significantly to breast preparation for lactation alongside estrogen, progesterone and prolactin. hPL acts via prolactin receptors to promote mammary epithelial differentiation.<br><br>hPL secretion increases progressively with placental mass, reaching peak in third trimester. Combined with estrogen-driven ductal proliferation and progesterone-driven alveolar development, hPL prepares the breast for lactation. Postnatally, abrupt placental hormone withdrawal permits prolactin-driven lactogenesis II.<br><br>Oxytocin (B) mediates milk ejection. FSH (C) regulates follicular development. LH (D) stimulates ovulation; none have lactogenic action like hPL.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Placental estrogen production depends mainly on precursors from:',o:['Maternal ovary','Fetal adrenal gland','Maternal pancreas','Maternal kidney'],a:1,
e:`Placental estrogen production depends mainly on precursors from fetal adrenal gland, principally dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate (DHEAS). Placenta lacks 17-alpha-hydroxylase and cannot synthesise androgens de novo from cholesterol.<br><br>Placental sulfatase desulfates DHEAS, then aromatase converts it to estrogens. Most estriol production additionally requires fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation. This obligate cooperation creates the fetoplacental unit, with maternal estriol monitoring assessing integrity.<br><br>Maternal ovary (A) ceases significant estrogen production after corpus luteum involutes. Maternal adrenal (C) and fetal liver (D) provide minor contributions only.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone has structural similarity to LH and is detectable in early pregnancy tests?',o:['hPL','Relaxin','Progesterone','hCG'],a:3,
e:`hCG has structural similarity to luteinizing hormone, sharing the alpha subunit with LH, FSH and TSH. The beta subunit is 80% homologous with LH beta, allowing hCG to bind LH receptors on corpus luteum cells.<br><br>hCG is detectable in maternal serum from day 8 after fertilisation. This early detection makes hCG the basis for pregnancy testing. Quantitative serum hCG monitors early pregnancy progress, with doubling every 48-72 hours indicating viable intrauterine pregnancy.<br><br>hPL (A) is similar to growth hormone. Estrogen (B) and progesterone (C) are steroid hormones, structurally unrelated to LH.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone contributes to increased uterine blood flow during pregnancy?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','hPL','Prolactin'],a:0,
e:`Estrogen contributes to increased uterine blood flow during pregnancy through induction of endothelial nitric oxide synthase and prostacyclin in uterine vascular endothelium, producing vasodilation. Estrogen also stimulates angiogenesis through VEGF expression.<br><br>Uterine blood flow increases from 50 mL/min nonpregnant to 500-700 mL/min at term, supporting placental gas exchange and nutrient delivery. Inadequate spiral artery remodelling underlies placental insufficiency syndromes including pre-eclampsia and fetal growth restriction.<br><br>Progesterone (B) maintains quiescence. hCG (C) maintains corpus luteum. Relaxin (D) contributes to systemic vasodilation but estrogen drives the uterine-specific increase.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone suppresses maternal immune rejection of the fetus?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Oxytocin','Relaxin'],a:1,
e:`Progesterone suppresses maternal immune rejection of the fetus by shifting cytokine balance from Th1 (cell-mediated, fetus-rejecting) toward Th2 (humoral, tolerogenic) and inducing progesterone-induced blocking factor in lymphocytes.<br><br>This adaptation prevents maternal rejection of the semi-allogeneic fetus expressing paternal HLA antigens. Disturbance is implicated in recurrent miscarriage, pre-eclampsia and other pregnancy complications. HLA-G expression on trophoblast and regulatory T cells contribute additional tolerance mechanisms.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. hPL (C) drives metabolism. Estrogen (D) supports tolerance partly but progesterone is principal immunosuppressive hormone.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone increases maternal lipolysis ensuring adequate nutrient supply to the fetus?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','hPL','hCG'],a:2,
e:`Human placental lactogen increases maternal lipolysis ensuring adequate energy substrates for fetus. It activates hormone-sensitive lipase in adipose tissue, releasing free fatty acids that maternal tissues use, sparing glucose for transplacental fetal delivery.<br><br>Combined with hPL-induced insulin resistance, this metabolic adaptation supports continuous fetal glucose supply during maternal fasting. hPL secretion increases progressively with placental mass, reaching peak in third trimester when fetal substrate demands are greatest.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (B) drives uterine growth. Progesterone (D) maintains quiescence; none drive lipolysis like hPL.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 28-year-old pregnant woman at 9 weeks gestation presents with threatened miscarriage. Laboratory investigations show markedly reduced serum hCG levels compared with expected values for gestational age. Ultrasound shows poor corpus luteum function and decreased progesterone support of the endometrium. Which physiological role of hCG is primarily responsible for maintaining early pregnancy in this patient?',o:['Maintenance of corpus luteum progesterone secretion','Stimulation of fetal adrenal cortex','Induction of uterine contractions','Suppression of maternal prolactin'],a:0,
e:`In threatened miscarriage at 9 weeks, hCG primarily maintains corpus luteum progesterone secretion essential for endometrial decidualisation and pregnancy maintenance. Adequate hCG and progesterone support continued pregnancy.<br><br>Quantitative hCG monitoring discriminates between viable intrauterine pregnancy (doubling every 48-72 hours), ectopic pregnancy and impending miscarriage. Vaginal progesterone supplementation may benefit some women with threatened miscarriage and previous miscarriages, though evidence for routine use remains limited.<br><br>Direct uterine relaxation (B) is progesterone effect. Decidual support (C) is progesterone-mediated. Inhibiting prostaglandins (D) is not principal hCG action.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman in her third trimester develops progressive insulin resistance and mild hyperglycemia despite no prior history of diabetes. This metabolic adaptation is considered physiological because it ensures continuous nutrient availability to the fetus. Which placental hormone is mainly responsible for producing this anti-insulin effect?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Human placental lactogen','Oxytocin'],a:2,
e:`Human placental lactogen is the principal cause of progressive insulin resistance in the third trimester. It interferes with insulin receptor signalling, particularly IRS-1 phosphorylation in muscle and adipose tissue.<br><br>hPL effects intensify with placental mass, peaking at term when maternal insulin requirements rise two to threefold. Insulin-treated diabetic women experience worsening glycaemic control alongside rising hPL. Postnatally, hPL falls rapidly after placental delivery, resolving insulin resistance and reducing insulin requirements.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (B) and progesterone (D) contribute mildly but are not the principal diabetogenic hormones.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with placental insufficiency demonstrates decreased estriol levels on maternal serum screening. Placental estrogen production requires cooperation between fetal and placental tissues. Which fetal organ provides androgen precursors necessary for placental estrogen synthesis?',o:['Fetal liver','Fetal adrenal gland','Fetal kidney','Fetal pancreas'],a:1,
e:`Fetal adrenal gland is essential for placental estriol synthesis through DHEAS production. Decreased estriol levels in placental insufficiency reflect impaired fetoplacental steroidogenesis at fetal adrenal, fetal liver or placental level.<br><br>Fetal adrenal at term weighs proportionally three to four times more than adult adrenal, with fetal zone specialised for DHEAS production. The pathway requires fetal adrenal DHEAS, fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation and placental aromatisation; disruption at any step lowers maternal estriol.<br><br>Maternal ovary (A) does not contribute. Maternal adrenal (C) provides minor amounts. Fetal liver (D) hydroxylates but is not the principal precursor source.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman presents with premature uterine contractions at 30 weeks gestation. Evaluation reveals reduced progesterone activity leading to increased uterine excitability and prostaglandin sensitivity. Which physiological function of placental progesterone normally prevents this condition during pregnancy?',o:['Maintenance of uterine quiescence','Stimulation of placental blood flow','Stimulation of fetal growth hormone','Activation of oxytocin receptors'],a:0,
e:`Progesterone normally maintains uterine quiescence and prevents preterm contractions. Premature uterine contractions at 30 weeks suggest functional progesterone deficiency or accelerated withdrawal at the receptor level.<br><br>Progesterone supplementation (vaginal pessaries or intramuscular hydroxyprogesterone caproate) reduces preterm labour risk in women with previous preterm birth or short cervix on transvaginal ultrasound. Tocolytics like nifedipine or atosiban may delay delivery, allowing time for antenatal corticosteroids and transfer to neonatal services.<br><br>Stimulating contractions (B) is opposite. Inducing cervical dilation (C) is opposite. Suppressing fetal adrenal (D) is not the role.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During normal pregnancy, maternal metabolism undergoes adaptations that increase lipid mobilization and reduce maternal glucose utilization so that adequate glucose remains available for fetal growth. Which placental hormone is primarily responsible for this metabolic shift?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Human placental lactogen','Relaxin'],a:2,
e:`Human placental lactogen is responsible for maternal metabolic adaptations during pregnancy, inducing insulin resistance, lipolysis and gluconeogenesis. These changes ensure continuous transplacental glucose delivery to the fetus.<br><br>hPL secretion increases progressively with placental mass, peaking in third trimester. Maternal pancreatic beta cells normally compensate with two to threefold rise in insulin secretion. When compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops, diagnosed at 24-28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (B) drives uterine growth. Progesterone (D) maintains quiescence; none drive metabolic adaptation like hPL.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant patient undergoes maternal serum screening which includes measurement of estriol levels. Estriol is produced through a cooperative interaction between the placenta and the fetus, particularly involving steroid precursors from fetal tissues. Which endocrine unit describes this physiological relationship?',o:['Hypothalamic-pituitary axis','Fetoplacental unit','Maternal ovarian axis','Placental endocrine loop'],a:1,
e:`Maternal serum screening for estriol assesses fetoplacental unit integrity. Estriol synthesis requires obligate cooperation between fetal adrenal DHEAS production, fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation, and placental aromatisation.<br><br>Reduced estriol indicates fetal compromise, growth restriction, fetal demise or anencephaly with adrenal hypoplasia. Unconjugated estriol forms part of triple test (with AFP, hCG) and quadruple test (adding inhibin A) for screening trisomy 21 and 18, with low values raising risk.<br><br>Corpus luteum (A) does not produce estriol. Maternal pituitary (C) and maternal adrenal alone (D) cannot produce estriol.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops increased uterine blood flow and enlargement of the uterus during pregnancy. These changes are mediated largely by placental hormones which stimulate vascular growth and uterine muscle hypertrophy. Which hormone plays the most important role in this process?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','hPL','Oxytocin'],a:0,
e:`Estrogen is responsible for increased uterine blood flow and uterine enlargement during pregnancy. It induces myometrial smooth muscle hyperplasia and hypertrophy, while stimulating angiogenesis and endothelial nitric oxide synthase production.<br><br>Uterine weight rises from 70 to 1000 grams; blood flow rises from 50 mL/min to 500-700 mL/min at term. Combined with progesterone-mediated quiescence maintenance, this enables uterine accommodation of fetus and placenta. Inadequate vascular adaptation contributes to placental insufficiency.<br><br>Progesterone (B) maintains quiescence. hCG (C) maintains corpus luteum. Relaxin (D) contributes to systemic vasodilation but estrogen drives uterine-specific changes.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant patient develops gestational diabetes due to hormonal influences that antagonize maternal insulin action. This change allows increased glucose availability for the developing fetus. Which placental hormone is most responsible for this effect?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Human placental lactogen','Relaxin'],a:2,
e:`Human placental lactogen is the principal hormone causing gestational diabetes through induction of peripheral insulin resistance. It interferes with post-receptor signalling, requiring two to threefold increases in maternal insulin secretion.<br><br>Effects intensify with placental mass through second and third trimesters. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops, diagnosed at 24-28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing. Tight glycaemic control reduces fetal macrosomia, neonatal hypoglycaemia and other diabetic pregnancy complications.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (B) and progesterone (D) contribute mildly but are not the principal diabetogenic hormones.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with placental dysfunction demonstrates decreased nutrient transfer and impaired growth. Placental hormones normally regulate maternal metabolism and nutrient availability to ensure fetal development. Which hormone plays the most significant role in mobilizing maternal energy stores?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','hCG','hPL'],a:3,
e:`Human placental lactogen contributes to fetal nutrient supply by inducing maternal insulin resistance, lipolysis and gluconeogenesis, ensuring continuous transplacental glucose delivery. Reduced hPL in placental dysfunction correlates with reduced fetal substrate availability.<br><br>hPL also stimulates fetal IGF-1 production directly promoting fetal growth. hPL secretion correlates with placental mass; reduced levels suggest placental insufficiency, often paralleled by reduced glucose, amino acid and oxygen transfer manifesting as intrauterine growth restriction.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (B) drives uterine growth. Progesterone (C) maintains quiescence; none directly modulate nutrient transport.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman undergoing routine antenatal care is found to have rising hCG levels in early pregnancy. These high levels are responsible for maintaining progesterone production until placental steroidogenesis becomes sufficient. What physiological transition marks the point at which the placenta takes over progesterone production from the corpus luteum?',o:['Luteal-placental shift','Placental endocrine transition','Fetal adrenal activation','Maternal pituitary stimulation'],a:0,
e:`Rising progesterone with falling hCG in second trimester reflects the luteal-placental shift. The placenta progressively assumes progesterone production from corpus luteum around 7-10 weeks, eventually exceeding luteal capacity.<br><br>Placental progesterone synthesis uses maternal cholesterol via CYP11A1 and 3-beta-HSD enzymes, reaching 250 mg per day at term. Removal of corpus luteum before this shift causes pregnancy loss; afterward does not affect pregnancy. Unlike estrogen, progesterone synthesis is independent of fetal contribution.<br><br>Fetoplacental unit (B) describes estrogen synthesis. Endocrine feedback (C) is general term. Maternal pituitary suppression (D) occurs but is not specifically this shift.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman at 20 weeks gestation experiences progressive enlargement of the breasts and development of mammary glandular tissue in preparation for lactation. These changes occur due to combined effects of placental hormones that stimulate ductal growth, alveolar proliferation, and metabolic adaptation. Which hormone plays the most direct role in promoting mammary gland development during pregnancy?',o:['Estrogen','hPL','Progesterone','Oxytocin'],a:1,
e:`Human placental lactogen contributes to progressive breast enlargement by stimulating mammary alveolar development through prolactin receptors. It also drives maternal metabolic adaptation including insulin resistance and lipolysis.<br><br>hPL secretion increases progressively with placental mass, reaching peak in third trimester. Breast preparation for lactation involves combined action of estrogen (ductal), progesterone (alveolar), prolactin and hPL. Postnatally, abrupt placental hormone withdrawal permits prolactin-driven lactogenesis II within 30-72 hours.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (C) drives ductal growth. Progesterone (D) develops alveoli; hPL provides additional lactogenic effect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During pregnancy, maternal immune tolerance is essential to prevent rejection of the fetus despite its partial genetic difference from the mother. Placental hormones play a critical role in modulating the maternal immune response. Which hormone contributes most to maintaining this immunological tolerance?',o:['Estrogen','hPL','Progesterone','Relaxin'],a:2,
e:`Maternal immune tolerance during pregnancy is essential to prevent rejection of the semi-allogeneic fetus expressing paternal HLA antigens. Progesterone is the principal hormone supporting this immune adaptation.<br><br>Progesterone shifts cytokine balance from Th1 toward Th2, induces progesterone-induced blocking factor in lymphocytes, and reduces uterine NK cell cytotoxicity. HLA-G expression on trophoblast and regulatory T cells contribute additional tolerance. Disturbance is implicated in recurrent miscarriage and pre-eclampsia.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. hPL (B) drives metabolism. Estrogen (D) supports tolerance partly but progesterone is principal immunosuppressive hormone.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus depends on the placenta not only for nutrient exchange but also for endocrine regulation that supports fetal growth and maternal metabolic adaptation. Which placental hormone primarily increases maternal fat metabolism and reduces maternal glucose utilization to ensure continuous glucose availability for the fetus?',o:['Progesterone','Human placental lactogen','Estrogen','Oxytocin'],a:1,
e:`Human placental lactogen supports fetal nutrient transfer and growth through dual mechanisms: maternal insulin resistance ensuring transplacental glucose delivery, and direct stimulation of fetal IGF-1 production promoting tissue growth.<br><br>hPL secretion correlates with placental mass, rising progressively to peak at term. Reduced hPL suggests placental insufficiency with paralleled reduction in fetal substrate availability, manifesting as intrauterine growth restriction. hPL also drives maternal lipolysis providing free fatty acids for maternal energy.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (C) drives uterine growth. Progesterone (D) maintains quiescence; none have hPL's direct fetal growth role.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman presents with hyperemesis gravidarum during the first trimester. This condition is strongly associated with elevated levels of a placental hormone that rises rapidly in early pregnancy and peaks around 10 weeks of gestation. Which hormone is most likely responsible?',o:['hCG','Estrogen','Progesterone','hPL'],a:0,
e:`Hyperemesis gravidarum severity correlates with hCG levels, with extreme elevations in molar pregnancy, multiple gestation and trophoblastic disease showing increased frequency of severe nausea and vomiting in the first trimester.<br><br>Mechanisms include hCG cross-reactivity with TSH receptors causing transient gestational thyrotoxicosis, and direct effects on the chemoreceptor trigger zone. Symptoms peak between 8-12 weeks when hCG is highest, settling as hCG declines. Severe cases require IV fluids, antiemetics and thiamine to prevent Wernicke encephalopathy.<br><br>hPL (B) drives metabolism. Estrogen (C) and progesterone (D) contribute to nausea but are not principally responsible for hyperemesis severity.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Placental hormones coordinate maternal physiological changes, fetal growth, and uterine adaptation throughout pregnancy. Which placental hormone is primarily responsible for maintaining pregnancy by suppressing uterine contractility and preventing premature labor?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','hPL','Relaxin'],a:1,
e:`Progesterone coordinates maternal physiological changes, fetal growth and pregnancy maintenance through multiple actions: maintaining uterine quiescence, supporting endometrial decidualisation, suppressing maternal immune rejection of the fetus, and stimulating breast alveolar development.<br><br>Placental progesterone reaches 250 mg per day at term, far exceeding corpus luteum capacity. Functional progesterone withdrawal through receptor isoform switching from PR-B to PR-A precedes term labour. Progesterone deficiency in early pregnancy causes inadequate decidualisation and recurrent miscarriage.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. hPL (C) drives metabolism. Estrogen (D) drives growth; none cover progesterone's broad maintenance role.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone is the earliest biochemical marker of pregnancy?',o:['hPL','Progesterone','Estrogen','hCG'],a:3,
e:`Human chorionic gonadotropin is the earliest biochemical marker of pregnancy, detectable in maternal serum from approximately day 8 after fertilisation following implantation, when syncytiotrophoblast begins secretion.<br><br>Modern urinary pregnancy tests detect hCG above 25 IU/L, providing reliable detection from the first day of missed period. Quantitative serum hCG is more sensitive at 5 IU/L and is used to monitor early pregnancy progress, with doubling every 48-72 hours indicating viable intrauterine pregnancy.<br><br>hPL (A) is detected later from second trimester. Estrogen (B) and progesterone (C) rise but are not specific for early pregnancy detection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone contributes most to maternal metabolic adaptation during pregnancy?',o:['hPL','Progesterone','Estrogen','Relaxin'],a:0,
e:`Human placental lactogen contributes most to maternal metabolic adaptation supporting fetal growth. It induces peripheral insulin resistance, lipolysis and gluconeogenesis, ensuring continuous transplacental glucose delivery to the fetus.<br><br>hPL secretion increases progressively with placental mass, peaking in third trimester. Combined with cortisol, estrogen and progesterone, it produces the diabetogenic state of pregnancy. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops at 24-28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing.<br><br>hCG (B) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (C) drives uterine growth. Progesterone (D) maintains quiescence; none drive metabolic adaptation like hPL.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone produced by the placenta increases maternal thyroid-binding globulin indirectly?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','hPL','hCG'],a:1,
e:`Estrogen produced by the placenta increases maternal thyroid-binding globulin levels through stimulation of hepatic protein synthesis. TBG approximately doubles during pregnancy, raising total thyroxine and triiodothyronine while free fractions remain unchanged.<br><br>This explains why thyroid function tests in pregnancy require trimester-specific reference ranges. Estrogen-driven hepatic synthesis also raises sex hormone binding globulin, cortisol-binding globulin and clotting factors, contributing to the procoagulant state of pregnancy and increased venous thromboembolism risk.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum and weakly stimulates TSH receptors. hPL (C) drives metabolism. Progesterone (D) does not significantly affect TBG.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone stimulates fetal adrenal steroidogenesis and may contribute to onset of labor?',o:['Progesterone','hPL','Placental CRH','Prolactin'],a:2,
e:`Placental corticotropin-releasing hormone stimulates fetal adrenal steroidogenesis and maturation through ACTH-driven cortisol and DHEAS production. Fetal zone of adrenal cortex enlarges progressively under placental CRH influence.<br><br>Placental CRH rises exponentially toward term, contributing to fetal lung maturation through cortisol-driven surfactant production. The placental clock hypothesis proposes that the rate of CRH rise determines parturition timing, with accelerated rise producing preterm labour. CRH directly stimulates fetal adrenal cortisol independent of fetal pituitary.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. hPL (B) drives metabolism. Estrogen (D) drives uterine growth; none stimulate fetal adrenal like placental CRH.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone contributes most to uterine growth during pregnancy?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','hPL','Relaxin'],a:1,
e:`Estrogen contributes most to uterine growth during pregnancy through estrogen receptor alpha activation, inducing myometrial smooth muscle hyperplasia and hypertrophy. Uterine weight rises from 70 grams nonpregnant to approximately 1000 grams at term.<br><br>Estrogen also stimulates uterine vascular development through VEGF expression, expanding the uteroplacental vascular bed and raising blood flow from 50 to 700 mL/min. Combined with progesterone-mediated quiescence maintenance, this enables uterine accommodation of fetus and placenta throughout pregnancy.<br><br>hPL (A) drives metabolism. hCG (C) maintains corpus luteum. Progesterone (D) maintains quiescence; none drive myometrial growth like estrogen.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone produced by placenta contributes to maternal insulin resistance in late pregnancy?',o:['hCG','Estrogen','Progesterone','hPL'],a:3,
e:`Human placental lactogen contributes most to maternal insulin resistance during pregnancy through interference with insulin receptor signalling, particularly IRS-1 phosphorylation in muscle and adipose tissue.<br><br>Maternal insulin requirements rise two to threefold to maintain euglycaemia. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops, diagnosed at 24-28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing. hPL effects regress rapidly after placental delivery, resolving insulin resistance.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (B) drives uterine growth. Progesterone (C) maintains quiescence; none have hPL's central diabetogenic effect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone supports fetal growth by increasing nutrient availability?',o:['Estrogen','hPL','Progesterone','Oxytocin'],a:1,
e:`Human placental lactogen supports fetal growth by increasing nutrient availability through dual mechanisms: maternal insulin resistance ensuring transplacental glucose delivery, and lipolysis providing free fatty acids for maternal energy needs.<br><br>hPL also directly stimulates fetal IGF-1 production, promoting fetal tissue growth and accretion. Secretion correlates with placental mass, rising progressively to peak at term. Reduced hPL suggests placental insufficiency, often paralleled by reduced fetal substrate transfer manifesting as intrauterine growth restriction.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (C) drives uterine growth. Progesterone (D) maintains quiescence; none drive fetal nutrient supply like hPL.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone contributes most to suppression of uterine contractions during pregnancy?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Oxytocin','Prostaglandin'],a:0,
e:`Progesterone contributes most to suppression of uterine contractions during pregnancy through downregulation of gap junction connexin-43, oxytocin receptors and prostaglandin synthesis, while reducing calcium influx in smooth muscle.<br><br>This blocks excitation-contraction coupling, preventing preterm labour and maintaining pregnancy. Functional progesterone withdrawal through receptor isoform switching from PR-B to PR-A precedes term labour, alongside rising estrogen and prostaglandins shifting balance toward myometrial excitability and contraction.<br><br>hCG (B) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (C) increases contractility. Relaxin (D) softens connective tissues; none have progesterone's quiescent action.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone increases progressively and reflects placental function in late pregnancy?',o:['hCG','hPL','Estrogen','Progesterone'],a:1,
e:`Human placental lactogen increases progressively throughout pregnancy and reflects placental function. Levels rise in proportion to placental mass, reaching peak at term at around 6 microgram/mL.<br><br>Reduced hPL suggests placental insufficiency and may correlate with fetal growth restriction. However, hPL has been largely superseded by ultrasound, Doppler studies and cardiotocography for fetal assessment. hPL falls rapidly after placental delivery alongside resolution of insulin resistance and other metabolic effects.<br><br>hCG (A) peaks early at 8-11 weeks then declines. Estrogen (C) and progesterone (D) rise but are less reliable indicators of placental function.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone is primarily responsible for stimulating corpus luteum in early pregnancy?',o:['Estrogen','hPL','hCG','Progesterone'],a:2,
e:`Human chorionic gonadotropin is primarily responsible for stimulating corpus luteum progesterone secretion during early pregnancy. hCG binds LH receptors on corpus luteum cells, mimicking LH signal and sustaining luteal function.<br><br>Without hCG rescue, corpus luteum would regress at day 14 triggering menstruation. hCG doubles every 48-72 hours, peaking at 8-11 weeks at around 100,000 IU/L. The placenta then assumes progesterone production at the luteal-placental shift around 7-10 weeks.<br><br>hPL (A) drives metabolism. Estrogen (B) is corpus luteum product. Progesterone (D) is the corpus luteum output, not its stimulator.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone plays a major role in maintaining uteroplacental blood flow?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','hPL','Prolactin'],a:0,
e:`Estrogen plays a major role in maintaining uteroplacental blood flow through induction of endothelial nitric oxide synthase and prostacyclin in uterine vascular endothelium, producing vasodilation. It also stimulates angiogenesis through VEGF expression.<br><br>Uterine blood flow increases from 50 mL/min nonpregnant to 500-700 mL/min at term, supporting placental gas exchange and nutrient delivery. Inadequate spiral artery remodelling and impaired vascular adaptation contribute to pre-eclampsia and fetal growth restriction syndromes.<br><br>hCG (B) maintains corpus luteum. Progesterone (C) maintains quiescence. Relaxin (D) contributes to systemic vasodilation but estrogen drives uterine-specific increase.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone increases maternal lipid metabolism?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','hPL','Oxytocin'],a:2,
e:`Human placental lactogen increases maternal lipid metabolism by activating hormone-sensitive lipase in adipose tissue, releasing free fatty acids that maternal tissues use for energy. This spares glucose for transplacental fetal delivery.<br><br>In early pregnancy, hPL also drives anabolism with appetite stimulation and fat storage, expanding maternal fat reserves by 3-4 kg. In late pregnancy, action shifts to catabolism with lipolysis predominating. This biphasic effect coordinates maternal metabolism with changing fetal demands.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (B) drives uterine growth. Progesterone (D) maintains quiescence; none drive lipid metabolism like hPL.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone supports breast alveolar growth during pregnancy?',o:['hPL','Estrogen','Progesterone','Oxytocin'],a:0,
e:`Human placental lactogen supports breast alveolar growth during pregnancy alongside estrogen, progesterone and prolactin. hPL acts via prolactin receptors on mammary epithelium, promoting alveolar differentiation.<br><br>hPL secretion increases progressively with placental mass, reaching peak in third trimester. Combined with estrogen-driven ductal proliferation and progesterone-driven alveolar development, hPL prepares the breast for lactation. Postnatally, abrupt placental hormone withdrawal permits prolactin-driven lactogenesis II within 30-72 hours.<br><br>hCG (B) maintains corpus luteum. Oxytocin (C) mediates milk ejection. Cortisol (D) supports lung maturation; not lactogenic.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone is mainly responsible for maintaining pregnancy by preventing uterine contractions?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','hPL','hCG'],a:1,
e:`Progesterone is mainly responsible for maintaining pregnancy through multiple actions: maintaining uterine quiescence by suppressing myometrial contractility, supporting endometrial decidualisation for trophoblast invasion, and immune tolerance favouring Th2 cytokine bias.<br><br>Placental progesterone reaches 250 mg per day at term, far exceeding corpus luteum capacity. Functional progesterone withdrawal through receptor isoform switching from PR-B to PR-A precedes term labour. Progesterone deficiency in early pregnancy causes inadequate decidualisation and recurrent miscarriage.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (C) drives growth. hPL (D) drives metabolism; none cover progesterone's broad maintenance role.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone contributes most to metabolic adaptation ensuring continuous nutrient supply to the fetus?',o:['Estrogen','Relaxin','Progesterone','hPL'],a:3,
e:`Human placental lactogen contributes most to maternal metabolic adaptation ensuring fetal substrate supply. It induces peripheral insulin resistance, lipolysis and gluconeogenesis, sparing maternal glucose for transplacental fetal delivery.<br><br>hPL secretion increases progressively with placental mass, peaking in third trimester. The diabetogenic effect ensures continuous fetal glucose supply while maternal tissues use alternative energy substrates. When pancreatic compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops at 24-28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Progesterone (B) maintains quiescence. Estrogen (C) drives uterine growth; none drive metabolic adaptation like hPL.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 27-year-old pregnant woman at 10 weeks gestation presents with vaginal bleeding. Laboratory investigations show low serum hCG levels compared with the expected range for gestational age. Ultrasound demonstrates inadequate support of the endometrium due to failure of corpus luteum function. Which physiological role of hCG is most important for maintaining pregnancy during this stage?',o:['Suppression of uterine contractions','Activation of oxytocin receptors','Maintenance of corpus luteum progesterone secretion','Stimulation of fetal adrenal steroidogenesis'],a:2,
e:`In threatened miscarriage at 10 weeks, hCG primarily maintains corpus luteum progesterone secretion essential for endometrial decidualisation and pregnancy support. Adequate hCG and progesterone maintain pregnancy.<br><br>Quantitative hCG monitoring discriminates between viable intrauterine pregnancy (doubling every 48-72 hours), ectopic pregnancy and impending miscarriage. Vaginal ultrasound at this gestation should demonstrate fetal cardiac activity. Vaginal progesterone may benefit selected women with previous miscarriages.<br><br>Direct uterine relaxation (A) is progesterone effect. Inducing labour (B) is opposite. Suppressing pituitary (D) is not principal hCG action.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 30-year-old pregnant woman at 32 weeks gestation develops gestational diabetes mellitus despite no prior history of diabetes. The condition is attributed to placental hormones that antagonize insulin action and increase maternal lipolysis to ensure glucose availability for the fetus. Which placental hormone is primarily responsible for this metabolic adaptation?',o:['Estrogen','Human placental lactogen','Progesterone','Oxytocin'],a:1,
e:`Human placental lactogen is the principal hormone causing gestational diabetes at 32 weeks gestation through induction of peripheral insulin resistance. It interferes with post-receptor signalling, requiring two to threefold rise in maternal insulin secretion.<br><br>Effects intensify with placental mass, reaching peak in third trimester. Tight glycaemic control reduces fetal macrosomia, neonatal hypoglycaemia, shoulder dystocia and other complications. Diet, exercise, metformin and insulin manage gestational diabetes; hPL effects regress rapidly after placental delivery.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Progesterone (C) and estrogen (D) contribute mildly but are not principal diabetogenic hormones.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with placental insufficiency demonstrates reduced estriol levels in maternal serum screening tests. Placental estrogen production depends on androgen precursors supplied by fetal endocrine organs. Which fetal organ primarily provides these steroid precursors?',o:['Fetal adrenal gland','Fetal pancreas','Fetal kidney','Fetal liver'],a:0,
e:`Decreased estriol levels in placental insufficiency reflect impaired fetoplacental steroidogenesis at the fetal adrenal, fetal liver or placental level. Fetal adrenal cortex provides DHEAS as principal precursor.<br><br>The pathway requires fetal adrenal DHEAS, fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation and placental aromatisation; disruption at any step lowers maternal estriol. Maternal estriol monitoring assesses fetoplacental unit integrity, with declining values indicating fetal compromise, growth restriction or demise.<br><br>Maternal ovary (B) does not contribute. Maternal adrenal (C) provides minor amounts. Fetal liver (D) hydroxylates but is not the principal precursor source.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman at 28 weeks gestation presents with premature uterine contractions. Evaluation shows decreased progesterone activity leading to increased myometrial sensitivity to prostaglandins and oxytocin. Which physiological role of placental progesterone normally prevents this complication during pregnancy?',o:['Stimulation of uterine blood flow','Promotion of fetal lung maturation','Maintenance of uterine quiescence','Activation of cervical dilation'],a:2,
e:`Progesterone supplementation maintains uterine quiescence at 28 weeks in women with premature uterine contractions or short cervix. Progesterone normally inhibits myometrial contractility through downregulation of gap junctions, oxytocin receptors and prostaglandin synthesis.<br><br>Vaginal progesterone pessaries or intramuscular hydroxyprogesterone caproate reduce preterm labour risk in women with previous preterm birth or short cervix on transvaginal ultrasound. Tocolytics may delay delivery, allowing time for antenatal corticosteroids and transfer to neonatal services.<br><br>Stimulating contractions (A) is opposite. Inducing labour (B) is opposite. Suppressing fetal adrenal (D) is not the role.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 35-year-old pregnant woman undergoes routine antenatal screening. Her serum human placental lactogen levels are significantly lower than expected for gestational age. Reduced levels of this hormone may impair fetal growth because its normal role is to modify maternal metabolism and increase nutrient availability for the fetus. Which metabolic effect of hPL is most important for fetal nutrition?',o:['Increased maternal lipid mobilization and insulin resistance','Increased maternal insulin sensitivity','Increased maternal glucose utilization','Suppression of maternal metabolism'],a:0,
e:`Human placental lactogen drives increased maternal lipid mobilization and insulin resistance during pregnancy. It activates hormone-sensitive lipase in adipose tissue while interfering with insulin receptor signalling.<br><br>This dual action ensures continuous transplacental glucose delivery to the fetus while maternal tissues use free fatty acids for energy. hPL secretion increases progressively with placental mass, peaking in third trimester. Maternal pancreatic beta cells normally compensate; when this fails, gestational diabetes develops.<br><br>hCG (B) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (C) drives uterine growth. Progesterone (D) maintains quiescence; none drive metabolism like hPL.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone abnormality is most strongly associated with hyperemesis gravidarum in early pregnancy?',o:['Increased prolactin','Reduced estrogen','Reduced progesterone','Excess hCG'],a:3,
e:`Hyperemesis gravidarum is most strongly associated with excess hCG levels. Conditions with extreme hCG elevation including molar pregnancy, multiple gestation and trophoblastic disease show increased frequency of severe nausea and vomiting.<br><br>Mechanisms include hCG cross-reactivity with TSH receptors causing transient gestational thyrotoxicosis, and direct effects on the chemoreceptor trigger zone. Severe cases require IV fluids, antiemetics and thiamine to prevent Wernicke encephalopathy. Symptoms typically improve as hCG declines after 12 weeks.<br><br>Excess hPL (A) drives metabolism. Excess estrogen (B) and excess progesterone (C) contribute to nausea but are not principally responsible.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Markedly elevated hCG levels are commonly seen in which condition?',o:['Hydatidiform mole','Ectopic pregnancy','Placenta previa','Oligohydramnios'],a:0,
e:`Markedly elevated hCG levels are commonly seen in hydatidiform mole, a gestational trophoblastic disease where abnormal trophoblast proliferation produces extreme hCG elevations often exceeding 200,000 IU/L.<br><br>Complete moles (46XX, all paternal) and partial moles (69XXX or 69XXY) present with first trimester bleeding, large-for-dates uterus, hyperemesis, theca lutein cysts and early pre-eclampsia. Ultrasound shows snowstorm appearance. Suction evacuation followed by serial hCG monitoring detects gestational trophoblastic neoplasia development.<br><br>Threatened miscarriage (B) shows low or slowly rising hCG. Anembryonic pregnancy (C) and ectopic pregnancy (D) typically have lower hCG levels.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Reduced maternal serum estriol during pregnancy may indicate dysfunction of the:',o:['Pituitary gland','Maternal ovary','Fetoplacental unit','Maternal thyroid gland'],a:2,
e:`Reduced maternal serum estriol may indicate dysfunction of the fetoplacental unit. Estriol synthesis requires obligate cooperation between fetal adrenal DHEAS production, fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation, and placental aromatisation.<br><br>Reduced estriol indicates fetal compromise, growth restriction, fetal demise, or anencephaly with adrenal hypoplasia. Unconjugated estriol forms part of triple test and quadruple test for screening trisomy 21 and 18, with low values raising risk and prompting diagnostic testing.<br><br>Maternal ovary (A) does not produce estriol. Maternal pituitary (B) does not regulate this. Corpus luteum (D) does not produce estriol.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone deficiency may predispose to threatened abortion in early pregnancy?',o:['Relaxin deficiency','Estrogen deficiency','hPL deficiency','hCG deficiency'],a:3,
e:`hCG deficiency may predispose to threatened abortion because hCG normally maintains corpus luteum progesterone secretion essential for endometrial decidualisation and pregnancy maintenance until placental takeover.<br><br>Inadequate hCG production from poor implantation or trophoblast development leads to corpus luteum regression, progesterone deficiency, inadequate decidualisation and early pregnancy loss. Quantitative hCG monitoring discriminates between viable intrauterine pregnancy and impending miscarriage by tracking the doubling rate every 48-72 hours.<br><br>Estrogen deficiency (A) is rarely primary. hPL deficiency (B) affects later pregnancy. Progesterone deficiency (C) is consequence of hCG deficiency.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Elevated maternal serum hCG levels are most commonly used in screening for:',o:['Down syndrome','Neural tube defects','Congenital adrenal hyperplasia','Turner syndrome'],a:0,
e:`Elevated maternal serum hCG levels are most commonly used in screening for Down syndrome (trisomy 21). hCG is a component of triple test (with AFP, unconjugated estriol) and quadruple test (adding inhibin A).<br><br>Down syndrome shows characteristic pattern: high hCG, low AFP, low unconjugated estriol, high inhibin A. Combined first trimester screening uses nuchal translucency, hCG and PAPP-A. Positive screen raises risk and prompts diagnostic testing with chorionic villus sampling or amniocentesis with karyotyping.<br><br>Trisomy 18 (B) shows low hCG. Open neural tube defects (C) show high AFP. Triploidy (D) shows variable hCG.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman at 9 weeks gestation presents with severe vomiting and dehydration. Laboratory findings reveal markedly elevated hCG levels. Which placental pathology is most likely responsible for this abnormal hormonal elevation?',o:['Placenta previa','Hydatidiform mole','Abruptio placentae','Placenta accreta'],a:1,
e:`Severe vomiting at 9 weeks with extreme hCG elevation suggests hydatidiform mole, gestational trophoblastic disease where abnormal trophoblast proliferation produces hCG levels often exceeding 200,000 IU/L.<br><br>Complete moles (46XX, all paternal) and partial moles (69XXX or 69XXY) present with first trimester bleeding, large-for-dates uterus, hyperemesis, theca lutein cysts and early pre-eclampsia. Ultrasound shows snowstorm appearance.<br><br>Normal pregnancy (A) shows lower hCG. Threatened miscarriage (C) shows declining hCG. Ectopic pregnancy (D) shows slow-rising hCG.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman undergoing antenatal screening shows significantly reduced maternal serum estriol levels. Ultrasound demonstrates intrauterine growth restriction. Which pathological process best explains this finding?',o:['Fetoplacental endocrine dysfunction','Maternal pituitary insufficiency','Maternal ovarian failure','Thyroid hormone deficiency'],a:0,
e:`Significantly reduced maternal estriol levels indicate fetoplacental endocrine dysfunction. Estriol synthesis requires obligate cooperation between fetal adrenal DHEAS production, fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation, and placental aromatisation.<br><br>Reduced estriol indicates fetal compromise, growth restriction, fetal demise, or anencephaly with adrenal hypoplasia. Unconjugated estriol forms part of triple/quadruple screening for trisomy 21 and 18, with low values raising risk and prompting diagnostic testing.<br><br>Normal pregnancy (B) shows rising estriol. Multiple gestation (C) shows higher estriol. Hyperthyroidism (D) does not directly reduce estriol.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with suspected ectopic pregnancy has lower-than-expected hCG levels and absence of intrauterine gestational sac on ultrasound. Which placental hormone abnormality is most characteristic of ectopic pregnancy?',o:['Increased estriol','Excess progesterone','Reduced hCG rise','Increased prolactin'],a:2,
e:`Lower-than-expected hCG rise in suspected ectopic pregnancy reflects impaired trophoblast function in extrauterine implantation. Normal intrauterine pregnancy hCG doubles every 48-72 hours; ectopic pregnancies typically show slow rise or plateau.<br><br>Quantitative hCG monitoring discriminates between viable intrauterine pregnancy, ectopic pregnancy and impending miscarriage. Combined with transvaginal ultrasound, this enables diagnosis. Suboptimal hCG rise (<53% in 48 hours) at sub-discriminatory levels warrants close monitoring or empirical methotrexate.<br><br>Normal hCG rise (A) suggests intrauterine pregnancy. Excess hCG (B) suggests molar pregnancy. Stable hCG (D) is intermediate finding.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman with gestational diabetes develops excessive insulin resistance due to placental hormone effects. Which hormone is mainly responsible for this pathological metabolic state?',o:['hPL','Estrogen','hCG','Progesterone'],a:0,
e:`Excessive insulin resistance in gestational diabetes is principally caused by human placental lactogen. hPL interferes with post-insulin-receptor signalling, requiring two to threefold increases in maternal insulin secretion to maintain euglycaemia.<br><br>Effects intensify with placental mass through second and third trimesters. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops, diagnosed at 24-28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing. hPL effects regress rapidly after placental delivery.<br><br>hCG (B) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (C) and progesterone (D) contribute mildly but are not principal diabetogenic hormones.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with severe growth restriction is found to have decreased placental hormone production. Which placental hormone deficiency most directly affects maternal metabolic adaptation required for fetal growth?',o:['hCG','Estrogen','Progesterone','hPL'],a:3,
e:`Fetal growth restriction with reduced placental hormone production reflects placental insufficiency, with hPL particularly affected. hPL secretion correlates with placental mass; reduced levels suggest reduced syncytiotrophoblast function.<br><br>hPL normally drives maternal insulin resistance and lipolysis ensuring transplacental glucose delivery, while directly stimulating fetal IGF-1 production promoting growth. Reduced hPL therefore parallels reduced fetal substrate availability and growth, manifesting as intrauterine growth restriction.<br><br>hCG (A) peaks early. Estrogen (B) supports uterine flow. Progesterone (C) maintains quiescence; none drive fetal growth like hPL.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Reduced maternal serum estriol levels during pregnancy are associated with which fetal condition?',o:['Down syndrome','Anencephaly','Turner syndrome','Placenta previa'],a:0,
e:`Reduced maternal serum estriol levels are associated with Down syndrome (trisomy 21) as part of antenatal screening. Down syndrome shows characteristic pattern: high hCG, low AFP, low unconjugated estriol, high inhibin A.<br><br>Triple test (AFP, hCG, estriol) and quadruple test (adding inhibin A) calculate combined risk for trisomy 21 and 18. Combined first trimester screening uses nuchal translucency, hCG and PAPP-A. Positive screen prompts diagnostic chorionic villus sampling or amniocentesis.<br><br>Pre-eclampsia (B) does not characteristically show low estriol. Polyhydramnios (C) and macrosomia (D) are not associated with low estriol.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone abnormality contributes to gestational diabetes mellitus?',o:['Reduced progesterone','Excess hPL','Reduced estrogen','Reduced hCG'],a:1,
e:`Excess hPL is the principal placental hormone abnormality contributing to gestational diabetes through induction of peripheral insulin resistance. hPL levels correlate with placental mass; excessive secretion exceeds normal compensatory rise in insulin.<br><br>hPL interferes with post-insulin-receptor signalling, particularly IRS-1 phosphorylation in muscle and adipose tissue. Effects intensify in second and third trimesters. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops at 24-28 weeks, requiring diet, exercise, metformin or insulin.<br><br>Excess hCG (A) causes hyperemesis. Reduced estriol (C) indicates fetal compromise. Reduced progesterone (D) causes preterm labour.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone abnormality is associated with molar pregnancy?',o:['Reduced progesterone','Reduced estrogen','Reduced hPL','Excess hCG'],a:3,
e:`Excess hCG is the placental hormone abnormality associated with molar pregnancy. Hydatidiform mole produces extreme hCG elevations often exceeding 200,000 IU/L due to abnormal trophoblast proliferation.<br><br>Complete moles (46XX, all paternal) and partial moles (69XXX or 69XXY) present with first trimester bleeding, large-for-dates uterus, hyperemesis, theca lutein cysts and early pre-eclampsia. Ultrasound shows snowstorm appearance. Suction evacuation followed by serial hCG monitoring detects gestational trophoblastic neoplasia.<br><br>Excess hPL (A) causes diabetes. Reduced estriol (B) indicates fetal compromise. Reduced progesterone (C) causes preterm labour.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Low hCG levels during early pregnancy may indicate:',o:['Polyhydramnios','Normal pregnancy','Ectopic pregnancy','Placenta accreta'],a:2,
e:`Low hCG levels in early pregnancy may indicate ectopic pregnancy where trophoblast implants outside the uterine cavity (most commonly fallopian tube). Suboptimal hCG rise reflects impaired trophoblast function in extrauterine site.<br><br>Normal intrauterine pregnancy hCG doubles every 48-72 hours; ectopic pregnancies typically show slow rise (<53% in 48 hours) or plateau. Combined with transvaginal ultrasound showing absent intrauterine sac at hCG above 1500-2000 IU/L (discriminatory zone), this confirms ectopic pregnancy.<br><br>Multiple gestation (A) shows high hCG. Hydatidiform mole (B) shows extreme elevation. Postdates (D) is not relevant in early pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which abnormal placental hormone pattern may indicate fetal demise?',o:['Increased progesterone','Declining hCG levels','Increased estriol','Rapidly rising hCG'],a:1,
e:`Declining hCG levels in early pregnancy may indicate fetal demise (missed miscarriage). Normal intrauterine pregnancy shows hCG doubling every 48-72 hours; declining levels suggest non-viable pregnancy.<br><br>Quantitative hCG monitoring discriminates between viable intrauterine pregnancy, ectopic pregnancy and missed miscarriage. Confirmation requires transvaginal ultrasound demonstrating absent fetal cardiac activity in fetal pole >7mm or empty sac >25mm. Management options include expectant, medical (misoprostol) or surgical evacuation.<br><br>Excess hCG (A) suggests molar pregnancy. Low estriol (C) indicates fetal compromise later. Excess hPL (D) is not associated with demise.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 29-year-old pregnant woman presents with severe nausea and vomiting at 10 weeks gestation. Laboratory evaluation reveals extremely elevated serum hCG levels far exceeding the normal range for gestational age. Ultrasound demonstrates a "snowstorm appearance" within the uterus without identifiable fetal structures. Which placental hormone abnormality explains the patient\'s symptoms?',o:['Reduced estrogen production','Reduced hPL secretion','Reduced progesterone secretion','Excess hCG secretion'],a:3,
e:`Severe nausea and vomiting in early pregnancy (hyperemesis gravidarum) is associated with excess hCG secretion. Conditions with extreme hCG elevation including molar pregnancy, multiple gestation and trophoblastic disease show increased frequency.<br><br>Mechanisms include hCG cross-reactivity with TSH receptors causing transient gestational thyrotoxicosis, and direct effects on the chemoreceptor trigger zone. Severe cases require IV fluids, antiemetics and thiamine to prevent Wernicke encephalopathy from prolonged vomiting.<br><br>Reduced hCG (A) suggests miscarriage. Excess hPL (B) causes diabetes. Reduced estriol (C) indicates fetal compromise.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman undergoes maternal serum screening which reveals significantly reduced estriol levels. The fetus is subsequently diagnosed with a chromosomal abnormality associated with placental endocrine dysfunction. Which fetal condition is most commonly associated with decreased maternal estriol levels?',o:['Down syndrome','Neural tube defect','Turner syndrome','Congenital heart disease'],a:0,
e:`Maternal serum screening showing significantly reduced estriol with elevated hCG and inhibin A suggests Down syndrome (trisomy 21). The quadruple test combines these markers with low AFP for risk calculation.<br><br>Down syndrome shows characteristic pattern: high hCG, low AFP, low unconjugated estriol, high inhibin A. Combined first trimester screening uses nuchal translucency, hCG and PAPP-A. Positive screen raises risk and prompts diagnostic chorionic villus sampling or amniocentesis with karyotyping.<br><br>Trisomy 18 (B) shows low hCG, low estriol, low inhibin A. Open neural tube defect (C) shows high AFP. Triploidy (D) is variable.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient presents with vaginal bleeding and abdominal pain at 7 weeks gestation. Serial hCG measurements demonstrate abnormally slow rise compared with normal pregnancy patterns. Ultrasound fails to demonstrate intrauterine pregnancy. Which diagnosis is most likely?',o:['Placenta previa','Hydatidiform mole','Missed abortion','Ectopic pregnancy'],a:3,
e:`Vaginal bleeding and abdominal pain at 7 weeks with positive pregnancy test should raise concern for ectopic pregnancy. Slow-rising hCG combined with absent intrauterine sac on transvaginal ultrasound at hCG above 1500-2000 IU/L confirms diagnosis.<br><br>Most common ectopic site is the fallopian tube. Risk factors include previous ectopic, tubal surgery, pelvic inflammatory disease, IVF and intrauterine device in situ. Management options include expectant, methotrexate or surgical (salpingostomy or salpingectomy), depending on hCG, size and patient stability.<br><br>Threatened miscarriage (A) shows intrauterine sac. Molar pregnancy (B) shows extreme hCG. Multiple gestation (C) shows high hCG with intrauterine sacs.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops gestational diabetes mellitus due to placental hormone-induced insulin resistance. Which physiological function of placental hormones becomes exaggerated in this pathological condition?',o:['Maternal lipolysis and insulin resistance','Decreased fetal glucose supply','Maternal glucose uptake','Reduced lipid metabolism'],a:0,
e:`Gestational diabetes results from placental hormone-induced increased maternal lipolysis and insulin resistance, principally driven by human placental lactogen. hPL interferes with insulin receptor signalling while activating hormone-sensitive lipase in adipose tissue.<br><br>This dual action ensures transplacental glucose delivery for fetal growth while maternal tissues use free fatty acids for energy. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops at 24-28 weeks. Tight glycaemic control reduces fetal macrosomia and other complications.<br><br>Increased glucose absorption (B) is not the mechanism. Increased insulin secretion (C) is compensatory. Decreased glucagon (D) is not relevant.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with placental insufficiency develops severe intrauterine growth restriction due to reduced endocrine function of the placenta. Which hormone deficiency most directly reduces maternal metabolic adaptation required for fetal growth?',o:['hCG','Estrogen','hPL','Progesterone'],a:2,
e:`Severe intrauterine growth restriction with decreased placental hPL reflects placental insufficiency. hPL secretion correlates directly with placental mass and function; reduced levels suggest reduced syncytiotrophoblast function.<br><br>hPL normally drives maternal insulin resistance and lipolysis ensuring transplacental glucose delivery, while directly stimulating fetal IGF-1 production promoting growth. Reduced hPL therefore parallels reduced fetal substrate availability and growth. Doppler ultrasound assesses fetal-placental flow alongside biochemical assessment.<br><br>Excess hCG (A) suggests molar pregnancy. Excess estriol (B) is not pathological. Reduced progesterone (D) causes preterm labour.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Excess maternal serum hCG levels are characteristic of:',o:['Hydatidiform mole','Abruptio placentae','Placenta previa','Oligohydramnios'],a:0,
e:`Excess maternal serum hCG levels are characteristic of hydatidiform mole, gestational trophoblastic disease where abnormal trophoblast proliferation produces hCG levels often exceeding 200,000 IU/L.<br><br>Complete moles (46XX, all paternal) and partial moles (69XXX or 69XXY) present with first trimester bleeding, large-for-dates uterus, hyperemesis, theca lutein cysts and early pre-eclampsia. Ultrasound shows snowstorm appearance. Suction evacuation followed by serial hCG monitoring detects neoplasia development.<br><br>Threatened miscarriage (B) shows declining hCG. Multiple gestation (C) elevates hCG but less extremely. Anembryonic pregnancy (D) shows low hCG.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Low maternal estriol levels may indicate:',o:['Maternal hypertension','Polyhydramnios','Fetal distress','Fetal chromosomal abnormality'],a:3,
e:`Low maternal estriol levels may indicate fetal chromosomal abnormality, particularly trisomy 21 (Down syndrome) and trisomy 18 (Edwards syndrome). Both show reduced estriol due to impaired fetal adrenal function affecting fetoplacental synthesis.<br><br>Unconjugated estriol forms part of triple test (with AFP, hCG) and quadruple test (adding inhibin A). Down syndrome shows high hCG, low AFP, low estriol, high inhibin A. Trisomy 18 shows low hCG, low AFP, low estriol, low inhibin A.<br><br>Multiple pregnancy (A) shows high estriol. Macrosomia (B) is not associated. Pre-eclampsia (C) is not characteristic.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone abnormality is most closely linked with hyperemesis gravidarum?',o:['Reduced estrogen','Elevated hCG','Elevated progesterone','Reduced hPL'],a:1,
e:`Elevated hCG is most closely linked with hyperemesis gravidarum. Conditions with extreme hCG elevation including molar pregnancy, multiple gestation and trophoblastic disease show increased frequency of severe nausea and vomiting in early pregnancy.<br><br>Mechanisms include hCG cross-reactivity with TSH receptors causing transient gestational thyrotoxicosis, and direct effects on the chemoreceptor trigger zone. Symptoms peak between 8-12 weeks when hCG is highest, settling as hCG declines. Severe cases require IV fluids and thiamine.<br><br>Reduced hCG (A) does not cause hyperemesis. Excess hPL (C) causes diabetes. Reduced estriol (D) indicates fetal compromise.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Placental hormone imbalance causing excessive insulin resistance leads to:',o:['Gestational diabetes','Placenta previa','Preeclampsia','Ectopic pregnancy'],a:0,
e:`Placental hormone imbalance causing excessive insulin resistance leads to gestational diabetes mellitus. Human placental lactogen is the principal diabetogenic hormone, interfering with insulin receptor signalling and requiring increased maternal insulin secretion.<br><br>Effects intensify in second and third trimesters with placental mass. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops, diagnosed at 24-28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing. Tight glycaemic control reduces fetal macrosomia, neonatal hypoglycaemia and other complications.<br><br>Hyperemesis (B) is hCG-related. Pre-eclampsia (C) is multifactorial. Polyhydramnios (D) results from many causes.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone abnormality may lead to early pregnancy loss due to corpus luteum failure?',o:['Reduced hPL','Increased progesterone','Increased estrogen','Reduced hCG'],a:3,
e:`Reduced hCG production may lead to early pregnancy loss because hCG normally maintains corpus luteum progesterone secretion essential for endometrial decidualisation and pregnancy maintenance until placental takeover.<br><br>Inadequate hCG from poor implantation or trophoblast development leads to corpus luteum regression, progesterone deficiency, inadequate decidualisation and miscarriage. Quantitative hCG monitoring discriminates between viable intrauterine pregnancy and impending miscarriage by tracking the doubling rate every 48-72 hours.<br><br>Excess hCG (A) suggests molar pregnancy. Excess hPL (B) causes diabetes. Reduced estriol (C) indicates later fetal compromise.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant patient undergoing routine antenatal screening shows extremely high hCG levels and ultrasound demonstrates multiple cystic structures within the uterus without a viable fetus. Which diagnosis best explains this placental hormone abnormality?',o:['Placenta previa','Abruptio placentae','Hydatidiform mole','Placenta accreta'],a:2,
e:`Extremely elevated hCG levels on routine antenatal screening should raise suspicion of hydatidiform mole, gestational trophoblastic disease where abnormal trophoblast proliferation produces hCG often exceeding 200,000 IU/L.<br><br>Complete moles (46XX, all paternal) and partial moles (69XXX or 69XXY) present with first trimester bleeding, large-for-dates uterus, hyperemesis, theca lutein cysts and early pre-eclampsia. Ultrasound shows snowstorm appearance. Suction evacuation with serial hCG monitoring detects neoplasia.<br><br>Multiple gestation (A) elevates hCG less extremely. Down syndrome (B) elevates hCG mildly. Pre-eclampsia (D) is not principally associated.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman with reduced placental endocrine function develops intrauterine growth restriction. Which hormone deficiency reduces maternal lipolysis and nutrient transfer to fetus?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','hCG','hPL'],a:3,
e:`Reduced placental endocrine function with insulin resistance points toward hPL pathology, though most often gestational diabetes results from excess hPL effect rather than reduction. hPL is the principal placental diabetogenic hormone.<br><br>hPL interferes with insulin receptor signalling, requiring two to threefold increases in maternal insulin secretion. Effects intensify with placental mass through second and third trimesters. Tight glycaemic control reduces fetal macrosomia, neonatal hypoglycaemia, shoulder dystocia and other complications.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (B) drives uterine growth. Progesterone (C) maintains quiescence; none drive insulin resistance like hPL.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman with suspected ectopic pregnancy undergoes serial hCG testing. Which abnormal pattern supports this diagnosis?',o:['Rapid doubling of hCG levels','Slow rise of hCG levels','Elevated progesterone levels','Sudden increase in estriol'],a:1,
e:`Slow rise of hCG levels (less than 53% increase in 48 hours) on serial monitoring suggests ectopic pregnancy. Normal intrauterine pregnancy shows hCG doubling every 48-72 hours; impaired trophoblast function in extrauterine site produces slow rise.<br><br>Combined with transvaginal ultrasound showing absent intrauterine sac at hCG above the discriminatory zone (1500-2000 IU/L), this confirms ectopic pregnancy. Management options include expectant, methotrexate (single or multi-dose), or surgical (salpingostomy or salpingectomy) depending on hCG, size and stability.<br><br>Normal doubling (A) suggests viable pregnancy. Static hCG (C) is suboptimal but ambiguous. Declining hCG (D) suggests miscarriage.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Reduced placental estrogen production may impair which physiological process in pregnancy?',o:['Uterine blood flow','Corpus luteum maintenance','Maternal lipid metabolism','Fetal adrenal development'],a:0,
e:`Reduced placental estrogen production may impair uterine blood flow during pregnancy. Estrogen normally induces endothelial nitric oxide synthase and prostacyclin in uterine vascular endothelium, producing vasodilation and increased flow.<br><br>Estrogen also drives angiogenesis through VEGF expression, expanding the uteroplacental vascular bed. Uterine blood flow rises from 50 mL/min nonpregnant to 500-700 mL/min at term. Inadequate spiral artery remodelling and reduced uterine perfusion contribute to pre-eclampsia and fetal growth restriction.<br><br>Maternal cardiac output (B) is independent. Maternal respiratory function (C) is unaffected. Fetal circulation (D) responds to placental flow but not directly to estrogen.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone abnormality is associated with poor fetal growth due to reduced nutrient mobilization?',o:['Increased estrogen','Reduced hPL','Increased progesterone','Reduced prolactin'],a:1,
e:`Reduced hPL is the placental hormone abnormality associated with poor fetal growth. hPL secretion correlates directly with placental mass and function; reduced levels suggest reduced syncytiotrophoblast function.<br><br>hPL normally drives maternal insulin resistance and lipolysis ensuring transplacental glucose delivery, while directly stimulating fetal IGF-1 production promoting growth. Reduced hPL therefore parallels reduced fetal substrate availability and growth, manifesting as intrauterine growth restriction. Doppler studies and biochemistry assess fetal wellbeing.<br><br>Excess hCG (A) suggests molar pregnancy. Excess estriol (C) is not pathological. Excess progesterone (D) does not cause growth restriction.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone abnormality contributes to severe hyperemesis in early pregnancy?',o:['Reduced progesterone','Increased prolactin','Increased hCG','Reduced estrogen'],a:2,
e:`Increased hCG is the placental hormone abnormality contributing to severe hyperemesis gravidarum. Conditions with extreme hCG elevation including molar pregnancy, multiple gestation and trophoblastic disease show increased frequency.<br><br>Mechanisms include hCG cross-reactivity with TSH receptors causing transient gestational thyrotoxicosis, and direct effects on the chemoreceptor trigger zone. Symptoms peak between 8-12 weeks. Severe cases require IV fluid resuscitation, antiemetics (cyclizine, ondansetron), and thiamine supplementation to prevent Wernicke encephalopathy.<br><br>Reduced hCG (A) does not cause hyperemesis. Reduced estriol (B) indicates fetal compromise. Excess hPL (D) causes diabetes.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone abnormality may indicate fetal compromise when measured in maternal serum?',o:['Reduced estriol','Increased progesterone','Reduced oxytocin','Increased prolactin'],a:0,
e:`Reduced estriol may indicate fetal compromise when measured in late pregnancy. Estriol synthesis requires obligate cooperation between fetal adrenal DHEAS production, fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation, and placental aromatisation.<br><br>Reduced estriol indicates fetal compromise, growth restriction, fetal demise, or anencephaly with adrenal hypoplasia. Maternal estriol monitoring assesses fetoplacental unit integrity. Modern fetal surveillance uses ultrasound, Doppler studies and cardiotocography rather than estriol assay alone.<br><br>Excess hCG (B) suggests molar pregnancy. Excess hPL (C) causes diabetes. Reduced progesterone (D) causes preterm labour.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone abnormality is commonly used as a biochemical marker for trophoblastic disease?',o:['Reduced estrogen','Reduced progesterone','Excess hCG','Reduced hPL'],a:2,
e:`Excess hCG is commonly used as a biochemical marker for hydatidiform mole and gestational trophoblastic neoplasia. Levels often exceed 200,000 IU/L in molar pregnancy, far above normal pregnancy range.<br><br>After molar evacuation, serial hCG monitoring detects gestational trophoblastic neoplasia (persistent or invasive disease) requiring chemotherapy with methotrexate or actinomycin-D. Failure of hCG to fall, plateau, or rising hCG after evacuation are diagnostic. Pregnancy must be avoided during follow-up.<br><br>Reduced hCG (A) suggests miscarriage. Excess hPL (B) causes diabetes. Reduced estriol (D) indicates fetal compromise.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Excess placental hormone-induced insulin resistance leads to which maternal complication?',o:['Gestational diabetes mellitus','Postpartum hemorrhage','Preterm rupture of membranes','Placenta previa'],a:0,
e:`Excess placental hormone-induced insulin resistance leads to gestational diabetes mellitus. Human placental lactogen is the principal diabetogenic hormone, interfering with insulin receptor signalling and requiring increased maternal insulin secretion.<br><br>Effects intensify in second and third trimesters with placental mass. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops, diagnosed at 24-28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing. Tight glycaemic control reduces fetal macrosomia, neonatal hypoglycaemia and other complications.<br><br>Pre-eclampsia (B) is multifactorial. Hyperemesis (C) is hCG-related. Hyperthyroidism (D) is endocrine but not principally placental.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone abnormality may impair fetal growth by reducing maternal nutrient mobilization?',o:['Increased estrogen','Increased progesterone','Increased hCG','Reduced hPL'],a:3,
e:`Reduced hPL is the placental hormone abnormality that may impair fetal growth by reducing nutrient supply. hPL secretion correlates with placental mass; reduced levels suggest reduced syncytiotrophoblast function and parallel reduced fetal substrate availability.<br><br>hPL normally drives maternal insulin resistance and lipolysis ensuring transplacental glucose delivery, while directly stimulating fetal IGF-1 production. Reduced hPL therefore reduces both substrate supply and direct growth stimulation, manifesting as intrauterine growth restriction.<br><br>Excess hCG (A) suggests molar pregnancy. Excess estriol (B) is not pathological. Excess progesterone (C) does not cause growth restriction.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman presents with severe nausea, uterine enlargement greater than expected for gestational age, and extremely elevated hCG levels. Ultrasound shows diffuse trophoblastic proliferation without a viable fetus. Which diagnosis best explains this hormonal abnormality?',o:['Placenta previa','Ectopic pregnancy','Hydatidiform mole','Abruptio placentae'],a:2,
e:`Severe nausea, uterine enlargement greater than dates, and extreme hCG elevation suggest hydatidiform mole. Complete moles (46XX, all paternal) produce hCG levels often exceeding 200,000 IU/L due to abnormal trophoblast proliferation.<br><br>Other features include first trimester bleeding, theca lutein cysts and early pre-eclampsia. Ultrasound shows snowstorm appearance. Suction evacuation followed by serial hCG monitoring detects gestational trophoblastic neoplasia (persistent disease) requiring methotrexate. Pregnancy must be avoided during follow-up monitoring.<br><br>Multiple pregnancy (A) elevates hCG less. Pre-eclampsia (B) is not the principal cause of hCG elevation. Threatened miscarriage (D) shows declining hCG.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with severe intrauterine growth restriction shows reduced maternal serum estriol levels. This suggests dysfunction of which physiological endocrine relationship?',o:['Maternal ovarian axis','Fetoplacental unit','Pituitary-placental axis','Maternal thyroid axis'],a:1,
e:`Severe intrauterine growth restriction with reduced maternal estriol indicates fetoplacental unit dysfunction. The pathway requires fetal adrenal DHEAS, fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation, and placental aromatisation; disruption at any step lowers maternal estriol.<br><br>Reduced estriol indicates fetal compromise, growth restriction, fetal demise, or anencephaly with adrenal hypoplasia. Modern fetal surveillance uses ultrasound (biometry, amniotic fluid), Doppler studies (umbilical artery, middle cerebral artery, ductus venosus) and cardiotocography rather than estriol alone.<br><br>Maternal hyperthyroidism (A) does not directly reduce estriol. Hypopituitarism (C) and adrenal insufficiency (D) alter maternal not fetal hormone production.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops progressive hyperglycemia due to placental hormones antagonizing insulin action. Which hormone is primarily responsible?',o:['Estrogen','hCG','Progesterone','hPL'],a:3,
e:`Progressive hyperglycaemia in pregnancy due to placental hormone-induced insulin resistance is principally caused by human placental lactogen. hPL interferes with insulin receptor signalling, requiring two to threefold rise in maternal insulin secretion.<br><br>hPL effects intensify with placental mass, peaking in third trimester. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops at 24-28 weeks. Cortisol, estrogen and progesterone contribute additional minor diabetogenic effects. hPL effects regress rapidly after placental delivery.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (B) drives uterine growth. Progesterone (C) maintains quiescence; none have hPL's diabetogenic effect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant patient with declining serum hCG levels in early pregnancy presents with vaginal bleeding and absent fetal cardiac activity. Which diagnosis is most consistent with this finding?',o:['Placenta previa','Missed abortion','Polyhydramnios','Gestational diabetes'],a:1,
e:`Declining serum hCG levels in early pregnancy with minimal symptoms suggests missed miscarriage (missed abortion), where fetal demise has occurred without expulsion of products. Normal pregnancy shows hCG doubling every 48-72 hours.<br><br>Confirmation requires transvaginal ultrasound demonstrating absent fetal cardiac activity in fetal pole >7mm or empty sac >25mm. Management options include expectant (allowing natural expulsion), medical (misoprostol with or without mifepristone) or surgical evacuation. Anti-D prophylaxis is given to rhesus-negative women.<br><br>Threatened miscarriage (A) shows continued viability. Ectopic pregnancy (C) shows slow-rising hCG. Hydatidiform mole (D) shows extreme hCG elevation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A clinician explains that abnormalities in placental hormone production may lead to pregnancy complications including fetal growth restriction, gestational diabetes, trophoblastic disease, and pregnancy loss. Which placental hormone abnormality most directly contributes to gestational diabetes mellitus?',o:['Reduced estrogen','Reduced hCG','Reduced progesterone','Excess hPL'],a:3,
e:`Abnormalities in placental hormone production cause specific pregnancy complications. Excess hPL is the principal hormone producing gestational diabetes through induction of peripheral insulin resistance, requiring increased maternal insulin secretion.<br><br>Effects intensify with placental mass through second and third trimesters. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops, diagnosed at 24-28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing. Tight glycaemic control reduces fetal macrosomia, neonatal hypoglycaemia, shoulder dystocia and other complications.<br><br>Excess hCG (A) causes hyperemesis. Reduced estriol (B) indicates fetal compromise. Reduced progesterone (C) causes preterm labour.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 25-year-old pregnant woman presents at 8 weeks gestation with severe vomiting and weight loss. Laboratory investigations reveal extremely high hCG levels. Ultrasound shows diffuse trophoblastic proliferation without a viable fetus. Which placental hormone abnormality explains the patient\'s symptoms?',o:['Reduced progesterone','Reduced hPL','Excess hCG','Reduced estrogen'],a:2,
e:`Severe nausea and vomiting at 8 weeks gestation is associated with excess hCG. Conditions with extreme hCG elevation including molar pregnancy, multiple gestation and trophoblastic disease show increased frequency of severe hyperemesis gravidarum.<br><br>Mechanisms include hCG cross-reactivity with TSH receptors causing transient gestational thyrotoxicosis, and direct effects on the chemoreceptor trigger zone. Severe cases require IV fluid resuscitation, antiemetics (cyclizine, ondansetron), and thiamine supplementation to prevent Wernicke encephalopathy.<br><br>Excess hPL (A) causes diabetes. Reduced estriol (B) indicates fetal compromise. Reduced progesterone (D) causes preterm labour.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman undergoes maternal serum screening and is found to have markedly reduced estriol levels. This suggests dysfunction in the endocrine interaction between placenta and fetal organs. Which physiological unit is affected in this condition?',o:['Hypothalamic-pituitary axis','Fetoplacental unit','Maternal ovarian axis','Maternal thyroid axis'],a:1,
e:`Maternal serum screening showing reduced estriol indicates dysfunction of the fetoplacental unit. The pathway requires fetal adrenal DHEAS, fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation, and placental aromatisation; disruption at any step lowers maternal estriol.<br><br>Unconjugated estriol forms part of triple test (with AFP, hCG) and quadruple test (adding inhibin A) for trisomy 21 and 18 screening. Down syndrome shows high hCG, low AFP, low estriol, high inhibin A. Trisomy 18 shows low hCG, low AFP, low estriol.<br><br>Maternal pituitary (A) does not regulate this. Maternal ovary (C) does not contribute. Maternal adrenal alone (D) cannot produce estriol.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops gestational diabetes mellitus due to excessive placental hormone activity that antagonizes insulin action. Which placental hormone is primarily responsible for this effect?',o:['hPL','Estrogen','Progesterone','hCG'],a:0,
e:`Gestational diabetes mellitus is principally caused by excessive human placental lactogen-induced insulin resistance. hPL interferes with post-insulin-receptor signalling, requiring two to threefold increases in maternal insulin secretion.<br><br>Effects intensify in second and third trimesters with placental mass. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops at 24-28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing. Diet, exercise, metformin and insulin manage the condition. hPL effects regress rapidly after placental delivery.<br><br>Excess hCG (B) causes hyperemesis. Excess estriol (C) is not pathological. Excess progesterone (D) does not cause diabetes.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A fetus with intrauterine growth restriction is found to have reduced placental endocrine activity. Which placental hormone deficiency most directly reduces maternal metabolic adaptation required to support fetal growth?',o:['Estrogen','hPL','Progesterone','hCG'],a:1,
e:`Intrauterine growth restriction with reduced placental hormone production reflects placental insufficiency. hPL is particularly affected, as its secretion correlates with placental mass and function.<br><br>hPL normally drives maternal insulin resistance and lipolysis ensuring transplacental glucose delivery, while directly stimulating fetal IGF-1 production promoting growth. Reduced hPL therefore parallels reduced fetal substrate availability and growth. Doppler ultrasound assesses fetal-placental flow alongside biometric and biophysical assessment.<br><br>Excess hCG (A) suggests molar pregnancy. Reduced estriol (C) is parallel finding. Excess progesterone (D) does not cause growth restriction.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant patient with declining hCG levels in early pregnancy presents with vaginal bleeding and ultrasound reveals absence of fetal cardiac activity. Which diagnosis is most consistent with this placental hormone abnormality?',o:['Placenta previa','Polyhydramnios','Missed abortion','Gestational diabetes'],a:2,
e:`Declining hCG levels with vaginal bleeding in early pregnancy presents as missed miscarriage. Normal pregnancy shows hCG doubling every 48-72 hours; declining levels suggest non-viable pregnancy.<br><br>Confirmation requires transvaginal ultrasound demonstrating absent fetal cardiac activity in fetal pole >7mm or empty sac >25mm. Management options include expectant, medical (misoprostol with or without mifepristone) or surgical evacuation. Anti-D prophylaxis is given to rhesus-negative women.<br><br>Threatened miscarriage (A) shows continued viability. Hydatidiform mole (B) shows extreme hCG elevation. Pre-eclampsia (D) is not relevant in early pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) is secreted from the:',o:['Anterior pituitary','Hypothalamus','Posterior pituitary','Pineal gland'],a:1,
e:`Gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) is secreted from the hypothalamus, specifically the arcuate nucleus and preoptic area neurons. GnRH is released in pulsatile fashion into the hypothalamic-hypophyseal portal system reaching the anterior pituitary.<br><br>Pulsatile GnRH stimulates anterior pituitary gonadotrophs to release LH and FSH. Continuous (non-pulsatile) GnRH paradoxically suppresses gonadotropin secretion, exploited therapeutically by GnRH agonists (leuprolide) for endometriosis, fibroids, prostate cancer and IVF protocols.<br><br>Anterior pituitary (A) is GnRH target, releasing LH and FSH. Posterior pituitary (C) releases oxytocin and ADH. Adrenal cortex (D) releases steroids.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The hormone responsible for stimulation of ovarian follicle development is:',o:['LH','Prolactin','Estrogen','FSH'],a:3,
e:`Follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) stimulates ovarian follicle development. FSH binds receptors on granulosa cells, activating cAMP-PKA signalling that drives granulosa cell proliferation and induces aromatase (CYP19A1) gene expression.<br><br>FSH-induced aromatase converts theca-derived androstenedione to estradiol, completing two-cell two-gonadotropin estrogen synthesis. The follicle with highest FSH response becomes dominant, while less efficient follicles undergo atresia from mid-cycle FSH fall. Recombinant FSH is used in IVF protocols for controlled ovarian stimulation.<br><br>GnRH (A) stimulates pituitary. LH (B) acts on theca cells and triggers ovulation. Prolactin (C) suppresses gonadotropins, not stimulating follicle development.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The surge of which hormone triggers ovulation during the menstrual cycle?',o:['FSH','LH','Progesterone','Prolactin'],a:1,
e:`Luteinizing hormone (LH) surge triggers ovulation during the menstrual cycle. Mid-cycle LH surge follows positive feedback from sustained high estradiol from the dominant follicle, switching from negative to positive feedback.<br><br>LH surge induces follicular wall enzymes, prostaglandin synthesis and protease activity that rupture the follicle approximately 36 hours after surge onset. LH also luteinises granulosa and theca cells forming the corpus luteum. Ovulation predictor kits detect LH surge to time intercourse for fertility.<br><br>FSH (A) stimulates follicle development. Progesterone (C) suppresses LH. Prolactin (D) suppresses gonadotropins, not triggering ovulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The proliferative phase of the menstrual cycle is mainly under the influence of:',o:['Progesterone','FSH','Estrogen','Prolactin'],a:2,
e:`Proliferative phase of the menstrual cycle (days 6-14) is mainly under the influence of estrogen produced by the developing dominant follicle. Estrogen stimulates endometrial mitosis through estrogen receptor alpha activation.<br><br>Endometrial thickness increases from 1mm post-menstruation to approximately 8-10mm by ovulation, with glandular and stromal proliferation. Spiral arteries elongate, preparing for potential implantation. After ovulation, progesterone from corpus luteum induces secretory transformation in the secretory phase, creating implantation-ready endometrium.<br><br>FSH (A) stimulates follicle development. Progesterone (B) drives secretory phase. Oxytocin (D) acts on uterine smooth muscle, not endometrial proliferation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The secretory phase of the menstrual cycle is primarily regulated by:',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','FSH','LH'],a:0,
e:`Secretory phase of the menstrual cycle (days 15-28) is primarily regulated by progesterone produced by the corpus luteum after ovulation. Progesterone induces endometrial secretory transformation through progesterone receptor activation.<br><br>Endometrial glands become tortuous and secrete glycogen-rich fluid; spiral arteries become coiled. The endometrium is prepared for blastocyst implantation. Without pregnancy, corpus luteum regresses at days 26-28, progesterone falls, vasoconstriction of spiral arteries causes ischaemia, and menstruation follows.<br><br>Estrogen (B) drives proliferative phase. FSH (C) stimulates follicle development. LH (D) triggers ovulation, then maintains corpus luteum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is mainly responsible for maintenance of corpus luteum in early pregnancy?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Prolactin','hCG'],a:3,
e:`Human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) is mainly responsible for maintenance of corpus luteum in pregnancy. hCG from syncytiotrophoblast binds LH receptors on luteal cells, sustaining progesterone secretion essential for endometrial decidualisation.<br><br>Without hCG rescue, corpus luteum would regress at day 14 triggering menstruation. hCG doubles every 48-72 hours, peaking at 8-11 weeks. The placenta then assumes progesterone production at the luteal-placental shift around 7-10 weeks. Quantitative hCG monitors early pregnancy progress.<br><br>FSH (A) stimulates follicles. LH (B) maintains luteum in nonpregnant cycle but is suppressed during pregnancy. Estrogen (C) is luteum product, not its rescuer.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Menarche normally occurs at the stage of puberty when:',o:['LH secretion stops','Ovulation ceases','Hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis becomes functional','Prolactin secretion increases'],a:2,
e:`Menarche normally occurs when the hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis becomes functional, with sufficient pulsatile GnRH driving FSH and LH that stimulate ovarian estrogen production. Critical body weight (~47 kg) and adequate fat stores supporting leptin signalling are required.<br><br>Mean age at menarche is 12-13 years in developed countries. Tanner stages of breast development (B2-B4) precede menarche by 2-2.5 years. Primary amenorrhoea (no menarche by 14 with no secondary characteristics, or by 16 with characteristics) warrants investigation including karyotype and hormone profile.<br><br>Adrenal maturation (A) drives adrenarche, separate from menarche. Increased adipose tissue (B) is contributory. Skeletal maturation (D) is parallel.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The primary source of estrogen in the ovarian follicle is:',o:['Granulosa cells','Theca cells only','Corpus luteum','Pituitary gland'],a:0,
e:`The primary source of estrogen in the ovarian follicle is granulosa cells, which express aromatase (CYP19A1) under FSH stimulation. Aromatase converts theca-derived androstenedione and testosterone to estrone and estradiol respectively.<br><br>This is the two-cell two-gonadotropin theory: theca cells under LH stimulation produce androgens (CYP17A1), which diffuse to granulosa cells where FSH-induced aromatase aromatises them to estrogens. The dominant follicle has highest aromatase activity, producing the late follicular estradiol surge that triggers LH surge and ovulation.<br><br>Theca cells (B) produce androgens. Stromal cells (C) have minimal aromatase. Oocytes (D) do not perform steroidogenesis significantly.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone primarily stimulates milk production in the breast after delivery?',o:['Oxytocin','Estrogen','Progesterone','Prolactin'],a:3,
e:`Prolactin from anterior pituitary lactotrophs is the primary hormone responsible for milk production after delivery. It binds prolactin receptors on alveolar epithelial cells, activating JAK2-STAT5 signalling that induces transcription of milk protein genes.<br><br>During pregnancy, high estrogen and progesterone prepare the breast but block lactation at alveolar level. After placental delivery, the abrupt fall in these steroids removes inhibition, allowing prolactin-driven lactogenesis II within 30-72 hours. Suckling maintains prolactin via neuroendocrine reflex inhibiting hypothalamic dopamine.<br><br>Oxytocin (A) mediates milk ejection from alveoli, not synthesis. Estrogen (B) stimulates ductal growth. hCG (C) maintains corpus luteum.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The hormone responsible for milk ejection reflex during breastfeeding is:',o:['Prolactin','Estrogen','Oxytocin','Progesterone'],a:2,
e:`Oxytocin from posterior pituitary mediates the milk ejection (let-down) reflex during breastfeeding. Suckling stimulates afferent nerves from nipple, triggering hypothalamic neurons to release oxytocin into systemic circulation.<br><br>Oxytocin contracts myoepithelial cells surrounding mammary alveoli, ejecting milk into ducts. The reflex can be conditioned (by infant cry or sight) and inhibited by stress (catecholamines). Oxytocin also stimulates uterine contractions postpartum, helping uterine involution and reducing postpartum haemorrhage during breastfeeding.<br><br>Prolactin (A) drives milk synthesis but not ejection. Estrogen (B) and progesterone (D) prepare breast but do not mediate ejection reflex.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'In the hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis, LH and FSH are secreted by the:',o:['Hypothalamus','Anterior pituitary','Posterior pituitary','Ovarian follicles'],a:1,
e:`LH and FSH are secreted by the anterior pituitary gonadotrophs in response to hypothalamic GnRH stimulation. Pulsatile GnRH from arcuate nucleus reaches gonadotrophs via the hypothalamic-hypophyseal portal system.<br><br>Different GnRH pulse frequencies favour different gonadotropins: high frequency favours LH, low frequency favours FSH. Sex steroid feedback modulates the axis: low estradiol exerts negative feedback, while sustained high estradiol switches to positive feedback triggering mid-cycle LH surge. Inhibin selectively suppresses FSH.<br><br>Hypothalamus (A) releases GnRH. Posterior pituitary (C) releases oxytocin and ADH. Pineal gland (D) releases melatonin.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During the menstrual cycle, the endometrium becomes thick and vascular mainly during the:',o:['Secretory phase','Menstrual phase','Proliferative phase','Ovulatory phase'],a:0,
e:`During the menstrual cycle, the endometrium becomes thick and vascular during the secretory phase under progesterone influence from the corpus luteum. Endometrial glands become tortuous and secrete glycogen-rich fluid; spiral arteries become coiled.<br><br>The secretory phase prepares the endometrium for blastocyst implantation. Without pregnancy, corpus luteum regresses at days 26-28, progesterone falls, vasoconstriction of spiral arteries causes ischaemia, and menstruation follows. With pregnancy, hCG rescues corpus luteum, sustaining progesterone and decidualisation.<br><br>Proliferative phase (B) is estrogen-driven, with thinner endometrium. Menstrual phase (C) is shedding. Ovulation (D) is single-day event.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The primary function of progesterone in the menstrual cycle is to:',o:['Initiate follicular growth','Cause ovulation','Prepare endometrium for implantation','Stimulate prolactin release'],a:2,
e:`The primary function of progesterone in the menstrual cycle is to prepare the endometrium for implantation. Progesterone induces secretory transformation, with tortuous glands secreting glycogen-rich fluid and stromal decidualisation supporting potential trophoblast invasion.<br><br>Progesterone also suppresses myometrial contractility, supporting potential pregnancy. Without pregnancy, corpus luteum regresses at days 26-28, progesterone falls, vasoconstriction of spiral arteries causes ischaemia and menstruation. With pregnancy, hCG rescues corpus luteum sustaining decidualisation until placental takeover.<br><br>Stimulating ovulation (A) is LH role. Inducing menstruation (B) is opposite of progesterone action. Promoting follicular growth (D) is FSH role.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is mainly responsible for the development of secondary sexual characteristics in females?',o:['Progesterone','FSH','LH','Estrogen'],a:3,
e:`Estrogen is mainly responsible for the development of secondary sexual characteristics in females during puberty. It drives breast development, fat distribution to hips and thighs, vaginal and uterine maturation, and skeletal closure of growth plates.<br><br>Estrogen acts via estrogen receptor alpha and beta in target tissues. Tanner stages B1-B5 chart breast development. Bone mineral acquisition during adolescence under estrogen influence determines peak bone mass. Pubic hair (pubarche) is largely driven by adrenal androgens (DHEA, DHEAS) at adrenarche, separate from gonadarche.<br><br>Progesterone (A) is luteal phase hormone. FSH (B) and LH (C) drive ovarian function but not directly secondary characteristics.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The luteal phase of the menstrual cycle usually lasts approximately:',o:['7 days','10 days','14 days','21 days'],a:2,
e:`The luteal phase of the menstrual cycle usually lasts approximately 14 days, more constant than the variable follicular phase. Corpus luteum forms after ovulation and produces progesterone and estradiol, maintaining secretory endometrium.<br><br>Without pregnancy, corpus luteum regresses at days 26-28 (luteolysis), progesterone falls and menstruation follows. With pregnancy, hCG rescues corpus luteum sustaining function until placental takeover at 7-10 weeks. Mid-luteal progesterone above 30 nmol/L confirms ovulation; luteal phase below 11 days suggests luteal phase defect.<br><br>7 days (A) and 10 days (B) are too short. 21 days (D) is too long; cycle would exceed normal length.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'In the ovarian cycle, ovulation usually occurs around which day in a typical 28-day cycle?',o:['Day 14','Day 10','Day 7','Day 21'],a:0,
e:`Ovulation usually occurs around day 14 in a typical 28-day cycle. The follicular phase is variable in length while the luteal phase is more constant at 14 days, so ovulation timing varies with cycle length.<br><br>Ovulation follows the LH surge by approximately 36 hours. Mid-cycle LH surge is triggered by sustained high estradiol from the dominant follicle (>200 pg/mL for 50 hours), switching from negative to positive feedback. Ovulation predictor kits detect LH surge to time intercourse for fertility.<br><br>Day 7 (B) is mid-follicular. Day 21 (C) is mid-luteal. Day 28 (D) is end of cycle, with menstruation imminent.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone is mainly responsible for suppression of ovulation during lactation?',o:['Estrogen','Prolactin','Progesterone','Oxytocin'],a:1,
e:`Prolactin is mainly responsible for suppression of ovulation during lactation. Sustained high prolactin from suckling-induced reflex inhibits hypothalamic GnRH secretion through dopaminergic mechanisms, reducing pituitary FSH and LH release.<br><br>This produces lactational amenorrhoea, providing natural birth spacing. Effectiveness depends on exclusive breastfeeding (LAM criteria: <6 months postpartum, exclusive breastfeeding, amenorrhoeic). Return of fertility precedes return of menses, so contraceptive counselling is needed before discontinuing exclusive breastfeeding or by 6 months postpartum at latest.<br><br>Estrogen (A) drives proliferative phase. hCG (C) is pregnancy-specific. Progesterone (D) inhibits LH but not principal lactation amenorrhoea cause.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The primary function of oxytocin during labor is to:',o:['Increase estrogen production','Prevent ovulation','Inhibit prolactin secretion','Stimulate uterine contractions'],a:3,
e:`The primary function of oxytocin during labour is to stimulate uterine contractions. Oxytocin from posterior pituitary binds oxytocin receptors on myometrial smooth muscle, triggering calcium influx and forceful coordinated contractions.<br><br>Oxytocin receptor density rises 100-fold near term, increasing myometrial sensitivity. Synthetic oxytocin (Syntocinon) is used for induction and augmentation of labour, given as IV infusion with continuous fetal monitoring. Postpartum oxytocin (10 units IM) reduces postpartum haemorrhage by promoting uterine contraction and placental separation.<br><br>Stimulating placental separation (A) is secondary effect. Increasing pelvic blood flow (B) is incorrect. Producing milk (C) is prolactin role.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During pregnancy, the placenta gradually takes over progesterone production from the:',o:['Corpus luteum','Ovarian follicle','Hypothalamus','Pituitary gland'],a:0,
e:`During pregnancy, the placenta gradually takes over progesterone production from the corpus luteum at the luteal-placental shift around 7-10 weeks gestation. Placenta progressively assumes synthesis using maternal cholesterol via CYP11A1 and 3-beta-HSD enzymes.<br><br>hCG initially rescues corpus luteum sustaining progesterone secretion. As placental output rises, it eventually exceeds luteal capacity. Removal of corpus luteum before this shift causes pregnancy loss; afterward does not affect pregnancy. Placental progesterone reaches 250 mg per day at term.<br><br>Pituitary (B) does not produce steroids. Adrenal cortex (C) produces cortisol. Hypothalamus (D) releases regulatory hormones, not steroids.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone contributes significantly to insulin resistance during pregnancy?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Human placental lactogen','Prolactin'],a:2,
e:`Human placental lactogen contributes significantly to insulin resistance during pregnancy through interference with insulin receptor signalling, particularly insulin receptor substrate-1 phosphorylation in muscle and adipose tissue.<br><br>Maternal insulin requirements rise two to threefold to maintain euglycaemia. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops, diagnosed at 24-28 weeks with oral glucose tolerance testing. hPL also drives lipolysis providing free fatty acids for maternal energy. Effects regress rapidly after placental delivery.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (B) drives uterine growth. Progesterone (D) maintains quiescence; none have hPL's diabetogenic effect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A teenage girl presents with delayed puberty due to failure of hypothalamic GnRH secretion. Which hormone would be directly reduced as a result?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Oxytocin','FSH'],a:3,
e:`Delayed puberty due to failure of hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis activation is characterised by low FSH (and LH) due to insufficient pulsatile GnRH stimulation. This hypogonadotropic hypogonadism contrasts with primary ovarian failure showing high FSH.<br><br>Causes include constitutional delay (most common, often familial), Kallmann syndrome (anosmia plus hypogonadotropic hypogonadism), pituitary tumours (craniopharyngioma), severe systemic illness, eating disorders and excessive exercise. Investigation includes karyotype, FSH/LH/estradiol, prolactin, thyroid function, MRI brain, smell testing.<br><br>GnRH (A) is hypothalamic, not measurable peripherally. LH (B) is also low. Estradiol (C) is reduced as consequence.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with hyperprolactinemia presents with infertility. The infertility occurs mainly because prolactin suppresses:',o:['LH surge and ovulation','Progesterone synthesis','Oxytocin release','Estrogen production'],a:0,
e:`Hyperprolactinaemia causes infertility by suppressing the LH surge and ovulation. Elevated prolactin inhibits hypothalamic GnRH secretion, reducing pulsatile gonadotropin release and preventing the mid-cycle LH surge required for ovulation.<br><br>This produces oligomenorrhoea, amenorrhoea or anovulatory cycles with infertility. Galactorrhoea may occur. Causes include prolactinoma (most common pathological cause), drugs (antipsychotics, metoclopramide), hypothyroidism, and stress. Treatment with dopamine agonists (cabergoline, bromocriptine) restores ovulation in most cases.<br><br>FSH stimulation alone (B) is reduced. Progesterone secretion (C) is reduced. hCG production (D) is unrelated to nonpregnant cycle infertility.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS) typically shows which hormonal pattern?',o:['Decreased LH and FSH','Increased FSH only','Increased estrogen only','Increased LH relative to FSH'],a:3,
e:`Polycystic ovarian syndrome typically shows increased LH relative to FSH (LH:FSH ratio above 2:1). Elevated GnRH pulse frequency preferentially stimulates LH over FSH, while granulosa cell dysfunction reduces inhibin B-mediated FSH suppression.<br><br>Elevated LH hyperstimulates theca cell CYP17A1 causing androgen excess, while reduced FSH impairs granulosa cell aromatisation. Rotterdam criteria require two of three: oligo/anovulation, hyperandrogenism (clinical or biochemical), polycystic ovarian morphology. Insulin sensitisers, COCP and lifestyle modification manage symptoms.<br><br>Decreased LH:FSH (A) suggests hypogonadotrophic state. Increased FSH only (B) suggests POI. Decreased androgens (C) is opposite.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A 45-year-old woman presents with irregular menses and hot flashes. Laboratory tests show increased FSH levels. What is the most likely physiological explanation?',o:['Increased ovarian estrogen production','Loss of negative feedback from ovarian hormones','Increased prolactin secretion','Pituitary adenoma'],a:1,
e:`A 45-year-old with irregular menses and hot flashes shows hormonal pattern of perimenopause: rising FSH and LH due to loss of negative feedback from declining ovarian estrogen and inhibin B production.<br><br>Falling inhibin B from declining cohorts of small antral follicles removes selective FSH suppression first. As estradiol production becomes erratic, gonadotropins rise further. Vasomotor symptoms result from oestrogen withdrawal narrowing hypothalamic thermoneutral zone. Diagnosis is clinical; FSH measurement is unreliable due to fluctuation.<br><br>Pituitary failure (A) would lower gonadotropins. Hyperprolactinaemia (C) suppresses gonadotropins. Hyperthyroidism (D) does not raise FSH.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A pregnant woman develops insulin resistance in the third trimester. Which placental hormone is mainly responsible?',o:['Human placental lactogen','Progesterone','Estrogen','hCG'],a:0,
e:`Insulin resistance in the third trimester is principally caused by human placental lactogen. hPL interferes with insulin receptor signalling, requiring two to threefold increases in maternal insulin secretion to maintain euglycaemia.<br><br>Effects intensify with placental mass, peaking in third trimester. Insulin-treated diabetic women experience worsening glycaemic control alongside rising hPL. Postnatally, hPL falls rapidly with placental delivery, resolving insulin resistance and reducing insulin requirements within hours of birth.<br><br>hCG (B) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (C) and progesterone (D) contribute mildly but are not principal diabetogenic hormones.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with Sheehan syndrome presents with failure of lactation after delivery. Which hormone deficiency explains this condition?',o:['Oxytocin','Estrogen','Prolactin','Progesterone'],a:2,
e:`Sheehan syndrome causes failure of lactation after childbirth due to ischaemic necrosis of the anterior pituitary, particularly affecting prolactin-secreting lactotrophs. Postpartum haemorrhage with hypotension precipitates pituitary infarction.<br><br>Failure of lactation is often the earliest sign. Subsequent panhypopituitarism develops with secondary hypothyroidism, hypoadrenalism, hypogonadotropic hypogonadism (no return of menses) and growth hormone deficiency. Diagnosis confirmed by low pituitary hormones and pituitary MRI. Hormone replacement (hydrocortisone, levothyroxine, sex steroids) is essential.<br><br>GnRH (A) is hypothalamic. Oxytocin (B) is posterior pituitary, less commonly affected. Estrogen (D) is ovarian.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with premature ovarian failure has high gonadotropin levels. Which hormone is typically most elevated?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','hCG','FSH'],a:3,
e:`Premature ovarian failure (premature ovarian insufficiency) presents with high FSH and LH due to loss of negative feedback. Depleted follicles fail to secrete estradiol and inhibin B, releasing pituitary gonadotrophs from suppression.<br><br>Diagnostic criteria require FSH above 25 IU/L on two occasions four weeks apart with at least four months of amenorrhoea, in a woman under 40. Causes include autoimmune (often associated with adrenal insufficiency), genetic (Turner syndrome, Fragile X premutation), iatrogenic (chemotherapy, radiotherapy, surgery), or idiopathic.<br><br>GnRH (A) is hypothalamic. LH alone (B) is also raised but FSH is more dramatic. Inhibin B (C) is reduced.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During pregnancy, uterine quiescence is mainly maintained by which hormone?',o:['Progesterone','Oxytocin','Prolactin','Estrogen'],a:0,
e:`Uterine quiescence during pregnancy is mainly maintained by progesterone, which inhibits myometrial contractility through downregulation of gap junction connexin-43, oxytocin receptors and prostaglandin synthesis.<br><br>Placental progesterone reaches 250 mg per day at term, far exceeding corpus luteum capacity. Functional progesterone withdrawal through receptor isoform switching from PR-B to PR-A precedes term labour. Progesterone deficiency contributes to preterm labour; supplementation reduces risk in women with previous preterm birth or short cervix.<br><br>Estrogen (B) increases contractility. Oxytocin (C) stimulates contractions. Relaxin (D) softens connective tissues; none maintain quiescence like progesterone.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A newborn female has ambiguous genitalia due to congenital adrenal hyperplasia. The underlying mechanism involves excessive production of:',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Androgens','Prolactin'],a:2,
e:`Newborn female with ambiguous genitalia due to congenital adrenal hyperplasia results from excess fetal androgens. 21-hydroxylase deficiency (95% of cases) blocks cortisol synthesis, raising ACTH that drives precursor accumulation and shunting to androgen pathway.<br><br>Excess fetal androgens (testosterone, androstenedione) virilise the external genitalia of female fetuses, producing clitoromegaly, labial fusion and varying genital ambiguity. Salt-wasting form additionally causes neonatal adrenal crisis. Lifelong glucocorticoid (with mineralocorticoid in salt-wasters) replacement and surgical correction manage the condition.<br><br>Estrogen (A) does not virilise. Progesterone (B) and cortisol (D) excess do not produce ambiguous genitalia.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A lactating mother experiences milk ejection when the baby suckles. Which neuroendocrine reflex mediates this response?',o:['Prolactin reflex','Estrogen feedback loop','GnRH surge','Oxytocin reflex'],a:3,
e:`Milk ejection in lactation occurs through the oxytocin reflex (let-down reflex). Suckling stimulates afferent nerves from nipple, triggering hypothalamic neurons to release oxytocin into systemic circulation from the posterior pituitary.<br><br>Oxytocin contracts myoepithelial cells surrounding mammary alveoli, ejecting milk into ducts. The reflex can be conditioned (by infant cry or sight) and inhibited by stress (catecholamines). Oxytocin also stimulates uterine contractions postpartum, helping uterine involution and reducing postpartum haemorrhage during breastfeeding.<br><br>Prolactin reflex (A) drives milk synthesis. Estrogen reflex (B) and FSH reflex (C) are not the milk ejection mechanism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Pulsatile secretion of GnRH from the hypothalamus is essential because continuous secretion would:',o:['Increase LH and FSH secretion','Stimulate prolactin release','Suppress gonadotropin release from the pituitary','Increase estrogen synthesis'],a:2,
e:`Pulsatile GnRH secretion is essential for stimulating gonadotropin release from the pituitary. Continuous (non-pulsatile) GnRH paradoxically suppresses gonadotropin secretion through receptor downregulation and desensitisation.<br><br>Different GnRH pulse frequencies favour different gonadotropins: high frequency (every 60-90 minutes) favours LH, low frequency favours FSH. This dynamic regulation underlies the menstrual cycle. GnRH agonists (leuprolide) initially stimulate then suppress gonadotropins (flare effect), exploited therapeutically for endometriosis, fibroids, prostate cancer and IVF protocols.<br><br>Suppress gonadotropins (A) is opposite. Stimulate ovaries (B) is GnRH-pituitary effect, not direct. Cause negative feedback (D) is steroid action.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman undergoing infertility evaluation has a mid-luteal serum progesterone level measured. The main purpose of this test is to confirm:',o:['Ovarian reserve','Ovulation','Pituitary function','Estrogen production'],a:1,
e:`Mid-luteal serum progesterone above 30 nmol/L (or 10 ng/mL) confirms ovulation has occurred. Corpus luteum forms after ovulation and produces progesterone, peaking around day 21 of a 28-day cycle.<br><br>Day 21 progesterone is the most commonly used test for confirming ovulation in fertility evaluation. In women with irregular cycles, the test should be timed to 7 days before expected menses. Levels below 30 nmol/L suggest anovulation or luteal phase defect; further investigation includes ultrasound follicle tracking.<br><br>Conception (A) is not directly indicated. Pregnancy (C) requires hCG. Implantation failure (D) is not indicated by mid-luteal progesterone alone.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The two-cell, two-gonadotropin theory of ovarian steroidogenesis states that estrogen synthesis requires interaction between:',o:['Oocyte and corpus luteum','Endometrium and ovary','Pituitary and hypothalamus','Granulosa cells and theca cells'],a:3,
e:`Two-cell two-gonadotropin theory of ovarian steroidogenesis states that estrogen synthesis requires cooperation between theca cells and granulosa cells under LH and FSH stimulation respectively.<br><br>Theca cells under LH stimulation produce androgens (androstenedione, testosterone) via CYP17A1 enzyme. Androgens diffuse to granulosa cells where FSH-induced aromatase (CYP19A1) converts them to estrone and estradiol. Neither cell type can complete estrogen synthesis alone, requiring this obligate cooperation throughout the menstrual cycle.<br><br>Theca alone (A) cannot aromatise. Granulosa alone (B) cannot synthesise androgens. Stromal cells (C) are not principal source.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During the late follicular phase, rising estrogen levels exert which effect on the hypothalamic-pituitary axis to trigger ovulation?',o:['Negative feedback on LH','Negative feedback on FSH','Positive feedback causing LH surge','Inhibition of GnRH secretion'],a:2,
e:`During the late follicular phase, rising estradiol from the dominant follicle exerts positive feedback on the hypothalamic-pituitary axis, triggering the mid-cycle LH surge. This switch from negative to positive feedback requires sustained high estradiol.<br><br>Estradiol must exceed approximately 200 pg/mL for 50 hours to trigger LH surge. The mechanism involves increased GnRH pulse frequency and amplitude, plus increased pituitary sensitivity to GnRH. LH surge induces follicular wall enzymes and prostaglandins that rupture the follicle approximately 36 hours later.<br><br>Negative feedback (A) operates with lower estradiol. Indirect feedback (B) is vague. No effect (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with luteal phase defect has recurrent early pregnancy loss. The underlying physiological problem is most likely:',o:['Excess estrogen production','Inadequate progesterone secretion from corpus luteum','Reduced prolactin levels','Decreased GnRH secretion'],a:1,
e:`Luteal phase defect causing recurrent early pregnancy loss results from inadequate progesterone secretion from the corpus luteum, leading to insufficient endometrial decidualisation to support implantation and early pregnancy.<br><br>Diagnosis is challenging; mid-luteal progesterone below 30 nmol/L on multiple cycles or short luteal phase below 11 days suggests defect. Underlying causes include luteinised unruptured follicle syndrome, hyperprolactinaemia, thyroid dysfunction. Vaginal progesterone supplementation may benefit women with recurrent miscarriage and luteal phase defect.<br><br>Inadequate FSH (A) affects follicular phase. Inadequate LH surge (C) prevents ovulation. Inadequate hCG (D) is consequence not cause.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'In a normal menstrual cycle, the hormone primarily responsible for converting proliferative endometrium into secretory endometrium is:',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','FSH','LH'],a:0,
e:`In a normal menstrual cycle, progesterone is primarily responsible for converting the proliferative endometrium to secretory phase. Corpus luteum forms after ovulation and produces progesterone, inducing secretory transformation.<br><br>Progesterone activates progesterone receptors causing endometrial glands to become tortuous and secrete glycogen-rich fluid; spiral arteries become coiled. The secretory endometrium is prepared for blastocyst implantation. Without pregnancy, corpus luteum regresses and progesterone falls, triggering menstruation.<br><br>Estrogen (B) drives proliferative phase. FSH (C) and LH (D) regulate ovarian function but do not directly induce secretory transformation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with hyperprolactinemia presents with galactorrhea and amenorrhea. The amenorrhea occurs mainly due to inhibition of:',o:['Estrogen secretion','Oxytocin secretion','Progesterone synthesis','GnRH release'],a:3,
e:`Hyperprolactinaemia causes galactorrhoea and amenorrhoea by suppressing GnRH release from the hypothalamus. Elevated prolactin inhibits GnRH neurons through dopaminergic mechanisms, reducing pulsatile gonadotropin release.<br><br>This produces oligomenorrhoea, amenorrhoea or anovulatory cycles with infertility. Galactorrhoea results from direct prolactin action on breast. Causes include prolactinoma (most common), drugs (antipsychotics, metoclopramide), hypothyroidism, stress and pregnancy. Treatment with dopamine agonists (cabergoline, bromocriptine) restores ovulation in most cases.<br><br>FSH stimulation (A) is reduced. LH surge (B) is suppressed. Estrogen production (C) is reduced as consequence.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which placental hormone has anti-insulin effects and promotes maternal lipolysis to ensure fetal glucose availability?',o:['hCG','Progesterone','Human placental lactogen','Relaxin'],a:2,
e:`Human placental lactogen has anti-insulin effects and promotes maternal lipolysis to ensure continuous fetal substrate supply. It interferes with insulin receptor signalling while activating hormone-sensitive lipase in adipose tissue.<br><br>This dual action raises maternal blood glucose for transplacental fetal delivery while mobilising free fatty acids for maternal energy. hPL secretion correlates with placental mass, peaking in third trimester. When pancreatic beta cell compensation fails, gestational diabetes develops at 24-28 weeks.<br><br>hCG (A) maintains corpus luteum. Estrogen (B) drives uterine growth. Progesterone (D) maintains quiescence; none have hPL's metabolic action.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The earliest endocrine signal of pregnancy detectable in maternal blood is:',o:['hCG','Estrogen','Progesterone','Prolactin'],a:0,
e:`Human chorionic gonadotropin is the earliest endocrine signal of pregnancy detectable in maternal blood. Syncytiotrophoblast secretes hCG from approximately day 8 after fertilisation, immediately following implantation.<br><br>Maternal serum hCG rises rapidly, doubling every 48-72 hours. Quantitative serum hCG detects from 5 IU/L; modern urinary tests detect from 25 IU/L from the first day of missed period. hCG peaks at 8-11 weeks at around 100,000 IU/L before declining as the placenta assumes progesterone production.<br><br>Estrogen (B), progesterone (C) and hPL (D) rise during pregnancy but are not the earliest detectable markers.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During normal pregnancy, estrogen is mainly produced by the placenta using precursors supplied from:',o:['Maternal liver','Fetal adrenal gland','Maternal kidney','Corpus luteum'],a:1,
e:`During normal pregnancy, estrogen is mainly produced by the placenta using fetal adrenal androgen precursors. Placenta lacks 17-alpha-hydroxylase and cannot synthesise androgens de novo from cholesterol; it depends on fetal adrenal DHEAS supply.<br><br>Placental sulfatase desulfates DHEAS, then aromatase converts it to estrogens. Most estriol production additionally requires fetal liver 16-alpha-hydroxylation. This obligate cooperation creates the fetoplacental unit. Maternal estriol monitoring assesses fetoplacental integrity, declining with fetal or placental compromise.<br><br>Maternal ovary (A) ceases significant estrogen production after corpus luteum involutes. Maternal adrenal (C) and corpus luteum (D) provide minor amounts.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with hypothalamic amenorrhea due to excessive exercise most likely has reduced secretion of:',o:['GnRH','Prolactin','Oxytocin','hCG'],a:0,
e:`Hypothalamic amenorrhoea due to excessive exercise most likely involves reduced pulsatile GnRH secretion from the hypothalamus. Energy deficit, low leptin and stress reduce GnRH pulsatility, lowering FSH, LH and estradiol.<br><br>This functional hypothalamic amenorrhoea presents with oligomenorrhoea or amenorrhoea, reduced bone mineral density and infertility. The female athlete triad (energy deficiency, menstrual disturbance, low bone density) is recognised. Management involves adequate energy intake, reduced training intensity, calcium and vitamin D, and HRT for severe hypoestrogenism.<br><br>FSH (B) and LH (C) are reduced as consequence of low GnRH. Prolactin (D) is normal in hypothalamic amenorrhoea.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The mid-cycle LH surge is triggered when circulating estradiol levels remain elevated for approximately:',o:['6 hours','12 hours','24-48 hours','5 days'],a:2,
e:`Mid-cycle LH surge is triggered when circulating estradiol levels remain above approximately 200 pg/mL for 24-48 hours sustained. This sustained high estradiol switches feedback from negative to positive on the hypothalamic-pituitary axis.<br><br>The mechanism involves increased GnRH pulse frequency and amplitude, plus increased pituitary sensitivity to GnRH. LH surge induces follicular wall enzymes and prostaglandins that rupture the follicle approximately 36 hours after surge onset. Ovulation predictor kits detect LH surge in urine to time intercourse.<br><br>6-12 hours (A) is too short. 12-24 hours (B) approaches but doesn't quite reach threshold. 72-96 hours (D) overestimates.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During lactation, suppression of ovulation occurs mainly because prolactin:',o:['Stimulates estrogen secretion','Inhibits GnRH secretion','Increases LH surge','Stimulates progesterone'],a:1,
e:`During lactation, suppression of ovulation occurs mainly because prolactin inhibits GnRH secretion from the hypothalamus through dopaminergic mechanisms. This reduces pulsatile gonadotropin release, preventing follicular development and ovulation.<br><br>This produces lactational amenorrhoea, providing natural birth spacing. Effectiveness depends on exclusive breastfeeding (LAM criteria: <6 months postpartum, exclusive breastfeeding, amenorrhoeic). Return of fertility precedes return of menses, so contraceptive counselling is needed before discontinuing exclusive breastfeeding or by 6 months postpartum.<br><br>Stimulates GnRH (A) is opposite. Causes ovulation (C) is opposite. Has no effect (D) is incorrect; prolactin actively suppresses HPO axis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A patient with Turner syndrome presents with primary amenorrhea and streak ovaries. Which hormonal pattern is expected?',o:['Low FSH and LH','High progesterone','High estrogen','High FSH and LH'],a:3,
e:`Turner syndrome (45,X karyotype) presents with primary amenorrhoea and short stature, with hormone profile showing high FSH and LH due to streak ovaries failing to produce estradiol and inhibin B, releasing pituitary gonadotrophs from suppression.<br><br>Other features include webbed neck, cubitus valgus, low-set ears, lymphoedema, cardiac anomalies (coarctation, bicuspid aortic valve) and renal anomalies. Diagnosis confirmed by karyotype. Management includes growth hormone for short stature, estrogen replacement for puberty induction and bone protection, plus screening for associated cardiac and renal anomalies.<br><br>Low FSH and LH (A) suggest hypothalamic. High prolactin (B) is unrelated. High androgens (C) is not Turner pattern.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'Which hormone produced by the placenta helps relax pelvic ligaments and soften the cervix during pregnancy?',o:['Relaxin','Oxytocin','hCG','Prolactin'],a:0,
e:`Relaxin produced by the placenta and corpus luteum helps relax pelvic ligaments and prepare cervix for childbirth. It activates matrix metalloproteinases that remodel collagen in symphysis pubis, sacroiliac joints and cervix.<br><br>Relaxin levels peak in the first trimester at approximately 1,000 pg/mL, remaining elevated until labour. This connective tissue remodelling increases pelvic outlet capacity for fetal passage. Relaxin also produces systemic vasodilation contributing to increased renal blood flow and reduced systemic vascular resistance.<br><br>Progesterone (B) maintains quiescence. Estrogen (C) drives uterine growth. Oxytocin (D) stimulates contractions; none soften connective tissue like relaxin.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'In early pregnancy, progesterone secretion is initially maintained by the:',o:['Placenta','Pituitary gland','Hypothalamus','Corpus luteum'],a:3,
e:`In early pregnancy, progesterone secretion is initially maintained by the corpus luteum under stimulation of human chorionic gonadotropin. hCG binds LH receptors on luteal cells, sustaining progesterone secretion essential for endometrial decidualisation.<br><br>This luteal support continues until the placenta assumes progesterone production at the luteal-placental shift around 7-10 weeks. Removal of corpus luteum before this shift causes pregnancy loss; afterward does not affect pregnancy. Placental progesterone reaches 250 mg per day at term using maternal cholesterol.<br><br>Placenta (A) takes over later. Fetal adrenal (B) provides estrogen precursors, not progesterone. Maternal adrenal (C) does not produce pregnancy progesterone.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman undergoing assisted reproduction receives GnRH agonists continuously. The expected physiological effect is:',o:['Suppression of pituitary gonadotropins','Increased LH and FSH release','Increased estrogen secretion','Induction of ovulation'],a:0,
e:`GnRH agonists given continuously cause suppression of pituitary gonadotropins through receptor downregulation and desensitisation. Initial flare effect with brief gonadotropin rise gives way to prolonged suppression within 1-2 weeks of continuous administration.<br><br>This produces medical hypophysectomy used in IVF protocols (long protocols) to prevent premature LH surge during controlled ovarian stimulation. Other applications include endometriosis, fibroids, central precocious puberty, and prostate cancer. Add-back HRT prevents bone loss from prolonged hypoestrogenism in extended use.<br><br>Stimulation of ovulation (B) is initial flare effect. Endometrial growth (C) is not direct effect. Increased estrogen (D) follows initially then falls.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'The hormone mainly responsible for cervical ripening near term is:',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Prostaglandins','Prolactin'],a:2,
e:`Prostaglandins (PGE2 and PGF2alpha) are mainly responsible for cervical ripening near term. They stimulate cervical collagen breakdown through matrix metalloproteinase activation and increase glycosaminoglycan content, softening the cervix.<br><br>Cervical ripening converts firm closed cervix into soft effaced and dilated cervix ready for labour. Synthetic prostaglandins (dinoprostone vaginal pessary, misoprostol) are used for cervical ripening before labour induction in women with unfavourable Bishop score. Mechanical methods (Foley catheter) provide alternative for ripening.<br><br>Estrogen (A) supports but is not principal ripening agent. Progesterone (B) maintains quiescence. Oxytocin (D) stimulates contractions but does not ripen cervix directly.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'During menopause, which physiological change occurs in ovarian hormone production?',o:['Marked decline in ovarian estrogen secretion','Complete cessation of estrogen and progesterone production','Increased estrogen production','Increased progesterone levels'],a:0,
e:`During menopause, the principal physiological change in ovarian hormone production is marked decline in ovarian estrogen secretion due to follicular depletion. Postmenopausal estradiol falls below 30 pmol/L while gonadotropins rise.<br><br>Postmenopausal estrogen comes from peripheral aromatisation of adrenal androstenedione to estrone in adipose tissue, with estrone replacing estradiol as the dominant estrogen. FSH rises to 30-100 IU/L, LH to 20-50 IU/L, with FSH disproportionately elevated due to selective inhibin B loss.<br><br>Increased estrogen (B) is opposite. Increased progesterone (C) is opposite; progesterone falls. No change (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

{q:'A woman with anovulatory cycles due to PCOS often has chronic exposure of endometrium to estrogen without progesterone. This increases the risk of:',o:['Cervical carcinoma','Ovarian torsion','Vaginal atrophy','Endometrial hyperplasia'],a:3,
e:`Anovulatory cycles in PCOS produce chronic exposure to unopposed estrogen without progesterone-induced secretory transformation, leading to endometrial hyperplasia. Continued exposure increases endometrial atypia and progression to endometrioid carcinoma.<br><br>Risk is amplified by obesity (peripheral aromatisation in adipose tissue) and insulin resistance. Management includes cyclical progestogens (medroxyprogesterone 10mg for 10-14 days monthly) or combined oral contraceptive pill to induce regular withdrawal bleeds. Levonorgestrel intrauterine system provides effective endometrial protection.<br><br>Endometriosis (A) is ectopic endometrial tissue. Cervical cancer (B) is HPV-driven. Ovarian cysts (C) occur but are not the principal endometrial risk.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

];
})();